<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' DEFENSE CAN'T KEEP UP WITH HORNETS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE DeWITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ If the New Jersey Nets were not engaged in a
daily battle for the eighth and final playoff spot in the NBA's
Eastern Conference, it might be easy to write off Wednesday night's
lackluster defensive effort against the Charlotte Hornets as
typical of a team impatient for the season to wind down.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, however, with just 15 games remaining, the 119-103
loss inflicted on New Jersey by Charlotte cannot be easily excused
or forgotten. It dropped the Nets three games behind Orlando, which
holds the last playoff spot and has 13 games to go.
</P>
<P>
   There was frustration all around over allowing the Hornets to
shoot 56 percent from the field and score a season-high 119 points.
Worse than blowing an opportunity to keep pace with the Magic, the
Nets also might have lost some momentum, for the Hornets entered
the game on a three-game losing streak, while the Nets were fresh
off of an energizing win over the Toronto Raptors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the heroes of that victory was Kendall Gill, whose
offense _ a game-high 24 points _ and defense on the Raptors'
superstar Vince Carter were a major part of the Net's fifth victory
in six attempts. But against the Hornets, Gill was one of the
primary reasons the Hornets gained early control of the game and
never handed it back.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gill's inability to match up with Anthony Mason became apparent
from the outset, particularly to the Hornets' coach Paul Silas.
Although he scored New Jersey's first eight points, Gill, who gave
up more than 50 pounds to Mason, could not stop the former Knicks
forward, who hit on four of his five first half shots.
</P>
<P>
   All the Nets could do was double-team Mason to prevent easy
layups, which allowed him to set up David Wesley and Eddie Jones
for wide-open shots from the perimeter. Wesley and Jones hit eight
of their nine first-half shots and Mason had five assists in the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Mason finished with 17 points, but that only tells part of the
story. His seven assists _ incredibly, the Hornets' 46 field goals
came on 37 assists _ and game-high seven rebounds were enough to
send the Nets searching again, if not for excuses, then for the
momentum that will propel them past the Orlando Magic, whose
victory on this night puts the Nets three behind with 15 to play. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets had failed to score 100 points in 11 of their last
14 games, but they reached it Wednesday night less than two minutes
into the fourth quarter. Jones led the way with 26 points, and
Derrick Coleman and Wesley added 22 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury paced New Jersey with 23 points, while Gill and
Keith Van Horn had 17 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really did a good job handling our double teams,'' said
Nets coach Don Casey. ``They spaced out well and located their
people. We seemed exasperated after we made runs. Charlotte was
very sharp. Coleman and Mason did a good job of posting up our guys
and that opened up their outside game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill sought help from his teammates, but it was largely
ineffective. ``It was hard, at first, to figure out what they were
doing,'' he said. ``When I'm guarding someone 6-8, 280 pounds, I'm
going to need help.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only Van Horn kept the Nets within striking distance. He
connected on 6 of 7 from the floor and 2 of 2 from the free throw
line for 15 first-half points, one of only two Nets to reach double
figures at the break. The Hornets had Wesley, Jones, Mason and
Coleman in double figures by halftime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nets cut the lead to four points on several occasions in the
second quarter. A last gasp attempt to stay close came with 1:53
remaining before intermission on a Van Horn driving dunk. But a
Coleman layup off of yet another Mason assist pushed the Hornets to
a nine-point halftime lead, buoyed by 24 of 38 shooting from the
field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marbury came alive in the third quarter, scoring nine points in
the first 4 1-2 minutes, including a tip-in off his missed shot
that cut the Hornets' lead to 73-65 at the 7:29 mark. But poor
defensive rotation on a Coleman drive into the lane ended in a
dunk, and a steal and basket by Wesley quickly countered the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   An inside basket by Jones and an uncontested Mason dunk in quick
succession put the Hornets in command, 81-65, at the 5:44 mark of
the third quarter and forced Casey to call a timeout, searching for
answers that did not come.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nets did not say back-to-back road games or a 3:00 a.m.
arrival in Charlotte were factors in the final score. ``That kind
of thing happens to every team,'' said Marbury. ``Offensively, we
really couldn't get into anything because our defense wouldn't
allow us. We didn't take advantage of our opportunities. We lost
because we didn't execute on defense.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
