<HEADLINE>
FOX SPORTS NET BUYS NON-CABLE BROADCAST RIGHTS TO STARS, RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 SPORTS NET-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN WOOD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Southwest Sports Group on Wednesday announced
a 10-year deal giving Fox Sports Net the non-cable broadcast rights
to the Texas Rangers and Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Southwest Sports Group, which owns both teams,
and Fox would not disclose the value of the deal. Southwest Sports
Group president and chief operating officer Mike Cramer called the
deal ``substantial'' and said it was of ``slightly less value''
than the 15-year deal for the cable rights to Southwest's sports
holdings, which also include the Mesquite Championship Rodeo.
Southwest Sports chairman Tom Hicks sold the cable rights to Fox
Sports Net for $300 million in September, a source familiar with
the agreement said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The non-cable deal is worth $200 million, Dallas station KDFW
reported last night.
</P>
<P>
   The deal goes into effect immediately for the 2000 Rangers
season. KDFI will broadcast 61 Rangers games starting with the
March 31 exhibition game against the St. Louis Cardinals. KDFW will
broadcast six games and Fort Worth station KXAS will broadcast five
games as part of an existing contract that expires this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' broadcasts will start next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very, very pleased to match cable games with the
over-the-air games,'' Cramer said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal took nearly four months to hammer out and was delayed
by Major League Baseball's attempts to develop rules for
broadcasting over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major League Baseball came out with a draft set of rules,''
Cramer said. ``But we're not done yet in terms of dealing with
Major League Baseball. But we're starting down the path, waiting
for MLB's final set of rules.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
