<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS EQUAL OPPORTUNITY, NASCAR-STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having failed to qualify for three of four NASCAR Busch Grand
National Series races this season, Tony Roper has more things on
his plate than the profile of his team owners.
</P>
<P>
   They include two athletes _ Joe Washington and Julius Erving _
who are retired superstars in professional football and basketball,
respectively, and successful post-jock businessmen. Together with
partners Fields Jackson Jr. and Asa Murray, Washington Erving
Motorsports is the first full-time, minority-owned team competing
in NASCAR since the late Wendell Scott ran as an independent more
than 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's fastest-growing spectator sport, NASCAR racing
takes a public relations hit every now and then over the fact that
despite its ``open garage door'' policy, it has failed to attract
comparative numbers of minority fans, owners and crewmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know why there isn't an influx of minorities
into NASCAR racing,'' said Roper, a second-generation driver who is
in his first year with Washington Erving. But you know that ``level
playing field'' NASCAR officials always are striving to maintain on
the racetrack? The principle extends into the garage area and the
front office, meaning each team joining the series has an equal
opportunity to succeed _ or fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we've missed the last three races,'' said Roper, who
tested at Texas Motor Speedway on Monday in anticipation of the
Albertson's 300 in Fort Worth on April 1. ``Our intention was to
build some brand new race cars for the start of the season, go
testing and add some personnel. To be honest, it never happened,
and we've found ourselves flat in a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   That rates as status quo for this team, which along with primary
sponsor Dr Pepper of Plano, was introduced during the NASCAR
weekend at TMS in the spring of 1998. That start-up group went
through a revolving door lineup of 10 drivers. In fact, Washington
Erving's highlight to date has been a modest 10th-place finish by
Mark Green at Atlanta Motor Speedway in March, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem I see is there's been not much continuity
here,'' said Roper, who put the No. 50 Chevrolet Monte Carlo on the
starting grid at North Carolina Speedway last month, but wasn't
fast enough at Daytona, Atlanta or Darlington. ``Our crew chief,
Darrell Bryant, told Joe after the Darlington race that this was
his third year with the team, and he'd never started with the same
engine program, the same body style, the same driver or with the
same crew members in any year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their goal is to have two Busch teams, and eventually a
Winston Cup team. But I think they realize now just how hard it is
to compete on this level.''
</P>
<P>
   Roper, who notched three top-10 finishes and a career-best
eighth in 16 starts as a rookie last year, said the race of his
owners was not a factor when he approached Washington about
replacing Green. A 35-year-old native of Missouri, Roper said he
and Washington have become fast friends during all that forced
down-time at the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe will tell you he started not at zero, but well below zero,
in racing,'' said Roper, speaking of the Port Arthur native and NFL
Pro Bowl running back. ``Every time he comes to the racetrack, I'm
amazed at some of the questions he asks _ simple questions, Racing
101 _ that he doesn't know about.''
</P>
<P>
   And Erving, signature player of the American Basketball
Association, and otherwise immortalized as ``Dr. J?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met him,'' Roper said of the Hall of Famer who
fashioned the dunk into an art form during the mid-1970s. ``But
when I was younger, he was one of my basketball heroes. Julius is
an owner, but he's awful busy with his job (executive vice
president) with the Orlando Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Roper said his crew includes two minority members, Kenneth
``Lighting'' Scott, the truck driver and gas man, and David Cropps,
the catch-can man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to see black drivers, more black crewmen
and more black owners in this sport,'' Roper said. ``And I don't
think that NASCAR or any of the owners that are involved now or
have been involved forever ... are going to act any different
toward them than they would anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's garage doors are wide open. And that means Washington
Erving will have an equal opportunity to succeed _ or fail.
SPOTLIGHT ON: ANDRETTI IS SURVEY'S CHOICE TO WIN CART CROWN
</P>
<P>
   CART's team managers secretly might admire multiple-car owner
Chip Ganassi's bravado in switching from the Honda/Reynard to the
Toyota/Lola package in a bid for a fifth consecutive FedEx Series
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   But practically speaking, the men who run the race-day
operations of the Championship Auto Racing Teams like Michael
Andretti as the driver to beat in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   CART's winningest active driver with 38 victories, Andretti
emerged as the favorite among 15 team managers who participated in
a survey for the official ``Champ Car FedEx Series Guide.'' The
20-race season is scheduled to begin Sunday at Homestead-Miami
Speedway, where Andretti is a proven commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti won the season-opening Marlboro Grand Prix of Miami in
1997 and 1998, and finished second on the 1.5-mile oval last year.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, 37, finished fourth in points in 1999 for Newman-Haas
Racing, and is locked in on his 17th CART season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience is a wonderful thing, for sure,'' said Andretti,
whose team has switched from the Swift to Lola chassis with power
supplied by the new Ford-Cosworth XF V-8. ``I feel that if I lack
anything of speed ... from the youth side, I can make it up in
experience. I'm hoping I can be a little more patient and wait for
things to come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Each team manager was asked to nominate, in order from one
through 10, the drivers he believed will fill the top 10 points
positions at season's end. Ten drivers received nominations. But
only Andretti and CART newcomer Kenny Brack, the former Indy Racing
League and reigning Indianapolis 500 champion, were selected as
eventual series champion on more than one ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, the 1991 series champion, finished ahead of Max Papis
(Team Rahal) and Dario Franchitti (Team Kool Green), with reigning
series champion Juan Montoya (Target/Chip Ganassi Racing) sliding
to fourth. The remainder of the top 10 included Christian
Fittipaldi (Newman-Haas), Paul Tracy (Team Kool Green), Brack (Team
Rahal), Adrian Fernandez (Patrick Racing), Gil de Ferran (Marlboro
Team Penske) and Jimmy Vasser (Target/Chip Ganassi).
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the elements have come together for the start of a
great season,'' said Andretti, who has 32 poles and became the
first series driver to lead 6,000 laps in his career last season.
``We always set our goals high during the off-season, but our
testing has given us a good level of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like there is more pressure to do well since we
won two of the last three races (at Homestead), and have had some
good luck at Homestead. I love racing on the track. It suits my
style. It would be nice to finish in second place or above ...
preferably above second place. I'm ready to go racing.''
PIT STOPS SRO TICKETS READIED
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Texas Motor Speedway are anticipating that all
seats will be sold for the NASCAR Winston Cup DirecTV 500 on April
2.
</P>
<P>
   Cup tickets are available at $60, $65 and $70. But no fan
wishing to attend the race will be turned away. Fans showing up on
race day without a secured seat can purchase a standing-room-only
infield ticket for $60, said Sarona Winfrey, TMS' director of
public relations. Those tickets will be available at either of the
two tunnel entrances, Gate 8 or Gate 12, allowing fans immediate
walk-in access to the infield. BUSCH TICKETS AVAILABLE
</P>
<P>
   A number of Cup regulars are scheduled to double-up at TMS,
beginning their racing weekends in the NASCAR Busch Grand National
Albertson's 300 on April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative list of drivers running in both events is topped
by Mark Martin, two-time winner of the BGN race here and 1998
winner of the Cup event around the 1.5-mile quadoval. Martin, the
BGN series' all-time winner with 43, has won three of four Busch
events he has entered in his final season on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Others planning double duty at TMS are BGN points-leader Matt
Kenseth, former TMS Cup race winners Jeff Burton and Terry Labonte,
Jeff Gordon, Ward Burton, Michael Waltrip, Kenny Wallace, Steve
Park, Joe Nemechek, Kevin Lepage, Mike Skinner and Kenny Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway officials are planning to confine seating for the BGN
race to the 120,000-seat frontstretch grandstands, unless demand
dictates otherwise. Frontstretch tickets are on sale from $31 to
$62. BODINE RECUPERATING
</P>
<P>
   Former Daytona 500 champion Geoffrey Bodine is recuperating in
North Carolina from the injuries he suffered in a fiery crash
during the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series season-opener at the
Daytona International Speedway on Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's home and now it's just time,'' said Todd Bodine,
Geoffery's youngest brother. ``He still gets tired real easy. His
back and his wrist have to heal, and it's just time. Hopefully, it
won't be a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine, who turns 51 on April 18, suffered a concussion,
fractured back and fractured right wrist in a violent wreck down
the frontstretch that involved 13 trucks. Todd Bodine said his
brother's back specialist told him a return to the Winston Cup
Series as driver of the No. 60 Power Team Chevrolet Monte Carlo is
possible in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be back some time this year,'' Todd Bodine said, ``for
sure.'' JOHNSON REACHES 80
</P>
<P>
   Warren Johnson scored his 80th career Pro Stock victory during
the Mac Tools Gatornationals on Sunday, placing him within striking
distance of the National Hot Rod Association's hallowed all-time
victory record.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Pro Stock champion Bob Glidden holds the record with 85
victories. Johnson, driver of the GM Goodwrench Service Plus
Pontiac Firebird, has won at least five national events during
seven of the past nine seasons. The five-time and reigning class
champion ``slipped'' to four victories in 1994 and 1997. THE LAST
WORD
</P>
<P>
   ``This hasn't been the way we wanted to start the season. We've
run like junk. But we've got nobody to blame but ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kyle Petty, on his 29th-place position in Winston Cup points
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
