u s BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDWEST-HNS &LR;      03-23 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDWEST-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ If Tom Izzo and his players are right,
their run to the Final Four last year carries little relevance now.
It's all about what Michigan State accomplishes the rest of this
NCAA Tournament, starting tonight with Syracuse in the Midwest
Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten Conference champions, 28-7 and the No. 1 seed in the
region, meet fourth-seeded Syracuse (26-5) at 6:55 p.m., followed
by second-seeded Iowa State (31-4) and sixth-seeded UCLA (21-11).
The winners are matched Saturday for a berth in the Final Four next
week at Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo, in his fifth year as the Spartans' head coach after first
pleading for a job as a part-time Michigan State assistant for
three years, always runs scared. Perhaps his is the nature of most
coaches at a high-profile program, one that has surpassed Michigan
as the state's best.
</P>
<P>
   After a conference-opening loss to Wisconsin a year ago, the
Spartans won 15 straight Big Ten games and four consecutive NCAA
Tournament games before losing to Duke in the national semifinals
to end a 33-5 season. The experience and adversity of that season
do mean a lot, the Spartans agree, but it doesn't make reaching
heightened expectations any easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of feel lucky to survive,'' Izzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo's goal, of course, is to prevent a possible Palace uprising
by the Orangemen, who exceeded preseason expectations, then dipped
below more current ones after a 19-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to the Final Four (last year) is one more step,'' Izzo
said. ``It's a major advantage, knowing you lose and you go home.
No more games after that. Have your bad day and you're not
advancing.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo repeats his own feeling, one shared by many in his
profession, that the battle to reach the top is actually only half
the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder to deal with the pressure of success than the
pressure of failure,'' he said. ``I've been on both sides, and
that's what I have learned through the years. It's been such a
whirlwind, so many things to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Jud Heathcote, the Spartans' former head coach and Izzo's former
boss, had much the same demeanor that he now watches from afar in
Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tom loses a game,'' Heathcote said, ``he doesn't think he
will ever win another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State point guard Mateen Cleaves delivers much of the
same message in a somewhat different form. His advice to younger
teammates? ``Turn off the TV and don't read the papers and don't
watch your face on TV and stay humble.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves believes figuring out that Tournament learning curve can
only happen through experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, it's an advantage,'' he said, ``We've been here
before and it's not overwhelming. We're used to the media, the
police escorts.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves' preseason fractured foot should have cured the Spartans
of any inflated notions, even though they were 8-4 in those 12
games. There were losses to nationally ranked Texas in Puerto Rico
and at Arizona and Kentucky before a stunning 53-49 defeat at
Wright State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was begging coach to put me in the game so I could take some
shots,'' Cleaves said.
</P>
<P>
   After that stretch, even though Cleaves struggled with his
shooting (43 percent from the field), the Spartans went on to win
their third straight Big Ten regular-season championship and second
straight conference tournament title.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question who played the biggest role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mateen never takes days off,'' said Izzo. ``When that guy
leaves I'm going to find out if I can really coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, the Big Ten's all-time assists leader, and Jason Hart,
his counterpart at Syracuse, will be one of the game's most
interesting sidelights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't come down to a one-on-one,'' said Hart, who averages
6.4 assists to Cleaves' 7.5. ``The battle will be respected by
whichever can lead his team to a win. Nobody is going to back
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, who has 165 assists to 81 turnovers, said of Hart, ``We
both run our team. He does a great job of getting guys open,
getting them easier shots, and he's great in transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Spartans could play in the Sweet 16 about 75 miles
from their campus, they had to overcome a six-point, second-half
deficit against Utah last week. Cleaves made three 3-pointers
during a 27-7 rally that gave Michigan State control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to stay calm and keep plugging away,'' said
Cleaves. ``That's the kind of team we are.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
