<HEADLINE>
WOODS' DOMINATION HAS FOES WAVING WHITE FLAG, MONTGOMERIE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Gentlemen, start your white flags.
</P>
<P>
   A surrender mentality is gripping the PGA Tour whenever Tiger
Woods' name surfaces on the leader board, say competitors who will
tee off in today's opening round of The Players Championship. Colin
Montgomerie, the European Tour's leading money winner the past
seven seasons, said he sensed it last week after the opening round
of the Bay Hill Classic, when Woods shot a 69 to emerge one stroke
off the pace with 54 holes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 24, went on to win by four strokes, capturing his seventh
title in his past 10 tour events. Woods has placed second twice and
has not finished below 18th during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods starts quickly today at the TPC at Sawgrass,
Montgomerie said peers likely will retreat into their shells once
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first round last week, when Tiger shot 69 on a windy
day, I think the view in the locker room, without saying it aloud,
was the tournament was finished. It was a matter of, `Who is going
to finish second?,' '' said Montgomerie, 36. ``It shall be very
interesting \Rtoday\S to find out what he is doing. ... The first
round is very important, especially when everyone is watching one
particular score. This is all very new, this complete dominance by
one player. We have never had someone as dominant as Tiger. Not in
my career, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt defeated one round into the Bay Hill event,
Montgomerie said: ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods joined other players yesterday in expressing surprise
about Montgomerie's candid comments. Hal Sutton said Montgomerie
must have been ``going in a different locker room than I was going
in'' last week in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either that, or he wasn't close to my locker,'' said Sutton,
the No. 14 player on the season money list.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested Montgomerie might be closer to the truth in his
assessment of Woods than most peers would prefer to admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty evident right now that if he is playing well
starting the week, that he is going to be ... the guy to beat,''
Jim Furyk said. ``No one has dominated the way he has in a long
time. Maybe \RJack\S Nicklaus.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III, the player Woods defeated in Sunday's final
round, conceded that frustrations are mounting as Woods' hot streak
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody starts beating you, you start to think, `Can I beat
him?,' '' Love said. ``And he's beating the whole tour, so I'm not
the only one. He thrives on that. ... He's driving this tour right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie said players who deny feelings of inadequacy when
compared to Woods, at this stage, ``are kidding you ... and they
are kidding themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie said Woods ``seems to'' have an ability to reach a
higher gear in crunch time that peers can't touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to have everything. There is no weakness,''
Montgomerie said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he appreciated Montgomerie's kudos, but did not
understand the sentiment about feeling out of a tournament after 18
holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That surprises me, because there's three rounds left,'' Woods
said. ``I guess others can get intimidated. I don't know if I'd
ever feel that way.'' \Nsubheds:Sutton eyes Colonial return Hal
Sutton, a member of the 1999 U.S. Ryder Cup team who last competed
at the MasterCard Colonial in 1994, said yesterday there is ``a
darn good chance'' he'll return to Fort Worth this season. The past
two years, Sutton has used that week to go on a family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get back to Fort Worth. Nothing is definite, but
I'm leaning that way,'' said Sutton, who has yet to make an
official commitment to the event. \Nsubheds:Finchem to review
policy PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem said yesterday he would
review the tour's policy on granting releases for players to
compete in European Tour events ``within the next two or three
weeks, to see if there's a problem'' in relation to Colonial week
(May 18-21).
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, tour players Tiger Woods, Nick Price, Jesper Parnevik
and Sergio Garcia have committed to compete in the Deutsche
Bank-SAP Open, a European event in Hamburg, Germany, with the same
playing dates as Colonial. Of that group, Parnevik and Garcia are
Europeans who compete on both tours. Woods is the defending
champion. In 1999, five high-profile players accepted six-figure
appearance fees to compete in the German event in lieu of Colonial,
causing Finchem to say he would consider limiting releases in
future years.
</P>
<P>
   As of yesterday, Finchem said: ``I haven't specifically looked
at \RColonial\S week at this point.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly Tim Finchem
said no decision will be made until summer, at the earliest, on
whether the PGA Tour will file an appeal with the U.S. Supreme
Court in the right-to-ride lawsuit involving disabled golfer Casey
Martin. Martin, 27, is permitted to use a golf cart during
competition under the Americans With Disabilities Act. If the tour
appeals, Finchem said, ``the odds are against it being heard,
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussions are ongoing about moving The Players Championship to
a May date, beginning next season. For the past decade, Finchem
said the subject has surfaced every time television agreements come
up for renewal, but the event has yet to shift from its March
window and might remain there. The existing TV agreements will be
renewed in the fall, but Finchem said he ``would not speculate'' on
the possibility of the TPC shifting dates.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
