<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-DAVIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TEACHER UNION, DAVIS SPLIT ON PUPIL SPENDING  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ A week before debate on Gov. Gray Davis' education
plan begins in earnest, the head of California's largest teachers
union said Wednesday there is a growing rift with the governor over
education policy.
</P>
<P>
   The split is one reason the California Teachers Association is
moving ahead with a November ballot measure that would raise the
state's per pupil spending to the national average, a proposal the
governor is against.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a debate I think California needs to have,'' Wayne
Johnson, president of the 300,000-member teachers association, said
in an interview. ``Do we want quality education, and are we willing
to pay for it at at least the national average. (Davis') philosophy
is that he wants above-average test scores with below-average
funding.''
</P>
<P>
   California spends $6,045 per pupil, a number Davis has proposed
raising to $6,313. The national average was $7,583 in the 1999-2000
school year.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between Davis and the politically powerful union
_ which holds great sway in the Democratic Legislature _ may signal
rough roads ahead for Davis' major education initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a serious lack of communication between the governor
and the education community,'' said Johnson, who met with Davis for
two hours last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Davis is sponsoring legislation that includes
creating merit scholarships, providing advance placement classes in
all schools and recruiting more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In a time when the state is expected to draw at least $4.2
billion more into its coffers than originally expected, Davis drew
pleas last week from school administrators who are looking for more
money with fewer strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping the legislative process will bring some
resolution to some differences,'' Johnson said. ``We will be a lot
stronger in our opposition than last time around.''
</P>
<P>
   San Rafael Democrat Kerry Mazzoni, chair of the Assembly
Education Committee said Davis' education proposals are ``as
controversial if not more controversial'' than last year's.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bustamante, Davis' spokesman, said he does not
understand how anyone can disagree with increased student
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor intends to build on last year's
accomplishments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the latest breakdown came over Davis' failure to
come through on pledged support for Proposition 26, an attempt to
lower the voting threshold for school bonds from a two-thirds
majority to a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't help at all for 26,'' Johnson said. ``He tries to
say we didn't ask, but we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he asked Davis personally to help, suggesting a
mention in the State of the State address. ``We waited,'' Johnson
said. ``When he didn't mention it in the State of the State, we
decided he didn't want to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said no propositions were granted mention in the
State of the State but said the governor did follow through on
support for the school bond initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were able to outspend the opposition 23 to 1, there is
not any reason they should lose,'' Bustamante said. ``To not
include the governor and then turn around and try to find a
scapegoat for their loss is rather poor form.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Davis told him that he would support a new
initiative only if the vote threshold was set at 60 percent and if
his people would be in charge of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said CTA and other Proposition 26 supporters have not
decided if they want to move ahead with a new campaign, or if they
are willing to accept Davis' demands.
</P>
<P>
   The CTA has not yet taken a position on Davis' latest education
reforms, Johnson said, adding that they did not come up at last
week's meeting. But the CTA is not going to be as willing to
cooperate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his education reform package last year, we thought some of
those ideas were not very good,'' he said. ``And on other ideas he
put forth, he didn't put forward enough money to make them work.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose group has supported Davis from the beginning,
said the group tried to get along with the governor despite
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting a significantly different relationship,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
