<HEADER>
A5478 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-SOFTMONEY-FEINSTEIN-S     03-23 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTMONEY-FEINSTEIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FEINSTEIN'S BILL TAKES AIM AT `SOFT MONEY'  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two days after Arizona Sen. John McCain returned to
Washington from his failed quest for the GOP presidential
nomination, Sen. Dianne Feinstein picked up his mantle of campaign
finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The California Democrat, who is making her own re-election bid
this year against South Bay Rep. Tom Campbell, introduced
legislation Wednesday that would raise individual campaign
contribution limits from $1,000 to $3,000, in return for banning
the use of ``soft money'' now used by parties in unlimited amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein also would impose disclosure requirements on the
so-called ``issue advocacy'' advertising during campaigns by
outside interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she wants to ``break the gridlock'' on campaign
finance reform because the odds of passing McCain's original bill,
co-sponsored by Wisconsin Democrat Russ Feingold, are virtually
nil.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold bill would not raise the individual
contribution limit, but would ban soft money and codify
restrictions on using union dues for political campaigns without
the consent of union members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have voted for versions of the McCain-Feingold campaign
finance reform legislation at least six times in the past four
years, and I continue to support passage of that bill,'' Feinstein
told the Senate. ``I am concerned, however, that this legislation
might not come up for a vote again in this Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he had ``nothing but support'' for Feinstein's
move. Campbell himself helped lead a renegade group of moderate
House Republicans who twice secured House passage of an even
tougher bill than Feinstein now proposes.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein's increase in the individual contribution limit _
something she has not advocated in the past _ is designed to entice
support from some Republicans who succeeded in killing the
McCain-Feingold measure on the ground that it would
unconstitutionally limit free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The huge amounts of time that federal elected officials spend
``dialing for dollars'' are often blamed on the $1,000 limit,
because it forces candidates to raise relatively small sums from
vast numbers of people.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said that in the 29 years since the limit was
established, inflation has shrunk the value of $1,000 to just $328.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the small contributions to an individual's campaign,
I think, that Americans view as corrupting,'' Feinstein said.
``It's the large checks of $100,000, $250,000 and $1 million or
more to parties that create this appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Wertheimer, former president of Common Cause, a leading
advocacy group for campaign finance reform, who now leads a similar
group called Democracy 21, suggested that Feinstein's bill only
muddies the waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain-Feingold is the reform bill that people should be
fighting to enact,'' Wertheimer said, since the two senators ``have
already identified themselves as leaders on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether raising the individual contribution limit will be enough
to break down GOP opposition to the total ban on ``soft money''
that Feinstein adopts from the original McCain-Feingold plan
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soft money'' consists of funds raised outside federal
contribution limits _ mainly from corporations, labor unions and
wealthy individuals _ for the purpose of ``party-building''
activities such as voter registration drives, but which are now
seen as a big loophole in campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties increasingly have turned to soft money to finance
elections; the money is often raised and indirectly controlled by
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore raised large
amounts of soft money in their 1996 re-election bid, nearly
bringing on an independent counsel investigation. Gore, now running
for the Democratic nomination, has since called his 1996
fund-raising activities a ``mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein also would impose disclosure requirements on so-called
``issue-advocacy'' advertising, which typically supports a
candidate without directly instructing voters how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Such ads are not currently limited. Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
running for the GOP presidential nomination, drew criticism last
month when a wealthy Texas supporter ran independent pro-Bush ads
during New York's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein would require any expenditures over $10,000 on such
ads, or any individual contributions over $3,000 to groups running
such ads, to be reported to the Federal Election Commission within
48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein's measure will be competing against a bill by Nebraska
Republican Chuck Hagel, with two Democratic co-sponsors, that would
limit, rather than ban, soft-money contributions to the national
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Reform advocates have blasted the Hagel bill as offering a
gigantic loophole to state and local parties that would still be
allowed to raise unlimited amounts of soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University Law School Dean Kathleen M. Sullivan and Ira
Glasser, executive director of the American Civil Liberties Union,
both testified that limits on ``issue advocacy'' endanger free
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said regulation of political money ``does implicate
free speech principles at the heart of the First Amendment,
contrary to the reformers' assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Existing campaign finance laws have created such anomalies,
Glasser said, as allowing wealthy individuals such as Ross Perot or
Feinstein's 1994 Senate opponent, Michael Huffington, to spend
unlimited amounts on campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if an equally wealthy donor wants to enable Colin Powell
to run against Perot, he commits a crime,'' Glasser said. ``This
should not be a result anyone would support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
