<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BARBARY TOAST MUST USE VODKA  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ That Hugh ``Windfall'' McColl, man, he must be
 &UR; good. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I was impressed when I heard that the CEO of BofA was awarded
$76 million in cash and prizes for his work last year (he ran the
bank  &UR; and  &LR; discovered a cure for jock itch).
</P>
<P>
   Then I got the  &UR; real  &LR; story. Diane Shields, a worried BofA
customer, showed me the front-page teaser headline in the Tuesday
home-delivery edition of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``BofA chief's '99 pay: $76 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   That's serious coinage.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the ``billion'' was a typo. Million, billion,
godzillion _ the way the Hearst folk are throwing money around,
what's the diff?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'VE WANTED to come here all my life,'' President Clinton said
at the Taj Mahal.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what this presidency has been all about _ fulfilling
Bill's fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   TWINKIE SHORTAGE leaves East Coast with frazzled nerves, said
the news story.
</P>
<P>
   To which folks in the Bay Area said, ``Whaaat?''
</P>
<P>
   Norm Howard of KQED was a bit more eloquent: ``A shortage of
Twinkies ought to be producing greater tranquility, even a
reduction in violent crime. In accordance with Dr. Blinder's
theory, the number of premeditated double murders of elected
officials, in particular, ought to be plummeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin Blinder was the creator of the ``Twinkie Defense'' in
the murder trial of Dan White.
</P>
<P>
   One other way of looking at that news story: There's a shortage
of Twinkies on the East Coast because they're all out here in the
Bay Area making zillions with Internet startups.
</P>
<P>
   HORS D'OEUVRE at the ``Caenfetti'' party Tuesday night at Wilkes
Bashford, celebrating a new musical about S.F. history from Herb's
POV, included: Barbary Toast, Baghdad by the Beef, Son of a Pun
Asparagus, and Strange de Jim Flavored Swordfish.
</P>
<P>
   The latter tastes best when lightly spritzed with Wilkes
cologne.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT TIME THEY'LL call Webvan.com:
</P>
<P>
   Danny Newhoff, 13, was undergoing leg surgery at Mt. Diablo
Medical Center in Concord last week. Once Danny had been knocked
out (as they say in the medical world), the doctor realized that a
peg to be inserted in the ankle was not going to be the right size.
</P>
<P>
   A peg hunt ensued, and the right one was located at the Stanford
Medical Center. ``Rush it over,'' Stanford was told.
</P>
<P>
   So someone at Stanford hailed a taxi, gave the cabbie the
package and instructions something like, ``Rush this to Mt.
Diablo!''
</P>
<P>
   And the cabbie did. He drove like a madman to the summit of Mt.
Diablo.
</P>
<P>
   From up there you can see the hospital, but it's a 40-minute
drive away.
</P>
<P>
   Cabbie finally made the delivery, doctor pegged the ankle, Danny
is doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   THE DOWNFALL of the Mansions Hotel in Pacific Heights might be
traced to the fateful moment 20 years ago when hotel owner Bob
Pritikin said, ``F_ you, Mrs. Bloomfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Pritikin built a dilapidated rooming house on Sacramento Street
into an elegant and quirky hotel that hosted JFK Jr., Barbra
Streisand, Liberace and Andrei Sakarov, though not all in the same
room at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   But Pritikin rubbed the right people the wrong way. He fell into
a two-decade battle with Anne Bloomfield and her
very-well-connected group of friends and neighbors, who didn't want
his hotel in their exclusive neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Long story short: He wound up with the city suing him for $15
million per year and calling his swishy hotel ``Dangerous to human
life'' because of what his attorney, Angela Alioto, says is,
basically, ``some peeling paint in the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the hotel was life-threatening,'' Alioto says, ``why didn't
they close him down? The city Planning Department held its
Christmas party there two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Pritikin finally cried uncle. He closed the place and is holding
the world's most elegant garage sale this Friday-Sunday (2220
Sacramento St.).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic,'' Pritikin says, ``that the very day I finally
was forced to sell, their chief crusader died. I wonder if she's in
heaven now, looking for code violations.''
</P>
<P>
   GO DODGERS. That's what the big signs all over town say.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get riled, Giants' fans. It's obviously a cute ad
campaign, and when everyone gets angry, the ad people will paint
``to hell'' in the ap- &QL; 
propriate spot on the signs, or ``and take your smog with you.''
</P>
<P>
   S.F. GOES HOLLYWOOD: Jennifer Lopez and Matthew McConaughey will
be all over City Hall tomorrow and next Tuesday, filming scenes
from ``The Wedding Planner.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the tumult was great over the problems caused by the
filming of Robin Williams' ``Bicentennial Man'' last year in the
supervisors' chambers, the Film Commission sent a four-page memo to
the supervisors and mayor, saying, essentially, ``Don't sweat the
Hall stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to ``Wedding'' producers: The supes are prima donnas; give
'em each a cameo role and they won't make a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``ON VACATION'' is the tag line they put where your column
usually is, and it conjures images of a lazy lout lounging poolside
somewhere, and sometimes that's how it is.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes not. The guy at the other paper, whom I've not
met, is on vacation, but the kind you never want to take, when
personal tragedy comes knocking. Best wishes, old sport.
</P>
<P>
   A MUNI BUS, as reported here, almost ran over Holly Krassner
just after she'd spent an entire day doing free PR work for Muni.
</P>
<P>
   Holly, young and nimble, dived across the pavement, suffering
only minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The story inspired Gar Smith of the Earth Island Journal to
create a new slogan for Muni: ``With friends like us, who needs
enemas?''
</P>
</TEXT>
