<SLUG> BC-BKC-BRASWL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRASWELL AWAITS WORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Bobby Braswell is still the men's basketball
coach at Cal State Northridge. But that could change.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell is one of three finalists for the Oregon State job and
a decision by OSU athletic director Mitch Barnhart is expected
within the next couple of days, possibly as early as today.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell, Colorado State coach Ritchie McKay and Milwaukee Bucks
assistant Don Newman are believed to be the front runners for the
position, vacated after the firing of fourth-year coach Eddie
Payne.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell, who interviewed for the job last week, said Wednesday
night that he preferred not to comment on his status.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second consecutive year Braswell, 37, has been
considered for a Pac-10 job. A year ago, he was a finalist at
Washington State. He has one year left on his CSUN contract that
pays him a base salary of $92,700.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell, who inherited a CSUN program that had only seven wins
in 1995-96, has a 65-53 record in four seasons. Northridge was
20-10 and made the Big Sky tournament championship game this past
year, losing to Northern Arizona in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge should have its strongest team next year, with
starters Brian Heinle, Markus Carr, Jeff Parris and Carl Holmes
returning. Five of the team's top seven scorers are coming back.
And John Burrell, the Highland High of Palmdale graduate who led
Nevada in scoring last season, also becomes eligible after
transferring to CSUN last year.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking over the Matadors, Braswell was an assistant for
four years at Oregon, and his West Coast recruiting ties make him a
strong candidate for the position in Corvallis.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old McKay, who Oregon papers say is the No. 1
candidate, was 37-23 in two seasons at CSU. He has four years left
on a contract that paid him $250,000 per year. He coached at
Portland State from 1996-98 and was 26-29. Three of those losses
came against Braswell and CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart interviewed McKay over the weekend but has been
unavailable for comment. His secretary said he was on an
out-of-town recruiting trip.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the three finalists, also interviewing for the
job have been Boston Celtics assistant Lester Conner, a former All-
America guard at OSU, USF coach Phil Mathews and Arizona assistant
Jay John.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
