<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA-ASSESS (New Delhi, India) _ President Clinton,
master of the televised town hall meeting, brought his powers of
empathy and persuasion Wednesday to India's Parliament House, where
often is heard an anti-American word. In the time it took him to
deliver his speech, he managed to entertain, flatter and inspire
much of this vast country's political leadership, even as he
tactfully told them things they would rather not hear _ for
example, that the United States still thinks India's 1998 decision
to test nuclear weapons has taken the country in the wrong
direction. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOONSHINE-TECH (Rocky Mount, Va.) _ Grinning seditiously, a
prominent citizen of this Blue Ridge foothills town takes from his
refrigerator an illegal gift from a moonshiner friend: a syrupy red
liquor in a quart jar packed with grapelike damsonberries. He
offers a taste to his visitor. It is sweet, silky brandy. To a
casual visitor, it all seems a quaint act of hospitality
appropriate to a town that likes to boast of being ``the moonshine
capital of the world.'' But to a task force of state and federal
agents, this area's illicit whiskeys are the work of big-time
criminals _ a new generation of moonshiners who in many cases have
transformed the woodsmen's stills of legend into efficient
distilleries capable of producing thousands of gallons of liquor a
week. Moonshine whiskey, mass-produced with little attention to
health or safety, is growing as a product of interstate commerce.
By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES-DRUG (Undated) _ Rezulin, the diabetes drug that
the FDA pulled from the market Wednesday, is the fourth of 39 drugs
approved in 1997 that the agency later withdrew. We look at
critics' accusations that changes in the agency's drug approval
policies are allowing dangerous medications to reach the
marketplace. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-IRISH-ANCESTORS (Undated) _ For any observer of last week's
St. Patrick's day parade who wondered where all those Irishmen came
from, science has provided an unexpected answer: from Spain. Using
ancient Irish surnames and DNA analysis, researchers at Trinity
College in Dublin have developed evidence that Irish men in
Connaught, a western province of Ireland, are almost all descended
from an ancestral population that inhabited Ireland before the
invention of agriculture. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
