<P>
   SIMPLE-LIFE-ROBOT (New York) _ How I wish I could say that I am
mowing the lawn while drinking my morning coffee. The trouble is, I
forgot to make the coffee, and also, the mower is doing all the
work here _ the rolling forward, the backing up, the turn-on-a-dime
maneuvering over in the corner by the London plane tree. And, yes,
the grass-cutting. All I am doing is watching a $700 robot whose
one purpose in life is to mow lawns. It is not beeping like R2D2 of
``Star Wars'' or talking like Hal, the maniacal star of ``2001: A
Space Odyssey,'' but its circuit-board brain does know things I do
not: Which way is north, for example. By James Barron.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-RUGS (New York) _ The 13-year-old import embargo on all
Iranian rugs was lifted this week, but that doesn't excite anyone
at Bloomingdales, which never missed carpets from Iran anyway.
``Embargo?'' says a salesman, referring to an open secret at
department stores countrywide: Smuggled carpets from Iran have been
pouring into the country all along, mainly from Canada, with bogus
paperwork to pass customs. By Christie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   CONRAD-PENTHOUSE (Hollywood) March 21 _ Penthouse life is not
what one normally associates with Southern California, land of the
rambling ranch and the gated compound. But if you were to imagine
someone embracing the sun-washed, sweeping views atop a West
Hollywood fake chateau, that person might well be Conrad L. Hall.
The man knows a thing or two about light. Hall is expected to take
home his second Academy Award on Sunday for his cinematography on
``American Beauty,'' the acidly funny dissection of dysfunctional
suburban America. It will have been 31 years since Hall won his
first Oscar for ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.'' By Rick
Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-HOUSES (Undated) _ People who live in glass houses are few
and far between. Although dazzling in photographs, the first glass
houses by Mies van der Rohe and Philip Johnson have been remarkably
tricky to emulate. In reality, they were hidden from prying eyes on
secluded country estates, like precious glass gems. That was 50
years ago. Recently, the privacy problem was campilycq dramatized
at a glass house on a busy Tokyo corner. There, the owners hung
full-length draperies all around _ on the outside. Surely, there
must be some middle ground. Lorcan O'Herlihy, an architect who
practices in the Culver City section of Los Angeles, has
successfully found a way to build glass houses that city dwellers
can live in. O'Herlihy's solution is stunningly simple. He uses
clear glass in those places where you want to see out, and
translucent glass in places where you don't. By Sydney LeBlanc.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Howto drawing has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
