<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTERS MIGHT GET SOME REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A moderately tough home stretch might not allow
it, but Los Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson is hoping to ratchet
down the minutes of his starters in the final few weeks of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen games remain after Wednesday night's home game against
the Golden State Warriors, and Jackson would prefer to use the
entire 12-man roster as the Lakers close out the regular season and
prepare for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we don't get out of sync doing that,'' he said.
``If we get out of sync in any possible way, then we've got to get
back to what does get us the wins and how we play to do it. It'd be
nice if you could say, well, you put together a good game in the
first three quarters, then you can rest players in the fourth
quarter, but that doesn't always happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has relied heavily on Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant
and to a lesser extent, Glen Rice. At the other end of the bench,
he's used rookie swingman Devean George and backup centers Travis
Knight and John Salley sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers entered Wednesday's game with a seemingly
insurmountable five-game lead over Portland, giving them plenty of
room for error. But they also play 10 of their last 13 games
against playoff teams, so the reserves will have to earn their time
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see how they produce,'' Jackson said. ``The
other night (at Miami), everybody had goose eggs off the bench
except for Robert (Horry), and he played a lot of minutes and had a
big shot down the stretch. But it was tough for our bench the other
night, and they felt the fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   __ On guards: Jackson has floated the possibility of giving Ron
Harper an extended rest by placing him on the injured list but said
he's leaving that decision to his veteran guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want him to be the determinator,'' Jackson said.
``He's been the guy that's gone through this process before with
us, and he knows the values of it and what he can get out of it and
if it's worth it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper, who underwent arthroscopic surgery on his right knee
last summer, was coy about his status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, I could really use some days off. I need that (golf)
swing work, so I can grip that swing right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harper wouldn't say how his legs are holding up but said he
would speak with Jackson today about the possibility of taking time
off to recharge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could play 82 games if I was called upon 82 games.
But since we have a nice comfortable five games (lead in the
standings), I think I can take some time off. It won't hurt
nobody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
