<SLUG> BC-BKC-SMU-SUSPENSIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMU SUSPENDS TWO BASKETBALL PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMU basketball players Jeryl Sasser and Renaldo Bratton were
indefinitely suspended from the team yesterday for violating team
rules.
</P>
<P>
   The university announced the suspensions in a news release last
night, without naming the players, and attributed the suspensions
to ``inappropriate and disruptive behavior involving a few
students'' in the early morning hours of March 10 at hotel in
Fresno, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report released by the Fresno Police Department,
Sasser and Bratton, both juniors, were questioned about incidents
that took place in their hotel room at a party that included
members of the SMU basketball team and the SMU spirit squad.
</P>
<P>
   The SMU basketball team was in Fresno competing in the Western
Athletic Conference tournament, where it lost its first-round game
against Hawaii on March 9. The team was staying at the Radisson
Hotel in downtown Fresno and, according to the police report,
several members of the team and the spirit squad spent the hours
after the loss drinking at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser and Bratton both remained on the team as SMU competed in
the National Invitation Tournament against Southwest Missouri State
last Thursday. SMU spokesman Bob Wright said the school did not
take action against any players before the NIT game because ``the
police report \Rreceived Tuesday by SMU\S contained information not
given to us previously.'' SMU lost the game, ending its season.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser, a 6-foot-6 guard, was named first-team all-WAC and led
SMU in scoring. Bratton, a 6-foot guard, played a reserve role.
</P>
<P>
   Three members of the spirit squad, spirit coordinator Darren
McCoy, an SMU employee and sophomore basketball player DeWayne
Floyd were also interviewed by police, who responded to a call from
a friend of a spirit-team member.
</P>
<P>
   Police informed SMU coach Mike Dement and SMU athletic director
Jim Copeland in the early morning hours about their investigation.
Copeland and Dement didn't return calls to the /Star-Telegram/
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Fresno Police Department spent more than] a week gathering
information regarding the events surrounding the party at the
Radisson. Lt. John Fries said any further criminal investigation on
the Fresno police's part is unlikely because the parties involved
in the report live in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   SMU, however, has launched its own investigation of possible
violations of the university code of conduct during a
school-sponsored trip. The student affairs office has indefinitely
suspended two members of the spirit squad, pending the findings of
the school investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're handling it the same way we would handle any other
potential violation of student conduct,'' said Jim Caswell, SMU
vice president of student affairs. ``There needs to be some
determination of university violations and what sort of response we
need to pursue from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among several issues being investigated by SMU are the many
documented instances of underage drinking in the police report.
Bratton and the three members of the spirit squad are 20 years old
and the report includes instances of a 21-year-old player giving
vodka to a 20-year-old member of the spirit squad.
</P>
<P>
   Caswell said the university also plans to investigate the role
of McCoy, who coached the spirit squad. McCoy, 22, voluntarily
resigned from SMU in the early stages of the investigation last
week. The police noted that McCoy had ``bloodshot watery eyes, a
strong odor of alcohol'' and said he ``attempted to obstruct police
questioning of one of the spirit members.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, that member of the spirit squad was
being questioned about her concerns of possible illegal behavior at
the party. Sgt. Tim McFadden of the Fresno police said ``there
appeared to be a lot of pressure put on her not to press charges.''
In the report the spirit-squad member said she was worried about
her future at SMU and with the spirit squad should she pursue
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit-team member said yesterday that her lawyers told her
not to comment. Caswell said he hopes to have the school
investigation finished next week.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
