<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5504 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-23 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ On a walking tour of what's left of
Bracketville, this is the one neighborhood where you don't want to
stand on a corner looking like a tourist who got off at the wrong
bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   Wham!
</P>
<P>
   Top-seeded Michigan State's smothering defense could land on
your head.
</P>
<P>
   Bam!
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 seed Iowa State could hit you right in the kisser with the
heavy dose of heavyweight forward Marcus Fizer.
</P>
<P>
   Slam!
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 seed Syracuse could send any shot you try right back into
your face, compliments of rejection machine/center Etan Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Jam!
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 seed UCLA could have guard JaRon Rush sail in from out of
the blue to rattle your rims with any number of slick moves, dunk
you very much.
</P>
<P>
   No room at the inn for Cinderella here. Uh-uh. No, sir. Not
unless she's wearing steel-toed boots and has the kind of right
cross that could stand up to at least Leila Ali.
</P>
<P>
   All across America this week, in the mourning after Wisconsin
beating Arizona and Seton Hall knocking off Temple and North
Carolina nailing Stanford, the same loser's lament could be heard
in offices everywhere, just before the NCAA Tournament brackets hit
the shredder: ``At least I got the Midwest right.''
</P>
<P>
   To quote some sage thinkers of our modern times: Duh.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of limited scholarships and parity and Gonzaga, the
Midwest Regional is where the prognosticationally challenged of us
have run for cover and reassurance that we are not the village
idiots of Bracketville.
</P>
<P>
   This is the place where the 12-step recovery program for fallen
hoop pickers starts with an open proclamation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, I'm Dickie V., and I don't know what happened to St.
John's, bay-bee!''
</P>
<P>
   Then it builds you back up by letting you guess from which
direction the sun will rise tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   This is the part of the bracket that even the lamest of us were
able to pick with our eyes closed.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, Iowa State, Syracuse and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so No. 3 Maryland did trip in front of UCLA to break up a
clean sweep by the top seeds. But if you've been paying attention
to the Bruins since the sophomore Rush won his eligibility battle
with the NCAA, you'd have realized this is an entirely different
UCLA team than the one that was so inconsistent all year.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that the Midwest Regional is being contested at
the Palace, because every team here possesses the talent to be
king.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest is Mateen Cleaves, Morris Peterson and Charlie Bell,
the so-called ``Flintstones'' of Michigan State, the team that lost
a hard-fought battle in the national semifinals last season and
seems to be more determined, more committed this time around.
Cleaves gets so much of the notoriety as the point guard, but the
all-around performer Peterson is the one who has so many NBA scouts
champing at the bit.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans of coach Tom Izzo have the kind of senior
leadership that can get them through the tight games, perhaps the
nation's best defense and the added benefit of playing before a
home crowd this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest is the amazing tale of Iowa State, picked to finish
last in the Big 12 but now hurtling along as one of the remaining
Tournament favorites thanks to Fizer. He left the inner-city
problems of Detroit as a young teen, sulked when the coach (Tim
Floyd) who recruited him left to join the Chicago Bulls, and now
returns to the old neighborhood as a sculpted (6-8, 265 pounds),
motivated, model performer.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest is perennial power Syracuse, which rolled to a 19-0
start, then suddenly stumbled with three losses in the span of five
games that had everybody asking questions. The Orangemen have been
close to the mountaintop so many times, but they never plant the
flag as coach Jim Boeheim whines about something.
</P>
<P>
   But in tonight's showdown with the vise grip of Michigan State,
Syracuse will have defense of its own in the 6-9 block of granite
Thomas, who is the Big East's two-time defensive player of the year
and ranks seventh on the NCAA all-time list with 422 blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest is UCLA, a month ago on the verge of getting coach
Steve Lavin fired and now hotter than the inside of a microwave
oven for this meeting with Iowa State. The Bruins have won eight in
a row overall and have taken a huge step up with Rush in the
lineup. They have talent and the swagger to go all the way. Just
like the rest.
</P>
<P>
   In the bombed-out shell of Bracketville, this is where the big
boys still live.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 0143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
