<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCLAADV-LADN-(SLA     03-23 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLAADV-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH SCHEDULE READIED BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ UCLA's schedule makers knew their
1999-2000 creation would be challenging. They knew the early-season
complaints would morph into late-season praise. But they never
expected this.
</P>
<P>
   They never expected it to rank among the nation's top-five late
in the season.
</P>
<P>
   They never expected seven of the 12 nonconference foes to make
the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And they never expected four to make the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, 25 percent of the tournament survivors played UCLA
this season: Purdue, North Carolina, Syracuse and Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing preps teams for March Madness like grueling schedules,
brutal road trips and competition in domed stadiums. Syracuse, in
February, qualifies on all counts, since success isn't as important
as experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Vitale and a lot of people said at the beginning of the
season that we didn't have a good schedule, but we've shown how
good it is,'' Bruins forward Rico Hines said on the eve of
tonight's Sweet 16 showdown against Iowa State. ``It's helped us a
lot. It was great preparation for the tournament. Look at how many
teams we played are still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look so tough four months ago. The Bruins opened with
Fairfield, Iona and Morgan State. Although Iona would later win the
Metro Atlantic Conference _ and lose to Maryland in the first round
_ the trio did nothing for UCLA's early-season power rating, which
is primarily based on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But the lineup got progressively tougher.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-December, the Bruins played Gonzaga, their first quality
opponent, and lost by 16 points in Pauley Pavilion in one of their
worst performances of the year. Gonzaga would win the West Coast
Conference and reach the Sweet 16 for the second year in a row.
What convinced UCLA to schedule the 'Zags?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always looking for teams we can play without having to
give them a return game,'' said Marc Dellins, UCLA's
media-relations director who doubles as the schedule coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of Pepperdine, which actually filled three
requirements: The Waves are local, and UCLA tries to schedule at
least one Southern California team each year; they did not require
a return game; and, at the time, they were coached by former UCLA
assistant Lorenzo Romar, who's now at Saint Louis.
</P>
<P>
   That the Waves made the NCAA Tournament as an at-large candidate
was an unexpected power-ratings bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also played tournament-bound DePaul and Purdue in the
first of two-year contracts (UCLA will visit both schools next
season).
</P>
<P>
   Then, in January and February, after most teams had finished
their nonconference schedules, the Bruins played at North Carolina
and Syracuse. The matchups were ideal tournament preparation _
high-caliber opponents, long road trips, spacious arenas that
duplicate the shooting conditions usually found in tournament
games.
</P>
<P>
   Add four games against eventual No. 1 seeds Stanford and
Arizona, and by Selection Sunday, the Bruins' once-weak schedule
packed a wallop.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were bashing at the start, but they didn't understand
that by the end it would be one of the toughest in the nation,''
said forward Jason Kapono. ``Playing it, and going through that
losing stretch like we did, really helped the team. It made us see
what we had to change to start winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect more of the same next year, when the Bruins play North
Carolina, Villanova, DePaul, Purdue, Georgia Tech (in the Wooden
Classic) and two games in the Coaches vs. Cancer tournament. St.
John's, Kentucky and Kansas are the other participants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5506 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PET-FEES-LADN     03-23 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PET-FEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. ALTERS PET FEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hoping to collar what one official called a
``crisis of epic proportions,'' the Los Angeles City Council on
Wednesday approved a series of rules and higher fees for unaltered
pets and breeder permits that are among the toughest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters expressed hope the new ordinance will reduce the
number of dogs roaming wild through city streets and dogs that are
euthanized.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure, which will be considered for final approval
next week, licenses would remain at $10 for all altered dogs. Dogs
not spayed or neutered will cost $100 a year and breeders will see
their permit go from $50 to $100, plus additional fees for any
unaltered animals in their possession.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents _ primarily breeders _ say the city already does a
poor job of enforcing its pet ordinances and the tough new rules
will lead even more people to break the law because they won't be
able to pay the higher fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we face a problem of too many stray dogs
and there are too many stray dogs and cats,'' said Charles Ober, an
opponent of the fee hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this will not work. It has been an abject failure in other
areas of the country where it has been tried and has been dropped.
Los Angeles has had success with its current programs. We should
let it try to work a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The council voted 10-3, with members saying they feel the
crackdown is needed to reduce the number of euthanized and stray
dogs. During the past fiscal year, the city's six animal shelters
received more than 46,000 dogs and 19,000 cats and about 70 percent
of those were euthanized. About 44,000 stray dogs are believed to
be wandering the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also requires the owners of unaltered cats to keep
their pets indoors as a way to reduce the feral cat population.
Cats are not licensed in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg, who recently completed a
successful campaign for the Democratic nomination for Assembly,
spoke firsthand of the city's stray dog problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you how bad the problem is,'' Goldberg said.
``Everywhere I went, I was chased through many city streets _ and
by well-groomed dogs as well as strays. I carried dog bones
everywhere I went. We have a huge stray and unowned- dog problem
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal Services Director Dan Knapp said the fees were set as an
incentive to get people to alter their pets. The cost of the
operation for most animals is less than $100, and the city also is
offering vouchers and free spay and neutering for low-income pet
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, who had proposed some type of
action last year to control the roaming packs of dogs through
neighborhoods, said it was an action long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crisis of epic proportions,'' Ridley-Thomas said.
``It is an alarming threat to public health and safety to the
residents of this region and particularly to children. The county
Health Department said this is the No. 1 health problem for
children, outstripping the likes of measles and mumps.''
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman Joel Wachs questioned whether the new program
will work, particularly since only about 25 percent of dog owners
even bother to license their pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fooling ourselves if we think this will solve the
problem,'' Wachs said. ``We were dealing with this 30 years ago.
The fact is the city has never given the resources to deal with
this problem. And it is inexcusable that we have a law violated by
75 percent of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   If the city is serious about dealing with the issue, he said, it
should contract with the U.S. Postal Service or the Department of
Water and Power to have those workers fill out cards on any
location where there are dogs. The workers could be paid a fee for
identifying any dogs that are not licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Wachs, however, did end up voting for the measure. The three
opponents were council members Nate Holden, Nick Pacheco and Rudy
Svorinich Jr., who were concerned about the size of the license fee
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The measure does give some leeway to the Animal Services
Department to issue warnings to dog owners and give them up to 60
days to comply before misdemeanor charges are sought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 0151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0023 </DOCNO>
