A5508 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG     03-23 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRED DUCKS FALL FROM 8TH PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON _ In the Western Conference playoff race, one night you
are in, the next night you're out.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after tying San Jose for the eighth
postseason berth, a tired flock of Mighty Ducks staggered into
Edmonton on Wednesday and lost a 2-1 decision to the Oilers before
15,673 at Skyreach Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of tying the Oilers with 78 points, the Ducks
(31-32-12-2) head to Vancouver two behind San Jose, three behind
Phoenix and four back of Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had won three consecutive games and were unbeaten in
four, but a 4:30 a.m arrival certainly couldn't have helped their
energy level against a struggling Edmonton team that was 2-5-1 in
its last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no sense whining and crying about it,'' Ducks coach
Craig Hartsburg said of the demanding travel schedule.
``Complaining isn't going to help us now. I'm sure every team has
some games they scratch their heads over.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like the Ducks have been scratching their heads about their
woeful penalty killing all season. Anaheim gave up one more
official power play goal and another that was scored three seconds
after a penalty had expired _ long before Ruslan Salei ever had a
chance to get back into the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't have a lot of energy, one of the worst things
to do is kill penalties,'' said Hartsburg. ``But we can't
over-anaylze things, we just have to get ready for Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyday something new comes up. You can't get too high when
you win or too low when you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had killed 12 of 13 penalties over the last four
games, but they still came into the game ranked last in the league.
And it took the Oilers only 25 seconds to convert on an
interference call against Vitaly Vishnevski.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Poti scored his eighth goal of the season at 10:52 when his
harmless looking shot from the point deflected off Anaheim
defenseman Kevin Haller past Guy Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim goalie turned in yet another strong performance,
stopping 33 of 35 shots, but he had no chance to prevent Doug
Weight's game-winning goal at 17:01 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks nearly tied the game in the finally minute, after
Hebert had been pulled in favor of an extra attacker. Fredrik
Oluasson set up Kariya for a one-timer from the right circle with
Edmonton goalie Tommy Salo out of position, but the Anaheim winger
missed the net badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't get good wood on it, I don't know what happened,
</P>
<P>
   But to Hartsburg, Kariya and Selanne didn't look like
themselves, especially in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have played a lot the last month, and you saw in the
third they just didn't have the zip to beat anybody. They are tired
guys,'' Hartsburg said. ``Most of the time that (Kariya's shot) is
in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had tied the game, 1-1, when Ed Ward slipped a rebound
past Salo at 15:23 of the first period after Antti Aalto got a shot
on goal off the face off. It was Ward's first point in four games
for the Ducks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
