<HEADLINE>
STORK HAS WAVES RIDING HIGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who's coaching the Pepperdine men's volleyball
team, Jeff Stork or Marv Dunphy?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the Waves can't tell.
</P>
<P>
   When the coach stands a certain way, gives a certain look and
utters, ``You know what,'' it's Dunphy.
</P>
<P>
   But not this year. This is Stork's team. The Taft of Woodland
Hills graduate is in charge while Dunphy takes a year off to coach
the U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got names like Marv Dunphy and Jeff Stork, who's going to
question their authority on volleyball?'' sophomore Chris Van
Ruesen said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Stork accepts the Dunphy comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   He knew Dunphy growing up in Topanga Canyon. He played for
Dunphy, first at Pepperdine and then on the 1988 gold medal-winning
Olympic team, and he has been Dunphy's assistant for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves haven't missed a beat. They're ranked second at 14-3
and 11-2 in the Mountain Pacific Sports Federation heading into
Wednesday's home match with fifth-ranked Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``My style tends to reflect his style,'' Stork said. ``This
feels like my team and I know I'm keeping it warm for Marv.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has there been a transition period. In fact, Stork became
interim coach at a right time.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine had graduated George Roumain, a two-time national
Player of the Year, leaving a big offensive hole to fill. Stork's
style is, in part, to spread out the offense, which is exactly what
the team needed and has done.
</P>
<P>
   The players immediately took to Stork and even kid him when they
see Dunphy mannerisms.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they notice subtle differences. Dunphy emphasizes blocking
more than Stork. Stork was a setter, so setting and the transition
game are more important to him. Plus, he substitutes more than
Dunphy But these same players also see Stork more as a guy you can
hang around with and not feel intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a little bit looser,'' senior setter Kurt Nelson said.
``He can joke around a little bit more with players. He was a
seteer, so he understands the position and is more demanding. He
demands a more leadership role.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunphy returns to his Pepperdine job Oct. 4, but he regularly
calls Stork for updates and already has watched the team play. He
sat behind the bench and ``coached'' by shouting during plays.
</P>
<P>
   Stork will be happy to turn the program back to Dunphy, but
perhaps by then, the Waves will have won their fifth national
title.
</P>
<P>
   __ Olympians in town: Don't be surprised if UCLA has a lovefest
when it hosts the Olympic softball team for a doubleheader
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the team's 15 members were Bruins: Christie Ambrosi,
Jennifer Brundage, Sheila Cornell-Douty, Lisa Fernandez and Dot
Richardson. A sixth, Stecey Nuveman, is redshirting to play for the
national team. A seventh, Amanda Freed, is an alternate and will
play with the UCLA team.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are $6 for adults and $4 for children at (310) 825-2946.
</P>
<P>
   __ On the track: The nonscoring Northridge Invitational,
featuring athletes from Cal State Northridge, USC, Cal Lutheran and
several other schools plus other unattatched athletes, begins
Friday with the hammer throws and continues Saturday at CSUN's
track at 9 a.m. One featured athlete is Taft graudate Quincy Watts,
who will compete as he continues a comeback attempt.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gymnasts clean up: UCLA's women's gymnastics team won every
event and won the Pac-10 championships at Arizona State, beating
runner-up Oregon State by 1.125 points.
</P>
<P>
   Mohini Bhardwaj won the all-around title and took first in the
vault. Bhardwaj narrowly beat Lena Degteva, who won on the uneven
parallel bars and the balance beam, by .025 in the all-around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
