<SLUG> BC-BKC-MATCH-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 
UCLA vs. IOWA STATE MATCHUPS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   __ Backcourt: It's difficult to compare the guards because Iowa
State prefers to play with three and UCLA prefers one, Earl Watson,
and two small forwards, Jason Kapono and JaRon Rush. Watson was
brilliant against Maryland (16 assists, no turnovers). Bruins don't
need him to score, but he must make good decisions with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State's lineup features 6-3 point guard Jamaal Tinsley
(10.7 ppg, 6.6 apg), one of the best in the land, and two 6-1 wing
guards, Michael Nurse, a super shooter (12.2 ppg, 40.9% 3-pt.), and
role player Kantrail Horton. Bruins must prevent Tinsley from
penetrating. __ Edge: Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Frontcourt: Iowa State has the best player in America, 6-8
power forward Marcus Fizer (23.2 ppg, 7.8 rpg), and he will try to
overpower the taller, lankier Bruins underneath. Alongside Fizer is
6-4 forward Stevie Johnson (9.1 ppg, 6.1 rpg), who is tough and
athletic.
</P>
<P>
   Bruins will try to force three forwards (Kapono, Rush, Jerome
Moiso) and one center (Dan Gadzuric) on the diminutive Cyclones.
Rush and Kapono must make open jumpers to prevent ISU's guards from
swarming Moiso and Gadzuric in the post. Also, Moiso, who has six
inches on ISU's Johnson, must play big. If he recoils from contact,
as he sometimes does, his size becomes irrelevant. __ Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bench: Also difficult to assess. Iowa State's fate might rest
on the play of two 6-8 forwards, Paul Shirley and Martin Rancik;
each is recovering from a broken foot. Rancik played a few minutes
last weekend. Shirley hasn't played in nine games. If available and
effective, they change the dynamics of the frontcourt matchup.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's bench is deceiving: Gadzuric and Rush are technically
reserves, but they play 25-30 minutes. The real reserves are point
guard Ryan Bailey, who will spell Watson, forward Matt Barnes, who
has played very well lately, and guard Ray Young, whose defense is
more dependable than his jumper. Bruins might need a big game from
Barnes if Gadzuric or Moiso is in foul trouble. __ Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coaching: After a rough three months, UCLA's Steve Lavin has
made all the right moves in the past five weeks, both strategically
and psychologically. But tonight he'll face one of the best coaches
in the country, Iowa State's Larry Eustachy, who will have his team
as well-prepared as possible. Eustachy doesn't have many options.
It's too late for dramatic changes and a lack of size limits the
way ISU can play. Unless the UCLA staff blunders, Eustachy's bench
advantage won't be enough. __ Edge: Slight to ISU.
</P>
<P>
   __ Intangibles: Bruins are confident but humble, calm but
excited. They are the lower seed and one-point underdogs but have
relished that role in recent weeks. Meanwhile, Cyclones have
exceeded all expectations. How will they react to the success to
being favored to win a Sweet 16 game? Also, there will be thousands
of Cyclones fans here, and Bruins have played some of their best
games away from Pauley Pavilion. __ Edge: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Outcome: Don't expect another 35-point win or a half-dozen
alley-oop dunks. Cyclones are tougher and much better coached than
Maryland. But once again the Bruins have more good players
especially more good big players than their opponent. The quintet
of Watson, Kapono, Rush, Moiso and Gadzuric is as talented as any
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Answers to two questions will determine the game: Will UCLA's
size offset ISU's quickness? Will ISU's quickness negate UCLA's
size? Cyclones are one-point favorites, but Fizer and Tinsley can't
beat the Bruins by themselves. __ Edge: UCLA, by eight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
