<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OTHER PLAYERS MUST STEP UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Los Angeles Kings coach Andy Murray says there is
a big difference between his team losing Ziggy Palffy for the rest
of the regular season and the Philadelphia Flyers, who learned
Wednesday they will be without top player Eric Lindros through the
first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that asterisk you see next to their name in the
standings, the one that means they've already qualified for the
playoffs,'' Murray said. ``We're still in a dogfight and probably
will be the rest of the way. But both teams have players who can
step up and keep their teams moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, the Kings' leading scorer with 66 points, could be out
another three weeks with a sprained right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, 27, was disagnosed Wednesday with a Grade II
concussion, his fourth since March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This concusssion, suffered March 4 when he was hit in the jaw by
Boston's Hal Gill, is considered the most serious, with greater
memory loss and longer recovery time. There also is fear that his
career might be in jeopardy since Gill's hit was not severe but
more like one of dozens a player could receive in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros aggravated the headaches by taking excessive amounts of
ibeuprofen, the painkiller found in Tylenol. Lindros' younger
brother, Brett, was forced to retire from the NHL in 1996 after
suffering three concussions with the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lindros missed the final seven games of the regular
season and the playoffs because of a collapsed right lung.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Flyers (39-22-12) have continued to play well without
Lindros and coach Roger Neilson, who is undergoing cancer
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' problems are confined to the ice. The loss to Anaheim
extended their winless streak to four. They are fifth in the West,
a point ahead of slumping Phoenix. But with nine games remaining,
the Kings need players to pick up their games.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy's linemate Luc Robitaille does not have a goal in 10
games and just one in the last 14. Robitaille and Murray spoke
Wednesday about the slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he is getting his chances and as long as he gets his
chances, they eventually will go in,'' Murray said. ``He is a
pretty upbeat guy by nature, but he knows how much we need him and
he's probably putting a little pressure on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   __ No Word: The Kings got to Philadelphia around 5 p.m. after a
fuel stop in Cleveland but had not heard whether defenseman Sean
O'Donnell will be disciplined for spearing Mighty Ducks defenseman
Vitaly Vishnevski in Wednesday's game at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell was issued a five-minute major for the incident, which
was viewed as retaliatory for Vishnevski's hard check last
Wednesday that has forced Palffy out of the lineup. Palffy is
expected to miss the rest of the regular season with a sprained
right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But all major penalties are reviewed by the league office and
the NHL has been coming down hard on offenders. Recently, San
Jose's Bryan Marchment was suspended three games for spearing the
Ducks' Paul Kariya. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
