<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOUTING THE AVENGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the first time in almost six years, I went the
other day to the training camp of a Los Angeles-based professional
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it was a slightly different experience than it was when I
used to visit the Rams and Raiders, for there were only 30 players
present compared to the 100 or so that would be on hand at each of
the those NFL teams' preseason workout sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Los Angeles Avengers are about as far removed
from being an NFL team as the Los Angeles Clippers now are from
being, well, an NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not that far, but L.A.'s newest professional athletic
franchise does operate in the Arena Football League, which is
staged in venues the approx imate size of Aaron Spelling's front
room and which limits its teams' active roster to fewer members
than can be found in Mike Tyson's entourage (20).
</P>
<P>
   But despite the innate quirkiness of a league known mostly for
the astonishing success of one of its alums, Kurt Warner its field
is a mere 50 yards long and 85 feet wide, punts are prohibited, 8
players to a side, etc. the Avengers already have generated more
than passing interest as evidenced by the 4,000 season tickets
they've sold for their eight home matches at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Long before they've played a game that counts they open in
Michigan against the Grand Rapids team on April 15 the Avengers
even have managed to create some controversy with those 1,380
crude, wacky, politically incorrect billboards that have become so
noticeable around Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely getting some attention,'' says the team's 25-
year-old owner, Casey Wasserman, who's had the genetic good fortune
of being the grandson of the legendary entertainment mogul, Lew
Wasserman.
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers are guaranteed of getting plenty of media exposure
this spring, which will be vital for them to succeed in an area
with a well-deserved reputation for being indifferent to such
start-up operations.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of their 14 games will be shown by Fox Sports and another
one will be seen nationally on TNN. All will be broadcast live by
the local One-On-One Sports affiliate, KCTD (1540 AM), with the
charismatic Larry ``Smiley'' Kahn and the aesthetically- pleasing
6-foot-5, 299-pound Cypress resident Mike ``Mr.'' Lamb bringing you
the action.
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers held their media gathering Tuesday, and the team's
highest-profile player, Todd Marinovich, was engulfed by reporters
wondering why the one-time starting quarterback of the Raiders
would bother to make another comeback at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I still can play and still am capable of providing
excitement,'' says Marinovich, who's certainly been capable of
getting his name in the news over the years with his penchant for
nude surfing and charges of marijuana use.
</P>
<P>
   But Marinovich was actually upstaged by the New York Jets' Pro
Bowl receiver, Keyshawn Johnson, who made an unexpected appearance
at the West Los Angeles College facility where the Avengers are
training and where Johnson performed his heroics before attending
USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling great, but I have no idea what's going on with the
Jets,'' says Johnson, who's been involved in a major contract
struggle with the Jets. ``I've been working out like crazy. My
weight's perfect at 215. But my future? Who knows what's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson came at the behest of Wasserman, a pleasant fellow with
a boyish face who put up $5 million in November of 1998 for the
rights to the expansion franchise and figures to spend another $3
million this year in expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably be in for at least $8 million before the season
concludes,'' says Wasserman coolly. ``We're hoping to have some
good crowds. There have been plenty of positive signs. The season
tickets sales have been good. We've received tremendous corporate
support. Staples Center has become a hot place to be in L.A. And I
think there are a lot of football fans around here thirsting to see
the sport in person.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, as the Avengers' 29-year old, 6-3, 300-pound center, Joe
Burgos, who had played the past four seasons for New Jersey, said,
``It's still football we play. There's plenty of hitting, blocking,
tackling, passing and running. And a whole lot of scoring. It's
just that we play football in a confined area, and everything moves
so much more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing to happen to the Arena Football League was the
tremendous season Kurt Warner had with the St. Louis Rams,'' says
Wasserman. ``You couldn't buy the publicity our league received
because of Warner. That did more for our credibility and visibility
than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   For many professional football-deprived L.A. fans, the Avengers
might well fill a vacuum, especially if Marinovich is able play
like he did when he was at USC.
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers' coach, Stan Brock, insists it is not even a
certainty that Marinovich will be a starter, and that he must beat
out a four-year Arena League veteran named Scott Semptimphelter.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a cherished L.A. ritual soon might be revived.
</P>
<P>
   But I doubt a Todd Marinovich-Scott Semptimphelter quarterback
debate will incite the passions of fans around here like the one in
the 1960s between Roman Gabriel and Bill Munson, or the one in the
1970s between Pat Haden and James Harris, or the one in the 1980s
between Jay Schroeder and Steve Beuerlein, or the one in the 1990s
between Jim Everett and T.J. Rubley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 0225EST &QL; 
