<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN26-CO     03-23 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Waiting for the shoe to drop
 &HT;    (For release March 26, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It is with considerable interest _ and foreboding _ that
I noted the jailing of Rev. Al Sharpton in New Jersey. Sharpton
entered prison on Wednesday to begin serving a 10-day term for
obstructing traffic as part of a July 4 Atlantic City demonstration
against police treatment of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly, something similar will happen here. The decision of a
federal judge in the custody case of little Elian Gonzalez has once
again stirred passions. These passions first spilled onto the
streets and expressways of Miami late last year when the Department
of Justice determined that Elian, the Cuban lad found floating on a
raft after his mother drowned escaping Cuba, should be sent back to
his father on the communist island.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, many arrests were made as misdemeanors. No one
served any time for blocking streets, for preventing people from
going to work or to the market, for paralyzing a city the Cuban
exiles adopted as their capital, and which they now dominate
politically.
</P>
<P>
   Looming is another emotional reaction to the decision of U.S.
District Judge K. Michael Moore, who ruled that the authority to
determine Elian's status rests with Attorney General Janet Reno and
the Justice Department. And Reno keeps saying the child belongs
with his father.
</P>
<P>
   (Ironically, Reno is a native Miamian who is expected to return
here once the Clinton Administration is phased out. She is
thoroughly despised by the Cuban exile community, and I concern
myself for her safety and peace of mind.)
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the judicial finding, I expected the traffic
to begin welling up again. It didn't. But it's coming, I just know
it. One of the most resolute Cuban exile Sharpton-types already has
promised a demonstration, ``a massive one.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest response will come from listeners to
Spanish-language radio, the Pied Piper of exile reaction. In the
past, Spanish-language radio (which tops Arbitron ratings in South
Florida) have stirred exiles to commit civil disobedience, so
there's no reason to expect anything else this time.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Spanish-language airwaves are crowded with
haranguing talk show hosts and agitated callers, upset that the
U.S. judicial system, in interpreting this nation's laws, went
against those who would keep Elian here forever.
</P>
<P>
   So when does the civil disobedience start? No one's quite sure.
Some say to expect it any moment. Others say it will wait until the
appeals process runs its course, likely all the way to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever it comes, there is going to be chaos in Miami's
streets. Angry paraders will wave their Cuban flags, while those
inconvenienced by it will be even angrier _ and spouting ethnic
epithets out of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the police, many of whom are of Cuban heritage, will
be required to enforce the law, to clear the streets. (It was
claimed in the last go-around that the police let the demonstrators
ride roughshod over them, then exiles later counter-claimed that
the police were too rough with them.)
</P>
<P>
   This brings us back to Al Sharpton. In his jail cell, he is
discovering the price he has to pay for his actions. Likely, he
believes it to be worth it. And perhaps he's right.
</P>
<P>
   If the Miami demonstrations cause similar hardships on the
remainder of the community, then it would appear to me that the
perpetrators ought to get the bill for their actions as well: jail
time, even fines.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the community, I doubt that they will. The anti-Castro
fanaticism that grips Miami is genuine, as heartfelt as any of the
American civil rights movement. We may disagree with their methods,
which include trying to muzzle anyone who does not adhere to their
principles, but their cause is so passionate that I doubt any would
shirk from demonstrating in the face of a prison term.
</P>
<P>
   We'll soon know.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
