<SLUG> BC-KOZMO-LIQUOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET DELIVERER KOZMO DROPS LIQUOR FROM MENU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ An instant-gratification Internet delivery company,
Kozmo.com, has abruptly withdrawn its applicaton to include liquor
on its products menu following pressure from college officials and
police.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University, Boston University, Boston College, and the
Boston Police Department raised concerns about the company's plans
to deliver everything from six-packs of beer to bottles of Dom
Perignon at no charge to its growing base of customers throughout
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is they expressed concern, and we're not
trying to rush this,'' said Will Weddleton, general manager of the
Boston branch of Kozmo.com, a free Internet service that promises
delivery of everything from CDs to Twinkies in less than an hour.
``We're delaying this process to make sure there's plenty of time
to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But university officials and police say they're not interested
in a dialogue. The bottom line for them: Kozmo.com can deliver as
much junk food as it wants, but it can't peddle alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have zero tolerance to underage drinking in this city,''
said Captain William B. Evans, commander of the police department's
Allston-Brighton Precinct, who helped organize local universities
to oppose the Boston Licensing Board's approval of a liquor license
for Kozmo.com. ``We just see this as a way of putting alcohol in
the hands of underage drinking. Who's going to be at that door to
see who's checking their IDs? We have a hard enough time now. We
don't want to open any doors. Really, it's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The protests against Kozmo's expansion come at a crucial time
for the New York-based upstart.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of reversing last year's losses of $26.4 million, the
company filed Wednesday to raise as much as $150 million through an
initial public sale of stock. Kozmo.com, which has more than
100,000 customers in six US cities, plans to offer its menu of
snacks, videos, and brand products such as Starbucks coffee in at
least 10 additional markets by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But the online delivery service could lose a sizable market if
officials in Boston and other cities block the company from getting
an alcohol license. Kozmo.com is seeking liquor licenses in other
cities, but has yet to win approval anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The company's local branch in Allston has another problem: The
landlord of its large warehouse on McDonald Avenue is Harvard
University. And school officials have already told Weddleton that
the company would be violating the terms of its lease if it starts
delivering alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sat down with them last week, we said we appreciated
that they had postponed their application,'' said Kevin McCluskey,
director of community relations at Harvard. ``But we said it would
be better if they withdrew it permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozmo officials, however, say they hope they can work out a deal
with Boston, which is home to some 100,000 college students, many
of whom are well-acquainted with the free service. The company
might ban all alcohol deliveries to college campuses, restrict beer
runs in certain zip codes, and limit the amount of alcohol and the
number of deliveries it would make to certain addresses, Weddleton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that wouldn't be enough for many local university
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would fly in the face of everything we've been working on
to control students' access to alcohol,'' said Jack Dunn, spokesman
for Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made it clear we're going to oppose this,'' said Colin
Riley, spokesman for Boston University, where about 88 percent of
students are under age 21. ``We can't envision any way that this
would work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
