<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5620 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-DUCHESS-INTERVIEW-ART     03-23 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUCHESS-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHING UP WITH THE DUCHESS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: To purchase this ``separate-buy'' feature
article from Victoria magazine, please contact one of the following
New York Times Syndicate representatives:  
 &HT;    --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files. One color
slide of Sarah, the Duchess of York, is available FREE OF CHARGE to
purchasers of this article and can be sent to you
electronically.)  
 &HT;    
 By CLAIRE WHITCOMB  
 North American rights only 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``Gerry, does that cup have a chip in it?''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Sarah has spied the most minute defect in her
Crown Sapphire cup, part of her Wedgwood wedding china that she's
taken to traveling with.
</P>
<P>
   Her publicist, who's unpacking the tea set from a huge leather
satchel, confirms the damage. Sarah passes it off with a shrug and
goes on to explain how a traveling tea service came to be part of
her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started working for Wedgwood, I said, `Why don't we
make a case so we can bring a tea service with us like Queen
Victoria?' I actually was being rather funny, thinking no one would
go for it, because it is such trouble to carry around. But I like
having tea out of a cup and saucer. My mother always said it tastes
better, and it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah knows quite a bit about the way Queen Victoria traveled,
having retraced her royal journeys through Europe for a remarkable
book, ``Travels with Queen Victoria,'' a companion to her first
publication, ``Victoria and Albert: Life at Osborne House.''
</P>
<P>
   An editor before her marriage, Sarah knew how to produce books.
She teamed up with a photographer and a researcher for both
projects, drawing on the queen's voluminous diaries and travel
sketchbooks, housed in the Royal Library at Windsor Castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Queen Victoria was wonderfully original,'' Sarah says. ``Off
she went in a horse and carriage to the Italian lakes and mountains
where few people traveled. She had a great sense of adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   And a great sense of history. In addition to her diaries,
Victoria journeyed with a watercolor box, sketching scenery and
supplementing her own painted views with commissioned watercolors
of gilded interiors, banquets and balls. Back in England, she and
Albert would spend nostalgic evenings assembling comprehensive
souvenir albums.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah has the same instinct for documentation. Quite a
proficient artist and photographer, she brought along her own
watercolor box and in Coburg, Germany, unwittingly painted the
exact same view the queen had.
</P>
<P>
   Like her royal predecessor, she made sure all her mementos found
their way into leatherbound scrapbooks, and in this effort was
helped by ``my journal lady, Ann Louise.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rule Sarah keeps paintings, photographs and press clips,
but no diaries. ``It's very sad, she says with a sigh, ``but media
and communications are different nowadays. If I kept a diary and it
fell into the wrong hands, it would just be awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Queen Victoria, she points out, wrote freely, knowing her
daughter Beatrice could be counted on to go through her diaries
after her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beatrice burned hundreds of pages,'' Sarah says. ``I think she
cleaned up things that would be misunderstood if made public _
sharp comments written before an argument was patched up, that sort
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sunninghill Park, Sarah's home, scrapbooks take up an entire
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine are green, Beatrice's are maroon and Eugenie's are
blue,'' says Sarah, referring to her daughters, 9 and 11, for whom
she also keeps meticulous records. ``I've saved everything they
have ever drawn, all their writings, every sticky note that says `I
love you,' every little `Welcome home, Mummy.' I like everything to
be kept beautifully for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The children, she says, are the centerpiece of her life. ``I
believe in giving them time,'' explains Sarah, who adds that she
dislikes the English custom of putting children at a separate table
in the kitchen during parties. ``We always eat together, which I
think is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   When she isn't traveling as a spokesperson, a job she does only
in the United States, Sarah tries to arrange her schedule according
to the girls' school hours. ``I still have all my charity work to
do and all my work in Poland and Europe,'' she says. ``But at least
the European flights are just one hour, and then I can be back in
time to pick the girls up from school.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently on plane trips, she's writing thank-you's, having
received 522 gifts and notes for her 40th birthday last October.
``Look at that lump on my finger,'' she says. ``I believe in the
fountain pen and the handwritten thank-you.''
</P>
<P>
   A great one for manners, which she defines as ``acts of
kindness,'' she credits her standards to her mother (``her manners
were impeccable'') and is intent on passing them on to her
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them, `Always remember that you are just like anybody
else,''' she says, and then recites a line from Rudyard Kipling's
poem, ``If'' _ ``If you can ... walk with Kings _ nor lose the
common touch ...''
</P>
<P>
   Manners, Sarah maintains, are quite different from protocol,
which she characterizes as ``a rule book designed by monarchs,''
and she has much less use for such tradition-bound restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   In her role as a royal rebel, she takes a modicum of inspiration
from Queen Victoria, citing an incident in Coburg where Victoria
saw the townspeople cooking bratwurst in the square.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought, `How on earth am I going to try this, because I'm
not allowed to break protocol to go out into the Market Square to
eat sausage?''' Sarah recounts. ``And so she asked one of her
ladies to run down to the Market Square in the dead of night and
bring a sausage back to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah has found her own way out of the constraints of royalty
and she's off to Bloomingdale's to do what would be unseemly in
Britain: lecture on table-setting (not surprisingly she's a great
believer in rule-breaking mixes of patterns).
</P>
<P>
   Her tea set, now packed securely in its blue leather case, will
follow, a very large reminder of her affection for Queen Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SIDEBOX: SETTING A ROYAL TABLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a myth that your fine china should be saved for the
holidays,'' says Sarah, who likes to think of innovative ways to
mix both the formal and the casual.
</P>
<P>
   She'll use her wedding china, but shape a centerpiece around a
daughter's art project. Since she travels frequently, she likes to
use maps and souvenirs to prompt international discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she gathers family heirlooms or finds old photos of
friends to set at each place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start with what you already have, like your family china and
linens, and have fun by changing the details,'' she says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Claire Whitcomb is editor at large at Victoria magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
