<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l BC-COLLECTING-MOVIE-POST     03-23 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLECTING-MOVIE-POSTERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING ATTRACTIONS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: To purchase this ``separate-buy'' article from
Smart Money magazine, please contact one of the following New York
Times Syndicate representatives:  
 &HT;    --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JENNIFER KEENEY  
 North American rights only 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Most of us don't exactly think ``great investment'' when we
think of posters. But movie posters are another matter.
</P>
<P>
   America's obsession with film, combined with movie posters'
striking imagery, has transformed yesterday's dorm-room wall
coverings into valuable art. A ``Dr. No'' poster you could have
bought for a couple of bucks in 1962, for example, now sells for as
much as $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out which current poster will be the next ``Dr. No,''
however, is tougher than ever. As demand has grown, opportunistic
dealers have passed off copies as originals, and movie studios have
diminished values with large print runs.
</P>
<P>
   It's as true for movie posters as for any other kind of art: Buy
what you love. Posters of films you like that also feature strong
visual images are most likely to please your eye and your wallet.
</P>
<P>
   But if you'd like to increase the odds of owning a winner,
follow these guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. BEWARE OF COPYCATS. &LR;  An original movie poster has investment
potential; a reproduction does not. Unfortunately, most copies of
contemporary posters are so good that even the experts are often
left scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   If you find a poster that measures 41-by-27-inches (the old
standard American ``one sheet'' size, now seldom used for either
originals or copies), is a more unusual size (the gigantic
three-sheet, especially, or the smaller half-sheet or lobby card)
or is printed on both sides (for placement in theater light boxes),
the odds are good that it's an original.
</P>
<P>
   But if there's a printing date or company name _ Portal
Publishing is one major producer _ in small type at the bottom of
the poster, you're looking at a copy.
</P>
<P>
   These indicators aren't foolproof, however. Jose Ma. Carpio, a
consultant for Sotheby's and the owner of poster gallery Cinemonde,
cites one example of a collector who tried to do it himself on eBay
and bought a poster for $6,000: ``When it arrived, it was a color
Xerox.''
</P>
<P>
   Galleries such as Carpio's Cinemonde in San Francisco
(415-776-9988) and the Motion Picture Arts Gallery in New York
(212-223-1009 or www.mpagallery.com) are good sources for
originals, but there are also many smaller dealers across the
country. See ``Learning the Ropes,'' below, for your best
resources.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. FOR YOUR CONSIDERATION ... OSCAR. &LR;  Posters of Academy
Award-winning films are more likely to become collectors' items,
but because studios print more of them, they're often less
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Look for surprise hits: Relatively few posters were made for
``Life Is Beautiful,'' for example, so they're worth more.
</P>
<P>
   Historical subject matter also makes for broader and more
lasting appeal, which is why ``Schindler's List'' and ``Saving
Private Ryan'' have already proven good investments.
</P>
<P>
   You should also find out if any print runs were noteworthy. One
``Titanic'' poster, for instance, mistakenly left out actress
Gloria Stuart's name and was printed only in small quantities; it's
much more valuable than other versions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. DEPEND ON DISNEY. &LR;  Disney restricts the number of posters
made for each of its movies, and the company's readiness to file
copyright-infringement suits means there are fewer illegal
reprints. Plus, Disney's artwork and subject matter have great
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, appreciation has been high: A 1967 ``Jungle
Book'' one-sheet cost $75 in the early '90s and recently sold for
$584 at Sotheby's. New posters should see similar returns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. BUY GENERIC. &LR;  Nowadays, vintage posters from certain genres
_ horror films, movies with all-black casts _ are especially
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Which current genres might do well in the future? As we move
into the 21st century, John Kisch, author of the ``Poster Price
Almanac,'' recommends posters of movies with futuristic themes:
``Blade Runner'' and, more recently, ``The Matrix'' have done well
on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Carpio adds that since movie-poster collecting is primarily a
male hobby, action movies are a good choice, particularly if they
star a popular male actor. Consider upcoming James Bond films or
those in the new ``Star Wars'' series.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. STUDY ABROAD. &LR;  If you think an American film will have
long-term interest, look out for a foreign version of its poster.
These can be quite valuable, since even the biggest blockbusters
typically have more limited distribution abroad, and different
printing and artwork make them novel.
</P>
<P>
   An American poster for ``The Terminator'' sells for $100 to
$200, according to Christie's consultant Tony Nourmand; the Czech
version costs $400 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6. BE AN EARLY BIRD _ OR FASHIONABLY LATE. &LR;  If an upcoming film
is predicted to be a hit, get an advance-release poster. They're
usually printed with high-quality techniques on very good paper and
in limited numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pulp Fiction'' advance poster now sells for about $150 _
and it's gone for as much as $316 at Sotheby's _ compared with $35
to $50 for the regular one-sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, watch out for rerelease posters of films that might
be a couple of years old; they occasionally feature better images
or designs than the originals, which make them more attractive to
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7. GET AN AIRTIGHT RETURN POLICY. &LR;  Always pay with a credit
card, and make sure your dealer will allow you to return your
poster at any time if it's not what you expected. Otherwise, Carpio
says, you should take your business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SIDEBAR: LEARNING THE ROPES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are many helpful references for movie-poster collectors.
``Collecting Movie Posters,'' by Edwin and Susan Poole, is an
excellent overview (McFarland &AMP; Co., $30). John Kisch's annual
``Poster Price Almanac'' is the hobby's bible: It lists more than
70,000 movie posters and their auction prices, as well as Internet
resources and reputable dealers across the country.
</P>
<P>
   On Kisch's www.posterprice.com, you can find out about auctions,
get appraisals on your posters and locate the best dealers in your
area. Founded by author and former Christie's consultant Bruce
Hershenson, www.brucehershenson.com is aimed at collectors who want
to share advice and trade information. Here, in addition to
searching for specific images, you can submit queries to the more
than 1,500 aficionados who belong to the site's e-mail club. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jennifer Keeney is a reporter for Smart Money magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
