<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5637 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN24-COX     03-23 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heading the Jeep down that long, lonesome highway
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD _ The idea is to see how far I can drive in
three-and-a-half days, to take the Jeep down some rough roads, and
to see a chunk of southwest Texas I've never seen before. That's
about as specific as my itinerary got during a recent jaunt through
West Texas. Before it was over, I had logged 1,500 miles, met a
couple of interesting characters, seen where John Wayne died at the
Alamo in the film version, and eaten some of the best barbecue
that's ever crossed my lips. Here are a few observations from my
time on the road:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Boerne, out in the Hill Country, where a buddy of mine owns
the newspaper, there's a modest ranch with the sign, ``El Rancho
Not So Grande.'' It looked like a mighty nice place to me, but I
guess it's all perspective.
</P>
<P>
   I meandered throughout the Hill Country on this trip, then
dropped south and came up along the Mexican border on U.S. Hwy. 90,
avoiding the interstate because it's boring though efficient,
stopping wherever the mood struck to talk to furniture makers, look
at antiques, buy a copy of the local newspaper and fuel up on
coffee and iced tea.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day, I made my way down a dusty road to Alamo
Village in Brackettville, where dozens of movies have been filmed,
including, of course, John Wayne's ``The Alamo.'' It's eerily
realistic, especially the chapel facade, until you realize there's
nothing behind it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other signs spied along the route:
</P>
<P>
   In Hondo, at the city limits, a sign reads, ``This is God's
Country. Please Don't Drive Through It Like Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   In Knippa, east of Uvalde, a community about the size of a
good-sized Holiday Inn, a sign implored, ``Go Ahead and Blink.
Knippa is Bigger Than You Think.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The mesquite trees are in full leaf. One of my column-writing
heroes, Leon Hale of the Houston Chronicle, makes an annual
pilgrimage through South Texas looking for the first signs of
spring, one of which he claims is when the mesquite trees bud out.
By the look of things on my journey, spring came to South and West
Texas at least a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of mesquite trees, which have always struck me as being
spindly, obnoxious plants that crowd out other, more worthy
vegetation, there are a number of folks in the Uvalde area who
build furniture out of mesquite. Mesquite lumber is reddish with
striking swirls of grain. I stopped outside of Uvalde at a woodshop
whose owner has stack-upon-stack of wide-board mesquite, taken from
trees whose girth is much larger than the trees I've seen on the
side of the road. The furniture he displayed was beautiful _ dining
room tables, dressers, and an elaborate lamp with a shade turned on
a lathe out of a single stump of mesquite. I ended up buying a
couple of boards of mesquite and a piece of pecan to make small
boxes. I may go back for a trailer-load some time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some of the best barbecue that's ever passed my lips can be
had at Haby's Hot Pit in Uvalde, home of Dolph Briscoe, a former
governor and the state's largest private landowner. A framed
article from 1997 on the wall from Texas Monthly names Haby's one
of the top 50 barbecue joints in the state. The brisket was to die
for, and the chicken fell off the bone when you looked at it
crossways. Stop there if you're in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outside of Del Rio, hard by the Mexican border, I stopped at
Lake Amistad, a dammed-up portion of the Rio Grande. Even though
the level is obviously down because of the drought, it's still an
impressive lake. Fact is, it's hard to believe this is the same
body of water that comprises the state's border with its southern
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of water, Seminole Canyon just west of Amistad is
practically worth the trip by itself. This is where the Pecos River
cuts through on its way to the Rio Grande a few miles south. This
close to the end of its voyage, the Pecos looks like a real river,
and the canyon rivals what can be found in Colorado. It's a far cry
from how the Pecos looks in West Texas, near Fort Stockton where I
ran a weekly in an earlier life. There, it's a modest waterway that
in spots you could walk across, especially in drought times like
these.
</P>
<P>
   _ I ended the westward part of my trip in Fort Davis, where I
revisited the McDonald Observatory and viewed some property my
friends own in the valley below. Then it was a quick visit to
Balmorhea pool where scuba divers mingled with catfish in one of
the largest natural pools in the country.
</P>
<P>
   With Junior Brown picking away on the CD, I buzzed quickly
through Fort Stockton to see that little has changed before heading
east along Interstate 10, back to the pine trees and red-dirt
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN24-COX     03-23 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Counting the November vote could be slow going
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Even though she's not a candidate, County Clerk
Dana DeBeauvoir is looking forward to the November election with
some trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the scenario: A famous Austinite at the top of the
national ballot in a close race. It's not a stretch to say that the
world waits for his home county to turn in election results. And
waits and waits and waits.
</P>
<P>
   It's a recurring nightmare for DeBeauvoir, who has known
repeatedly the frustration of slow ballot counts. She dodged a
bullet last week by reporting 60 percent of the primary votes by 10
p.m., but was frank in her assessment of that performance: ``The
light turnout saved my bacon.''
</P>
<P>
   As you may recall, DeBeauvoir was busy preparing for last
Tuesday's election by warning people not to expect early results.
She wasn't getting the volunteer help she needed, she said. On top
of that, election judges could be slow in getting the ballot boxes
to the central counting station because they also had precinct
conventions to convene immediately after the polls closed.
</P>
<P>
   DeBeauvoir was expecting a long night and a rerun of carping
about slow vote counts. She surprised everyone _ maybe even herself
_ with the faster-than-expected tabulations.
</P>
<P>
   She isn't promising miracles in November, though, when Travis
County and Texas will be in a national and international spotlight.
DeBeauvoir anticipates a heavy turnout because of Gov. George W.
Bush's presence on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   And a heavy turnout, while good for democracy, spells trouble
for the clerk. ``I don't think I'm going to make it by 10 p.m.,''
DeBeauvoir said.
</P>
<P>
   While the 10 p.m. deadline is artificial, it is one that
election officials are under pressure to hit to ensure that the
results are read on the nightly news shows. Because ballot boxes
are open only after the polls close at 7 p.m., that gives ballot
counters three hours to compile results. It's a daunting task even
if election judges don't stop for dinner on their way to the
central counting station, don't get stuck in traffic or are
otherwise delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The ballots are sorted and examined by hand to ensure accuracy,
and accuracy is something on which DeBeauvoir prides herself.
County Commissioner Karen Sonleitner notes that whatever other
complaints people have about Travis County vote counts, challenges
for accuracy are rare.
</P>
<P>
   DeBeauvoir has been pushing commissioners for updated equipment
that may help speed up the vote count, but it isn't cheap and
commissioners have thus far resisted, citing other priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The county will have to replace the 10-year-old ballot counting
technology sometime, but not now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of if, but when, we get a new system,'' said
Sonleitner, who knows firsthand the agony of a slow count.
Sonleitner, who represents north and northwest Travis County, won
re-election two years ago, but it was a long and agonizing wait for
results.
</P>
<P>
   It was tough, she said, but she lived. While obviously open to
the idea of a new counting system, a high-profile election year is
not the time to test something new.
</P>
<P>
   Better, Sonleitner said, to wait until next year, when the
electoral action will be less intense, to try different equipment.
</P>
<P>
   County Judge Sam Biscoe and Commissioner Todd Baxter get to the
same conclusion by slightly different routes. Biscoe and Baxter say
they are open to discussing modernizing ballot system, but hesitate
to do it just to make results available in time for the 10 p.m.
newscasts. And, they say, this is not a burning issue with most
voters.
</P>
<P>
   They are right, of course. One hears an awful lot of bellyaching
from political junkies about slow vote counts, but the issue
quickly dissipates.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a different story in November, though, when Travis
County is still counting votes after midnight. DeBeauvoir was
wasting no time last week to warn us about that very prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
