<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Makeup pro to celebrities offers advice
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Laura Mercier lands on more magazine
covers than the busiest model.
</P>
<P>
   She's on this month's Harper's Bazaar and last year was on the
front of Mirabella, Marie Claire, More and Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't heard of her? You undoubtedly know the women that
Mercier, a makeup artist and creator of a popular cosmetics line,
makes cover-worthy: Julia Roberts, Meg Ryan, Ashley Judd, Susan
Sarandon ...
</P>
<P>
   Mercier products can be found on the vanities of celebs (Madonna
and Celine Dion are fans) and in the recent InStyle roundup of the
top foundations, concealers, powders and blushes (four of her
formulas are in the top 17).
</P>
<P>
   The Paris native, and a team of 15 makeup artists, visited Saks
Fifth Avenue in Palm Beach last month for five hours of color
consultations and quickie makeup lessons. Roughly 100 women
participated, and a couple were so enchanted that they asked
Mercier to autograph sponges.
</P>
<P>
   Because her trademark is ``the flawless face,'' we asked Mercier
for her top five tips on creating a smooth-as-silk look, regardless
of the products used.
</P>
<P>
   Laying that groundwork is the most important part of your makeup
routine, says Mercier, 41. ``You can push the eyes, you can push
the lips. But the skin should be realistic and light.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Start with a blank slate. ``The preparation of the canvas is
important,'' Mercier says. A smooth foundation cannot be achieved
unless skin is clean, moisturized and protected from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use a light hand. You want to apply just enough foundation
``that gives a sense of the real skin underneath,'' she says. The
trend now is for foundation that looks shiny and glowy. But when
the pendulum swings back to matte, still ``use the least amount of
foundation possible.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Attack imperfections one by one. ``If you have flaws, treat
them separately'' with a concealer, Mercier says. ``Don't try to
cover pimples and flaws with the foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're trying to conceal blemishes, Mercier recommends a
brush because it is more precise. A sponge is good for foundation
because the area to be covered is so much larger. Just remember,
when it comes to foundation, the byword is ``sheer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay proper attention to your eyes. If you have dark circles
under your eyes, apply a concealer. ``This is crucial to make an
even look,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But skip foundation around the eyes. The more layers you add,
the more wrinkles will be noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set everything with translucent powder. Take a big, fluffy
brush, dig it into colorless powder and apply a little at a time
around the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   If you used foundation, use a puff with the powder to push the
pigment into the face _ don't rub the puff on your skin or move it
around, just gently push.
</P>
<P>
   Only after you've set the foundation with powder should you move
on to powdered blushes and eyeshadows. Powder on top of powder will
blend easier.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if using creme blush or creme shadows, apply
those before you powder.
</P>
<P>
   Sound complicated? No way, Mercier says. ``It's easy, in fact.
It makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
