<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COCONUTGROVE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the Grove groove
 &HT;    By Mary Thurwachter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCONUT GROVE, Fla. _ Modern art aficionados are likely to find
the Coconut Grove Bed &AMP; Breakfast especially appealing. Not only is
it in a shaded corner of a historic district, but the
turn-of-the-century home belongs to a Grove artist, Annette
Rawlings, whose work has been exhibited in museums and galleries
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Examples of Rawlings' work _ from tunic dresses and T-shirts to
vases, placemats, dinnerware, paintings and drawings _ are
displayed prominently throughout the two-story house. Guests can
purchase many items, while others adorn the walls of the bedrooms,
hallways and dining area.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't particularly like Rawlings' geometric paintings
with their flowing lines, or her abstract nudes, you may prefer a
more conventional inn. My husband, who appraises art, appreciated
the textiles and paintings far more than I did. But Rawlings'
ceramic pieces, with their bright colors, and swirling lines,
intrigued me.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed in the front bedroom facing the road. It had a
comfortable king-size bed, television, phone, modern white desk and
chair, fresh flowers, and several of the artist's paintings. It had
everything we needed and one thing we didn't: traffic noise. We
couldn't believe how many cars zoomed through this historic
district before midnight. Undoubtedly, the back bedroom would have
been better, but it had already been booked.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there was plenty to like about our visit to Rawlings'
casa. The breakfast, for example, was delightful _ and well
presented. There was orange juice and coffee, of course, but I
especially liked the Belgian waffles, topped in a colorful design
of raspberries and whipped cream. The napkins and dinnerware were
of her own design.
</P>
<P>
   We also enjoyed sitting on the back porch for a picnic before
heading to an antique show at The Mayfair Hotel. We watched the
Rawlings' cat totally ignore the squirrels that raced around what
Rawlings said was one of the oldest, largest banyan trees in the
state. This was a very relaxing spot.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the living room with its high ceiling, fireplace and
hardwood floor provided another comfy place to sit and read or
chat.
</P>
<P>
   The house is a mile away from the shopping area that includes
CocoWalk, a fun spot to shop or people-watch, and The Streets of
Mayfair, an open-air, pedestrian-friendly shopping, dining, and
urban entertainment complex.
</P>
<P>
   Monty's Stone Crab, where we had dinner, is a short drive away.
Also close by is Fairchild Tropical Garden, 83 acres with peaceful
paths through horticultural displays, a rainforest, and palm trees
of all varieties. The $8 admission (which included a tram tour) was
worth every penny.
</P>
<P>
   For those looking for a small inn close to shopping and
restaurants _ and for those who like the idea of staying in an
artist's house _ the Coconut Grove Bed &AMP; Breakfast is a good place
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Coconut Grove Bed &AMP; Breakfast, 4286 Douglas Road, Miami, FL
33133. Phone: (305) 665-2274. Web:
http://www.kwflorida.com/coconut.html
</P>
<P>
   Accommodations: Three suites with private marble baths, tropical
garden views, phones and television. Breakfast included. Rates are
from $120 to $150 per night.
</P>
<P>
   Directions: From West Palm Beach, go south on Interstate 95
until the interstate becomes U.S. 1. Continue south on U.S. 1 to
42nd Avenue (LeJune Road). Turn left, or east, to the second
traffic light (Ingraham Highway). Turn right and go to Edgewater
Drive. Turn right and continue on Edgewater to Douglas. Turn left
on Douglas to 4286.
</P>
<P>
   Seafood restaurant: Monty's Stone Crab, 2550 S. Bayshore Dr.,
Coconut Grove. Good selection of stone crabs, Florida lobster tail,
Jamaican spiced red snapper and grouper. Prices are moderate. All
major credit cards accepted. Phone: (305) 285-5176.
</P>
<P>
   Of interest nearby: Fairchild Tropical Garden, 10901 Old Cutler
Road. The 83-acre outdoor museum includes an extensive collection
of palms, cycads and other tropical plants. Hours are from 9:30
a.m.-4:30 p.m. daily. Admission is $8 for adults (includes tram
ride). Children under 13 get in free. Phone: (305) 667-1651.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
