<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EYMAN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gish biography lovingly renders a great career
 &HT;    By Scott Eyeman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On the short list of great actresses of
the recently expired century, Lillian Gish would have to be in the
top five. Not only did she maintain a career for 80 years, she
created indelible images in films. She could do it on stage as
well, with ``A Trip to Bountiful'' and a reputedly great Ophelia
opposite John Gielgud's Hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   Until her death at age 99 in 1993, Gish symbolized and
personified the history of the movies, and did it with an integrity
that never wavered or became sanctimonious. More than a great
actress, she was a great lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lillian Gish: A Life on Stage and Screen'' (McFarland) is the
first posthumous biography of Gish. It was written by noted
silent-film musician Stuart Oderman, who was helped by a friendship
with Gish that extended for more than 30 years. Oderman has done a
first-rate job of documenting a one-of-a-kind career and a
remarkable life.
</P>
<P>
   BOO! MORE AHEAD FROM STEPHEN KING
</P>
<P>
   Stephen King has re-upped with Simon &AMP; Schuster for three more
books. The first will be a novel titled ``From a Buick Eight.''
King signed with S&AMP;S a couple of years ago in an innovative
arrangement that gave him a high percentage of the proceeds in
exchange for a very low, possibly nonexistent, advance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
