r e BC-BOOKS-MOUNTAINROAD24-     03-23 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MOUNTAINROAD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sad story of author's youth may be Anderson's best
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hesper Anderson writes a good first
sentence: ``My mother killed herself on the first day of spring.''
</P>
<P>
   She also knows how to write a quietly spectacular book.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Mountain Road'' is the story of Anderson's youth, more
or less from 12 to 21, from World War II to the mid-'50s, and of
the extended family that was nearly as important as her blood
family.
</P>
<P>
   Among that extended family were Kurt Weill and Lotte Lenya,
Milton Caniff, Burgess Meredith, Alan Jay Lerner and his wife of
the moment, and the momentarily popular Marion Hargrove, author of
``See Here, Private Hargrove,'' and Anderson's first great crush.
</P>
<P>
   They all lived in granite castles deep in the Rockland County,
N.Y., woods, near the mountain called High Tor, on and around South
Mountain Road.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrities that Anderson name-drops throughout the book
aren't there for effect, for ``South Mountain Road'' is the story
of a community of artists, people who took care of each other's
children, listened to each other's troubles, worked on each other's
projects and, in one or two cases, were capable of a truly
astonishing cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Cumulatively, she creates an absolutely believable picture of an
entire social structure, of an insecure girl surrounded by
beautiful vessels of talent that only made her more insecure.
</P>
<P>
   There is a haunting sadness here, not merely because of the way
Mab Anderson died, but in the way it all slowly fell apart. The
band of friends drifted away to other climes and other marriages
and, for a time, Hesper Anderson floundered.
</P>
<P>
   Years after her mom's suicide, after she finally found out what
that tormented woman's wound was, Hesper Anderson became a writer
herself, with such movies as ``Children of a Lesser God'' to her
credit.
</P>
<P>
   Those credits are good, but the achievement she's likely to be
remembered for is ``South Mountain Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
