<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-CALVINO24-COX     03-23 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CALVINO24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calvino gives us posthumous reason to read the classics
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Each year, in the early 1960s at Bishop
Kenny High School in Jacksonville, came the school raffle. We were
supposed to sell at least 10 chances, at $1 each. For those who did
not, a terrible punishment awaited.
</P>
<P>
   The redoubtable Mr. James Durant IV, an eccentric man who taught
us Latin, French and mathematics, would assign the errant slacker a
book report on Pliny's ``Natural History,'' four massive volumes of
close-printed text kept in the morgue of the Jacksonville Public
Library.
</P>
<P>
   Gaius Plinius Secundus was a Roman official who read
voraciously, wrote encyclopedically and perished spectacularly
during the eruption of Vesuvius in 79 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of having to read him so horrified us that we sold
raffle tickets like born-again Fuller Brush men. Some students
bought tickets themselves, with their own pocket money. Anything to
avoid Pliny!
</P>
<P>
   In our junior year, a classmate named Robert Pippin failed to
sell his quota. I can recall him walking around with one or more of
the four volumes of Pliny under his arm, like a lost soul in hell.
I doubt he read the whole thing, as his book report dealt largely
with the habits of ants. Yet it was unexpectedly fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   But not fascinating enough to make us want to read Pliny. For
that, I had to wait for the splendid ``Why Read the Classics?,'' a
posthumous collection of essays by Italo Calvino. It is really 36
books in one, with Calvino examining great writers and books in
quirky ways that shed new light on old and often neglected
masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Each essay is worth a review in itself, but I will concentrate
on Calvino's fifth piece, ``The Sky, Man, the Elephant,'' in which
he examines Pliny so brilliantly and engagingly that he turns a
punishment into a treat.
</P>
<P>
   People mostly read Pliny, Calvino says, ``to winkle out bizarre
facts and curiosities.'' Even Pliny's index, contained in Book I,
is bizarre. Under fish, he lists ``Fish which have a small stone in
their head; Fish which hide in winter; Fish which are influenced by
the stars; Fish which have fetched extraordinary prices ...''
</P>
<P>
   Calvino goes far beyond this. He finds poetry in Pliny's
description of the moon, the ``ultimate star, the star most
familiar to those who live on earth, their remedy against the
dark.''
</P>
<P>
   He finds philosophy in Pliny's observation that God is less free
than man, in that he cannot kill himself and cannot make someone
who has lived, never to have lived. Calvino ferrets out some of
Pliny's choicest oddities and notes little clues that give us a
picture of the author's mind and heart. He must have been a decent
fellow, for he noted that ``Men's corpses float on their back,
women's on their front, as if nature wanted to respect the modesty
of women even after death.''
</P>
<P>
   Pliny's favorite creature was the elephant, and Calvino notes
that Book 8 of the ``Natural History'' begins with the elephant,
both because of its ``preeminent size'' and because spiritually
this animal is ``closest to man.''
</P>
<P>
   Why closest? Because the elephant recognizes the language of its
native land, obeys orders, memorizes what it has learned,
experiences the passion of love and the thirst for glory, and
practices virtues that men do not always practice: probity,
prudence, fairness and a decent regard for the sun, moon and stars.
</P>
<P>
   In this admiration for elephants, Calvino acutely describes in
Pliny a kind of ecological, almost sociological awareness, an
empathy with other life forms that is very modern, and quite at
odds with the bloodthirsty picture of Roman antiquity we so often
see on the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Calvino has accomplished something magical: He has made
you eager to read Pliny. He does the same for other classic
writers, among them Homer, Ovid, Defoe, Voltaire, Stendhal, Balzac,
Flaubert, Dickens, Tolstoy, Twain, James, Conrad, Borges, Hemingway
and obscurer authors like Giammaria Ortes, Raymond Queneau and
Cesare Pavese.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction, Calvino gives 14 definitions of a
``classic.'' They are brilliant, poetic and occasionally very
funny. A few examples:
</P>
<P>
   ``The classics are those books about which you usually hear
people saying: `I'm rereading...' never `I'm reading...'''
</P>
<P>
   ``A classic is a book which with each rereading offers as much a
sense of discovery as the first reading.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A classic is a work which constantly generates a pulviscular
(dusty) cloud of critical discourse around it, but which always
shakes the particles off.''
</P>
<P>
   And, eeriest of all: ``A classic is the term given to any book
which comes to represent the whole universe, a book on a par with
ancient talismans.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a book to be devoured, or gulped down, or listened
to on tape while commuting. It's a classic on classics, and you
come away from each chapter with a quickened understanding, an
enlivened curiosity, a stirred soul. You have been in contact with
a very humane, brilliant man who has introduced you, or
reacquainted you with, humane, brilliant books.
</P>
<P>
   You vow _ again! _ to watch less TV.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to Jacksonville, I visited the downtown public
library to see if the once-dreaded Pliny was still there. It is,
all four volumes, edited by John Bostock, M.B., F.R.S. and H.T.
Riley Esq., published by Henry Bohn in London in 1855, and donated
to the library on Dec. 27, 1924.
</P>
<P>
   It had last been checked out on May 19, 1964. Pippin's name
wasn't on the card, but that was the very month he failed to sell
his 10 raffle tickets and became forcibly acquainted with Gaius
Plinius Secundus, his ants, his fish, his moons, his stars, his
handsome and sympathetic elephants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
