<HEADER>
A5647 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-GEFFEN24-COX     03-23 1890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GEFFEN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Geffen biography stirs controversy _ but little else
 &HT;    By Jeff Salamon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The most revealing passage in Tom King's
controversial biography of David Geffen isn't about David Geffen's
sex life, or David Geffen's legendary temper or David Geffen's
infinite capacity for betrayal. In fact, it isn't really about
David Geffen at all.
</P>
<P>
   The most revealing passage in Tom King's controversial biography
of David Geffen is about Tom King.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction, King details his strenuous efforts to get
estranged Geffen confidante Joni Mitchell to sit for an interview.
``I wrote her yet another letter and _ at the suggestion of a
friend who had heard Mitchell mention in a National Public Radio
interview that her cat Nietzsche had learned to dance _ I sent a
box of gourmet cat treats to her home in Bel-Air,'' King writes.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell doesn't nibble, but the reader takes note of King's way
with a cat treat and suspects right off why Geffen was at first
drawn to and then repelled by his choice of biographer.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring that a savvy, gay entertainment reporter for The Wall
Street Journal would be a sympathetic observer of a savvy, gay
entertainment mogul, Geffen in 1996 gave King unprecedented access
to his life, clearing the way for the first-time author to
interview nearly 300 associates, right down to his childhood
shrink. A year later, Geffen turned on King and stopped speaking to
him. Oddly, he didn't stop King from continuing to talk to his
friends and colleagues. But as the publication date approached,
Geffen turned again, doing everything he could to get the book
quashed.
</P>
<P>
   All of which would lead one to expect that ``The Operator: David
Geffen Builds, Buys, and Sells the New Hollywood,'' would be a
dazzling and damning narrative of greed, ego and libido run amok.
But there's nothing amok about King's book at all. Rather than
making Geffen seem monstrous, King commits a worse sin: He makes
David Geffen seem boring.
</P>
<P>
   King lines up the story squarely enough. David Geffen was born
in 1943 in Brooklyn, N.Y., to Abe and Batya Geffen, Jewish
immigrants from Russia and the Ukraine. Abe was a ne'er-do-well
whom Geffen looked down on; Batya an iron-fisted seamstress who ran
the household, supported the family and instilled a strong will to
power in her favorite son. (``The Explanation,'' Geffen's
colleagues dubbed her decades later.) Geffen was a small, antic
child, who spent most of his school hours fidgeting and making
trouble. Today, he'd be hooked up to a 24-hour Ritalin drip.
</P>
<P>
   After an abortive semester at the University of Texas convinced
him he wasn't college material, 21-year-old Geffen got his show-biz
start in the William Morris Agency mailroom and, through hard work,
smarts and ethical corner-cutting, quickly moved up. By his late
20s, he had founded Asylum Records, a Warners subsidiary that gave
him the footing to discover and nurture the likes of Jackson
Browne, Joni Mitchell and the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Geffen's personal life was similarly manic. In between
assignations with male prostitutes and short-term dalliances with a
series of younger, usually troubled men, he dated, with a puzzling
intensity, Cher and Marlo Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, his fortunes took a decisive turn for the better when
he sold his second record company, Geffen Records, home of Nirvana
and Guns N' Roses, to MCA for $545 million in stock. When
Matsushita bought MCA a year later at an inflated price, he was,
give or take a hundred million dollars, a billionaire. A few years
and wise investments later, he, Steven Spielberg and Disney refugee
Jeff Katzenberg founded the Dreamworks studio.
</P>
<P>
   This is, to say the least, rich material for a biographer.
Having participated in the gay liberation movement, the media
transformation of the presidency (Geffen has served as an
unofficial adviser to Bill Clinton), and the simultaneous rise of
recreational drugs, psychotherapy, multinational corporations, and
youth culture, Geffen is basically the latter half of the 20th
century stuffed into one convenient 5-foot-7 package. But ``The
Operator,'' despite its ploddingly chronological structure, barely
gets 1979 right _ or any other year you might care to mention.
</P>
<P>
   What King misses, again and again, is how colorful the world of
show business is. Geffen is undoubtedly a lonely guy, but on the
surface, at least, he's led a fabulous life. Exposing the
tawdriness beneath that surface is a worthy enough endeavor, but
you'd have to give the glitz its due to make the project more than
a mug's game. And King, for whatever reasons, seems
constitutionally incapable of sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   Geffen's wild drug- and sex-fueled Studio 54 years, for
instance, would seem like red meat for a biographer. But King
settles for a brief description of the fabled 54 VIP room (``an
amazing space where such diverse luminaries as Elizabeth Taylor and
Mikhail Baryshnikov could be seen sitting on leather banquettes
chatting with the likes of Betty Ford or Jimmy Carter's elderly
mother Lillian'') that makes it sound like the site of a Pat
Moynihan fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Here is his description of Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young's
Woodstock performance, which ``perfectly embodied the mood and
feeling of the festival'':
</P>
<P>
   ``The stage crew brought out the band's amplifiers, and the
musicians went to work delivering their powerful electric set.''
</P>
<P>
   It's almost like you're there, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   There's more in this vein. Kurt Cobain, Axl Rose, and Neil Young
pass through these pages and hardly strike a chord. Courtney Love
comes and goes, and the reader isn't even mildly revolted. Beside
making for a duller read than necessary, this lack displaces a key
part of Geffen's context. Since King fails to make clear what is
actually compelling about the record industry, it's easy for him to
portray Geffen's greed and ambition as that much more naked. Give
Geffen this much: He wasn't a junk bond trader or a takeover
vulture _ he worked with artists, and King gives us no reason to
believe that his support for Laura Nyro and Jackson Browne wasn't
informed by a genuine love of their music.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to pin an ulterior motivation on King, but the
book is so scattershot that much can be chalked up to simple
incompetence. On Page 61, Geffen, in his role as a young talent
agent, is trying to pitch ``a hippie named Lorne Michaels and soon
got him a gig writing for a situation comedy.'' Two hundred and
thirty-two pages and 13 years later, Geffen's friend Paul Simon
``introduced him to his neighbor Lorne Michaels, the producer of
NBC's `Saturday Night Live.''' On Page 439, King writes that Warner
Chairman Steve Ross ``had always said he would buy Geffen Records
when Geffen was ready to sell'' _ a statement that blithely ignores
the fact that, 34 pages earlier, Ross refuses Geffen's offer to
sell the company. On Page 311, when Geffen is trying to sign John
Lennon, King states that the two had met previously, on ``that
bizarre night in 1975 when he, Lennon, Cher, and Harry Nilsson had
ended up in Hugh Hefner's hot tub after Phil Spector had waved a
gun at Geffen.'' Unfortunately, the passage about Spector waving a
gun occurs a page after the hot tub episode _ though the narrative
is so muddled it's tough to parse cause and effect.
</P>
<P>
   This is sloppy work, and though King has to take some of the
blame, as much should be laid at the door of Random House, which
seems to have offered its neophyte author almost none of the
support he clearly needed. (Ironically, what he needed was a David
Geffen-type advocate to hold his hand.)
</P>
<P>
   As a result, King hasn't written a biography at all, but a
600-page log. A biography is supposed to be more than a record of a
person's comings and goings; it should offer a reading of someone's
life. But on the rare occasions that King reaches for that level of
interpretation, he fails.
</P>
<P>
   Early on he writes, ``having tossed aside all notions of right
and wrong, young David Geffen simply lived by different rules than
did the rest of society around him.'' This is a staggeringly naive
statement for an entertainment reporter to make. Geffen's rules, in
fact, are identical to those of the world he belonged to. Cheating,
stealing and lying are common occurrences in show business, which
was established by a host of unsavory types (many of them from the
same immigrant Brooklyn milieu that produced Geffen). Say what you
want about David Geffen, but to the best of King's knowledge, he
never got into bed with organized crime, sent Pinkerton workers to
club strikers over the head or bribed government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Geffen may be a loudmouth and a lousy friend, but by Hollywood
standards of predation, he's a piker. In fact, you'd have a tough
time finding a Hollywood fortune that was bought with fewer victims
per dollar. Most of the people in this book with an ax to grind are
millionaires who think they should be multimillionaires and
multimillionaires who think they should be billionaires. Most of
them play the same crooked game, by the same crooked rules, that
Geffen did _ just not as well. But since King fails to provide an
ounce of professional context for Geffen's behavior, it's easy for
him to write the story as a morality tale rather than a social
history.
</P>
<P>
   One cool customer, King seems _ imagine this _ like David Geffen
without the grace notes. Geffen walks all over people, but you
suspect that's because they're too vividly alive for him to deal
with. His belief in their capacity to reject him is so powerful he
has to beat them to the punch by betraying them first. (That they
are then rendered harmless enough to be welcomed back into his good
graces makes sense, though not to King, who reports one
breakup-to-makeup after another without hazarding a guess as to
what's going on.)
</P>
<P>
   King, by contrast, seems barely acquainted with the people in
his own book. Late in ``The Operator,'' he describes Geffen and
agent Sandy Gallin as ``like brothers, having spoken to each other
on average five times a day, every day _ barring other spats _
since the late 1960s.'' Odd, then, that, Gallin makes no more of an
impression on the reader than a half-dozen other show-biz types who
pass wraithlike through these pages. Likewise, Geffen's one-time
lover and longtime friend Bob Brassel is described in a handful of
passages as dramatically struggling with drug addiction _ and then
the matter's dropped. Brassel continues to show up here and there
as a friend and colleague, but whether or not with a monkey on his
back we don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Geffen supposedly lost his lunch when he discovered how much of
his business dealings ``The Operator'' would detail, but the truth
is it bears little substantive malice. It's too disembodied to do
much damage.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that Geffen's rage was instead triggered by the
realization that King was simply too much of a stiff for the book
to make the sort of splash Geffen was hoping for?
</P>
<P>
   If so, give the Operator this much credit: By making a big stink
about King's botch, he drove it to the No. 20 slot on Amazon before
it even came out. Thanks to him, the last thing anyone is going to
do is ignore the story of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
