<HEADER>
A5648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-ROBERTS24-COX     03-23 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ROBERTS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Books are easy part author Nora Roberts
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Nora Roberts does indeed sleep _ every night, she
says _ but her output indicates otherwise. In 20 years, she's
published 134 novels under various names, the most famous being
Nora Roberts, which is all her readers need to know. They'll buy
the book and they'll devour the book, and way more often than not,
they'll love the book if it's by Nora Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't get ideas in my sleep,'' she says wearily.
Roberts, 49, is well into a six-week book tour and frankly, she's
tired, having been asked every conceivable question in every
conceivable way. ``I can't imagine what I haven't been asked,'' she
said. ``If it can be said, I've said it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been on the road for a couple of weeks, you
suddenly start thinking this is what you do. This is your
reality,'' she said. ``You start thinking, `I don't really write, I
just travel across the country, stay in hotels, talk to reporters
and sign books. And that's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Her publisher, G.P. Putnam's Sons, believes in the power of the
book tour, and Roberts hits the road nearly every spring in support
of a new hardcover. This time out, she's pushing ``Carolina Moon,''
a romantic mystery set in the South. Publisher's Weekly said it may
be her personal best, ``as atmospheric and unsettling as a
Tennessee Williams play.'' One hundred thirty-four books under her
belt, and not even the critics can find fault.
</P>
<P>
   But the tour takes its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty good at the tour, but the only part that's fun is
actually making contact with the reader. It's really nice to make
that face-to-face contact ... It's the connection, a personal
connection, for me anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traveling is horrible, the getting up at 4:30 a.m. is
horrible, and possibly in violation of the Geneva Convention,'' she
said. ``I believe that book tours are the only legalized torture in
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' story is well-known: Stuck at home during the 1979
blizzard with a 2- and a 5-year-old, she saved her sanity by
writing down the stories that had always been in her head. She's
never stopped. She's well into her second marriage, to a carpenter
hired to build bookshelves. Her children are well grown and she's
undeniably rich enough to take it easy.
</P>
<P>
   But she won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would I do? I love the process of writing a book. It's
hard work, and has all the pitfalls of hard work, but it's the best
job in the world, and I don't have to wear pantyhose to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home, in a secluded house in a small Maryland town, her
``dream of a typical day'' would be an early-morning workout
(``After all, you sit on your butt the rest of the day''), time
spent on e-mail correspondence and cruising the Internet (``I love
the Net''), then down to work for six to eight hours before
thoughts of what to make for dinner take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for my process, I do a fairly quick draft, from Page 1 to
the end. Then I go back to Page 1 to see if the story holds, get to
know my characters better, figure out the thread of the theme,
while fleshing it out, adding texture and taking out what doesn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'll do at least one more draft to polish,'' she said.
Never has she given up once a story has begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too stubborn. I have a fairly fluid imagination and a
flexible mind, so that when I do run into a wall with a book, I can
figure a way over, under or around it instead of just backing
off.''
</P>
<P>
   She's an Energizer Bunny of a writer, albeit a bunny with six or
seven arms. She writes under the pseudonym J.D. Robb ``darker,
gritter, slightly more mystery-oriented books, set in the near
future.''
</P>
<P>
   She also keeps her hand in the paperback original romance trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like that form, the short form,'' Roberts said. ``I
remember what it was like to be a voracious reader with a 2- and
5-year-old, and not have much time. I remember how those short, fun
romances saved my sanity.''
</P>
<P>
   She's still a voracious reader _ ``If you don't read, how can
you write?'' _ having packed some Patricia Gaffney, Lisa
Scottoline, Stephen King, Lawrence Block and others for her trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read all across the board,'' she said, before launching into
a glowing recommendation of Gaffney's ``The Saving Graces.'' She's
not reluctant to talk about the scandal involving romance writer
Janet Dailey, who was accused of plagiarizing Roberts' work in
multiple books over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' she said. ``I do think writers,
publishers and readers should take plagiarism more seriously than I
discovered a lot of them do. That is one line that should never be
crossed in our business. I'm pleased we settled and I'm pleased I
could donate the financial settlement to the cause of literacy.''
</P>
<P>
   She as certain as she can be that she won't repeat herself, no
matter how long she continues to write.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain themes that reverberate, and that becomes a
matter of style,'' she said. ``Family becomes important in a lot of
my work, and certainly romance _ that human need to find a mate,
someone who loves us warts and all and vice versa. Those things
echo with different character types, situations, canvases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having just 88 keys on piano: You can still make a
lot of music.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
