<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-AROUND-WORLD24-COX     03-23 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AROUND-WORLD24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making scents of each country
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Why go around the world?
</P>
<P>
   Because it has been only 600 years since people thought the
world was flat.
</P>
<P>
   Because I've never done it.
</P>
<P>
   Because there's still a mystique to circumnavigating the earth,
to see its boundaries, to see what's out there, to see that that's
all there is. It's still frightening, and exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   And I wanted to experience it, if only briefly. I left West Palm
Beach on Feb. 3 and traveled east with a few detours south to
Arabia, north to China, and who could go around the world without
seeing Australia?
</P>
<P>
   I was back home at 4 a.m. March 3 throwing rocks at my
roommate's second-floor window to let me in.
</P>
<P>
   In that short length of time, I was on 12 airplanes for a total
of 64 hours _ 2 1/2 days _ and in airports probably just as long;
on trains for 24 hours; on a river boat for one day; and on ferries
for seven hours.
</P>
<P>
   It was a marathon trip _ eight countries in four weeks and
sometimes several cities in one country. There were at least four
24-hour periods when I didn't sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, nothing bad happened. My schedule ticked away like a
Swiss clock. Nothing was stolen and I didn't miss a plane, although
an ATM in Hong Kong told me there was no money available in my
checking account, which worried me quite a bit until I went to
another machine, which said I had plenty. Whew!
</P>
<P>
   I had to do business in nine currencies.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one major inconvenience and that was in Sydney.
At 1 a.m., I was standing on a road with my backpack in a rough
neighborhood waiting for a taxi. The hotel where I had reservations
was too awful even by my low standards. And the phone in the rooms
didn't work, so I couldn't use my laptop to send my stories. So I
left.
</P>
<P>
   At least I wasn't alone on the sidewalk. There were several
homeless drunks to keep me company, friendly and polite fellas, but
who needs that? A taxi finally came and I said, ``Is there a Hyatt
or Hilton nearby?''
</P>
<P>
   Eight countries, each with different sights, cultures and
smells.
</P>
<P>
   St. James Park in London smelled of clover; Athens of pine
trees; Bahrain and Oman had the dry sagey scent of the desert;
Singapore, the heady fragrance of gardenias and jasmine; Australia,
cow manure and grass, and in China, damp, rich earth.
</P>
<P>
   In that short time, I saw so much _ Buckingham Palace and the
Changing of the Guard, and I was one of the first to ride the new,
humongous Ferris wheel-type ride next to the Thames.
</P>
<P>
   I saw the ancient Parthenon on top of the Acropolis in Athens,
the Eiffel Tower in Paris, the Opera House in Sydney, and the
Yangtze River in China.
</P>
<P>
   Many times the fast pace had the surreal feeling of a cruise,
especially when I was half awake. I saw a cathedral and had a
fleeting thought: When did Notre Dame get a clock on the tower?
Oops, wrong city, that's Westminster in London.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, the real joys of the trip were the people I met.
And by traveling alone, I met many kind and generous men and women,
and I mostly stayed quiet and listened to their stories. I think of
them as my extended family because the world is small and we are
connected in so many ways.
</P>
<P>
   It's wonderful how people will open up to you. I met an Indian
man on the Bahrain-to-Singapore flight who was agonizing over a job
opportunity in Bahrain. He worried that the money wasn't worth the
change in lifestyle from his new home in New Zealand, where he had
a wife and new baby waiting for him. He described the situation and
asked me my opinion. I told him not to take the job, and he decided
then and there to stay put, and he was greatly relieved.
</P>
<P>
   A young, professional Chinese woman on the Hong Kong to
Chongqing flight told me how she missed her job and friends in
Melbourne, Australia, where she and her husband had gone before
Hong Kong's handover to China. Now she lived in Chongqing, where
her husband worked. ``He told me he would never live in China
again, and now we've been there for a year,'' she said sadly.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Lisa Rickard, the beautiful vegetarian jillaroo
(cowgirl) in Australia, and Brian Skerrett, the cattle station
owner who chuckled at everything I said. And my Australian stock
horse, Lucille. What a good-natured, big-boned gal.
</P>
<P>
   And of course all the people who helped me, who gave me
directions, suggested where to sleep and where to eat, who helped
me with my backpack, and otherwise made the long road wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   I came away from the trip with two frightening conclusions: The
world is so small and there are so many people, factories, cities
and new suburbs in such a finite place; and the world is so large,
especially when you're on the other side, and it suddenly hits you
that it would take at least two days to get home.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to be home, but I feel like I'm standing still, that I
should be exploring.
</P>
<P>
   And I already miss my greater home _ the world.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   MY 42,000 MILES AROUND THE WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Favorite way to communicate with home and work: Cybercafes,
which come in all shapes and personalities, are the best way to
stay in touch. In Singapore, I went to a coffee shop, in Athens I
found a rowdy hangout for Greek computer nerds, and in Sydney I
stumbled on a computer in a bar by the harbor. There was a machine
that you could blow into to check your blood-alcohol level. You
wouldn't want to get an EUI _ e-mailing under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   Easiest way to get money: ATMs are not Greek to me. There are
many things I don't know how to do, but I do know how to work an
ATM, and in just about any language _ Arabic, Greek, Chinese, you
name it. If I'm in doubt about boxes to check, I just guess, and
everything generally turns out OK. Except in Bahrain, I got about
$300 worth of Bahrain dinars when all I needed was $10 for a taxi.
Luckily they had an exchange bureau at the airport, because who
else would want Bahrain money?
</P>
<P>
   Best psychic experience: I always ask taxi drivers how much the
fare will be before I get in. In Chongqing, China, the driver
quoted an amount, but soon it became clear he had no idea where I
wanted to go. He made a flying motion, which meant he wanted to
know if I wanted to go to the airport. I shook my head ``no'' and
repeated the name of the hotel. He didn't understand me, and I was
wondering what to do when I happened to see the hotel up on a hill,
and pointed to it. He laughed, and he explained to the desk person
that he had concentrated on what I was thinking and that's how we
went directly to the hotel _ Chinese mental telepathy.
</P>
<P>
   Most gross moment: At the jackaroo school in Australia, where I
was learning to be a jillaroo, I got the great job of helping
scrape maggots out of a horse's infected hoof. The smell was
indescribable. That was the first of many times I figured I should
probably keep my day job.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
