   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   AROUND-WORLD _ My incredible journey around the world: eight
countries, 12 flights, five trains and one old seamship.
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COCONUTGROVE _ COCONUT GROVE, Fla. _ The Coconut Grove
Bed and Breakfast has modern art and it's near great Miami sites.
(Thurwachter, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EUROPE _ The dawn of a new century finds much to and even
more changing in Europe. Our special expanded Travel section visits
emerging destinations such as Krakow, Poland, Salamanca, Spain and
Basel, Switzerland, as well as perennial favorites such as London
and Paris. Rick Steves, host of the PBS series ``Travels in
Europe'' picks 11 hot spots for 2000 and beyond. And our readers
share memories of previous European adventures and their dreams of
ones to come.
</P>
<P>
   Cover is a Vernon Carne illustration of a collage European flags
framing a photo of a young woman feeding the pigeons in Venice's
St. Mark's Square, with teases across bottom to various
destinations highlighted inside.
</P>
<P>
   (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND _ BASEL, Switzerland _ Clang. Creak. Clang. Creak.
You can hear the art of the Museum Jean Tinguely before you see it.
The source of all that noise is a fountain set in the green expanse
in front of the garden entrance. The Swiss artist's Rube
Goldbergesque contraption grinds its gears for no other reason than
to delight viewers with its whimsy. The airy Tinguely museum_ where
the assemblages of machinery, cow skulls, and musical instruments
look like giant toys _ is only one of the many sources of appeal
for art lovers in this town of 200,000 in northwest Switzerland.
(Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
</P>
<P>
   POMPIDOU _ PARIS _ After two years and upwards of $88 million,
the Pompidou Center is back in fine fettle. No more peeling paint.
No more cigarette butts in the crevices of its famous exterior
elevator. Best of all, the renovation has improved the place. Renzo
Piano Building Workshop, the Genoa-based firm designed the exterior
and public spaces. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN _ SALAMANCA, Spain _ This is a town time forgot to forget,
a place where you can stumble through the ages just by ...
stumbling. Stepping down narrow streets after debating fascist
politics late into the night with a Franco-yearning bartender (his
argument: the trains ran on time), running a hand along sandstone
walls centuries have worn smooth or artisans have carved into the
likenesses of saints or popes or frogs or clamshells, passing
students and nuns and old couples locked arm-in-arm ... Traveling
through Salamanca like this, buzzing on its college-town ambiance
and rounds of canas (draft beer), you turn a dark corner you didn't
mean to turn and suddenly find yourself all alone _ as removed from
the modern world as a mid-millennium monk.(Jubera, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
</P>
<P>
   WARBIRD _ KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ For almost every day of every week
during the past 29 years, Tom Reilly has taken ``living history''
to a higher altitude. Reilly, the founder and owner of the Flying
Tigers Warbird Restoration Museum, a few minutes up the road from
Disney World, specializes in amusements for big boys and girls.
Reilly makes the past come alive _ obtaining, for the most part,
the wreckage of World War II airplanes, then rebuilding them from
top to bottom.(JESMITH, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WARBIRD-FLY _ KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ At 6,000 feet, my left hand was
on the stick of the 1944 model AT-6 Texan, my right making sure
once again that the emergency release of my parachute was still
where it should be. I listened via headphones to the instructions
of Jay Vandersluis, the veteran pilot who sat in the rear seat of
the Marine Corps two-seat trainer, as we zipped along at 230 mph.
It's all a part of Warbird Adventures, operated alongside Tom
Reilly's warbird museum near Orlando.(JESMITH, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
