<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5668 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-TEXAS-DRAWL-HNS &LR;      03-23 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DRAWL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S IN THE DRAWL, Y'ALL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ He pronounces nuclear as ``nuclar,'' calls the
Midwestern state ``Illinoise,'' brags about his ``sussesses''
(that's successes) and has practically dropped the letter ``g''
from his alphabet when it ends a word.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound like the next president?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his father, George W. Bush will never have to fend off
accusations that he lacks Texas roots. While the Texas governor
doesn't have former President Lyndon Johnson's deep drawl, there
are traces of his West Texas upbringing in almost every syllable.
</P>
<P>
   The way ``Dubya'' talks is not expected to become a campaign
issue, although some language experts believe that in a close
election his accent might cost him some votes by subtly reinforcing
a perception that he is not up to the job.
</P>
<P>
   An accent says an ``enormous amount'' about a person, says Donna
Jo Napoli, director of the linguistics program at Swarthmore
College. It can provide clues about where an individual lives or
was reared and his or her level of education and cultural, ethnic
or racial background.
</P>
<P>
   Some accents continue to perpetuate stereotypes. A ``New Yawk''
accent can connote pushiness, while a Southern accent can mark
someone as slow or uneducated. There remains ``a terrific amount of
prejudice'' against most Southern accents, Napoli says.
</P>
<P>
   One of her students, who lived in Georgia until high school when
her family relocated to Pennsylvania, taped a passage with a
Southern accent and a Philadelphia dialect.
</P>
<P>
   The student randomly approached strangers and asked them to
determine age, race and intelligence level from listening to the
tape. Most associated the Georgia accent with lower intelligence
and less education, Napoli says.
</P>
<P>
   However, having a distinct accent is no longer seen as a
detriment to becoming president. Two of the last four presidents _
Bill Clinton and Jimmy Carter _ have strong Southern accents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all used to a Southern variety of speech with Bill
Clinton, and no one thinks he is dumb,'' says Napoli. ``You might
think that Bill Clinton is a man of poor judgment, but you don't
think he's a man of deficient intellect.''
</P>
<P>
   In other areas _ particularly the workplace _ a strong accent
can still be a hindrance no matter how smart or talented you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are going to succeed in any kind of traditional
organization don't have to just dress alike, but they have to sound
alike to some degree for their ideas to be valued,'' says Tony
Shelton, president of Shelton &AMP; Caudle, a Houston-based firm that
specializes in communication training.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton says speaking the same language in the same way is
particularly important at big oil, banking and accounting
companies, although not so much in the emerging ``dot.com''
companies that value individuality.
</P>
<P>
   Television news is another area where reporters often get rid of
any trace of an accent to be successful. Reporter Cynthia Hunt of
the ABC affiliate in Houston says she has been turned down for
``many jobs'' in television because of her Alabama accent.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Hunt, accents don't matter at KTRK-Channel 13,
which has remained the city's No. 1 news station in part by
highlighting strong personalities. The station snapped her up three
years ago, and she reports the top story on many nights.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt has worked with a vocal coach to learn to control her
accent when needed since it tends to be more pronounced when she is
excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound like everybody else or not sound like
me, but I do want to sound professional enough so that I'm not a
distraction,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She takes heart from the fact that ABC News anchor Peter
Jennings has been successful without losing all traces of his
Canadian accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, diversity in the way people look and sound is being
accepted more,'' Hunt says. ``We're given so many images, I think
that's the way it has to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain accents are almost always advantageous. To many
Americans, a British accent connotes being refined and educated,
while a French or Italian accent sounds romantic.
</P>
<P>
   Before appearing on TBS's film-and-food show ``Dinner &AMP; a
Movie'' earlier this month, Alberto Baffoni, the Italian-born
executive chef and owner of Simposio Ristorante Italiano, went to
Shelton's firm for help in preparing for his appearance on the
nationally televised broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston chef had won a competition among 10 chefs from
throughout the country to appear on the show. He prepared the
``Sole Sister's Seafood Medley with My God's Holy Sauce'' during
breaks of the TBS showing of ``Sister Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton gave Baffoni some tips for staying calm during the
taping but didn't attempt to alter his accent. ``It reinforced what
he was doing there,'' Shelton says. ``One thing we associate with
Italy is food.''
</P>
<P>
   During the taping, the host of the show was so charmed by
Baffoni's accent that she said, ``Just talk. I don't care what you
say.''
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian salesman who came to Shelton's firm was not so
well-accepted. Although he was charming, his accent did not go over
with his clients in central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``His accent always said he was an outsider,'' Shelton says.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Heath, professor of communication at the University of
Houston, recalls that a neurologist once came to him for help in
making his speech more interesting, clear and lively.
</P>
<P>
   But the physician, who studied at a renowned medical school in
Colombia and testified often in insurance cases, did not want his
Spanish-tinged accent fiddled with because he believed it made him
sound more authoritative.
</P>
<P>
   ``My accent earns me an additional $150 to $200 an hour,'' he
told Heath.
</P>
<P>
   What effect accents will have on the presidential race is, thus
far, unclear. Though the likely Democratic nominee, Vice President
Al Gore, claims Tennessee as his home, he retains little vestiges
of a Southern accent. He spent much of his childhood in Washington,
D.C., where his father was a senator, and he attended Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that many people retain the accent they picked up as
a child, which accounts for Bush's Texas-tinged way of speaking.
Although Bush spent summers in Maine and attended an East Coast
boarding school and Yale University, he retains an accent from
early years in Midland and Odessa.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Lyndon Johnson's Texas accent, though, Bush's accent
is ``melodious,'' says Heath. ``LBJ's accent hurt peoples' ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's nonverbal mannerisms, such as the smirk on his face at
inopportune times during some primary debates, has drawn more
negative reaction than his ``hybrid accent,'' which combines a
Texas twang and the flat sounds typical of New Englanders, Heath
says.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's accent is not strong, agrees Sydney Lamb, professor
emeritus of linguistics and cognitive science at Rice University in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he has a tendency to stumble on his words a little bit.
And he doesn't like long, complex sentences the way Bill Clinton
does or Al Gore,'' Lamb says. ``But he's not nearly as bad as
(former Vice President Dan) Quayle.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tendency to mangle the English language has happened so
frequently that the Internet publication Slate has compiled a list
of ``Bushisms,'' including this one:
</P>
<P>
   During a celebration of ``Perseverance Month'' at a New
Hampshire elementary school, Bush said, ``This is Preservation
Month. I appreciate preservation. It's what you do when you run for
president. You have to preserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb says, ``It will be interesting to see what happens when he
debates with Al Gore, because Gore is very fluent.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shelton points out that sometimes a politician can overcome
the drawback of a distinctive accent through the sheer force of his
personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at John F. Kennedy. He was so charismatic he was able to
get the audience past his saying `Cuber' instead of `Cuba',''
Shelton says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
