<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-RUSSIA-AID-$ADV26-COX     03-23 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-AID-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILLIONS IN U.S. AID TO RUSSIA UNLIKELY TO STOP WITH PUTIN
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With chart information attached at end of story.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-SECURITY-$ADV26.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the years after the Soviet Union's
disintegration, the United States has sent Russia more than $7
billion to safeguard its nuclear arsenal, feed its people, prop up
its space program and nourish the seedlings of a private enterprise
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been, by almost all accounts, less than
stellar.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economy has taken a nose-dive. Its space program fell
behind in building its components for the International Space
Station, creating delays for the project and cost overruns for U.S.
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a six-year effort and a half-billion dollars in U.S.
assistance, only a small amount of Russia's nuclear materials are
now stored in secure buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there are few signs that America is about to cut off
the aid spigot, now that acting President Vladimir Putin, the
former KGB officer, moves toward becoming Russia's second
democratically elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already tolerated all kinds of shenanigans in Russia for
a very long time,'' said Dan Goure, a deputy director at the
Washington research group, Center for Strategic and International
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin would have to go almost out of his way to do something
so outrageous, so anti-American that it would cause either (the
United States or Russia) to ratchet back their relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Goure and others readily concede that direct American aid, plus
$22.6 billion in loans from the International Monetary Fund and $11
billion from the World Bank have not accomplished a great deal
toward solving Russia's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he held that it is hard to see how any U.S. administration
would suspend aid to a country with the world's largest land mass
and a second largest stockpile of nuclear weaponry. ``If anything
goes wrong, the blame falls on the administration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one outspoken critic of aid to Russia predicted that
Putin may prove more successful in dealing with the United States
than his ailing predecessor Boris Yeltsin, whose U.S. relations
went from sweet to sour during his often-rocky tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin is smarter, shrewder and more calculating,'' said David
Kramer, senior fellow at the Project for the New American Century,
a small conservative research group based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Direct bilateral aid, in financial terms, is not very
significant for propping up Putin,'' Kramer said. But, he added
that it has symbolic power: ``It sends a political message: if
there is no change in (aid) policy, then it suggests that we are
continuing business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's strategy has been to talk tough and crack down on
Chechen rebels at home as he proposes more accommodation on nuclear
issues abroad. He has endorsed ratification for the long-delayed
START II missile treaty, and said he might be open to changing the
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty to permit a U.S. missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   The new Russian leader also restored NATO ties which had been
frayed during the U.S.-led bombing of Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk could avert attention from Russian problems, ranging
from widespread corruption to the glacial pace of reforms and
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence of friction in U.S.-Russian joint efforts
continues. Among recent examples, the U.S. General Accounting
Office warned earlier this month that Russia and the rest of the
old Soviet Union still have 650 metric tons of enriched uranium and
plutonium. That's enough to make about 40,000 nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those nuclear materials remain in unsecured buildings
and under increasing threat of theft, said the GAO, which is the
investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after spending $481 million over six years, the United
States completed installation of security systems for just 7
percent of that material, the accounting office reported.
</P>
<P>
   The slow pace was traced largely to resistance from the Russian
government, which has locked U.S. officials out of the nuclar
weapons complex where much of the material is stored. Moreover, the
Russian government has soaked up some of the U.S. aid by taxing it.
</P>
<P>
   American costs for safeguarding and dismantling the nuclear
arsenal have reached $5 billion with no clear end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone recognizes that these are large amounts of money,''
said Jon B. Wolfsthal, an associate with the Carnegie Endowment for
Peace and a former special assistant and policy adviser for the
U.S. Department of Energy, which runs much of nuclear safeguard
efforts in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, there's no way to overstate the threat that
the United States now faces from the former of Soviet Union,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the nuclear material watched over by guards who had no
coats or boots in the winter and no pay in summer, and nuclear
weapons labs where Russian scientists, unpaid for months at a time,
could sell their expertise to Iran, Iraq or China.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. subsidies have not been completely successful, he
acknowledged, but he added, ``Half a loaf is better than no loaf.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems have also haunted the U.S.-Russian space projects.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's failure to complete its space station components on
time have been estimated by the House Science Committee to have
cost billions of dollars in extra expenses to NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, congressional investigators are currently looking into
safety problems with two Russian-built modules, including one that
has already been launched into orbit for the space station. Neither
module offers enough protection from space debris, neither can
operate after loss of cabin pressure and both have excessive noise
levels, Allen Li, a GAO official, told a House subcommittee on
March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Concern in Congress over whether the Russian space agency was
helping Iran develop long-range missiles prompted both houses to
pass resolutions threatening to cut off Russian space subsidies
unless the president can certify that no missile information was
passed along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the policy of an ally, but that's not what we are,''
said Goure of CSIS. ``The notion of a strategic partnership which
the Clinton administration touted five years ago is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be a difficult relationship. There's no doubt
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   FOLLOWING ARE CATEGORIES AND TOTAL EXPENDITURES FOR U.S.
ASSISTANCE TO RUSSIA FROM 1992 THROUGH (FISCAL YEAR) 1999:
</P>
<P>
   DIRECT U.S. AID
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $2.3 billion from the Freedom Support Act, which includes
funds to support reforms for farmers, businesses and criminal
justice authorities and other segments of the country;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $2.4 million??? in food assistance;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $790 million from the U.S. Department of Defense to assist in
nuclear weapons dismantlement;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $778 million in subsidies to the Russian space agency;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $584 million from the U.S. Department of Energy to assist in
improving safety for nuclear reactors and for the stockpiles of
nuclear weaponry and nuclear materials;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $168 million in miscellaneous programs, including the U.S.
Information Agency and Peace Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Total: $7 billion
</P>
<P>
   MULTILATERAL AID
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $11.0 billion in loans from the World Bank
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $22.6 billion in loans from the International Monetary Fund
</P>
<P>
   Sources: U.S. State Department; House Science Committee; and
World Bank.
</P>
