<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5673 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BARBER-FAMILY-HNS &LR;      03-23 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBER-FAMILY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNIPS OFF THE OLD BLOCK 
 
FOR THE ORTUNO FAMILY, BECOMING A BARBER IS A TIME-HONORED
TRADITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Ortuno)  
 
By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Whenever the Ortuno family gets together, you could
say it's a hair-raising experience.
</P>
<P>
   Ezequiel Ortuno is a barber. So is his brother, Amado. And his
other brother, Manuel. Sister Janete Ortuno Castro is also a
barber. So are sisters Laura Fraire, Mayda Ortuno, Gloria
Rodriguez, Leticia Ramirez, Maria Alma Ortuno Pineda and Marisela
Ortuno. Of the seven sisters, five are cosmetologists as well as
barbers.
</P>
<P>
   Only one sister, Reyna Gonzalez, defied the odds. She became an
optician.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   Ezequiel's wife, Elizabeth, didn't start out as a barber, but
she is one now.
</P>
<P>
   So is Ortuno cousin Jaime Gonzalez. And he's not the only one.
All told, there are some 60 Ortuno-family cousins who live in
Houston; almost all are barbers. Some are married to barbers.
</P>
<P>
   Get anywhere near the Ortuno family, it seems, and you get the
urge to cut hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father always told us, `Wherever you go, if you have a comb
and scissors, you will always have a job, always have a means to
eat,''' Ezequiel says.
</P>
<P>
   He and his siblings stand inside Peluqueria Acapulco Unisex No.
1 and Acapulco Barber Shop No. 2, two comfortably worn shops
located next to each other on the city's east side. Together, the
brothers and sisters represent a veritable coiffure empire
traceable to one man _ father Jesus Ortuno, a barber from Mexico
who moved to the United States in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Now back in Mexico City to care for his aging parents, Ortuno,
65, left behind his hair-trimming offspring _ call them snips off
the old block _ to run his shops. And they run those shops in the
same fashion as their father _ staying open late, working on
weekends, catering to a steadfastly loyal clientele year after
year.
</P>
<P>
   The siblings, who range in age from to 22 to 41, grew up
standing next to their father's chair, watching and learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all went to formal school, too, but that's just where you
learn the basics,'' says Janete. ``The real techniques, we learned
from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The shops are in a neighborhood dotted with modest homes, little
shops, taquerias and signs in Spanish, across from a large,
burned-out lot. Housed in a reconverted old home and garage, the
shops are still decorated with white Christmas lights. Inside,
there are maroon leather barber chairs, some cracked with age, and
TVs and music playing. The sons work on the barber side, the
daughters on the beauty parlor side. (A handful of nonfamily
employees work there, as well.)
</P>
<P>
   The Ortuno family is one of those big, loud, loving families.
The sisters breeze in one at a time, to a flurry of hugging and
cheek-kissing. A passel of toddlers and small children wearing
backpacks (future barbers and cosmetologists, no doubt) circulate
rambunctiously through the store. All the siblings talk at once,
offering their own rendition of history, sometimes slipping into
Spanish, the decibel level rising, until one of them catches a wave
and starts telling an anecdote, at which point the others say
``Sshh!'' and ``Esperate!'' to those who would cut in.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has great hair.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, born in Guerrero, Mexico, was the oldest of nine
brothers, says Janete, the office manager and natural family
storyteller. As a young man, he spent time on a ranch, where he
taught himself to cut hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no mirrors, so they used bowls of water as their
reflection,'' says Gloria, who, as the eldest, serves as a
repository for some of the earliest stories.
</P>
<P>
   He started with his own shop in Mexico City in 1967. Ezequiel
was 4. ``I would help with the cleaning, sweeping, and shining
shoes,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   When their father arrived in Houston, he worked as a barber at
Figaros _ a shop around the corner, just recently closed _ then
rented a shop, saving money to open a shop of his own. For a time,
he also ran a Mexican restaurAn8 &QL;  Wc)it burned down.
</P>
<P>
   Ezequiel was the first of the siblings to become a barber, after
he graduated from high school in 1983. Gloria followed. The rest
fell in line, one after the other. (All went to barber and beauty
school.) Over the years, about 40 nephews were sent from Mexico to
live with Jesus, so he raised not only his own large brood but many
of his brothers' children as well. Through him, all were infused
with the barbering bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want the truth?'' asks Janete, feisty and outspoken. ``My
dad was very strict. If it hadn't been for him, we probably would
have gone our separate (career) ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The only one, it seems, who did not become a barber was their
mother, Maria. Ironically, it was she who cut the children's hair
when they were little. (Dad was too busy.)
</P>
<P>
   Marisela, 23, is another one who, like Reyna, might jump ship
one day. Working toward a business management degree at the
University of Houston, she wants to become an entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll still do hair on the side,'' she insists.
</P>
<P>
   She and Mayda, 22, the only ones who aren't married, still live
in the small family home down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up under the unnerving gaze of an expert barber wasn't
always easy, the siblings say. Jesus Ortuno is a man of exacting
ways. He held his children to high standards and was stinting with
praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would mess up, he would make `stop' motions with his
hands,'' says Gloria, making the cut-throat sign to illustrate.
``So we would stand there combing, combing, until he would finish
with his customer, and then he would come over and start saying,
`What's wrong with you? I send you to school and you still can't
cut hair?'''
</P>
<P>
   It hurt, they say. But it pushed them to get better.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, their father was a pioneer, pushing his daughters
to excel in a nontraditional career. Often, male customers were
skeptical that a female could be a good barber _ a manly skill that
involves shaving, trimming mustaches and so on. Gloria, the first
female, had to blaze the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men would come in and my father would be busy, and they'd say,
`That's OK, we'll wait,''' says Janete. ``When (Gloria) finally got
her chance, she just blew them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrella Ortuno, the oldest of Ezequiel's four daughters, is an
eighth-grader and already making noises that she wants to cut hair
one day. Gloria's daughter, Claudia, already has her cosmetology
license, as does Jasmin, the daughter of Ever Ortuno, a half-sister
from Jesus' first marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Amado's sons say they want to become barbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see us doing it and they want to do it,'' says Janete.
</P>
<P>
   It's because they enjoy their work, she says, and the
companionship that follows. Most of the family members play soccer,
taking over a nearby park after 9 p.m., when the shops close. And
they have big family birthday parties at night _ a cousin acts as
disc jockey _ in the larger shop, covering the windows so clients
won't come knocking for a haircut. (Some do anyway, even during the
family's Thanksgiving celebration.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tips on how to trim, shave and razor cut, Jesus
Ortuno taught his children other important lessons, Ezequiel says.
An important one was to respect one another and other people. To
always be polite, even when others are rude. To stay together, no
matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see other families here in the year 2000, and they're all
scattered,'' says Janete. ``My dad's goal was always the unity of
the family. We're workers, but we're also family.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a family empire that recently came under siege. Last March,
Del Sol, a collection of indoor shops in the adjacent lot, burned
down. The store's management had allowed the hair shops and other
nearby businesses to use its large parking lot for clients. Janete
says the new owner recently asked about buying their shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it wasn't for sale,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to fence the parking lot, taking away the
shop's parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, she replied. No sale.
</P>
<P>
   The fence went up. Still, the customers come, parking where they
can, making do. This doesn't surprise the Ortunos: They have
clients who drive from as far away as Austin _ about 2 hours _ to
get their hair cut the Ortuno way. It's really not about
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``To them, this feels like little Mexico,'' Ezequiel says. ``And
they say we're `autentico.' Authentic barbers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's how their father taught them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
