<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-$A     03-23 3144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE SADDEST FACE OF AFRICA'S BURGEONING AIDS CRISIS: ORPHANS
 &HT;    (2500&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With half-page color map-graphic from the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MBARE, Zimbabwe _ In a wooden shed behind one of the tiny
cinderblock houses that line this district's narrow dirt roads,
12-year-old Nomsa Mwale struggles with her new role as mother.
</P>
<P>
   Nomsa's father died of AIDS in 1998. Six months ago, her mother
followed him, leaving the five children to make their way in a
world that offers little comfort and less hope.
</P>
<P>
   As she speaks, Nomsa stares vacantly away from the people who
have come to see her. She is thin and has a sweet, doe-like face.
With a tiny, wispy voice, she answers the questions about her
family's circumstance, but she does not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The first-born girl, it has fallen to her to care for older
brother Sibongile, 15, and the three younger children: Shonia, 10;
Garikai, 9; and Betina, 8.
</P>
<P>
   Their life is a frenzy of survival guided by little more than
the advice given by their mother as she prepared her children for
their journey without her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me to tell the boys not to go to people's houses
because if something is missing, they will blame them,'' Nomsa
says. ``She said, 'You need to feed the others but also you must
learn to take care of yourself.'''
</P>
<P>
   This was the best advice, because Nomsa has almost no one but
herself.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS epidemic in Africa is an orphan-making machine,
striking down millions of men and women in their prime
child-rearing years. A recent United Nations report estimates that
Africa is home to more than 9 million children who have lost their
parents to AIDS. If nothing changes, this number is expected to
triple over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   In Zimbabwe, there are as many as 800,000 AIDS orphans. In one
rural school, 24 percent of its 946 students have lost their
parents to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   As international aid groups stagger under the weight of their
task and complain bitterly over the of the lack of funding from the
West _ most notably, the United States _ the machine shows no sign
of slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, about 400 Zimbabweans die from AIDS-related illnesses,
most of them likely to have children. It is the same story across
Africa, where new statistics show that 23.3 million people are
infected with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS. In 1998, 2.2 million
Africans died from AIDS-related illnesses; while 200,000 died in
the continent's many wars.
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of Zimbabwe's 11 million to 13 million
residents are HIV-positive, the highest AIDS rate in Africa. In
this one country, roughly half the size of Texas, twice as many
people are infected with the AIDS virus than in all of North
America. An estimated 3,000 more are infected each week.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something unexpected happens, virtually all will die.
AIDS already permeates most lives here. Stories of stricken
relatives are as common as comments on the weather. There is a
never-ending parade of funerals. Mortuaries in the major cities _
Harare and Bulawayo _ remain open 24 hours a day to handle the boom
of bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The epidemic has decimated the country's most productive layer
of society _ the 18- to 40-year-olds who do the work, pay the taxes
and raise the children.
</P>
<P>
   They leave behind legions like Nomsa with little prospect of the
most basic emotional, physical or material necessities.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-by-8-foot shack occupied by Nomsa and her siblings is
surrounded by rusting lean-tos inhabited by tough-looking older
men. The children share a foul-smelling toilet and shower with the
men.
</P>
<P>
   When the children have food, usually a little something provided
by local charities, they cook on a one-burner stove. From time to
time the food is stolen by the lodgers, who pay Nomsa's uncle to
sleep in the hovels that surround the shed.
</P>
<P>
   The structures are behind a slovenly house owned by Nomsa's long
dead grandparents. The children have no legal rights to the
property, which is owned by their uncle. They have no birth
certificates to prove who they are.
</P>
<P>
   The children do laundry once a month when they have soap. The
girls sleep on the one bed inside the shed. The boys sleep on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   None go to school. They can't afford the equivalent of US$6 to
US$10 in fees each per term much less the US$10 it costs each for
uniforms and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And her extended family?
</P>
<P>
   Their uncle wants to evict them. Nomsa has a legal paper from
him demanding that they vacate the property. He has told them he
wants their space so that he can take in a few more paying lodgers.
He complains to the children bitterly about the money they're
costing him by using up his real estate. He has never been violent,
but the children are terrified of him.
</P>
<P>
   Already numbed by her losses, Nomsa cannot seem to get her mind
around this new threat.
</P>
<P>
   When asked where she will go, she has no answer. A tear streams
down her cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Local charities are struggling with the uncle trying to see if
they don't need to just pay him off to leave the children alone.
The uncle has shown little inclination to be compassionate with his
nieces and nephews.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what can we do?'' asks Kizito Makore, a volunteer with the
Mashambanzou Charity, noticeably depressed after visiting children.
``They need so much and we have so little to give.''
</P>
<P>
   While the case of Nomsa and her siblings is a bad one, it is
hardly unique.
</P>
<P>
   Before the AIDS epidemic, only 2 percent of African children
were orphaned. The rate now is as high as 11 percent, and UNICEF
expects it to reach 35 percent in Zimbabwe within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Half of those with HIV become infected before the age of 25 and
die while their children are too young to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of orphans comes at a time when extreme poverty has
reduced to near nothing an already feeble social welfare system in
this largely agrarian society. About 63 percent of the people in
Zimbabwe are classified as poor. The unemployment rate is more than
50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When AIDS strikes parents, incomes dry up. The family slips
deeper into poverty as it devotes its meager resources to caring
for sick loved ones and eventually transporting a body home and
funeral. In the rural areas, it can cost the equivalent of two
years income to bury a loved one.
</P>
<P>
   The disease has shattered the traditional system of extended
families, as witnessed with Nomsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now a fallacy that the African family is there to cushion
the impact on orphans,'' said Marvellous(CQ) Mhloyi, the chair of
population studies at the University of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Worsening economic conditions have pushed relatives to be
indifferent, even callous. ``Human beings are selfish,'' Mhloyi
says. ``Under difficult economic times, that degree of selfishness
increases.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, an uncle or other relative would take control
of the parents' assets but would also assume responsibility for the
well-being of the children, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now if the parents die, then the uncle will try to take
the house and other property and depend on others to absorb the
orphans.''
</P>
<P>
   New studies show that AIDS orphans are more likely to be
malnourished than other children. When they go to foster families,
they tend to shoulder heavier workloads than other children already
in the families. They are less likely to go to school.
</P>
<P>
   Even with so many AIDS orphans, their numbers almost certainly
will rise dramatically. More children live with parents who are
HIV-positive than the number who have already become orphans.
</P>
<P>
   Ngoni Guba, the orphan coordinator for Midland AIDS Service
Organization in Gweru, said the future for these children is grim.
Her organization cares for more than 720 AIDS orphans in central
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of them are out of school and have no skills training to
allow them to find something to do,'' she says. ``For the boys, you
can foresee delinquency and early manhood. Girls will get married
early _ maybe 15 _ and then what?''
</P>
<P>
   Girls are the most vulnerable. Teenage girls in Africa are eight
times more likely to have AIDS than boys in the same age group.
Most girls get it from older men, ``Sugar Daddies'' who trade sex
for a little money, protection or food.
</P>
<P>
   Many older HIV-infected men will pressure young girls because of
the widely accepted myth in Africa that says a man can be cleansed
of the AIDS virus by having sex with a virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a desperate struggle to care for their brothers and
sisters, many teen-age girls turn to prostitution, aid workers say.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS epidemic is also making more and more elderly people
parents again, forcing many to consume their already modest savings
on school fees and the other expenses they had assumed were behind
them. Others must resort to backbreaking manual labor to produce
enough food to feed the additional mouths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these grandparents are at the stage in life when they
need someone to look after them and then suddenly that are forced
to begin again looking after children,'' said Felicity Hatendi,
UNICEF's external relations officer in Harare.
</P>
<P>
   On a disused golf course outside Harare, Lina Smoke sits on the
hard sandy earth in the shade of a peach tree. Not far away are the
two rusting shacks she's called home for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke, who at 88 seems all bone and callous, smiles sweetly at
Terrence, her 4-year-old grandson who now knows her as mother.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence squats beside her, sucking ravenously on the peal of an
orange, a rare treat. Black ants gather under him, attracted by the
drops of juice.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Terrence and his three siblings, Kenneth, 7;
Sharon, 8; and Rovesai, 10, came to their ``ambuya'' _ the local
word for ``granny'' _ after their mother died of AIDS. Their father
was already dead from an AIDS-related illness.
</P>
<P>
   After their mother died, social workers found their ambuya and
delivered the children to her. Smoke says this was the last time
the government gave her anything.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband used to caddy at the gold course, which has been
reclaimed by native weeds, bushes and trees. He built the shacks
himself two decades ago, and they lived together there until he
died five or six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   To feed the children, she works the hard dry land to grow corn
and a green leafy vegetable around the shacks. The children, she
laughs, are too young to help her much with the tilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel too tired, I'm so old,'' she says, sitting in
the wilting afternoon heat. ``I feel I'm going to die any time,
even in the middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Then what of the children? She looks at Terrence. ``Put them in
a home.''
</P>
<P>
   Her biggest problem today is water. There is none at her home. A
neighbor who used to share now refuses the ambuya and children even
a drop. Another neighbor agreed to supply water but for 100
Zimbabwean dollars a month (a little more than US$2), a shockingly
high price. ``At the moment, I have nothing, so there is no water _
except from the rain,'' she says, clasping her tired, leathery
hands together tightly.
</P>
<P>
   She has another problem. The local government, which owns the
land she occupies, wants to sell off the old golf course and has
told her and the children to leave.
</P>
<P>
   So close to the end of her life, she cannot imagine living
elsewhere and indeed knows nowhere to go. ``Soon, I will be gone
and they can just take it all,'' she says. ``I hope they can
wait.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half the AIDS orphans end up under the care of their
grandmothers. As little support and assistance as there is for AIDS
orphans, there is less for the grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie Vlembeu, Zimbabwe's deputy director for social welfare,
said her country's resources are simply too limited to reach AIDS
orphans. In her office in central Harare, she compares the scale of
disaster to Zimbabwe's 1980 war for independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to deal with children who would be brought to us by
Army officers and others, but now we have to go out and find
them,'' she said. Her department has only one caseworker in each of
57 rural districts. Many don't have cars. ``Some areas are very
weak, and children are suffering because of it,'' she says. ``We
have inadequate resources, but even the meager resources we have,
people cannot access them.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country there are efforts to fill this enormous void.
</P>
<P>
   In a small remote valley near the northeastern village of
Mutoko, Jean Cornneck tries to provide orphans something
approximating a home. Cornneck _ called Momma Jean by everyone at
the Mother of Peace home _ says the site was selected by divine
provenance six years ago. She says that clues supplied from God via
a woman in South Africa led the home's founders to this site near
an old leper colony.
</P>
<P>
   On instructions from above, the home accepts no government
support and tries to make itself self-sufficient by farming. ``The
Lord told us to help those infected and affected by AIDS,'' says, a
gentle but forceful woman with a round face and short, snowy hair.
``And that's exactly what we do here.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she and volunteers have built a half-dozen cottages.
Each has two rooms for sleeping quarters for children, with as many
as 15 in each Spartan room. Each cottage has a kitchen and small
quarters for a woman, who acts as caretaker but is rewarded with
the title ``momma'' by her charges. Mother of Peace is home to 80
children, 35 of whom are under the age of six.
</P>
<P>
   But there are limits. Mother of Peace is at capacity but more
children continue arriving. On once recent day, Momma Jean was
handed a tiny baby, upon whom she immediately began to shower
affection.
</P>
<P>
   Both the baby's parents had died of AIDS and the child's
relatives no longer can care for it. The baby can stay until he is
old enough to leave.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the children at the home have all the signs of AIDS,
many show symptoms of other diseases such as tuberculosis, which is
enjoying a renaissance along with the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of all children under 15 are infected with HIV,
often it came with their mother's milk. In them, the virus lives on
as a morbid connection to mothers and a sad omen of their futures.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In the central Zimbabwean village of Mucheke, Tinashe Cami has
known for some time that he's not healthy. He's on the verge of 16,
yet he is so small and frail that he could easily be mistaken for
10 or 11.
</P>
<P>
   Children at school have teased him about AIDS because he is so
thin and often is wracked by a cough. A recent test shows he's
HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   He lost both his mother and the woman he came to regard as an
aunt to AIDS. He's lucky because a local group pays for his school
fees and uniform. His aunt's sister allows him to remain in the
house, where he has lived the nine years since his mother's death.
</P>
<P>
   He's a good student, even promising at geography and English.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a soldier and a teacher,'' he says, sitting on
the sofa decorated by his late aunt with a fabric adorned with
Valentine hearts. He likes the idea of being a soldier because he
views the army as a force deployed to help people in need.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to teach because he loves children. Even talking about
this ambition causes a smile to break across his face. Despite his
love of children, he has no plans to have any _ in part because of
his illness, but also because he judges the world a poor place for
kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are going this century, it's very hard to think
of having a family.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks of his mother often. ``I remember her face, it was
round and sweet,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The happiest moment of his life came during the ceremony held
when his aunt was laid to rest. In Africa, this usually takes
places some time after the body is buried and represents a farewell
and celebration of the departed one's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a very good feeling about the prospects for her soul,''
he says, smiling a little with the memory. ``Her soul has gone to a
very pure place.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the room from where he sits is a framed copy of her death
notice. On a yellowed newspaper clipping is her picture and the
words: ``No more pain, no more sleepless nights.''
</P>
<P>
   For Tinashe and the mass of Africa's AIDS orphans, this must
describe heaven itself.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Mhloyi, the University of Zimbabwe professor, expresses deep
frustration and helplessness over the epidemic and its unbridled
destruction of her people and society.
</P>
<P>
   She wonders why more isn't done. ``Sometimes you wonder if in
the West AIDS isn't seen as some kind of population control program
for Africa,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, she has watched with amazement the spectacle
over 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, the child at the center of a
custody battle between the United States and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this over one boy, when here there are hundreds of
thousands of children in Zimbabwe in so much pain,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The UN's AIDS agency estimates that it needs up to $3 billion to
fight the disease in sub-Saharan Africa. The world spent $600
billion to ward off Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Administration is seeking $325 million from a
reluctant Congress to fight the AIDS crisis in Africa. About $7
billion a year is spent in the United States on prevention,
treatment and research for AIDS _ even though there are about 25
times more people infected with HIV in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's a war, the international community reacts
decisively on the basis that it is trying to save lives,'' she
says. ``Look at Bosnia and Kosovo. I don't understand why the
international community hasn't reacted in the same way here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This too is a war.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------------
</P>
