<P>
   WOMEN-VOTERS (Washington) _ Behind much of the political debate
in recent weeks, on issues from gun control to education, is an
intensifying struggle for the votes of women, particularly suburban
mothers. One of the first tests may come on the issue of gun
violence and gun control, which pollsters say is a far more
powerful issue among women than among men. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES _ Washington &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' news category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno comments on
the case of Elian Gonzalez at her weekly news conference. By David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-TELECOM (Paris) _ France Telecom is buying 28.5 percent
of Mobilcom of Germany for $3.6 billion, giving France Telecom an
entry into Europe's biggest market after a failed attempt last
year. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-TELECOMS (Tokyo) _ Talks between the United States and
Japan over deregulation of the Japanese telecommunications market
ended in failure Thursday. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   NY-ASIAN-ART (New York) _ Asian art in Manhattan is not what it
was a few years ago, an exotic subspecies confined to the remoter
quarters of museums. At some point in the 1990s, it broke through
the silence barrier and assumed a position of prominence from which
it is not likely to retreat. And it says much for the health of the
local scene that many young Asian artists have settled in New York.
On the International Asian Art Fair, opening Friday, and events
exhibitions, galleries and artists devoted to Asian art. By Holland
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY-BIENNIAL (New York) _ The 2000 Biennial at the Whitney
Museum of American Art is truer than previous biennials to what
goes on across the country, truer to the character of the American
scene, where artists come from other countries, more respectful of
different generations and multiple strategies. But it is flat,
which may partly be chalked up to the quality of art at this
moment. By Michael Kimmelman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIDA-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Pretty much everything that's
right about ``Aida,'' the new Disney cartoon pretending to be a
Broadway musical, can be summed up in two words: Heather Headley.
By Ben Brantley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANIME-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Fans of anime _ the visually
detailed and often doom-oriented Japanese animation features that
include ``Princess Mononoke,'' ``Ghost in the Shell'' and ``Akira''
_ are bound to be delighted by ``X,'' the director Rintaro's
adaptation of the Clamp collective's graphic novels (or manga) of
the same name. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ADRENALINE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Shinobu Yaguchi's road comedy
``Adrenaline Drive'' feels as if it was built to fit the contours
of pop music, with oddball, freaky bits of comedy that leap out of
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   By Elvis Mitchell.
