<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF BADGERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE _ In Dick Bennett terminology, the man who sets a
screen is known as a ``blocker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started coaching high school in the Green Bay area,''
explained the Wisconsin mentor, ``and if I didn't use football
terminology when I arrived there I couldn't get anyone to listen to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   So he takes no umbrage when people say his Badgers are nothing
but a pad-less collection of misplaced gridders who happen to be
playing basketball. ``We try to play as physically as we can within
the rules,'' he said. ``Those who say that are pretty close to the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   With Temple sitting back on on North Broad Street wondering why
the sun had to shine so brightly on them, Wisconsin has officially
become the 2000 NCAA tournament Opponent From Hell. Regardless of
the game's outcome, the Badgers will win the fight. And they may
also win the game that goes along with it. The eighth-seeded
Badgers (20-13) have already broken the will of a pair of
high-octane offensively-oriented teams in Fresno State and
top-seeded Arizona, and now they will try to frustrate, disorient,
aggravate, and just plain humble fourth-seeded LSU (28-5) in the
West Regional semifinals at the University of New Mexico's Pit
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Wisconsin is not your prototypical modern college
basketball powerhouse is to say that coal is no longer America's
heating method of choice. The Badgers are perfectly at home in a
45-44 game. Only junior forward Mark Vershaw averages double
figures in scoring (12.2). Their marquee player, if you'll pardon
the expression, is a rugged guard who gets his jollies by shredding
offensive reputations. Surely, Mike Kelley won't be sailing into
the NBA by virtue of his 5.2 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   They are all happy doing what they do because they all know who
they are. Or aren't. There will be no team meetings asking Coach
Bennett to jazz up his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to play on a running team,'' said Andy Kowske,
another junior forward, ``I'd pull a hamstring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely not the running type,'' echoed Vershaw, whose
chief claim to fame is that he is the Big Ten's only married
player. ``That's why I came here. If we were a running team, I'd
probably play five minutes a game.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kelley makes three. No biggies were recruiting him out of
Milwaukee's Pius XII High School. Most Top 40 schools prefer their
point guards to have a smidgen of quickness and be able to shoot,
at least a little. That lets out Mike Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   But to Bennett, this kid looked like a regular Isiah Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike wasn't a flashy scorer in high school,'' Bennett pointed
out. ``But I saw him once and I knew I wanted him to play for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach and the kid can't even get their stories straight.
Coach Bennett says the lad set his heart a'flutter at an AAU
extravaganza in Las Vegas. The kid thinks the coach started making
the goo-goo eyes at him in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing they do agree on was the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike, I'd like to offer you a schol-''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it!''
</P>
<P>
   Thus did wily Bennett secure for himself the services of the
1998-99 Big Ten Defender of the Year (he lost out this year to Ohio
State swatmeister Ken Johnson).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Kelley epitomizes what we are going after,'' said
Bennett. ``He's a low-risk, low-maintenance player who doesn't take
unnecessary chances. He is going to be safe with the basketball.
And on defense he will guard everybody from the point guard to the
power forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, you now have the Wisconsin profile. First, you have
sticky, unyielding, aggressive, unrelenting, irritating, and, on
many happy Badger occasions, terrifying, man-to-man defense. The
Wisconsin defense is where offensive reputations come to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can see the frustration in their eyes,'' said
Vershaw. ``And when we see the other players start to fight among
themselves, we know we have them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then you have the Wisconsin offense. The Badgers have no go-to
guy. What they have are a bunch of ``Do You Mind Taking The Shot?''
guys. A quick shot for these guys is anything taken with fewer than
five seconds on the clock. Transition? Maybe _ maybe _ if there is
a steal between the top of the key and midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I value possession of the basketball,'' said Bennett. ``I like
to eliminate mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Egos, too. He eliminates them completely. Ten players have
started a game this season for the Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't good enough for me to say at any time, `These are
our five guys,' '' Bennett explained. ``The players seem to
understand this. We need to make adjustments according to the
opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett is a certified industry phenomenon. He coached
Wisconsin-Stevens Point for nine years (the name ``Terry Porter''
might ring a bell) before upgrading to Wisconsin-Green Bay for a
10-year run that included three appearances in the NCAA tourney and
three in the NIT. He came to Wisconsin five years ago. Though he
says he occasionally got a little frisky at Stevens Point, he has
spent his 15-year Division 1 career recruiting the plowhorses left
behind after the glamour boys were through picking over the
thoroughbreds. Hence the methodical style.
</P>
<P>
   The public may not know him, but his peers certainly do. When
Sports Illustrated surveyed 115 Division 1 coaches last year and
asked which coach's clinic they'd most like to attend, the only
people selected ahead of Bennett were Mike Krzyzewski, Rick
Majerus, and Bob Knight. And when the Seattle Post-Intelligencer
asked 113 Division 1 coaches to identify the coach who regularly
does the best job under the most difficult circumstances,'' Bennett
was No. 2 on that list.
</P>
<P>
   LSU coach John Brady knows who he's up against. ``I have a great
deal of respect for Dick Bennett,'' Brady said. ``I have attended
his clinics.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, what's with Wisconsin's NIT-looking record entering the
tournament (18-13)? Start with a Big Ten schedule (the Badgers
finished sixth). Then remember that it's not easy being
out-athleticised every night you're not playing Northwestern. But
be advised that things began to fall in place for this team in the
middle of February and that Wisconsin, playing under
tournament-type, win-or-else pressure, is 9-3 since Feb. 5, with
all three losses coming to consensus tourney favorite Michigan
State.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Badgers are in the tournament and tournament basketball
is usually half-court basketball. Advice to the Bayou boys: buckle
'em up, sons. The way the Badgers look at it, the team that bleeds
together, beats higher seeds together.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
