<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-FORTE-BOS &LR;      03-23 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-FORTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAR HEELS FLOWER WITH FORTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At first, he was just one of those
happy-to-be-here type players. All Joseph Forte wanted was a chance
to play. Beyond that the 6-foot-4-inch freshman had no great
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In November, at the Maui (Hawaii) Invitational, North Carolina
coach Bill Guthridge gave Forte that chance in the season's first
game against Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Forte scored 24 points in the Tar Heels's 82-65 win. Two wins
later _ over Georgetown and Purdue _ Forte was making a similar
speech. ``All I want is a chance to play,'' he said as he accepted
the tourney's most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to last weekend in Birmingham, Ala. NCAA tournament
South Regional second-round game. No. 8 seed North Carolina vs. No.
1 seed Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Second half. Tie game. Until . . . a 3-point shot from the top
of the key by Forte, followed by another bomb from the top of the
key gave the Tar Heels a 60-53 victory, a win that propelled the
Tar Heels into the South semifinal game against No. 4 seed
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Forte's box score line: 17 points, 5 rebounds, 1 assist, and no
turnovers in 38 minutes 24 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Typical. Predicatable and now, as the season moves into an area
that even the most die-hard Tar Heel fans didn't expect their team
to reach, necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main goal was just to start,'' said Forte, who has done so
all season and is the first freshman in UNC history to lead the
team in scoring (16.2 points per game), which is not insignficant
when you look at an alumni list that includes players named Jordon,
Perkins, Worthy, and Ford. ``After that, I was going to let
whatever happen, happen. But after I got here and started playing
it seemed like everything kept rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Forte's journey to North Carolina began in Marietta, Ga. He was
a budding superstar in eighth grade and the subject of a recruiting
war of sorts for his services in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Forte was scheduled to move on to Marietta's Campbell High
School, but his mother, Wanda Hightower, thought her son didn't
need to be the savior of a program.
</P>
<P>
   So she searched and focused on nationally-known DeMatha High
School in Maryland and famed coach Morgan Wooten.
</P>
<P>
   In a bigger pond, Forte could develop at his own pace, which he
did from the start.
</P>
<P>
   At DeMatha, Forte had to learn some humility as well as
basketball. Forte had him play a season of junior varsity before he
was deemed ready to receive any kind of star treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was tough on my ego,'' Forte conceded. ``But looking back
on it, it was probably the best thing for me. I looked as it a
humility-type thing.''
</P>
<P>
   By his senior season, everyone was chasing him, but Carolina,
with its tradition of success, won the recruiting war.
</P>
<P>
   Forte thought Maryland seemed lukewarm in its pursuit of him,
particularly from coach Gary Williams. Georgetown did not have the
same mystique after John Thompson retired, which put North Carolina
in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   But not even Tar Heels coach Bill Guthridge knew quite what
would happen when he started Forte in the first game of the first
season.
</P>
<P>
   If he had seen some summer league games in which Forte more than
held his own with talent like former Maryland guard Steve Francis,
who was the No. 2 pick in last season's NBA draft, Guthridge would
have felt even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Joseph was a good prospect,'' said Guthridge. ``But
until you work with him, it's hard to tell. I didn't know what to
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   He learned quickly. After scoring 24 points against USC, Forte
followed with 17 points against Georgetown and 21 in the
championship game against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Forte was doing more than starting. He was starring. ``I knew
after the three games in Hawaii that the cat was out of the bag,''
said Forte. ``I felt like I was kind of cheating because nobody
knew who I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon everyone knew his name. In a season that had been, until
the NCAA tournament wins over Missouri and Stanford, bittersweet
with the most losses for any UNC team in 50 years, Forte has been
the constant, showing up every game, playing 30-35 minutes a night
and producing numbers a veteran might produce, not someone who is
not even 40 games into his college career.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Tar Heels struggled through a series of injuries
and illnesses that kept them on the fringe of the Top 25, or out of
it, for most of the season, Forte has provided the team with a
sense of well-being, that when things do go wrong, he can somehow
provide an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ```He does have a sense of confidence,'' said Guthridge. ``He
knows how to play and poise is a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Poise is very much a part of it. Against Stanford, with a season
on the brink of ending, Forte was the Tar Heels' go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   Forte said he thought that early in his career. ``After the Maui
tournament I wasn't surprised by keeping it up,'' he said. ``I got
a feeling for it and realized it wasn't all that different from the
speed I played in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   That confidence, which would sound cocky coming from a more
vocal playeer, has been part of Forte's personality.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent success, this is hardly a vintage Carolina
team in terms of talent. Although there are the requisite veteran
stars, such as point guard Ed Cota and center Brendon Haywood, no
one on this roster is likely to find his number hanging from the
Dean Dome rafters in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   No one, that is, except Forte. ``He is probably the only
legititmate `banner' player they have,'' said one UNC insider who
has watched the program closely for a number of years.
</P>
<P>
   Forte does not know where his season or his career will go
beyond Friday.
</P>
<P>
   With everyone healthy and confident, the Tar Heels matchup well
against Tennessee, Miami, and Tulsa, the other teams still playing
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   If they can win Friday night, and get by the winner of the
Miami-Tulsa winner on Sunday night, anything would seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Tar Heels are just enjoying the turn in a season
that seemed to be doomed to failure only a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is going to see our best shot,'' said Forte with a
sense of confidence that now seems to be legitimate. ``I feel like
I'm going to step it up and do everything I can.''
</P>
<P>
   He started with a dream of just wanting to play in Maui.
</P>
<P>
   Now the dream has been expanded to the point where anything
seems possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
