<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5710 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-BOS &LR;      03-23 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S GEM SHINES BRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ There are those who would tell you the Arizona
Diamondbacks should have to pay a tariff for their success. Their
rapid rise to the level of the elite clubs is almost intimidating.
Twenty months is just too quick.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no denying the fact that in winning 100 games last
year and reaching the National League playoffs faster than any
expansion club in history, Phoenix has become the envy of all
baseball. So much so that when the long-awaited realignment, it
will be a coup for the league that gets this one-time desert
outpost.
</P>
<P>
   As a franchise, the Diamondbacks have it all. The Diamondbacks
play in a new 49,000-seat stadium and have drawn 6.6 million fans
in two seasons. Only Colorado, which drew 4 million to Denver's
Mile High Stadium (80,000 capacity) has done better in its opening
season.
</P>
<P>
   Calling themselves ``The Southwest's Team.'' Phoenix is being
marketed with the same efficiency of the NBA's Phoenix Suns. The
Diamondbacks should be. Jerry Colangelo is a managing general
partner of both franchises. What he has done to stabilize the
growth of professional sports in the Valley of the Sun is nothing
short of amazing.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have expressed a preference to be in the
National League. But a two-year trial period is over and the odds
are very good that you'll see them in Fenway Park in 2001.
According to a recent interview with Red Sox chief executive
officer John Harrington, it's a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep hearing rumors about that,'' said Arizona manager Buck
Showalter. ``But it's all the same to me. Just so we get to put on
a major league uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter makes a good point. Last year, Arizona went from worst
to first, something that has only happened six times in major
league history. The Diamondbacks won the NL West by 14 games. In
1995, Colorado made the playoffs in its third year but as a wild
card. The Florida Marlins, who began in 1993, won the 1997 World
Series and then dumped all their key players. You can bet the house
that it won't happen that way for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Coangelo is committed to doing whatever it takes to field a
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that this would be Arizona's team,'' said
Showalter, who was on the job as manager in 1995, two years before
the expansion draft. We're the Southwest's team. Not just
Phoenix's. We never want to take things for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the novelty of a new stadium and a new franchise would
wear off some day and we were down some the second year (from
3,600,412 to 2,887,170). But the reason our fans are continuing to
support us is because we put a product on the field that they can
be proud of. We take the responsibility very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the moves Coangelo and the Diamondbacks made last year
was the signing of free agent lefthander Randy Johnson. Johnson won
the National League Cy Young award and the heart of Phoenix fans
with a 17-10 record. He led the NL in ERA (2.48), strikeouts (364),
innings (272), and complete games (12). He expects to do as well,
if not better.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson lost his only start in the division playoffs against the
Mets, who won the five-game series, 3-1. But the lift he gave his
teammates by helping get them there meant more to the Diamondbacks
than they could every say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of what they accomplished ,'' said Showalter.
``And anybody who was at Shea Stadium last year and thought we'd be
happy with the way things ended doesn't know the makeup of these
players we're lucky enough to surround ourselves with. Good players
make good teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work we did as an organizationn reflects a constant
proving ground. What we did last year has to thrown out the window.
We all know that. Nobody wants to take a step back, but we know
that it's going to be very challenging
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there is any one approach. We have a lot of
people here you can trust. The do their work. They don't assume
anything or take anything for granted. Everyday is another proving
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Diamondbacks went to work last spring, they were given
little chance for success. Johnson had left a Houston club that
hocked part of its future to get him. That he would sign with an
expansion club helped put the Diamondbacks in a new light.
</P>
<P>
   With veterans like Luis Gonzalez, Jay Bell, and Steve Finley
pushing the less-experienced players, there was an old-time
baseball attitude that emerged after a 1-5 start and stayed the
rest of the season. Gonzalez hit .336, second in the NL. Outfielder
Steve Finley won a Gold Glove. Bell hit 38 home runs. Matt
Williams, who drove in 142 runs, was like an extra coach and his
chats with young players were said to be invaluable. Tony Womack
stole 72 bases. The Diamondbacks outscored opponents, 908-676.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mix well,'' said Gonzalez, who had hit .300 or better only
once in a nine-year career that included stints with the Astros,
Cubs, and Tigers. ``It's a good group of guys who go out there and
play hard. We get along in the clubhouse and that carries on to the
ballfield. The younger guys feed off the older guys. We run balls
out. We hit home runs and sprint around the bases. We respect the
game of baseball. It carries over to the younger players.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing surprises the Diamondback players anymore, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great front office and manager,'' Gonzalez said.
``They went out and got key players as well as blue-collar guys.
That's who we feel we are. We're not a flashy team. Just a bunch of
guys who play hard. I don't know about where we might finish. Last
year it was predicted we'd be third or fourth in our division. This
year we're probably the favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will be the favorite because of solid defense
and pitching. They lost starter Andy Benes to St. Louis and
reliever Gregg Olson to Los Angeles, but the rotation still has
Omar Daal (16-9), Armondo Reynoso (10-6), Todd Stottlemyre (6-3),
and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a special group of guys here,'' said pitching coach
Mark Connor. ``They all get along well. I just want them to be
themselves. Already this spring, I've seen veterans take the young
kids and put their arms around them. That great. I think of lot of
that comes from Buck. As a manager, he has tried to mold the club
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter says it's the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are the ones who get the credit and that's as it
should be,'' he said. ``There's no secret here. The players made
the adjustments during the year. They met the challenges that April
presented us. I don't think anybody who went through our start
would have thought we'd be where we were at the end of the year.
But the way they stayed together was a real tribute to our
players.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
