<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPPING FURNACE MAKES A DIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My new hot-air furnace works wonderfully, almost too well,
because the plenum really pops when it heats up and cools down. The
popping is telegraphed throughout the duct system, so it is heard
close up and far away. How can I silence it?
</P>
<P>
   J.A., Wilder, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A. Short of building a fiberglass plenum (the big metal duct on
top of the furnace), you have to separate that plenum from the rest
of the trunk ducts (the large, rectangular metal ducts coming out
of the plenum).
</P>
<P>
   To do that, unfasten the ducts from the plenum, and separate
them by a few inches. Then insert a canvas sleeve to make the
reconnection. The plenum will still snap and pop (you can't easily
fix that), but it will not telegraph through that soft canvas
connection. You might be able to have your furnace man do this.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible fix is to have the furnace man reduce the heat
of the air in the plenum; a slight reduction might make a
difference, unless of course it makes the house too cold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Someone burned alcohol in the bathroom and it scorched an 8-
by 5-inch area of wood on a linen cabinet. It does not look
blistered. How can I restore it?
</P>
<P>
   CHESTER GAY, Foxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Whether it is painted or stained and varnished, the part must
be sanded heavily to remove all the scorched wood; and that usually
means to the bare wood. Then refinish the surface where the damage
occurred. You will not have to refinish any other part.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have some old drawers that are recessed, and do not move
very well. I would like to find some drawer slides to make them
work better. Where can I find them?
</P>
<P>
   RICH WEBER, Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try the Rockler catalog (formerly Woodworkers store). It has
at least three pages of wood and metal slides. Call 800-279-4441.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am remodeling my kitchen, and am wondering which way to go
with the counter tops: Corian vs. granite. And could the draining
board be granite?
</P>
<P>
   CAROL DAVIS, Wayland, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First off, I do not suggest a granite draining board. Use a
dish drainer or rubber drainer.
</P>
<P>
   As for Corian vs. granite, it's a tossup. Prices are similar,
although some householders have told me they found granite to be
less expensive. Corian is virtually maintenance free, and scratches
and smudges can be sanded or abraded out with a plastic scrubber.
It's also sensitive to heat. Granite should be sealed with a
masonry sealer; otherwise it will spot and stain. Use the sealer
the granite people give you, or should give you. Stains on granite
are difficult, if not impossible, to remove. Corian comes in many
styles, colors, and granite look-alikes. Choice of granite
``patterns'' is limited, but they are spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   All this said, some householders sing the praises of Corian for
the bathroom, but not the kitchen; others swear by it in the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   I have two Corian vanities with self-contained sinks in my
bathrooms and my wife and I like them. My wife priced Corian for
her kitchen redo and reversed her field immediately upon hearing
the cost. She opted for tile. We both are happy with it. The grout
joints are very, very thin, reducing but not eliminating the plague
of dirty, uncleanable grout.
</P>
<P>
   If push came to shove, I would opt for Corian. Remember, there
is more than one type of Corian (the first brand name for this
dense plastic material) out there, each claiming to be better than
the other.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I bought a garden-style condo, and had it painted before
moving in. In the kitchen and living room I see cracks and splits
at the top of the wall, where it meets the ceiling. The painter
returned and covered the splits with plaster, then repainted. The
cracks came back. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   ELLEN SHERR, Danvers, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds as if the real crack and split is at the joint
between wall and ceiling. If cracking appears in the paint itself,
it is because it was put on too thickly. The cure there is to sand
off the paint and apply two thin coats of whatever is being
applied.
</P>
<P>
   The joint, however, is another matter. Putting plaster, spackle,
joint compound, or anything else that gets hard in the joint won't
fix it; the movement of wall and ceiling will break it up again,
very quickly, making it look worse. The gap is there because there
was no tape and compound applied originally.
</P>
<P>
   There are two cures: Install a paper or nylon mesh tape to the
joint and finish off with joint compound. The tape will prevent the
crack from showing through again.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative cure is easier: Either do this yourself or have
the painter do it. Apply a bead of white latex or acrylic caulk in
the joint, then smooth it off with your finger. It will cover the
joint, look reasonably attractive, and will not open up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where can I find large tiles of fairly thick cork for a
floor? I can't find anything in the stores, except for little
bulletin boards of very thin corklike material.
</P>
<P>
   PAT FITZPATRICK, Foxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try Wincander Enterprises, 69 Main St., Box 276, Exeter, N.H.
03833; telephone 603-778-8558.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
