<SLUG> BC-WEB-SHAKEOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY SPIGOT SHUTTING OFF FOR MANY E-BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beautyscene.com strutted into the online marketplace last fall
with a star-studded editorial board that included former
Cosmopolitan editor Helen Gurley Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of beautiful has arrived,'' the San Francisco
e-retailer crowed in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in a market crowded with dot-coms offering lipsticks and eye
shadows, beautyscene.com barely made a blush. Less than seven
months after its debut, the Internet cosmetics store recently
acknowledged it faces a cash crunch.
</P>
<P>
   Its experience reflects the harsher climate in which e-commerce
companies now operate. Once flush with investment, a growing number
of Web stores are now running on empty and some are casting about
for new markets. Analysts say these are signs that the industry is
headed for a shakeout.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Internet grocer Peapod Inc. said it may not be
able to continue without additional funds. And now that its merger
with Columbia House Co. has been scrapped, music e-retailer CDnow
Inc. needs a new suitor with deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't too long ago that it was thought any entrepreneur with
a good idea could flourish in cyberspace, selling paperback books,
stereo systems, and other products.
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; today &LR; 's Web isn't as accommodating. Investors are
tightening their purse strings, and e-retailing stocks are falling
back to earth. Smaller dot-coms face increasingly crowded fields in
which to carve out a niche and attract customers. Many are forced
to plow their venture capital money into marketing, spending
millions on everything from billboards to Superbowl advertising in
an effort to build their brands.
</P>
<P>
   And, competition is getting stiffer as old-economy retailers
such as Wal-Mart Stores Inc. are starting to figure out what clicks
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big guys will continue to consolidate and get bigger,''
said Rick Neely, interim chief executive of software seller
Beyond.com, based in Santa Clara, Calif. ``The small guys are
finding smaller places to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely is searching for his own corner in cyberspace. An early
leader in electronic commerce, Beyond.com tried to mimic Amazon.com
Inc. by raising huge investment capital and growing as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The effort failed. And like other companies, Beyond.com is now
moving away from its unsuccessful consumer retailing business to
focus on sales to other firms.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as Value America Inc. and even Amazon.com,
have cut staff. Attempting to avoid a financial squeeze,
MotherNature.com, a Concord start-up that sells vitamins, has been
trimming advertising expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the current Web environment will make it
increasingly difficult for dot-coms such as Furniture.com Inc. to
take their shares public. Furniture.com, a Framingham home
furnishings retailer, announced in January its plans to raise $50
million in an offering that has yet to be scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That feeling is that what's done is done,'' said David
Cooperstein, an analyst with Forrester Research in Cambridge.
``There are no new stories, no new plots.''
</P>
<P>
   Another backlash could come from manufacturers who have been
willing to supply young dot-coms. Left with a stack of unpaid
bills, some suppliers are getting nervous about selling to new
e-retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a few manufacturers are seething. Andrew Auwerda,
president of cosmetics maker Tony &AMP; Tina, said his New York company
called beautyscene.com's offices many times about overdue bills
totaling $7,500. When the e-retailer finally called back, he was
told the company was having cash-flow problems.
</P>
<P>
   Auwerda said he was upset. ``It's a lot of money to me,'' he
said, ``considering that we've never had the time to do national
advertising, including those large billboards that they've had.''
Beautyscene.com officials did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Such cash crunches, ironically, are coming at a time when busy
consumers are flocking to the Web to buy books, videotapes, and
even automobiles. One forecast, by Forrester Research, estimates
online retail sales will nearly double this year to $39 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But studies of Internet traffic patterns indicate that the
largest and best-known retailers are ringing up most of those sales
_ bad news for upstarts who have spent millions of dollars on
advertising to lure new shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Today &LR; , investors frustrated with the growing losses and heavy
start-up costs of the dot-coms seem to have little interest in
supporting fledgling electronic retailers. The exceptions are those
that have a clear lead over rivals or have carved out narrow
niches.
</P>
<P>
   But many corners of the marketplace, such as beauty and pet
products, are already too crowded to support new players. And with
deep-pocketed companies like Best Buy Co. and Wal-Mart entering the
fray, fewer investors want to back a tiny dot-com, even if it could
be the next Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't start a company focused on selling books right
now,'' said Jonathan Guerster, a general partner with Charles River
Ventures in Waltham. ``The bar has gone up. . . . Those who are
late to the market should not have unrealistic expectations about
their ability to raise money.''
</P>
<P>
   At Battery Ventures, a $450 million venture capital firm in
Wellesley, executives seem almost embarrassed by their forays into
Web sales. They'd rather be known for picking standouts such as
Akamai Technologies Inc., which operates a network of servers, than
sluggish performers such as Petstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the poster child for why (Internet consumer retailers)
stink,'' said Tom Crotty, a general partner with the venture
capital firm. ``Right after the pets.com deal, we decided this is
not our type of deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1307EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
