<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5722 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-ERIN-PHOTOS-B     03-23 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-ERIN-PHOTOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and e coding)  
 JULIA'S TRASHY TOGS IN `ERIN' INSPIRE A FASHION DIALOGUE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people would be mortified if their boss told them to
``rethink'' their wardrobe because it was making co-workers
``uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Julia Roberts's character in the new film ``Erin
Brockovich.'' The sassy legal assistant _ who insists on wearing
push-up bras, leather miniskirts and sheer leopard-skin blouses _
retorts to her law-office manager, ``You may want to rethink those
ties.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the sartorial tension in the box office hit, which
chronicles the real-life story of how Brockovich discovers a
utility company cover-up of contaminated water which is making
residents of a California town ill.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when more men and women are breaking traditional
workplace dress codes, Brockovich's in-your-face attitude and
subsequent success says a lot about society. Is this rebel in a
tank top a role model and a heroine for the new millennium? Or is
she an embarrassment to working professionals?
</P>
<P>
   The Boton Globe invited two women to participate in a dialogue
about office dress codes and self-expression in the workplace.
Kirsten Blocker is an editor at the Boston-based female youth
magazine Teen Voices and a 21-year-old English major at Pine Manor
College in Chestnut Hill. Shari Thurer, 52, is a psychologist in
private practice and an adjunct professor at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   As they began debating over dinner recently, the two were quick
to engage in some Brockovich bashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's a feminist's nightmare. Her dress is very
provocative, completely inappropriate, and trashy. It's conveyed in
the movie that a lot of things happened for her because people
found her attractive. . . . I found it sickening,'' says Blocker.
</P>
<P>
   Says Thurer, ``I think the Hollywood writers, directors, and
pitch people wanted her to be trashy and powerful. . . . In this
movie, anyone trashy is good and anyone buttoned-up is bad. . . .
They played with your stereotypes. But in the end, a trashy,
powerful woman is also a cliche. . . . It goes against middle-class
sensibilities and good taste. . . . I would want Erin on the couch
to find out what she was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Blocker was incredulous that a twice-divorced mother of three
young children who is living in a roach-infested house with no
savings or marketable job skills would continuously risk her
paycheck by flashing her bra and cursing at her colleagues. ``Most
of us would lose our jobs,'' says Blocker.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, dragging her kids along on company business also
made no sense, says Thurer. ``It's using your children to justify
your humanity. She's saying, `I have three kids. I'm a good
character.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you couldn't be sexy and be a mom. Demi Moore,
who posed on the cover of Vanity Fair nude and pregnant, changed
all that.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which is set in the desert town of Hinkley, Calif.,
certainly seems a long way from the realities of a city like
Boston. Would Brockovich _ sporting a miniskirt _ have been
successful here? ``Someone watching `Ally McBeal' would say she'd
do great,'' says Blocker, who typically wears casual clothing to
work such as sweaters, skirts, jeans and boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yesterday, I was walking by Park Street station and I saw
a woman (in a very short skirt) with her whole leg exposed. She
looked successful. I wanted to say, `Is your skirt caught in your
hose?' I assume she met (her job's) dress code. Still, it was
shocking. That skirt didn't come mid-thigh.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Thurer, ``At the university, some of the girls dress quite
sexy. They are clad in . . . tight black pants, fitted shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an element in high fashion that's straight from the
trailer park . . . Nowadays, street culture influences high
culture. It's not just in fashion but in art and music, too. If you
look at modern art, the source might be graffiti. In fashion, it
could be a ripped sweatshirt or a baseball cap.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, sexy dressing isn't always shunned by society.
Consider the popularity of singers like Jennifer Lopez, who
attended the Grammy Awards last month wearing a Versace scarf-dress
with a neckline that plunged to her navel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is being normalized,'' says Blocker, shaking her
head. The Dorchester native, who spends about 20 hours a week
helping area teenagers write articles for the Teen Voices on-line
edition, says many teenagers today admire and accept provocative
attire. ``They say it's fashionable. The feeling is, if you've got
the figure, then you go, girl. It's a feminist's dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   Or is it? Thurer, a Bethpage, N. Y., native who calls herself a
first-generation feminist, remembers a time in the '60s, when ``you
couldn't be a feminist and be attractive. You couldn't shave your
legs or wear lipstick. I got my engagement ring, and I wouldn't
wear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when it wasn't cool to pursue materialism.
You were supposed to join the Peace Corps . . . To be a feminist,
you had to be a drone. I support Erin's right to dress as she
wants. My patients do that. It doesn't mean they're bad or good. In
real life, there are good people with bad taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Thurer dresses the way she wants. A typical work
outfit for her is a faux leopard-print furry short skirt, black
sweater and black boots. ``I like funky clothes. You can sort of
get away with it in the academic world. You don't have to dress in
a gray flannel, buttoned-down way. I have a zebra-print belt, a
bracelet made of dominoes, and a million things with exposed
zippers and seams. I would never wear Talbots or L.L. Bean. I would
think I was dead. That's so non-expressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurer concedes there was a time when she did submit to office
dress codes. ``If you're low on the totem pole, you have to
conform.'' What about Brockovich? ``I think what the director
wanted you to think was she derived power from this. She could get
people to look at her. It doesn't particularly offend me. It's not
my taste. It did her as much harm as good. She couldn't get a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madonna, Dolly Parton, and Courtney Love all did this. Madonna
exposed her boobs and now she's a mother. But she portrays herself
as master of her soul. If you're powerful enough, you can do
whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a pause at the dinner table and suddenly Brockovich
doesn't seem so offensive after all.
</P>
<P>
   Blocker recalls how the movie's protagonist emotionally
described her tenure as Miss Wichita long ago. ``She said she was
going to work to end world hunger. She never gets around to it.
Then she grasps rather tenaciously this opportunity to make a
difference in people's lives'' with a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be a woman. You get paid less . . . Often, we're
just looking for a way to shine. It goes beyond money. Often times,
we just want to get out there and start'' changing the world.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Blocker reveals, she plans to launch her own publishing
house for female authors one day. ``I want to fight for a cause. My
mother worked for Planned Parenthood and the YWCA. When we were
children, she taught me a lot about reproductive rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of women I know, life is about seizing an
opportunity to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Brockovich doesn't just dress provocatively; she
flaunts her sexuality to manipulate men. In one scene, for example,
her manager Ed Masry, played by Albert Finney, asks her how she
intends to retrieve hard-to-find records from the local water
regulatory board. Her response? ``They're called boobs, Ed.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it obnoxious, but Blocker says, ``A lot of us use our
femininity to get stuff. I get free bus rides.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Thurer, ``Hello! It's called charm. If you know what you're
doing, go for it. Sexual power is real. Men do it too. They use
their masculinity.''
</P>
<P>
   As the meal winds down and Thurer and Blocker prepare to leave,
it's clear Brockovich has earned mixed reviews. She scored points
for her work and her convictions but not for her methods. The one
question both diners felt went unanswered in the movie was why _
with so much to lose _ did Brockovich insist on her call-girl look?
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Kurland, costume designer for the movie, asked the real
Erin Brockovich the same question before he created outfits for
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Her reply? Says Kurland, ``She likes dressing that way. She
thinks she looks good. I think she looks at herself and says, `As
long as I can do it and look good, why shouldn't I?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brockovich does have one complaint since she saw Roberts
portraying her on screen, Kurland adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin said she never wore skirts that long. And she meant it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
