<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5725 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-KNITTING-ART-BOS     03-23 1788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-KNITTING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NEW, YOUNGER GROUP DISCOVERS THE JOY OF KNITTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Some people can get a thrill / Knitting sweaters and sitting
still.'' These lines by Stephen Sondheim don't automatically bring
to mind people in their 20s and 30s. But recently the enthusiasm
for knitting has hit well below the middle-age belt. College
students and young professionals are turning back the clock and
adding a bit of old-fashioned knit-one-purl-two rhythm to their
high-tech lives.
</P>
<P>
   And they're doing it big time.
</P>
<P>
   They're taking lessons and learning from one another. Joining
knitting groups at local libraries and yarn shops. Checking out Web
sites on their computers. And buying patterns to re-create the
couture creations they see on catwalks, in fashion magazines, and
on their favorite celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   They're knitting in the evenings in front of the television. At
noon in cafeterias. They're knitting on subways, buses, planes, and
in waiting rooms. They're even knitting _ contortion style _ while
walking down the street, needles in motion and cell phone pressed
to one ear.
</P>
<P>
   And they're not only women.
</P>
<P>
   Jim H. Grassi, 30, a graduate student in chemistry at Boston
University, took up knitting last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was looking for a creative outlet and decided to take
a knitting course,'' says Grassi. ``I said I'd take it with her.
I'm a skier and thought maybe I'd be able to make a sweater I liked
and one so thick it would stop a bullet. The course lasted eight
weeks. I loved it. I'm hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   An avid baseball fan, Grassi does most of his knitting while
listening to games on the radio. He completed an Icelandic sweater
with snowflake pattern last year. This year he figures he'll double
his output _ 162 games times three hours per game equals two
sweaters by the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about knitting is it's utterly mindless,'' says
Grassi. ``It unhinges the mind. And you don't feel like you're
completely vegetating because when the game's over _ you're halfway
done with a sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Scope, co-owner of the 15-year-old Putting on the Knitz
store in Newton, Mass. and Grassi's instructor, says there's a
waiting list for his evening knitting classes and a shift in his
store's clientele. Today's yarn buyers, he says, are professional
women in their 20s and 30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of the attraction is computer related,'' says
Scope. ``Everything is so mechanical these days and knitting is one
thing that a person has complete control over. They're creating a
garment from scratch _ starting with one string and one stitch at a
time. They can fix their mistakes. They're in complete control. And
doing something very creative.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he says, big sweaters knitted with big yarn on big
needles are in. And the ever-growing number of yarn choices include
blended wools, soft alpacas, mohairs, chenilles, and high-end
cashmeres and camel hair. Acrylics are out, natural fibers in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can knit almost everything for under $100,'' says Scope.
Or you can knit single things for many hundreds of dollars. Cathi
Rosengren, owner of I'm in Stitches in Newburyport, says many of
her customers pay $80 a skein for special-order silk blends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new yarns feel great in the hands and are so colorful,''
says Scope. ``Plus knitting is therapeutic. I had a customer in
yesterday. She's a lawyer who said she'd shut her office door the
day before and knitted for two hours. No one knew. Knitting is the
most beneficial when you're the busiest. It makes you relax and
helps you concentrate. Some college kids knit during lectures
because it helps them focus _ they aren't daydreaming or looking
around to see what everyone else is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Gonzalez, 27, learned to knit from her aunt as a child and
then picked it up again in college, where she knitted her way
through many a lecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I retaught myself to knit because I was seeing intricate
knits, cable structures, and color work I wanted to make for
myself,'' says Gonzalez, who began her college career as a pre-vet
major before switching to design at North Carolina State
University. ``I love the feeling of raw wool and its preparation _
the spinning and dyeing. I like creating a structure out of
stitches. It's all very logical, which ties into my science
background.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gonzalez, who works at Woolcott &AMP; Co., a knitting store
in Cambridge, Mass., knits weekly with a group of fellow knitters
whom she's taught over the past few years. Although they knit at
different levels, they get together for the sheer pleasure of
knitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knitting has skipped a generation, so learning to knit is now
cool,'' says Carla Scott, senior editor of Vogue Knitting magazine.
``There are plenty of patterns out there for sweaters, ponchos, and
shrugs. And the novelty yarns and washable wools are great. Plus
knitters can get answers to their questions and share ideas on the
Internet (eknitting.com, knitlest.com, www.kniton.com, to name a
few).''
</P>
<P>
   Knitting even found a seat at the most recent Super Bowl. Not
one but two ads featured knitting, one with Tara Lipinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Piantigini, a librarian, recently started a knitting group
that meets every Monday night at the library, and another new group
has begun meeting at the Brookline Brooksmith. Jennifer Walsh is a
member of a monthly knitting/book club and has also begun to attend
a Thursday afternoon knitting group made up of young neighborhood
mothers. And over at WGBH-TV in Boston, a large group gets together
weekly to knit and lunch in the station's cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Frude, who owns Woolcott &AMP; Co. and presides over a
five-year-old knitting group, says she noticed a big influx of
younger knitters in her store last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of them are high-tech people looking for low-tech
creative outlets,'' says Frude. ``But basically, knitting is and
has always been dictated by fashion. Back in 1978, Perry Ellis came
out with $300 short sweaters with puff sleeves. Women who hadn't
knitted since they were Girl Scouts said `I can do that.' The same
thing's happening today with the chunky designer knits.''
</P>
<P>
   And, she says, celebrities add fuel to any trend. Julia Roberts,
a knitter, helped push the little knitted hat into prominence in
1998 by plopping one on her handsome head in the movie ``Stepmom.''
Other on-the-set knitters are Winona Ryder, Cameron Diaz, and
Hilary Swank of ``Boys Don't Cry.'' Monica Lewinsky told Barbara
Walters that she kept her sanity during her year of infamy by
churning out scarves and sweaters for friends.
</P>
<P>
   Frude says she's thinking of bringing a ``knit out'' to Boston
this spring _ an all-day affair that would feature instruction,
supplies, and fashions. Last October's Knit Out in New York City,
sponsored by the Craft Yarn Council of America, drew 7,000 knitters
and membership in the Knitting Guild of America has increased 10
percent in three years. And according to the council, 4 million
people began knitting last year, a number some store owners cite as
too high.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all newcomers to knitting hover around the
Generation X mark. Dixie Walker, 44, who began knitting two months
ago, attends two knitting classes a week, one in Littleton and
another in Harvard. Although many of her classmates are highly
skilled knitters, they come to class to socialize.
</P>
<P>
   Knitting, in other words, is both a sociable and portable craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about what's happening in our towns, about our
families, and how we hide our yarns from our husbands,'' says
Walker, who works for publisher John Wiley &AMP; Sons. ``It's very hard
to resist yarns on sale. There's always future projects to buy for.
I've got five projects lined up at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Katzenstein, owner of the 24-year-old Wild &AMP; Woolly store
in Lexington, Mass., which imports a wide array of luxury yarns,
credits part of the recent wave of enthusiasm to an innovation by
several yarn companies _ beautifully photographed, hardcover
designer pattern books with accompanying specially dyed yarns.
</P>
<P>
   ``These designer pattern and yarn packages have evolved over the
past couple of years,'' says Katzenstein. ``Some of the most
popular designers are Alice Starmor from Scotland _ she has
wonderful books and beautiful yarns. Kaffee Fassett is an American
who lives in England, and he's very popular. And Jo Sharp, a
relatively new designer, is from Australia, and there's Colinette
from Wales.''
</P>
<P>
   The store also carries yarns from Japan, New Zealand, South
Africa, Japan, and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think knitting attracts process-oriented people _ folks who
like the process of knitting, not just the end product,'' says
Katzenstein. ``The take-charge professional women of today want
something they can't buy. They're also interested in cooking and
gardening. I hate the word `cocooning,' but that's what it's all
about. Yet, like anything else, there are cycles and trends, and
knitting is now trendy.''
</P>
<P>
   And also practical. ``We live in New England; it gets cold here;
people wear sweaters and scarves,'' says Katzenstein.
</P>
<P>
   As well as meditative.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Hinard, a seasoned knitter and psychotherapist, led
two knitting groups in Boston during fall 1998 called ``Knitting as
a Spiritual Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of my friends who are in their early 40s were getting a
little disillusioned with trying to find a practice that would
bring them peace of mind and centeredness,'' says Hinard, an avid
knitter who picks up her knitting at red lights and during workouts
on a treadmill. ``That made me think about how I've always found
stillness and calm while knitting. Knitting's so rhythmic and
methodical. In meditation you concentrate on either your breath or
a mantra. In knitting the focus is on your hands and the creation
of stitches. The concentration brings a sense of relaxation, ease,
and balance.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, accomplishment and challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jaeger, 41, vice president of the Greater Boston Knit and
Crochet Guild, says he learned to knit as a child, from his
grandmother, and remembers many hours happily knitting while
watching ``Wild Kingdom.'' As an adult, he took classes, joined the
guild, and now knits sweaters for himself and his six children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to worry about sizing,'' he says with a laugh,
since whatever comes off his needles will fit one of his offspring.
``But I do feel pressure. I have to knit better than the women (in
the guild) to prove myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
