<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT ALL DOWNHILL FOR US SKI TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes the darkness is so dark, the bleakness so bleak, that
a couple of lights shine all the brighter. This is the case with
the US Alpine ski team, as two US skiers created a shining finale
to this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the post-Picabo/Tommy/Kyle/A.J. era, closed out by Picabo
Street's super-G Olympic gold at Nagano, the US team has generally
reverted to its usual World Cup performance, in which a top 20
result is a reason to rejoice.
</P>
<P>
   But heading toward the end of another rather dismal season in
which everyone remained in the shadow of the Austrian juggernaut,
Daron Rahlves and Kristina Koznick made blockbuster finishes, each
winning twice, back-to-back. Rahlves won a rare pair of downhill
victories March 10-11, and Koznick took two World Cup slaloms in
the last two weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In Bormio, Italy, last Sunday at the World Cup finals, Koznick,
a 24-year-old from Burnsville, Minn., burned the tricky bottom of
the second run to nail her second win in two consecutive World
Cups, marking the fourth World Cup slalom win of her career.
</P>
<P>
   Her winning margin Sunday was .13 of a second. An elated Koznick
told Gary Black, publisher of Ski Racing News, that she had been
slow on top and knew the steep, rutted bottom of the course was her
last chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just pathetic at the top,'' she said. ``I knew I had to
turn it up on the bottom section'' to beat Sweden's Anja Paerson,
who was leading after the first run.
</P>
<P>
   According to Marjan Cernigoj, head coach of the US Alpine team,
Koznick nailed the turns on the bottom with the nearly perfect form
that had given her a No. 2 world ranking.
</P>
<P>
   A bright spot looking ahead to Salt Lake City in two years?
</P>
<P>
   Too far to look, said Cernigoj. ``She's just getting started. I
can hardly wait till next season.''
</P>
<P>
   Koznick told Black she had some problems in the beginning of the
season that delayed her ascent on the slalom points board. ``I
changed equipment, and we all turned to shorter skis,'' she said.
``Now I'm in great shape and everything is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Before she picked up the pace, Koznick's best finish was
December 1998, when she won at Semmering, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struggling so much earlier this year, it's great to end
like this,'' she said. ``It gives me a big boost. It's better that
I struggled this year rather than next year, when there are medals
to fight for.''
</P>
<P>
   Koznick sounded more European than American when she said of
next year: ``I want the slalom title. I know I can win if I'm
consistent _ consistently in the top three, not top 15.''
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, Rahlves recaptured some of the downhill glory
that came to this country 16 years ago, when Billy ``Red Sleds''
Johnson pointed his Atomics down the Wengen course, nearly crashed
in winning, and then went on to win three more straight downhills,
one of them in the 1984 Sarajevo Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   From Johnson and A.J. Kitt to Tommy Moe and Kyle Rasmussen, the
US men downhillers have been just about the only bright spot since
the Phil Mahre era faded.
</P>
<P>
   But just when Moe, Kitt, and Rasmussen were suddenly gone, along
came ``Beach Boy'' Rahlves, a 27-year-old from Truckee, Calif., who
hung 10 and shot the curl to win a pair on the Lillehammer downhill
course.
</P>
<P>
   At 180 pounds, Rahlves is lighter than most downhillers, who
range in the 200-pound class. But with a tailwind and some
excellent gliding skis, Rahlves beat the best, including Austrian
tough guys Hermann Maier and Herman Trinkl.
</P>
<P>
   Rahlves's first win came two weeks ago Friday night, when he
stunned the Kvitfjell crowd after having scored personal bests of
10th and 11th earlier in the season. The first win was unexpected
and sweet. The second, that Saturday, was amazing, even to Rahlves,
who then placed fifth in the super-G the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've won the first race, you don't want to lose,'' said
Rahlves, who called his season finale ``the best week of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these US bright spots, the Austrian and its head honcho,
Maier, made the real headlines of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Maier won four titles _ the downhill, super-G, giant slalom, and
overall _ to tie the all-time greats: Jean Claude Killy (France)
and Pirmin Zurbriggen (Switzerland).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony chamberlain writes about skiing for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
