u s BC-GLF-COOL-BOS &LR;      03-23 1820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIP TURN FOR GOLFERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contrary to popular belief, it wasn't so hard to put together a
varsity golf team in high school 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the coach would do,'' said Brad Faxon, ``was go through
the hallways on the day of a match. If you had an Izod shirt on and
your collar was up, you were on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Faxon, who was one of the few who wanted to be on the
team, some discretion was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the day of a match, you would sneak your clubs into
school,'' he said. ``You never, ever wanted anyone to know you
played on the golf team.''
</P>
<P>
   Girls would laugh, and true jocks _ the ones who collected
letters, scholarships, and cheerleaders _ would make your life
miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were a geek,'' said Billy Andrade. ``Everyone busted you
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that they went around with pocket protectors, but golf just
wasn't a cool thing for kids to do. Well, perhaps in some parts of
the country it was, and perhaps for those sons of club
professionals such as Davis Love and Curtis Strange, but generally
golf was considered the sport your father would play with friends
during weekends at the club. A stuffy game with snobby rules and
loud clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, people would say, `You play golf? That's not even a
sport,'' said PGA Tour veteran Brandel Chamblee.
</P>
<P>
   So, for the most part, you played baseball, football,
basketball, or hockey. If you pursued golf, you did so in your
spare time, perhaps on weekends with your father or grandfather,
but rarely as a solitary pursuit. At least until life got in the
way and the choice was made for you.
</P>
<P>
   For Andrade, the baseball fields got bigger but he didn't, and
those throws from shortstop to first base took a couple of bounces.
</P>
<P>
   For Chamblee, there was the chance to challenge himself without
depending on teammates.
</P>
<P>
   For Mark Calcavecchia, it was a move with his family from
Nebraska, where he was quite large in a small setting, to Florida,
where he watched 13- and 14-year-olds jam basketballs over him.
</P>
<P>
   For Faxon, it was the realization that he was pretty good at
hitting that stationary, white, dimpled ball.
</P>
<P>
   Different reasons for abandoning other sports and concentrating
on golf, though none of them had the slightest to do with being
cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' said Andrade. ``You were still a geek.''
</P>
<P>
   As he said this, Andrade was on the putting green at the Bay
Hill Club &AMP; Lodge in Orlando, Fla., dressed impeccably from the
Footjoys on his feet to the Bobby Jones shirt on his back. He was
in the midst of a PGA Tour event that would eventually earn him
$27,043, and there were times when he would not go 10 feet without
signing a half-dozen autographs.
</P>
<P>
   And if they could see him now _ you know, the ones who so many
years ago called him a geek _ what would they say? The question
made Andrade's friend Faxon laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is, when I go back home now,'' said Faxon, ``kids
who used to play football are telling their friends they used to
play on the golf team.''
</P>
<P>
   How cool is that?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His ability to swing a golf club with unheard-of ferocity and
send a golf ball unheard-of distances quite possibly will make him
the sport's finest player ever. Yet the true measure of Tiger
Woods's greatness may be this simple reality: He has made golf
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, Arnold Palmer breathed life into the game 40 years ago
and made it fun to watch. But while Palmer put golf on TV virtually
by himself, Woods is the one who has gotten people to tune in like
never before.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Jack Nicklaus set a standard of excellence that may
never be equaled. But while Nicklaus stockpiled 18 professional
major championships, Woods is the one who has steered pro golf in
directions never imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's driving the Tour,'' said Love. ``No doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving it like a Porsche on an open road. To the top of the
leaderboard in TV ratings, consistently past the NBA, where it has
never been. To record-breaking attendance numbers week in and week
out. To the cover of national magazines. To weekly purses that are
in the millions. To city neighborhoods. To a generation of kids
with cell phones, credit cards, and Nintendo games stuck to their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   And no one has noticed the phenomenon more than his colleagues
on the PGA Tour, many of whom, despite getting fewer chances to
win, are benefitting handsomely from Woods's overwhelming presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is the in thing to do,'' said Chamblee, 37. ``I think
Tiger has a lot to do with it. People see him on TV every single,
solitary weekend. You can't watch Tiger and think he's uncool. He
looks pretty cool. He's a big, strong guy. He hits it great. Looks
pretty cool doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Chamblee got turned off by golf's difficulty, but he
returned to the game as a teen-ager and never left its embrace. He
caddied for Ed Sneed in the Colonial Invitational years ago and
remembers one thing about the galleries. While they weren't very
big, said Chamblee, ``They were very polite, very mature.'' But
very ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off the 18th green at Sawgrass after Tuesday's practice
round for The Players Championship, Chamblee glanced around at the
hundreds of kids waiting for autographs. Most of them held
programs, flags, photos, or posters they had purchased. Then he
looked at the thousands of spectators who had bought tickets to
walk in the sunshine and watch golf shots that did not count. Many
of them wore designer golf shirts and pleated pants, two-tone golf
shoes, and golf hats from their favorite clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing, thought Chamblee, and far different from when he broke
in on Tour a dozen years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd is now younger and they don't necessarily play
golf,'' said Chamblee. ``But they're just coming out to see Tiger
or David Duval. The whole image of Duval even, with the sunglasses.
The look is a young, hip look.''
</P>
<P>
   That's great for him, Chamblee knows, because of the chain
reaction. More fans mean bigger crowds, bigger TV audiences, more
sponsors paying more money. All of which leads to better purses.
It's just that Chamblee and friends have to get used to a different
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the people who are out here wouldn't ordinarily watch
golf, so the crowd is more vocal and apt to yell,'' said Chamblee.
``They'll scream and holler in your backswing. But it's here to
stay, so you better get used to it. There's going to be more
distractions on the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Faxon said it's naive to think that Woods didn't punch the
button that started this wild ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of him, kids made their parents take them out to
tournaments,'' said Faxon. ``It's Tiger, and it's been great for
the game, because when they come, they've seen what a great venue
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is where golf wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a parent, you wouldn't mind your kid spending a
whole day at a golf course,'' said Chamblee. ``You're not going to
get in trouble. You have to go out there and practice and work all
day and be good at this game. If I had a kid, I'd want him to play
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. Junior golf is exploding in this country, and
while the PGA Tour, US Golf Association, and PGA of America all
concede that more progress is needed to make the game available to
youngsters, high school and college coaches have more talent at
their disposal than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Drennan, the men's golf coach at the University of Rhode
Island, said a trend has jumped out at him in recent years: Good
athletes are leaving other sports to concentrate on golf at a
younger age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that kids would jump into golf between seasons
of other sports, but no more,'' said Drennan. ``Now they are
locking into golf, polishing their games at a young age, and taking
care of themselves. There is a great pool of talent out there for
scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not have to wander the dormitories of URI in search of
kids with Izod shirts and turned-up collars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We present the success of Matt Griesser as Exhibit A of golf's
new state of ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're drawing a blank, we'll give you a hint: ``Sign Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, him. Didn't know his name? Neither did the young boy on that
golf course in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he recognized me from the commercials,'' said Griesser,
who was playing golf with European sales representatives as part of
a promotional tour for Footjoy when he was spotted.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a 12-year-old boy in Ireland recognized him from a
series of 30-second commercials for golf shoes and golf gloves
``blew my mind,'' said Griesser. ``I had an extra glove and gave it
to him. Then he asked me sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   How cool is golf? Consider that an obscure actor who plays an
annoying character in TV commercials gets asked for an autograph in
Ireland. Consider that this same actor recently had his own
promotional tour in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty amazing,'' said Griesser, who considers the commercials
a career break of mammoth proportions.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Sign Boy,' '' said Griesser, ``connects with fans because
people really see themselves in him.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, if they could get as close to the players as ``Sign
Boy'' gets to Duval, Love, Justin Leonard, Jesper Parnevik, Tim
Herron, and Phil Mickelson, they, too, would try to interact with
them. In fact, Griesser said Leonard told him that his portrayal of
``Sign Boy'' was strikingly close to many volunteers he had met.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise to Chamblee that fans are flocking to the game.
Pro golfers dress well, sign lots of autographs, play a game
millions of people can identify with, and follow a code of rules
and etiquette that is admirable.
</P>
<P>
   This popularity was what the Footjoy ads were designed to take
advantage of, specifically with the younger crowd, said Peter
Winch, management supervisor for Arnold Communications in Boston,
creator of the Footjoy commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to show that Titleist/Footjoy was hip, fun again,
that it was not your father's shoe,'' said Winch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It presented (Footjoy) with a big opportunity with the younger
generation, showing that the brand was cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Other giants of the corporate world have realized the star power
golfers have with the younger generation. Microsoft, for example,
recently recruited Sergio Garcia to help sell its new home video
golf game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these companies know the results of a survey you may
have missed. When a group of New York youngsters, aged 7-13, was
asked what their favorite sport was, golf finished No. 1. Ahead of
football, basketball, and baseball. Don't be stunned, because Woods
is arguably the most recognized athlete in the world, supplanting
Michael Jordan for that distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan? To a new generation of kids, they aren't sure what he
used to do, but they know he plays golf. Lots of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's cool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
