<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCING WEALTH SECONDHAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My heart goes out to all those multimillionaires afflicted with
Sudden Wealth Syndrome. There is nothing quite so poignant as the
pain of the rich. I feel I share that pain, in a way, as a victim
of secondhand Sudden Wealth Syndrome. It works kind of like
secondhand smoke. You get sick from hearing so much about other
people's money.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden Wealth Syndrome has been much in the news lately. It's an
affliction identified by an enterprising pair of California mental
health professionals who have set up something called the Money,
Meaning and Choices Institute in a San Francisco suburb. The
institute assists the newly rich grapple with the psychological
torment of having so much money.
</P>
<P>
   The people who seek their help aren't fly-by-night ``Who Wants
to Be Millionaire?'' rich. These are people with serious money,
some of the new multimillionaires who, if I can believe what I read
(not always a wise idea), are multiplying faster than Easter
bunnies.
</P>
<P>
   According to a story in the Los Angeles Times, victims of Sudden
Wealth Syndrome worry about having so much money and at the same
time worry about losing it. They find themselves questioning their
values, their purpose in life. They have everything they always
wanted _ the big house, the fancy cars, the exotic trips. Yet
money, according to the people at the Money, Meaning and Choices
Institute, has also brought these people ``a sense of isolation,
uncertainty and imbalance.''
</P>
<P>
   One patient complained of a ``growing gap with his old friends
that made it difficult to talk about the most mundane things in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he can't talk to his old friends the way he used to.
He's rich. Money changes friendships, relationships. Money changes
everything.
</P>
<P>
   According to the LA Times story, the founders of the Money,
Meaning and Choices Institute maintain that Sudden Wealth Syndrome
isn't about money at all, but about change. Still, it's the
peculiar change that money brings, which means that at root, it
really is all about money.
</P>
<P>
   Our national love affair with money may be a fatal attraction.
Sometimes, I catch myself hoping for an economic recession, nothing
really devastating, just serious enough to put an end to the plague
of Sudden Wealth Syndrome and with it secondhand Sudden Wealth
Syndrome, the feeling that you can't bear to hear or read one more
story about somebody with gobs of money.
</P>
<P>
   Money, money, money. That's all people talk about. Stock options
and IPO's. Executive bonuses. Market fluctuations. Investment
opportunities. You mention you saw a movie and nobody asks if you
liked it. They want to talk about the financing, and how much it
grossed last weekend. You can't pick up a newspaper or a magazine
without seeing the face of some newly hatched millionaire grinning
at you. Everybody is full of tales of instant riches and
conspicuous consumption.
</P>
<P>
   How are those of us who'll never make even our first million
supposed to feel about all these people awash in money? Should we
envy them? Resent them? Be grateful? Learn from them? Worship them?
Pity those who suffer from Sudden Wealth Syndrome? Take perverse
pleasure in their unhappiness? Or should we just be appalled by the
excess? Maybe somebody will set up an institute to help people with
secondhand Sudden Wealth Syndrome. I hope they'll accept credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
