A5742 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-23 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRAISE OF GREAT AND GRAND WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   March is Women's History Month, that time of year when we have
our attention called to yet another set of women whose
contributions to civilization have been dismissed by the powers
that be. This throng of hidden heroines made me think of women
whose contribution to my own life I've personally overlooked,
carelessly thinking their lives had been undistinguished.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, I had the most unusual grandmothers and
great-grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   My father's mother was born in Russia, and after some
particularly nasty pogroms, she and my grandfather made the
decision to come to the United States. They traveled for weeks to
the nearest port, but when they went to board the ship, my
grandmother Hessie found her way barred because she was visibly
pregnant with my father.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get on this ship in that condition,'' the guard
informed her, but when my grandfather turned around, planning to
return home with her, Hessie is reported to have said, ``You're not
pregnant. Go!'' She planned to follow when my father was born.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather, it turns out, had a terrible time. He ended up
in Worcester, &UR;  &LR; Mass., alone and unemployed, and so he wrote Hessie
that he would be returning to Russia and his lucrative hat-making
business. She replied with a warning: If he came back, he would
find the key to his house with a neighbor because she and the
children were on their way to America.
</P>
<P>
   Hessie made that decision because soon after my father was born,
a band of marauding Cossacks rode into the village. My grandmother
stuffed her sleeping infant into a cold oven and then hid with her
three older children in the woods behind her house. She had no
intention of remaining in such a dangerous place for Jews and so
she finally boarded that boat, with a 6-week-old baby and the other
children in tow. She found work in Worcester as a lady barber. As a
child, I lived below her in a four-family house she finally managed
to purchase with her earnings.
</P>
<P>
   She never said a word about the difficulties of immigrating to a
new country. I heard this story from my dad.
</P>
<P>
   My mother's mother was a young child when she and her parents
and an aunt and uncle set off from Russia, determined to leave for
the same reasons. An epidemic cut a wide swath through the party in
Constantinople, killing Sarah's father, her aunt, and her uncle.
Though Sarah became ill, my great-grandmother Anna hid her from
officials who were collecting the bodies of the afflicted. She also
refused an offer to leave Sarah with a kind Turkish family eager to
adopt an adorable 2-year-old. Instead, the two slowly made their
way to America.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard life. When my great-grandmother went off to work,
the neighbor watching my grandmother locked her in a closet. When
Anna remarried a man with four children, and then rapidly gave
birth to five sons, Sarah was expected to run the household and
care for the children as if she were an adult. When she met my
grandfather, she sprinted for the door. My grandfather owned an
Army &AMP; Navy store that thrived after the Depression; he and Sarah
managed to send their fourth child and only son to college. As a
preteen, I lived with my grandparents in the triple-decker they'd
managed to buy for themselves in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother never breathed a word about her past. I heard
this story from my mom.
</P>
<P>
   From the security of my position, it's hard to imagine the
insecurity of theirs. My foremothers arrived at Ellis Island only
two generations ago, not knowing the language, uncertain if they
could find housing, work, or a sense of belonging. Still, there was
no going back and so they marched boldly into an unknown future,
thereby ensuring mine.
</P>
<P>
   I was watching TV a number of years ago, observing Russian women
lining up for hours to buy bread. Something stirred in me and I
found myself picking up the phone and calling my dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen,'' I said, ``I never thought to thank your mother or
you for coming to this country and offering me a chance at the
American dream. If the women in our family hadn't been so daring,
I'd be one of those ladies in line, hoping to secure some food for
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   My father laughed. ``Are you out of your mind?'' he asked. ``You
wouldn't be in line anywhere. You'd be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, grand women. For everything.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
