<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING SERIOUS ABOUT PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it didn't generate any Page 1 headlines, a conference
last weekend at Wheelock College could turn out to be a banner
event for parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   For years, it's been clear that the people who make toys and the
people who study children's development aren't on the same page.
``Playing for Keeps: A Conference on the Future of Play'' hopes to
be the beginning of the end of the disconnect between the two
groups, bringing manufacturers and educators together for the first
time to explore the role that play and toys have in our children's
lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers like conference presenter Diane Levin, a Wheelock
professor and author, have long documented the way single-purpose
toys such as Rock &AMP; Roll Ernie by Fisher Price (push a button and
it sings a song and shakes) rob play of its creative value and
interfere with children's learning. Professors Dorothy and Jerome
Singer of Yale University, who also spoke on Saturday, have spent
years looking at the way violence in children's television and
videos impedes imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the $20 billion toy industry hasn't been listening.
</P>
<P>
   Toy manufacturers continue to offer a steady stream of toys that
thwart healthy development. In recent years, one of the most
troubling trends has been the way content intended for adult
audiences is marketed to children, typically through toys spun off
from movies, said presenter Daphne White, founder and executive
director of the Lion &AMP; Lamb Project (www.lionlamb.org), a
grass-roots initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix,'' for instance, is an R-rated movie, but Matrix
action figures are marketed for preschoolers. Duke Nukem 3D, a new
adult video game set in a porn shop, features hard-core violence
and pornography, but the action figures based on it are sold in toy
and comic-book stores and the grip game is marketed for children 10
and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When play is endangered, kids are at risk,'' says early
childhood educator Edgar Klugman, cofounder of the ``Playing for
Keeps'' conference and a professor at Wheelock.
</P>
<P>
   Cofounder John Lee, CEO of Learning Curve International, an
educational toy manufacturer, hopes the conference will lead the
entertainment and toy industries to develop a code of ethics about
the marketing of violence for children. His company manufactures
toys that promote healthy development, including Thomas the Tank
Engine wooden train set and Felt Kids, a pretend-play system.
Educational companies like his have a 15 percent share of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   That the two sides of the fence were even in attendance was
gratifying to Klugman and Lee. There were about 200 registered
attendees, including the CEO of FAO Schwarz and representatives
from Fisher Price and ToySmart.com. But the biggest players in the
toy market, Hasbro and Mattel, were not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just beginning to get the message,'' says Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying premise of ``Playing for Keeps'' is that it is
through play that children make sense of the world and learn how to
cope with it. Whether their play becomes a healthy foundation for
developent and learning depends on the materials and toys they
play, with as well as the environment they play and grow in, said
keynote speaker James B. Comer, psychiatrist, author and professor
at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   The more unstructured, open-ended, and imaginative the play, the
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``By being active agents in their world, children learn they can
have a positive effect on it,'' said Levin. If a preschooler
playing in the sandbox, for instance, concludes, ``I can make this
log not fall over, I can solve this problem,'' she's on her way to
becoming a problem-solver. ``She's seeing the world as something
she can navigate, not as something to be defeated by,'' said Levin.
</P>
<P>
   That has far-reaching implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that child is learning to read, she's more likely to
conclude, `I can figure this out, I can accomplish this because I'm
a person who can figure things out,' '' said educational
psychologist Doris Bergen, a professor of child development at
Miami University in Ohio who also spoke at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, creative play fosters a sense of competence that
carries over into academic learning and into an outlook on life
while the lack of it puts children at risk, said Klugman.
Unfortunately, creative play is increasingly under assault.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the conference and in interviews, researchers
explained why:
</P>
<P>
   --TV, video, and computer screens. The time children spend in
front of screens takes away from time spent in creative play and
increases their dependence on the screen for entertainment. The
younger they are when screen exposure begins, the more this is
true. ``Kids can get to the point where they don't know how to
play,'' said Levin. She is author of ``Remote Control Childhood?:
Combating the Hazards of Media Culture'' (NAEYC).
</P>
<P>
   --Too much structure. When children are in control of their own
play, setting its parameters, solving problems, and making the
rules, it translates into self-confidence and a sense of personal
efficacy, said Bergen. The more they are engaged in lessons and
organized sports, and the younger they are when they begin them,
the less control they have, the less beneficial the play. ``It's
good exercise and it may sometimes be fun, but it's not good
play,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   --Single-purpose toys. Open-ended toys, from blocks and
manipulatives to art supplies and pretend props, serve as an
adaptive mechanism, said Bergen: ``They're a way for kids to work
out the worries and concerns of life. When you can't feel in
control in real life and you can be in control in play _ you say
when the dolls go to bed, what they have to eat or wear, or whether
the trucks go up the ramps or speed down them _ the play becomes a
coping mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Toys that come with an agenda don't let that happen. ``Push a
button and music plays, push another one and a different kind of
music plays _ that isn't nearly as good as handing a child a toy
instrument and letting her make her own music,'' said Levin.
Unfortunately, the need for these toys is a vicious cycle: The more
single-purpose toys a child has, the more dependent she is on the
toy's agenda. Because she isn't getting the chance to develop her
imagination or rely on herself to create interesting play, she gets
bored more easily, needs another structured toy, and flexes her
imagination less and less.
</P>
<P>
   --Toys with violent themes. These toys carry a double whammy,
said Levin: Not only does violent content desensitize a child so he
begins to accept it as normal, but the content and nature of the
toy don't allow him to develop a sense of personal competence.
``There's no problem-solving involved; it's the same theme repeated
over and over again,'' she said. The less well developed a child's
sense of personal efficacy, the more susceptible he is to violent
content. The ramifications for this are far-reaching, too, but not
in a positive way: ``Kids are more likely to lash out (in
aggressive and violent ways) when they haven't had the experience
of feeling effective and competent,'' says Levin. The younger they
are when they're exposed to violence in toys and on the screen and
the more frequent the exposure, the more they internalize the
message that violence is the way to feel powerful.
</P>
<P>
   --Technology in toys. Just as this is a subject of debate among
parents, this was an area of tension among the presenters.
``Healthy play gives children the chance to have ownership of
ideas, technology in toys tends to take that away from them,'' said
Bergen. She said research shows that exposure to computer play and
toys with technology affects how a child's brain develops,
typically shortening attention spans and increasing the need for
instant gratification.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchel Resnick, an associate professor in the Media Lab at
MIT, said technology has been unfairly painted as demonizing
creativity. Done right, he said, ``new technology can expand the
range of fantasies kids can try out.'' LEGO's Mind Storm, for
instance, enables a child to build with LEGOs and create a program
on the computer to make the creation respond to light or touch.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of ``Playing for Keeps,'' two subcommittees had been
formed. One, headed by White, was charged with drafting a
preliminary code of ethics.
</P>
<P>
   As daunting a task as that might be, anything less could not
only shortchange our children and the future of play but also all
of society. ``If coalitions like this one are not successful,''
said Comer, ``by the year 2050, we will be living in a very
different and difficult society.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --For information and materials on ``Playing for Keeps,'' write:
``Playing for Keeps,'' Wheelock College, 200 the Riverway, Boston,
MA 02115 or e-mail cofounder Ed Klugman at
eklugman(at)wheelock.edu.
</P>
<P>
   --The Lion &AMP; Lamb Project (www.lionlamb.org) organizes and
sponsors violent toy trade-ins nationwide; offers workshops for
parents and teachers; and has Parent Action Kits. For information
or membership, e-mail them at lionlamb(at)lionlamb.org or write:
4300 Montgomery Ave., Suite 104, Bethesda, MD 20814.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ For the first time, there's a baby monitor that
lets you know not only when your baby is crying but also if he is,
or isn't, moving. Anglecare Sound and Movement Reassurance System
is marketed by Safety 1st.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
