<HEADLINE>
A FREE DAILY STARTS A FUROR IN PHILADELPHIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ ``If we owned a cow it would give condensed
milk.'' That slogan for Philadelphia's two-month-old Metro paper
reinforces the most crucial point about the free daily distributed
in partnership with the area's public transportation agency, SEPTA.
Size isn't everything.
</P>
<P>
   Metro is shrunken news in a shrunken format, a 24-page tabloid
filled with three-paragraph Associated Press stories designed to be
read in a short commute. It has an editorial staff of 18 and
harbors few journalistic pretensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a summary of the news,'' says Floyd Weintraub, a vice
president for Metro International in North America. ``Nothing more
or nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Metro/SEPTA deal has spawned a big controversy. Monday,
about 60,000 of the roughly 160,000 daily Metros began being
distributed on 1,100 city buses, a location off limits for the sale
of The Philadelphia Inquirer or its tabloid sister, The
Philadelphia Daily News. That kind of access issue has generated
cries of First Amendment foul, and a lawsuit, from the companies
that own the Inquirer and Daily News, The New York Times and Boston
Globe, and USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Metro's Swedish-based parent company _ having launched
papers in European cities from Prague to Helsinki _ is looking to
bring the free commuter daily to other US cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have identified 60 cities worldwide,'' says Weintraub, of
possible future markets. At a time when many papers are losing
time-pressed readers, could they lose ad dollars to a Metro
offering a Cliff Notes version of the news?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fear level here,'' says Philadelphia magazine editor
Stephen Fried. ``Whether it's really something to be afraid of in
the marketplace . . . it's hard to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The most striking aspect of Metro is its two-page color TV
listings. The rest of the color-splashed paper is a tightly
formatted mini-review of the day's major events _ from the NASDAQ
rebound to the furor over former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet
_ that is heavily reliant on wire services. There are local
columns, sports news, entertainment tidbits, weather maps, movie
listings, and Roger Ebert film reviews. One page, marked as an
advertisement, is produced by SEPTA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've designed a product for people to read in 20-25
minutes,'' says publisher Jack Roberts, an ex-Daily News hand.
``I'm not going to say I'm anything other than what I am.''
</P>
<P>
   But the question of what exactly Metro is _ victim or villain _
is the subject of tangled litigation. In late January, Philadelphia
Newspapers Inc., Gannett Satellite Information Network Inc. and The
New York Times Co. challenged Metro in federal court. Having lost
several legal skirmishes, the plaintiffs are now bogged down in the
appeal process.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, according to plaintiffs' attorney Michael Schwartz,
is the arrangement that allows Metro favored access to areas like
the SEPTA buses. In a recent case, a Chilean court ruled against a
partnership between Metro and the Santiago mass transit system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern here is that SEPTA, a government agency, has sold
to Metro preferential distribution rights on its property,
government property,'' says Schwartz. ``What we were really dealing
with . . . (are) First Amendment circulation rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Metro attorney Edward Rogers has accused the plaintiffs of
``gang(ing) up on a fledgling, free transit newspaper in order to
preserve their choke hold on print advertising in the Philadelphia
region,'' in a display of ``economic bullying.''
</P>
<P>
   For distributing Metro, SEPTA receives $30,000 a month in ad
revenue, another $15,000 a month for cleanup costs, and uses the
daily page to communicate with readers. For the nation's fifth
largest public transportation system with almost 1 million daily
riders, Metro is ``all part of upscaling the travel experience,''
says general manager John Leary Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The nagging question is whether Metro is under SEPTA's editorial
sway. ``If we were to have a major controversy, I would fully
expect it to be a front page story and I would have zero problem
with this,'' says SEPTA director of public affairs Richard Maloney.
Roberts also stresses Metro's independence, but acknowledges that
it would ``treat those stories just like we treat the other
stories,'' meaning with a few short paragraphs.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to assess Metro's impact in the market is difficult at
this point. Roberts cites a readership survey indicating that its
audience skews young (more than 50 percent are under 45) and female
(57 percent of readers are women). According to the survey, a third
of Metro's readers also say they don't read other papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have a readership that's closer to a broadcast
(audience) than a newspaper readership,'' says Roberts. ``I'm
bringing people into the market who don't read newspapers.'' Given
the declining circulations at the Inquirer and Daily News, that's a
touchy subject. ``I can't be responsible for their circulation
losses,'' adds Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in Philly, it may not be Metro's only US
testing ground for a newspaper/public transit alliance that could
roil the local media scene. According to MBTA spokesman Joe
Pesaturo, Metro officials approached them about moving into Boston
in 1998, but ``we declined to participate in this endeavor.'' A
spokeswoman for the Chicago system says conversations with Metro
``never got beyond the exploratory stages.'' Cheryl Johnson, of the
Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority, says discussions
there are in ``very preliminary stages. We've certainly been very
willing to listen to what they had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   More bullish is Dennis Mochon, marketing manager for the San
Francisco area's BART system. ``We've been talking with them for
over a year. There is interest,'' he says. ``The revenue could be
as much as $1 million a year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mark Jurkowitz covers media isues for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
