<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAME OF THE GAME IS MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I just paid $35 to hang onto my Internet domain name for one
more year. Antony Van Couvering says I paid too much. ``Let's put
it this way,'' says Van Couvering. ``If e-mail is free, domain
names should be free.''
</P>
<P>
   And for an hour on the evening of March 23, they will be.
</P>
<P>
   Van Couvering says his New York company, registerfree.com, will
give away an Internet domain name to anyone who stops by and
requests one between 9 and 10 p.m. Eastern time. It's a flagrant
publicity stunt, aimed at snatching a bit of attention from Network
Solutions Inc., the giant of the business of selling domain names.
</P>
<P>
   When the federal government first began commercializing the
Internet, NSI won the monopoly right to sell all domain names
ending in .com, .net, and .org. Now that monopoly is at an end, and
dozens of small firms are offering cut-rate domain name sales.
Despite its name, registerfree.com generally charges for its
services. Still, Van Couvering's price of $19.95 per year beats
NSI's $35. And Van Couvering says he'd welcome a future in which
domain names don't cost anything.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, domain names aren't absolutely essential to life on
the Internet. For proof, start your Web browser and type in the
following: 204.71.200.74.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to our old friend, Yahoo. That clump of numbers you just
typed is Yahoo's ``IP address,'' the true address of the site as
far as Internet computers are concerned. All that www.yahoo.com
stuff you usually type was created to make life easier for humans,
who have the devil of a time remembering strings of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   When you type in words, they're translated into numbers by a
network of server computers called Domain Name Servers, or the DNS
system. Your Yahoo request goes to a DNS computer which checks a
list and finds that www.yahoo.com equals 204.71.200.74. The
connection is made, and off you go.
</P>
<P>
   When you buy your own Internet domain, you're buying your own IP
address, and a handy word address that's linked to it. The company
that sells you the domain, known as a ``registrar,'' inserts the
data into the DNS system. Now, anyone who wants to find you on the
Internet won't have to memorize your IP address, just your domain
name. Instead of typing 207.155.252.14 to see my Web site, just
type www.monitortan.com.
</P>
<P>
   The system works quite well. But why should it cost $35? We're
talking about a trivial exercise in database management; basically
adding one domain name and its underlying IP address to the
millions of others stored in the DNS system.
</P>
<P>
   NSI also charges $35 a year to renew the domain name. Partly,
this is to make sure that unused domain names eventually get
deleted and resold to others. But that means you're paying $35 a
year to make sure that NSI leaves your domain name alone. It feels
a little like a protection racket.
</P>
<P>
   But NSI has parlayed it into a position of extraordinary
strength. The company has just agreed to be acquired by data
security firm VeriSign Inc. of Mountain View, Calif., for $21
billion.
</P>
<P>
   This sum astonished even jaded veterans of the Internet economy.
But it makes a certain degree of sense, now that Gartner Group
analyst John Pescatore has explained it to me:
</P>
<P>
   VeriSign is creating a one-stop service for companies moving
onto the Internet. Firms that come to NSI for a domain name will be
offered a range of other services from VeriSign that they will need
to open their virtual shops, such as encryption to protect
customers' credit card numbers. The NSI acquisition is just an
aggressive way of guiding all these would-be e-commerce titans to
VeriSign's front door.
</P>
<P>
   If VeriSign plays its cards right, Pescatore says, those $35 a
year domain name fees will soon become irrelevant, anyway. He
expects the prices to fall and the fees to be waived altogether for
e-commerce firms willing to buy lots of other services.
</P>
<P>
   Van Couvering also hopes to make big money by selling follow-on
services to e-commerce, with domain names tossed in for free. But
lacking the name recognition of NSI, he's hoping to attract
customers by giving away free domains to all comers.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like another desperate Internet something-for-nothing
business plan. My favorite kind. Besides www.monitortan.com is too
long. Time for something short, snappy, and absolutely free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Hiawatha Bray can be reached by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5756 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-LOTUS-BOS &LR;      03-23 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-LOTUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTUS COMMITTED TO SMARTSUITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When computer network administrator Bill Bonner types a memo, he
uses the omnipresent word processor Microsoft Word, which is part
of Microsoft's equally commonplace Office software suite.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonner's just about the only Microsoft Office user you'll
find at his company, Hitchiner Manufacturing Co. of Milford, N.H.
The other 300 white-collar workers at this metal casting shop have
standardized on SmartSuite, from Lotus Development Corp. And Bonner
has no intention of making them switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're under a lot of pressure from some of our customers to
convert,'' says Bonner. But SmartSuite works fine, and even though
he personally prefers Office, Bonner can't justify the cost of
switching over the entire company.
</P>
<P>
   While 120 million users worldwide run Microsoft Office, Lotus,
based in Cambridge, Mass., has found a profitable niche serving 20
million users who want an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clearly a number two player in this market, says Lynne
Capozzi, Lotus' vice president of SmartSuite development, ``but
it's still a strong position for us.''
</P>
<P>
   SmartSuite is overshadowed by Lotus' flagship Notes and Domino
groupware products, and Lotus officials admit they've cut back on
SmartSuite research and development. Still, Lotus officials say
they plan to maintain their presence in a market Lotus once
dominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a longstanding commitment to SmartSuite,'' says
Capozzi. ``We have no plans to walk away from the product.''
</P>
<P>
   SmartSuite's low profile is a sharp contrast from Lotus' early
history. One SmartSuite component, the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet, was
one of the world's most popular software programs during the 1980s.
Indeed, 1-2-3 is generally credited with sparking the success of
the original IBM Personal Computer, the parent of most of today's
PCs. The software was a ``killer app'' that made personal computers
so useful that companies bought millions of PCs just so they could
use 1-2-3 to do their bookkeeping and financial analysis.
</P>
<P>
   But 1-2-3 had been designed for Microsoft's earlier operating
system, MS-DOS. When Microsoft introduced Windows 3.0 in 1990,
Lotus was slow to produce a Windows version of 1-2-3. Microsoft
filled the gap with Excel, a graphically oriented spreadsheet
originally designed for Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh. Soon Excel
was gobbling up market share from 1-2-3. Matters got worse when
Microsoft began selling complete suites of office software, with
word processor, spreadsheet, database and presentation graphics
program all in one.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Lotus had SmartSuite ready to go in 1993, the race
was essentially over. Both Lotus 1-2-3 and WordPerfect, once the
world's most popular word processing program, had been consigned to
also-ran status.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Le Tocq, research director for the Gartner Group in San
Jose, Calif., says only about 8 or 9 percent of new office suite
sales are going to Lotus. But that doesn't count upgrades to its 20
million existing users. ``You sell updates to your installed base,
and that doesn't count as share,'' says Le Tocq. ``Lotus still has
quite a good update base.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the company continues to produce enhanced versions of
SmartSuite, such as the Millennium Edition 9.5 released last year.
Recent versions of SmartSuite have included IBM's ViaVoice speech
recognition technology, enabling people to write documents by
speaking to their computers. Capozzi admits that few customers use
this feature, but the numbers are growing.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lotus isn't looking to make too many more dramatic
improvements to future versions of SmartSuite, and the company has
reduced its R&AMP;D expenditures on the product. The logic is simple:
Office software suites are ``mature'' products. A word processor
processes words, a spreadsheet crunches numbers. Capozzi says
there's little point in adding more bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   But that means Lotus' SmartSuite unit can keep selling
essentially the same product with minor improvements. This keeps
costs down. Capozzi won't break out the exact profit numbers.
Still, she insists that SmartSuite makes money, even though it
usually sells for a discounted upgrade price of $149, compared to
Microsoft Office's upgrade price of $249.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus moves a lot of copies of SmartSuite by including them with
new computers. Parent company IBM will sell 10 million PCs this
year with SmartSuite pre-installed, and Lotus has similar deals
with some other firms, including the Japanese PC maker Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
   Capozzi won't say how much the company collects on these
bundling deals, but admits that the chief goal here is market
share, not profit. ``It's definitely a volume play,'' Capozzi says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Lotus also benefits from the popularity of its Notes
and Domino software for helping people work in teams. SmartSuite is
designed to meld seamlessly into a Notes environment, so companies
that standardize on Notes and Domino are often quite willing to go
with SmartSuite as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just found ourselves in Notes so much that it made sense to
go with SmartSuite,'' says Eric Stratmann, director of information
resources for Albemarle Corp., a chemical manufacturer in Baton
Rouge, La. Stratmann checked out Microsoft Office, but preferred
the way SmartSuite and Notes worked together. ``We felt it was more
tightly integrated with Notes, and it had the same look and feel as
Notes.''
</P>
<P>
   As Microsoft has proven time and again, customers need a mighty
good reason to buy someone else's software once you've got them
hooked. Too bad Lotus lost most of its customers before it grasped
this principle. Still, there are 20 million left, and Lotus plans
to keep them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
