<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLVO XC _ SMOOTH AND SURE OF FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was expecting the brawny, solid ``clunk'' that the doors made
when I slammed them. Classic, rugged Volvo. The smooth ride on the
highway and the stiff, clinging carve through corners was no
surprise, either.
</P>
<P>
   What I was not expecting was its performance in snow and, more
particularly, on ice. It was as sure-footed there as any SUV, and
more stable, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   And I am thankful that, before I took it on the road for a week,
I got to test the Volvo on the slippery course used by the New
England Motor Press Association in its annual winter vehicle
competition. It was here that the 2000 Volvo XC AWD chewed through
snow and would not let ice keep it from its assigned line.
</P>
<P>
   Set it in half a foot of crusty snow and try to make it spin. No
go. Drive it straight ahead at 40 on a sheet of glare ice, stomp
the ABS, and take your hands off the wheel. It came to a steady,
straight stop. Put it into a tight turn on the ice and try to make
it fishtail. The Volvo would allow no such thing. Start from a stop
on an icy upgrade. You could feel the ABS and traction control
working in concert to reduce spin, wheel-by-wheel, so that it
seemed it was a four-legged creature walking its way up a slippery
hill.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're longing for one of those $50,000-plus SUVs, this
may be the best all-season car a cold-weather driver could own.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo has long been associated with sturdiness, safety, a
certain tweedy cachet, and station wagons. Until recently, a third
of all Volvos sold were wagons. Then, in 1997 the XC _ for Cross
Country _ was introduced as a 1998 model. Now, the XC accounts for
25 percent of Volvo's wagon sales, and has helped boost wagon sales
to 50 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between the minivan and the SUV, the Volvo XC has
found a home.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo, of course, makes other wagons: front-wheel drive, the V70
all-wheel drive. The XC is the countrified version of the latter,
and Volvo has aimed it correctly at city and suburban drivers with
an eye on an active, outdoor lifestyle. But it is also a great car
for folks who live in the country, folks for whom any trip out for
anything is at least a 30-minute round trip and for whom the
weather is not always an ally.
</P>
<P>
   As I said, I'm grateful I got to drive this in the winter test.
Otherwise, I might not have realized what was in my hands. Outside,
even though it's a bit more of a wedge than the boxes of the past,
it still looks simple, pure Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, add the $2,200 package that includes leather seats, a
sunroof, simulated wood appointments, and you could be in any
luxury sedan. The leather buckets up front are fairly firm, though
I'd like them a bit more supportive at the thigh _ like the bench
seat in the rear, for instance. It's a 60/40split that opens to a
generous cargo area as big as most found in SUVs. The cargo area
also features a pop-up, rear-facing seat for children (as many as
three tots).
</P>
<P>
   The Cross Country has 6.5 inches of ground clearance, an inch
more than the V70 AWD. It's also two inches taller. This doesn't
mean you'll want to go off-road bushwhacking with it, but it does
mean it will move a bit better through deep snow and that you get
some of the up-high, airy feeling an SUV can give you.
</P>
<P>
   The list of standard features is lengthy and includes heated
outside mirrors, heated front seats, dual-zone climate control,
pollen and dust filters, sunroof, remote keyless entry and
security, eight-way power adjustable driver's seat, and a premium
sound system.
</P>
<P>
   Safety features, too, are impressive and they include a
high-strength steel passenger safety cage; transverse engine that
distributes crash energy away from front-seat occupants; air bags
for front passengers and side curtains for front and middle seats;
and seatbacks that change shape to cushion front-seat passengers
and reduce back, head, and whiplash injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Cross Country is powered by a 2.4-liter, in-line
five-cylinder engine. It's a 20-valve DOHC power plant with light
pressure turbo. Power gets transferred through an
electronically-controlled, four-speed automatic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   You do not get the impressive snap that some turbocharged
engines give you, but on the highway it gives a smooth, steady
surge that is impressive after how sedate it seems moving slowly
over country roads. It delivered just over 20 miles per gallon in a
wide mix of driving.
</P>
<P>
   The ride, quite firm and with no sense of lateral sway even at
speed on sharp corners, is delivered with a front suspension that
mixes hydraulic struts, coil springs, and a stabilizer bar. In the
rear is Volvo's multilink, semi-independent suspension, coupled
with coil springs and gas shocks.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Cross Country stand out, however, is its traction
control/drive train system. Most of the time, 95 percent of the
torque is being delivered to the front wheels. If there's minor
slippage up there, a traction-control system adjusts
wheel-to-wheel. When the going gets slippery or rough or reckless,
however, a monitoring system picks up differences in rotation
between front and rear wheels and, using a viscous coupler that
acts much like a clutch, distributes more torque to the rear. At
times, 95 percent of the torque can be delivered there, depending
on where the wheels are spinning and where the best bite can be
had. It is a seamless transfer that the car does for you.
</P>
<P>
   It was this system, which also employs the ABS brakes to cut
wheel spin to one wheel while delivering torque to others, that
gave the Cross Country the sensation of a stalking, four-footed
beast that I felt while running it uphill on a sheet of glare ic.
And it is this system that puts it among the best winter cars you
could buy.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The center console/armrest is too low. I found myself hunching
down to put my right elbow onto it.
</P>
<P>
   --The driver's side seat controls, down on the outer edge of the
seat, are in too cramped a space and you end up fumbling around for
them. Volvo ought to go the way of some other manufacturers and put
them on the door.
</P>
<P>
   --The cupholder, shaky and shallow, could not hold a bottle of
water securely.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The two-step bins in the front doors. You could keep change,
pens, other small items on rubber-bottomed top step; maps, larger
items on lower step.
</P>
<P>
   --The cargo-netted bins that ran along the side of the cargo box
at the rear of the car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
