<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AN UNCOMMON MELON WITH DELICATE FLAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you saw them in the store, you probably didn't know what
they were. Pepino melons are one of those odd things placed on the
exotic fruit table.
</P>
<P>
   Like more common melons, pepinos can be eaten raw but they are
certainly now as big as a crenshaw or a cantaloupe. They are also
called melon pears because of their demure size _ each one is only
about the size of a hand _ and slightly elongated shape.
</P>
<P>
   Though they haven't caught on in the United States, Elizabeth
Schneider writes in ``Uncommon Fruits and Vegetables,'' that in
Japan, pepinos are offered as a gift, as a dessert, and even as a
showpiece. Not unreasonable since pepinos have a lightly
greenish-yellow skin with violet or mauve dappled stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Pepino melons have a delicate flavor and are as refreshing as
summer cucumbers, writes Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   Availability: Erratically available somewhere between late
winter and early summer.
</P>
<P>
   Selection and storage: Sniff the fruit deeply, writes Schneider.
It should smell lightly sweet, almost like honeysuckle. When
pressed, the flesh should give like a partly ripe plum but not be
soft. Avoid pepinos with dents or bruises. The undercolor of the
skin should be golden to pinky-apricot, Schneider writes, not
greenish.
</P>
<P>
   If the color is not quite right, keep the pepinos at room
temperature until they become more golden. Try not to keep it
longer, as the delicate flavor will fade quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Preparation: Pepino melons simply need to be sliced and peeled.
Even the soft, pulpy seeds are edible.
</P>
<P>
   Uses: Serve pepino raw in fruit salads, wrapped in prosciutto as
you would honeydew.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional information: Pepino is low in calories and high in
vitamin C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
