<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-ART-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE SPEAKS AT HOLOCAUST MEMORIAL AND MEETS WITH SURVIVORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(See also POPE-REACT) 
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing his week-long spiritual pilgrimage to the Holy Land,
Pope John Paul II visited the Yad Vashem Holocaust memorial in
Jerusalem on Thursday, where he declared that the Roman Catholic
was ``deeply saddened'' by the Christian persecution of Jews
through the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But some Jews were disappointed that the pope stopped short of
apologizing for the failure of Pope Pius XII and the Vatican to
speak out when Nazi Germany was rounding up millions of Jews across
Europe and dispatching them to death camps for extermination.
</P>
<P>
   ``As bishop of Rome and successor of the Apostle Peter,'' the
pope said Thursday, ``I assure the Jewish people that the Catholic
, motivated by the Gospel law of truth and love, and by no
political considerations, is deeply saddened by the hatred, acts of
persecution and displays of anti-Semitism directed against the Jews
by Christians at any time and in any place.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope continued, ``The rejects racism in any form as a denial
of the image of the Creator inherent in every human being.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke at a ceremony in the memorial's darkened Hall of
Remembrances, where his aides laid a wreath in memory of the 6
million Jews killed in the Holocaust. The pope recalled that the
victims had included some Jewish neighbors and friends from his
childhood in Nazi-occupied Poland, when he was known as Karol
Wojtyla.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's emotionally charged remarks were broadcast live on
Israeli television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to Vad Yashem to pay homage to the millions of
Jewish people who, stripped of everything, especially of human
dignity, were murdered in the Holocaust,'' the pope said. ``More
than half a century has passed, but the memories remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish to remember. But we wish to remember for a purpose,
namely to ensure that never again will evil prevail, as it did for
the millions of innocent victims of Nazism.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward the pope met a half dozen Holocaust survivors and
Polish Jews from his hometown, Wadowice. When one woman began
weeping, the pope consoled her with a gentle touch on her arm.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak, whose grandparents died in the Nazi
death camp at Treblinka, was among the Israeli officials at the
ceremony. ``You have done more than anyone else to bring about the
historic change in attitude of the toward the Jewish people,''
Barak told the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``You raised the flag of fraternity to full mast, setting into
liturgy a request for forgiveness, for wrongs committed by members
of your faith against others, especially against the Jewish
people,'' the prime minister said. ``We appreciate this noble act
most profoundly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis said they wished the pope had gone further and
explained the Vatican's silence during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   But other Israelis observed that the pope had already gone
further than his predecessors in working for greater understanding
between Jews and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope's very gesture of coming here marks a turning point
for Jews and Christians,'' Eli Zborowski, one of the Holocaust
survivors who met the pope, said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope also issued a blessing of Israel when he met President
Ezer Weizman. When the last pope to visit the Holy Land, Pope Paul
VI, did so in 1964, he refrained from even mentioning Israel by
name.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The pope used his visit to the Holocaust memorial to press for
solidarity between Jews and Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this place of solemn remembrance, I fervently pray that our
sorrow for the tragedy which the Jewish people suffered in the 20th
century will lead to a new relationship between Christians and
Jews,'' the pope said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us build a new future in which there will be no more
anti-Jewish feeling among Christians or anti-Christian feeling
among Jews,'' he said, ``but rather the mutual respect required of
those who adore the one Creator and Lord, and look to Abraham as
our common father in faith.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the need for amicable coexistence between Jews and
Christians, the pope also met with Israel's two chief rabbis,
Eliyahu Bakshi Doron and Israel Meir Lau. They presented him with a
Bible inscribed with a passage from the book of Micah: ``For
everyone who will walk, everyone in the name of his God, and we
will walk in the name of the Lord, our God, forever and ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope has already broken new ground for the Vatican during
his week-long pilgrimage, visiting a Palestinian refugee camp near
Bethlehem, where he deplored the ``torment'' of the Palestinians,
and celebrating Mass in Bethlehem's Manger Square.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul was also the first pope to visit the Nazi death camp
of Auschwitz and to attend worship services at a synagogue in Rome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5776 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-DADDIO-HNS &LR;      03-23 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DADDIO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IF IT'S NOT WORTH WATCHING, IT MUST BE ON NBC 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why NBC doesn't throw in the towel is beyond understanding. The
network has only a few quality shows left and its new shows this
season outside of ``West Wing'' have been embarrassingly bad.
</P>
<P>
   What it really ought to do is join ABC in giving up entirely.
Just use Regis Philbin to mop up and turn out the lights. Forget
sitcoms and dramas. Go with a game show.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, NBC doesn't have Regis, it has Maury Povich, so it
ought to schedule ``Twenty One'' every night, even though it's
horrible. Why? Because nothing could be as bad as the network's two
latest shows, ``Daddio'' and ``Battery Park'' (both Thursday).
Unless you count the two shows they replaced, ``Jesse'' and ``Stark
Raving Mad,'' the heretofore double nadirs of big-league network
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when Thursday was ``must-see'' TV? Now it's
unwatchable. Now we're begging for Maury Povich and that simpleton
game show of his, even though he's so easy to loathe. Just try to
survive two minutes of ``Daddio.'' Go ahead. You'll be begging for
Maury's sound-proof booth where the contestants can't hear his
inanities.
</P>
<P>
   If only it were that easy on ``Daddio.'' This is a family sitcom
and you ought to know from experience that NBC doesn't do well with
families (or sitcoms, of late). This hugely embarrassing, laughless
black hole is centered on stay-at-home dad Chris (Michael Chiklis
of ``The Commish'') and his lawyer wife Linda (Anita Barone). They
have four kids to juggle. Reminder: Cloying TV kids are best served
as singles or, in dire moments, in pairs. Four make you think about
murder. Or Maury.
</P>
<P>
   The premise, and we use that term loosely once again, is about
the adventures of Chiklis as a stay-at-home father. Boy, there's a
cutting-edge idea. That's never been done before. That's a rarity
in the real world. What next, a sitcom about these weird, wacky
things called computers?
</P>
<P>
   So what we get are endless jokes about manhood, spilled food,
disciplining the kids, plus a mean-spirited neighbor thrown in for
what appears to be comic effect but in reality is a diversion from
the lack of laughs in the main plot. Formulaic doesn't begin to
describe how utterly lame this show is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddio'' will lose about 8 million ``Friends'' viewers and
won't lead people to ``Frasier,'' either.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Battery Park,'' which attempts some kind of
broad, stylistic approach to cop humor but feels forced and
strained and witless throughout. The show centers on a group of
detectives a la ``Barney Miller'' but fails to ignite the sense of
character that show did so wonderfully. This show is from Gary
David Goldberg (``Spin City''), who loves standard sitcom
convention more than almost anyone. But this time he doesn't have
Michael J. Fox _ or good writers _ to lift the material from the
grasp of the mundane.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Perkins is the cold-hearted captain who aspires to be
mayor. She's thoroughly unlikable and can't wring a laugh from the
turgid one-two jokes that Goldberg employs throughout. The only
shining light here is Justin Louis as Lt. Ben Hardin. He can make
the flattest of all jokes stand up and almost sing because his
delivery is so good. With a little help, he could stand out. The
problems, however, go way deeper than one guy waiting desperately
for a knock-out punch line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Battery Park'' is just dumb. The characters are broadly drawn
and uninteresting. There are two gonzo detectives. A dumb one. A
dumber one. And a woman who, when not showing her bare midriff, is
put in super-tight sweaters that scream, ``I'm packing heat.'' You
get the feeling that a lot of sitcom hack tendencies are being
tossed around and mixed together here, hoping that out of
familiarity laughs will spring.
</P>
<P>
   They don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddio'' and ``Battery Park'' are excellent examples of why
the sitcom genre is dying. They break no new ground. They rely on
laugh tracks _ loud ones _ to slap a giggle out of viewers who
otherwise would be unaware that something funny was just said. They
put cardboard cut-out characters on the screen so that we will
easily identify with them (wacky neighbor, dumb cop, cute kid,
etc.) and take the easy, tried-and-true route whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   A minimum of creative effort is being put forth in these shows.
NBC ought to know _ from ``Jesse'' and ``Stark Raving Mad'' and a
lot of other examples _ that the public is too smart for this.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
