<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5788 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a bc-LADN-WAKE     03-23 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
bc-LADN-WAKE
Even the 'Dead' have chemistry and charisma 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The film: ``Waking the Dead'' (R; language, sexuality). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes: Directed by Keith Gordon. Written by Robert
Dillon. Executive produced by Jodie Foster. Released by USA Films. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The stars: Billy Crudup, Jennifer Connelly, Janet McTeer, Hal
Holbrook. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: One hour, 46 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Playing: Town Center 5 Encino; Century 14, Century City;
Playhouse 7, Pasadena; and other select theaters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !By Evan Henerson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking the Dead'' is the kind of movie that will one day have
clerks at video stores furrowing their brows. Even now I can hear
the exchange at Blockbuster now: ``Hey Bill, where does this one
go? Drama? Politics? Love story?'' ``Dunno, Ed. Stick it
miscellaneous. Next to 'Titanic.'''
</P>
<P>
   Resistant to categorization as it is, ``Waking'' tries on
several hats and manages to wear most of them skillfully. Taken as
a man's evaluation of his own self-worth, it's insightful and
complex. As a romance, the movie is even more effective despite
some clunky dialogue and a script that doesn't always know what to
do with its characters when they're not in love. At a different
time, ``Waking the Dead'' might have been marketed as a Valentine's
Day date movie. During an election year, it's a ``to thine own self
be true'' warning to Bush and Gore, et al.
</P>
<P>
   As he demonstrated in the little-seen ``Mother Night,'' director
Keith Gordon can really sink his teeth into a story about a morally
conflicted hero. He's got a lulu of one in Fielding Pierce (played
by Billy Crudup), an idealistic U.S. Coast Guard officer turned
district attorney who has ``future in politics'' all but stamped on
his birth certificate. The year is 1972, the scene Chicago; our man
has a Kennedy profile and the integrity to match.
</P>
<P>
   The potential Achilles heel to a ``Mr. Smith'' outcome for
Fielding is a passionate relationship with Sarah Williams (Jennifer
Connelly), a heavily left-leaning activist whose world views don't
entirely mesh with those of our future Washingtonian. She calls
herself his ``Jiminy Cricket,'' but they stay happily if not always
philosophically together. After Sarah is killed in a politically
motivated car bombing, a devastated Fielding enters the `80s with a
new girlfriend, influential backers and an eye toward winning a
vacant congressional seat.
</P>
<P>
   One problem: He can't shake Sarah from his thoughts neither her
person nor her principles. As the election draws closer, Fielding
finds himself increasingly racked with self-doubt and heading
toward a breakdown. Plus he's seeing Sarah everywhere he goes at
the foot of his bed, in crowds and airport corridors.
</P>
<P>
   The film jumps back and forth between the two decades,
juxtaposing the election-minded Fielding with the open-minded guy
he used to be. We get extended glimpses of Sarah, including a
couple of scenes demonstrating how uncomfortably she fits in the
life he is creating, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, of course, this premise shouldn't work. Fielding and
Sarah wouldn't last a month together, much less two years. But
somehow, inexplicably, Crudup and Connelly make us believe that
nothing can or should keep these two people apart. Their chemistry
is simply wonderful. Charismatic even when he's conflicted, Crudup
is in practically every scene, delivering the kinds of monologues
that are usually reserved for plays. It's a potentially star-making
performance, if anybody sees this movie. But then again, people
said the same thing about Crudup's turn as Steve Prefontaine in
``Without Limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Connelly's is the trickier part, largely because in Robert
Dillon's script (adapted from the novel by Scott Spencer), Sarah is
underwritten as the teary martyr. Often reduced to the kind of
dialogue that real people don't speak ``You are the incarnation of
your family's ambition. I am the incarnation of your family's
fear'' Connelly still manages to bring the character beautifully to
life. In some of her earlier exchanges with Fielding, her
mannerisms and deliveries even suggest Jodie Foster, ``Waking the
Dead's'' executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its two leads, ``Waking the Dead'' doesn't bother
with developing any of the other characters in any great detail.
Hal Holbrook is on hand as Fielding's political mentor and Molly
Parker is Holbrook's niece, Fielding's second girlfriend. And
here's hoping that Janet McTeer's Oscar nominated work in
``Tumbleweeds'' will keep her from ever again having to play
nothing roles like Fielding's sympathetic older sister.
</P>
<P>
   Keep an eye on Gordon, the talented actor turned director who
seems more than capable of steering a multifaceted story in several
directions without losing its heart. ``Waking the Dead'' should
give a viewer plenty to think about, no matter where it is shelved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
