<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INVESTIGATION (Washington) _ The Justice Department has
launched a criminal inquiry into whether thousands of White House
e-mail messages were illegally withheld from congressional campaign
finance investigators. The probe will focus on White House computer
breakdowns that made it impossible to search thousands of incoming
e-mails in response to congressional subpoenas. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON-TRAVEL (Washington) _ The Republican-led
Congress opens an inquiry into Hillary Rodham Clinton's
reimbursement for her travel on Air Force planes during her New
York Senate campaign. Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., heading the House
panel looking into the issue, says she took 26 trips to New York in
seven months last year. That cost taxpayers $182,421, and the
Clinton campaign reimbursed the government $36,685, Kolbe says.
Democrats call the probe a ``partisan exercise conducted at
taxpayer expense.'' By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The ghost of Newt Gingrich's rampage
through the House of Representatives still haunts the Republican
majority on Capitol Hill. Term limits, a big GOP issue six years
ago, is driving many Republican members to retire. But the big
change is that the retirees will include the heads of five powerful
committees who were due to lose their chairmanships under the
voluntary rules imposed by the former speaker in 1994. By MARIANNE
MEANS
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Directors Guild of America
made a terrible mistake when it removed the name of D.W. Griffith
from an award it gave filmmaker Steven Spielberg. Griffith was a
racist but he was one of the greatest pioneers in motion pictures,
and the removal of his name was an extreme example of political
correctness. The directors' action would be like judging the
presidencies of Lyndon Johnson, Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton only
by their mistakes. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
