<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, March 24:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND (Jerusalem) _ At Yad Vashem, Pope John Paul II
condemns the Holocaust but does not apologize for the Catholic
Church's role. Earlier, he and the cardinals with him met all the
top Israeli rabbis. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2, and a map.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   POPE-REACT (Jersulem) _ Local reaction to the pope's visit. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-NAZILABOR (Berlin) _ A final settlement has been reached
on compensating Nazi-era slave and forced laborers. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA (Naila, India) _ President Clinton visits an
Indian village, says democracy can defeat poverty. By Celia W.
Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TIGERS (Dateline to kum) _ The president goes looking
for wild tigers. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-ELECTIONS (New Delhi, India) _ Pakistan's military
ruler, Pervez Musharraf, gave his country a a timetable for local
elections on Thursday, but he said he had not decided on a date for
elections to the National Assembly and four provincial assemblies.
President Clinton, who will visit Pakistan briefly on Saturday,
said Musharraf's general's announcement was good news but not
enough. (Summary from wires.) By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-U.S. (United Nations) _ A bitter debate is expected
Thursday over the U.S. effort to reduce its assessments at the
United Nations. By Barbara Crossette.
