<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5838 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DADDIO-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      03-23 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DADDIO-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHERLY POTENTIAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2{ stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Daddio,'' a situation comedy about a smart and fun
stay-at-home dad, is mildly progressive-minded in its set-up and
comfortably old-fashioned in all other facets of its execution. One
is easily forgiven for wishing the laugh lines had a little more
sparkle, and it's a less than ideal companion series to the bawdy
``Friends,'' which airs before it, but the premise and the cast are
solid enough to expect future improvement and a decent prime-time
run.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chiklis stars as Chris, a guy who chucks his dead-end
job to stay with his kids when his wife, Linda (Anita Barone),
lands a lucrative post in a law firm. The kids are your usual
precocious brood _ ace jockette Shannon (Cristina Kernan),
conniving Max (Martin Spanjers), adorable Jake (Mitch Holleman) and
a baby. There's also an intelligence-challenged pal (Kevin Crowley)
and a grumpy neighbor (Steve Ryan) who both could easily have just
been drained out of a Cuisinart in the Nick at Nite offices.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising comic possibilities here come from Chris'
induction into the ``mommies club,'' an assortment of neighborhood
women who hang out and share parenting tips. In particular, Amy
Wilson as Barb, a painfully earnest woman determined to be the
perfect mother _ while wringing all the fun and spontaneity out of
her children's existence _ seems a perfect foil for Chiklis, who
does a nice slow burn as she goes into a mini-lecture on the
difference between ``fruit juices'' and ``fruit drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's episode ends with Chris delivering, in essence, the
series' statement of purpose: There's no shame or emasculation
whatsoever in a man doing this kind of work when he loves his
children. There's more than a little commitment, as well as ample
wit, in the moment, and it ensures that we're willing to watch
executive producers Matt Berry and Ric Swartzlander build on the
modest promise of tonight's pilot. &QL; 
---The show: ``Daddio.'' &QL; 
What: Family sitcom about a stay-at-home father. &QL; 
The stars: Michael Chiklis, Anita Barone, Cristina Kernan, Martin
Spanjers, Amy Wilson. &QL; 
Where: NBC. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1419EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5842 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-GARAGE-DOOR-TRIAL-HNS     03-23 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARAGE-DOOR-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FIREFIGHTER TESTIFIES IN LAWSUIT AGAINST DOOR-OPENER COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A former San Francisco firefighter testified
that she tried in vain to inhale oxygen from outside a burning
garage where she and other firefighters were trapped because of
what her lawyer contends was a malfunctioning door opener.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Stapper, now 39, says she clawed at the garage door in
the early morning of March 9, 1995, before losing consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   She is suing the Genie Corp., a leading manufacturer of garage
door openers, for some $8 million in damages. Stapper contends that
the garage door opener did not work, and that the nylon cord that
can disengage the door from the automatic system had burned.
</P>
<P>
   In the third week of the trial, Stapper was guided to the
witness stand Wednesday, she recalled the house fire that left her
blind, with burns over 40 percent of her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled my mask off because I was suffocating in it, and I
tried to stick my face in the crack in the garage door so I could
get some air,'' Stapper said Wednesday, turning her head in the
direction of the Superior Court jury. ``When I sucked in I ... felt
like I was breathing fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-alarm fire, which started at 1 a.m., took more than
two hours to control in part because of 70 mph winds.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters reportedly didn't see smoke or flames when they
entered the open garage at the home in the city's Diamond Heights
neighborhood. By the time they retreated, the garage door had
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Louis Mambretti, a 25-year veteran of the department, died
in the fire. Besides Stapper, two other firefighters, Keith Onishi
and John Pieretti, were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Genie declined to comment outside court. The company
has maintained that the garage door opener did not malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree that what happened to Melanie Stapper is a tragic
situation,'' Mary Wirth, a lawyer for the company, said at a
pretrial hearing. ``But it didn't happen because of a faulty garage
door opener. She was injured because the firefighters did not watch
her back.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapper wore her dark blue firefighter's dress uniform to court,
and was guided up to the witness stand by her lawyer, Browne
Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Greene began his questioning by asking if Stapper could see
where she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't know if it was a courtroom, I would just see a
bunch of blurs,'' Stapper said.
</P>
<P>
   Stapper turned her head in the direction of the jury as Greene
asked her if she saw any colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just see some white,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, tears flowed as Stapper talked about her slow recovery.
Several jurors looked at the floor and at least one reached for a
tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accepted the fact that my vision is not getting any
better,'' Stapper said before breaking into sobs.
</P>
<P>
   Stapper said she counsels other burn victims, and speaks to
firefighters about the incident, but needs daily medical care. She
said she has flashbacks and nightmares about the fire and recovery
process, which she described as ``pure hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last at least two more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, one of the witnesses estimated that Stapper
could be entitled to as much as $6.9 million in economic damages
for wages loss and medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Genie lawyers disputed the figure.
</P>
<P>
   Stapper is also asking for non-economic damages for pain and
suffering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1422EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5853 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WHATEVER-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      03-23 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHATEVER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MATTER WHAT, IT`S NOT ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What took them so long to remake last year's instant classic
``She's All That''? Regardless of the reasons for the unacceptable
delay _ and from the evidence onscreen, creative perfectionism was
not one of them _ ``Whatever It Takes'' is finally here. And boy,
those who thought ``She's All That'' could never be equaled were so
wrong. In fact, this thing proves that it can be virtually carbon
copied.
</P>
<P>
   This one's got it all. It's got the sub-Cliff's Notes reworking
of a literary masterwork _ in this case, ``Cyrano de Bergerac'' as
opposed to ``Pygmalion'' _ in a modern-day high school setting.
It's got Jodi Lyn O'Keefe playing the exact same kind of snooty
teen queen. It's got an even cuter actress than O'Keefe as the
unconvincing ugly duckling. It's got a big, climactic prom scene.
And it's got a really sweet guy hero who takes the whole movie to
realize the obvious about which girl is right for him.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, director and former television actor David Raynr
presents it all in the most homogenized, flavorless sitcom style
imaginable. See? Classic all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan (Shane West of TV's ``Once Again'') and Maggie (Marla
Sokoloff of TV's ``The Practice'') are lifelong next-door neighbors
and best friends. They're both at a loss for prom dates because,
apparently, he's obsessed with the school's most popular girl
(O'Keefe's Ashley) and his neighbor's too smart and picky. The
thing is, Ashley's dumb jock cousin Chris (James Franco) wants
Maggie in the worst way, mainly because she's the only girl who's
never given him the time of day.
</P>
<P>
   So Chris and Ryan make a secret pact. They'll trade their inside
knowledge to help one another get that crucial prom date with their
heart's desire. Through such modern miracles as call waiting, Ryan
helps the crass Chris appear sensitive to Maggie's mind. Via tips
on how to act like a jerk, Chris teaches Ryan to convince
status-conscious Ashley that he's more than just an
accordion-playing geek.
</P>
<P>
   It hardly needs mentioning that, through all of this mildly
titillating skulduggery, we never have the slightest doubt that
there's no one like the girl next door.
</P>
<P>
   What's that you say? You want what? Originality? Or at least
something marginally distinctive? That's not what these movies are
about!
</P>
<P>
   But OK, if you must have something different, how about Ryan's
posse of dweeby friends who do mildly risque things? It looks like
their scenes were written and shot after the rest of the movie _
and after ``American Pie'' became a huge hit _ and they play like
afterthoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Still not different enough for you? How about the totally
outrageous moment when the gym floor opens up and all the fancy
dressed dancers fall into the pool underneath? Now, some killjoys
may mention that that scene is lifted from something called ``It's
a Wonderful Life,'' like such an obscure reference matters or
something. Who cares about movies that were made during the time of
``Cyrano'' anyway? &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The film: ``Whatever It Takes'' (PG-13; language, nudity). &QL; 
The stars: Shane West, Marla Sokoloff, Jodi Lyn O'Keefe, James
Franco. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by David Raynr. Written by Mark
Schwahn. Produced by Paul Schiff. Released by Columbia Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 32 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
