<HEADLINE>
AOL-TIME WARNER'S MAIDS OF HONOR CAUGHT THE BOUQUET  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Columbus and San Diego _ note 3rd graf)   (This 350-word ``separate-buy'' financial story is from the March
issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her
e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By NICK PACHETTI  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Jan. 10, Time Warner shareholders from Ted Turner on down
were high-fiving one another as they watched their stock soar 39
percent, to $90 a share, after America Online said it planned to
acquire the media giant.
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't the only investors celebrating. That same day,
frenetic trading drove the stock prices of Time Warner rivals up an
average of 14 percent: Walt Disney (15 percent), News Corporation
(19 percent), Seagram (11 percent), and Viacom (10 percent).
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't come as a big surprise, according to new research
from academics at San Diego State University and Ohio State
University. After looking at takeovers of 141 companies and their
competitors from 1982 to 1991, researchers found that most rival
companies experienced a jump in market value as well.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? There's an increased probability that those
competitors will become targets themselves, and investors know
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is very, very smart,'' says co-author Ralph
Walkling, a finance professor at Ohio State's Fisher College of
Business. ``It factors the probability into the stock price.''
</P>
<P>
   Those rivals whose price doesn't move _ which is less than half
of them _ may never make it to the merger alter. But those
companies whose shares rise, the study found, have certain
attractive characteristics in common, including lower managerial
ownership and a greater debt capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The company with the biggest gains on the day of the merger
announcement is the one most likely to consummate a merger within a
year.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation as the most
likely takeover candidate among Time Warner's rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing which company is the next target in a given industry is
appealing. After all, shares of target companies typically increase
more than those of the bidding company.
</P>
<P>
   But Walkling cautions investors who are eager to plow money into
companies like News Corporation. ``Remember _ stocks may have
already adjusted by the time individual investors get into them,''
he says. ``That definitely is a big risk factor.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the market may be smarter than you are. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Nick Pachetti is a staff writer at WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
