<HEADER>
A5860 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-MARRIAGE-NO-MORE-NYTS     03-23 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-NO-MORE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 MARRIAGE: JUST A BUDGET ITEM? Or THE BEDROCK of AMERICAN &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax,
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JACK HITT  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    California voters recently passed Proposition 22, which says
that only marriages between men and women are officially
recognized, and yet the state legislature already extends some
benefits to domestic partnerships.
 &HT;    In December, the Vermont Supreme Court ruled pretty much the
same thing: Gay couples cannot be deprived of the legal benefits
enjoyed by married heterosexuals. In both cases, the usual brigade
of talking heads bobbed across my television screen screaming that
these cases constituted an assault on marriage.
 &HT;    I'll say. This is what marriage has come to? A bunch of pension
rollover deferments, tax loopholes and health-care portability
abatements?
 &HT;    Now, I'm a straight first-time husband with two legitimate kids,
and according to America's family-values czar, the thrice-married
Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia, my love-laced nest is the source of all
that is good and true in this world (where are my royalties?) and
is now under siege.
 &HT;    I happen to think Barr is right. But it's not gay folks I'm
worried about; it's Adam Smith. Increasingly, marriage is being
recast as just another budget item in everyone's personal finance
portfolio.
 &HT;    The House just passed a bill reducing the ``marriage tax
penalty.'' Prenuptial agreements were once optional instruments for
multimillionaires; now legal Web sites instruct us that ``every
couple should and must have a prenuptial agreement or marriage
contract.''
 &HT;    In our pop culture, the wife or husband as economic object is
now a routine Hollywood plot device. Ever since ``Indecent
Proposal,'' that consumerist reworking of the fabled ``droit du
seigneur,'' and all the way up to the recent ``The Bachelor''
(Chris O'Donnell must marry somebody by a certain date or lose the
big inheritance), the message is clear: Next to money, romance is
second-rate bunk.
 &HT;    Must I mention Rick Rockwell and ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'' At one point the show's proposed host was none
other than Marla Maples.
 &HT;    Increasingly, marriage is being converted into a neo-feudal
property arrangement for the Nasdaq gentry. Even dating these days
is understood as little more than the discovery period before the
big merger.
 &HT;    WB's new dating show, ``Change of Heart,'' arranges for a boy or
girl who is going out with someone to date someone else and then
come on the show to discuss the two before deciding between them.
You may recognize this process. It's called comparison shopping.
 &HT;    What is happening to marriage is the culmination of the market's
radical reshaping of the culture at large. The invisible hand is
tearing away the ideals that once held together most of our
institutions. Hospitals used to operate under some unwritten notion
of altruism. Now patients are ``health care consumers'' told to
shop among various doctors or ``gatekeepers'' whose new duties
include monitoring the flow of gross costs.
 &HT;    Schools are also undergoing a similar metaphorical shift with a
customer-clerk relationship replacing the old student-teacher one.
The Dewey principle of public education for all? Let 'em eat
vouchers.
 &HT;    Even churches have hired market consultants, and now the surging
congregations out West gather in huge warehouse temples selling
spirituality the way Home Depot moves precut lumber. It makes sense
that love would go the same way _ just another failed ideology,
like communism, collapsing in the path of the market's
indiscriminate force to lay bare the economic decision at the core.
 &HT;    According to the academics, this is where marriage began. Feudal
dads chose their children's spouses to upwardly mobilize
themselves. Romantic passion is said to be a cultural construction
that dates from the 12th-century poetic tradition of courtly love
and developed into a new ideal of romance in the court of Eleanor
of Aquitaine.
 &HT;    Then, the story goes, the growing humanism of the Renaissance
and the Industrial Age emancipated men and women to become wild
romantic honeys _ like Scott and Zelda Fitzgerald or Nick and Nora
Charles.
 &HT;    I've never bought this stuff. Maybe that's how it developed for
some Burgundian merchant class. But I spent four college years with
my face in a Lewis &AMP; Short dictionary translating Latin. Horace's
Pyrrha, Catullus's Lesbia. Trust me, romantic love predated the
French.
 &HT;    But the public institution of marriage, declared sacred and
presided over by the clergy, did not. Despite what Barr may think,
marriage was largely a private vow made between two people without
witnesses. (For Christianity's first 1,000 years, marriage was even
a suspect state, arguably a mockery of God's love and doctrinally
inferior to celibacy.)
 &HT;    Protestant agitation made marriage into an official public
occasion, with licenses, clergy and witnesses. The Catholic Church
didn't catch up until the Council of Trent in 1563. The British
Parliament did not make marriage a state-sanctioned event until
1753. America's common-law marital tradition is not some hick
version of free love but, in fact, the remnant of the oldest form
of marriage, the romantic vow.
 &HT;    Have you ever fallen in love? And run around cooing to all your
friends like a moon-drunk calf? That fine little moment, I'm
willing to bet, has always been at the beginning of most marriages.
Recasting the institution as some kind of tax-loophole, Defense of
Marriage Act, comparison-shopping, bridal-auction bargain deal is
the real threat _ not homosexuals in love.
 &HT;    But I don't want you to think I don't set limits. I have kids; I
am a father; I draw the line.
 &HT;    Precisely because Barr and I agree that love-in-marriage is the
bedrock of Western civilization, I would never permit Marla Maples
or Rick Rockwell in my house _ or any of their kind, whether it be
prenuptially arranged dot-com tycoons or old-school climbers who
shed one legal spouse after another, like Pamela Churchill Harriman
or, come to think of it, Bob Barr. I've got to think of my
children.
 &HT;     c.2000 Jack Hitt  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jack Hitt is a contributing writer for The New York Times
Magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
