<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5873 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-COOKSCORNER-LADN &LR;      03-23 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD WORLD COOKIES
</HEADLINE>
 CORNER-LADN  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three readers came to Mary Menchaca's rescue with similar
recipes for Ricotta Cookies _ and were happy to share them.
Hopefully, they're like the ones Menchaca remembers her grandmother
making.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine M. Blagg of Tujunga noted that the recipe she sent
along is one of her favorite cookies and can be decorated with
buttercream frosting and assorted candies for any holiday or
festivity. ``The batch is so large that it is great to take to work
or other social functions.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Bushelle of Woodland Hills shared the same recipe except
hers has 1 cup of softened buttered instead of 1/2 cup margarine as
in Blagg's, and she drops them by tablespoonfuls instead of
teaspoonfuls. So suit yourself and try either way.
</P>
<P>
   A bit different variation on the theme was submitted by Sandra
Smith of Sylmar. Give them a whirl. Sounds like you're in for a
special treat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ITALIAN COOKIES &QL; 
(Shared by Catherine M. Blagg, Tujunga and Linda Bushelle, Woodland
Hills) &QL; 
1/2 cup margarine, softened &QL; 
2 cups granulated sugar &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
1 pound ricotta cheese &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
4 cups flour &QL; 
1 teaspoon baking soda &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
Vanilla frosting &QL; 
Colored candies
</P>
<P>
   Cream together margarine, sugar and eggs until light and fluffy.
Beat in ricotta cheese and vanilla until mixed. Add flour, baking
soda and salt, mixing until well blended
</P>
<P>
   Drop by teaspoonfuls on lightly greased cookie sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 12 minutes or until bottom of
cookies are lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Frost with your favorite vanilla frosting and sprinkle with
colored candies as desired. Makes lots of cookies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RICOTTA-CHEESE COOKIES &QL; 
(Shared by Sandra Smith, Sylmar) &QL; 
2 cups granulated sugar &QL; 
1 cup margarine OR butter (2 sticks), softened &QL; 
1 container (15 ounces) ricotta cheese &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
2 large eggs &QL; 
4 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
2 tablespoons baking powder &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1 1/2 cups powdered sugar &QL; 
3 tablespoons milk &QL; 
Red OR green sugar crystals
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, with mixer at low speed, beat granulated sugar
and margarine until blended. Increase speed to high; beat until
light and fluffy, about 5 minutes. At medium speed, beat in ricotta
cheese, vanilla and eggs until well combined.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce speed to low. Add flour, baking powder and salt. Beat
until dough forms.
</P>
<P>
   Drop by level tablespoons about 2 inches apart on ungreased
cookie sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven about 15 minutes or until
cookies are very lightly golden (cookies will be soft). Remove
cookies to wire rack to cool.
</P>
<P>
   When cookies are cool, prepare icing. In a small bowl, stir
powdered sugar and milk until smooth. With small metal spatula or
knife, spread icing on cool cookies. Sprinkle with red or green
sugars. Allow icing to dry completely, about 1 hour. Makes about 6
dozen cookies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Can you help &QL; 
If you have recipes that can help these readers, please send them
along to us at the address below to share in a future column. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
I would appreciate an easy Caesar Salad dressing recipe without
eggs. I make all my salad dressing, since I have not found any
bottled dressings to my liking. &QL; 
Rose Cooper, Woodland Hills &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
I would like a recipe similar to the Hearty Autumn Harvest Soup
served at the Fresh Choice restaurant. It is thick and creamy and
includes butternut squash.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Schroeder, Canoga Park &QL; 
______
</P>
<P>
   Cook's Corner welcomes recipe requests from readers. While we
cannot reply to them individually, we will answer those of general
interest in this column. Also, if you can help another reader with
a recipe request, write to Cook's Corner, Daily News Food
Department, P.O. Box 4200, Woodland Hills, Calif. 91365-4200.
Please be sure recipes specify exact package sizes, can and pan
sizes and baking times and temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes printed are from the source indicated and have not been
tested by the Daily News Food Department unless noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
