<HEADLINE>
TIMELY STORIES FOR CLINTON'S VISIT TO INDIA...(3-22)  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (These excellent ``separate-buy'' articles are distributed by the
New York Times Syndicate.)  
  
 (To publish these TIMELY articles, they must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; INDIA ISN'T PAKISTAN'S SIAMESE TWIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESPECT-INDIA-OPED-IHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ India resents being treated by U.S. policy as a
Siamese twin of Pakistan. It also frets at the respect accorded to
China, to the extent that Washington has let Beijing off the hook
on its nuclear and missile transfers to Pakistan. India would like
Washington to be on the side of the world's largest democracy, not
on the side of the world's largest autocracy....By Brahma Chellaney
for the International Herald Tribune &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Wed., March 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON STEPS INTO THE KASHMIR QUAGMIRE HE HELPED CREATE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; US-TREASON-KASHMIR-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DELHI _ Forty Sikh villagers have died to burn the message home
to visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton that the Kashmir problem
won't go away. Meanwhile, Pakistan's former leader, Nawaz Sharif,
sits in a Karachi jail string into the hangman's noose as a result
of repeatedly doing what America told him to do. And this week his
friend Bill Clinton arrives to bestow his blessing (that is how it
will play in Pakistan) on the man responsible....By Peter Popham,
The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tuesday, March 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 925 words; 1,275 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEN-ARMED CLINTON MAKES UP FOR 20 YEARS OF NEGLECT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MR.FIXIT-CLINTON-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Bill Clinton arrived in New Delhi Monday
to start a tour of the Indian subcontinent, presented in Washington
as the opening of a new chapter of diplomacy and trade. Seen in the
context of Washington's overture to Iran at the end of last week,
the president's week-long trip appears not just as an attempt to
address years of neglect, but as part of a much wider shift in U.S.
policy for the whole region _ from the bipolar to the multipolar
post-Cold War world....By Mary Dejevsky, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Monday, March 20) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAKISTAN: THE WORLD'S MOST DANGEROUS PLACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCARY-PAKISTAN-ECONOMIST-925&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It takes a brave man, or a foolish one, to step
between mortal enemies spoiling for a fight. Bill Clinton may be
the leader of the world's most powerful country but, if he puts a
foot wrong during his tour of India this week and his brief
touchdown in Pakistan, he could exacerbate the tensions that last
year brought these two nuclear sibling states to blows over
Kashmir....By The Economist &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in The Economist's March 18 issue) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 100-word optional trim at 925; 1,050 words uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON'S VISIT CAN MAKE A DIFFERENCE, HOWEVER SMALL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFEREE-CLINTON-OPED-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Bill Clinton's tour of South Asia that got under way
Monday marks the first visit by a U.S. president to India and
Pakistan in more than 20 and 30 years respectively. In that sense
alone, the trip is historic. In addition, however, this represents
an important moment where a powerful outsider can play a role in
nudging the two nuclear weapon-wielding countries towards a kind of
sanity....By The Editorial Board of The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORIAL) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Monday, March 20) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BANGALORE OR HYDERABAD: TWO HIGH-TECH CITIES VIE FOR CLINTON
VISIT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CYBER-INDIA-CLINTON-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DELHI _ Which is it to be, Mr. Clinton? The American president
arrived in India on March 20, the first such visit for 22 years,
and the subcontinent's two most strenuously forward-looking cities,
Bangalore and Hyderabad, are competing furiously for his attention.
Both are vying to become the most important center of India's
booming software industry....By Peter Popham, The Independent of
London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tuesday, March 14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDIA'S HIGH-TECH BOOM IS GREAT SUCCESS STORY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INDIA-HITECH-BOOM-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Indian high-tech boom is one of the great
under-publicized stories of the world economy. For many years the
Indian subcontinent has produced talented computer people who have
headed off to the developed world to make their fortunes. Silicon
Valley in California is attracting upwards of 50,000 of them a
year. And last year, Indian software exports were nearly $3 billion
_ ten times the level of four years earlier....By Hamish McRae, The
Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Feb. 23, 2000) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (475 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
