<P>
   &UR; CLINTON STEPS INTO THE KASHMIR QUAGMIRE HE HELPED CREATE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; US-TREASON-KASHMIR-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DELHI _ Forty Sikh villagers have died to burn the message home
to visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton that the Kashmir problem
won't go away. Meanwhile, Pakistan's former leader, Nawaz Sharif,
sits in a Karachi jail staring into the hangman's noose as a result
of repeatedly doing what America told him to do. And this week his
friend Bill Clinton arrives to bestow his blessing (that is how it
will play in Pakistan) on the man responsible....By Peter Popham,
The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tuesday, March 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 925 words; 1,275 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. CENSUS ATTACKED OVER RACE QUESTIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CENSUS-RACISM-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Within 24 hours of the first deliveries of Census
2000 forms to American mailboxes last week, Census Bureau officials
received more than 600,000 calls. The vast majority of them were
complaints about the probing nature of the questions on race....By
Mary Dejevsky, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tuesday, March 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S `VLADIMIR THE CLEANSER' IN IVAN THE TERRIBLE'S TOWN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN-IVAN-TERRIBLE-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KOLOMNA _ Workers at Vladimir Putin's campaign headquarters in
Kolomna are so confident of success in the Russian presidential
election Sunday that they do not even have a picture of their
candidate on the wall. In Kolomna _ once Ivan The Terrible's
favorite town _ Putin is seen as the man who will clean up the mess
left by President Boris Yeltsin. Although how exactly he will do
that is, like the man himself, a mystery....By Patrick Cockburn,
The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...TIMELY for Sunday's election,
Russia) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tuesday, March 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `E-WASTE': TOXIC COMPUTER PARTS POSE POLLUTION NIGHTMARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOXIC-COMPUTERS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Millions of redundant computers and their highly
toxic components are storing up a huge hidden environmental problem
in Britain and America. If action is not taken soon, campaigners
say, the countries will have billions of pounds of hazardous
contaminants in their soils. The full scale of the potential
pollution nightmare can be judged by the U.S. experience....By Paul
Lashmar, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Tuesday, March 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN OPPONENTS COMPETE ON `WHO WANTS TO BE A MILLIONAIRE?' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KREMLIN-REGIS-GAMESHOW-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If you think America has a bizarre way of electing its
presidents, check out Russia. Desperate for attention in an
election campaign dominated by Kremlin heir-apparent Vladimir
Putin, four of the other 11 candidates took part Saturday night in
the Russian version of the hit TV program, ``Who Wants To Be A
Millionaire?''...By Phil Reeves, The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for Sunday's Russian election, March 26) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 700 words; 975 uncut) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
