<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-WAVING-MAN-HNS &LR;      03-23 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAVING-MAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LONGTIME FRIENDS SALUTE THE `WAVING MAN' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Calif., La.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Joseph Charles has waved his way onto the
national news, into the hearts of thousands and into his 10th
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he says, he's outlived two of his physicians,'' said John
W. Taylor, one of some 50 admirers who gathered at an Oakland
restaurant Wednesday night to celebrate the 90th birthday of
Berkeley's famous Waving Man.
</P>
<P>
   It has been eight years since Charles retired from his
celebrated hobby of waving to passing cars at the corner of Oregon
Street and Martin Luther King Jr. Way.
</P>
<P>
   Each weekday morning for 30 years, Charles greeted every
passerby with his waving hand _ a tradition that began in 1962 with
a daily exchange of waves between him and a neighbor. In the
mid-1960s, an admiring motorist presented Charles with a pair of
yellow gloves, which made his waves easier to spot from the fast
lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``People laughed at me, said I was crazy for doing it,'' Charles
said when poor health forced him to hang up his gloves in 1992.
``Some people called me communist. Neighborhood high school kids
would pass by, go home and tell their parents, `Mr. Charles must be
going crazy,' but it just stuck, and I enjoyed it so.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles later moved inside and started to wave from his front
window. People still noticed, and honked in appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Charles, who was born in Louisiana, was elevated in popular myth
to the pantheon of Great Berkeley Characters. He has been the grand
marshal of two parades. His yellow gloves have been enshrined in
the Berkeley History Center.
</P>
<P>
   And Charles' contribution to the mental stability of his
community, not to mention the hundreds of thousands of motorists
who happily waved back over three decades, is well-remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bush, now a young adult, recalls the Waving Man as a
neighborhood institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember growing up and leaving to go to school, and he
would stand on the corner, rain or shine, and wave to the cars
going by,'' he said. Bush added that local kids took delight in
imitating Charles' admonition to all who passed by: ``Have a GOOD
day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We respected him,'' Bush said. ``He showed us that no matter
what, you could be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's mother, Cleopatra Bush, said Charles continued giving to
those who knew him. ``Even after he stopped waving, he was always
working in his yard, and he would stop and give me a hug,'' she
said. ``He would always call on my birthday, and he would always
send me a card.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolie Conger, an Alameda County Superior Court judge, got to
know Charles after exchanging waves with him on her drive to work.
They, too, share birthday traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there at 6 a.m. tying balloons to his porch railing,''
she said Wednesday. ``And he makes me gumbo for my birthday every
year. He cooks wonderfully.''
</P>
<P>
   As his birthday guests spoke, Charles worked the tables at
Kinkaid's restaurant in Oakland's Jack London Square. Wearing a
black suit and walking with a cane, he shook hands, kissed the
women and told each person to ``Enjoy yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love them all, my friends,'' he said after returning to his
table and his glass of Jack Daniels. Charles said growing older
didn't daunt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know nothing about that, because I feel good,'' he
said. ``The Good Lord lets me feel good every day, loving everybody
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Then his eyes landed on a female friend who had just arrived.
``Come here, sweetheart,'' he said. ``Gimme sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles also traded kisses with Mable Cotter, who leaned forward
from her wheelchair as her husband, Ralph Cotter, looked on with a
smile. The Cotters and Charles became friends during Charles'
career at the Oakland Naval Supply Center, where he worked from
1942 to 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep smiling,'' he told Mable Cotter. ``Call me every day,
now. I'll be looking for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles' oldest friend at the party was Jessie Esprit, who will
turn 90 next week. She attended 12 years of public school with
Charles in their hometown of Lake Charles, La.
</P>
<P>
   Esprit remembered Charles as a ``very, very beautiful'' young
man who was devoted to his high school sweetheart, Flora Shade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had one girlfriend, and he never left that girlfriend,''
Esprit said. ``She was a pretty girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles married her after graduation. She died in 1982, having
seen her husband praised on the CBS evening news by the late
Charles Kuralt.
</P>
<P>
   Esprit said other women were attracted to the young Charles
``because he was a baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles was widely lauded for his skill at first base during his
years with the Lake Charles Black Yankees, a Negro League team.
Charles said he was once struck out by the great Satchel Paige.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1450EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
