<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5896 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR &LR;      03-23 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROADBLOCK FOR MISTER
 STRAIGHT TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - You're John McCain and you can no longer talk
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you want to remain a Republican. Not if you still want to
be president of the United States. And you do.
</P>
<P>
   During your long campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination, it was your plain-spoken, unvar nished, often brazen,
occasionally insolent talk that got you the most attention and the
most respect.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you must keep your mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   Or worse, you must play an elabo rate game of make-believe by
faking genuine support for George W. Bush, the man who defeated
you.
</P>
<P>
   You don't like Bush. It was clear to everyone who watched you
during the campaign. You haven't changed your mind.
</P>
<P>
   You dislike Al Gore even more, of course. But if Bush becomes
presi dent, he'll have the Republican nomination locked up again
four years from now and you won't get another shot at the big
prize.
</P>
<P>
   You need Bush to lose.
</P>
<P>
   You're in the same position Ronald Reagan was in when he lost
the nomination to Gerald Ford. If Ford had managed to defeat Jimmy
Carter in 1976, Reagan's running mate, Nelson Rockefeller, would
have had the inside track on the nomination in 1980, and Reagan may
not have gotten an other shot at the big prize.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan needed Ford to lose.
</P>
<P>
   He pretended to support Ford but really didn't. And Ford lost.
The rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bush needs your support and you're going to give it to him,
Reagan-style.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, you told CBS' Dan Rather that you'll support Bush
but, ``Exactly how that happens and under what circumstances and my
degree of enthusiasm obviously are questions that are yet to be re
solved.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Straight Talk Express stops here.
</P>
<P>
   It came to a grinding halt earlier this month in Sedona when you
pulled out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Your speech was a first-rate demon stration in exactly how to
damn with faint praise.
</P>
<P>
   You stood under a beautiful blue sky with the majestic Red Rocks
behind you, dusted with snow, and said, ``I congratulate Governor
Bush and wish him and his family well. He very well may become the
next president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   You didn't say he should become the next president, or that he
must become the next president. And you certainly didn't say you
were going to do everything in your power to make sure Bush became
the next president.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, John McCain, the maverick presidential
candidate and Vietnam War hero, the man who models himself after
Teddy Roose velt _ often using the big stick of his convictions to
pummel politicians and journalists _ decided to talk softly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of saying exactly what you feel about the
soon-to-be-crowned Republican nominee, you chose to beat around the
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves the best wishes of every American,'' you said of
your former opponent. ``He certainly has mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Best wishes?
</P>
<P>
   That's what you offer via greeting card to the third-cousin
you've never met after she sends you the an nouncement of her
impending nup tials.
</P>
<P>
   You have other options.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to run for president as an independent candidate,
you could go back to talking straight. You could be even more
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't. That would leave you without the backing of a
major political party and, in the end, you'd lose. You want to win.
You still want to become president.
</P>
<P>
   You're John McCain and you can no longer talk straight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1452EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
