<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, March 24.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-ASIAN-ART (New York) _ Asian art in Manhattan is not what it
was a few years ago, an exotic subspecies confined to the remoter
quarters of museums. At some point in the 1990s, it broke through
the silence barrier and assumed a position of prominence from which
it is not likely to retreat. And it says much for the health of the
local scene that many young Asian artists have settled in New York.
On the International Asian Art Fair, opening Friday, and events
exhibitions, galleries and artists devoted to Asian art. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY-BIENNIAL (New York) _ The 2000 Biennial at the Whitney
Museum of American Art is truer than previous biennials to what
goes on across the country, truer to the character of the American
scene, where artists come from other countries, more respectful of
different generations and multiple strategies. But it is flat,
which may partly be chalked up to the quality of art at this
moment. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT4,5,6.
</P>
<P>
   AIDA-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Pretty much everything that's
right about ``Aida,'' the new Disney cartoon pretending to be a
Broadway musical, can be summed up in two words: Heather Headley.
Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT10,11.
</P>
<P>
   NY-THEATER-MURAL (New York) _ A long-forgotten actor, the toast
of 1900s Broadway and a star of silent films, will soon retake his
rightful place in the Times Square theater that bore his name for
decades. And, fittingly, he'll be doing it in drag. Julian Eltinge,
a once-famous female impersonator is thought to be depicted on a
mural that was lost for 60 years under layers of paint and that
will be unveiled later this month. By John Holusha.
</P>
