<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Court burdens GOP with tobacco issue
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conservative majority of the U.S. Supreme Court did
congressional Republicans no favor when it held that the federal
Food and Drug Administration lacks the authority to regulate
tobacco as a drug.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is congenial to GOP policy inclinations and is
legally defensible against an also strong argument pressed by the
court dissenters. It is not clear that Congress hasn't kept tobacco
regulation within its own purview, as the five-justice majority
ruled. With the record muddled, it is arguably best to default to
congressional authority.
</P>
<P>
   But even the court majority conceded _ indeed, emphasized _ that
tobacco use is the nation's No. 1 public health issue, especially
the industry's addiction of the young as a future victim clientele.
</P>
<P>
   It was the prevention of youth smoking that FDA was trying to
address, and the court, though disallowing that, all but invited
Congress either to license the agency to take it up or to undertake
the matter itself with legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was certainly not the justices' intention to do so,
the ruling hands Democrats another big-stick issue with which to
pound Republicans in this especially crucial election year.
</P>
<P>
   The public health interest here is clear and overwhelming. Even
the industry itself now concedes tobacco is addictive and that its
use sickens and often kills. Tobacco is the leading cause of
preventable diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But what ought to be a bipartisan, in fact a universal interest
in public health is not. As Democrats have become willing in recent
years to regulate tobacco, the GOP has let itself become a virtual
subsidiary of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   From 1991 through last year, the leading tobacco companies
contributed $14.3 million to the Republican Party and its election
committees, just $3 million to the Democratic Party and its
election committees.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, tobacco companies and their political action
committees gave $2.2 million to GOP organizations and candidates,
$564,000 to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco-regulation legislation Democrats are now certain to
push adds to the GOP's already considerable issue woes.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are fighting popular gun-control legislation in
tandem with an increasingly shrill gun lobby, another big
contributor. To broad concerns about education, Republicans can
tender, since they believe there is no legitimate national role,
only the constitutionally dubious and otherwise doubtful panacea of
vouchers. And they are again drumming huge tax cuts of the sort
that flopped in Congress last year to vast public indifference.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of their own John McCain's near thing lost of them,
Republicans have even let Al Gore, although himself a political
misdemeanant on such matters, swipe the campaign-reform issue.
</P>
<P>
   Issue debilities don't necessarily translate into candidate
losses; personalities and personal records count. But GOP
candidates are starting the presidential and congressional races
with some pretty heavy luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
