<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTILOCK BRAKES WORK _ WHEN USED PROPERLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (l and f coding)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It can be both fascinating and perplexing to watch new
automotive technology make its way to the market. It seems
inevitable that promise will, for at least a time, get snagged on
the horns of ignorance and distrust.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen it with the automatic transmission, brighter
headlights, seat belts (Remember the bizarre argument that seat
belts were not safe because they might trap you in your car after a
wreck?) and air bags.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ABS _ anti-lock brake systems. I've had experienced
drivers tell me they don't trust them, don't understand them, don't
want them. I've talked to young drivers who learned nothing in
driver's education about how to use them safely.
</P>
<P>
   What is called for is an unlearning of old ways (pump the
brakes) by the experienced driving generation and a concentrated,
mandatory education in their use in driver training programs for
the young gneration.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing for a combination of these is the ABS Education
Alliance, a nonprofit coalition of companies that manufacture
anti-lock brake systems.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-lock brakes are not a new invention. They were used in
Germany in the 1930s to stop trains; used in World War II to stop
airplanes on carrier decks; Plymouth offered a model with ABS in
the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Their first major inroads in the United States came in the
mid-1980s in high-end autos, according to Rosemarie Kitchin of the
education alliance. Four years ago, ABS systems crept into less
expensive models, and last year they were installed in about
two-thirds of all cars built.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Kitchner said, too often the salespeople at dealerships do
not instruct car buyers in their use, and an education alliance
survey found that two-thirds of drivers between 18-24 had not been
taught how to use ABS in driver education.
</P>
<P>
   And all of this is unfortunate because ABS is a great safety
feature that, once understood, is comfortable to live with and easy
to use.
</P>
<P>
   Some basics:
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that in an emergency, you had to pump your brakes
while trying to slow down. It was up to the driver to sense wheel
lock-up and back off the brakes before the car turned into a
hurtling sled that could not be steered. Even a single wheel
locking up meant that the braking capabilities of all four wheels
had to be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ABS is designed to do that ``sensing'' for you and to help you
not only stop your vehicle in an emergency situation, but to let
you steer even with the brakes jammed on.
</P>
<P>
   When you stomp the brakes in a four-wheel ABS vehicle, a central
control unit monitors electronic pulses from sensors at each wheel.
If a sensor tells the control unit that a wheel is about to lock
up, a computer signals a valve to limit hydraulic pressure to the
brake at that wheel. This allows the wheel to rotate, even if for a
brief moment, and thus avoids lock-up. Meanwhile, the other brakes
can remain fully engaged, though it is likely that they, too, will
be gripped and ungripped at various times as each approachs
lock-up.
</P>
<P>
   So young or old or somewhere in between, if you don't know about
ABS and how to use the system, get yourself educated.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't own an ABS car now, you likely will in the future,
and you should, because they are a good thing. If you rent a car,
Kitchin said, chances are 9 in 10 you'll get one with ABS.
</P>
<P>
   Know your own car, of course, but always check for ABS in cars
you rent or borrow. If you own one car with ABS and one without,
think about braking before you drive either.
</P>
<P>
   Learn that the pulsing of the pedal and the chattering sounds
you hear when ABS brakes are applied with force is normal. It's the
grip and ungrip function at work.
</P>
<P>
   If you hear that chatter and feel that pulse each time you slow
when driving, you are probably driving too fast in bad conditions.
</P>
<P>
   If you are taking driver training, insist that your teacher
instruct you in using ABS. If you already have a license, take a
course, or take Kitchner's advice: Go to church. On a Tuesday. When
the parking lot is deserted. Set up some cardboard boxes and use
your brakes as you try to avoid hitting them.
</P>
<P>
   You can also try them out on a deserted road that has snow,
gravel or ice on it or is slippery with rain. Learn to put the
brakes on and keep them on. Put the brakes on before you attempt to
steer around any obstacles (particularly important in SUVs). Learn
to steer with the brakes on.
</P>
<P>
   A warning: If you have a car with only rear-wheel ABS, the rules
are different. These are found mostly in light trucks, vans, and
SUVs. In these vehicles, you can still lock up the front wheels and
lose the ability to steer. When you feel lock-up, let off the
brakes and let the front wheels start rolling again so you can
steer.
</P>
<P>
   If you have ABS and have mastered its uses, don't get stupid and
think the system makes you invulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ABS will not eliminate the possibility of skidding. ABS will not
stop your vehicle in a shorter distance, and, in fact, in some
instances will increase that distance slightly (though the tradeoff
for control is well worth this slight boost in stopping distance).
</P>
<P>
   For new drivers, ABS education should be mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   For older drivers, reluctant to embrace new technology, Kitchin
has other advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you say is that if they know how to use it and can avoid
a squirrel, a dog, a ball, somebody chasing a ball _ if they can
avoid one obstacle, they'll avoid a crash, an injury, they might
save a life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford covers automotive issues for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
