<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND JAPAN FAIL TO AGREE ON TELECOMMUNICATIONS DEREGULATION
PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Talks between the United States and Japan over
deregulation of the telecommunications market ended here in failure
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although negotiators had extended their discussions for one day,
they failed to reach an agreement on the magnitude and speed of
reductions in the fees that Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
charges for access to its local network, to which 99 percent of the
phones in Japan are connected.
</P>
<P>
   Further deregulation of the telecommunications market here is
fast becoming the most contentious trade debate between the United
States and Japan since negotiators struggled over opening the
Japanese automobile market in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The United States contends that Japan's refusal to move more
swiftly to allow unfettered competition here imperils the future of
the Japanese economy. ``This is not the U.S. against Japan,'' said
Richard Fisher, deputy U.S. trade representative, at a press
briefing. ``This is Japan against the future.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Japan's resistance to further deregulating
telecommunications forced Japanese consumers and businesses to pay
high prices for telephone services and Internet access. He
contrasted the rate his daughter pays to use the Internet in the
United States _ less than $9 a month or about 900 yen _ with the
7,830 a month that one of her Japanese friends pays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should a Japanese girl be at such a disadvantage to an
American girl?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been seeking an immediate 41 percent
reduction in the fees, which eat up as much as 40 percent of the
revenue of NTT's competitors. Japan has offered to reduce rates by
22.5 percent over four years.
</P>
<P>
   Japan says that the United States' demands threaten 70,000 jobs
at NTT, the former government telephone monopoly in which the
government retains a 59.1 percent stake. Japan also argues that
sharply lowering interconnection fees would reduce service in
unprofitable areas.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher countered by saying that while it was a government's
responsibility to worry about social issues like layoffs, opening
the market to competition would create more jobs. He noted that in
the United States in the last four years, 90,000 new jobs have been
created in the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who governs Japan?'' he asked. ``The elected people, the Diet,
the government or a monopoly?'' The Diet is Japan's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is worried that the United States will take the matter to
the World Trade Organization before the heads of the leading
industrialized nations meet in Okinawa in July. Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi considers the success of that meeting to be critical
to the success of the ruling party in parliamentary elections that
must be held by mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher played to those concerns. ``The road to Geneva begins in
Tokyo,'' he said, referring to the headquarters of the WTO. ``We'll
see what actions might be taken and we reserve all options.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1521EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
