<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-POLITICS-430     03-23 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-POLITICS-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN'S MILITARY RULER SCHEDULES LOCAL ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ With President Clinton due to visit Pakistan
on Saturday, the country's military ruler on Thursday announced a
first step toward the gradual return of democracy _local elections
that are to begin in December.
</P>
<P>
   But full restoration of a civilian government is likely to be a
long way off.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Islamabad, Gen. Pervez Musharraf, who
seized power in a coup last October, said voting for a new
three-tier system of local councils would continue through July
2001. He offered no schedule for elections after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``From here we will move forward, step by step, to provincial
and national levels, in due course of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, like many other countries, has been pushing
Musharraf for a timetable to bring Pakistan, a nation of 150
million people, back to democracy. But the general dismissed any
notion that he was responding to foreign pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am doing everything in the national interest,'' he said. ``I
don't need approval from anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did not get approval, at least not from the White House.
``It is a positive step, but what we are looking for is a road map
to national elections and a restoration of democratic rule in
Pakistan,'' said the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Since overthrowing Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on Oct. 12,
Musharraf has vowed to set in place a ``real democracy,'' replacing
what he called a ``sham democracy'' that he said was dedicated more
to corruption than to good government.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, as in the past, the general sounded much like a
dedicated populist, proposing a vast system of village and district
councils and a guaranteed number of seats for women, minorities and
the poor, whom he referred to as ``workers and peasants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to empower the impoverished, the people at the
grass-roots level,'' he said, adding that the voting age would be
lowered from 21 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   These professed democratic impulses are in contrast to some of
Musharraf's recent actions. In January, he required all higher
court judges to take a loyalty oath that would bar them from
challenging army decisions. And last week he banned all political
meetings at public places, as well as strikes and processions.
</P>
<P>
   Since gaining independence in 1947, Pakistan has been a pinwheel
of alternating civilian and military governments. Musharraf's coup
came after 10 years of democracy, which in turn came after 11 years
of army control.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In past months, the general has sloughed aside demands for
elections, saying there were more important tasks at hand, like
forestalling national bankruptcy and collecting unpaid bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday one of Pakistan's English-language newspapers, Dawn,
reported that the government had so far recovered $291 million in
non-performing loans, a sizable sum but still only 10 percent of
the total amount in default.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf said that past elections had been corrupted by money
and that new voter rolls needed to be compiled and identity cards
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   The elections ``have been manipulated and distorted,'' he said.
``No one has any faith in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has been in South Asia since Sunday night, is
scheduled to arrive in Pakistan on Saturday morning and stay about
five hours.
</P>
<P>
   A specific time frame for a complete return to democracy is
still likely to be high on the president's agenda, as will the
subject of Islamic militants who train in Pakistan and operate in
Indian-controlled Kashmir.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
