<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5963 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EMERGENCY-CARE-HNS &LR;      03-23 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMERGENCY-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STATE WEIGHS RESPONSE TO EMERGENCY CARE PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California lawmakers are struggling with ways to
address the shrinking number of emergency rooms in the state,
chronic overcrowding and specialists who are refusing to be on call
for complex cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unmitigated disaster,'' said state Sen. Jackie Speier,
D-Daly City, who co-chaired a Senate hearing Wednesday on emergency
medicine. ``California has lost 19 emergency rooms since 1997,
while the number of visits have increased from 8.8 million to 10
million this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors testified about lines of people on gurneys in crowded
hallways, near-death experiences for patients and the refusal of
insurers to pay a reasonable amount for services, if they pay at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Their complaints reflected what has been happening around the
state. Physicians and their practice groups have gone bankrupt,
teaching hospitals are buried in debt, and more emergency rooms are
turning away ambulances because of overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers expressed concern, but the intricacies of the
market and unpalatable decisions involving paying for and rationing
health care have left many shaking their heads in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a road map, it's so complex,'' said state Sen. John
Vasconcellos, D-Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency wards have been especially hard hit because the system
leaves them without any leverage in the marketplace, said Dan
Abbott, medical director of the emergency department at St. Jude
Hospital in Fullerton. They are required to see everyone who walks
in, including the estimated 22 percent who have no insurance, but
no one is willing to pay the tab, Abbott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a federal mandate for care, but there is no federal
mandate for payment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Abbott said, California's insurance plan for
the poor pays the lowest amount per beneficiary of any of the 50
states.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, private managed care companies are paying as little
as 20 or 30 percent of the cost of services, Abbott said. The
California chapter of the American College of Emergency Room
Physicians cited the case of a young woman with a Tylenol overdose
whose insurance would only reimburse the doctor $20.90.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of token payments: $20.90 to treat a 10-month-old
with a seizure; $16.77 to treat a 38-year-old with a kidney stone;
and $70 to treat an 84-year-old man with a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the emergency room for a Los Angeles inner-city
hospital dropped a 6-inch stack of computer printouts on the
witness table that represented all the claims they had sent to
insurers that remained unpaid after six months. Some had been
submitted five and six times over two years.
</P>
<P>
   William Wehrle of the California Association of Health Plans
said many bills are sent to the wrong address or have errors in
them. He said it is normal for insurers to take more time to review
claims submitted for emergencies because there is typically no
prior authorization for services and no existing contract with the
treating physician.
</P>
<P>
   Wehrle sympathized with the emergency physicians, but said
health plans are being squeezed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is volunteering to pay higher health insurance
premiums,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One consequence of low physician payments is a growing rebellion
among specialists needed to treat complex emergency cases. They are
taking themselves off on-call lists.
</P>
<P>
   Some hospitals have been forced to pay specialists like
neurosurgeons as much as $500 per day to be on call, said Anthony
Armada, senior vice president of Northridge Hospital Medical Center
in Northridge. Furthermore, he said, the hospitals are having to
guarantee the doctors a minimum amount for their services if the
patient is indigent or doesn't pay.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, it is not always possible to convince specialists to
be listed for on-call work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, where the University of California at San
Francisco/Mount Zion Medical Center closed its emergency room in
November, the remaining hospitals are increasingly turning away
ambulance traffic because they are overwhelmed. When three or more
hospitals go on diversion, patients in need of emergency care are
taken to the nearest hospital, which must accept them, no matter
how crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a slow-motion disaster,'' said John Brown, director of
emergency services for the San Francisco Health Department. ``When
we have our next big problem, an earthquake or flu epidemic, we
will be having preventable deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   Speier said the state needs to step in and insist that a minimum
number of emergency beds are available in each community.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, has included an extra $25 million
in the latest budget to pay emergency room physicians who care for
indigent patients. A bill sponsored by state Sen. Don Perata,
D-Oakland, would penalize insurers that fail to pay on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's got to pay it's fair share, and the HMOs have to
pay for services rendered, and the consumers are going to have to
be willing to pay for quality care,'' Speier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
