<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHATEVER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHATEVER IT TAKES': A THINLY VEILED `CYRANO' WITH THE PROM IN
MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever taken high school French, chances are you know
the plot of ``Whatever It Takes,'' which is basically ``Cyrano de
Bergerac'' updated to the age of e-mail and two-line phones. Not
that anyone has a long, misshapen nose. Please! One character does
have an embarrassing rash on her feet, and (though we never
actually see it) hair on her back, but this information is supplied
as deserved comeuppance to a teen-age princess who thinks she's, as
it were, all that. Most everyone looks fresh-faced and appealing,
sexy but not too sexual, just like they did in high school.
Remember?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you've made it past junior high, you aren't part
of this movie's target audience in the first place. ``Whatever It
Takes,'' directed by David Raynr from a script by Mark Schwahn, is
yet another teen-ager-oriented romantic comedy showcasing the looks
and talent (mostly the former) of young television stars. It's also
the latest evidence that, when it comes to realistic, emotionally
complex renderings of adolescent life, shows like ``Freaks and
Geeks,'' even the second-rate ``Get Real,'' to say nothing of ads
for Mentos and Mountain Dew are far ahead of most theatrically
released feature films aimed at the same market.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan (Shane West) is a nerdy accordion player whose best pal is
his sensitive, Salinger-reading next door neighbor Maggie (Marla
Sokoloff). Blind to his true feelings, he pines after Ashley (Jodi
Lyn O'Keefe), the most popular girl in school, whom the camera
follows around like a lecherous assistant principal. So far, this
could be a summary of ``Snow Day.'' But to complicate matters,
Maggie is pined after by Chris (James Franco), a hunky,
narcissistic jock. With three weeks to go before the prom, Chris
and Ryan, boldly transgressing the line between the social elect
and the socially invisible, enter into a pact. Each will help the
other win his dream girl. But their plans go comically awry when
...
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. If you don't know in the first five minutes who will
end up with whom, not even summer school can help you. The
predictable plot is not itself a crime: you can guess the endings
of ``As You Like it,'' ``His Girl Friday,'' and ``Pretty in Pink''
fairly easily too. But the script's way of handling its romantic
complications is unusually obtuse and insensitive.
</P>
<P>
   As he wakes up to his true feelings for Maggie, Ryan loses his
sweetness and vulnerability and becomes as much of a creep as
Chris. This might be interesting were it within the scope of the
film' s intentions, but his sustained, gratuitous humiliation of
Ashley played entirely for laughs strikes an ugly, misogynist note.
Like Chris and Ryan, Raynr and Schwahn exploit Ashley and O'Keefe
for her sex appeal and then proceed to trash her.
</P>
<P>
   What will make ``Whatever It Takes'' watchable when it shows up
some Saturday night six months from now on cable are jokes and
situations that have nothing to do with the main characters. Aaron
Paul as Ryan's dorky loser friend provides a welcome burst of
loose, anarchic energy, and Richard Schiff has a lunatic turn as a
coach with control problems.
</P>
<P>
   There is an amusing takeoff on Tom Cruise's Bob Seger-in-briefs
lip sync from ``Risky Business,'' this time featuring an accordion,
boxer shorts, a cowboy hat and ``Play That Funky Music, White
Boy.'' There is also a crowd-pleasing safe-sex demonstration,
conducted by Ryan's mother, the school nurse (Julia Sweeney).
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the much anticipated prom is ``Titanic Dreams,''
and it inspires a slapstick finale that nearly rescues the movie
from the watery grave of its perfunctory and meretricious happy
ending.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Whatever It Takes is rated PG-13. It contains some
sexually suggestive situations and language, and brazen mockery of
one of the top-grossing films of all time.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WHATEVER IT TAKES'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Raynr; written by Mark Schwahn; director of
photography, Tim Suhrstedt; edited by Ronald Roose; music by Edward
Shearmur; production designer, Edward T. McAvoy; produced by Paul
Schiff; released by Columbia Pictures. Running time: 92 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Shane West (Ryan), Marla Sokoloff (Maggie), Jodi Lyn
O'Keefe (Ashle), James Franco (Chris), Aaron Paul (Floyd), Richard
Schiff (Physical Education Teacher), Julia Sweeney (Kate Woodman),
Colin Hanks (Cosmo) and Kip Pardue (Harris).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
