u e BC-WANNA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     03-23 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANNA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALL I WANNA DO': WITH SUGAR AND SPICE AND RAVIOLI EATEN COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title of ``All I Wanna Do'' tells you nothing at all about
the movie except, by inference, that it's for and about teen-agers.
Like ``She's All That,'' ``Down to You'' and ``Whatever It Takes,''
this innocuous, intermittently charming coming-of-age comedy has
been given a name that refers to nothing at all, evokes no
particular associations and is likely to be forgotten shortly after
you leave the theater.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, the title _ the third, after the more
evocative but less marketable ``Strike'' and ``The Hairy Bird''
were scrapped _ seems especially inapt. ``All I Wanna Do,'' which
opens Friday in Manhattan, takes place in 1963 at Godard's, a
proper New England boarding school for girls. In this milieu, if
the script is to be trusted, young ladies expressed themselves
crisply and grammatically, with occasional malapropisms and
redundancies (``I loathe and abhor it'') thrown in for effect.
</P>
<P>
   Conducting this symphony of high diction is Lynn Redgrave as the
school's embattled headmistress, whose grimacing upper-crustiness
seems to have been learned from studying the accents of the
millionaire and his wife on ``Gilligan's Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Godard's is the kind of place where Odette Sinclair (Gaby
Hoffmann), newly arrived from Detroit with her horse in tow, soon
earns a reputation among her peers for daring verbal wit because
she says things like (I'm not kidding) ``up your ziggy with a
wah-wah brush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I Wanna Do,'' the first feature directed by Sarah
Kernochan, a screenwriter who has worked on such diverse projects
as ``9{ Weeks'' and ``Sommersby,'' mixes such prim old-fashioned
naughtiness with more consequential misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   Odette, a smart, politically astute young woman, soon joins a
proto-feminist consciousness-raising group called the DAR
(Daughters of American Ravioli, in honor of the young women's
favored snack, which they consume cold, straight from the can.)
</P>
<P>
   The daughters are the usual melange of teen-age girl types: the
slut (Monica Keena), the angry rich girl (Kirsten Dunst), the
bulimic (Heather Matarazzo) and so on. They dream of becoming
magazine editors and scientists, but Odette, who has the talent to
become, in the words of one of her chums, ``a speechwriter or a
demagogue,'' aspires to be an ``ex-virgin'' instead and enlists her
pals in a conspiracy to arrange a clandestine tryst with her
boyfriend, Dennis (Matthew Lawrence).
</P>
<P>
   The '60s arrive just in time. Godard's is about to merge with a
boys' school called St. Ambrose, and a faction of the DAR mounts an
ingenious (if slightly incredible) plot to preserve the school's
identity. The film's politics seem a bit anachronistic, projecting
a 1990s feminist critique of co-education onto a time in which
ambitious young women were more likely to be agitating for
admission to institutions reserved for men.
</P>
<P>
   But in any case ``All I Wanna Do'' is more fable than history.
How else does one explain the presence of a gang of skinny, artsy
townies who seem to be hanging around waiting to be cast as extras
in the new Beck video?
</P>
<P>
   ``All I Wanna Do'' lurches between girl-power melodrama and
bratty farce, but the ungainliness is part of the film's charm.
Adolescence is an awkward time, and so were the '60s, for that
matter. It's hard not to be won over by the spirited sloppiness of
Kernochan and her cast, who gamely assay even the most stilted
period absurdities of the script. Sometimes you think you're
watching a finishing-school remake of ``Animal House,'' at others a
made-for-the-WB version of ``The Group.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film is surprisingly pleasant, thanks to smart,
unstereotyped performances _ especially by Hoffmann and Dunst _ and
the filmmaker's evident respect and affection for her characters. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ALL I WANNA DO' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Sarah Kernochan; director of
photography, Anthony Jannelli; edited by Peter Frank; music by
Graeme Revell; production designer, John Kasarda; produced by Ira
Deutchman and Peter Newman; released by Redeemable Features.
Running time: 94 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kirsten Dunst (Verena Von Stefan), Gaby Hoffmann (Odette
Sinclair), Lynn Redgrave (McVane), Rachael Leigh Cook (Abby
Sawyer), Thomas Guiry (Frosty Frost), Vincent Kartheiser (Snake),
Monica Keena (Tinka Parker), Matthew Lawrence (Dennis) and Heather
Matarazzo (Tweety Goldberg). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `All I Wanna Do' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned). It
includes some sexual references and situations, a good deal of
vomiting (self-induced and otherwise) and the casual display of
elaborate, historically accurate foundation garments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
