u i BC-GERMANY-NAZILABOR-669     03-23 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-NAZILABOR-669&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$5 BILLION DISBURSEMENT SETTLED FOR WARTIME FORCED LABORERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ A long, often bitter negotiation intended to settle
once and for all Germany's financial obligations from the Nazi
years ended Thursday with an agreement on how to allocate $5
billion among surviving forced laborers and others driven to work
in Hitler's concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached after a long night of talks, provides for
the payment of $4.075 billion to the forced laborers, mainly
non-Jews from Central European countries overrun by the Nazis, and
to a much smaller number of mainly Jewish slave laborers.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that perhaps 1 million former forced laborers
will qualify to receive payments, as will about 240,000 former
slave laborers who toiled in the Nazi camps. An advertising
campaign will alert potential claimants, who are each expected to
receive an average of $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining money _ just under $1 billion _ will be divided
principally between a new German foundation intended to provide
educational programs related to the Holocaust and people who lost
property, money that was in German banks, or money owed to them by
German insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of how the money is to be shared out has been
successfully settled,'' said Otto Lambsdorff, the chief German
negotiator. The agreement came three months after an accord on a
sum of $5 billion was reached.
</P>
<P>
   Talks in recent weeks were marked by heated disagreements _
between Poland and negotiators for Jewish victims, between the
German government and all the claimants and between Central
European states. ``Frankly, people were getting very tired of the
sight of each other,'' said one person involved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   After heated disagreements, the parties decided that $906
million should be paid to Poland and that the same amount should be
given to the Jewish Claims Conference. About 3 million Polish Jews
and roughly the same number of Catholic Poles were killed during
World War II, giving rise to a competitive victimhood that has
often proved acrimonious.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine will receive $862 million, Russia $417.5 million,
Belarus $347 million, and the Czech Republic $211.5 million. A
further $400 million will be divided among other countries, and
another $25 million will be reserved for those who suffered
injuries from Nazi medical experiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is late in the day, and perhaps it's little, but it's
something,'' said Israel Singer, the chief negotiator for the
Jewish Claims Conference. ``What would be welcome now would be a
German statement spelling out the moral dimension of this accord.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in a speech to the Israeli Knesset, Johannes Rau,
the German president, said: ``I ask forgiveness for what Germans
have done _ for myself and my generation, for the sake of our
children and our children's children.'' Singer suggested that the
president should append some similar statement to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But German feelings have been severely tested by the talks. What
began more than a year ago with a preemptive offer of $1.7 billion
from German firms and the government, intended in part to head off
potential suits against German companies in the United States,
often degenerated into angry haggling that led to a tripling of the
initial sum.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many companies that have invested heavily in the United States _
including DaimlerChrysler and Deutsche Bank _ were anxious for what
they called ``closure,'' an assurance that they would not face
class-action suits. At the same time, they clearly resented what
they saw as the unreasonable pressure to pay more.
</P>
<P>
   Claimants were often exasperated by the slow-moving talks and
the sometimes defiant attitude of the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has already paid more than $50 billion in reparations to
victims of Hitler since World War II, but had generally avoided
payments to compensate the millions of people put to work by the
Nazis for their labor and suffering.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stuart Eizenstat, the U.S. deputy treasury secretary who was
co-chairman of the talks, said the United States would put in place
measures aimed at preventing further lawsuits. A statement from
German firms involved in the fund said details of their legal
protection would be spelled out in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said it hoped
that the payments would begin before the end of the year. The
Bundestag must pass relevant legislation before payments are made.
</P>
</TEXT>
