<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5975 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-POMPIDOU26-COX     03-23 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POMPIDOU26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `New' Pompidou perfect for contemporary arts
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Imagine mooring an ocean liner in the Fairlie-Poplar
district, one with all the big pipes on the hull, to boot.
</P>
<P>
   That, in effect, is what architects Renzo Piano and Richard
Rogers did in 1977 with their Pompidou Center on the Right Bank of
Paris. The high-tech-looking behemoth, a multidisciplinary arts
center, dwarfed the historic buildings nearby and thumbed its nose
at their architectural traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Castigated as an affront to the dignity of this courtly city,
the painted (vivid blue, green, red and yellow) lady nevertheless
became one of Paris' most popular tourist attractions. But
accommodating 23,000 visitors a day _ half the number that fills
Turner Field _ for 20 years took a toll. When it closed in 1997 for
renovation, it needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after two years and upwards of $88 million, the Pompidou
Center is back in fine fettle. No more peeling paint. No more
cigarette butts in the crevices of its famous exterior escalator.
Best of all, the renovation has improved the place.
</P>
<P>
   Renzo Piano Building Workshop, the Genoa, Italy, firm creating a
master plan for the Woodruff Arts Center, designed the exterior and
public spaces. The spacious lobby is flanked by two mezzanines. One
houses Zed Zed, a snappy cafe done up in red velvet and chrome,
which is run by the chic restaurateur Costes, of Cafe Marly fame. A
new art bookstore is off the lobby below it; Printemps Design
Boutique is on the other side. Neon signs make finding one's way
around easier.
</P>
<P>
   There are four new theaters for dance, music, cinema and plays.
A retrospective of Piano's architectural career inaugurated space
to be devoted to design.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth and fifth floors have been given over to the National
Museum of Modern Art. It reopens in retooled galleries with
revamped exhibits. The design takes better advantage of the great
view. New terraces show off the sculpture collection against the
rooftop vista.
</P>
<P>
   The galleries offer a broader perspective of modern art that
encompasses all the arts. Models of important buildings, as well as
displays of chairs and appliances, are in galleries adjacent to
their chronological analogues in painting and sculpture. There are
even a few works of outsider art: Bedecked with red and black
signs, ``Le Magasin de Ben'' (Ben's Store), for example, would be
at home in Georgia but for the French words and the signs' European
handwriting.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's take on the unfolding of modern art has a European
spin. However, mixing nationalities is de rigueur, to the point
that country of origin is not even mentioned on the labels.
Large-scale installations, by artists such as Jean Dubuffet, Josef
Beuys and contemporary American stars Tony Oursler and Mike Kelley,
literally add an extra dimension to the display.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller galleries alternating with the spacious ones are perfect
for showing drawings, sketches and photographs that need more
intimate scale. In fact, some of these displays, which often travel
on the side roads of art history, are among the most interesting.
Atelier Breton shows off French writer Andre Breton's stuff:
Curios, walking sticks, primitive art and paintings by his
surrealist friends hang in a happy jangle.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth floor is given over to temporary exhibits and a
white-tablecloth restaurant, Georges, which features a spectacular
view. It is also run by the Costes family, the Parisian equivalent
of the Buckhead Life Group. (Cafe Beaubourg on the plaza, an ``in''
haunt for artists and intellectuals, is also a Costes property;
reservations, 01-48-87-96-65.)
</P>
<P>
   You can round out your visit by touring the Brancusi Atelier, a
small building adjacent to the center built in 1997. The Renzo
Piano design makes use of the contents of the original studio _
tools, sculptures, bases _ without trying to re-create it.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget to stop by the fountain on the opposite side of
the plaza from the atelier. The perfect distillation of the
insouciant character of the Pompidou, it is the only place in Paris
where you will find a pair of voluptuous red lips spitting water
into a pool against the backdrop of a Gothic cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: The Pompidou Center, on Rue St. Martin, is open
11 a.m.-10 p.m. daily except Tuesdays. Admission is $2.25-$13.50,
depending on which and how many things you visit. For program
information: www.centrepompidou.fr., or call 01-44-78-12-33.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
