<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5976 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SPAIN26-COX     03-23 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vibrant college town an age-old Spanish gem
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALAMANCA, Spain _ This is a town time forgot to forget, a place
where you can stumble through the ages just by ... stumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping down narrow streets after debating fascist politics
late into the night with a Franco-yearning bartender (his basic
argument: the trains ran on time), running a hand along sandstone
walls centuries have worn smooth or artisans have carved into the
likenesses of saints or popes or frogs or clamshells, passing
students and nuns and old couples locked arm-in-arm ... Traveling
through Salamanca like this, buzzing on its college-town ambience
and rounds of canas (draft beer), you turn a dark corner you didn't
mean to turn and suddenly you're all alone _ as removed from the
modern world as a mid-millennium monk. Just you and that empty,
walled-in street and central Spain's carbon-black sky and the
inevitable medieval cathedral, looming up ahead like a sacrament
you feel obligated to observe.
</P>
<P>
   It's at moments like these that you check your watch and wonder:
Is this the 21st century? Or the 13th?
</P>
<P>
   Then the time-traveling spell is broken: The sound of students
from the nearly 800-year-old University of Salamanca laughing their
heads off, or caroling some Spanish ditty, rolls out a cafe window
cut into one of those thick old walls. And instead of a friendly
fascist bartender (``Not fascist _ Francoist,'' Miguel, the
bartender at the wonderful La Fontana, insists), this cafe is
likely to be equipped with computers for e-mailing friends around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Salamanca does all the centuries well. Though its streets are
lined with one vintage architectural showpiece after another, it
has avoided calcifying into a for-tourists-only museum. Unlike
look-but-don't-touch vacation jewels, Salamanca remains a vital
university town of 160,000 people, even at its most historic core.
</P>
<P>
   As a tourist destination, the city _ a three-hour train ride
west of Madrid _ isn't as well-known as other midsize stopovers,
such as Toledo, Seville and Granada. But Conde Nast Traveler
recently declared Salamanca one of Europe's unknown gems, and its
widest reputation is as a haven for students and adults to spend a
summer or semester learning Spanish, at the University of Salamanca
or at a host of other language institutes in town.
</P>
<P>
   So those who know Salamanca tend to love it in a very personal
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to Salamanca, you don't have to go anywhere else.
It's one of the best-kept secrets,'' says Daniel Stone, an Atlanta
elementary school teacher who has lived in Salamanca twice, first
to attend the university and most recently as a chaperone for
Atlanta high school students who studied there for a semester last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he'd recommend Salamanca to someone traveling through
Spain, Stone smiles prankishly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me says no,'' he says. ``I'd like to keep it a
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Salamanca has drawn students and tourists for centuries. The
university, founded in 1218, is Spain's oldest, and by the 15th
century was considered one of the ``leading lights of the world''
(according to one pope), up there with learning centers in Oxford,
England; Bologna, Italy; and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the city goes back a lot further. It has been
conquered by all the greats: Hannibal (217 B.C.), the Arabs, the
Visigoths, the Muslims, Napoleon. The Roman Bridge, 2,000 years
after it was erected, still spans the gentle River Tormes.
</P>
<P>
   Salamanca today rises from the stark, bull-raising plains of
Castilla y Leon province like an ancient oasis, the domes and bell
towers of its two cathedrals visible from miles away. It's a busy,
compact town that in a bright light has a honey glow, the result of
the fine-grain sandstone used on so many of the buildings.
Intricate, almost overwhelming carvings grace many of the
buildings, in a style known as Plateresque, described in one
guidebook as ``Spain's version of Flamboyant Gothic.''
</P>
<P>
   Full of tourists, Salamanca is not annoyingly touristy; its
many, eclectic bookstores contain far more books than postcards. It
is a city where one minute you're standing inside the roaring
silence of a 12th-century church, the next you're listening to a
pizza joint's mellow piped-in remake of the Bee Gees' ``Where Is
the Love?'' The ancient and the contemporary often are virtually
the same thing here: Salamanca has been designated by UNESCO as a
World Heritage City (essentially a national monument), so building
codes allow some interiors to be modernized, as long as the
exterior is returned to its original form _ brick by brick.
</P>
<P>
   So the Casa de las Conchas (House of Shells), one of the city's
most distinctive landmarks, with scalloped shells playfully carved
over the 18th-century mansion's exterior, today is used as a
bright, modern library where you can find the latest issue of
Sports Illustrated or The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salamanca felt like home. It's comfortable,'' says Heather
Stoltenberg, an Ohio Wesleyan University junior who spent last
semester studying at the University of Salamanca. ``I loved the
Plaza Mayor, being able to sit outside and watch people stroll by
and have a (coffee) or a Coke. The culture there is so much more
relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   All roads here do seem to lead to the Plaza Mayor. It's
considered by many to be Spain's finest public plaza. A wide,
four-story, arcaded space built by the native Churriguera brothers
around 1755, the plaza sets the town's tone.
</P>
<P>
   It's an easygoing gathering place (it hosted bullfights through
the 19th century) where adults drink and eat at the outdoor cafes,
and students meet ``under the clock'' to hang among musicians and
magicians and hordes of other students. You don't need an agenda
here: Just stroll. You'll bump into a restaurant or tapas bar or
boutique (one sells Lladro, the fine Spanish porcelain many
tourists covet) for almost any taste, though the welcoming Cafe
Novelty is a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   The plaza comes even more alive for a couple of weeks beginning
Sept. 8, when live music fills it nightly during Salamanca's
festival.
</P>
<P>
   The city's other physical and psychic anchors, the cathedrals
and the university, are within easy walking distance of the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The two main churches are impressive, worthwhile stops, even for
the cathedral-weary. The Old and the New Cathedral look like one
building, the old leaning against the new, as one observer
described it, ``like a chick under the wing of a hen.''
</P>
<P>
   The golden stone facade of the New Cathedral (begun in 1513 and
finished in 1733) is a stare-at-forever wonder, sculpted with
religious imagery _ popes, bishops, angels _ to within an inch of
its life. Inside is a booming, almost never-ending series of
medieval chapels, altars and crypts.
</P>
<P>
   Explore this cathedral and you might never have to explore
another _ except for the Old Cathedral, which you enter through the
new one.
</P>
<P>
   With your first step through the Old Cathedral's door, you
instantly step back another couple hundred years. Started in 1150,
it has a simpler, more burnished feel than its neighboring upstart.
The bright religious art makes it seem as much gallery as
cathedral; the breathtaking main altarpiece is made up of 53 panels
depicting the life of Christ and the Virgin, painted in colorful
tempura.
</P>
<P>
   The university is two blocks away. While no longer ranked with
the world's great schools, it still gives the city a distinctly
hallowed flavor.
</P>
<P>
   When you walk through the halls, you walk in the footsteps of
Columbus, who came here to consult the school's then-famed
astrology (yes, astrology) faculty, before his journey to India _
er, America.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its famous facade _ it puts the plater in plateresque,
with ornate carvings of kings, popes, gods, goddesses and a famous
frog, which brings good luck if you can spot it _ lies the austere
lecture room of Friar Luis de Leon. It remains as it was four
centuries ago, when in 1573 de Leon was arrested there and jailed
during the Inquisition (among his crimes: preferring the Hebrew
version of the Bible to the Latin).
</P>
<P>
   He returned famously five years later, striding back into the
classroom and beginning his lecture to rapt students, ``As I was
saying yesterday ...''
</P>
<P>
   Salamanca has always done all the centuries well.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: All major domestic and international carriers
fly to Madrid. Sale fares on mid-
</P>
<P>
   week departures are $348 for travel through April 12; $398 April
13-30; and $438 May 1-30. (Reg-
</P>
<P>
   ular fare is $890 for midweek departures April 1-May 27.) Up to
four trains a day leave for Sala-
</P>
<P>
   manca from Madrid ($15 one way). Buses leave more frequently
($14 one way).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to stay: Our first choice is the Hotel Rector,
relatively pricey (about $114 for a double), but as tasteful and
accommodating as a small (14 rooms) hotel gets. Located blocks from
the Roman Bridge and the River Tormes (but about a 15-minute walk
to the plaza). Call: 923-218-482; fax 923-214-008.
</P>
<P>
   A less expensive, more centrally located choice: The Hotel Don
Juan, just steps from the plaza. Call: 923-261-473; fax
923-262-475.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Language classes: University of Salamanca: 923-29-44-00. There
are also a number of other language institutes in Salamanca. For a
list, call the Education Office of Spain, 212-741-5144.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tourist Office of Spain, 305-358-1992,
www.okspain.org
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
