<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SWITZERLAND26-COX     03-23 1659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWITZERLAND26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't miss Swiss city rich in art, museums
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASEL, Switzerland _ Clang. Creak. Clang. Creak.
</P>
<P>
   You can hear the art of the Museum Jean Tinguely before you see
it. The source of all that noise is a fountain set in the green
expanse in front of the garden entrance. The Swiss artist's Rube
Goldbergesque contraption grinds its gears for no other reason than
to delight viewers with its whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   The airy Tinguely museum _ where the assemblages of machinery,
cow skulls and musical instruments look like giant toys _ is only
one of the many sources of appeal for art lovers in this town of
200,000 in northwest Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Its Kunstmuseum, which Basel claims is the oldest public art
institution in the world, is known for its holdings of Holbein and
other northern masters, and the city has several venues devoted to
contemporary art and architecture. Only 20 minutes out is the
Fondation Beyeler, a must-see collection of modern art ensconced in
a serene building designed by Italian architect Renzo Piano, who is
creating the master plan for the Woodruff Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   Basel is also a great spot to take in sights just over the
close-by French and German borders. Vitra, a furniture
manufacturer, has commissioned a group of buildings by
international architects for its German headquarters in Weil am
Rhein, a half-hour away. Le Corbusier's dramatic pilgrimage
cathedral in Ronchamp, France, is about 80 miles from Basel.
</P>
<P>
   But Basel's offerings are hardly limited to fine art. Even
though you can walk from one end of the historic city center to the
other in a morning, this tidy town along the Rhine River is home to
30 museums on just about anything that might pique your interest.
Fire engines. Antiques. Medicine. Teddy bears. You can find it
here, in a picturesque setting that looks like something out of the
Brothers Grimm.
</P>
<P>
   Basel's history is as a center of learning and culture. It is
home to the oldest university in Switzerland, founded in 1460, and
to the country's first musical theater. Humanist scholar Erasmus is
buried in its cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost imagine him walking the winding, hilly streets of
the densely woven old town. Packed with charming buildings in brick
and stucco that are often enhanced by wide shutters and flower
boxes, it wears its history with pride. Wandering around is
certainly part of the fun. The red stone Rathaus (Town Hall),
decorated with frescoes, is the jewel of Market Square. The
12th-century Munster, the largest cathedral, rises along the Rhine.
Goldsmiths work in their shop windows so you can stand and watch
them maneuver their tiny precision tools.
</P>
<P>
   The comfortable scale of city and the broad reach of
institutions make Basel a good destination for families. Also
helpful, at least some of the labels in most museums are translated
into English.
</P>
<P>
   Here is just a sampling of its cultural amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Basel Paper Mill
</P>
<P>
   Basel, a center of knowledge in medieval times, was also a
capital of book publishing and its related industries. The water
wheel still churns in the canal outside the half-timbered mill,
dating from 1478, powering the paper-making going on within. In
what might be one of the most delightful experiences of your stay,
you can follow the process that turns rags into paper (they are
literally beaten to a pulp) and even make some yourself.
</P>
<P>
   As a man (who seems to be straight out of central casting's
medieval artisans division) stirs a vat of boiling rags with a
wooden spoon on the ground floor, a craftsman upstairs makes tiny
letters from molten metal. You can set these letters yourself on
the next floor of the narrow building and run the whole concoction
through a press. Among several other displays is a section on
book-binding.
</P>
<P>
   Fondation Beyeler
</P>
<P>
   A highlight of your trip will be a visit to this 3-year-old
museum, which displays the splendid collection of Basel art dealer
Ernst Beyeler and his wife, Hildy. Beyeler's impeccable eye is
evident in the choice examples he acquired of classic modern
masters Monet, Picasso, Matisse, Miro, Giacometti _ and ensuing
generations from Andy Warhol to Anselm Kiefer. The museum
intersperses European art with examples of the tribal arts that
were a source of inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The one-story stone and glass museum is a treat in itself.
Architect Piano, whom the High Museum wants to design its expansion
(partly on the basis of this building), has created an elegant but
understated environment for the art, enhanced by a roof that lets
in natural light. Nestled in the countryside, it offers views of
gardens and rolling hills. The Beyeler, which has a restaurant in
an adjacent building, an old villa, is an easy 20-minute tram ride
from Basel.
</P>
<P>
   Historical Museum
</P>
<P>
   Housed in a deconsecrated 14th-century church, the museum, whose
collection started in the 16th century, chronicles the history of
Basel dating to the Celts. The medieval armor and ornamented swords
in the military displays will grab the kids. Dress uniforms make
peacocks out of soldiers. Richly paneled medieval and Renaissance
guild rooms, featuring stained glass, ceramic stoves and heavy
furniture, suggest the lifestyles of the periods.
</P>
<P>
   Museum Jean Tinguely
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Swiss architect Mario Botta, this museum offers an
in-depth look at the late Swiss sculptor and experimental artist,
who died in 1991 at age 66. Known for his imaginative merging of
junk sculpture and kinetics, he's a sort of mechanized
Rauschenberg. Tinguely is more complicated than he first appears.
Death is a frequent subject, and some of the works take a macabre
turn.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, his work is great fun. Witness the delight of the children
making their own art on a replica of his drawing machine, which
requires inserting the crayon into a holder, turning on the machine
and watching it doodle.
</P>
<P>
   More telling are the otherwise dignified adults stomping on
floor buttons to make, say, a mechanized hammer pound like Woody
Woodpecker on the head of a toy doll.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Museum of World Culture
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has no equivalent facility devoted to the study of man
around the world, and this one, which owns one of Europe's finest
ethnographic collections, is fascinating. Life-size tableaux
display, often quite dramatically, cultural artifacts from places
such as Oceania and Africa. Besides the traditional ceremonial
objects, such as masks and weapons, the museum presents a sense of
everyday life. The interior of one African hut even includes a
late-model fridge bearing a Coke magnet.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, which occupies a high-ceilinged old building it
shares with the Museum of Natural History, owns an exhaustive
collection of textiles. Costumes on display during my visit spanned
the globe, from embroidered leatherwear of Eastern Europe to
gorgeous Japanese kimonos.
</P>
<P>
   Museum of Natural History
</P>
<P>
   Lions and tigers and bears, oh my! Kids will enjoy this array of
taxidermied animals (also insects) set in small displays suggesting
natural habitats. Considering that the delight in dinosaurs will
never be extinct, the room devoted to their remains will definitely
be a draw. Be sure to see _ and how could you miss? _ the
multihorned triceratops.
</P>
<P>
   Doll's House Museum
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of bears, the teddy variety is present in abundance in
this delightful little museum ensconced in a newly renovated
department store. Take a kid for cover if you want, but you'll find
plenty of childless adults openly enjoying the displays of dolls,
toys and year-round Christmas items. Best of all are myriad
miniature vignettes, which re-create their subjects in startling
detail. The 19th-century bakery, for example, is represented down
to the currants on a bun. Don't tell your kid, but these displays _
which encompass various aspects of daily life, including a
hospital, a bridal shop and an amusement park, replete with moving
parts _ are actually history in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   Vitra Design Museum
</P>
<P>
   This manufacturer of high-design furniture has created the
appropriate manufacturing compound by commissioning stellar
international architects, three of them Pritzker Prize winners, to
design its buildings 10 miles across the German border. Portuguese
architect Alvaro Siza designed a factory building. Japanese star
Tadao Ando turned a conference center into a series of spare
meditative spaces. Frank Gehry, in a commission before his
celebrated design of the Guggenheim Museum Bilbao in northern
Spain, made a museum of cubes and sweeping forms in 1989. Vitra's
collection of modern chairs originally installed in the Gehry
building, is housed in the garage of the former firehouse, all
sharp diagonals and cantilevered planes by deconstructivist Zaha
Hadid.
</P>
<P>
   Take a Swiss or German taxi to reach Vitra, in the city of Weil
am Rhein. Bring your passport. You'll need to book a tour to see
all the buildings on the campus other than the public museum.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Swissair, Air France and British Airways fly to
Basel. Sale fares on midweek departures are $436 for travel through
April 6; $488 April 7-30; and $528 May 1-June 15. Saturday night
stay required. (Regular fare is $959 for midweek departures through
May 27.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging: The city of museums is also a city of hotels. Der
Teufelhof is both. In two adjacent mansions housing two
restaurants, two theaters and a bar as well as guest rooms, the
hotel offers eight rooms that are decorated by different artists
(changing every two years). Also available: 25 bright modern rooms
with original art. For more information, call 61/261 10 10, or send
a fax to 61/261 10 04.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Basel Tourism Office: 61/268 68 68, or
www.baseltourismus.ch.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
