<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-WARBIRD26-COX     03-23 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARBIRD26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where warbirds go to fly again
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By J. Edwin Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ For almost every day of every week during the
past 29 years, Tom Reilly has taken ``living history'' to a higher
altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, the founder and owner of the Flying Tigers Warbird
Restoration Museum, a few minutes up the road from Disney World,
specializes in amusements for big boys and girls. Reilly makes the
past come alive _ obtaining, for the most part, the wreckage of
World War II airplanes, then rebuilding them from top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes to put them back into original condition and
make them fly once again, we do it,'' Reilly says as he leads a
visitor through his 19,000-square-foot hangar in which restored
relics are parked wing to wing. Some of the older, lighter aircraft
are hanging from the ceiling, held aloft by support cables.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of this tour is that Reilly and the rest of the
museum's guides have actually flown these planes or helped restore
them. Because there is no time limit on these tours, guides are
eager to answer any and all questions, and expound at length on the
various aircrafts' strengths and weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's technicians are working on a P-51 Mustang, the wreckage
of which was found on a hillside in Minsk, Russia. Within a year,
Reilly says, the warbird will be flying once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's the fascination with not only this project, but all
the others,'' Reilly says. ``They're heavy and fat, drip oil and
smell bad. But darned if I haven't fallen in love with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The old warbirds have had that effect on others also. On this
day, two visitors approach Reilly as he works on an aircraft
engine. Fascinated, they humor him when he asks them to hand him a
wrench. Next thing they know, they are up to their elbows in
``bomber blood'' (aviation-speak for hydraulic oil), spending the
better part of a half-hour learning the intricacies of a Cyclone
nine-cylinder radial, air-cooled engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They loved it,'' Reilly says. ``Not only did they get to see
history in the making, they also got to touch it.''
</P>
<P>
   What visitors to this vast complex get to see, smell and touch
is the history of flight, everything from 1920s biplanes to Cold
War-era jets, with plenty of WWII warbirds in between. On permanent
display is a B-25 Mitchell bomber, the plane Jimmy Doolittle's
pilots flew en route to their famous ``30 seconds over Tokyo''
bombing run against Japan in the early days of the war. Movie buffs
will also recognize the two B-17 Flying Fortress bombers, the focal
point of ``12 O'Clock High,'' starring Gregory Peck.
</P>
<P>
   Less-recognizable aircraft, at least to the untrained eyes of
the aviation-impaired, include Corsairs and Warhawks, Stearmans and
Ryans, Magisters and Starfighters.
</P>
<P>
   Tour guides will give you an aeronautical primer, pointing out,
for example, that the two-seat Ryan trainer you're looking at was
manufactured by the same company that built The Spirit of St. Louis
for Charles Lindbergh. The 1943 two-seat Stearman also is a biplane
of distinction: According to the plane's flight records, it was
flown by former President George Bush. And the yellow-and-green
camouflage 1955 Fouga Magister, recently obtained from Israel, was
used in ground-attack combat during the 1967 Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most of the World War II aircraft come and go,'' says
Reilly, 57. ``We restore them for clients, then put them on public
display until the clients are ready to take possession of them.
It's an ongoing, never-ending process. For every project we
complete, another two come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly and his technicians have restored 27 warbirds in the past
29 years, and a 28th is almost ready to roll out the door and take
to the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence,'' he says, ``what we do is restore rich toys for
rich boys and girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage toys, to be exact _ 57-year-old combat aircraft with
colorful names and heroic bloodlines: Thunderbolts, Liberators,
Lightnings, Texans and Mustangs.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring these relics takes at least two years and can cost as
much as $2.5 million _ a bargain, according to aviation experts.
After all, Corsairs, Warhawks and Mitchell bombers no longer roll
off wartime assembly lines. Of the more than 11,000 Mitchell
bombers manufactured during the war, for example, only 38 exist
today _ nine of which were restored by Reilly's crew. And, as is
the case with most antiques, values have escalated in the past 30
years. The fully restored Mitchell bomber that could be purchased
in 1979 for $6,000 today costs $500,000. In 1979, a Mustang _ the
plane Chuck Yeager flew in combat years before breaking the sound
barrier _ was worth $30,000. Today it is valued in excess of $1
million. That Flying Fortress that cost $30,000 in 1979 now sells
for $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly began this venture in 1970, the year the soft-spoken,
unassuming New Jersey native settled in the Orlando area, after
purchasing five pre-WWII fixed-gear planes in Canada. Selling four
of them to other aviation enthusiasts, he decided to restore the
other for himself. In short order, his hobby became a passion,
which eventually turned into a very lucrative business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing you know, I've got more planes than I know what to
do with,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That problem was solved in 1988, when he purchased the hangar
complex at Kissimmee Airport. It wasn't long before WWII pilots
started showing up with their family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we started calling this place a museum and
charging admission,'' Reilly says. ``Of course, it's not like most
museums in that we encourage people to touch whatever they like.
Our philosophy from the start was that everyone should be in touch
with history. Everything's just sort of blossomed from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has traveled the world over _ Bolivia, Greece, Greenland,
Germany and France _ in search of planes and parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accumulate enough parts and pretty soon you've got enough to
rebuild a warbird,'' he says. ``I've got haystacks of parts. That's
why, while some people like to call this place a working museum,
others call it a fairy tale land for junk collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Orlando is $83 each way on AirTran and Delta
airlines, with a 14-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Address: The museum is at 231 N. Hoagland Blvd., in Kissimmee,
a few minutes from Disney World. Take I-4 to Exit 25A to Fla. 192,
go east about 7.5 miles, turn south onto Hoagland Boulevard, 1 mile
to museum.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours, admission: 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m. daily. $8 adults, $6 senior
citizens and children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On display: 20 flyable warbirds, including an A-26 Invader,
AT-6 Texan, B-25 Mitchell, P-40 Warhawk and a C-47; restoration
projects include two B-17 Flying Fortresses, an F4U-4 Corsair, A-4
Skyhawk, two P-38 Lightnings, two AT-6/SNJ-4 Harvards and a TB-25N.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Programs: Five-day restoration school ($995) includes work on
sheet metal, hydraulics, engines and carburetors, props and
governors, fuel and oil systems, control systems, magnetos,
electrical systems and welding, plus a flight in a B-25.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 407-933-1942; www.warbirdmuseum.com.
</P>
<P>
   J. Edwin Smith writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
