r t BC-WARBIRDFLY26-COX     03-23 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARBIRDFLY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Off he goes into the wild blue yonder
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By J. Edwin Smith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ At 6,000 feet, my left hand was on the stick
of the 1944 model AT-6 Texan, my right making sure once again that
the emergency release of my parachute was still where it should be.
I listened via headphones to the instructions of Jay Vandersluis,
the veteran pilot who sat in the rear seat of the Marine Corps
two-seat trainer, as we zipped along at 230 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a part of Warbird Adventures, operated alongside Tom
Reilly's warbird museum by owner Graham Meise and his top gun, Thom
Richard. For a nominal cost, these pilots will take you aloft, test
out the strength of your stomach with a few barrel rolls and loops,
then turn over the controls to you _ even if you're not a licensed
pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. If you run into trouble, your instructor can
immediately regain control of the craft with an identical set of
controls aft.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, you've got the appearance of control. And it
doesn't take long to gain a true appreciation for precision, and
for the craftsmanship of the mechanics and technicians far below in
the hangar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you ready for some fun?'' Vandersluis asks. And before my
mind can rationalize the question, the aviator drops the Texan's
left wing, and the deep-blue panorama of open sky slides away,
replaced moments later by the tiny checkerboard of distant earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we call a wing-over,'' Vandersluis says. ``It's
one of the basic defensive entry-level maneuvers for aerobatics.
Now it's your turn. Level off ... uh-huh, now you've got it. Slow
it down ... good, keep it at 80 mph, right rudder ... yeah, that's
it. Way to go. Now we'll do a loop.''
</P>
<P>
   Never has life gone by with such dizzying clarity. Wing-overs to
the left, wing-overs to the right at 80 and 90 mph, followed by
loops at 180 mph. Then Vandersluis' all-time favorite: the Cuban 8,
a loop followed by a roll-out to the left and then another loop.
</P>
<P>
   Once we've leveled out and turned back toward the airport, he
asks, ``So what did you think of that? Sort of gives you a greater
appreciation for those pilots of yesterday, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   I was speechless. Awed. Subdued by the ride of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Our touchdown on the airport's runway minutes later was the
perfect culmination of a historical day _ first seeing and touching
aviation history in the warbird museum, then tasting it as never
before at 6,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Prices start at $140 for front-seat flying for 15
minutes to an hour. Extra packages include aerobatics, in-flight
video and in-flight 35mm still pictures. Instruction is also
offered in 5- and 10-hour courses ($2,500-$4,750), depending on
your experience as a pilot; aerobatics and tailwheel training; and
formation training. 1-800-386-1593.
</P>
<P>
   _J. Edwin Smith writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
