<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WAKING-FILM-REVIEW-NY     03-23 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAKING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WAKING THE DEAD': THE GHOSTS OF IDEALISM AND AN OBSESSIVE LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keith Gordon's painfully earnest screen adaptation of Scott
Spencer's novel ``Waking the Dead'' grasps at a fusion of
historicism and heartbreak that we normally expect to find in
sprawling Hollywood epics, not in interior psychological dramas
like Spencer's novel. But in falling short of its goal, the movie
raises the question of whether it's possible to film an intelligent
tear-jerker that prompts us to think and cry at the same time. Or
are serious suds and serious ideas a cinematic oxymoron? At its
best, ``Waking the Dead'' suggests an intellectually upscale answer
to ``Love Story.'' At its weakest, it comes off as a stiff, muted
exercise in countercultural nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though ``Waking the Dead'' flaunts an advanced
degree in political science. But the movie, which resurrects a
shopworn but still useful debate about joining the system to change
it from within versus working from outside to bring it down is
certainly thoughtful by Hollywood standards. In framing the debate
as a quarrel between an aspiring Kennedy-like politician and his
radical activist girlfriend in the 1970s (and taking her side more
than his), the movie makes an honorable attempt to enshrine the
impassioned idealism of an era that has faded into ``Forrest Gump''
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking the Dead'' is also a more politically sophisticated
rewrite of Spencer's most famous novel, ``Endless Love'' (whose
screen adaptation by Franco Zeffirelli flattened a tale of crazy
erotic obsession into smoochy teen-age kitsch). Each book focuses
on an obsessive love affair whose demise leaves its male
protagonist suffering psychotic tremors.
</P>
<P>
   The brokenhearted hero of ``Waking the Dead'' is Fielding Pierce
(Billy Crudup), a working-class golden boy who ascends from Coast
Guard officer through Harvard Law School into the rough-and-tumble
of Chicago politics. His true love, Sarah Williams (Jennifer
Connelly), is a beautiful, headstrong idealist who on their first
date lightly announces, ``I want a life of unbelievable adventure
and profligacy and at the last possible moment ... sainthood.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah makes good on that pronouncement. She travels to Chile
under the auspices of the Roman Catholic Church to help feed the
poor and organize resistance to the oppressive right-wing
government. Shortly after returning to the United States in 1974,
she is murdered in a car bombing in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding never gets over it. Although he moves on with his life
and runs for Congress under the tutelage of Isaac Green (Hal
Holbrook), a hard-boiled Chicago power broker, and conveniently
becomes engaged to Isaac's niece Juliet (Molly Parker), he is
increasingly haunted by the past. As his first congressional race
heats up, his obsession with Sarah escalates to the point where he
begins catching glimpses of her on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, he begins entertaining serious doubts about her
death and wonders if somehow she escaped the car bombing and for
mysterious reasons has remained in hiding. Ultimately, his
obsession puts his political career, his forthcoming marriage and
his sanity in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   In bringing ``Waking the Dead'' to the screen, Gordon, whose
previous movies ``A Midnight Clear'' and ``Mother Night'' (from
Kurt Vonnegut) exuded the same aura of heavy-duty seriousness, has
captured his protagonist's romanticism but little of his
self-destructive craziness. The movie has its rapturous moments,
but its emotions never spill over familiar romantic bounds into the
realm of the scary. As hard as ``Waking the Dead'' works to make us
wonder if Sarah is really still alive, the movie refuses to follow
its protagonist over the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the disappointment of ``Waking the Dead'' has to do with
its central performance. Crudup is a creditable actor who puts a
great deal of craft into his performance, but (it may be a trick of
the camera) there is no light in his eyes, and for that reason,
here, as in earlier movies, he seems strangely unknowable. That
absence of a gleam translates into a diminished charisma that is
further undermined by Robert Dillon's screenplay, which gives
Fielding too little of substance to say, especially when he is on
the political stump. Crudup is much stronger in moments of
emotional stress, especially in a scene near the end in which his
tightly wound composure suddenly cracks.
</P>
<P>
   As Sarah, Connelly captures a burning ethereality and
willfulness that are very much of the period. And she and Crudup
connect powerfully in love scenes that convey the fierce tenderness
of a relationship whose passion carries a tinge of religious
fervor.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie makes a terrible mistake by continually and
abruptly cutting back and forth between the '70s and the early
'80s. The movie is forever stumbling over itself and breaking its
own spell. At exactly the moment it begins to draw us in to one of
its stories, it makes another leap, and the mood is broken. Because
it barely distinguishes between the two decades, the flashbacks
have none of the resonance of treasured memories.
</P>
<P>
   The movie still has some aching moments, but they come mostly
from a soundtrack that makes haunting use of Joni Mitchell's ``Case
of You,'' Peter Gabriel's ``Mercy Street'' and Lori Carson's wisp
of a ballad ``Snow Come Down,'' which wafts over the final credits.
If the ghosts that the rest of the movie wants to conjure never
come into focus, in these beautifully chosen musical moments, you
can hear their sad, eerie call.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Waking the Dead is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has sexual situations
and some strong language.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WAKING THE DEAD'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Keith Gordon; written by Robert Dillon, based on the
novel by Scott Spencer; director of photography, Tom Richmond;
edited by Jeff Wishengrad; music by tomandandy; production
designer, Zoe Sakellaropoulo; produced by Gordon, Stuart Kleinman
and Linda Reisman; released by USA Films/Gramercy Pictures. Running
time: 106 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Billy Crudup (Fielding Pierce), Jennifer Connelly (Sarah
Williams), Molly Parker (Juliet Beck), Janet McTeer (Caroline
Pierce), Paul Hipp (Danny Pierce), Sandra Oh (Kim) and Hal Holbrook
(Isaac Green).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
