<HEADER>
A5983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-ELECTION-UPSET-HNS &LR;      03-23 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-UPSET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LONE VOTE, HIS OWN, COSTS TEXAS POLITICIAN HIS SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It took only one vote to unseat Edwards County
Commissioner James Epperson.
</P>
<P>
   His own.
</P>
<P>
   Epperson faced no opposition in the March 14 Republican primary
in his bid for a second term. Unaware of the consequences, he
decided to vote in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't really have any contested races in our Republican
primary, but we did in the Democratic primary, so I asked an
election judge if I was allowed to vote Democrat without
jeopardizing my status on the Republican ballot,'' he said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer was yes, it wouldn't have any effect, so I voted.
But it did,'' Epperson said from his ranch outside the county seat
of Rocksprings, about 150 miles west of San Antonio
</P>
<P>
   The price of bad advice, Epperson learned this week, is stiff.
According to state election law, because he voted in the Democratic
primary, he cannot run for his own seat as a Republican in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well informed of the law now. I just made a stupid
mistake. That's all it boils down to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Presley Hatley, the Democratic candidate for
Precinct 3 commissioner who made Epperson's vote public, faces no
Republican opposition in November.
</P>
<P>
   State law gives the county Republican Party the right to name a
candidate to replace Epperson on the Nov. 7 general election
ballot, but Jodie Greene, the Edwards County GOP chairwoman,
declined to comment on the party's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party Chairwoman Connie Lees, however, said Greene
has told her that Hatley will likely not get a free ride in the
fall election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a good idea. I like a race where there is a
choice,'' said Lees.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Hatley said she and her husband debated reporting
Epperson after they discovered his signature on the voter roster
for the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're friends with Mr. Epperson, and he's a good commissioner.
We're sorry he didn't' check it out, but politics is politics,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I talked it over, and we decided that if the
situation was reversed, Mr. Epperson would have done the same
thing. If you're running for office, and you can disqualify your
opponent, most of the time you do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatley notified the Republican and Democratic chairwomen of his
discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Secretary of State's election division confirmed
Hatley's contention that Epperson had disqualified himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was just a slipup that he made. Mr. Epperson was a
friend; I don't know if he is now or not,'' said Hatley, who once
worked under Epperson as the county road superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Him being a candidate, I think, he should have checked into
the law a little more before he crossed over to vote. I hope the
friendship survives, but I imagine it will be a sore spot for some
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Politics in Edwards County, population 2,900, is a low-key
affair where partisan lines are not drawn too darkly and where most
political debate is about state or national issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one takes politics too seriously up here. This is a county
where you cross lines to vote, depending on which primary is the
most interesting,'' Lees said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1607EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
