<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BUDDY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     03-23 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDDY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUDDY BOY': HE'S TWITCHY AND SHY; SHE'S ASKING FOR TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By DAVE KEHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Hanlon's ``Buddy Boy'' begins with some grimy
black-and-white images of a plaster Christ suspended on a cross and
then introduces its no less tortured protagonist. Francis (Aidan
Gillen) is a shy stutterer and compulsive self-abuser who lives in
a filth-encrusted apartment in a nameless big city.
</P>
<P>
   His one human connection is Sal (Susan Tyrrell), a one-legged
alcoholic with an unconvincing wig who may or may not be Francis'
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Francis devotes his unhappy life to caring for Sal, lugging her
unconscious body back to the La-Z-Boy when she's had too much to
drink, and preparing her daily meals from the dozens of cans of
processed meat that fill the kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   But an angel has moved in across the street in the form of an
attractive Frenchwoman, Gloria (Emmanuelle Seigner), who loves to
linger in front of her picture window in various degrees of
undress. Francis studies her intently through a hole he has cut in
his wall _ an image that seems meant to evoke Anthony Perkins'
watching Janet Leigh in the room next door in ``Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   As in Hitchcock's film, sexual tension leads to violence, though
``Buddy Boy'' takes a more meandering, metaphorical route. Holding
out the prospect of grace and redemption, Gloria falls improbably
in love with Francis and takes him to bed.
</P>
<P>
   But this development only seems to increase Francis' twitchy
desperation, and soon he has added hallucinations to his collection
of hysterical symptoms. He imagines seeing Gloria, an avowed
vegetarian, feeding on a secret cache of raw, red beef.
</P>
<P>
   Hanlon, who both wrote and directed ``Buddy Boy,'' is working
the curious vein of the sentimental grotesque. As unattractive as
Francis may be, he has been designed as a repository for all of the
viewer's feelings of self-consciousness and self-pity; we are meant
to identify with his status as God's all-purpose, undeserving
victim, and to shed a tear for Francis and ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his victimhood is couched in such absurdly extreme,
cartoonish terms that identification is impossible. Tyrrell, a camp
icon since her boozy turn in John Huston's 1972 ``Fat City,'' plays
Sal in a spray of sloppy laughter and angry outbursts; her
character has no more of a reality component than does her
apartment, a symphony in brown and beige littered with cigarette
butts, empty bottles and half-eaten meals. Even the walls seem to
be sweating something viscous and unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden as he is behind scraggly hair, a moon-shape birthmark and
a downcast, mumbling manner, it is almost impossible to recognize
Gillen as the swaggering sexual predator of the cult British
television series ``Queer as Folk.'' It's the kind of performance
that calls on all of an actor's technical skills and none of his
personality, whereas it's usually the opposite that's most
effective in movies.
</P>
<P>
   Seigner, who can currently be seen as a supernatural being in
``The Ninth Gate,'' has magnificent cheekbones and a look of
perpetual distraction. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BUDDY BOY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Mark Hanlon; director of photography,
Hubert Taczanowski; edited by Hughes Winborne; production designer,
Robert Morris; produced by Cary Woods and Gina Mingacci; released
by Independent Pictures. Running time: 103 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Aidan Gillen (Francis), Emmanuelle Seigner (Gloria) and
Susan Tyrrell (Sal). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Buddy Boy' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It contains sexual situations, graphic violence
and excessive consumption of alcohol. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1608EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5986 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-BOS     03-23 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES FIGHTING BATTLE OVER BILLS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and p coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Democrats are pushing to include
Texas Governor George W. Bush's five-year, $483 billion tax cut
plan as part of the 2001 budget, an idea Democrats have repeatedly
criticized as ``risky'' and too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   It's not expected to pass. And that's just fine with Capitol
Hill Democrats, who don't want the Republican presidential
candidate's tax cut to become law.
</P>
<P>
   What Democrats hope to do is to embarrass Bush and his
congressional supporters. Since most Republicans are pushing a much
smaller tax cut _ in the neigborhood of $150 billion to $200
billion _ Bush's own party faithful would have to vote the idea
down.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about seeing any ground-breaking legislation passed on
Capitol Hill this year, with Congress still bitterly partisan and
mutually suspicious following the impeachment and trial of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Hill has instead become a political playground and
shadow debate stage for the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns of Vice President Al Gore and Bush have begun
meeting with their allies in Congress, making sure their respective
messages are in sync.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign manager Joe Allbaugh was wandering the halls of
Congress Wednesday morning, meeting with party leaders and the
campaign's point people, Senator Paul Coverdell of Georgia and
Representative Roy Blunt of Missouri, both Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore chatted with House Democrats Wednesday, and Gore campaign
director Tony Coelho is set to confer with Senate Democrats
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is ``mainly to keep them in the loop,'' said Coverdell
aide Linda Cox. ``We're also keeping the campaign alerted to
`bumps,' issues that pop up that they might not have been aware
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is enjoying a second honeymoon with congressional
Democrats, members say. After the impeachment debate, there was a
somewhat strained relationship between the White House and Capitol
Hill, but Democrats are now unified behind Gore and are ready to
work hard to make him president, said Representative Richard Neal,
Democrat of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the issues expected to come up in Congress this year are
central themes of the presidential campaign, and both parties are
hoping to use those debates to their respective advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Floor fights over gun control, education, tobacco control, the
environment, the budget, taxes, minimum wage and the so-called
patient's bill of rights are not expected to produce substantial
changes in the law this year. But they do allow both Democrats and
Republicans to shore up the campaign agendas of their parties'
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what's happening in Congress is going to play out on
the presidential trail,'' said Jenny Backus, a spokeswoman for th
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress takes up campaign finance legislation, for
example, Democrats will do their best to coordinate with Gore, so
the vice president can appear to be a leader on the issue, said
Representative Martin T. Meehan, Democrat of Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   And where issues fail, there's always politics. Representative
Edward J. Markey, Democrat of Massachusetts, fought the House Rules
Committee Wednesday to allow him to offer Bush's tax cut plan as an
amendment to a budget priorities bill the House is soon to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans in Congress should be given an opportunity
to vote in favor of a $1.2 trillion tax cut,'' Markey said
sardonically, referring to the 10-year cost of the Bush plan.
Markey intends to make a fuss on the House floor Thursday to force
a vote on the tax plan.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats are planning a similar political strategy and
will soon propose the Bush tax cut to the Senate Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have one clear advantage _ the ability to set the
legislative calendar. Republicans can schedule debates to coincide
with a Bush annoucement, should they wish to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, plan to use well-timed news conferences
and congressional hearings as forums aimed to highlight Gore's
agenda. Wednesday, a half-dozen Latino members of Congress held a
news conference on education, an issue both Gore and Bush say is a
central theme. The members also served to remind Bush, who is
popular among Texas Hispanics, that Bush does not have a lock on
that voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are expected bring up conservative social
issues, such as bans on flag-burning and late-term abortions.
Congress has debated the issues many times and has yet to produce
compromise legislation, but the debates themselves would help Bush
appease the Christian right wing of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things they can do,'' Meehan said. But
``there's no interest in reaching an agreement on some of these
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
