<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HERE ON EARTH': STILL NEVER HAVING TO SAY YOU'RE SORRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Here on Earth,'' with its shameless sob story on teen loss, is
the Best Movie of 1961, lacking only the beautiful and vacant
visages of Troy Donahue and Suzanne Pleshette to make it complete.
A pair of teens finally find each other and fall in love, only to
learn _ sob _ that she's dying of cancer: It could be called ``Love
Story, Too.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is part of a genre so moribund _ suffering young lovers
kept apart by class and, inevitably, tragedy _ that the Pop artist
Roy Lichtenstein, vamping on the Young Romance comics covers of
that period (a perfect pearly tear gliding from the rosy cheek of a
heroine), sent it up before the parents of this movie's young leads
were of consenting age. John Waters, who parodied such fare in
``Hairspray,'' is bored with this brand of filmmaking by now.
</P>
<P>
   The winsome Leelee Sobieski, who looks like Helen Hunt
reincarnated as a Valkyrie, is the down-to-earth Sam, who seems to
live in a small farm town so near in spirit to Lake Woebegon, where
all the women are pleasant and all the men are good-looking, that
Garrison Keillor should get a royalty check.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Klein, who has the swagger of a spoiled young god, is the
rich boy from the other, wealthier side of the tracks. His name is
Kelley, and maybe someone thought it would be funny if the first
names of the protagonists were interchangeable _ as everything else
about them is. Oh, the townies call him Richie _ y'know, after
Richie Rich. Little do they know that behind his bored insouciance
is a poor little rich boy. Only Sam can see through him, though he,
like everyone else in the movie, is transparent.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably canny marketing to remake ``Love Story'' and other
films of its ilk for a generation who didn't grow up fighting to
change the radio station every time that picture-haunting theme
came on. ``Here on Earth'' eliminates that problem by grafting on a
clutch of alt-rock favorites, though the Foo Fighters' band leader,
Dave Grohl, probably won't be too happy at the thought of a whole
generation saying, ``I'll never be able to hear Foo Fighters
again'' after sitting through this film.
</P>
<P>
   Staring thoughtfully into the middle distance, Sobieski looks as
if she is already contemplating better scripts. There's more of a
danger for Klein and his open-faced, blank handsomeness. So far
he's been very well used in films _ particularly when his unformed,
top-of-the-world demeanor is made part of the joke, as it was in
``Election'' and ``American Pie'' _ and he's not closed off as an
actor. But in this movie, he's alternately smug and pouting. The
rest of the actors, including the always welcome Annette O'Toole,
are skilled enough to well up with tears on cue. But their efforts
fail to compensate for the film's many deficits.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HERE ON EARTH'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mark Piznarski; written by Michael Seitzman;
director of photography, Michael D. O'Shea; edited by Robert
Frazen; music by Andrea Morricone; production designer, Dina
Lipton; produced by David T. Friendly; released by Fox 2000
Pictures. Running time: 97 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Chris Klein (Kelley), Leelee Sobieski (Samantha), Josh
Hartnett (Jasper), Michael Rooker (Malcolm Arnold), Annie Corley
(Betsy Arnold), Bruce Greenwood (Earl Cavanaugh) and Annette
O'Toole (Jo Cavanaugh).
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Here on Earth'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes intense romantic clinches and mild
violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
