<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nominees' Next Life
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, two days after it will have either won or lost the
Oscar, M. Night Shyamalan's ``Sixth Sense'' will become the first
of the five best-picture nominees to land on video racks. Next will
be Michael Mann's ``Insider,'' to be released on April 11, then Sam
Mendes' ``American Beauty,'' available on May 9 (but don't expect
the DVD until fall). Warner plans Frank Darabont's ``Green Mile''
for early summer. Lasse Hallstrom's ``Cider House Rules'' is to
arrive in June or July. All but Darabont are nominees for best
director.
</P>
<P>
   April 11 is designated for ``Tumbleweeds,'' with Janet McTeer, a
nominee for best actress; April 18 for ``Boys Don't Cry,'' with
Hilary Swank, one of McTeer's competitors; April 25 for ``Music of
the Heart,'' with Meryl Streep, once again a best-actress nominee.
Spike Jonze's ``Being John Malkovich'' (he's the fifth nominee for
best director) is scheduled for May 2; ``The Straight Story,'' with
Richard Farnsworth, a nominee for best actor, for May 9; ``The End
of the Affair,'' with Julianne Moore, another best-actress nominee,
for May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Skimming other categories, one finds few nominees already on
tape and disc. But down in the documentary feature field lies a
very notable exception: ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' Wim Wenders'
acclaimed celebration of Cuban music as rendered by the
prerevolutionary old guard, which was released by Artisan in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Another strong documentary contender, Nanette Burstein and Brett
Morgen's engrossing ``On the Ropes,'' follows three young boxers
who aspire, stumble and rise again in Brooklyn. The film will be
released on tape and DVD by Winstar on April 25.
</P>
<P>
   Burstein, 29, found her subjects at the New Bed-Stuy Boxing
Center. ``I wanted to learn how to box, actually, so I went out to
this gym because they train women,'' she said. There she found a
social environment. ``It was as much a community center as a boxing
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bed-Stuy's proprietor, chief trainer and father confessor is
Harry Keitt, a former sparring partner of Muhammad Ali. At times in
the film Keitt seems literally to pick up his three fighters _ and
himself _ and carry everybody through very tough times. His
fighters include George Walton, a smiling, soft-spoken young man
who looks and punches like a small Mike Tyson. Walton turns
professional during the film. Noel Santiago, the second fighter, is
an engaging high school boy more in need of discipline and
self-esteem than the thumpings he often gets in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The third boxer is a diminutive, ferociously resilient young
woman named Tyrene Manson. Rocked but not defeated by a dangerous
domestic situation, Manson at one point asks a judge for permission
to leave a courtroom and race to Madison Square Garden for her
Golden Gloves bout at the exact moment he is sentencing her to 4{
to 9 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said no on that occasion, but permission has been
granted for Manson, out of jail on a work-release program, to leave
the state and go to the Oscar ceremony Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Crazy in Alabama &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, a madcap woman named Lucille (Melanie Griffith) cuts
off her husband's head and departs for what she hopes will be an
acting career in Hollywood. In the town she has left there is an
attempt to integrate the whites-only municipal swimming pool, but
that's not of paramount interest to Lucille as she rolls west.
Trying to link her liberation to the civil rights struggle as a
similar expression of freedom, Antonio Banderas' directorial debut
is a stretch, but, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, he
manages ``capably enough to keep the film lively.''
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77; DVD, $24.95. 111 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: March 28.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marcello Mastroianni: I Remember &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``A crazy, stupid idea,'' says Mastroianni about always being
regarded as the archetypal Latin lover. Revealing an irrepressibly
comic outlook, the actor, who died at 72 in 1996, looks back on his
life and career. Yes, there were the films of Fellini and De Sica,
but he would also like to play an elderly Tarzan. Part travelogue,
part biography, part philosophical rumination on cinema and the
actor's art, Anna Maria Tato's documentary about Mastroianni, her
companion for the last 22 years of his life, ``preserves his charm,
his intellect and his splendid body of work'' (Lawrence Van
Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   -1997. Winstar. $89.99; DVD, $29.98. 199 minutes. Italian with
English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Last Night &LR;
</P>
<P>
   We never learn the nature of the impending disaster, but tonight
is everybody's last night on earth. That could start riots and
summon macho superstars, but in Toronto people gather as if it were
New Year's Eve. With her car vandalized, Rita (Sandra Oh) is trying
to contact her husband (David Cronenberg), a gas company executive
who has spent the day leaving reassuring messages on people's
answering machines. Patrick (Don McKellar) is too despondent over a
woman's death to care very much what happens, but he reluctantly
gives Rita a ride and the two try to establish rapport by pouring
out their secrets. As it methodically links up other quirky
Canadians, McKellar's film ``offers itself as a smart,
stiff-upper-lip alternative to a movie like `Armageddon''' (Stephen
Holden).
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Universal. $99.36; DVD, $24.98. 94 minutes. R. Release
date: March 28.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pokemon: The First Movie &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of the popular pocket monsters rally to one another's
defense after evil scientists clone Mew, the rarest Pokemon of them
all, but make him 10 times as large and 50 times as mean. Demanding
to know what his purpose is, the big cat decides he is meant to
rule the world with the help of a cloned Pokemon army in a tale
that is fun to watch at times but whose lure ``is still a secret of
the grammar school set'' (Anita Gates).
</P>
<P>
   -1999. Warner. $26.98; DVD, $24.98. 75 minutes. Closed
captioned. G.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   Four releases are available from Video Artists International:
EILEEN FARRELL, arias from ``Alceste,'' ``Madama Butterfly,''
``Aida,'' ``La Gioconda'' and ``La Forza Del Destiono''; songs by
Gabriel Faure, Claude Debussy, Francis Poulenc and George Gershwin.
Orchestra of Radio-Canada. 1969. $29.95. 45 minutes. CHICAGO
SYMPHONY ORCHESTRA, Historic Telecasts, Vol. 6. Paul Hindemith
conducting his Concert Music for Strings and Brass; Anton
Bruckner's Symphony No. 7, first movement; Academic Festival
Overture by Johannes Brahms. 1963. $24.95. 53 minutes. RENATA
TEBALDI, broadcasts from the Bell Telephone Hour series, 1957-69.
Selections from ``Madama Butterfly,'' ``Tosca,'' ``Adriana
Lecouvreur,'' Cavalleria Rusticana'' and ``La Gioconda.'' Bell
Telephone Hour Orchestra. $24.95. 30 minutes. BENJAMIN BRITTEN WITH
PETER PEARS. Selected songs in rehearsal and performance. CBC
Vancouver Chamber Orchestra. 1962. $29.95 60 minutes. Information
(800) 477-7146.
</P>
<P>
   THE OMEGA CODE. Good and evil fight it out over a cryptogram,
but don't expect sex or anything else R-rated in an otherwise
intense action thriller.
</P>
