<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AFFAIR-FILM-REVIEW-NY     03-23 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFAIR-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A PORNOGRAPHIC AFFAIR': SEX OUT OF SIGHT, BUT NOT MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``A Pornographic Affair,'' one of the two movies that
open the New Directors/New Films festival at the Museum of Modern
Art in Manhattan Friday night, may shock you, but not necessarily
for the expected reasons. It concerns the relationship of two
anonymous, respectable people (Nathalie Baye and Sergi Lopez) who
spend each Thursday afternoon in a Paris hotel room doing something
that dare not speak its name.
</P>
<P>
   If you're anticipating the next ``Last Tango in Paris,'' think
again. ``A Pornographic Affair'' is more like ``When Harry Met
Sally'' remade as a panel discussion on the highfalutin French talk
show ``Apostrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry and Sally were best pals who discovered, almost too late,
a sexual attraction. This made their story a romantic comedy. Elle
and Lui (Her and Him), as our dutiful pornographers are known,
start out as sex partners and then fall in love, which makes ``A
Pornographic Affair'' _ well, what exactly? A movie that takes
itself, and its subject, very seriously indeed.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its earnest intellectualism, this film tells you
everything you already knew about sex but wouldn't have bothered to
ask in the first place, including that, if presented in just the
right way, it can be just as boring as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Baye's character, finding herself single and at loose ends,
places an advertisement in an adult magazine soliciting a man
willing to fulfill a long-standing fantasy of hers. Lopez's
character _ can't they at least have silly dirty-minded pseudonyms,
like real porn stars? _ finds her request compatible with his
tastes, so they meet at a cafe, have a drink and then repair to a
hotel. We never see what happens behind the door.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will either one, in the otherwise candid postmortem
interviews, identify the special practice that binds them together.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this reticence is supposed to make our imaginations run
wild, or expose us for the crass voyeurs we are. Perhaps Elle and
Lui are playing pinochle, or doing the crossword puzzle in Le
Monde. Whatever it is, their esoteric hanky-panky never ruffles the
air of pleasant, faintly melancholy sincerity that they display on
the other side of the door.
</P>
<P>
   Only when they decide to get really crazy and have normal sexual
intercourse (which we are allowed to see, and which is tastefully
cinematic) do they discover any real, risky emotion.
</P>
<P>
   But not, in the end, all that much. ``A Pornographic Affair,''
directed by Frederic Fonteyne, posits an eroticism without heat and
discovers a romantic passion without intensity. Lui and Elle
present themselves to each other and to us entirely without
context.
</P>
<P>
   They seem to chat quite amiably in their cafe (and, for all we
know, in bed), but they never mention their jobs, their friends,
their life histories, or anything else that might make them
recognizable as people. The film operates on the premise that to
suppress such detail is to strip characters to their emotional
essence. But with so little information, it's hard to see what
would draw these people to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, it's impossible to figure out why we should be interested
in them. When the film reaches its, uh, climax, we don't feel the
vicarious longing that would make us care whether they stayed
together or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Pornographic Affair'' is too busy congratulating itself for
its restraint, good taste and edifying absence of prurience to
bother with such mundane concerns. Baye and Lopez are good-humored
and pleasant to watch, but their characters are unable to remember
how long their dalliance lasted, or how many times they did
whatever it was they were doing. Do they even recall what it was?
Clearly, this is an affair to forget. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `A PORNOGRAPHIC AFFAIR' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Frederic Fonteyne; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Philippe Blasband; director of photography, Virginie
Saint-Martin; edited by Chantal Hymans; music by Jeannot Sanavia,
Andre Dziezuk and Marc Mergen; production designer, Veronique
Sacrez; produced by Patrick Quinet; released by Fine Line Features.
Running time: 80 minutes. This film is not rated.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Nathalie Baye (Elle) and Sergi Lopez (Lui). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
