<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6005 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-HUMAN-WIRED-COX     03-23 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMAN-WIRED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yearning to become one with a computer
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kevin Warwick wants to connect with his computer. And
he thinks that other people will want that connection as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sort of feel it in this century,'' says Warwick, a
professor of cybernetics at the University of Reading in England.
``There's a buzz about it and a willingness to accept this kind of
thing that you wouldn't have seen if people had read about it 10
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The connection that Warwick yearns for is physical. Sometime
next year, surgeons will implant a glass-enclosed, 1-inch computer
circuit in Warwick's upper left arm. The circuit will be tied
directly into the nerve bundle that runs from Warwick's brain into
his arm and down to his left hand. In effect, the implanted circuit
will act as a wiretap, monitoring his body's electric signals and
transmitting them wirelessly to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The new implant will be a more sophisticated version of a chip
that was implanted in Warwick's arm for nine days in 1998. Warwick
expects to keep the second implant for as long as two weeks, and he
has ambitious research plans to pursue. For example, he wants to
give himself a sixth sense: sonar, the navigational system employed
by bats, porpoises and submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Warwick, 46, plans to carry a portable sonar system on his chest
and allow the system to send electric signals to the chip implanted
in his arm. The chip will in turn relay those sonar signals to
Warwick's brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll feel that electronic signal in my body somewhere,
although I'm not sure how,'' he predicts. ``So when I look around
and see something in front of me, I will also be feeling the data
input from the sonar system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, I will train myself how to interpret that data, so
that when I have my eyes closed, people will be able to put things
in front of me and I'll be able to tell if anything is there, just
as a bat can. It will be like adding an extra sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Warwick's wife, Irena, may also be equipped with a wireless
implant, allowing the two to exchange bodily data via the Internet.
Since emotions also are expressed in electric currents in the body,
Warwick expects the implants to pick up pain, boredom, joy, sexual
arousal and other feelings and to communicate that data from one
spouse to the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can change who you are and who you think you are,'' he says
of the implants. ``We will not be merely human, but something
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic implants are finding other applications, with
apparently willing human subjects. Gen-Etics, an Italian company,
offers to implant a special computer chip in the bodies of
celebrities, business people and others who might be targets of
kidnapping. When activated, the chip becomes a human version of the
Lojack system for recovery of stolen cars. The kidnap victim's
location can be pinpointed by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   According to company spokesmen, the technology was developed by
Mossad, the Israeli intelligence agency. They claim that more than
40 people have been equipped with the chip, although they decline
for security reasons to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   Medical researchers, meanwhile, are implanting special monitors
in patients who are prone to congestive heart failure. Once the
system is operational, information about the heart's performance
will be sent daily from the patient's body through the Internet to
a doctor's office, where the data will be monitored for
abnormalities. Other researchers are implanting a form of
electronic pacemaker in human brains to help treat epilepsy.
Similar brain implants also are being tested as a way to treat
severe depression.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, such scenarios have raised concerns about
privacy and about the eventual use of implanted chips by
governments and others to monitor individuals. For example, law
enforcement officials could use implanted chips to monitor sexual
arousal in those previously convicted of sex crimes. Warwick
himself has warned that a direct link between brain and computer
could lead to computer control of human beings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that concern, Warwick plans an experiment that would
give a computer temporary control over his fingers
</P>
<P>
   ``When I move my hand or finger, the implant will pick up those
electric signals and send them straight away to the computer,''
where they'll be recorded, Warwick notes. Later, he plans to see
what happens when the computer replays that recorded signal into
his central nervous system. He expects that the signal sent by the
computer will cause his hand or fingers to move involuntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we link up more and more closely with technology,'' Warwick
says, ``we will see a conflict between those who are human and
those who have become superhuman. Some of us will have extra
senses, a superior ability to communicate, access to far greater
processing power, the ability to think part machine, part human.
Your power will come with being a node in a computer network,
rather than the individual that we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
