u w BC-AIDS-FUNDS24-COX     03-23 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUNDS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIDS FIGHT SHOULD FOCUS ON PREVENTION, CONGRESSMAN SAYS
 &HT;    By ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prevention is ``dead last'' in the nation's fight
against AIDS, Rep. Tom Coburn said Thursday as he released a
congressional audit of federal HIV and AIDS programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must ask ourselves, why are we failing to halt or even slow
down this epidemic?'' said the Oklahoma Republican, who asked the
General Accounting Office to find whether racial, gender and
geographic funding disparities existed within the Ryan White CARE
Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is obvious,'' Coburn continued. ``Our prevention
strategy has failed. It has failed primarily because it has ignored
successful interventions that have historically been utilized to
curtail other contagious diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Congress and the executive branch must strengthen laws
to require HIV-positive people to notify their partners that they
are infected. ``We also must empower individuals to make the right
choices rather than enabling them to engage in activities that are
guaranteed to put them at risk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any epidemic, the most important thing is to prevent the
next person from being infected,'' Coburn said at a Capitol Hill
news conference. ``Until we develop an effective HIV prevention
system, we are going to continue to increase the dollars needed
each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the $10 billion meted out by the government last year for
AIDS spending, less than 10 percent was used for HIV prevention,
Coburn said. He said more money needs to be spent on prevention
because 40,000 HIV infections occur each year, a number that has
remained steady over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report examined three federal programs that fund
prevention, health care and other assistance for HIV and AIDS
victims: the Ryan White Care Act, grants from the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), and grants by the Housing
Opportunities for Persons Living with AIDS (HOPWA) program.
</P>
<P>
   The audit found that Ryan White Care Act was serving blacks,
Hispanics and women in higher proportions than their share of the
AIDS population. The act funds health clinics treating low-income
AIDS patients and to train people caring for HIV-infected
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   However, the audit also cited a recent national study showing
that blacks and Hispanics were less likely than whites to receive
appropriate medical attention and drug treatment for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The audit found that the CDC funds supported a wide range of
state and local HIV prevention activities. It said that two-thirds
of the HOPWA funds were used for housing assistance for AIDS and
HIV victims.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO found that while the vast majority of people with AIDS
live in urban areas, the number of cases is growing in rural areas.
Treatment funds under the Care Act are reaching rural victims in
proportion to the number of victims living in those areas, it
found.
</P>
<P>
   But Coburn said rural HIV and AIDS victims are being
shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the built-in funding disparities, those living with
HIV and AIDS in rural America have limited medical and social
services and oftentimes may have to travel to urban areas to
receive proper care,'' said Coburn, a practicing physician who has
treated AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
