<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-BOXING-MOVIES-THEN-AND-NOW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING MOVIES GET BACK THEIR PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Jimmy Smits in
a scene from ``Price of Glory.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Boxing and Hollywood have been happy sparring partners for more
than half a century.
 &HT;    In fact, movieland's relationship with pugilism has been long
and fruitful. More than 400 movies have focused on ``the sweet
science'' of fisticuffs, many of them now classics.
 &HT;    And still Hollywood can't seem to get enough. After a down
period for most of the 1990s, these days boxing movies are back in
force.
 &HT;    Last year's ``The Hurricane,'' based on the story of real-life
contender Ruben ``Hurricane'' Carter and his struggle against
unjust imprisonment, drew its share of uppercuts for its
still-in-dispute accuracy. But few challenged the title performance
by Denzel Washington, who has been nominated for an Oscar as Best
Actor for his efforts.
 &HT;    In January, ``Play It to the Bone'' cast Woody Harrelson and
Antonio Banderas as a couple of bush-league fighters who somehow
get a chance at a big-time payday. Although generally well
reviewed, the film had only a short theatrical life and is headed
for the video-store shelves.
 &HT;    Boxing is again at center ring in ``Price of Glory,'' which will
open March 31. Starring former ``NYPD Blue'' mainstay Jimmy Smits,
this one differs from past fight movies in focusing on a Hispanic
family of pugilists.
 &HT;    Smits plays Arturo Ortega, a former fighter who never made it to
the top. Instead, he pours his passion for the ring into his three
sons, obsessively shaping them into fighting machines in a quest
for the title he wasn't able to win himself.
 &HT;    Written by Phil Berger, former boxing writer for The New York
Times and author of biographies of Joe Frazier, Larry Holmes and
Mike Tyson, ``Price of Glory'' began as a play that was never
produced. Its story line derives from Berger's experience covering
boxing, however, and he claims that it's closely grounded in
reality.
 &HT;    ``The tale of a fighter who tries valiantly, with mixed results,
to micromanage his sons' future careers is all too familiar,''
Berger says. ``It happened when former heavyweight champion Joe
Frazier tried without success to turn his son Marvis into a mirror
image of himself.''
 &HT;    Current super-featherweight champion Floyd Mayweather is
embroiled in a dispute with his manager/trainer/father, Berger
adds, and the antagonism between light-heavyweight champion Roy
Jones Jr. and his manager/father reached dangerous proportions.
 &HT;    ``Roy began carrying a gun in fear of his father, who had gone
so far as to shoot his son's dog,'' Berger says. ``When you're
dealing with families, there's a lot of emotion invested and the
relationships are very complex.''
 &HT;    The situation may be familiar, but few boxing films have
previously featured Hispanic fighters _ a situation bound to
change, Berger says, because Latin fighters are increasingly
dominant at nearly every level of boxing.
 &HT;    ``The decision to make them Latin was made because they are the
latest line of immigrants to try to win the lottery in the fight
game,'' he says.
 &HT;    Moctesuma Esparza, producer of the $10 million ``Price of
Glory,'' hastens to add that the film isn't about Hispanic boxing
as such.
 &HT;    ``It's not so much a boxing film or a Latino movie,'' Esparza
says. ``It's an American story, like `Rocky.'''
 &HT;    Smits agrees, and argues that the movie should appeal to any
audience.
 &HT;    ``Our story has a universal theme,'' he says. ``It's about
dreams being frustrated and not being achieved. The family's name
happens to be Ortega.
 &HT;    ``How's that different from the Irish in the United States in
the 1940s, or the Rocky Graziano or Rocky Balboa stories in the
movies?'' Smits continues. ``They're all looking for the American
dream, which can be captured inside the confines of the ring.''
 &HT;    It's boxing as metaphor, Smits says, and it's been remarkably
durable.
 &HT;    ``That's why America loves boxing movies,'' he says. ``It's the
conquest, the guy grappling for a leg up. It's the immigrants'
story. And all those elements are there in our picture.''
 &HT;    Director Carlos Avila, making his movie debut, says the film is
right on the cutting edge, given how many young Hispanic fighters
are seeking to punch their way out of the ghetto these days.
 &HT;    ``The father's obsession is the most tragic,'' he says. ``He
walks a fine line. He wants to give them a future by giving them
boxing expertise _ for him it's a gift of love. So our story is the
father's journey as he finally learns to let his sons make their
own decision.''
 &HT;    Both Smits and Berger say they grew up on classic boxing
pictures such as ``Body and Soul'' (l947), with John Garfield as a
Jewish fighter whose mother wants him to get a decent job,
``Champion'' (l949), starring Kirk Douglas, and ``Somebody Up There
Likes Me'' (l956), in which a youthful Paul Newman played the
real-life Italian fighter Rocky Graziano.
 &HT;    But two more recent films provide the context for ``Price of
Glory'' and all the other recent boxing films: ``Rocky'' (l976),
written by and starring Sylvester Stallone, resurrected the genre
with its romantic, inspirational story of a Philadelphia pug who
has big dreams, while Martin Scorsese's ``Raging Bull'' (l980)
provided a grim, almost pathological look at the real-life champion
Jake La Motta (Robert De Niro).
 &HT;    And more are to come _ even now, actor/rapper Will Smith is
using his star power to try to win his dream role in a biopic
focused on the legendary Muhammad Ali.
 &HT;    That's not surprising, Smits says, since boxing movies offer
actors a chance to play dynamic characters in a naturally dramatic
context. Boxers are often seriously flawed characters, too, which
appeals to actors such as Smits, who has previously played more
than his share of too-good-to-be-true heroes, most notably in the
television series ``L.A. Law'' and ``NYPD Blue.''
 &HT;    ``It's not always about playing the knight in shining armor,''
the actor says. ``TV audiences have seen me in this idealistic
lawyer/cop genre. Ortega is more like an antihero _ he believes
what he's doing is right, and it's all for the love of his kids.''
 &HT;    In short, Smits finds in ``Price of Glory'' what actors,
directors and screenwriters have always found in the boxing ring:
pride, pain and, above all, humanity.
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Price of Glory,'' consult the
official Web site at www.priceofglory.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
