<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6010 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BRAIN-MAIN-COX     03-23 2257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meld of mind, machine may transform our lives
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The future has many birthplaces. Part of it is
taking shape in the cramped and cluttered laboratory of John
Chapin.
</P>
<P>
   Chapin and his team wired the brains of lab rats directly to a
computer, giving the animals an ability unknown to human beings.
</P>
<P>
   When the rats got thirsty, they would use a robotic arm to bring
them water. That kind of task has become almost second nature to
lab rats, but these particular animals did it with flair. They
operated the device with their minds alone, moving it merely by
thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people first heard about this work, I'd get e-mails
wondering whether people could use a mind-controlled robot to mow
their lawns,'' jokes Chapin, a neurobiologist. ``But my mind worked
differently. I was thinking about a robot that could bring me a
beer.''
</P>
<P>
   By physically linking a living brain to a computer and then
allowing the two to communicate, Chapin has broken down an
important barrier between the animate and inanimate worlds. In a
step that sounds like something out of science fiction, he also has
given a living mind the power to directly affect the outside world
without having to use the body in which it is housed.
</P>
<P>
   He's hardly a lone researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of scientists around the world, working quietly in
fields as varied as linguistics, biology, chaos and robotics, are
in their own ways blurring the boundaries that once separated
``wetware'' _ the living brain _ from the hardware of silicon-based
computers. At the furthest frontier, some scientists are even
building computers out of living brain cells, literally fusing
silicon with life itself.
</P>
<P>
   Their research represents a looming revolution, the next
world-changing generation in computer science. It promises to
produce computers that seem much more human and lifelike, and less
like machines. It also will transform the relationship between
human beings and computers. They won't be tools that we operate
with our hands, as we do a hammer or a car. Instead they will
become almost a part of us, intimately linked to our minds and
bodies and greatly augmenting human abilities to think and
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   At Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Ohio, for example, the
military's Alternative Control Technology Laboratory has
experimented with systems that allow pilots to ``fly by thought.''
By controlling their brain waves, human subjects at the laboratory
can steer a flight simulator left or right, up or down, a skill
that most people at the lab master in only an hour.
</P>
<P>
   In England, Kevin Warwick, a cybernetics professor at the
University of Reading, had a computer chip surgically implanted in
his left arm two years ago. The chip communicated by radio waves
with the computer that runs Warwick's office building and in
essence made Warwick a living node in the computer's network. The
computer monitored the professor's passage into and around the
building, opening doors for him, turning on his computer as he
approached, even greeting him by name as he walked through the
front door.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (experience) changed my mind-set quite a bit,'' Warwick
says. ``I felt as if the computer became a part of me, and I became
a part of the computer. And I was quite comfortable with that.
There was an affinity there.''
</P>
<P>
   When the implant was removed after nine days, Warwick recalls
feeling an odd sense of disappointment at being disconnected from
the network. He is planning to repeat the experiment next year,
this time with a more sophisticated implant capable of a wider
range of communications. Among other things, he plans to use the
device to give himself a sixth sense, in addition to the five given
him by nature.
</P>
<P>
   With a computer chip in his arm, Warwick refers to himself as a
cyborg. The term was coined in the '60s by NASA scientists and has
since become a staple of science fiction novels and movies. In a
cyborg, computer hardware has become so much a part of a human
being that it creates a new species _ part machine, part human _
with impressive new powers. The title character of the movie
``RoboCop''would fit that definition, as would the Borgs in the
``Star Trek'' TV series.
</P>
<P>
   However, some theorists in computer science argue that cyborgs
are not some sci-fi fantasy and already walk among us by the
millions. They believe that a person with a cell phone and beeper
on his belt and a Palm Pilot in his hand has attained cyborg
status.
</P>
<P>
   To many others, that's still a stretch. They see their
electronic gizmos as tools, not as an integral part of themselves.
But the cyborg description will become far less strained if
researchers in the growing field of wearable computing are proven
right. They are trying to tear down the second major barrier
between human beings and their electronic assistants: the size and
weight of computers.
</P>
<P>
   The world's first modern computer _ ENIAC, for the Electronic
Numerical Integrator and Computer _ was built in 1946 just a few
miles south of Chapin's lab in Philadelphia. ENIAC consisted of
almost 18,000 vacuum tubes, weighed 30 tons and took up 1,800
square feet. Since then, computers have gotten a lot smaller,
lighter and more powerful. IBM's Thinkpad laptop is 30,000 times
faster than ENIAC; at barely 6 pounds, it is also 10,000 times
lighter.
</P>
<P>
   As that trend continues, computers will become extremely
portable and powerful. Human beings won't need a computer chip
implanted in their body to experience the intimate relationship
with computers described by Warwick.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, every morning they would don a lightweight, unobtrusive
computer just as they now slip on a wristwatch or tuck a wallet in
their pocket. That computer would give them full-time wireless
access to the Internet and to other human beings equipped with
wearables, as well as to e-mail, cell phone and other services. At
no waking moment would they be disconnected. Like Warwick in his
office building, they would become individual nodes connected full
time to a vast computer network, but in this case the network would
be shared by millions of other people.
</P>
<P>
   Wearables are already used in the military and industry. Through
its high-tech Land Warrior program, the U.S. Army will equip a
platoon of soldiers with wearable systems for war-fighting
exercises this summer. It plans to deploy 34,000 units in the field
within the next few years. Businesses are buying wearables to let
employees who are out of the office or on the factory floor have
fast, easy access to a computer database or the Internet. As the
wearable product is refined through research and experience,
companies hope to eventually produce the units for sale and use as
a consumer product.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mann, a pioneer in wearable computing and a professor at
the University of Toronto, has been building and using his own
wearable computers since he was a high school student in Canada.
Like Warwick, he calls himself a cyborg. In fact, Mann says that in
the 20 years he has worn computers, he has experienced a powerful
synergy between human being and silicon, which he calls
``humanistic intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience, the human being and computer become elements
of each other's feedback loop,'' Mann explains. ``They support and
extend each other and create something new.''
</P>
<P>
   If cyborgs such as Mann represent the human being augmented with
machinelike powers, they have a close counterpart in the inanimate
world _ the machine equipped with humanlike powers. That's the
third major barrier now under attack: making computers more like
people.
</P>
<P>
   To some researchers, giving computers a more human ``feel'' is a
way to make the computers friendlier and less intimidating to
users. Researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology are
working on ``affective computing'' _ computing that uses human
emotion as a tool. If the computer senses its human user getting
exasperated or angry, for example, it might employ the same
frustration-reducing tactics that a human co-worker would use. It
might apologize or suggest that the user take a break for a few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, software engineers are creating humanlike characters
that are capable of interacting with human beings, asking and
answering questions, commenting on the weather, even flirting. They
are like robots, but without physical bodies. Instead of operating
in the physical world, they will live and work on the Internet,
serving as guides and hosts on commercial Web sites. The characters
are programmed to have personal histories and individual quirks,
just like human beings, and according to their creators are
``emotionally and socially intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, that illusion of humanity is still crude. Steer
the conversation away from a software creature's programming and
its artificial nature quickly becomes apparent. The irony is, it
probably doesn't matter. The human subconscious turns out to be
easily fooled by anything that seems the slightest bit human.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way that people relate with the computer is fundamentally
social,'' says Clifford Nass of Stanford University, who has
conducted considerable research in human-computer interaction. ``We
treat computers as if they were people. Everyone knows it's a
machine. No one thinks a computer is a person. But subconsciously
they can't help treating the computer as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Nass says even computer experts who know better fall prey to the
illusion that the computer is human. It seems that millions of
years of evolution did not equip us to distinguish between what's
human and what isn't, at least on a subconscious level. It just
wasn't a necessary skill because, until now, anything that seemed
human actually was. As a result, our subconscious is easily fooled.
</P>
<P>
   The tendency to project human thoughts and emotions onto
inanimate objects will become even more pronounced as scientists
move closer to building a computer with humanlike intelligence.
That task has long been the Holy Grail of computer science, and
many experts still believe it's unattainable, at least by
traditional means.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of that task may be hard to accept in an era when
computers are unlocking the secrets of the human genetic code and
trouncing Garry Kasparov, acclaimed as the greatest human chess
player in history. So aren't computers already smarter than human
beings?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is no, not even close. Although a computer can
multiply 427 by 62 far faster than any human, even the most
powerful supercomputers have a hard time with mundane tasks that
human beings perform instinctively, without struggle. The classic
example is pattern recognition, the ability to pick out an object
from a crowded visual field.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, my desk right now is very cluttered,'' explains
Joel Davis of the U.S. Office of Naval Research, based in
Arlington, Va. ``I could take this pencil here in my hand, lay it
on my desk and mix things up a bit, so that it's partially hidden
under some papers. Now, a Cray (supercomputer) couldn't find that
pencil, but my 4-year-old daughter, she could find it easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe that the key to human intelligence _ the
difference between Davis' daughter and the Cray _ lies in
architecture. The human brain is a network of as many as 100
billion neurons, with any single neuron connected to as many as
10,000 other neurons, and with each connection varying in
intensity. The number of possible combinations within that tangled
neural network is immense, which makes the human mind very
flexible.
</P>
<P>
   A Cray supercomputer, on the other hand, has a far simpler
architecture. It solves a problem by a rigid step-by-step process
that precludes creativity and imagination.
</P>
<P>
   So Davis and others at the frontiers of computer science are
trying to use nature as a model. That approach has many
subspecialties and many names: bioengineering, biomimicry,
biomechanics. They all assume that the way to make computers and
other machines more powerful is to make them more lifelike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say that you can make an airplane fly faster
by gluing feathers on its wings,'' Davis says. ``But I do believe
that biology can do things that we can't do yet electronically, and
that's where the answer lies.''
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of that approach, scientists are building artificial
neural networks and teaching them to operate as real neural
networks do in the human brain. A few scientists are even taking
that approach to its most far out and literal extension: Instead of
building computers that act like living brain cells, they are
building computers out of brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ditto, a Georgia Tech researcher in neurosilicon computing,
leads a team that has built a simple adding machine out of the
neurons of a leech. In five years, he predicts, his team will have
built a much more complex machine out of living rat neurons grown
on a sheet of silicon. Such a computer might be taught to think as
living brains do.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds like something out of Mary Shelley's
``Frankenstein,'' but Ditto rushes to reject the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're building something out of living body
parts,'' Ditto says. ``Well, OK, actually it is. It is a little
Frankensteiny, I admit. But we're not trying to create a new life
form that's going to go out and do evil. We just want to build a
living computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
