<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANNA BET? OSCAR ODDS A TANGLE OF FAME, MONEY AND BUZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the nominations for the 72nd annual Academy Awards were
announced in mid-February, they were generally thought to
constitute the levelest Oscar playing field in a generation _ with
four of the five best picture nominees having an equal shot at
winning.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the vast establishment of movie pundits,
analysts and soothsayers that spends six weeks every year
handicapping Hollywood's great race has dramatically changed its
tune.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is directly related to the commodity that Hollywood
holds sacred above all else: money.
</P>
<P>
   According to Entertainment Weekly, both ``The Insider'' and
``The Sixth Sense'' have virtually dropped out of the best picture
sweepstakes: ``The Insider'' because its nomination has done
nothing for its moribund box-office; ``The Sixth Sense'' because it
has continued to spin money like it's going out of style since its
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The wisdom here is that Oscar voters have no respect for a movie
that's perceived to be a flop, no matter how good it may be; and
they believe that their highest honor has no business going to a
genre picture (a horror movie at that) that's such an ongoing
audience phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Miramax has spent so much money advertising ``The
Cider House Rules'' _ which won none of the earlier pre-Oscar
awards and seemed a surprise nominee in this category _ that it has
steadily moved to the front of the pack right next to ``American
Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   And since the lightweight ``The Green Mile'' has no chance, the
best-picture Oscar race now looks like a photo-finish between
``Cider House'' and ``American Beauty,'' with their studios _
Miramax and DreamWorks _ trying to outspend each other in a flood
of last-minute trade ads. (It's a repeat of their competition last
year with ``Shakespeare in Love'' and ``Saving Private Ryan.'')
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you're right. It's crazy _ and something of an insult to
the 6,000 members of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and
Sciences who vote on this thing. Are they really so shallow that
they're influenced by such considerations? Would an intelligent
professional filmmaker not vote for what he considered the best
picture because it was a box-office disappointment? Would he vote
for one movie over another simply because he'd seen more
self-congratulatory trade ads for it?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, apparently, is yes. It's what makes the Oscars such
a poor judge of long-term motion-picture quality _ and so much
tawdry fun for office pools across the country and around the
world. And the task is not to pick what should win, but what will
win _ based on a zillion influences acting on the small band of
Southern Californians who have access to a ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Blowing off the 12 months of accumulated dust from my crystal
ball, here is how I think the vote will go:
</P>
<P>
   Best picture: ``The Insider,'' with its riveting drama and
devastating warning of the dangers of a corporate-run world, still
strikes me as the most important film of the year. But it failed to
capture the Zeitgeist of the time, and ``American Beauty'' did.
Something about this portrait of suburban angst speaks to the
collective unconsciousness in a way that defies analysis. Since
``American Beauty'' also captured the largest number of nominations
(a feat matched by 15 of the last 16 best picture winners), it is
sure to edge ahead of ``The Cider House Rules'' to become the first
non-period best picture since 1991's ``Silence of the Lambs.'' The
winner: ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Best director: Since best picture and best director invariably
match up except for once a decade or so, and since they split last
year between ``Shakespeare'' and ``Ryan's'' director Steven
Spielberg, it's not likely to happen again this soon. Especially
since ``Cider House'' director Lasse Hallstrom has been getting
less credit for the film's success than John Irving's screenplay
and his tenacity in getting the film made. And, rightly or wrongly,
the success of ``American Beauty'' is regarded as the triumph of a
directorial vision. The winner: Sam Mendes for ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Best actor: The front-runner had been Denzel Washington for
``The Hurricane.'' But that film has been getting bad buzz lately,
mainly because it has been reported that its ``true'' story was
wildly fictionalized to make its character a martyr, with all the
complexities of his character and background filtered out. So now,
except for Sean Penn's cad of a jazz musician in ``Sweet and
Lowdown'' (which London oddsmakers rate a 33-1 long shot),
Washington has competition from Kevin Spacey (``American Beauty''),
Russell Crowe (``The Insider'') and even 79-year-old Richard
Farnsworth (``The Straight Story''). I think Spacey deserves it,
but since Crowe has the most pre-award wins, and this could be the
only place to honor ``The Insider,'' he would seem to be the
stronger of the alternatives. The winner: Russell Crowe for ``The
Insider.''
</P>
<P>
   Best actress: This category is regarded as the only sure thing
in the acting races. Hilary Swank's inspired male-impersonation in
``Boy's Don't Cry'' has swept most of the important pre-awards, and
she's the only nominee that Vegas oddsmakers have rated at even
money. Still, the magical Annette Bening of ``American Beauty'' is
nine months pregnant, she's half of Hollywood's foremost power
couple, and her husband, Warren Beatty, is getting the prestigious
Irving Thalberg Award at the ceremony. So my suicidal impulse is to
believe the voters will go for a huge upset here, and make it a
banner evening for the couple. Janet McTeer of ``Tumbleweeds,''
Julianne Moore of ``The End of the Affair'' and Meryl Streep of
``Music of the Heart'' won't figure. The winner: Annette Bening for
``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Best supporting actor: If ever an actor deserved to take home
this prize, it's 11-year-old Haley Joel Osment of ``The Sixth
Sense.'' This extraordinary film works solely off the eerie
believability of his performance. Not since ``The Miracle Worker''
has a child actor been this impressive, or this crucial to the
success of a big film. But my guess is that the voters will not be
able to resist rewarding the spectacle of Hollywood's biggest star,
Tom Cruise, slumming as a supporting player in the arty
``Magnolia,'' even though he's the weakest link in the film's
ensemble and his male-chauvinist character is not a bit believable.
Michael Caine (``The Cider House Rules''), Michael Clarke Duncan
(``The Green Mile'') and Jude Law (``The Talented Mr. Ripley'')
haven't a prayer. The winner: Tom Cruise for ``Magnolia.''
</P>
<P>
   Best supporting actress: Like Osment, Chloe Sevigny of ``Boys
Don't Cry'' deserves to win in this category, simply because her
movie completely rests on the believability of her performance _
and she pulls it off. But the competition is unusually stiff from
Toni Collette (``The Sixth Sense''), Angelina Jolie (``Girl,
Interrupted''), Samantha Morton (``Sweet and Lowdown'') and
Catherine Keener (``Being John Malkovich'') playing, respectively,
a devoted mother, a mental patient, a deaf-mute and a temptress _
all Oscar-favorite roles. Still, I'm feeling optimistic. The
winner: Chloe Sevigny.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the Oscar races, France's ``East-West'' is exactly
the kind of epic period love story that Oscar traditionally finds
irresistible; ``Buena Vista Social Club'' was by far the year's
highest profile and most popular documentary feature; and the
year's biggest hit, ``Star Wars _ Episode 1: the Phantom Menace,''
should pick up status for best sound, sound-effects editing and
visual effects (unless the Academy is in the mood to snub perpetual
outsider George Lucas, and gives these prizes to the
slightly-less-deserving ``The Matrix'').
</P>
<P>
   The best original screenplay award will go to ``Being John
Malkovich,'' since, whatever you may think of it, it was definitely
original, and this seems the appropriate place to honor that fact.
The best adapted screenplay and best score will likely go to ``The
Cider House Rules,'' as consolation prizes for missing best picture
and director.
</P>
<P>
   The cinematography statue will go to 73-year-old legend Conrad
L. Hall for ``American Beauty''; editing will go to that same
film's Tariq Anwar; costume design and makeup to ``Topsy-Turvy'';
art direction to ``The Talented Mr. Ripley''; and song to ``You'll
Be in My Heart'' from Disney's animated ``Tarzan.''
</P>
<P>
   Already confirmed for lifetime achievement awards are Poland's
master director Andrzej Wajda; and producer-director-writer-star
Beatty, from whom the assembly is expecting, if not the
announcement of a presidential candidacy, at least some profound
and possibly emotional utterance on the artistic responsibility of
their business.
</P>
<P>
   Moving things along this year on Oscar night will be host Billy
Crystal, who is regarded as the best Oscar master of ceremonies
since Johnny Carson retired. Thus, we hope the show will be a big
improvement over last year's stiff, tedious and often tasteless
affair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
