<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, March 24. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POPE-HOLYLAND (Jerusalem) _ Standing before the ashes of death
camp victims in the candlelit shadows of Israel's Holocaust
memorial, a visibly moved Pope John Paul II said Thursday that his
church was ``deeply saddened'' by Christian persecution of Jews
through the centuries. (Summary from wires) By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1,2, and map.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA (Nayla, India) _ In this dusty village, President
Clinton listened Thursday to heartfelt stories of women's struggles
for a better life and told them they are proof that democracy can
conquer poverty and inequality, even if that journey is slow.
(Summary from wires) By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EMAIL (Washington) _ The Justice Department has launched
a criminal inquiry into White House computer breakdowns that made
it impossible to search thousands of incoming e-mails in response
to congressional subpoenas. The existence of the criminal probe was
revealed in papers filed by the White House counsel with the U.S.
District Court for the District of Columbia in connection with a
civil case there involving the conservative-oriented legal
organization Judicial Watch. (Summary from wires) By David Johnston
and Mark Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MD-GUNS (Annapolis, Md.) _ Amid growing public and political
pressure for stronger gun control laws, Maryland's state Senate put
aside legislative tradition Thursday and bypassed a key opposition
committee to bring to debate Gov. Parris N. Glendening's proposal
for mandatory locks on all new handguns. The bill would enact one
of the toughest laws in the country, mandating trigger locks this
year, integral locks in three years and an annual monitoring of gun
technology with an eye to making Maryland a pioneer in requiring
``smart gun'' limitations by which only a lawful owner would be
able to fire new weapons. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN (Washington) _ Sen. John McCain on Thursday cast himself
as a vigorous campaigner for the Republican congressional majority
and insisted he was ''not interested in harming'' Gov. George W.
Bush's candidacy. At the same time, the Arizona senator left the
door slightly open for another presidential run of his own four
years from now. In an hour-long interview about his political
plans, McCain acknowledged several times that he was walking a
``very careful line'' in trying to be loyal to his party while
still keeping faith with the millions of new voters his insurgency
drew into the Republican primaries. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-ALLIANCE (Undated) _ First Alliance Corp. of Irvine,
Calif., a nationwide home equity lender facing a host of consumer
and regulatory lawsuits accusing it of deceptive sales practices,
has filed for bankruptcy protection. By Diana Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT15.
</P>
<P>
   MARGIN-TRADING (Undated) _ Borrowing money to buy stocks has
become immensely popular among individual investors today. And who
can blame them? When stock prices are rising, the biggest gains go
to those who buy shares on borrowed money. When stock prices are
falling, however, borrowing to buy stocks is an expensive and
highly risky business. While recent tremors in some formerly hot
market sectors may have awakened some investors to this unhappy
reality, market regulators are growing concerned that the recent
surge in investor indebtedness, which has been greatest at online
firms, reflects the participation of many people who do not
understand how dangerous stock market debt can be. By Gretchen
Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FRUITFLY-GENOME (Pittsburgh) _ Opening a new window into the
mysteries of animal design and the nature of life, biologists
described here Thursday how they had decoded almost the entire
genetic rulebook for making the fruit fly, an organism whose study
is deeply interwoven with the progress of modern biology. The
achievement marks a major milestone toward completing the sequence
of the human genome because it seems to validate the high-risk
decoding strategy chosen by Dr. J. Craig Venter of Celera Corp. By
Nicholas Wade (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ An important piece of the global
warming picture has come into clearer focus with a confirmation by
government scientists that the world's oceans have soaked up much
of the warming of the last half century, in effect delaying its
full effect on climate. This delaying effect, which had been
predicted but not demonstrated, was proven by analysis of 5.1
million measurements of temperature patterns in the top two miles
of ocean waters around the world from the mid-1950s to the
mid-1990s. By William K. Stevens. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-VIRUS (New York) _ To cut chances of a repeat of last year's
outbreak of the West Nile virus, state, city and county health
officials on Thursday launched the first phase of a concerted
attack on mosquitoes, specifically on a city-loving species, Culex
pipiens, that breeds in sewers, seeks meals in backyards and
bedrooms, and is the link known to carry the virus from birds to
people. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
