<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-SERIES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION BUSINESS, TECHNOLOGY AND LIFESTYLE EDITORS
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS THAT WILL TRANSFORM OUR LIVES/A four-part series
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of scientists around the world are working quietly in
fields as varied as linguistics, biology, chaos and robotics and in
their own ways are blurring the boundaries that once separated
``wetware'' _ the living brain _ from the hardware of silicon-based
computers. Their research represents a looming revolution, the next
world-changing generation in computer science. Computers of the
future will become almost a part of us, intimately linked to our
minds and bodies and greatly augmenting human abilities to think
and communicate. Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Jay
Bookman explores the evolution of these new computers in a
four-part series. Here is an outline of the series. Each part will
move in the Business and Lifestyle wires. If you have questions or
need assistance, please call the CoxNet desk in Atlanta at 404
526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   PART ONE
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Thursday, March 23)
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN-MAIN _ The boundary blurs between humans and computers.
(Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HUMANS-WIRED _ Professor Kevin Warrick, professor of cybermetics
at the University of Reading in England, seeks the ultimate plug-in
_ a computer circuit inserted into his body that is connected to
his nervous systems and transmits wireless signals to a computer.
(Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   RATS-WIRED _ Scientists at MCP Hahnemann University in
Philadelphia have given laboratory rats the ability to move a
robotic arm with their minds. Their research is a step in helping
paralyzed or quaraplegic humans regain control of a limb. (Bookman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   PART TWO
</P>
<P>
   (Will move Friday, March 24)
</P>
<P>
   EMAN-PART2 _ Alexander Graham Bell, the inventor of the
telephone, would be astounded by today's portable wireless cell
phone. And early radio aficionados never envisioned their
grandchildren walking down the street with a Sony Walkman perched
on their heads. Today, computers are making that same transition.
Once heavy and place-bound, they are becoming so lightweight and
portable that they will soon be wearable, part of the clothing and
accessories that people don each morning. (Bookman, Palm Beach
Post). 60
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EMAN-WIRED _ ``For two years I had 30,000 people inside my head,
watching what I did everyday, altering my reality, offering
suggestions on what I should do next,'' recalls Steve Mann, a
professor at the University of Toronto. ``I finally had to shut it
down, though. My head space got a little too crowded.'' Mann is not
crazy. From 1994 to 1996, while a grad student at MIT in Boston, he
streamed live video directly onto the Internet from a device that
was mounted on his head. Everything Mann saw and heard, visitors on
his website could see and hear as well.
</P>
<P>
   EMAN-MILITARY _ At military exercises in Louisiana this summer,
American troops will find themselves engaged in fake battle against
a rifle platoon of ``cyborgs'' from the 82nd Airborne Division,
headquartered at Fort Benning, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   PART THREE
</P>
<P>
   (ETA 0402)
</P>
<P>
   Human smarts _ and emotions _ in silicon.
</P>
<P>
   Slugs for lead story and sidebars TBA.
</P>
<P>
   PART FOUR
</P>
<P>
   (ETA 0409)
</P>
<P>
   What does computer research that melds mind and machine mean for
the 21st century? For religion, medicine and human values? A
readers' forum.
</P>
<P>
   Slugs for lead story and sidebars TBA.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
