<HEADER>
A6020 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TREK-LEVAR-BURTON-DIR     03-23 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-LEVAR-BURTON-DIRECTS-STAR-TREK-VOYAGER-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, `VOYAGER': LEVAR BURTON STEPS BACK BEHIND THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of LeVar Burton
in a scene from ``Star Trek: Insurrection.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The universe can be a strange place so far as coincidence is
concerned.
 &HT;    Just ask LeVar Burton, who returns to the ``Star Trek: Voyager''
director's chair with the April 26 episode ``Live Fast and
Prosper.''
 &HT;    ``Robin Burger, who wrote the episode, used to be my next-door
neighbor,'' Burton says, laughing. ``That's a fun fact to know and
tell.
 &HT;    ``Also, one of the actors in the episode is named Guinan,'' says
Burton, whose close pal Whoopi Goldberg played the sage barkeep
Guinan on ``Star Trek: The Next Generation.'' ``It's not the first
time that I worked with Francis Guinan _ in `Ex Post Facto,' which
was the very first `Voyager' I directed, Francis played (Minister
Kray), one of the bird people.
 &HT;    ``The synchronicities abound, don't they?''
 &HT;    Synchronicity aside, ``Live Fast and Prosper'' finds three wily
and conniving aliens (Kaitlin Hopkins, Greg Daniel and Guinan)
impersonating Captain Janeway (Kate Mulgrew), Tuvok (Tim Russ) and
Chakotay (Robert Beltran) in order to sell phony Federation
memberships to other species in the Alpha Quadrant. When the
impostors' actions engender tremendous ill will among those
deceived, Janeway and company race to correct the situation.
 &HT;    ``The challenge on this one was finding the humor and walking
that fine line between having the humor come out of the situation
and the characters, and having it be setup-setup-joke,'' Burton
says by telephone from his Los Angeles home. ``I wanted to find a
way to explore and exploit the humorous aspects of the situation
without it going over the top.
 &HT;    ``It was also an opportunity to cast really terrific guest
stars,'' he adds. ``We were lucky to get Kaitlin Hopkins, who is
Shirley Knight's daughter and a star in her own right. She has
spent most of her career on Broadway, and she is just a terrific
talent.
 &HT;    ``It was a fun one to do,'' Burton says. ``Plus that crew _ I've
known most of these people for 11 or 12 years. Directing `Voyager'
is always like going home for me.
 &HT;    ``I haven't actually started to edit yet,'' he says, ``but I was
extremely happy with the dailies. I think it will be an
entertaining, fun episode.''
 &HT;    On other ``Trek'' fronts, Burton has nothing newsworthy to offer
about either the fourth ``Next Generation'' feature or the
top-secret, now-in-the-works new ``Star Trek'' series.
 &HT;    He would, however, like it known that he'd happily make himself
available to direct either project.
 &HT;    ``I'd be interested in that,'' he says succinctly and playfully.
``Absolutely.''
 &HT;    That's not to say that Burton is sitting around waiting for
future ``Trek'' ventures to come together. On the contrary, he's
generating numerous enterprises of his own.
 &HT;    He directed ``Camp P,'' a pilot for MTV that centers on a boot
camp for juvenile delinquents who are one step away from prison.
He's developing ``At Water's Edge,'' a television movie for James
Earl Jones. And he intends to direct ``Trek'' veterans Whoopi
Goldberg and Alfre Woodard in a CBS presentation, ``The Watsons Go
to Birmingham.''
 &HT;    At some point, Burton _ who's currently hosting and producing
the 18th season of the PBS children's educational series, ``Reading
Rainbow'' _ also hopes to ``pull a Michael Landon'' and create a
one-hour dramatic series that he'd produce, star in and frequently
direct.
 &HT;    Most of Burton's endeavors are shaped at the offices of Eagle
Nation Films, his production company, which is based on the
Paramount Pictures lot in Hollywood. The Eagle Nation offices are a
parsec away from Goepp Circle Productions, Jonathan Frakes'
company, and it's not unusual for the mini-moguls to bump into one
another as they race to and from meetings and sound stages.
 &HT;    ``Jonathan and I run into each other all the time,'' Burton
says. ``We're pretty lucky, pretty fortunate to be doing what we're
doing.
 &HT;    ``We both work hard at being successful at what we do, at being
producers and directors as well as actors,'' he says. ``It's nice
to have that brotherly support.
 &HT;    ``Things are very nice right now, very nice.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
