</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES: PICASSO `TULIPS'; MICHELANGELO SKETCH; 7-ELEVEN PHOTOS;
AUDIO ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT8 and 9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spring Tulips From Picasso
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the important spring and summer auctions
approaching, Sotheby's and Christie's have begun crowing about the
big-ticket works they have to offer. And with all the negative
publicity from the continuing federal antitrust investigation into
their practices, both companies are more determined than ever to
put out the word that business is going on as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's says it will have the season's most important work:
``Still Life With Tulips,'' a 1932 portrait by Picasso of his
mistress Marie-Therese Walter. Estimated at $25 million to $30
million, the painting is to be auctioned in New York on May 9.
</P>
<P>
   The composition, reminiscent of a Spanish old master work, is
particularly unusual because it is both a portrait and a still
life. Picasso placed Walter's head on a white sculptural pedestal
with a delicate garland of greens in her hair. The figure is posed
on a black armchair, her legs swathed in a blue cloth, with a
basket of tulips in her lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painted on March 2, 1932, and on the back of the
painting, not only is the date recorded but the hours Picasso
painted it _ 9 p.m. to 11:30 p.m. _ which is very unusual,'' said
Franck Giraud, head of 19th- and 20th-century art for Christie's
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's has sold several 1932 portraits of Walter that have
brought big prices. Last year it sold ``Nude on a Black Armchair''
for $45.1 million; in 1997 ``The Dream,'' for $48.4 million; and in
1995 ``The Mirror,'' for $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Giraud said that ``Tulips'' was being sold by a European
collector, whom he would not identify. It has not been on the
market since 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Michelangelo With Pen
</P>
<P>
   Great old masters have traditionally been sold in London, and
while sales of such paintings and drawings by Christie's and
Sotheby's in New York have been growing stronger, often eclipsing
auctions in London, Christie's is still saving a few jewels for its
major old master drawings sale in London on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   The star will be a Michelangelo drawing, ``Study for the Risen
Christ,'' in pen, and red and black chalk, a study for a marble
statue commissioned for the Church of Santa Maria sopra Minerva in
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The drawing, which dates from 1514-16, is estimated at $7.2
million. It comes from the well-known collection of Sir Brinsley
Ford, an authority on 18th-century art, who died in 1998. Ford
bought the drawing at Christie's in 1936 when he was in his early
20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those amazing drawings,'' said Noel Annesley,
deputy chairman of Christie's and an expert on old master paintings
and drawings. ``There are only a handful of drawings by
Michelangelo left in private hands, and this is an incredibly rare
example of the artist's mature work.''
</P>
<P>
   The drawing depicts the male abdomen and the rounded form of the
left leg. The artist sketched the figure in black chalk and then
retraced the contours in pen, using crosshatching to make it seem
as if light was streaming through the work.
</P>
<P>
   Annesley said Ford's estate was selling the drawing to raise
money to preserve the rest of his collection.
</P>
<P>
   Art and a Slurpee
</P>
<P>
   For years Sotheby's has sold works from some of the great
corporate art collections in the United States, including those of
IBM and Reader's Digest. On April 5 and 6, it will offer a rare
group of photographs from 7-Eleven Inc. that is expected to sell
for $1.6 million to $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The photography market is red-hot right now,'' said Denise
Bethel, director of Sotheby's photography department in New York.
``There are things in this collection that people have been looking
for for years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s 7-Eleven began buying photographs to furnish a new
42-floor, 1.5-million-square-foot corporate headquarters in Dallas.
But since then the company has drastically cut back its operations,
and much of the collection has been in storage, Bethel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1980s, before the big photography boom, they
began buying blue-chip images by blue-chip photographers,'' she
said. Many of the images for sale exist in only one or two vintage
prints.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stars are a range of masterworks by Paul Strand,
including two rare early images: ``Shadows, Twin Lakes,
Connecticut'' (1916), one of four Strand porch shadow studies
included in the Metropolitan Museum of Art's Strand exhibition two
years ago, which is estimated at $200,000 to $300,000; and
``Rebecca, New York'' (1921), a portrait of Strand's wife that is
expected to bring $150,000 to $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The sale also includes works of lesser-known photographers,
among them four rare images by the California photographer Alma
Lavenson. Her 1931 ``Standard Oil Company'' and 1932 ``Calaveras
Dam II'' are both estimated at $15,000 to $25,000 each. Only two or
three prints of each image are known.
</P>
<P>
   Aural Appreciation
</P>
<P>
   This year's Whitney Biennial has several firsts, among them the
group of outside curators who assembled the exhibition, its section
of Internet art and its audio guide. This is no academic, highly
curatorial audio guide. It has voices of more than 60 of the
artists represented in this survey of contemporary art. Some
describe their creative processes; others discuss their
inspirations; and some have substituted commentary with music or
sound effects. ``It is a way of making the experience of
contemporary art not so off-putting, more accessible,'' said
Maxwell L. Anderson, director of the Whitney Museum of American
Art.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Antenna Audio, a California-based company that has
developed audio guides for museums worldwide, the guide is free and
uses a hand-held player smaller than a cellular phone that operates
with headphones or can be held up to the ear and heard through a
small speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went around the country and interviewed some 70 artists
over a four-month period,'' said Chris Tellis, founder and chief
executive of Antenna Audio. ``The whole point was to connect the
voice of the artist with the work.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1657EST &QL; 
