<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6030 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-WAKING24-COX     03-23 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-WAKING24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An entertaining love, politics, ghost story
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Great loves endure beyond the grave. Oh,
OK, so that's a sentimental literary and cinematic conceit, but it
is not without dramatic impact in the movie ``Waking the Dead.''
Call it a political romance and ghost story, a hybrid genre picture
at best, but written and performed well enough to be diverting for
a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Scott Spencer's novel, it is grounded in an interesting
character study of attracting opposites. Fielding Pierce (Billy
Crudup) is an ambitious lad, groomed for politics ever since he was
given his patrician name. His understanding of the art of
compromise is typified by his serving in the Coast Guard during the
Vietnam War, protecting New York Harbor instead of the politically
detrimental alternatives of fleeing to Canada or landing in jail.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, as the movie begins, he meets and falls quickly in love
with the politically committed and unable-to-compromise
humanitarian radical Sarah Williams (Jennifer Connelly). As he
ignores his pride in the name of diplomacy, smiling and kowtowing
to the political hierarchy, Sarah becomes his needling conscience,
his ``Jiminy Cricket.'' While he is introduced to fat-cat donors by
his mentor (Hal Holbrook), Sarah snaps back at them and
increasingly becomes a liability to Fielding. Then abruptly she is
killed by a car bomb retaliating for her leftist activities in
support of Chilean rebels.
</P>
<P>
   A devastated Fielding continues to see Sarah wherever he looks,
not unlike Jimmy Stewart and his obsessional spottings of Kim Novak
in ``Vertigo.'' But is Sarah alive, a ghost or a mere delusion?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question on which the second half of ``Waking the
Dead'' hinges, as Fielding keeps encountering her while running a
punishing, close race for Congress. At one point, he leaps up from
a restaurant table to rush outside and chase what he perceives to
be Sarah through the snowy Chicago streets. By the movie's
conclusion, suffice it to say that this ghost story is
significantly less satisfying than ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   As Fielding, Crudup makes a worthy bid for recognition above the
crowded field of capable young actors. He chews up with relish a
few scenes where he is wracked with remorse and regret over Sarah,
culminating in a too-loud public pronouncement that he has lost
touch with reality.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly is also persuasive and appealing as the strident Sarah.
Together, they definitely send out sparks, particularly in their
numerous bedroom trysts.
</P>
<P>
   Janet McTeer delivers another letter-perfect American accent,
completely different from the Southern drawl of her Oscar-nominated
turn in ``Tumbleweeds.'' But the role of Fielding's supportive
sister hardly allows her to demonstrate other acting skills. Paul
Hipp keeps popping up in a curiously conceived part as Fielding's
hippie-dippy brother. And if you blink, you might miss a cameo by
Ed Harris as a congressman resigning under a cloud of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Director Keith Gordon (``Mother Night'') handles the story's
emotional terrain with relative restraint, perhaps too much so for
more action-oriented moviegoers. He also navigates the numerous
time shifts of Robert Dillon's screenplay with clarity, enhanced by
subtle wardrobe and hair-length changes.
</P>
<P>
   Is it something about the millennial Zeitgeist that brings us
several ghost stories now, or is it mere coincidence? In any event,
it would help your enjoyment of ``Waking the Dead'' if you were
predisposed toward spectral beings or at least undying love.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
