<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6032 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-OSCAR-RINGEL26-COX     03-23 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-RINGEL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everything appears to be coming up roses for `Beauty'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The power clout of Miramax is doing its considerable best to
turn tonight's Oscars into a real horse race by pushing former long
shot ``The Cider House Rules'' as the rival to DreamWorks'
``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   If you accept the horse-race notion, let's just say it's likely
to be a run for the roses _ those ``American Beauty'' roses.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some thoughts and predictions for the top six
categories that may or may not prove helpful in your own Oscar
pool. Just remember: The only thing anyone was sure about last year
was that ``Saving Private Ryan'' would win best picture.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PICTURE
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'': Still the favorite and deservedly so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'': It's making a mighty come-from-behind
run, but when supporting contender Michael Caine is off-screen, the
movie sort of disappears, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile'': It does it all and it does it right, but it
still doesn't feel like a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider'': The ringer in the group. Knocked askew by star
ego (Al Pacino's).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sixth Sense'': They say blockbusters don't win, but does
anyone remember ``Titanic''? It's the only movie in the same class
as ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's choice: ``American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My choice: ``American Beauty,'' with ``The Sixth Sense'' a
close second.
</P>
<P>
   BEST DIRECTOR
</P>
<P>
   Lasse Halstrom, ``The Cider House Rules'': Should've won for
1985's ``My Life as a Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Spike Jonze, ``Being John Malkovich'': The hipness is in the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Mann, ``The Insider'': Should've won for 1981's
``Thief'' (now we're getting obscure).
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mendes, ``American Beauty'': Beginner's luck or
bred-in-the-bones brilliance? Either way, he's the man.
</P>
<P>
   M. Night Shyamalan, ``The Sixth Sense'': If anyone can pull an
upset ...
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's choice: Mendes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My choice: Mendes, with Shyamalan a close second.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Russell Crowe, ``The Insider'': It's the best performance, but
it lacks glamour. And co-star Pacino takes away a lot of screen
time.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Farnsworth, ``The Straight Story'': Has a chance if the
flashier candidates cancel each other out, but it doesn't feel like
a ``Harry and Tonto'' year (Art Carney in 1974).
</P>
<P>
   Sean Penn, ``Sweet and Lowdown'': The nomination keeps him
bankable.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey, ``American Beauty'': About as good as Crowe and in
a better movie. Plus he recently won a Screen Actors Guild Award.
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington, ``The Hurricane'': A terrific performance
that could succeed simply on star presence.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's choice: Spacey, with Washington as a possible upset.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My choice: A dead heat between Spacey and Crowe.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Annette Bening, ``American Beauty'': She's got the Hollywood
establishment on her side, and winning a SAG Award didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Janet McTeer, ``Tumbleweeds'': Not her year, but you can bet
she'll be back if she gets the right role.
</P>
<P>
   Julianne Moore, ``The End of the Affair'': Won't somebody please
give this woman an Oscar? She can handle anything from ``Safe'' to
``The Lost World: Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Streep, ``Music of the Heart'': She's the best, but this
isn't her best work.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Swank, ``Boys Don't Cry'': The early favorite, but she
seems to be losing momentum.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's choice: Bening.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My choice: Moore.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caine, ``The Cider House Rules'': It's the best work,
and his surprise SAG win makes him a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cruise, ``Magnolia'': He was perceived as a shoo-in. May
still be. Or he could be this year's Lauren Bacall.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Clarke Duncan, ``The Green Mile'': A lovely performance
that was harder to pull off than it looked. But the movie just
doesn't have that winner's aura.
</P>
<P>
   Jude Law, ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'': Unless something really
weird happens, he's the designated also-ran.
</P>
<P>
   Haley Joel Osment, ``The Sixth Sense'': A truly wonderful
portrayal, but I'm not sure Oscar is in a kiddie mood this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's choice: Cruise, unless Caine pulls an upset.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My choice: Caine.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Toni Collette, ``The Sixth Sense'': She was much better in
``Muriel's Wedding,'' but the nomination won't hurt her career.
</P>
<P>
   Angelina Jolie, ``Girl, Interrupted'': Those lips. Those eyes.
That talent. That role.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Keener, ``Being John Malkovich'': Her time will come.
Right now, she's splitting the hip vote with Chloe Sevigny.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Morton, ``Sweet and Lowdown'': A poignant but feisty
mute, straight out of a Chaplin film. How old are the academy
members?
</P>
<P>
   Chloe Sevigny, ``Boys Don't Cry'': Like Swank, she seems to have
lost her early momentum. Plus, there's the Keener factor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oscar's choice: Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  My choice: Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
