<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-OSCAR-BALL-BIO26-COX     03-23 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-BALL-BIO26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ALan Ball file
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  His first movie script: ``American Beauty,'' up for eight
Oscars at tonight's 72nd annual Academy Awards, including best
original screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The bottom line: ``American Beauty'' was made on a budget of
$15 million. To date it's earned more than $225 million at the box
office worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Among his plays: ``Five Women Wearing the Same Dress,'' ``My
Mother's Butt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Among his TV shows: ``Grace Under Fire,'' ``Cybill,'' ``Oh
Grow Up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His next project: He's finalizing a deal with HBO to write and
direct a pilot about a family-run funeral home in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O, holy night: Ball caught the stage bug in elementary school
in Marietta, Ga., during the Christmas pageant. ``I was a shepherd.
I just sort of sat there and stared at the baby Jesus while the
class sang a carol. I was very nervous. But it was a thrilling
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Religion and his family: ``I grew up in the Methodist church.
We went on Christmas and Easter. And then when my sister died,
everybody suddenly got religion in that weird Gothic kind of (way)
that focuses on the Rapture and the end of the world and the whole
punishing side of God. It really helped my parents deal with my
sister's death because they were both just devastated and lost. But
it wasn't doing anything for me. Since then my religious stuff has
veered toward Eastern philosophy and Buddhism.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For love of humor: ``Life is just funny. It's so absurd. And
I'm a person whose sense of humor is so intrinsic and so basic that
I can't write anything that doesn't have humor in it or I get
bored. Every time I go see a movie that doesn't have any humor in
it or takes itself too seriously or see a play that is ponderous, I
just go, `Snooze.'''
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
