<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANIME-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     03-23 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIME-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`X': EVEN ANIMATED, POOR TOKYO CAN'T GET A MOMENT'S PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of anime _ the visually detailed and often doom-oriented
Japanese animation features that include ``Princess Mononoke,''
``Ghost in the Shell'' and ``Akira'' _ are bound to be delighted by
``X,'' the director Rintaro's adaptation of the Clamp collective's
graphic novels (or manga) of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a not-too-distant future _ 1999 _ that's now a
not-too-distant past, ``X'' has to cram in enough exposition to
float several books of the New Testament, or the first few issues
of the manga series.
</P>
<P>
   As a comic book, ``X,'' like a number of other comics, started
as a mood piece, setting the stage by introducing the characters
through action. ``X'' the movie has an entirely different mandate.
It is better at developing the gloomy world of cybermagic in a few
strokes than the comic was.
</P>
<P>
   The story: Kamui (the voice of Alan Marriot), whose name means
God's power, is the key to preventing the destruction of Tokyo,
both the destruction and its prevention being longstanding
traditions. And he is determined to protect his love, Kotari
(Larissa Murray).
</P>
<P>
   His best friend and Kotari's brother, Fuma (Adam Henderson), is
enchanted into becoming Kamui's enemy. Dual goddesses, Kanoe
(Denica Fairman) and Hinoto (Stacey Jefferson), tell of a battle
for the world's future that moves from dreamscapes to bloody
struggles on the city's streets. The film's motley band of world
protectors include a stripper and a 14-year-girl and her magic
wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the power of ``X,'' which opens Friday in Manhattan,
derives from the potency of the adult imagery. It begins with
Kamui's mother plunging a hand into her stomach and withdrawing a
sword, a weapon for her son to use in his travails. Showers of
flower petals cascade over the picture _ a lovely motif.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the constant rivers of explanation _ narration dusty
with portent _ ``X'' requires a great deal of concentration. And if
you know the material, the breakdown of the story for the first
third may become exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   Once the summarizing is done, ``X'' has the sleepy feel of an
urban fairy tale, but getting there is a long trip. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `X' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rintaro; written (originally in Japanese, dubbed
into English) by Asami Watanabe, Nanase Ohkawa and Rintaro, based
on the original story by Clamp, Satsuki Igarashi, Mokonaapapa,
Nanase Ohkawa and Mikku Nekoi; director of photography, Jin
Yamaguchi; edited by Harutoshi Ogata, Yukiko Itoh and Satoshi
Terauchi; music by Harumitsu Shimizu and Santora: Victor
Entertainment; character design and director of original drawings,
Nobuteru Yuhki; produced by Kazuo Yokoyama, Masanori Maruyama and
Kazuhiko Ikeguchi; released by Manga Entertainment. Running time:
98 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Alan Marriot (Kamui), Adam Henderson (Fuma),
Larissa Murray (Kotari), Denica Fairman (Kanoe), Stacey Jefferson
(Hinoto) and Mike Fitzpatrick (Sorata). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1703EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6036 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-OSCARS-ALANBALL26-COX     03-23 2780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-ALANBALL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Screenwriter Alan Ball says his highly praised critique of
Middle America isn't aimed at his hometown (backslash)
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My name is Lester Burnham. This is my neighborhood. This is my
street. This ... is my life. I'm 42 years old. In less than a year,
I'll be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With eloquent simplicity, these words begin
``American Beauty,'' the dark comedy about a modern-day American
family on the skids that's up for eight Oscars at tonight's 72nd
annual Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   They are words, like the provocative narration in Billy Wilder's
classic ``Sunset Boulevard,'' spoken by a dead man. And they were
written by one of Hollywood's newest cinematic talents, a
42-year-old first-time big-screen movie writer born at Emory
Hospital in Atlanta and raised in Marietta, Ga. He's an
off-Broadway playwright, a TV sitcom writer and one-time Six Flags
Over Georgia employee whose job one summer included guessing the
ages and weights of theme park visitors.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Alan Ball.
</P>
<P>
   This is his neighborhood: the narrow, ever-twisting roads of
Hollywood Hills where monied Southern Californians race its riskier
curves in gleaming Mercedes and hulking Range Rovers.
</P>
<P>
   This is his street: a line of pricey, small, flat-roofed homes
built in the '60s near the top of the Hollywood Hills. The street's
petite, manicured gardens are dotted not with beautiful, red-red
American roses, but with exotic green cacti and orange-flamed birds
of paradise.
</P>
<P>
   In less than 24 hours, Ball could be holding an Oscar. This
one-time Marietta High drum major and school newspaper editor is
nominated for best original screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an early-on and uncanny ability to see what he wanted
to accomplish,'' says longtime friend Donna Arrants, 42, of
Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have great ideas but can't get it done. He gets it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the anticipated victories tonight for fellow ``American
Beauty'' nominees _ including director Sam Mendes; producers Bruce
Cohen and Dan Jinks, who could win best picture for Steven
Spielberg's DreamWorks SKG; and maybe even Kevin Spacey and Annette
Bening, both contenders in the top acting categories _ it's a good
bet among Hollywood insiders that Ball will win.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things about this screenplay that was so compelling
and rare _ I didn't think there was a single scene that was
repetitive,'' says Spacey (an Oscar winner for 1995's ``The Usual
Suspects''), who played ``Beauty's'' central, tragic figure. ``What
I felt was so startling was that this screenplay kept moving
forward. It was a page turner.''
</P>
<P>
   Spacey and Bening portray Lester and Carolyn Burnham, the
parents of a family that, behind its rosy veneer, is wilting. He's
burned out, a cynic's demigod. She's the ultimate ice princess.
Together, they wig out in a biting screenplay that marches toward a
profound sense of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Ball won the Writers Guild Award for
``American Beauty,'' beating out his main Oscar competitors,
Charlie Kaufman (``Being John Malkovich''), Paul Thomas Anderson
(``Magnolia'') and M. Night Shyamalan (``The Sixth Sense''). Ball
also won this year's Golden Globe. (That shiny trophy is upstairs
in his home behind a stack of papers.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep my head about this and not take it too
seriously,'' Ball says of tonight's Oscars. ``At least not overly
seriously. You know, I wrote this off-Broadway play _ `Five Women
Wearing the Same Dress.' Everybody kept saying, `It's guaranteed to
move to Broadway.' And it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole Oscar thing, he says, is ``incredibly stressful. I'm
not used to this attention. My whole perspective as an artist has
been as an outsider so I'm sort of nervous about losing that
because I think that's very beneficial as a writer. And you see
success spoil a lot of people, a lot of great actors and a lot of
great directors. And I don't want that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm also really enjoying this,'' he says. ``It's fun.
Would I love to have an Oscar on the shelf? Yeah. But it's not why
you do the work. It's incredibly ...'' He pauses briefly until he
finds just the right words. ``It's kind of like being voted prom
queen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn: ``This is a $4,000 sofa upholstered in Italian silk.
This is not just a couch.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester: ``It's just a couch!
</P>
<P>
   (Gesturing around the room.) This isn't life. This is just
stuff. And it's becoming more important to you than living. Well,
honey, that's just nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Ball's house doesn't look anything like the interiors in
``American Beauty.'' There's not a single $4,000 sofa upholstered
in Italian silk.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, his California modern home is much more casual.
There's a small entrance area marked by an oversize bronze foot. A
large black-and-white painting, done in 1992 by his friend Marc
Ashmore, a New York artist, hangs at the front door. A lacquered
piano dominates the narrow living room, which includes a vintage
lowback sectional sofa in front of a concrete fireplace. Small
Asian statuary, symbols of Ball's interest in Eastern religions,
rest on the hardwood floors. An ironing board is up in his messy
kitchen, which is strewn with water bottles, glassware and used
cups.
</P>
<P>
   He remains, say friends in L.A. and Cobb County, modest to a
fault. ``You're never aware he's the writer of this brilliant
script,'' says ``American Beauty'' co-producer Cohen. ``He's
unassuming and delightfully down-to-earth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my L.A. home. I've got my hot tub,'' Ball says,
lounging with his feet up on his sofa. ``I'm so embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' skewers this country's preoccupation with
designer labels and supermodels. Our marketing mania. Dressing for
success. Homophobia. And corporate greed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's instilled in us that wealth and success and materials
stir people's happiness. That is just an out-and-out lie,'' Ball
says.
</P>
<P>
   Some recent news articles have suggested Ball is aiming his
criticisms at Marietta, especially in regard to homophobia. He's
been quoted as saying it's a town he ``had to get out of'' because
it's ``not exactly the most friendly place for gay people.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not quotes he recalls, but he doesn't deny them; he
just thinks they were taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   When he left Georgia in the late '70s, he says, ``I didn't even
know I was gay at the time. That was such a taboo I couldn't even
acknowledge that about myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It was later, while he was studying theater at Florida State
University, that he told his mother he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't believe that everyone who lives in Marietta
is shut down and living in denial,'' he says. ``There are people
like that everywhere. There are tons of people here in L.A. living
that way. I remember reading the quotes and being horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I left Marietta is very practical. I think if you
are going to pursue a career in entertainment you have to live in
New York or L.A. And that's really my only reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, he says, is ``not about Marietta at all. It's about
Middle American values.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Lester: ``Brad, for 14 years I've been a whore for the
advertising industry. The only way I could save myself now is if I
start firebombing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A lot of ``American Beauty'' is about the misunderstandings that
plague us, the tragedies that befall us.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of it is also about Alan Ball.
</P>
<P>
   He began writing his movie two years ago, late at night after
12- and 14-hour days hammering out scripts for Cybill Shepherd's
CBS sitcom ``Cybill.'' ``American Beauty'' was his sanity.
``Cybill'' was his hell on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was writing for `Cybill' at the time, but my experience in
writing for both `Grace Under Fire' (the old sitcom starring former
Mariettan Brett Butler) and `Cybill' was an eye-opening experience
because it was just deeply, deeply dysfunctional,'' Ball says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love actors and both of those women _ they're not actors,
they're stars _ were terribly, terribly self-indulgent.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``American Beauty,'' when Spacey's Lester Burnham hands over
his management-ordered job description to Brad, the freshly hired
consultant, the venom in Lester's document is merely Ball purging
his own real-life frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was used to situations on `Cybill' where we'd written a
great script,'' Ball says, ``and the night before the table read,
I'd get a phone call (from Shepherd) and she'd go, `Well, I think
this character who comes from Italy to be with (her TV daughter)
Zoey after she lost her virginity two years ago should meet me and
fall in love with me. And then I think I should sing opera in this
episode.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ball drops his jaw to exaggerate the gall of Shepherd's
``suggestions.'' He says she viewed the show as public relations
for her life and resented any other actor in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   So he turned to his own script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me really felt I have to write something that means
something or I'm just going to go crazy,'' he says. ``Otherwise I
would have had to accept the fact that I had become a total whore
and was just doing it for the money. And I didn't just ever want to
be one of those people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn (in bed with real
</P>
<P>
   estate king Buddy Kane,
</P>
<P>
   post-sex): ``I was so stressed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy: ``Know what I do when I feel like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn: ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy: ``I fire a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Just inside the front door of Ball's childhood home in Marietta,
leaning against the wall behind an umbrella stand, is a gun. It's
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the BB gun Alan bought me for my birthday,'' says his
mother, Mary, 86. ``The neighbor used to have 17 cats. It doesn't
kill them. It just stings them a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ball and her husband, Frank, a one-time Lockheed employee,
moved into this tiny, wood-sided home in 1955, two years before
Alan came along. He was the youngest of four children, born when
his mother was 44. One brother was a senior in high school. His
only sister, Mary Ann, was 8.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ball says she always knew Alan would be successful. ``He
was a smart little boy. He's always written a lot. And he was very
active in high school.'' Senior class president. A drum major who
choreographed at least one halftime show. He played piano and
trombone and wrote music. There didn't seem to be a club he didn't
join.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Ball says he had created ``this persona for myself
of really being an overachiever, kind of an All-American guy that
really wasn't me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's how he coped.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 10, Ga. 120 was built around Marietta, gutting the
Balls' street. Their home now sits at a dead-end next to the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hated that,'' he says. ``When I was a kid, we spent a
lot of time playing in the woods, and those just got removed and
replaced by a highway. That was probably my first experience with a
profound sense of loss. You know, of something being really
important that was suddenly gone. And it was weird and never the
same after that.''
</P>
<P>
   At 13, he saw his sister die. On her 22nd birthday, Mary Ann was
killed in a car accident while driving Alan to a piano lesson.
About six years later, his father died at home from lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone close to you dies, it's like a part of you
dies,'' Ball says. So he distracted himself by being active in high
school and college. It wasn't until years later _ after Columbia
Pictures optioned his off-Broadway play and he was able to quit his
day job _ that he became deeply depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all this unexpressed grief and trauma because I was in
the car with my sister and I had never dealt with it,'' he says. He
began therapy. ``It was a really ugly six months of my life, but
I'm really glad I went through it. Those experiences really deepen
you. They make you stronger, and you're kind of forced to come out
on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   He also told his mother that he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty bad about it, and Alan felt bad about it, too,''
she says. ``He didn't know if I was going to kick him out of the
house or what. But we both cried a little bit. It took a little
getting used to, but he gave me some books to read and I understand
that God made him like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it,'' she says, sitting on her living room couch and
stopping to stare out her open front door. ``I wish he wasn't gay.
But he seems to be happy. And I'm very pleased for him about
everything. Whatever he's done, he's done well.''
</P>
<P>
   His brothers are crazy about him, she says _ but some of the
extended family is less supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think he's going to hell,'' she says. And some who have
seen ``American Beauty,'' got up and walked out of the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what? I don't care,'' Alan Ball says. ``Everybody is
capable of making their own decisions and if people make different
decisions than me, it doesn't mean my decisions aren't right _ and
it doesn't mean those people's decisions aren't right for them. But
that's a worldview of tolerance and acceptance that certain members
of my family do not have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Ricky: ``It was one of those days when it's a minute away from
snowing. And there's this electricity in the air, you can almost
hear it, right? And this bag was just ... dancing with me. Like a
little kid begging me to play with it. For 15 minutes. That's the
day I realized that there was this entire life behind things, and
this incredibly benevolent force that wanted me to know there was
no reason to be afraid. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   The little white bag in ``American Beauty'' _ the movie's
centerpiece image of grace, peace and beauty _ is one memory Ball
carries with him every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in New York walking to a subway stop after brunch, and I
was actually in front of the World Trade Center, and this white
plastic bag appeared out of nowhere. It was just blowing around,
and then I noticed it was circling me. And it continued to do that
for a weirdly long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure certain people would look at that and go, `It's just
wind.' But it was this very bizarre zen moment out of nowhere. And
I suddenly felt this completely unexpected sense of peace and
wonder. That moment has always stayed with me. And when I started
writing the movie, it just was sort of organic and found its way
into the script.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-producer Jinks says he'll never forget the first time he read
Ball's screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was unique to find a script that was unbelievably
funny on one hand and quite moving on another. I thought there were
so many characters of various ages that were relatable. It told us
something about their world that made me think about my life and
about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball's agent began shopping the screenplay in 1998. Steven
Spielberg read it and was so impressed he told Ball in a chance
meeting, ``You should only write movies, and you should only write
your own movies.'' Spielberg's DreamWorks SKG bought ``American
Beauty'' for $400,000. Jinks and Cohen signed on as producers.
Mendes, the English stage director of the gigantic hit ``Cabaret,''
lobbied personally to direct.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, only two big changes were made to Ball's screenplay.
One involved the main character's relationship with his daughter's
classmate; the other was a courtroom scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little upset (over the cutting of the trial scene) for
about 24 hours,'' Ball says. ``But then I saw Sam's cut ... with
all that removed, and I could tell that it worked and I said, `OK,
you're right.'''
</P>
<P>
   Others were moved by the final cut, too. Bening cried.
Spielberg, who watched the film alone at DreamWorks while a nervous
Mendes waited outside, emerged to tell the director, ``You have
created a classic.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ball does win tonight, he'll have a prepared speech. ``My big
fear is that I will forget somebody, and then I will be really,
really mortified.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will he thank?
</P>
<P>
   Probably the same group he thanked after winning the Writers
Guild honor.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes. For ``always being interested in what I had to say and
what I thought.'' His producing buddies Cohen and Jinks. For
``promising me in the beginning to always keep me involved. They
kept that promise.'' DreamWorks, of course. His various therapists.
For ``obviously not doing their job.'' And one more thank you for a
little item that needs no explanation. ``That plastic bag in front
of the World Trade Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
