 &HT;    On the web
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each year, Oscar's celebrity rises on the Internet. Here's a
quick rundown of Web sites involved in pre-awards, live and
post-awards events:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WATCHING IT: At www.live-at
</P>
<P>
   .com/feature/oscar/index.html you can click through many of
tonight's Oscar-related parties. Beginning at
</P>
<P>
   7 is the Night of 100 Stars Black Tie Dinner Gala. At 8 p.m.,
it's the O2K Party at the House of Blues with host Rob Schneider.
Also at 8 p.m. are the Governor's Ball and a soiree held by
</P>
<P>
   E! Online's Ted Casablanca. Finally, beginning at 1 a.m. is
Elton John's eighth annual InStyle Oscar Night Party. Those who've
already RSVP'd to Sir Elton include Annette Bening, Toni Collette,
Michael Clarke Duncan, Jude Law, Chloe Sevigny, Kevin Spacey and
Hilary Swank.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WEARING IT: The world's stuffiest shirt, Mr. Blackwell, will
preside in a live Web cast on estar.com and make his comments about
all the designer wear and the show itself.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WADING THROUGH IT: It's called filmsite.org/oscars.html, and
it has a complete rundown of all past Oscar winners and nominees.
You'll find more minutiae (``Australians at the Oscars'') on a site
dubbed Awards Heaven (geocities
</P>
<P>
   .com/Hollywood/Academy/5762) and another called Wesley Lovell _
The Oscar Guy (geocities.com/Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   /3713). On his site, which includes Lovell's predictions with
analysis and reviews, he says, ``Useless trivia is my forte.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WAXING ELOQUENT: The major Oscar sites include, of course,
oscar.com (including trends in fashion), eonline.com (live Academy
Award coverage starts at noon), mrshowbiz
</P>
<P>
   .com (submit your own predictions) and ew.com (facts, quizzes
and Oscar odds).
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
