<P>
   MAJOR LEAGUE BASEBALL ADVISORY
</P>
<P>
   Here is an advance look at stories being planned by Cox
Newspapers previewing the upcoming Major League Baseball season. If
you need additional information, please contact CoxNet in Atlanta
at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA JOURNAL-CONSTITUTION
</P>
<P>
   Copy will be ready by Friday, March 31 at 5 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SELIG _ It was only a short time ago when Bud Selig was
serving in the role as acting baseball commissioner. Entering the
2000 season, he's now the full-time commissioner with wide-ranging
power that could have a huge impact on the sport. A look at Selig
and his possible impact on the game. (Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ALPREVIEW _ Previewing the American League heading into the
2000 season. (Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES _ Can anyone stop the New York Yankees from winning
another World Series title? The team with the highest payroll and
lived up to expectations in recent years, winning two consecutive
and three of the last four world championships. The team returns
virtually intact from last year and appears to be the favorite in
2000. What makes the Yankees so strong? (Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-NLPREVIEW _ Previewing the National League heading into the
2000 season. Will the Braves continue to dominate? Will the
addition of Ken Griffey, Jr. help the Reds? (Stinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-SCHUEROLZ _ The life and times of Braves' General Manager
John Schuerholz, who has turned the Braves into a perennial power.
(Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 80. WITH chart his major
moves.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-PITCHING _ The Braves' vaunted Big Three _ Greg
Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz _ is getting old. John Smoltz
has already broken down, being forced to miss the entire season
after elbow surgery. How much longer can Maddux and Glavine keep
going without missing starts? Age catches up with all pitchers, no
matter what they do to fool Father Time. (Rogers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40-50.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-BULLPEN _ The Braves' bullpen will have a different
look this year, even after John Rocker serves his two-week
suspension. The biggest change will be the return of Kerry
Ligtenberg, who missed all of last season with elbow surgery.
(Rogers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15-20.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-ANDRUW _ At 22, Andruw Jones is already being billed
as one of the best outfielders in baseball. But most of that praise
has come from his defensive work. Is this the year that his
offensive play catches up to the defense and he becomes the
complete player that everyone expects? (Rogers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35-40.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-CHIPPER _ What has the last year been like for
Chipper Jones? After his well-publicized marital problems, Jones
bounced back to have an MVP season in 1999. After a somewhat
peaceful off-season, is Chipper ready to retun to MVP form in 2000?
(Rogers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-FURCAL_ He's the top prospect in the Braves' minor
league system and it appears that it's only a matter of time before
he joins the big team. He's Rafael Furcal, the 19-year-old
infielder who could be the team's shortstop of the future. (Rogers,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-METS_ The Braves-Mets rivalry has turned into one of
the most fierce rivalries in baseball. Reliever John Rocker added
fuel to the fire with his comments about Mets' fans during the
playoffs last season, but the seeds of the rivalry had already been
planted earlier. The Mets accused Chipper Jones of cheating after a
key three-game series last season and Mets manager Bobby Valentine
has taken his shots at the Braves in the past. A look at what has
made this rivalry so intense. (Wilkinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 60-70.
</P>
<P>
   PALM BEACH POST
</P>
<P>
   Copy will be ready by 5 p.m. EST on Thursday, March 30.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-MELTINGPOT _ Baseball, more than ever, has become much more
than America's pastime. It's increasingly becoming a melting pot of
whites, blacks, Latins, Asians, etc., and with that has come
issues/problems regarding racism (John Rocker), marketing (Sammy
Sosa vs. Mark McGwire) and coaching and playing together (language
barriers). (Capozzi/Gutierrez, Palm Beach Post).
