<HEADER>
A6042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-ASIAN-ART-3TAKES-N     03-23 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ASIAN-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KINETIC MOMENT FOR ASIAN ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
(editors: optional sidebar at end of article) 
 (bl)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In these first days of spring, Asia Week has blown
into town like a lion and like a lamb. It brings the roar of
big-deal auctions and a big-guns art fair. It also offers a chance
to linger quietly over a fantastic array of Asian art.
</P>
<P>
   The real news, though, is that the festivities are in some ways
just a deluxe version of business as usual. Asian art in Manhattan
is not what it was a few years ago, an exotic subspecies confined
to the remoter quarters of museums. At some point in the 1990s, it
broke through the silence barrier and assumed a position of
prominence from which it is not likely to retreat.
</P>
<P>
   New York still doesn't create the kind of hoopla that London
does for  &UR; its &LR;  Asia week in November, with a schedule of lectures,
scholarly symposiums and special exhibitions linking the worlds of
museums, academia and commerce. Christie's, in its new Rockefeller
Center digs, is heading in that direction with its show titled
``Treasures From Ancient Beijing,'' but there's a lot more that
could be done in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the situation is impressive. The Metropolitan Museum of
Art, with its pan-Asian master plan complete, is mounting superb
exhibitions. One, ``The World of Scholars' Rocks: Gardens, Studios
and Paintings,'' fills the Chinese painting galleries; a choice
gathering from the famed Mary Griggs Burke collection of Japanese
art opens next week.
</P>
<P>
   Asia Society, which really picked up steam in the 1990s, is in
the process of expanding its headquarters but has organized two
off-site shows. A selection from its John D. Rockefeller
collection, ``Spiritual Perfection: Religious Sculpture of South
and Southeast Asia,'' is installed at Christie's former home on
Park Avenue. And Grey Art Gallery downtown is the host for ``Sheer
Realities: Clothing and Power in 19th-Century Philippines.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Manhattan's best Asian galleries _ among them the
Chinese Porcelain Co., Kaikodo, J.J. Lally, M.D. Flacks and China
2000 Fine Art _ are being joined by energetic newcomers
specializing in contemporary work.
</P>
<P>
   And it says much for the health of the local scene that many
young Asian artists have settled in New York or have settled in the
way that artists settle anywhere these days: with one foot here,
the other there and much time spent in transit.
</P>
<P>
   International Asian Art Fair
</P>
<P>
   If a single event can be said to have sparked the Asian fires,
it was probably the first International Asian Art Fair in 1996. The
fair, which opens Friday at the 7th Regiment Armory, is a shrewd
mix of promotion and education. Top dealers from around the world
rustle up top-notch things, and many of those things have no
equivalent in the city's public collections.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult for any fair, especially one that came out of the
gate with such force, to sustain momentum. Fresh material is always
scarce; audiences get spoiled. The strain is showing a bit in the
2000 edition. The show looks both more subdued and more cluttered
than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But item for item, it's still the best game in town. If the
Armory were housing Western-style old master work of quality
comparable to some of the Asian art on view, Park Avenue would be a
logjam of double-parked limos.
</P>
<P>
   Several familiar galleries are making return visits. Gisele
Croes from Brussels is on hand with her dark, bank vault-style
booth of early Chinese bronzes, and Chinese Porcelain Co. weighs in
with a spectacular life-size pottery figure of a supercilious court
official. Intended as a tomb guardian, he apparently kept evil at
bay just by giving attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Japanese culture will want to visit Hiroshi Yanagi
Oriental Art from Kyoto and Judith Dowling from Boston, first-time
exhibitors. Work at Yanagi ranges from a cinematic Edo period
screen to a little wood-carved Shinto goddess. Another Edo screen,
at Dowling, depicts a kind of neo-Confucian day-care center, with
small children engaged in edifying pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   Art by living Chinese artists, of variable interest, seems to be
at an all-time high this year, which makes practical sense. The
supply is pretty much limitless, and authenticity is rarely an
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Goedhuis, a dealer in classical art who has led the pack
in the contemporary area, is offering recent ink paintings by Gu
Gan. The Chinese Porcelain Co. has a single flower painting, at
once pinpoint fine and flamboyant, by Liu Dan. (The artist is also
seen in a solo show at the gallery's Park Avenue shop).
</P>
<P>
   China 2000 has hand-painted, high-color Mao-era posters. (``Read
the Red Book to strengthen your will,'' says one.) Ethan Cohen Fine
Arts, in a debut appearance, presents a contingent of Chinese
conceptual artists who appeared in the Asia Society's ``Inside Out:
New Chinese Art'' two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What pushes the Asian Fair into the must-see category, though,
is its wealth of South Asian art. On the whole, New York gets a
healthy diet of Chinese and Japanese work these days. But even a
subsistence helping of Indian art is rare, and this is what the
fair provides.
</P>
<P>
   Just go to the booth shared by Doris and Nancy Wiener, where you
will see a heart-stopping 10th-century sculpture of a divine maiden
carved from West Indian marble and a small, shapely figure of the
goddess of music, Sarasvati, her finger poised on the string of her
vina. Their voluptuousness is tempered by the figure of a seated
nude Jain deity as light and cool as a rain cloud.
</P>
<P>
   John Eskenazi also has amazing Indian things, ranging from a
serene Gandharan Buddha to a dynamic bronze icon of the goddess
Durga. Bristling with karmic vibes and perched on the back of a
yelping lion (his face almost all mouth), she is a ``folk'' image
of a kind that has only recently received museum recognition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At Spink, you will find a concentration of hot-red sandstone
Mughal carving, and at Alexander Goetz a near life-size standing
Buddha from the first or second century, his face incandescent with
peculiar spiritual verve and eagerness that marked the early phases
of this religious art.
</P>
<P>
   And there is painting. An illuminated Sikh holy book and an
action-packed Kangra miniature, unusually large, of Krishna and
Radha head the starry list at Sam Fogg. Terence McInerney has a
panoramic painting of a royal procession, with a lush, humid forest
backdrop, from the Deccan. And at Art of the Past, look for a
dashing Kalighat image of Durga that Matisse would have flipped
over.
</P>
<P>
   If you are in the market for an art of glamour, humor,
sensuality, profound devotion, conceptual daring and formal
perfection, Indian art is for you, and the International Asian Art
Fair, even in a relatively sleepy year, is a great place to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Society
</P>
<P>
   Certain institutional shows are timed to coincide with Asia
Week, and two stand out. One is ``For the New Century: Japanese
Treasures From the Asian Art Museum of San Francisco'' at the Japan
Society. It's just the right size, installed with plenty of air,
and for a total immersion in sheer beauty it's hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   The 50 or so objects have been chosen by Yoko Woodson, a curator
at the Asian Art Museum, which is currently awaiting a new Gae
Aulenti-designed home, scheduled for completion in 2002. The
objects here are arranged chronologically, beginning with one of
the museum's best-known images, an exceptionally personable Haniwa
warrior, wearing balloonlike trousers and a hi-there smile.
</P>
<P>
   The Buddhist sampling that follows pairs two wonderful
12th-century figures, a seated Amida Buddha and a svelte Kannon.
Facing them is a 14th- to 15th-century painted scroll of a cosmic
mandala, its packed, Collier brothers heaven framed by narrative
panels as complex as those in any Renaissance altarpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Farther along, a famed 15th-century Shigaraki jar seems to
embody an abstract landscape of its own within a drift of snowy
glaze. (Don't miss the astute wall text comment on such ceramics by
the film director Akira Kurosawa, who was himself a painter.)
Monumental vistas in the form of screen paintings round out the
selection.
</P>
<P>
   It's a vaulting leap from 12th-century Buddhas to the gritty
contemporary photographs of Daido Moriyama that filled the same
gallery just last fall. But these are the kinds of interesting
moves Japan Society Gallery, under its director Alexandra Munroe,
is making these days.
</P>
<P>
   China Institute
</P>
<P>
   A very different kind of exhibition, but one no less entrancing,
is ``Dawn of the Yellow Earth: Ancient Chinese Ceramics From the
Meiyintang Collection'' at China Institute, that pot of cultural
gold gleaming away on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   The compact show, organized by Regina Krahl, focuses on early
Neolithic work, the study of which is still at the baby-steps
stage. Recent archaeology has moved the Neolithic in China back
much further than suspected, lining up its cultures timewise with
the civilizations of Mesopotamia and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Krahl offers her theories on the subject with wise
circumspection. Not in doubt at all, however, is the urbane
stylishness of the art itself. A plump pottery pigeon looks
Brancusian; a pantaloon-shaped tripod jug is ur-Louise Bourgeois.
And that Majiayao bowl with the zippy brushed-on curves might have
been done by Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation is straightforward but with lots of nice
touches. A lineup of five black ``egg shell'' goblets, with slitted
hollow stems so that light shows through, is an inspired stroke.
The good-looking catalog, of a kind regularly produced by China
Institute, is a valuable addition to a little-explored field.
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Lally
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Lally also includes appealing examples of Neolithic pottery
vessels in its Asia Week show titled ``Ancient Chinese Ceramics and
Tomb Sculptures.''
</P>
<P>
   A stout oval tripod vessel with a ruddy patina and pointy legs
has the heft of monumental sculpture. But a squat cup-size bowl,
with a painted fishnet design and a belt of bouncy white dots, is
pure old-fashioned fun. You just want to hold this little item in
your hand, as some lucky person did millenniums ago.
</P>
<P>
   The same lyrical spirit turns elegant in a set of gray pottery
figures of female dancers from the Han period (206 B.C.-220 A.D.).
Each, in her long-sleeve robe, is differently posed, and if one
looks quickly from one to the next, they seem to turn, flip-book
fashion, into a single figure, a dancer in action, changing
positions and gestures. Who could ever think of Chinese art as
static? It's bursting with kinetic life.
</P>
<P>
   Guiseppe Eskenazi
</P>
<P>
   Guiseppe Eskenazi, cousin of John Eskenazi at the Asian Fair, is
in town at PaceWildenstein with his fourth annual New York show,
``Masterpieces From Ancient China: Millennium Exhibition.'' The
London-based Eskenazi Gallery is 40 years old, and it's celebrating
its anniversary with fireworks in the form of 10 dazzling Chinese
bronzes.
</P>
<P>
   They are all high-end luxury objects, or parts of objects, with
jewel-like workmanship, from an archaic bronze ritual wine vessel
in the shape of an owl and a drum base entwined with a serpentine
dragon, to a pair of chariot fittings depicting dragons chasing
phoenixes in inlaid gold and silver.
</P>
<P>
   The most touch-inviting object, though, as at Lally, is a cup.
Dated from the Early Western Han period, it is made from thin
plaques of jade fixed in place by a fine, gold-inlaid bronze frame,
and it is supported by feisty pint-size phoenixes that seem to be
chirping, or whatever phoenixes do.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
