<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV26-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGING PUBLIC FIGURES: DO SINS OUTWEIGH ACHIEVEMENTS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, March 26)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Few individuals today recognize the name of David
Wark Griffith or know of his achievements and his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet anyone who enjoys motion pictures owes a debt of gratitude
to D.W. Griffith, who was, in the words of three-time Oscar winner
Frank Capra, ``the giant of all filmmakers ... the Leonardo (da
Vinci) of the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiography, Capra wrote that everything added to
filmmaking _ ``sound, color, technique'' _ since Griffith released
``The Birth of a Nation'' in 1915, is just ``embellishment.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Griffith who pioneered the conversion of powerful
panoramic stories to the screen, thus moving the art of movie
making from the era of jumpy, nickelodeon fare to sweeping dramatic
productions.
</P>
<P>
   By today's standards, his silent-screen productions appear
primitive affairs. But they are classics that were unequaled in
their day. Certainly, he was a motion picture genius.
</P>
<P>
   It was shocking, therefore, to read that the Directors Guild of
America has stripped Griffith's name from the prestigious annual
award it has been presenting for many years because the great movie
pioneer was a racist.
</P>
<P>
   Born and reared in the post-Civil War South, Griffith reflected
the disdain that millions of southerners felt toward African
Americans whose fathers and mothers had been their parents' slaves.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Birth of a Nation,'' which opened a whole new and
exciting horizon for movie makers, the villains were northern
carpetbaggers and freed slaves, as they had been in the novel from
which it was adapted. The heroes were members of the Ku Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
   All my adult life I have opposed racial prejudice and cannot
defend Griffith's attitude toward blacks. Yet, I believe the
Directors Guild erred badly in removing the name of a great motion
picture pioneer from its award. African Americans have suffered
badly in our country, but demeaning Griffith does not help them or
their cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Guild's action raises a pertinent question as to whether we
should judge individuals by their achievements or their sins _ or
try to balance one against the other.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, a colleague of mine became irate when he heard that the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences was going to award a
special Oscar to Charlie Chaplin, who was seen by millions of
Americans as a communist sympathizer.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to explain to him that Chaplin was being honored for his
tremendous contribution to motion pictures and not because of his
political beliefs and activities. But my friend refused to accept
such reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   A similar problem exists with three presidents of recent
vintage: Lyndon Johnson, Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton. Is Johnson
to be judged solely on the tragedy of Vietnam, or is that disaster
balanced by his monumental legislative achievements, including
Medicare, Medicaid, federal aid to education, protection of the
environment and an end to legal racial segregation?
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Nixon was dishonorable. But are we not now mature
enough to recognize that he had a distinguished record in foreign
policy and a good one in domestic policy before the horrors of
Watergate destroyed his presidency?
</P>
<P>
   What results await us when we try to weigh Clinton's tenure,
which includes his amoral personal conduct as well as the longest
period of economic prosperity in American history?
</P>
<P>
   In 1968 anti-Vietnam War liberals clamored for the Democratic
Party presidential nomination of Robert F. Kennedy with Senate
Foreign Relations Committee Chairman J. William Fulbright for vice
president because both opposed the war. What the war critics
conveniently overlooked was the fact that Fulbright, as a senator
from Arkansas, had opposed every effort to extend civil rights to
African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-war critics had blinded themselves to the man's dark
side while illuminating his bright side. Little did many of them
realize that earlier, President John F. Kennedy had to forego his
desire to name Fulbright as secretary of state because his
anti-civil-rights record would have made him anathema in a number
of places, including Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The drive for a Kennedy-Fulbright ticket ended, of course, with
Robert Kennedy's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   We do not strip the names from memorials to George Washington,
Thomas Jefferson, James Madison or Andrew Jackson because those
great leaders owned slaves. So why do it with an award honoring
Griffith?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently in an effort to make amends for the racial bigotry of
``The Birth of a Nation,'' Griffith in 1916 produced
``Intolerance,'' a gigantic spectacle in which he wove together
four stories of prejudice from Biblical times to the beginning of
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have called ``Intolerance'' the greatest movie ever
made, although it became a costly box-office flop that almost
bankrupted Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting this year's DGA award, the talented Steven Spielberg
took note of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to ask myself a very tough question when I heard the DGA
was making this change,'' he said in his acceptance speech on March
11. ``Would I have agreed with changing the name of one of the
highest awards of our profession, if it was widely known that that
award had been named after a director whose portrayal of Jewish
people fostered negative stereotyping? ... I would have had to
agree with that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the National Society of Film Critics said the decision was a
``depressing example of political correctness as an erasure and
rewriting of American history.''
</P>
<P>
   That is true. The DGA did not condone Griffith's racial bigotry
when, in his name, it honored great motion picture directorial
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Revision of history, which has become popular in recent years,
is a dangerous game to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1709EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-ASIAN-ART-3RDTAKE-     03-23 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ASIAN-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: phoenixes do.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This object was probably meant for ritual use. But whoever drank
from it would discover a glorious pattern of flowerlike dragons
unfurling on the bottom, and held up to the light just so, the cup
would glow like a lamp. Once again, Eskenazi leaves New Yorkers
with an image to treasure. Kaikodo
</P>
<P>
   Kaikodo also delivers stimulating sights in a dramatically
staged exhibition titled ``Realms of Faith.'' Some of the work is
specifically religious, as in a 13th- or 14th-century painting of
the formidable Japanese Buddhist poet-saint Kukai, known as Kobo
Daishi, who wears a monk's robe and holds tantric instruments, and
in a colossal polychrome stucco head of a crowned bodhisattva,
protectively flanked by painted screens.
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual, with its mingling of certainty and doubt, is the
substance of Chinese and Japanese landscape paintings, of which
there are some fine examples here. Among the commercial venues for
Asian art in the city, Kaikodo, with its scholarly foundations and
an expansive program that includes new art, is exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   Museum of Chinese in the Americas
</P>
<P>
   It's always a moving experience to visit the Museum of Chinese
in the Americas, in an old building in Chinatown that serves as a
neighborhood cultural center. The museum's lantern-shaped central
display is filled with relics of immigrant life. A second gallery
holds new art.
</P>
<P>
   On view now is work of the artist and filmmaker Brenda Joy Lem,
a third-generation Chinese-Canadian living in Toronto. Her spare
installation is the visual equivalent of oral history. She has
silkscreened blowups of old family photographs onto bannerlike
vertical strips of cloth and added brief quotations from the people
depicted to form an impressionistic chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are accordion-style books in which she looks back
on her own childhood. In one, based on the metaphor of nourishment,
she records meals her mother prepared for her as a child and
includes remembered recipes. Lem's resonant art exactly complements
a vibrant memory bank of a museum that exists very much in the
present.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-American Arts Center
</P>
<P>
   The Asian-American Arts Center, founded and run by Robert Lee in
Chinatown, has had a full-time gallery since 1984. Many notable
artists, young and old, have exhibited here, sharing their space
with the center's community educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   On at the moment is an inventive three-woman show organized by
Mihee Ahn and titled ``Apt. No. 3 F.'' Two of the artists work
entirely with discarded materials. Jean Shin fills the bedroom
section of the exhibition with sculptures made of lost socks from
laundromats, which she stuffs with lint.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese-born Niizeki Hiromi, in charge of the living room,
has stitched a curtain from junk mail envelopes, with hundreds of
small plastic windows. Yangah Ham, from Korea, shows videos of
herself showering and projects films of flickering landscape onto
the bottom of a cratelike box that serves as the apartment's
bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   The show points in several directions. It may be seen as a
version of the ``apartment art'' popular in China, where artists
exhibit at home to avoid the hassles of officialdom. It is also a
reminder of the difficulty of finding living quarters in New York
with ever-escalating rents: you literally have to make your own
home. Finally, it speaks of the intimacy of shared space and
sensibilities, an old story for artists and immigrants alike.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Cohen Fine Arts
</P>
<P>
   Farther west in Tribeca, the young dealer Ethan Cohen has opened
a street-level gallery concentrating on new work by Asian artists.
As its present exhibition, ``Conceptual Ink,'' demonstrates,
exciting things are happening here.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen provides an up-to-the-minute look at the role of
ink-and-brush painting in China, as a formal and intellectual
medium, and he has assembled some terrific work as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Gu Wenda and Xu Bing, two artists familiar in New York, come
through with first-rate pieces. Huang Chih Yang from Taipei
contributes three huge hanging scrolls of fantastic, whipped-up
figures. Xing Fei moves calligraphy into the third dimension with
her knitted ``strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the eminent painter and collector C.C. Wang is
represented by calligraphy brushed on pages of New York City phone
books, joining the hand-wrought, individualist mark-making of one
culture with printed evidence of the cultural diversity of another.
</P>
<P>
   Wang is now in his 90s, which gives some idea of the age range
covered by ``contemporary'' in this fascinatingly varied gathering.
But his painted books, with their generous conceptual gesture, look
fresh, youthful, poetic and springy. These are qualities inherent
in much of the art of Asia. No wonder New Yorkers have taken it to
heart.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Far From Remote: Where the Shows Are
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here are details about visiting the Asian Art Week
exhibitions mentioned in Holland Cotter's review. Admission to the
gallery shows is free; most galleries are open Tuesdays through
Saturdays from about 11 a.m. to about 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``ANCIENT CHINESE CERAMICS AND TOMB SCULPTURES,'' J.J. Lally &AMP;
Co. Oriental Art, 41 E. 57th St., (212) 371-3380. Through April 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``APT. NO. 3 F,'' Asian-American Arts Center, 26 Bowery, Lower
East Side, (212) 233-2154. Through April 29. Organized by Mihee
Ahn. Hours: Tuesdays through Fridays, noon to 6 p.m.; Saturdays, 4
to 6 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   ``CONCEPTUAL INK,'' Ethan Cohen Fine Arts, 37 Walker St.,
Tribeca, (212) 625-1250. Through May 20.
</P>
<P>
   LIU DAN, Chinese Porcelain Co., 475 Park Ave., at 58th Street,
(212) 838-7744. Through April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``DAWN OF THE YELLOW EARTH: ANCIENT CHINESE CERAMICS FROM THE
MEIYINTANG COLLECTION,'' China Institute, 125 E. 65th St., (212)
744-8181. Through June 18. Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 10
a.m. to 5 p.m.; Tuesdays and Thursdays, to 8 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 5
p.m. Admission: $3; $2 for students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``FOR THE NEW CENTURY: JAPANESE TREASURES FROM THE ASIAN ART
MUSEUM OF SAN FRANCISCO,'' Japan Society, 333 E. 47th St., (212)
832-1155. Through July 9. Hours: Tuesdays through Fridays, 11 a.m.
to 6 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.. Admission: $5;
$3 for students and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE INTERNATIONAL ASIAN ART FAIR,'' Seventh Regiment Armory,
643 Park Ave., at 66th Street, (212) 642-8572. Through Wednesday.
Hours: Friday, Saturday, Monday and Tuesday, 11 a.m. to 8 p.m.;
Sunday and Wednesday, 11 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission: $15.
</P>
<P>
   BRENDA JOY LEM, Museum of Chinese in the Americas, 70 Mulberry
St., Chinatown, (212) 619-4785. Through June 30. Hours: Tuesdays
through Saturdays, noon to 5. Admission: $3; $1 for students and
the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``MASTERPIECES FROM ANCIENT CHINA: MILLENNIUM EXHIBITION,''
Guiseppe Eskenazi at PaceWildenstein Gallery, 32 E. 57th St., (212)
421-3237. Through April 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``REALMS OF FAITH,'' Kaikodo, 164 E. 64th St., (212) 223-0121.
Through April 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``SHEER REALITIES: CLOTHING AND POWER IN 19TH-CENTURY
PHILIPPINES,'' Grey Art Gallery and Study Center, New York
University, 100 Washington Square East, Greenwich Village, (212)
998-6780. Through April 22. Hours: Tuesdays through Fridays, 11
a.m. to 6 p.m.; Wednesdays to 8 p.m.; Saturdays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Free.
</P>
<P>
   ``SPIRITUAL PERFECTION: RELIGIOUS SCULPTURES OF SOUTH AND
SOUTHEAST ASIA,'' Asia Society at Midtown, 502 Park Ave., at 59th
Street, (212) 517-2742. Through April 1. Hours: Mondays through
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission: $4; $2 for students and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``TREASURES FROM ANCIENT BEIJING,'' Christie's, 20 Rockefeller
Plaza, (212) 636-2000. Through April 2. Hours: Mondays through
Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 5 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WORLD OF SCHOLARS' ROCKS: GARDENS, STUDIOS AND
PAINTINGS,'' Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth Avenue and 82nd
Street, (212) 879-5500. Through Aug. 20. Hours: Sundays and
Tuesdays through Thursdays, 9:30 a.m. to 5:15 p.m.; Fridays and
Saturdays to 8:45 p.m. Admission: $10; $5 for students and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
