<HEADLINE>
EERIE `WAKING' WORKS AS GHOST STORY AS WELL AS ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 OUR GRADE: B  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hero of the eerie romantic ghost story ``Waking the Dead''
is Fielding Pierce (Billy Crudup), a law student who, in the winter
of 1974, suddenly learns his fiancee, Sarah (Jennifer Connolly),
has been killed by a bomb set off by agents of the Chilean
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back two years to 1972. Fielding is a right-leaning young
Coast Guard officer intent on a big political career who meets the
idealistic and left-leaning Sarah in his brother's office, falls
madly in love with her, and begins a relationship that defies their
ideological differences.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward 10 years to 1982, and Fielding _ a cocky, shoo-in
candidate put up by the local Democratic Party machine to fill a
recently vacated seat in the U.S. Congress _ abruptly, out of
nowhere, starts seeing the image of the dead Sarah virtually
everywhere he goes. But when he looks again, the image has
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   From this intriguing setup, the movie flashes back and forth
between the two decades, tracing the course of the love affair and
the events leading to Sarah's death in the '70s, and the emotional
crisis that arises in Fielding in the '80s as he realizes he is
facing either the ghost or the reality of the love whose loss he
never got over.
</P>
<P>
   It's a likably odd little riff on the basic ``Vertigo'' premise,
nicely adapted from a novel by Scott Spencer (``Endless Love'').
The film was directed by Keith Gordon (``The Chocolate War,''
``Mother Night''), who has a keen eye for period detail and a
pleasing penchant for letting his actors develop their characters
in long, somewhat static, dialogue scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Intentional or not (and, given the timing, probably not), the
film apes the tone and visual style of ``The Sixth Sense,'' with
its slow fades to black between scenes, its resolutely somber mood,
its refreshing lack of tricky special effects, its minimalist urban
locations and its bleak, wintry setting.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also very much its own thing, a film with a real depth,
resonance and texture, and room for an ensemble of supporting
characters. Among them are Hal Holbrook as an old-line machine pol,
Janet McTeer as Fielding's artist sister, Paul Hipp as Fielding's
reprehensible publisher brother, and Molly Parker as the
long-suffering new love in Fielding's life.
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite as successful as Gordon's last film _ the
underrated 1996 Kurt Vonnegut adaptation ``Mother Night'' _ but
``Waking the Dead'' definitely works. Crudup and Connolly are both
unusual and unusually appealing young stars, the chemistry between
them is potent, and their teaming creates a palpable sense of
haunting, breathless romance.
</P>
<P>
   Waking the Dead. Directed by Keith Gordon. Written by Robert
Dillon and Keith Gordon. Cast: Billy Crudup, Jennifer Connolly, Hal
Holbrook, Janet McTeer. USA Films. 103 minutes. Rated R for
language, sexuality and brief nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
