<HEADER>
A6048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CASTLE-DRAWING-REVIEW     03-23 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASTLE-DRAWING-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEAF, MUTE ARTIST CONVERSES WITH HIS DRAWINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to New York Times photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the more disconcerting shows of the season
consists of drawings by James Castle, who was born in 1900 in
Garden Valley, Idaho. The youngest of seven children, he grew up in
the family house, which doubled as a dry goods store and the local
post office. His mother was a midwife who went about her duties on
horseback.
</P>
<P>
   The family house was a busy place. If James Castle took little
or no part in its activities, it was because he was born deaf and
mute. He made no attempt to mitigate these handicaps. (Sent to a
special school when he was 12, he refused to take any part in its
activities and was eventually sent home.)
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that interested him was drawing. It was in
drawing that he could record and structure his existence. His
parents did their best to foster this activity and would have
gladly provided him with conventional drawing materials. But he
insisted that he could draw only with materials provided (and often
invented) by himself.
</P>
<P>
   He made his own substitutes for pencils and pens. He also made
his own colors and worked with found papers, soot, string, colored
pulp and cardboard. He used sharpened sticks instead of brushes.
</P>
<P>
   Disregarding the very notion of ordinary ink, he used _ so the
catalog tells us _ ``a composite of spit mixed with soot taken from
wood-burning and, later, oil-burning stoves.'' When color was
called for, he made a pulp from water and ground colored paper that
he mashed into the artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Put like that, these methods may sound messy almost to the point
of perversity. But to see a large room full of Castle's mostly
quite small drawings is, on the contrary, a remarkable experience.
His lifelong subject matter was his own surroundings, sometimes
drawn from memory and at other times directly. They were never
``improved'' or prettified, although sometimes a patch of bright
color might sing out from the matchboxes or scraps of found paper
from the post office. (Mail order catalogs, left over from the post
office, were useful but not flaunted.)
</P>
<P>
   As he had never been taught drawing, he clearly went his own
way, but with a sureness of touch and an intensity of concentration
that have a cumulative effect as our tour proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   What emerges in the end is an autobiography in which scene after
scene is set, but nothing is ever seen to happen. Clothes are hung
but never worn. Dishes are laid out on a shelf, as if in readiness
for a little party, but no guest ever comes. There is an ``interior
with friends,'' but the friends are not brought to life. We even
see the interior of the general store in some detail, but nobody is
at home.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that all the interiors we see are ones that Castle
had lived in and knew in their every detail. The same applies to
the much smaller number of farm exteriors. But whether the scenes
are indoors or out, James Castle's is the predominant presence. He
does not need to show us what he looks like. ``I draw, therefore I
am'' was his lifelong attitude.
</P>
<P>
   It is important that these are not examples of what is sometimes
called ``other art.'' They are everyday art, often at a remarkably
high level of sureness, stage setting and inner conviction. The
more you see of it, the more you want to see. There is no generic
Castle. ``Seen one, seen them all'' would be a totally mistaken
response.
</P>
<P>
   They are not naive, either. Castle drew only what he knew and
not what he guessed at. To the actual execution of each drawing _
the choice of materials, the mixing and making of their physical
substances, and sometimes their wrapping or tying up _ he proved
himself the master of a craft of which he is the only known
practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   Never to have spoken a normal word and never to have heard a
human voice are terrible deprivations. It does not seem that Castle
ever learned to write. His drawings were his conversation, his
autobiography, his report from a world of silence and
speechlessness.
</P>
<P>
   It is in his drawings that he talked, in his own way. He knew
what to stress, when to leave off and when to spring a little
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   He also did the work of a social historian in an area and at a
time that has not often been recorded with such subtlety and so
detailed an appreciation. For that, thanks are due to Jay Tobler, a
longtime student of Castle's work. His catalog notes are required
reading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
