</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENETRATING THE SECRETS OF THE HARSH RED PLANET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSION TO MARS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sinise, Tim Robbins, Don Cheadle, Connie Nielsen, Jerry
O'Connell, Kim Delaney &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brian De Palma &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 113 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If he ever escapes the interminable backyard barbecue that
begins this movie, Luke (Cheadle) will lead a manned flight to the
red planet. During the party, though, he and the NASA gang all
agree that Jim McConnell (Sinise) should be commanding the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since McConnell's wife, also an astronaut, became ill and
died, McConnell has been too depressed for space work. Now he can
only smile wistfully while everybody makes it more than clear what
a shame it is that he (like the Sinise character in ``Apollo 13'')
will stay behind.
</P>
<P>
   Just as well. Cut to Cydonia, Mars, where Luke and crew spot a
white nose-shaped thing jutting from the red hilltops. Approaching
the area cautiously, they send what must be the wrong signals
because a giant whirlwind arises, destroying them and revealing a
huge human face.
</P>
<P>
   Back on Earth there is nothing to do but mount an investigatory
mission. This time the commander is the jaunty Woody Blake
(Robbins), but he insists that McConnell be included. Also along
are Terri (Nielsen), who seems mainly interested in getting her
hands on Woody, and Phil (O'Connell), an excitable techie who cries
``Please work!'' in tight situations.
</P>
<P>
   Many hazards and one calamity mar the approach to the Martian
surface. On the ground we learn why gardening is a good skill to
have on other planets. But it is left to McConnell to figure out
the face and what it wants. Buckle up for a celestial crescendo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE People implode and fly apart, and while this isn't
extremely graphic, it is real enough to upset some young viewers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX No actual sex, but Woody and Terri float around cooing,
smooching and growling at each other to the point where one thinks
this mission is about to sail off on another tangent altogether. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Astronauts under stress cuss some. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6 The film is too loud, violent and complicated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-10 They should be at least half on board, although some
could have a rough jolt or two at scarier moments (which are
moderately scary) and have trouble following some of the deductions
and explanations. Parents should give careful consideration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11 AND UP There shouldn't be a problem. More sophisticated
teen-agers may pass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ERIN BROCKOVICH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts, Albert Finney, Aaron Eckhart, Cherry Jones, Peter
Coyote, Veanne Cox &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Steven Soderbergh &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 127 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too stunning by half for the fix she's in, Erin Brockovich
(Roberts) finds herself dropped from the sky with three children,
no prospects and no money. Two ex-husbands and plenty of attitude
indicate that Erin isn't that easy to be around on occasion, but it
remains all but impossible to pin destitution on Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   But on with the story, which is a true one. After discovering
her life experiences count for little on the job market, Erin
manages to talk her way into the employ of a rumpled
ambulance-chasing lawyer named Ed (Finney). Assigning her to filing
and sorting, Ed hands her a box of stuff pertaining to a pro bono
real estate matter. Taking the material home with her, Erin notices
something odd. Mixed in with papers about a house sale are the
homeowner's medical records.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping into her battered flivver, Erin drives deep into the
desertlike Los Angeles exurbs to interview the woman named in the
file. Here begins a movielong expose of a power company's efforts
to avoid the fact that chromium from its plants is spreading
illness and death.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty abrasive around the office, Erin talks Ed into letting
her investigate and soon is crawling around wells, collecting dead
polliwogs and running into scores of folks with histories of
cancer, miscarriages and hysterectomies.
</P>
<P>
   On the romantic front she comes up with George (Eckhart), a kind
of Heck's Angels motorcyclist and sweet guy who is content to
baby-sit in return for being Erin's new boyfriend. Meanwhile, the
power company turns threatening, Ed begins to realize he has lucked
into one of the biggest damage cases in United States history and
Erin, bursting with righteous indignation, shows she's up for a
court battle. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Erin uses her cleavage to help the case, and there is other
talk about sex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY The dialogue is set up for Brockovich retorts and
wisecracks, many of them loaded with obscenities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-14 Language earns the R rating. If that isn't too much
of a problem, parents wouldn't be entirely remiss in letting
children attend a film that, for all its stacking of the emotional
deck in favor of Roberts/Brockovich, is entertaining and relatively
harmless.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP They'll go if they like. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINAL DESTINATION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Devon Sawa, Ali Larter, Kerr Smith. Kristen Cloke, Seann William
Scott, Tony Todd &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by James Wong &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 110 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rustling curtains and lightning streaks signal a hex on the
Mount Abraham High School senior trip to Paris, but it takes a
premonition of disaster to make Alex Browning (Sawa) rear out of
his seat and frantically want off the plane shortly before takeoff.
In the ensuing commotion he and six others from the group end up
back in the terminal, where they watch the ascending plane explode
and sprinkle the ocean with flaming debris.
</P>
<P>
   What starts as another Hollywood salute to commercial aviation
then settles down to a story of teen-age horror. Those victims on
the flight were meant to die, and by leaving the plane beforehand
the survivors defied Death's plan. But that doesn't excuse them
from the process. Just home from the airport, one shaken student
manages to not so accidentally strangle himself in his bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a truly unusual mishap, a teacher who also left the
plane spills some vodka into her computer, whereupon it detonates
and slashes her throat with a piece of metal and sets off other
bizarre incidents that culminate in her entire house blowing up.
</P>
<P>
   Since Alex seems to have foreknowledge, he is of primary
interest to the FBI. On the run, he and another survivor named
Clear (Larter) must figure out who's next on Death's list, not that
it matters much. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE This is a blood bath _ not a pretty sight in the
least. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Maybe later, but for now there are other matters to attend
to. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Obscenity to match. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14-17 Reaching for the satiric flavor of other ``Scream''
knockoffs with a supernatural twist, the film will be a hoot to
many teen-agers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
