<SLUG> BC-FILM-ONEGIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIENNES SIBLINGS TEAM UP FOR CHILLY `ONEGIN' ADAPTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is an aloofness to director Martha Fiennes' adaptation of
Aleksandr Pushkin's 150-year-old tragedy about infatuation and
loss, but it's hard to fault her for the chilliness that permeates
her stunning movie.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly its main character, Evgeny Onegin (Ralph Fiennes, the
director's brother), is no hearth of warmth. He's a disaffected
Russian dilettante who regretfully, but out of necessity, leaves a
dissolute life of gambling and romance in St. Petersburg after he
inherits a country estate from his late uncle.
</P>
<P>
   In the bleak and cold rural place, Onegin has little to do but
look for ways to fill his idle time. So the bored womanizer begins
to flirt with Olga (Lena Headey), fiancee of the passionate,
insecure Vladimir (Toby Stephens). But it is really Tatyana (Liv
Tyler), Olga's younger sister, who catches his eye.
</P>
<P>
   In a quest for her love that begets disappointment, Onegin must
muster the courage to understand his own heart _ even if it
perpetuates the loss of that which he purports to love most.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Fienne's adaptation of Pushkin's novel is eerily
beautiful, stark and wintry, with an exceptional and haunting
visual scheme. The film is so full of atmosphere that ``Onegin''
might be a completely chilly trip if not for the performances of
Headey and Stephens (son of Dame Maggie Smith) as impassioned
lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Fiennes is so appropriately iceberglike that he could sink
the Titanic. While his icy persona works in the context of the
story, we can never warm up to him. His Onegin is clueless to
anything other than the sensual world, and is finally more
repellent than sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Onegin. Directed by Martha Fiennes. Written by Michael
Ignatieff, Peter Itedgui. Cast: Ralph Fiennes, Liv Tyler, Lena
Headey, Martin Donovan, Toby Stephens. Samuel Goldwyn. 106 minutes.
Not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
