<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COBBLING TOGETHER THIS REALLY CUTE YOUNG BAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area; check local listings.)  
 (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a scientific formula behind the hottest boy bands like
'N Sync. You need the cute blonde guy, the sensitive dark-eyed guy
and the guy who looks like he's really 34.
</P>
<P>
   If the outer age limit of the group in ``Making the Band'' seems
lower, more like 27, that's because this series is ``The Real
World'' for 10-year-olds. The show constructs from scratch a new
group called O-Town, with cameras capturing auditions that pare
down the applicants to the eight chosen at the end of Frinight's
premiere. Over the next weeks they will compete for the five slots
in the band, and O-Town will be ready to record, make money and
appear on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, grown-ups can mull over a philosophical issue: even
more than MTV's ``Real World,'' which throws strangers together in
one house, even more than CBS' summer ``Survivor,'' which will
throw strangers together on one tropical island, this kiddie
version of a reality show depicts a purely manufactured
``reality.'' O-Town is a shrewdly devised commercial product, as
artificial as real people can be.
</P>
<P>
   That cynical view exists well beneath the engaging surface,
though. The band members' personalities are appealing, and among
the 25 semifinalists (ages 18 to 25) a few stand out right away.
There is Ikaika from Honolulu, cute and brown-eyed, with a passing
resemblance to Billy Crudup.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob, with curly blonde hair, vaguely brings to mind 'N Sync's
heartthrob Justin Timberlake, though he looks more like an earlier
teen-age idol, Mark Wahlberg. Echoing established stars may be more
at a premium here than being a fresh face.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor, a tall Californian, looks mature but as the cameras find
him in his family's kitchen, he cries when saying that if he makes
the band he'll use the money to help his parents. He is biracial,
and though the show (at least in its first episodes) does not
discuss the group's need for ethnic balance, it is clearly a factor
in the package. And Erik can really sing, which is a help but not
anyone's first priority.
</P>
<P>
   A stylish mix of candid documentary film and
talking-to-the-camera interviews, the show looks like ``The Real
World'' for a reason; it has the same producers. Musical scenes of
the auditions and of dance and vocal practices become sharply
edited mini-music videos; another producer is MTV.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a good reason why O-Town's slick choreographed
look and syrupy, homogenized sound is familiar. On and off camera,
the figure behind the group is Lou Pearlman, who was manager of 'N
Sync and the Backstreet Boys until lawsuits by those groups,
settled out of court, freed them from what sounds like the musical
version of indentured servitude. (Don't expect any mention of
lawsuits on this show.)
</P>
<P>
   On screen, the portly Pearlman resembles an older version of the
actor Philip Seymour Hoffman, so good in creepy roles; this is not
exactly the image of the benevolent father.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is happily on the boys, though. The eight finalists
move into a house together in Orlando, the home base that gives the
band its name. The cameras trail along as the boys phone their old
girlfriends and try to be true, though there are groupies in the
wings. Everything is perfectly calculated to play to
pre-adolescents' obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   And though ``Making the Band'' is not meant to offer an overt
lesson in evolution, the eight finalists have entered a Darwinian
world. Three will be eliminated, but no sooner than episode 10.
There is plenty of time for friendly bonding and fierce
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's episode ends with a vocal coach reprimanding the
boys for arriving at a practice session late. ``You already know
how many talented people are out there,'' he says. ``You
(italics)can(end italics) be replaced. Quickly.'' Apparently it's
never too soon to learn about cutthroat careerism, even in the
guise of a wholesome boy band's saga. There's reality for you. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MAKING THE BAND' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday at 9 p.m. on ABC (Channel 7 in New York) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Bunim/Murray Productions and MTV Productions. Ken
Mok, executive producer for MTV Productions; Mary-Ellis Bunim and
Jonathan Murray, executive producers for Bunim/Murray Productions;
Clay Newbill, supervising producer; Kathy Wetherell, line producer;
C.B. Harding, lead director for the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
