<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ANTIQUE-MAIN24-COX     03-23 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUE-MAIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Show creates interest in that junk in the attic
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Betty Carr has three items in a bag by
her side.
</P>
<P>
   She pulls them out, one by one, and tells their stories. Or what
she knows of them, at least.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a ``very old porcelain doll,'' with a simple, flowing
dress. It was once her godmother's. Here's a figurine of a black
child eating a slice of watermelon. He's perched atop a pincushion,
an item that falls into a collector's category of ``black
memorabilia.''
</P>
<P>
   And here's a toy dog, a spooky-looking, mangy thing with wooden
wheels on its feet and holes in its face. She bought it, in a
boxful of stuff, for $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, you see his stuffing is coming out,'' Carr
says, as she points to the toy's two gnarled spots. ``I had a real
dog that was jealous of it, and he chewed it. I don't know anything
about it, though.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why she _ and more than 500 others _ are at the
Appraisal Fair 2000, which was held earlier this month. In its
second year, the Appraisal Fair is a free service provided by
Interior Marketplace, an upscale consignment shop in Tequesta.
Seven professional appraisers came from as far away as New York to
look at everything from oil paintings to comic books.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons so many people came out today is because of
the popularity of the public television program, ``Antiques
Roadshow.'' At least, that's what most of folks here are saying.
The show documents free antique appraisals ... and collectors'
reactions when they find out that old lamp is actually a $10,000
Tiffany. (A recent episode of the popular sitcom ``Frasier''
revolved around the upscale Crane brothers' fascination with
``Roadshow.'')
</P>
<P>
   Basically, ``Roadshow'' is making people reevaluate the stuff
that once would've gone in the box labeled, ``For Yard Sale.''
</P>
<P>
   ``See, people are really interested in what's in their attic,''
says Rusty LaScala, organizer of the Appraisal Fair. ``They really
want to know about their old possessions, and if they're valuable.
It's definitely worth investigating.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the news came at the fair. And for most folks, it was
good. Bob and Beverly Cowan were ``elated'' when their gold
bracelet was appraised for more than $2,000. Susan and Eddie Rieck
of Jupiter were surprised to hear that a reproduction of a Rodin
sculpture they bought for $100 was actually worth about $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   Another fellow had items dating back to the Civil War:
Confederate bonds, letters, report cards ... all signed by Robert
E. Lee. The appraisers were a little overwhelmed, trying to make an
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   They said they'd get back to him.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also a day of heartbreak. There were a few fake
paintings, and ``antique'' dolls that were actually made only a few
years ago. And there was stuff that looked valuable but would fetch
only $100, at best. One woman was told there wasn't much of a
market for old, German-made accordions these days. Another woman
complained that her ivory business-card holder _ which was carved
in mind-boggling detail _ was worth $500 less than a simpler
carving owned by her sister.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there isn't much a market for that, either.
</P>
<P>
   David Hochstetler had a good day, though. He brought in a framed
original 1896 presidential campaign poster: ``McKinley and Hobart:
Republican nominees.'' The Palm Beach Gardens resident got it at a
flea market for $50 in 1988. With a little restoration, it could go
for $500.
</P>
<P>
   And Betty Carr? At first, it was bad news. Her porcelain doll,
which she thought could be at least 90 years old, was only about
50.
</P>
<P>
   The black memorabilia is worth about $75, she was told.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's that creepy dog toy. At the fair, appraiser Tim
Luke examines it gingerly, and looks at Carr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Steiff,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Carr gasps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is? Oh my GOD!'' she cries, recognizing the German name _
and its legacy in the toy business. ``I didn't know! I had no
idea!''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the condition, it could sell for $200 to $300, Luke
tells her. Not a bad return on a $10 investment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if it were in better shape, it could have fetched
$800 to $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh well. I can't punish the dog,'' Carr says, after the
appraisal. ``He died a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
