<HEADLINE>
GERMAN WINS UNANIMOUS APPROVAL TO HEAD IMF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa)  (js) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Horst Koehler of Germany became the International
Monetary Fund's managing director Thursday just as the Clinton
administration and members of Congress were discussing how the
agency might be improved.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, 57, the president of the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, was unanimously endorsed by the 24
members of the IMF board of directors, putting an end to an awkward
episode in which Koehler became Germany's second choice for the job
after its first candidate failed to garner broad international
support. Koehler succeeds Michel Camdessus of France.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Koehler had become a virtual certainty in recent
days. Last week, he said his goals for the 182-nation organization
included making it ``a cornerstone for promoting growth and
stability'' around the world and having a better relationship with
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers talked about those very
things Thursday before the House Banking Committee, where he
defended the core missions of the IMF and its sister institution,
the World Bank. While conceding that they had made mistakes,
Summers said that the IMF and World Bank were vital, for reasons
both humanitarian and practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Countries that are helped to succeed economically are much
more likely to become democratic, and their people more likely to
avoid debilitating disease, to learn to read and to work with human
dignity,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the experience of Germany in the 1930s to Bosnia and
Africa in more recent times, history teaches us that conflicts are
most likely in situations of economic distress, when populations
turn their frustration to nationalist leaders because of a lack of
a sense of economic opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and World Bank were created in the mid 1940s to promote
economic stability around the world and lend money to developing
countries. Congressional critics say the institutions have
sometimes doled out money unwisely to try to bring about social
change, or lent it to recipients with unclean hands. A
congressional panel headed by Allan Meltzer, an economics professor
at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh, recommended recently
that the roles of the IMF and World Bank be sharply curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   Recent IMF loans to Ukraine proved embarrassing after it was
revealed that officials there might have manipulated foreign
exchange reserves to create false optimism about the country's
financial condition. Summers said the administration had found that
affair troubling and had pressed the IMF to put new lending
safeguards in place.
</P>
<P>
   Summers also used the hearings to promote his own proposals to
introduce changes in how the IMF and the World Bank work. He has
suggested that the IMF focus more on making short-term loans to
countries that have financial crises and less on long-term lending
and development assistance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The secretary also outlined a program of changes for the World
Bank, a plan first introduced in a speech earlier this week. He
said the bank should take steps to make sure that its loans do not
crowd out money that could be provided by the private sector. It
should also limit its assistance to countries that do not have a
good track record for using development loans effectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said he was troubled with the Meltzer panel's most
drastic recommendations, which the secretary said would hobble the
IMF. and World Bank to the point where they ``would no longer be
able to advance America's core values and interests around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Leach, the Iowa Republican who heads the banking
committee, said Thursday that he backed Koehler, but that the way
he was chosen ``lacked diplomatic sensitivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States opposed the first candidate to head the IMF,
Caio Koch-Weser of Germany. Stanley Fischer of the United States,
the IMF deputy managing director, and Eisuke Sakakibara, a former
Finance Ministry official in Japan, then emerged as candidates
before Koehler won out.
</P>
</TEXT>
