<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BAND-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAKING THE BAND' GOOD FOR THE DREAMER IN US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's not about being famous. This is about music.''
</P>
<P>
   With these words forming our TGIF mantra, we wade happily,
warily into the latest selective-reality series from Bunim/Murray
Productions, packagers of ``The Real World'' and ``Road Rules'' for
MTV.
</P>
<P>
   This one, called ``Making the Band,'' starts Friday night on
ABC, allowing millions more the voyeuristic thrills cable audiences
have cherished for years. Bunim/Murray Productions does this sort
of thing so often that anyone who has seen their other work will
know what's coming in Friday's one-hour setup: the teary goodbyes
at the airport, the hopeful expressions of confidence, the
immediate bonding when the gang is assembled. The big difference
this time: The selection process isn't over yet. Well, it is in
real life, but for the purposes of ``reality'' TV, it's not.
Friday, in short order, we see a thousand hopefuls whittled to 25,
and then to eight. Over the next 13 episodes, that group is further
reduced to five lucky guys who will become the hot new boy band,
O-Town, if Lou Pearlman has anything to say about it.
</P>
<P>
   Pearlman, who helped launch such pop-culture phenomena as
Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync, is assembling what he and ABC hope
will be the next pop group to send teens scurrying to the record
stores.
</P>
<P>
   The hook for TV viewers? They get to look in as the final cuts
are made. Think of it as the next best thing to having a camera in
the room the day Pete Best was told he was out as drummer of the
Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think for a minute that this is some lame-o lip-sync
agglomeration. It may not be Lennon, McCartney et al., but it's not
Milli Vanilli, either. Last November's eight-city tryouts, in
addition to gauging poise, personality and potential for making
young girls swoon, made sure that our O-Town candidates could carry
a tune, or at least pick it up and bounce it off their uvulas a few
times.
</P>
<P>
   Dancing was another matter. Some couldn't trip the light
fantastic without getting black and blue, but with a few lessons
and the knowledge that stardom is waiting in the wings, it's
amazing how even the stiffest hoofer can summon his terpsichorean
muse.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the spoken word, the one-hour premiere of
``Making the Band'' borders on tiresome. Expressions like the one
at the beginning of this piece, along with ``I can only do what I
can do,'' and ``I gave it my best,'' and ``Everybody's a winner in
this situation,'' and ``Everything happens for a reason,'' make a
baseball manager's post-game quotes sound like Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   But, if ``The Real World'' and ``Road Rules'' can be used as
benchmarks, the subsequent half-hour episodes should peel back the
layers of our eight finalists and reveal some authentic
personalities. And even if all eight continue to be as
fresh-scrubbed and downright agreeable as they seem tonight,
``Making the Band'' already promises to capture a thrill of
victory/agony of defeat ethos that's irresistible to the average
dreamer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, even if the music makes you wince, watching a bunch of
young guys have the run of a luxury pad in Orlando _ O-Town, get
it? _ as they chase their dreams is like having a backstage pass
every week.
</P>
<P>
   Making the Band. Half-hour reality series about the making of a
male pop band. One-hour series premiere is Friday on ABC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
