<HEADER>
A6059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ANTIQUESIDE24-COX     03-23 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUESIDE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appraise-worthy item was right in plain sight
 &HT;    By Chris Hutchins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The plan: Go to the Appraisal Fair 2000,
talk to some folks, come back with a story.
</P>
<P>
   And while you're at it, the boss said, take something of your
own to be appraised.
</P>
<P>
   Cool.
</P>
<P>
   So I went home and started thinking. The synapses fired for a
good half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Should I take in some of my vintage ``Star Wars'' toys? How
about my Lego collection, complete with two very hard-to-find
``viewscreen'' pieces thatappeared in only one set from the late
1970s? I couldn't forget my growing collection of DC superhero
action figures, or my comic books.
</P>
<P>
   I grinned. Decisions, decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But the smile faltered. I'm right out of college. I'm really not
old enough _ or wealthy enough _ to have acquired anything truly
antique-y. Anything I consider ``valuable'' is low-quality,
mass-produced, and less than 20 years old. I realized I had no
one-of-a-kind treasures in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, I don't even have an attic.
</P>
<P>
   But the synapses kept firing: What about ``Superman 75,'' the
issue where the Man of Steel is killed by a supervillain? Nah, too
common. My bootleg Beatles CDs? Nope. Too illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket stubs from a B-52s concert?
</P>
<P>
   Old college textbooks?
</P>
<P>
   My high school ID card?
</P>
<P>
   I shuddered. Was there anything I owned _ anything at all _ that
was valuable?
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly, Beethoven's ``Ode To Joy'' blared in my ears. I
looked at the walls in my apartment and saw the answer: Two framed
magazine stories, personality profiles I had written two years ago,
signed by the folks I had interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   You've probably never heard of Devin Grayson and Bernie
Wrightson, but that doesn't matter. Devin writes comic books.
Bernie draws them. Devin's been in the comic-book business for
about three years; Bernie, about 30. I went to their homes and
interviewed them back in '97, for Wizard magazine.
</P>
<P>
   And this is what I'd take to the Appraisal Fair. Bernie, with
his blue-inked invitation: ``Hey Chris! Come on out to L.A.! Cold
beer's on me!'' And Devin, with her polite compliments: ``It was
nice getting to know you as you got to know me.'' Truly unique
items. Probably not worth $20 between them, but unique nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   When I got to the fair, I was pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wrote the story. It's your byline there, on the page. And
you had these artists sign it to you. Collectors go crazy for that
stuff,'' appraiser Tim Luke told me. ``But because they signed it
to you, it limits the interested parties. In essence, you've
limited this to all the 'Chrises' of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   I could live with that.
</P>
<P>
   If I were to sell Devin's autograph, Luke said, it'd go for
anywhere from $75 to $125. See, appraising for the comic-book
market is tricky: The fan base is ferocious, but fickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have a fan say, 'Wow. I gotta have this' and another
might say, 'I don't want that,''' Luke explained. ``This is
difficult to say. You've got the signature, but there's not a whole
lot of value right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernie's autograph was a different story. He's been drawing
horror comics for the past three decades. He's worked with Stephen
King. He's considered the father of the modern horror comic. His
original artwork has sold for thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great piece, because Bernie is such a fantastic
artist,'' Luke said. ``And his signature is known by most comic
fans. Some say, 'Oh my gosh, I'd buy anything signed by Bernie
Wrightson.' ... If you were to sell it now, it could go for $125 to
$200.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow. Two hundred clams for a hastily written invitation to get
soused. God, I love this country.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Luke what would increase the value of my framed
autographs. ``The future success of the artists,'' he replied. Or
the future success of the magazine the stories were published in.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. I wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if I win a Pulitzer Prize?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   Luke laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could make all the difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah. I'm sitting on a gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
