<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ODONOHUE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Combining Celtic spirituality with traditional theology
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ John O'Donohue found himself in California on St.
Patrick's Day this year, where he did not drink green beer or wear
a shamrock. Americans, it seems, have gotten a bit carried away. It
was almost enough to send him running back to his native County
Clare, Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But he stuck around for his national book tour, to promote his
latest spiritual effort, ``Eternal Echoes: Celtic Reflections on
Our Yearning to Belong'' (Cliff Street Books, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Like his first book, ``Anam Cara,'' (''Soul Friend,'') ``Eternal
Echoes'' plumbs Celtic wisdom to seek answers to contemporary
spiritual ills. O'Donohue, who has a doctorate in philosophical
theology, draws upon his own background in Catholic theology, but
also draws from Zen Buddhism, Jewish mysticism, Nietzsche and Jorge
Luis Borges. This time out, O'Donohue's focus is the deep sense of
loneliness that is fostered by modern life. ``On the surface, we've
never been more connected (to one another),'' he says, referring to
the Internet and other technology. ``But at the deeper level of the
heart and mind and spirit, there is such a haunting loneliness. ...
Where do I belong? Who do I belong with?''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks his books sell so well in the United States because so
many Americans have Irish roots. ``America is a young country. A
young country always has trouble with its (sense of) roots. There
have been a lot of fashions in spirituality: the Orient, Native
American. But Celtic mysticism ``is a return of something that is
our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he understands the study of comparative religion. ``It's
as if one mountain were the search for the divine, and each (faith)
tradition takes a different path to the top. You come away with a
sense of the individuality of each tradition, as well as a sharper
eye to the blindnesses of each tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donohue doesn't shy away from claiming his own Roman
Catholicism: ``The Catholic tradition is lovely, the sacraments are
beautiful, the intellectual substance is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he calls his own tradition to task for its authoritarianism
and its ``huge difficulty with the feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   He has hopes, though, that the church can continue to serve the
function it has always served: Through its tradition, it is ``the
great memory bank of a community.''
</P>
<P>
   The modern church, though, ``has syncopated the tradition into
an ideological mechanism.... The notion of Jesus (for example) has
become so simplified, so reductionist. He was hugely complex, an
outsider in his own tradition. (The church) has started off from a
living flame ... but it has become a cage of the flame, rather than
a source.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't write the book so that people would agree with him.
``I invite people to engage in conversation with their own
questions. That's what a good book should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
