u l BC-FACE-SIDEBAR24-COX     03-23 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACE-SIDEBAR24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beauty combines bone structure, skin
 &HT;    _ and a great personality doesn't hurt
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Despite what your mother told you,
beauty is more than skin deep.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of bones, muscles and proportion. At least that's
how plastic surgeons judge attractiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we think about what constitutes an attractive face,
without exception, there are two things that make that face
attractive,'' says Devinder Mangat, a Cincinnati surgeon and
president of the American Academy of Facial Plastic and
Reconstructive Surgery. ``One is the bone structure, and the other
is the quality of the skin covering that bony framework.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy recently asked its members to name their ideal faces
of beauty. Elizabeth Hurley and George Clooney topped the list,
which included Halle Berry and Ricky Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even among surgeons, we acquire our aesthetic concepts in a
variety of ways,'' Mangat says. Those concepts could be drawn from
movie stars, fashion models or people encountered in day-to-day
life. ``But ultimately, when a cosmetic surgeon looks at a face and
says whether it's attractive, he's really thinking more
analytically.''
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bones _ Strong jawbone, chin, cheekbones, nasal bone and the
bones around the eyes. ``If those bones aren't prominent enough,
the face doesn't acquire a chiseled or sculpted look,'' Mangat
says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Skin _ Skin that isn't oily, scarred or dotted with blemishes,
``thin skin'' with small pores. ``You can have good bone structure,
but if you don't have healthy skin on top of that, it takes away
from the good looks,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Muscles _ For example, the way a smile can light up someone's
face _ or make it look positively creepy. ``How muscles contract
causes changes in the face that could be attractive or not so
attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Balance _ Vertically, a well-proportioned face can be divided
into three parts of equal size: from the hairline to the eyebrows,
from the eyebrows to the bottom of the nose, and from the bottom of
the nose to the bottom of the chin. Horizontally, a balanced face
is five eyes wide.
</P>
<P>
   Michelangelo devised those formulas when he attempted to draw
the perfect face, Mangat says. ``We're still using some of those
parameters as facial plastic surgeons.''
</P>
<P>
   For the vast majority of us not blessed with physiological or
mathematical perfection, personality can be a saving grace.
Mangat's prime example: Cameron Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, Cameron Diaz. She's beyond hideous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to tell you she does not have what we consider an
ideal nose for a female,'' he says. ``But gosh, she's beautiful.
She's got the other ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
