<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d BC-OSCAR-PARTYTIPS24-COX     03-23 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-PARTYTIPS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A night to remember
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here are some tips on making your Oscars
party a winner. Roll 'em!
</P>
<P>
   _ The theme has to be films, but that's a broad category. If you
don't like this year's nominees, make a menu from the all-time
favorite flick of your choice. Best food picture award, if there
were one, would almost always go to the foreign films (``Babette's
Feast,'' ``Tampopo'' and ``Eat, Drink, Man, Woman'') and you can
take inspiration from them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Timing is everything. Since the awards show runs late on TV,
have enough nibbles to last through the night, especially if liquor
is on the menu. Two ways to serve liquor safely: Don't offer it
until food is served, then cut off service and switch to
after-dinner teas and coffees for the remainder of the party.
</P>
<P>
   _ Schedule dinner early to avoid missing any of the ceremony.
Alternately, win the award for ``most casual'' party, and have
guests eat at TV trays placed around the set.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dress up the mundane: Popcorn and chocolate-covered raisins
are tried-and-true movie party nibbles. But elevate the ideas, and
make tiny herbed popcorn balls or chocolate-dipped strawberries
instead.
</P>
<P>
   _ An Oscar party lends itself to potluck. Pick your starring
cooks carefully, though, for best results. As host, provide one
course and keep a list of the guest food, so you don't get
multiples of the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have ballots for voting along with the awards. Creative award
goes to the host who makes up new categories (and answers) for
voting _ the sillier, the better. Another game: Alternate casting
among friends. (Whom do you know who could have starred in place of
the actors in the nominated movies?) Award movie candy, books on
the movies or theater tickets to the winners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
