<HEADER>
A6065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d BC-OSCAR-RECIPES24-COX     03-23 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-RECIPES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And the Oscar for best recipe goes to ...
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here are recipes to go with some of the
movies nominated for this year's Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   This is simple, and best of all, can be made in advance. Use
home-grown, pesticide-free roses for food safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN BEAUTY ROSE PETAL SORBET
</P>
<P>
   2 egg whites, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 cup loosely packed red rose petals, rinsed and patted dry
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons rose syrup _ see note
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Candied rose petals, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl, beat egg whites with the cream of tartar until
stiff peaks form. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, combine the water and rose petals.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to a rolling boil.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat, and let steep, covered, for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With a slotted spoon, remove and discard rose petals. (Or shred
them, if desired, to fold back into the sorbet for color.)
</P>
<P>
   Add the sugar and rose syrup, and return to boil for 2 to 3
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, pour the boiling mixture in a slow stream into the
egg whites, beating continuously.
</P>
<P>
   Add the half-and-half and lemon juice, and beat the mixture for
1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Freeze until set, stirring several times during the freezing
process to prevent the mixture from separating.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, spoon sorbet into individual bowls, and garnish with
candied rose petals.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Rose syrup is available in shops that sell Middle Eastern
foods.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Edible Flowers, a Kitchen Companion,'' by Kitty Morse,
10-Speed Press, 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   CIDER HOUSE RULES POTATO AND APPLE SALAD WITH SWEET &AMP; TART
CURRANT VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   2 medium red-skinned potatoes, skin on, boiled and cooled
</P>
<P>
   2 Braeburn apples, cored
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup apple cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons red currant jelly
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   6 cups mesclun
</P>
<P>
   2 cups spinach leaves, stemmed
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces goat cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Make the vinaigrette: In a food processor, blend the apple cider
vinegar, horseradish, red currant jelly, 1/2 teaspoon salt and 1/2
teaspoon black pepper until smooth. Stir in mayonnaise,
incorporating it well.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the mesclun and spinach together with enough of the
vinaigrette to lightly coat the greens.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the salad on 4 individual serving plates.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the potatoes into small cubes and sprinkle on top of the
salads.
</P>
<P>
   Cut 1 and 1/2 of the apples into small dice and add to the
salads, reserving the remaining 1/2 apple for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle the remaining vinaigrette over the salads.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the goat cheese on top of the salads.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the 1/2 apple as garnish and arrange on salad dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Adapted from ``Main Course Salads'' by Ray Overton, Longstreet
Press, 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   TUMBLEWEEDS TEX-MEX CHILI MELT
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound ground sirloin
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons powdered chili mix
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces thinly sliced jalapeno jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 slices rye and onion bread
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   For condiments:
</P>
<P>
   Chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   Chopped jalapeno peppers
</P>
<P>
   Chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   In a mixing bowl, mix ground sirloin, chili mix, and salt and
pepper. Divide into two mounds. Press each mound into a slight
rectangle to fit bread.
</P>
<P>
   Butter one side of each slice of bread; set half the bread
aside. Heat a cast-iron skillet or heavy griddle over medium heat.
Add one slice of bread, butter-side-down and top with meat patty.
Cook until bread is lightly grilled. Flip sandwich so meat is
cooking on bottom of pan. When meat is nearly cooked through, turn
sandwich again and top with uncooked bread, butter-side-up. Flip
sandwich to grill bread and finish cooking meat.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with second sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Serve garnished with chili sauce, jalapeno peppers and chopped
onions. Tobacco onion rings, below, make a great accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   Makes two sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   (Recipe adapted from traditional recipe for patty melt.)
</P>
<P>
   A whistle-blower is central to the story of ``The Insider,'' a
movie about the tobacco industry. The onions below are so named
because they resemble strings of tobacco when cut thinly.
</P>
<P>
   THE INSIDER TOBACCO ONION RINGS
</P>
<P>
   5 cups peanut oil, for frying
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons chile molido, or other pure red chile powder
</P>
<P>
   1/3 teaspoon salt, plus more to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 large white onion, very thinly sliced into rings
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil to 375 degrees in a deep fryer or deep, heavy
skillet. In a mixing bowl, combine the flour, cayenne, chile
molido, salt and pepper. Place the buttermilk in a separate bowl.
Dip sliced onions into the buttermilk to moisten, draining off
excess. Dip onions into the seasoned flour, thoroughly coating and
shaking off excess.
</P>
<P>
   Place coated onion rings in hot oil and fry until golden brown,
2 to 3 minutes. Remove from skillet and drain on paper towels while
the rings are still hot. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Red Sage'' by Mark Miller, 1999, 10-Speed Press.)
</P>
<P>
   Denzel Washington is up for a best-actor award for his role as
boxer Ruben Carter in ``The Hurricane.'' Our drink, a hurricane, is
a staple of coastal Florida bars.
</P>
<P>
   THE HURRICANE HURRICANE 1 ounce light rum
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce gold rum
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce passion fruit syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Pour all ingredients into cocktail shaker. Shake with ice;
strain and pour into cocktail glass.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 drink.
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Atomic Bodyslams to Whiskey Zippers: Cocktails for the
21st Century,'' Adam Rocke, Surrey Books.)
</P>
<P>
   These jazz-brunch eggs are a perfect late-night food, prepared
ahead, to serve for late-nighters. They're good, too, for a brunch.
Play them up if Sean Penn wins best actor for his role as a jazz
guitarist in Woody Allen's ``Sweet and Lowdown.''
</P>
<P>
   SWEET AND LOWDOWN JAZZ BRUNCH EGGS IN A TOMATO NEST
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons plus 2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 medium vine-ripened tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped fresh chervil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound garden lettuces
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the bread crumbs with 2 teaspoons olive oil and a pinch of
salt. Place on a baking sheet in the hot oven for 5 to 6 minutes to
dry them out. Do not brown. Remove from the oven and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse and dry off tomatoes. Insert a sharp paring knife into the
top of each tomato and cut out a 2-inch diameter section. Gently
remove pulp and seeds with a spoon to create a little cup. Season
the tomatoes liberally with salt. Crack an egg into each tomato.
Season eggs with salt and pepper. Put the tomatoes on a small sheet
pan or in a shallow baking dish and place them in the hot oven for
10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the tarragon, chervil and shallot with the bread crumbs
while the tomatoes are baking. After 10 minutes, sprinkle the bread
crumb mixture and 1/2 teaspoon of butter over the top of each egg.
Continue to bake for 6 more minutes or until the crumbs are golden
and the eggs are just set.
</P>
<P>
   Dress the garden lettuces with 2 tablespoons of oil and the
vinegar and place on four salad plates. Remove the tomatoes with a
spatula and nestle them into the lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
