<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6066 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BAND-REVIEW24-COX     03-23 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAND-REVIEW24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'N Synthetic: Casting the boy band
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You see them on MTV. Buy their CDs,
watch their videos.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync. The Backstreet Boys. 98 Degrees. Yes, boy pop bands are
all the rage. They make giggly girls swoon, pimply faced boys strut
and cash-starved record companies rich. But, ever wonder what it's
really like hoofin' and sweatin' with the same guys all the time?
</P>
<P>
   We never see close-up the grueling rehearsals,
confidence-draining insecurities and petty jealousies that make
being in a band an exhilarating, yet maddeningly frustrating
experience. Well, if you watch ``Behind the Music,'' you do see all
that juicy stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Making The Band,'' ABC's new ``Real World''-like series,
lets you see those real-life dramas while they're happening. The
promising reality series, produced by the same ``Real World'' of
MTV team, goes behind-the-scenes for the making of O-Town, a new
Orlando-based band. In tonight's opener, 25 finalists are chosen
from a nationwide talent search that took place in eight cities,
including New York, Los Angeles, Las Vegas and Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Hawaiian kid who can sing, but can't dance. ``If I
were only singing, I'd be kickin' a--, you know,'' he says. There's
the chick-obsessed guy who can't get screaming girl fans out of his
head. ``I wonder if there's going to be, like, teen-age girls in
the audience?'' he wonders. ``If there is, I'm going to try, like,
flirt a little bit and get them to make some noise.'' Then there's
the brooding guy who looks like he might give up on life if he's
doesn't become an O-Town member. ``I can't see myself going back to
school,'' he says almost despondently.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five finalists are narrowed down to eight tonight. The
five winners, however, won't be revealed until the 10th episode. In
the meantime, cameras will shadow the eight O-Town wannabes at
their rented Orlando pad. You'll see them practice five-part
harmony. Work on dance steps, and get chastised by their vocal
coach for showing up late for rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   They also brush their teeth and look nervous a lot.
</P>
<P>
   As the producers say, ``Making the Band,'' sort of ``The
Monkees'' meet The Backstreet Boys, will give you the ``whole''
story. But ``Making the Band,'' filmed in Orlando, isn't your
typical TGIF fare. It doesn't star annoyingly cute sitcom kids.
There's no laugh track or wacky next-door neighbors. That means the
series might actually boost ABC's once thriving Friday night
franchise. Teen girls will no doubt enjoy watching these baby doll
cute boys do their thing.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for ``Making the Band'' was hatched when Ken Mok
couldn't get into his MTV office in Times Square last August. There
were 5,000 kids jammed into the area to see 'N Sync on ``Total
Request Live.'' It dawned on Mok, an MTV vice president and
``Making the Band'' executive producer, that it would be
interesting to see how 'N Sync became a Beatles-like phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   But what about ``The Real World'' comparisons?
</P>
<P>
   ``This has a broader appeal than `The Real World','' says Jon
Murray, another executive producer. ``These boy bands are huge.
There's a whole soap opera aspect, the girls they leave behind and
how band members vie for leadership. It'll be more gritty than what
people are used to seeing on TGIF.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Young guys on the road. Tension. Stress. Girls. Should
be a lot of foul language, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these kids come from church choirs, so they're
well-spoken and use very little profanity,'' Murray says. ``We were
really shocked. There's very little bleeping we had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
