<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOBY24-COX     03-23 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moby: Electronica wiz after stints as DJ, punker
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Whatever you do, don't call him a DJ.
</P>
<P>
   That's the first lesson learned in a brief phone conversation
with Moby (real name Richard Melville Hall), the electronic artist
who has gone from a career on the club circuit to mainstream
success, replete with radio play, a couple of Grammy nominations
and a spot on the current ``MTV Campus Invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Moby, whose moniker derives from the fact he's a
direct descendant of ``Moby Dick'' author Herman Melville, can't
spin records with the best of them. It's that he chooses to define
his artistic life in broader terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DJ thing was a way to pay the rent, but my background is
as a musician,'' he says by phone from his New York apartment.
``I'm 34 years old, but I started playing guitar when I was 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Those years of training are starting to pay off. Next to
Santana's ``Supernatural,'' Moby's ``Play'' was probably the most
critically acclaimed album of 1999, landing on numerous top-10
lists (Rolling Stone, Entertainment Weekly, USA Today) as well as
Spin magazine's collection of the 90 best albums of the '90s. It's
vintage Moby, mixing hip-hop grooves, rock licks, hyperkinetic
rhythms and unfettered lyricism. In other words, pop music taken to
classical heights _ and yet, you can still dance to it.
</P>
<P>
   Moby, however, begs to differ. ``I don't see this as being a
dance record at all. I love dance music, but if I was DJ-ing
somewhere, I would never play this.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's artistic thread is a series of vocal samples, taken
from the legendary field recordings of American folk musicians made
by Alan Lomax. This is the blues stripped bare, only to be
repackaged in a context suited for the 21st century. Listen to a
cut like ``Why Does My Heart Feel So Bad?'' in which Moby takes a
few fragments sung by members of a gospel choir and turns them into
a shimmering techno opus: It's music that's old and new at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found those vocals, I fell in love with them,'' Moby
explains of the Lomax material. But he insists they are just a part
of the sonic canvas, not the predominant element. And he points out
that he plays all the instruments on the album, including
keyboards, guitars, bass and drums. (For his concerts, he brings
along a three-piece band.)
</P>
<P>
   The album's classical underpinnings _ these are pieces of music,
not mere songs _ shouldn't come as a surprise, given that the New
York-born, Connecticut-raised Moby studied with a classical
guitarist as a child. But even he admits his ``classical education
was quite idiosyncratic. My teacher was also into heavy metal.''
</P>
<P>
   During his teen years, Moby discovered punk rock. But he
eventually gravitated to dance music, making his mark first in
England, where his ``Go'' became a million-seller in the early '90s
and his style became associated with the burgeoning rave scene. In
a way, he was the first true electronica star, not William Orbit or
Prodigy. But because he chose to follow a less traditional path,
his career never exploded in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of the 1997 release ``Animal Rights,'' his second
album for a major label. It was more punk than techno, throwing his
then-fledgling fan base for a curve. But Moby insists it was the
only record in him at the time. ``There's something really
satisfying about playing guitar and screaming at the top of your
lungs,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That road-less-traveled point of view extends into Moby's
personal life. Among other things, he's a devout Christian and a
strict vegan (he refuses to use animal products of any kind) _ not
traits usually associated with an artist who's made it to the top
of trendy New York's party-guest list.
</P>
<P>
   Moby is as amazed at his sudden success as anyone else. ``I
assumed my record would suffer the same fate as a lot of
idiosyncratic records,'' he says. And though ``Play'' didn't win in
the two Grammy categories it was nominated _ best alternative music
performance and best rock instrumental performance _ Moby was
pleased to find all the famous fans he had. Among those who
complimented him were Barry Manilow, Elton John, Melissa Etheridge
and Kid Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``After being out there for three days, I became kind of
jaded,'' Moby recalls. ``It's like, `Oh well, Stevie Wonder likes
my record.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
