<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INDIA-CLINTON-0324-CO     03-23 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CLINTON-0324-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ADVISOR: CLINTON TO CONVEY 'HARD REALITIES' TO PAKISTAN
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With INDIA-HIGHTECH-0324.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAIPUR, India _ Worried about the ``potential failure'' of
Pakistan and the dangers that could pose to South Asia, President
Clinton will lay out some ``hard realities'' when he meets with the
country's military government on Saturday, a senior White House
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will express U.S. support for Pakistan, a key American
ally during the Cold War. He'll also urge the country's junta
leaders to end support for paramilitary attacks in Kashmir,
however, and to focus on returning their deeply beleaguered country
to civilian rule, said National Security Adviser Samuel Berger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are worried about the future of Pakistan,'' Berger told
reporters traveling with Clinton in India.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has economic problems, it has political problems, it has
terrorist groups that are operating out of Pakistan, and I think
that, in some ways, one of the great dangers in this region is the
potential failure of Pakistan,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message the president will give to Pakistan is 'You've got
to decide what's important here, in terms of your own future.'''
</P>
<P>
   Winding up a week-long swing through the Indian subcontinent,
Clinton stops for several hours Saturday in Islamabad, the
Pakistani capital, to meet with Chief Army Gen. Pervez Musharraf,
who seized control of the government in a coup last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also plans to deliver an address, live and unedited,
directly to the people of Pakistan over its state-controlled
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective,'' Berger said, ``is to reaffirm to the
Pakistani people that we care about their future, that we don't
want Pakistan to fail, to convey some hard realities to Musharraf
and to talk directly to the Pakistani people about the hard choices
they face.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faced a hard choice himself in deciding whether to go to
Pakistan. He's been criticized by human rights advocates and others
who worry that the visit lends the stamp of presidential legitimacy
to what is, essentially, a military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf overthrew the deeply flawed but democratically elected
government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Far from endorsing the coup, Clinton will tell Musharraf that
the sooner he lays out a plan for returning the country to
democratic rule, the better. In Islamabad on Thursday, Musharraf
announced a schedule for local elections sometime between December
2000 and May 2001, but said a public vote on a new national
government would only come ``step-by-step,'' and ``in due course of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a positive step but what we are looking for is a road map
to national elections and a restoration of democratic rule in
Pakistan,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will stress that such ambiguity won't help Musharraf in
gaining the support and confidence, inside Pakistan and outside of
it, needed to address the long list of ills in a country of 130
million people with an average annual income of just $480 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in the nature of persuasion,'' Berger said, ``to say
to him that you'll have a stronger basis generally on which to
address these problems if people can see a clear road map back to a
democratic government.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though, White House officials fear that to snub
Musharraf would leave Pakistan deeply isolated.
</P>
<P>
   That could prove dangerous given the country's vulnerability to
economic collapse _ its economy is stagnant and it narrowly averted
default last year on foreign debt approaching $30 billion _ its
constitutional crisis and Pakistan's long simmering conflict with
its giant rival, India, over the future of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has urged Musharraf from afar to end Pakistan's support
for the paramilitaries waging a campaign of violence against Indian
authorities in Kashmir, saying that an end to the tactics is
essential to engaging in peace talks with India. Saturday will be
Clinton's first opportunity to deliver that message in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should turn our back on the Pakistani people,
with whom we've had a very strong relationship,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a country that is in trouble and really needs to put
all of it's energy into self-renewal and not territorial
conflicts,'' Berger said. ``They don't have the luxury of that.''
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan _ the world's two newest possessors of
nuclear capability _ have fought three wars over Kashmir in the
past 50 years. Analysts regard it as one of the most volatile
flashpoints in the world, and Pakistan's deepening troubles have
only added to the regional instability.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   When the British partitioned the Indian subcontinent into Muslim
Pakistan and secular-Hindu India in 1947, the Hindu ruler of
Kashmir, a predominantly Muslim state, chose to become part of
India.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan never accepted that outcome. It has fought, on-and-off,
ever since to pull Kashmir into its own territory and has actively
supported the paramilitary groups _ Pakistan regards them as
freedom fighters, but to India they're terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Just Monday night, such groups killed 40 Sikhs in Kashmir.
India's government blamed Pakistan for the killings. The U.S.
position is that too little is known about the details to hold
Musharraf directly responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan was a key U.S. ally during the Cold War. It served as
the launchpad for billions of dollars in U.S. military aid to
Afghan guerillas fighting against Soviet troops. The Soviet defeat
in Afghanistan in 1989 was central to the collapse of the Soviet
Union two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has also assisted in the arrest of several radical
Muslims who have targeted U.S. officials in the past and the
country has contributed peacekeeping troops to a number of
Clinton's foreign policy initiatives, including the restoration of
democratic rule to Haiti and the effort to bring peace to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
