<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-KIDNAP-MOM-NYTR-NYT &LR;      03-23 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNAP-MOM-NYTR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER OF KIDNAPPED GIRL WANTS TO REGAIN A NORMAL LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KAREN VOYLES   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, Fla. _ Jennifer Graham went to bed on March 5 thinking
about the same details most moms worry about at the beginning of
the week. Were the school clothes washed? Had all the homework been
done? Was there milk for breakfast?
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, she was on several national television news
programs pleading for the safe return of her oldest child,
10-year-old Jessica Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this really makes you understand what is
important and what doesn't mean all that much,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica was taken from her family's driveway as she and her
sisters walked home from the school bus stop on March 6.
Investigators believe she was held at a Gainesville home until she
was released in the parking lot of a Wal-Mart in Gainesville on
March 9.
</P>
<P>
   After a medical exam and interviews with investigators, Jessica
and her family went into seclusion for a few days. Jessica and her
sisters are now back in school.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing what could have happened to her daughter is something
that Graham tries not to dwell on, but it is seldom far from her
thoughts. She said that law enforcement officials had told her that
kidnapped children were usually found in shallow graves, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how rare it happens that a child gets to go back home
after they are taken,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said that it seemed as if her children were doing a
better job of recovering than she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jessica runs around here like nothing ever happened, but I am
living in fear,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham has begun locking her doors when she is home alone during
the day, and her fiance, Thomas Keeley, tries not to leave the
family if he can avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder for us, me and Tom, to get back to normal because
I think we know what could have happened and the girls don't know
that,'' Graham said. ``I try not to let Jessica know I'm afraid.
She's amazing and I'm so proud of her for being able to just move
on, but I worry all the time now about if they are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham credited investigators and the media for quickly
distributing a sketch of the suspected kidnapper.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica's sister, Jerrica Rodriguez, 8, provided a police artist
with much detail about the man's appearance despite only seeing his
face for a few seconds during the kidnapping. Then, as Jessica was
being forced into the man's Jeep, Jerrica and a third sister,
Serenity Shumake, 4, did what their mother told them to do in an
emergency _ run toward an adult they know and scream to attract
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The sketch of the suspect, along with details provided by
Jessica following her release, led investigators to James Paul
Johnson, 38, of Gainesville, who was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Now that her child has been returned and a suspect arrested,
Graham said she was ``really, really angry about what happened, but
I don't hate him for this. I just want to know why. Why do people
do things like this to children?''
</P>
<P>
   Graham had some advice for parents of a kidnapped child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pray as hard as you can and go to the media for help and don't
ever, ever give up faith that your child will be returned,'' Graham
said. ``You may want to sit there and think bad things, but make
yourself pray and keep your faith.''
</P>
<P>
   While Graham and Keeley acknowledged the help they received from
the media, they were upset about some of the questions and
treatment they have received from a few television outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one television reporter ask me how it felt to be a
celebrity, and I told him flat out that I never wanted to be on
television and I wouldn't be on television except that I needed to
get my daughter back,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   She still gets calls from talk show employees trying to cajole
or bully her into appearing on a specific program. Immediately
after her daughter was found, Graham said she was shocked by the
behavior of one network employee who gave her a tongue lashing for
not appearing on a certain morning news program first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we could have done _ if we could have gotten
Jessica back _ without all the newspaper stories and television and
all, so I don't want to sound ungrateful, but some of them were
rude,'' Graham said. ``When we found Jessica, I wanted to thank
them, but now they just don't stop and they keep on and keep on and
keep on.''
</P>
<P>
   While her daughters aren't dwelling on the kidnapping, it does
come up. Before going back to school, Serenity asked Graham, ``Is
the bad guy who took Jessica away in jail?'' Graham said she tried
to keep the answer short, specific and reassuring, telling Serenity
that a man was in jail and he probably shouldn't be getting out for
a long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   Among Jessica's questions was one about why Graham was crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her they were happy tears because I was so glad she was
back with us,'' Graham said. ``I feel like God has a special plan
for Jessica and that is why she is back here with us.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville, Fla., Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6076 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CARWSH-SLAYINGS-TEX     03-23 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARWSH-SLAYINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY RAMPAGE AT CARWASH DESCRIBED
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Note contents) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MIILES MOFFEIT 
And MITCH MITCHELL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Mi-T-Fine Car Wash employee Jason Shields
stopped for doughnuts Monday morning and noticed three of his
co-workers ambling across a parking lot on their way to work.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Shields pushed open the front door of the carwash
to absorb a chilling scene: the same three co-workers sprawled in
puddles of blood, and a fired employee, Robert Wayne Harris,
blurting an equally terrifying remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's three more back here in the office,'' Harris said,
according to police affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   All the victims were shot in the head, authorities said
Wednesday. Harris' family members said they believe that the
shootings flared during an argument, but crime scene specialists
contend that the head wounds are consistent with a calculated
killing.
</P>
<P>
   Shields' encounter triggered a massive police search that led to
Harris' arrest the next day in the shooting deaths of five carwash
employees and the wounding of another.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses described the hours before Harris' arrest at an
acquaintance's Dallas home, and police turned over documents that
lay bare details about the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Harris had been free for months after being targeted as a
suspect in the disappearance of Irving resident Sandra Estes Scott,
who has been missing since November, documents show.
</P>
<P>
   After a police interview with Harris on Tuesday night,
investigators on Wednesday found what is believed to be Scott's
body.
</P>
<P>
   According to affidavits, police concluded as early as January
that Harris was the last person to have seen Scott alive. In police
interviews, he gave ``deceptive'' responses during polygraph tests,
according to records. ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Harris was fired from the carwash Friday after a female customer
reported March 15 that he was performing a sexual act in a restroom
with the door open.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested Friday at the carwash on suspicion of indecent
exposure. Employees said they heard yelling and commotion in the
lobby where Harris was being handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was going on, because everyone was quiet,'' said one
worker who wouldn't give her name.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, after Harris was released from Lew Sterrett Justice
Center in Dallas on $500 bail, he returned to his former workplace
to ask for a free carwash, making employees and a supervisor
nervous, an employee said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, sometime before 7:30 a.m., Harris returned to the
carwash, this time wearing work clothes _ faded gray pants, a
maroon jacket and a dark baseball cap, _ according to witnesses and
affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, Shields had stopped at The Donut King while other
employees trickled into the carwash.
</P>
<P>
   About 7:40 a.m., Shields, entering from the merchandise area,
encountered the bloody scene and saw Harris standing amid three
bodies. ``Numerous shell casings'' littered the floor, the police
report states.
</P>
<P>
   Harris stood at the counter and motioned to the three other
bodies, according to affidavits, prompting Shields to look. He
recognized the bodies of assistant manager Dennis Lee and cashier
Rhoda Wheeler. Shields fled in shock, returning to the doughnut
shop, where he asked an employee for a telephone so he could dial
911.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted the door locked,'' a doughnut store employee told
the Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   At the crime scene, three people were dead from gunshot wounds.
Two more died later at Parkland Memorial Hospital in Dallas. The
victims: Agustin Villasenor, 36, of Arlington; and Benjamin
Villasenor, 32; Roberto Jimenez Jr., 15; Wheeler, 45; and Lee, 48,
all of Irving. Lee's neck was slit, police documents state.
</P>
<P>
   Octavio Ramos, 36, of Irving was listed in critical condition
last night at Parkland Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   All five slaying victims died of gunshot wounds to the head,
according to autopsy reports released yesterday by the Dallas
County Medical Examiner's Office. The report does not specify the
exact locations of the wounds. A friend of Lee's who saw his body
said he was shot in the temple.
</P>
<P>
   Shields, through his girlfriend, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still not over this,'' Stacie Douthitt said.
``Physically, he's OK, but not emotionally.'' ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After taking Shields' report, police launched a search, staking
out Harris' Irving apartment along Rock Island Road and residences
of his acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   About 10:30 p.m. Monday, Marie Noble, 29, a longtime friend of
Harris' who lives in east Dallas, heard a knock at her door.
</P>
<P>
   It was Harris, who initially appeared calm, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But later, she said, ``The way Robert was talking, I knew
something was wrong, the way he was smoking cigarettes, smoking one
right after another.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Noble talked awhile, but Noble said she had no idea
that Harris was a murder suspect. Then her 8-year-old daughter saw
Harris' photograph on television between 11 and 11:30 p.m. and
said, `Mom, look at this ... look at him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Noble confronted Harris, but he did not admit guilt, she said.
He told her later that night that he should talk to police, and he
asked her to take him to the police station in Garland. She
declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I wouldn't take him in my car because they were
saying he was armed and dangerous, and I didn't want to jeopardize
my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she told him, ``Bobby it's like this, if you did it,
you've got to turn yourself in.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris stayed up all night talking to Noble and her brother, she
said. Sometime before 10 a.m. Tuesday, Noble said, she got a call
from a police officer saying he had learned that Harris was at her
house and that officers were at her back door.
</P>
<P>
   She said she tried to avoid letting Harris know about the police
because she feared he might cause a commotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert asked me what was going on. I said, `I have to open the
door. The police are here.' He said, `No, please don't.' I told
him, `I have to,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Noble said Harris cooperated with police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we'll never see him again,'' she said. ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Harris' brother told a television station Tuesday evening that
Harris admitted the slayings. He is in Irving Jail and has been
arraigned on suspicion of capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, police said, they recovered ``clothing and papers''
during a search of his Irving apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Because all the victims were shot in the head, crime scene
analysts characterized the killings as premeditated. Harris'
brother said Harris snapped during an argument with co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't sound like a frenzy shooting,'' said Max Courtney
of Forensic Consultant Services in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, if a gunman is shooting randomly at a group of
people, victims would have more wounds, Courtney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With five people shot in the head and there are no missed
shots, it certainly would suggest that there were no wild shots,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Jason, a crime scene analyst in Pinole, Calif., and a
former San Francisco police officer, agreed that the shootings
probably did not happen during a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``His statement that he shot all the people in a very brief
period of anger appears to be inconsistent with the facts as I know
them,'' Jason said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers would have tried to run or defend themselves, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After one or two shots were fired, generally it draws their
attention and they would take defensive action. They wouldn't stay
in one place.
</P>
<P>
   ``To shoot five different people in different rooms goes beyond
a fit of anger.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Domingo Ramirez Jr. and Susan Gill Vardon
contributed to this report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
