<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6077 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CARWASH-BODY-TEX     03-23 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARWASH-BODY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN CAR WASH SLAYINGS BELIEVED LINKED TO DISAPPEARANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By GORDON DICKSON 
And SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Already accused of killing five co-workers,
Robert Wayne Harris had something else he needed to tell police:
where to find a body.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, acting on Harris' information, police found a
body believed to be that of an Irving woman missing since November.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of Sandra Estes Scott, who disappeared Nov. 29,
said they were told by police that the decomposed body found in
another Dallas suburb is almost certainly hers. A positive
identification will be made using dental records, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's her,'' said Charles Gaylor, a field agent for
the Dallas County Medical Examiner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 28, who is accused of capital murder in connection with
the slayings of five people Monday at a Mi-T-Fine Car Wash in
Irving, had been a suspect in Scott's disappearance since early
December, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's family members and friends said police told them that
Harris gave officers the location of a body but would not claim
responsibility for Scott's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't tell them it was Sandy, he just gave the location,''
said Barbara Bonome, Scott's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Scott's relatives cried and hugged one
another outside Irving police headquarters after officers briefed
them about the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame five other people had to die so I can find out
what happened to my daughter,'' said Scott's father, Charles Estes
of Irving. ``My heart goes out to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris is believed to be the last person to see Scott alive. On
Jan. 14, he failed a polygraph test when questioned about her
disappearance, records state. Until the carwash shooting renewed
investigators' interest in the Scott case, police said, they did
not have enough evidence to arrest Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Scott's loved ones stopped short of saying that Irving
police did not push hard enough to determine what happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could have linked him to Sandy's disappearance, he
would have been in jail. These people wouldn't have been killed,''
Bonome said. ``I think the police did what they could. They just
didn't find evidence to arrest him.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Scott's friends, Sharon Summers, was more critical of
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``They let him go and he killed these other people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Irving police acknowledged that the investigation of Scott's
disappearance started slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors complicated the case, police spokesman David
Tull said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 48 hours passed between Scott's disappearance the
night of Nov. 29 and her family's first call to police about 10
p.m. Dec. 1, according to police records.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's case probably was not placed on a national missing
persons database until the morning of Dec. 2 because of a shift
change at the Police Department, Tull said. At that time, the case
would have been assigned to a detective in the youth investigations
division, which investigates all missing persons reports, Tull
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, the possibility surfaced that this woman left on
her own,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A week into the investigation, Harris was interviewed by police.
He told them that Scott, 37, came to his apartment Nov. 29 to sell
a bag of marijuana, according to a police affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Police learned that about 9:45 p.m. Nov. 29, Scott placed a call
from Harris' apartment to a friend, Christina West, the affidavit
states. The Caller ID on West's telephone displayed Harris' number.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's abandoned pickup was found nearly five hours later, and
the gap between the phone call and the discovery of the pickup made
it difficult to connect Harris to any foul play, Tull said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got several hours when she may have seen someone else,''
he said. ``In that time frame, she could have seen other people.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 19, police searched Harris' apartment but found nothing
connecting him to Scott, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got off to a sluggish start,'' Tull said. ``If we erred in
some way, it may have been that we didn't start interviewing right
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish we could do more, too,'' he said. ``We work with what
we've got. We're getting better, but even with technology and
manpower, this one did not work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott was divorced. Her children, Michael Wright, 13, and
Tiffinee Williams, 17, live with relatives in Irving, family
members said.
</P>
<P>
   As word spread that Scott's body may have been found, her
friends and relatives swarmed to the Irving police station and to a
remote area near where the body was found on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Scott's family members, including her father,
stepmother and grandfather, live a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in horror,'' said Jessie Estes, Scott's stepmother.
``She was so close to our home.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives said they had searched that area shortly
after Scott disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought my horse out here and checked this area myself,''
said her ex-husband, Michael Wright, who lives about one mile from
where the body was located. ``Every time I drove down this road I
wondered if Sandy could have been out here somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Family friend Barry Preston, 16, of Irving said, ``We were out
here about a week after Sandy disappeared. We walked along this
road barefoot. I mean, we were all right here searching.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott's son expressed anger at the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to pay for what he did,'' the boy said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, he had been pulled out of class by a
counselor who told him that his father wanted to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling it was about my mom,'' he said. ``It's been
too long. I've been missing her a lot. Every day, I wanted to pick
up the phone and call her.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Domingo Ramirez Jr. contributed to this report.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
