<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6078 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER24-COX     03-23 1626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Yet another White House investigation
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department has launched a criminal inquiry into
White House computer breakdowns that made it impossible to search
thousands of incoming e-mails in response to congressional
subpoenas. The investigation, to be handled through the Justice's
campaign finance task force, focuses on whether the subpoenas
issued to the White House went unanswered because of the
breakdowns. The e-mails involved campaign fund-raising and other
matters.
</P>
<P>
   IF SHE WERE A NEW YORKER, WOULD SHE HAVE TO TRAVEL AS MUCH?
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans released White House data Thursday
showing Hillary Rodham Clinton reimbursed taxpayers for only about
18 percent of the cost of her New York Senate campaign trips on
government aircraft. The documents showed Clinton's trips to and
from New York cost $182,471, but that she reimbursed taxpayers only
$32,878. Still, the figure was far below the $905,406 the
Republican National Committee estimated as recently as Wednesday.
The first lady flies on government aircraft on the advice of Secret
Service, and reimburses the government the same way presidential
candidates do: at the rate of a first-class commercial ticket.
</P>
<P>
   TRIAL LAWYERS' WORST NIGHTMARE
</P>
<P>
   While trial lawyers have long been heavy donors to Democrats,
the prospect of a George W. Bush presidency, along with the
possibility that like-minded Republicans will retain control of
Congress, has ratcheted up the stakes, and the donations. Trial
lawyers are spending huge amounts of money from the tobacco
settlement to keep him and other Republicans from being elected.
Bush has made attacks on lawyers a campaign centerpiece, pointing
with pride to his record in Texas of curbing civil litigation,
capping legal fees and limiting jury awards. It all comes under the
banner of tort reform, or what Bush claims are efforts to rid the
legal system of ``junk'' lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   X'S AND O'S OF GORE GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The presidential election is 229 days away, and Al Gore and the
Democrats have settled on their initial line of attack. Paint
George W. Bush as a phony education reformer. Explain away the
glowing test scores posted in recent years by Texas students.
Depict Bush as an insensitive penny-pincher. Put out the word that
he is no friend to young Latinos. In short, leave the impression
that Bush is a garden-variety Republican, and therefore no match
for the vice president on the issue of boosting the quality of
America's public schools. Such were the messages when top Democrats
huddled in the wind and rain in Washington to brief journalists
from several news organizations on the downside of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH SCORES POINTS WITH THIS DEMOCRAT
</P>
<P>
   Democratic national Chairman Joe Andrew charged that George W.
Bush merely ``talks a good game'' on education. But in an interview
with Knight Ridder, Will Marshall, a 1992 Clinton-Gore adviser who
runs the Progressive Policy Institute, a moderate Democratic think
tank, countered: ``Test scores have been rising, and the
achievements of low-income and minority students have been rising.
Campaign hyperbole aside, Texas has one of the best accountability
systems in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   CREDIBILITY, WITH EMPHASIS ON TAXES
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says Al Gore is an ``obstacle to reform'' who is
too partisan to be president and build consensus on fixing Social
Security or making meaningful changes to the campaign finance
system. In an interview in Thursday's Washington Post, Bush pledged
to continue pushing his plans for a tax cut despite polls showing
little interest in one and said he would make saving Social
Security a focus of the campaign. He said Gore has a ``major
credibility problem'' that goes beyond the campaign finance matter,
and that he plans to make it a central campaign issue as well.
</P>
<P>
   NOT JUST SHOOTING FROM THE HIP
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has repeatedly said about Al Gore: ``This is a
man who will say anything to get elected.'' What wasn't known is
that line of attack had been tested, and proven effective in a
Republican ``push poll'' conducted in early February. The results
of the poll, obtained by ABC News, provide a road map for Bush's
strategy going into the fall campaign: Go after Gore on
trustworthiness and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS IN MILITARY: ALL DELIBERATE SPEED
</P>
<P>
   Although Al Gore pledged that if elected president he would end
the ban on gays serving openly in the military, he would not issue
an immediate, sweeping order to achieve that goal, a key aide says.
Leon Fuerth, Gore's national security adviser, said Gore would move
more deliberately. Said Fuerth: ``We are not really talking about
an executive order; we are talking about a presidential action to
enter into a dialogue with people who are concerned about this.''
Fuerth said Gore ``fully understands'' the military's arguments for
not allowing gays and lesbians to serve openly, namely that it
could erode morale and disrupt ``unit cohesion.''
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN STILL PUSHING BUSH ON ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   Juggling party loyalty with political independence, John McCain
promised House Republicans he'll campaign vigorously for them, then
prodded his victorious rival, George W. Bush, to support federal
regulation of tobacco. ``I hope the governor will take that
position,'' he told The Associated Press in an interview. Bush has
declined to say whether he favors federal regulation.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE CHAPLAIN SOUL SEARCHING
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Charles Wright, whose selection as House chaplain
triggered charges of religious bias in Congress, offered to
withdraw this week in a private meeting with House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, Cox's Rebecca Carr reported. With his nomination in limbo
for months, Wright, a Presbyterian minister, made his offer amid
signs that Hastert was moving quickly to find a replacement.
Republicans are eager to quell a controversy in which some
Democrats accused them of anti-Catholic bias for passing over a
Catholic priest last fall when Wright was tapped.
</P>
<P>
   BAD THINGS CAN REALLY PILE UP
</P>
<P>
   The Senate candidate who began his campaign to unseat Sen. Ted
Kennedy by issuing an embarrassing report detailing his own
personal failures has steered himself into a new mess. Jack E.
Robinson III was involved in a three-car accident Tuesday and is
accused of trying to leave the scene _ just hours after releasing
an 11-page personal history that included allegations of drinking
and driving, sexual misconduct, plagiarism and carrying an illegal
weapon. The Republican businessman was talking on his cell phone at
the time of the accident, giving an interview to WBUR-FM in Boston
about Gov. Paul Cellucci's decision to withdraw his support because
of the revelations. The accident was blamed on a 17-year-old who
lost control of his car and crossed into oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JOB FOR DAN QUAYLE
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle, an early dropout from the presidential race, has
joined Denver-based investment banking firm JD Ford and Co. as a
principal. The company ``specializes in arranging merger and
acquisition transactions for middle market companies,'' according
to their press release. Quayle ``will assume a senior level role in
the firm's activities'' and will be based in Phoenix to assist
clients ``in closing transactions with the goal of maximizing their
objectives.'' Quayle offers the firm's clients access to national
and international decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE SHOOTING ISSUE FESTERING . . .
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton accused Rudy Giuliani of essentially
ignoring New York City's black residents. Reacting to the mayor's
statement that he felt no responsibility to reach out to the black
community after the latest police shooting of an unarmed black man,
Clinton said: ``He's basically written off whole communities in the
city that he's supposed to lead. What does that say about how
people would be represented by him?'' The mayor's campaign
spokesman, Bruce Teitelbaum, shot back: ``It sounds like Mrs.
Clinton is still reading off the same script prepared by Al
Sharpton.''
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND SOME IN GOP WORRY
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani's attacks this week on an unarmed black man who
was fatally shot by the police are causing bewilderment among
members of his own party, who say they are concerned about
Giuliani's temperament and the tenor of his Senate campaign against
Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``I don't think she can beat him, but he
can beat himself,'' said Rich Bond, former chairman of the
Republican National Committee, who once worked for Giuliani. Bond
added that Giuliani's strong defense of the police in this case
``could bleed into the overall electorate and become a modest
negative instead of a huge positive.''
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS SENATE RUNOFF SET
</P>
<P>
   An ex-state legislator and a retired Air Force lawyer have
advanced to a runoff in the Democratic primary for Republican Kay
Bailey Hutchison's Senate seat in Texas. Unofficial returns had
determined that Charles Gandy, who served one term in the Texas
house in the mid-1980s, finished second in the March 14 primary to
lawyer Gene Kelly. But Gandy's margin over the third-place finisher
was so close that officials waited to make the formal announcement.
Kelly had 35.7 percent of the vote, Gandy 22.7 percent, and the
third candidate, Don Clark, had 22.5 percent. The runoff will be
April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
