<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHINA-CITRUS-420&AMP;ADD-     03-23 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CITRUS-420&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA OPENS ITS MARKET TO FLORIDA CITRUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., Ariz., Texas)  (js) 
 By LLOYD DUNKELBERGER   
 (New York Times Regional Newspapers)   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida Agriculture Commissioner Bob
Crawford will be in a Beijing market on Monday, selling oranges and
grapefruit to Chinese customers.
</P>
<P>
   That simple act represents a sweeping economic development:
China, with its 1.2 billion potential consumers, has agreed to let
Florida growers sell fresh citrus in the world's most populous
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge,'' Crawford said Wednesday. ``People have been
talking about this for years. We saw the opportunity. We just went
to work on it and may have helped play a role in making it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's first commercial shipment of citrus to China is the
result of an agreement last April between China and the United
States that allows the sale of citrus, wheat and beef to the Asian
country. The citrus sales, which will also benefit California,
Texas and Arizona growers, were delayed until Chinese officials
were convinced that importing the fruit would not expose their
native crops to new pests or plant diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The approval came after a team of Chinese inspectors toured
groves and packing houses in the United States in January. Although
Florida is currently battling an outbreak of citrus canker,
Crawford said Chinese officials were less concerned about canker,
which is a problem in China, than about a fruit-fly infestation.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement is the first step in the wider opening
of the Chinese market to Florida growers.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford and citrus growers will lobby Congress to approve
China's entry into the World Trade Organization. When China joins
the WTO, it will begin reducing tariffs on U.S. citrus from 40
percent to 12 percent over a five-year period as the result of a
previous agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush said citrus sales in China are a historic
opportunity for the state and the citrus industry. ``Florida
farmers are going to benefit from this and so are a whole lot of
other people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture is Florida's second leading industry, trailing
tourism. And citrus is the state's top agricultural product.
</P>
<P>
   The potential economic benefits of the Chinese market are
sizable. Crawford's marketing experts predict that about 300
million Chinese have the economic means to become regular consumers
of citrus.
</P>
<P>
   By 2005, the U.S. Department of Agriculture projects that this
country will sell more than $500 million worth of citrus to China.
Florida, as the nation's largest citrus producer, should have the
largest share of that business, Crawford said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Florida's sales will start more modestly. Crawford will fly to
Beijing this weekend with ten boxes of fruit, including ruby red
and white grapefruit as well as oranges. Then, next month, a
two-container shipment from an Indian River packer will arrive in
China.
</P>
<P>
   China is the fifth leading producer of oranges in the world and
the leader in tangerines. Crawford said, however, that Florida
offers a higher quality of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Using phrases like ``abundant opportunities'' and ``boundless
promise,'' Crawford repeatedly emphasized the staggering potential
for the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, half-jokingly, the new sales could reverse the
trend of selling Florida citrus groves to make way for subdivisions
and other development.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always predicted that if we got into China, we'd be pushing
down condominiums and planting citrus trees,'' he said. ``So we'll
see.''
</P>
<P>
   (Lloyd Dunkelberger is Tallahassee bureau chief for the New York
Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
