<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-TAXES-$ADV26     03-23 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE DEADLOCK, INTERNET TAX PANEL ADVANCED THE DEBATE
 &HT;    With INTERNET-VOTE. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the final meeting of a federal commission on
Internet sales taxes stumbled to an acrimonious close last week,
its work was widely described as a failure.
</P>
<P>
   But in the days since the Advisory Commission on Electronic
Commerce disbanded, apparently unable to make a formal
recommendation to Congress, a new assessment has been developing.
</P>
<P>
   Now observers say the panel may have succeeded in killing
Congress's option to declare the Internet free of sales taxes
forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it sounds good to say 'No taxes, now and forever,' ``
said Richard Prem, a sales tax expert with Deloitte &AMP; Touche, a
nationwide accounting firm. ``But when you really look at what that
would do to state tax revenues, you start to realize the losses
could be staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales taxes account for about a third of all state revenues. As
more business shifts to online merchants who do not collect taxes
from out-of-state customers, states could begin losing $10.8
billion annually within three years, according to a study by the
University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's debates revealed that the need to collect sales
taxes for schools, roads, police and other basic services is too
compelling to grant Internet-based businesses a permanent break
from tax collection duties, Prem said.
</P>
<P>
   So now as the debate moves to Congress, the arguments will
likely focus on how to move the nation toward a tax system in which
all merchants will have to collect and remit state sales taxes,
whether they operate out of storefronts, through the Internet, by
telephone or by mail.
</P>
<P>
   But it's far from clear how long that transition will last, or
how Congress and the states will shape the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's not even clear which committees in Congress will
spearhead the debates. The Senate Finance Committee last week
announced it soon will hold hearings on Internet sales taxes, but
the Senate Commerce Committee also plans to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to controlling the tax debate, ``it's the top of
the first inning,'' said Mike Waterman, press secretary for Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., ranking minority member of the
Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's two-day session in Dallas brought out a full
range of passionate arguments from anti-tax ideologues,
Internet-based businesses, traditional retailers, and tax-dependent
state and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, it forced Congress _ which already has blocked new
Internet taxes temporarily _ to take notice of just how complex and
important the tax issue is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of the outcome, the commission has raised the level
of awareness on this issue, and that's going to make it tough for
Congress to ignore it,'' said Prem.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-member advisory commission deadlocked because no tax
option could garner 13 votes, the number required for a
``supermajority'' recommendation. By a vote of 11-8, the group did
back a plan to extend the moratorium on new Internet taxes until
October 2006, eliminate telephone excise taxes and permanently ban
taxes on Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected the commission to deliver such a mixed message
when it was was created as part of a bill sponsored by Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz. Then, most experts thought the group would fall
into line behind McCain, who declared the Internet should not
``become a tax collection machine for politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   But now even McCain has softened. He introduced a bill last week
to extend the moratorium for five years, rather than permanently
ban sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he has ``become convinced that we need more time to
determine ... how to ensure a level playing field for all venues of
commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   His use of the phrase ``level playing field'' was music to the
ears of traditional retailers, who use the phrase often as they
argue it would be unfair to make them continue to collect sales
taxes while their online competitors largely escape those
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Though the ``levelers'' are gaining ground, anything can happen
amid election-year politics. No one in Congress or on the
presidential campaign trail seems eager to take a firm position on
such a charged issue.
</P>
<P>
   That means lobbyists and campaign contributors will be busy
during the coming months, trying to make sure that the new
president and Congress arriving in the capital next January will be
inclined to help them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really looking at next year,'' said Lisa Cowell,
spokeswoman for the E-Fairness Coalition, a lobbying group
representing traditional retailers. ``We're putting our efforts
into high gear to educate the members of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
