<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     03-23 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oscars are on Sunday, which means only one thing: It's just
about time for Tony guessing to begin.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of critical reaction alone, there seem to be
several curious _ and competitive _ races for Tony Awards shaping
up. And with 12 openings in the next five weeks, things can only
get better.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks alone, two productions, ``A Moon for the
Misbegotten'' and ``True West,'' have garnered glorious notices,
have had torrid sales and have become near-certainties for
nominations in the revival category _ unless, of course, the
producers of ``True West'' can convince Tony pooh-bahs that the
1980 play is a new one. (Their logic: it has never before been
produced on Broadway.)
</P>
<P>
   All this before April, which has an acclaimed revival of ``The
Real Thing'' and a promising ``Uncle Vanya'' in the offing. One of
last year's entries, like ``The Rainmaker,'' ``Amadeus'' or ``The
Price,'' could fill out the category.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for all the talk of revivals' dominating Broadway,
the musical revival category may be short a candidate, as only
three shows look to be in the mix, including the early favorite,
``Kiss Me Kate.'' April supplies the other two: ``Jesus Christ
Superstar'' and ``The Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Of new musicals, one is a shoo-in for a nod: ``Contact,'' which
started at Lincoln Center's Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater and reopens
at the Vivian Beaumont Theater on Thursday. ``James Joyce's `The
Dead,''' which received some of the season's best reviews, also
looks strong.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically _ and this is all theoretical _ that leaves two
nominations up for grabs. Industry types seem to think that the
season's two remaining new musicals, ``Aida,'' which opened
Thursday night , and ``The Wild Party,'' which is to open on April
13 (more on this later), are strong possibilities. Earlier
productions, including ``Marie Christine,'' ``Swing'' and
``Saturday Night Fever,'' are seen as more distant candidates,
having suffered some rough reviews.
</P>
<P>
   On the new-play front, after a barren fall, next month should
bring the openings of three or maybe all four nominees. One early
favorite is likely to be ``Copenhagen,'' which comes to New York
with the vestigial glow of its award-laden London run; it opens on
April 11. The next day, another prospect from London, ``Rose,''
opens at the Lyceum.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only one nominee for best new play, ``Side Man,'' was
written by an American with a pulse, but this year conventional
wisdom is that more living Americans will be represented.
Candidates include Arthur Miller's ``Ride Down Mount Morgan''
(April 9) and Elaine May's ``Taller Than a Dwarf'' (April 24).
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``True West,'' two older entries may be
considered ``new'' plays, including a new adaptation of ``The Green
Bird,'' an 18th-century fable directed by Julie Taymor, and
``Waiting in the Wings,'' Noel Coward's 1960 play, which is
receiving its first Broadway run.
</P>
<P>
   The last potential nominee is the last to announce an opening:
``Dirty Blonde,'' Claudia Shear's meditation on the divine Mae
West, opening _ when else? _ on May 1 (May Day), at the Helen Hayes
Theater. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Show girls' Comeback &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Details are slow in coming, but a planned revival of Stephen
Sondheim's ``Follies'' is penciled into the schedule of the
Roundabout Theater Company for next season. No casting or design
team is set, but the director will likely be Matthew Warchus
(``True West''), and the target opening is spring of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Specifics about another Roundabout show are closer at hand.
``Design for Living,'' by Noel Coward, is to open next February,
with Joe Mantello directing. Mantello said he can't confirm any
casting, but Alan Cumming, Julianne Moore and Rupert Everett have
been mentioned. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not a Party Pooper &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mandy Patinkin watch continues. The star, who has been
battling a vocal inflammation, has been out of his lead role in
``The Wild Party'' since March 16. But Thursday a spokesman said
that he was improving and was likely to return to the show early
next week. Patinkin's absence has aroused speculation about a delay
in the show's opening, but producers said it was still set for
April 13. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No Rest for the Busy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Sullivan has little of the bluster often associated with
directors, and no booming baritone, either. With a salt-and-pepper
beard and guarded gray eyes, he looks a bit like an Irish shepherd
and smiles about as often.
</P>
<P>
   His appearance notwithstanding, Sullivan is currently the
best-represented director in New York, with three plays running,
including ``Dinner With Friends,'' ``Ancestral Voices'' and the
most recent to open, ``A Moon for the Misbegotten.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which elicits a sort of embarrassed shrug from the
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see something besides my own work,'' Sullivan said
recently over a cup of coffee. ``And I'm sure New York would,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, buddy, a vacation doesn't seem in the cards. Sullivan is
already lending his talents to his next project: ``Proof,'' David
Auburn's mathematical drama opening in May at the Manhattan Theater
Club. Then he'll tackle ``Spinning Into Butter,'' a play about race
by Rebecca Gilman; Hope Davis is to star.
</P>
<P>
   And Sullivan is to be the director of ``10 Unknowns'' by Jon
Robin Baitz, a play that starred Julianna Margulies in its last
reading and is to open at Lincoln Center early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, 59, said the plays all shared a sense of ambiguity, a
quality he likes and displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm much more interested in the idea that you can't really
know people,'' he said. ``But you can attempt to get as close as
you can.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the Dept. of very limited runs: Karen Finley will work the
kinks out of her new piece, ``Shut Up and Love Me,'' at the
Westbeth Theater Center, April 14-15. Another Westbeth alumna,
Margaret Cho, will play Town Hall on June 17. And Eddie Izzard, who
plays Westbeth in early April, will return as promised to New York,
performing on June 22-24, at Town Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Murphy is to star in ``Wonderful Town,'' at the Encores!
Concert Series at City Center, May 4-7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
