 &HT;    With INTERNET-TAXES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce
failed to pull together the two-thirds majority needed to make a
recommendation to Congress on Internet sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The closest it came to reaching that goal was an 11-8 vote in
favor of a proposal to extend the moratorium on new Internet sales
taxes through 2006, repeal the federal 3 percent telecommunications
excise tax, and grant certain tax exemptions for goods that can be
``digitized,'' such as records and books.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the vote broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners voting for the proposal:
</P>
<P>
   Dean Andal, chairman of the California Board of Equalization
</P>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong, chairman and CEO of AT&AMP;T
</P>
<P>
   James Gilmore, governor of Virginia
</P>
<P>
   Paul Harris Sr., delegate to the Virginia House
</P>
<P>
   Grover Norquist, president of Americans for Tax Reform
</P>
<P>
   Richard Parsons, president of Time Warner, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pittman, president of America Online
</P>
<P>
   David Pottruck, president and co-CEO of Charles Schwab and Co.
</P>
<P>
   John W. Sidgmore, vice chairman of MCI WorldCom
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Sokul, independent consultant Association for
Interactive Media
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Waitt, chairman of Gateway, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners voting against the proposal:
</P>
<P>
   Joseph H. Guttentag, senior advisor to the assistant secretary
for tax policy, U.S. Department of the Treasury
</P>
<P>
   Delna Jones, commissioner of Washington County, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Kirk, mayor of Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Michael Leavitt, governor of Utah
</P>
<P>
   Gene Lebrun, past president of the National Conference of
Commissioners on Uniform State Laws
</P>
<P>
   Gary Locke, governor of Washington
</P>
<P>
   Robert Novick, general counsel, U.S. Trade Representative
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Pincus, general counsel, U.S. Department of Commerce
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
