<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1STLD-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE SOFT UNDERBELLY OF 'SOFT MONEY'
 &HT;    Eds: Restores open quotes in last sentence of 5th graf.
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (p) political categories for
release
 &HT;    Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Who knows? Perhaps we'll wake up between now and
Election Day to find that George W. Bush and Al Gore have renounced
soft money, the unlimited contributions they busily solicit from
just about every possible source.
</P>
<P>
   After having all but ignored soft money in the previous race for
the White House, the press has now decided to make a very big deal
out of it. (The soft money issue did make a late splash in the 1996
contest, but that's only because of a sizzling Chinese angle.)
</P>
<P>
   Since then, John McCain has pursued the need to ban soft money
as his political Holy Grail. On his return from Bora Bora, the
senator called on both presidential candidates to eschew soft
money. And Gore has issued his own separate challenge to Bush along
those lines.
</P>
<P>
   On Election Day, Bush could wind up as a martyr on the stake of
media vengeance and McCain's wrath. But, thus far, he's chosen to
hold fast to his faith in the power of money to win elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is to be able to encourage individuals to
participate in the process so I can get my message out, so I can
fight through the (media) filter,'' Bush said in explaining his
refusal. ``Well, viva 'soft money' if it can do the trick.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to bear in mind that after this summer's
political conventions, it'll be illegal for either candidate to
spend so much as a dime that hasn't come from the taxpayers'
pockets. That's because they will opt to fund their general
election campaigns out a special $3-a-head contribution _ it's not
a surtax _ that income tax filers can check off on their federal
returns.
</P>
<P>
   So-called ``hard money'' outlays will be off limits to Bush and
Gore as well.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a bit of history: Since 1907, it has been illegal for
corporations to spend any money in a federal election. Since 1947,
it has been illegal for labor unions to spend any money in federal
elections. And since 1974, it has been illegal for anybody to
contribute more than $1,000 to a federal candidate, or more than
$20,000 a year to a political party to use in any way the party
chooses, including directly supporting its candidates.
</P>
<P>
   So all that's left for Bush and Gore to renounce is soft money,
which they can't use directly.
</P>
<P>
   One major school of thought argues that soft money donations
unfairly tilt the political playing field. ``Money is property;
money is not speech,'' Justice John Paul Stevens wrote in a recent
Supreme Court opinion that upheld the right of a state to limit
soft money contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has also come close to passing such a federal statute:
at one time, 58 of the needed 60 senators voted for an outright
ban. But until two more come along, soft money remains protected by
the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   So, try as they might to get the press hounds unleashed by
McCain off their flanks, Bush and Gore remain powerless to keep any
rich person from saying what he or she will about them.
</P>
<P>
   Were they to collude with those rich guys in mounting an ad
campaign, then all involved could conceivably go to jail. In point
of fact, Bush says that's just what Gore did four years ago, aided
and abetted by his boss in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It's known as having your issue and spending it too.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
