<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INDIA-HIGHTECH-0324-C     03-23 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-HIGHTECH-0324-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO HIGHLIGHT INDIA'S GROWING COMPUTER INDUSTRY
 &HT;    With INDIA-CLINTON-0324.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAIPUR, India _ A high-tech revolution isn't the first thing
that comes to mind when Americans think of the impoverished
villages of India.
</P>
<P>
   In the hamlet of Nayla, though, just outside of Jaipur on
Thursday, President Clinton got an inspiring glimpse of the future
on Thursday, when he peered into a computer screen and saw
children's health records, downloaded from the Internet, staring
back.
</P>
<P>
   It got Clinton thinking about how the information revolution
could spawn an entire new approach to solving the problems of
health, education and grassroots development across the
impoverished villages of the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they really can make this work, and they get wired like
this, it'll take your breath away how much they'll grow and what
they'll do to attack poverty,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could change everything in a very, very short period of
time, and India is very well attuned to this.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton will spotlight the contributions India is
making to the global information revolution, when he travels to
Hyderabad, one of three cities forming India's ``Silicon
Triangle,'' center of a burgeoning computer industry that has made
India one of the world's most important players in the global
information revolution.
</P>
<P>
   From Hyderabad and the nearby cities of Bangalore and Pune,
India exported an estimated $4 billion worth of software and other
information technology products last year, helping to power the
country's economy to a 6.8 percent growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   India's high-tech industry, though, is exploding: government
economists estimate that the sector's exports will hit $85 billion
by 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister (Atal Bihari Vajpayee) has set a goal of
making the country an information technology superpower and a
leading exporter of software within the next 10 years,'' said Lael
Brainard, deputy White House national economic adviser. ``It looks
very likely that those goals are achievable.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies _ Texas Instruments, Microsoft, IBM, Oracle,
Motorola and GE Capital among them _ are playing an increasingly
large role. Each has operations in India, part of the $13.1 billion
U.S. companies have invested in the country overall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to give a speech on the subject Friday at the
Hyderabad Information Technology-Engineering Consultancy City _
HI-TEC City, for short _ one of the country's newest and best known
software centers.
</P>
<P>
   From HI-TEC City, Indian computer engineers and software design
experts are working for U.S. companies, often on-line in a virtual
office place, for a fraction of the salaries paid to American
workers with comparable skills. India has a deep talent pool _ the
second largest (after the United States) concentration of
scientists and engineers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``American and western management expertise and advanced
engineering technology can be married with the intellectual assets
around here, and these products can be downloaded and marketed to
the global user,'' a U.S. official explained. ``That's, in a
nutshell, what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
