<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR'S SEAT IN CANNES?; WEST COAST STORY; PRIMAL IMAGES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE KEHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Paris they call him Le Dauphin. His real name is Olivier
Barrot, and he is the heir apparent to one of the most powerful and
prestigious positions in the world of film, director of the Cannes
International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have heard that,'' chuckled Barrot, reedy and animated.
He was in New York to meet with members of the local film industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is official yet, but in December, Barrot was named to
the newly created position of ``artistic counselor'' to the
festival by Gilles Jacob, who has been the ``delegue general''
(French for honcho) of Cannes since 1978. At the same time Jacob
announced that he would be stepping into the more ceremonial role
of president after this year's festival, leaving his position, it
is widely expected, to be filled by Barrot.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as a surprise to many members of the
French film establishment, who had assumed that the job would go to
one of the prominent critics, film magazine editors or arts
administrators who had been publicly jockeying for it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Barrot comes from television, where since 1991 he has
been the host of ``Un Livre un Jour'' (``A Book a Day''), a
two-minute critique of a literary work that is broadcast six times
a week on the public network FR3.
</P>
<P>
   Barrot, whose impeccable English is tinged with a faint British
accent, acknowledges that his outsider status probably helped in
his appointment _ he arrives at the job free of favors owed _ but
points out that he has written several books about the movies,
including a study of the director Rene Clair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of people to meet and to listen to,'' Barrot
said. ``I want to be a good listener. I'm sure that Cannes, which
is No. 1, has to remain and will remain No. 1. Of course, we need
to think things over. If Gilles Jacob picked me, it's because he
thought I might have a few suggestions to make.''
</P>
<P>
   One priority for Barrot is to tighten the festival's
relationship with American producers and distributors. Because of
its placement at the middle of May, Cannes often misses out on the
more prestigious American productions, which tend to be released in
September (at which point they go to the Venice Film Festival) or
in December (when they are scooped up by Berlin). After his New
York visit, he was headed for Hollywood to meet with studio
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to know that 500, 600 films come in for
consideration. It's something else to actually screen those films,
which I've been doing. We have daily shows, we screen six, seven,
eight a day for our two committees, one for foreign films and one
for French films.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two committees never intermingle. It's all very secretive,
very confidential. It's night and day and weekends over three
months. And then, by tradition, Gilles Jacob has a press conference
on April 20 when he reveals the selection.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime Barrot is keeping his day job, which requires
him to read and review six books a week. ``After May,'' he said,
``we will see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   West Coast Story
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience always wants something fresh,'' said Jet Li, the
Asian martial-arts star who, with ``Romeo Must Die,'' has just
realized his first leading role in an American film. ``So every
year you need to create something new.''
</P>
<P>
   A hugely popular figure in Hong Kong since his first feature,
``Shaolin Temple,'' was released in 1979, Li is now hoping to
follow his friends and colleagues Jackie Chan, Chow Yun-Fat and
John Woo into Hollywood filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Li defines his style as ``a little bit different from Chan's, a
little bit cool, so it looks like dancing.'' He uses acrobatics to
create big, comedy movements. ``I am a little bit serious,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Why have Asian stars and Asian styles suddenly caught on with
the American public? ``Since 1990, the world has changed a lot,''
Li said by telephone from Los Angeles. ``Because of satellite TV
and the Internet, people get to know each other very well. Maybe 10
or 20 years ago, Americans could hardly understand what Chinese
people look like, what is their life, what kind of house or what
kind of bicycle they have. But now the audience has had a chance to
watch old Hong Kong movies, and Hong Kong people watch a lot of
American movies, so they know each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Romeo Must Die,'' a very loose adaptation of
Shakespeare set among warring black and Asian gangs in San
Francisco, is a departure from Li's established style. In Hong Kong
films like ``Fong Sai Yuk'' (1993) and ``Once Upon a Time in
China'' (1991), the boyish-looking Li plays very pure, virtuous
heroes with powers just this side of the supernatural. In
``Romeo,'' which opened nationwide on Wednesday, his character, a
vengeance-seeking escaped convict, is darker and more morally
ambiguous than his standard character.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cultural thing,'' he said. ``In Asia, from the
beginning the good guy is the good guy, and the bad guy is the bad
guy,'' he said. ``In America it is more complicated. In Chinese
films, the martial arts we can a little bit overdo. In America, in
this kind of story, we cannot do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he plan on commuting between Hong Kong and U.S.
productions? ``In America, productions are bigger and better than
in Hong Kong, so If I have a chance, I want to work here,'' he
said. ``Because you have more help and more money, you can tell a
story a little bit better than in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to dream!'' exclaimed Li. ``I think a movie is a dream.
I want to become a producer because you can bring some good ideas,
and then find a good, talented director and choreographer and
writer to finish your dream. To make your dream become truth! That
way is very interesting to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Primal Images
</P>
<P>
   Stan Brakhage describes his work as ``independent personal
filmmaking,'' and he has been at it for nearly 50 years, producing
classics like ``Window Baby Water Moving'' and ``Scenes From Under
Childhood.'' His subject is light in all of its qualities; his
imagery is abstract and primal.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Bard College will present Brakhage with an honorary
fine arts degree; in turn, Brakhage will present the college with
the world premiere of three new works, the 60-minute ``The God of
Day'' and the short films ``Persian Series No. 9'' and ``Water for
Maya.` The event, free and open to the public, begins at 6:30 p.m.
in Olin Hall on Bard's Annandale-on-Hudson campus; for more
information, call (914) 758-7512.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
