<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6106 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AIDA-REVIEW24-COX     03-23 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDA-REVIEW24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bold and sexy, `Aida' revels in magnificent metamorphosis
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Aida,'' in a word, soars.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets, even. Launched from the same biracial love story as
Verdi's opera, it's the passionate, stirring, thrilling Elton John
musical for which this Broadway season was gasping.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which opened Thursday night at the Palace Theatre,
needed every inch of its 3,000-mile runway, which started 18 months
ago with lots of promise and big problems at Atlanta's Alliance
Theatre, then hung a big right turn in Chicago. The development was
fueled by the bottomless coffers of Disney: a budget estimated at
$15 million, matching the Mouse's ``Lion King'' for the Broadway
record.
</P>
<P>
   The lucre yields a state-of-the-art spectacle in the Andrew
Lloyd Webber mode. New sets by Bob Crowley (good riddance to
Atlanta's electronic pyramid) and lighting by Natasha Katz
transport viewers to a dream world in which ancient Egypt and a
brave, new multicultural America intersect. It's as if the
Tony-winning Irish set designer (``Carousel'') took his cue from a
phrase by the poet Wallace Stevens, shaping eternity with the image
of palms at the end of the mind.
</P>
<P>
   More important are talents firmly on track since Atlanta:
composer John and lyricist Tim Rice, who honed their solid pop-rock
score; and Sherie Rene Scott, who, er, fills out the role of the
voluptuous, romantically wronged Amneris with a
clowning-through-tears vulnerability that recalls Marilyn Monroe.
Those mighty Verdi divas were never this much fun.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Heather Headley, even more electrifying than
she was in Atlanta. She plays Aida, the Nubian princess torn
between duty to her vanquished people and her love for Radames
(Adam Pascal of ``Rent''), the Egyptian captain who defeated them.
Raising the emotional stakes is the big fat coincidence (where
would opera be without it?) that Aida, hiding her royal lineage,
becomes the slave and confidante to Amneris, who's heartbroken at
Radames' lack of enthusisam over their betrothal.
</P>
<P>
   This love triangle is strikingly illustrated in the Act 2
opener, ``A Step Too Far,'' in which the three leads sing marooned
in separate pools of light inside a pyramid-shaped neon tube that
traps them like a deadly laser beam.
</P>
<P>
   It's not these high-tech trimmings, though, that lift ``Aida''
from the mixed condition it showed in Chicago three months ago to
the dazzler it is now. It was clearly sweat _ and strict attention
to musical theater traditions as old as ``Oklahoma!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, finally, there's a number for Pascal alone (the most
improved player in the cast), ``Fortune Favors the Brave.'' It's
nothing special as a song, but it strongly establishes Radames'
swaggering, imperious character so that he can travel a full arc to
redemption as Aida's pacifist lover. It's in keeping with the more
sophisticated adult tone of the new book by David Henry Hwang and
director Robert Falls (with original author Linda Woolverton still
credited) that fleshes out Radames and balances the triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, finally, there's a clear, moving moment when Aida and
Radames forge their spiritual bond (in ``Enchantment Passing
Through''), which kindles to passion in their fiery clinch during
``Elaborate Lives.'' By the time Aida runs her hands the length of
her body with fierce longing, we've officially jumped the fence of
standard, sexless Disney fare. No wonder the company is producing
the musical under the new banner, Hyperion Theatricals, and keeping
the squeaky-clean Disney brand off the program's title page.
</P>
<P>
   Now, finally, that slave boy Mereb (Damian Perkins), who holds
the secret of Aida's birth, is not just a walk-on but the brave,
funny sidekick _ a classic Disney type. His signature theme is one
of those heart-tugging throwbacks to the classic Broadway sound,
fitting nicely into the John mix of rock, pop and gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Now Headley, barely 25, appears to have crossed some magical
threshold of maturity, so that she has a regal authority to go with
her magnificent voice. Her show-stoppers, ``The Dance of the Robe''
and ``The Gods Love Nubia,'' nearly rival ``The Lion King's''
legendary opener on the goose-bump meter. In fact, Headley must
belt too much music, and it might take the elimination of a good
ballad, ``Easy as Life,'' to prevent overkill.
</P>
<P>
   The only other serious problem with the production is a
jarringly idiotic fashion show, a shameless pandering to the campy
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida'' is a watershed in several ways. It establishes director
Falls _ who conquered the dramatic end of the theatrical spectrum
with 1999's ``Death of a Salesman'' _ as the king of Broadway, for
it's his genius that steered ``Aida'' through stormy development.
It's a breakthrough for the Alliance as a national player to be
credited on the title page as the show's original venue (even
though the 1996 tour of ``Blues for an Alabama Sky'' was the
Atlanta theater's own, higher achievement).
</P>
<P>
   And the production should win Disney _ if not love _ at least
respect from the theater and media worlds. The company could have
chosen the safe route of ``Beauty and the Beast'' but instead kept
sweating the details, striving for a bolder, more original magic in
the tradition of ``Lion King.'' On Tony Award night in June, the
word ``Aida'' will surely be the most frequent refrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida''
</P>
<P>
   Open-ended run. $25-$80. Palace Theatre, Broadway at 47th
Street, New York.
</P>
<P>
   1- 800-755-4000 or www.ticketmaster.com.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The rocking opera legend that started shakily in
Atlanta has been retooled into Broadway's hottest new musical.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
