<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Margaret Mitchell House host to literary happenings
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta's literary scene suffered a setback when Cliff Graubart
ended the champagne-and-chatter book parties at his Old New York
Book Shop in 1996. For years, the shop had been a gathering place
of the literati and literary groupies anytime an Atlanta author
such as Paul Hemphill, Anne Rivers Siddons or Terry Kay published a
book.
</P>
<P>
   The Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum will try to fill the
cultural gap and become a center for Southern literature, says
spokeswoman Heather Hjetland. ``Working with members of our
literary advisory board, such as Tom Wolfe and Pat Conroy, we will
be hosting a series of literary events on an ongoing basis.''
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m. Tuesday, Robert Morgan will read from his novel ``Gap
Creek,'' a recent pick for Oprah's Book Club. At 4 p.m. April 2,
three winners of the recent Southeast Booksellers Association Book
Award will be featured: Fred Chappell will read from his novel
``Look Back the Green Valley,'' Janisse Ray will talk about her
memoir, ``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood,'' and poet Rodney Jones
will read from his ``Elegy for the Southern Drawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Both events will be at the Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum, 999
Peachtree St. N.E., 404-249-7012. ($5 donation requested.) More
programs will be announced in April.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Books on the Web: After the stunning success of Stephen King's
Internet-only novella, ``Riding the Bullet,'' other authors are
looking at e-books more seriously. British author Jeffrey Archer
may tailor a short story for the Internet, says spokesman Stephan
Shakespeare. ``He has written one short story with four endings,''
Shakespeare told the London Independent. ``The Internet opens all
kinds of narrative possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
