<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6109 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS26-COX     03-23 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For 40 years, with wit and grace, Red Smith chronicled events of
`major insignificance'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, March 26.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Red Smith was in the middle of the ocean when news came by radio
dispatch that Babe Ruth had died. It was August 1948. Who knows
what the premier sportswriter of the day was doing in the middle of
the ocean in the middle of the baseball season _ the season he
liked best _ but in no sense was he out to sea. From the ship M.V.
Brittanic he filed a column that was vintage Red Smith:
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the Babe is gone, what's to be said that hasn't been
said? Nothing, when you come down to it. Just that he was Babe
Ruth. Which tells it all, for there never was another and never
will be. Probably he was the greatest ball player who ever lived,
Ty Cobb and Honus Wagner and the rest notwithstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   There is likewise a consensus that Walter W. (for Wellesley)
``Red'' Smith was the greatest sportswriter who ever lived. The
sports pages are the recycling center for superlatives, but when
Editor &AMP; Publisher magazine chose the 25 most influential newspaper
people of the 20th century last year, there was H.L. Mencken and
Ernie Pyle, Joseph Pulitzer and Adolph Ochs, and there was also Red
Smith. No other sportswriter. Donald Hall, poet and essayist,
thought Smith's columns as perfect as sonnets. Jacques Barzun
recommended him to students at Columbia University as a model of
colloquial prose style. And Ernest Hemingway, in ``Across the River
and Into the Trees,'' writes of a character who ``was reading Red
Smith, and he liked him very much.''
</P>
<P>
   When Smith died in 1982, he had been writing about events of
``major insignificance'' for four decades. He began on the
Milwaukee Sentinel and finished with The New York Times. In between
were stops in St. Louis and Philadelphia and, before it folded, at
the New York Herald-Tribune. He once wrote seven columns a week.
</P>
<P>
   An evolving prose
</P>
<P>
   Any retrospective of Smith's work invites iconoclasm, as Ira
Berkow, Smith's biographer and a fine sportswriter himself,
doubtless knows. If dues should be paid, so too should
reconsideration be uninfluenced by nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as ``Red Smith on Baseball'' amply shows, there was
none better, day after day, year after year. But how good was he?
Line by line, there have been better stylists. Roger Kahn _ who
writes of Smith in a dust-jacket blurb, ``He wreathed himself, as
he wreathed his writing, in wit and grace, courtesy and kindness''
_ had more reach. Robert Lipsyte and George Vecsey, sportswriters
for the Times, have more depth. And not many have matched John
Updike in The New Yorker, writing of Ted Williams' home run in his
last at-bat at Fenway Park, where Williams had heard so many boos
over his tempestuous career:
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran as he always ran out home runs _ hurriedly, unsmiling,
head down, as if our praise were a storm of rain to get out of. He
didn't tip his cap. Though we thumped, wept and chanted, `We Want
Ted,' for minutes after he hid in the dugout, he did not come back.
...,'' Updike wrote. ``Gods do not answer letters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Red Smith was doing it day after day, or close to it, some
days more felicitously than others. Reading him decade by decade,
from the 1940s until 1982, you see how his celebrated prose in fact
changed quite noticeably. He came of age in the day of Damon
Runyon, Heywood Hale Broun and Grantland Rice, and his early
columns have echoes of a style that does not wear well (``By
special arrangement with the Hudson Tubes,'' he began a column in
1946, ``an expedition to this model political community was made
today to get a look at Jackie Robinson, the model Negro infielder
of the Dodgers' model Montreal farm'').
</P>
<P>
   A captive of the sports page
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, when his syndicated column appeared in 250 papers,
his voice was losing the occasional mannerism; the turns of phrase
were lighter. He had come to admire the natural ease of E.B.
White's prose, and the emulation is evident. But he never quite
achieved a range and fluency that would be at home outside the
sports page. Easy and often enjoyable as he was to read, he was
seldom memorable.
</P>
<P>
   This is not, on its face, a criticism: He was paid only to write
a sports column, and in his prime he wrote the best one in the
land. But it's worth asking whether those events of ``major
insignificance'' he wrote about did not, now and then, bear closer
examination than he gave them. It never occurred to Smith that
baseball's color line, for example, was something to be challenged
in print. Or that women sportswriters should have the same right of
locker-room access that male reporters enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   He was both a master of his craft and a captive of it.
``Looking,'' he wrote once of Babe Ruth, ``you would have seen a
barrel swaddled in a wrap-around camel-hair topcoat with a flat
camel-hair cap on the round head. Thus arrayed he was instantly
recognizable not only on Broadway in New York but also on the Ginza
in Tokyo.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age of ESPN, as Wilfrid Sheed once put it, sportswriters
are ``heralds without news, eyewitnesses in a world of
eyewitnesses.'' Smith, at his best, recalls a day when they were,
if not lords of the earth, at least of the late edition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red Smith on Baseball: The Game's
</P>
<P>
   Greatest Writer on the Game's Greatest Years. Foreword by Ira
Berkow. Ivan R. Dee, Publisher. $24.95. 363 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
