<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVES-BUSINESS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's hard work making career of party scene
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Atlanta's party scene flourishes, some people are
raving for dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Weil, 28, and Sabrina Sexton Weil, 25, have turned their
passion for raves into Lunar Magazine, an e-zine that features DJ
profiles, party reviews and a calendar of Atlanta parties.
Launching in February 1999, Lunar (www.lunarmagazine.com) now has
50,000 visitors a month. Although it hasn't turned a profit, it
carries ads from companies such as Microsoft, Priceline.com and
Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   The couple met in 1992 at the University of Georgia. They threw
parties that attracted as many as 700 to Athens, Ga., from all over
the Southeast. In Atlanta, they found computer industry jobs, but
they wanted to continue in the rave scene. ``There are times when
we've looked at each other and said, `Let's just quit,' because
it's so much work,'' Sabrina said. ``But if we did, I think people
would bomb our house.''
</P>
<P>
   Other area ravepreneurs include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Darren ``D-Funk'' Hart, 23, and his girlfriend, Jennifer
Horton, 24, of Lawrenceville, Ga., who have been throwing raves for
about a year under the name Charisma. They and their other
investors put up $30,000 for their first party. ``When you throw
your first party, you always lose your shirt,'' said Hart. For the
next party, Charisma is printing about 20,000 fliers for
distribution at record stores, under windshields and at an Atlanta
clothing store called Wish, which specializes in rave gear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gene Carbonell, 27, of Atlanta, who recently quit his day job
_ and his girlfriend _ to devote more time to his career. He's
hired an agent, landed his first foreign gig at a dance club in
Mexico and signed a recording contract with an Orlando record
label. ``This is my livelihood now,'' said Carbonell. ``But it's
not about the money. I've done this for free, and I will again. I
love this so much I will be doing it until the day I die.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
