<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, March 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The jet stream disturbance that brought thunderstorms and some
tornadoes to the southern Plains in the last two days will weaken
as it moves to the northern Mississippi Valley on Friday. As a
result, thundershowers from southern Minnesota to the western Ohio
Valley should not be severe, although local downpours will occur.
Lighter showers will spread across the Great Lakes states Friday
night. In the wake of the showers, breezy, cooler conditions will
arrive in the northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and unseasonably mild weather will cover most of the East on
Friday. Sprawling high pressure will promote ample sunshine over
most areas near the Atlantic seaboard. Sun will mix with clouds
west of the Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   The West will be mainly dry, although scattered snow showers
will accompany a front in the southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DOPPLER RADAR
</P>
<P>
   Spring is when Doppler radar proves its worth. The radar can
detect twisting winds in a thunderstorm, a sign that a tornado
might be developing. The radar relies on a principle called the
Doppler effect. As a train approaches, its whistle seems to have a
higher pitch. When the train is moving away, the whistle has a
lower pitch. This is the Doppler effect. In essence, raindrops
caught in the rotating winds in a severe thunderstorm have
different ``pitches,'' depending on whether they move toward or
away from the radar. Forecasters can thus get an early clue of an
impending tornado. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
