<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-RESIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RWANDA PRESIDENT QUITS, UPSETTING POLITICAL BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Rwanda's president resigned Thursday, capping
months of growing tension in the government and casting uncertainty
over the central African country's pursuit of ethnic reconciliation
between Hutus and Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
   Pasteur Bizimungu's departure follows the forced resignations
earlier this year of four Cabinet ministers who had been the
targets of parliamentary investigations into official corruption.
In what turned out to be his last major speech, Bizimungu lashed
out at the legislature Monday, accusing it of destabilizing the
country and contravening the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in government comes during Rwanda's delicate healing
process six years after 800,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus were
slain in a genocidal spree sponsored by the former Hutu leadership.
A prominent Hutu in a predominantly Tutsi government, Bizimungu
served as a symbol of national unity.
</P>
<P>
   It also coincides with rising anti-Tutsi sentiment throughout
the region as frustration grows with Rwanda's involvement in the
war in neighboring Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a reconciliation point of view, this will shake up the
show,'' said Jan van Eck, a specialist from the University of Cape
Town on conflict resolution in central Africa. ``The government has
been accused of being Tutsi. If they don't have a Hutu in there at
all, it will create a poor impression. The picture of a joint front
will be tarnished.''
</P>
<P>
   Bizimungu came to office after the 1994 genocide as part of a
government of national unity and reconciliation established by the
Rwandese Patriotic Front, the Tutsi-led rebel army that toppled the
murderous Hutu government and set about trying to reverse decades
of ethnic polarization. Compulsory identity cards, indicating
whether one was Hutu or Tutsi, were banned. The new parliament
included a careful mix of both ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the new president was never the fulcrum of power. Real
authority rested with the new vice president and defense minister,
Colonel Paul Kagame, a talented young military strategist who led
the rebellion. Kagame heads both the military and the ruling party
and is widely considered to be the driving force in government.
</P>
<P>
   Rising tensions in the government in recent months have
reflected that uneasy relationship, sources said. Numerous
corruption inquiries aimed against senior government officials
allied more with Bizimungu than Kagame have resulted in a wave of
resignations. Two of the four ministers recently forced out were
close friends of the president. Joseph Sebarenzi, a Tutsi from a
small opposition party who was speaker of the National Assembly,
resigned in January after being accused of graft.
</P>
<P>
   Bizimungu's speech Monday followed the announcement a day
earlier of a new Cabinet constructed by the ruling party over his
objections.
</P>
<P>
   But all sides were united Thursday during an emergency session
of the parliament to debate and accept Bizimungu's resignation,
according to one senior legislator. ``Hutus and Tutsis were all
together on the decision to condemn the president,'' said Tito
Rutaremara, a member of parliament from the ruling party, speaking
on the phone from Kigali, the capital. ``All the people who heard
his speech were scandalized.''
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic ramifications of Bizimungu's resignation both within
Rwanda and throughout central Africa may be determined in the next
few days as a successor is put in place. ``This is a most delicate
moment,'' said Tarsis Karugarama, a prosecutor general in Kigali.
``Let's see how it is handled constitutionally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
