<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6127 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-23 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEASONING VERSUS NEW BLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are always two sides to politics: an inside
and an outside.
</P>
<P>
   The insiders are usually seasoned veterans of the party
establishment, and the outsiders usually younger versions eager to
shove aside their elders to make room for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This continuing job rotation pits seasoned, experienced heads
against those who can bring fresh energy and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the old-timers have outstayed their welcome and are
out of touch with the changing needs of their constituents. But
sometimes the newcomers are uninformed egotists who lack the
character and integrity of the incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   Old is not necessarily bad, and new is not necessarily good.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, thanks to former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the
Republican congressional majority is about to find out whether a
massive turnover of powerful GOP House chairmanships next year
makes government more responsive or less.
</P>
<P>
   This assumes that the Republicans retain control of the House in
the fall election, which is far from a sure thing. If the Democrats
recapture the majority, they will control the chairmanships and set
their own House rules.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Gingrich's devotion to term limits, he imposed
mandatory caps of six years on every chairmanship in the flush of
the 1994 Republican capture of Congress. The action was meant to
help consolidate his own power as speaker, which failed
spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, congressional Republicans are stuck with the rule.
And the most important consequence is certain turmoil in the ranks
next year. Five current committee chairmen have chosen to retire
rather than be demoted from their powerful positions.
</P>
<P>
   The five departing Republican heavies are Ways and Means
Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas; Commerce Chairman Tom Bliley,
R-Va.,; Education Chairman William Goodling, R-Pa; Budget Chairman
John Kasich, R-Ohio, and Appropriations Chairman John Edward
Porter, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, in his 15th term, is 72 years old. Bliley, in his 10th
term, is 68. Goodling, in his 13th term, is 72. Kasich, the baby of
the group at 48, is in his 9th term. Porter, in his 10th term, is
64.
</P>
<P>
   These men are not ancient by today's standards. They possess all
their marbles and have a wealth of experience. Archer and Kasich
are better-known nationally than the others and have often clashed
over their differing budget priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But only Kasich can be considered a major legislative influence,
credited with winning a balanced budget deal with President Clinton
in 1997. Kasich was tarred, however, by the 1995-1996 budget
stalemate that led to a government shutdown, for which the GOP took
most of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Archer has had trouble dominating his own committee and for
years has promoted a tax on consumption to replace the income tax,
an idea for which he has been unable to garner any support.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley is best known for announcing when he took over the
Commerce Committee chairmanship that there would be no more
hearings into tobacco industry practices. It was before his
committee, under the previous Democratic chairman, Henry Waxman,
that five industry giants raised their hands and vowed they did not
know smoking was addictive. Despite the escalating political
struggle to contain smoking, the Commerce Committee under Bliley
has been missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   Goodling is a strong conservative who initially tried to dump
the popular school lunch program in favor of unmonitored block
grants to the states. He backed away from that plan when it became
a public relations disaster but has since tried to do in other
domestic programs, undercutting the minimum wage and limiting
unions in various ways.
</P>
<P>
   Porter is the only moderate of the group on social issues. He
has departed from the party line often enough to arouse right-wing
opposition at home and in Congress. He was even briefly inclined to
oppose the impeachment of President Clinton although in the end he
joined his GOP colleagues in the official condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   No individual is indispensable. These men can be replaced, and
few voters will notice. But the internal dynamics will surely be
different. The personalities, political skills and ideology of
their successors will determine how these all-important committees
change.
</P>
<P>
   Congress used to operate strictly by seniority, but that too has
been transformed. Now the next-in-line must often withstand a
challenge from an aggressive colleague of less seniority, which can
make for a healthy policy dialogue or build fresh resentments.
</P>
<P>
   The basic term limits cause, which Republicans used to eagerly
embrace, has now fallen on bad times as members of Congress elected
on a pledge to limit their service face their own, unwanted
retirement. Some are keeping their word, but two prominent men are
not.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Watts Jr., R-Okla., chairman of the House Republican
Conference and the party's most visible elected black official,
said when he was elected in 1994 that he would serve only three
terms. But now that the deadline is here, he has changed his mind,
saying he no longer thinks limiting terms is a potent political
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger hypocrite, however, is George Nethercutt, R-Wash.,
who took House Speaker Thomas Foley's seat away largely on a pledge
to serve no more than three terms to avoid the ossification of long
service. Nethercutt says he made a mistake and has discovered that
seniority can be useful after all. What a mush-head.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
