<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-FTOREK-BOS &LR;      03-23 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FTOREK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON REPLACES FTOREK AT HELM OF DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shaky ground that every coach treads crumbled unexpectedly
Thursday beneath the feet of Robbie Ftorek, who woke up as head
coach of the first-place Devils and soon found himself walking the
fault line of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek, whose Devils held the top spot in the NHL's Eastern
Conference with a 41-25-8 record, was replaced by Hall of Fame
defenseman Larry Robinson, who will be behind the bench when the
Devils face the Islanders Friday night in Uniondale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that his Devils were playing without ``ice
discipline'' of late, New Jersey general manager Lou Lamoriello
said the move was necessary because he ``did not see light at the
end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old Ftorek, a star with Needham High School in the
'60s, was not popular with the Devils' players, including veterans,
which ultimately led to his downfall. Widely considered to be
stubborn, strong-willed, and unwilling to coddle players _
essential for every coach here in the 21st century _ Ftorek was
dismissed after going 39 games over .500 in his nearly two years
behind the Exit 16W bench.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defenseman Lyle Odelein, recently traded to Phoenix,
said upon leaving that the Devils, though successful, were
``playing for themselves and not for the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say the team is not as happy as it appears,''
Odelein added. An unrestricted free agent July 1, Odelein bluntly
said he would not consider re-signing with the Devils as long as
Ftorek remained coach.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Souray made similar comments upon being dealt to the
Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost respect for me,'' said Souray, referring to Ftorek,
``and I lost respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The move was reminiscent of Boston's firing of Fred Creighton
nearly 20 years to the day, March 22, 1980. With rookie Ray Bourque
in the lineup, Creighton's Bruins were an impressive 40-20-13 with
seven games left.
</P>
<P>
   But with the club in a 1-2-4 tailspin, and with veterans
grumbling that Creighton was a poor and unlikable replacement for
beloved coach Don Cherry, general manager Harry Sinden dumped
Creighton and moved behind the bench himself.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden, in his office Thursday, recalled that he made the move
after conferring with a number of players upon the club arriving in
Atlanta following a loss the night before in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say who they were,'' said Sinden. ``But from that
meeting, it became clear to me that the team had tuned out Fred. I
don't know if it was a matter of them not liking him, or what, but
from what they were telling me, they'd tuned him out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, with Sinden back there for the first time since
coaching them to the Stanley Cup in '70, went 6-1-0 in the final
seven games and dumped Pittsburgh in the opening round of the
playoffs before falling to the Islanders in Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils are looking for the same kind of emotional jolt with
Robinson, their former assistant coach, now calling the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Winners of the Stanley Cup in '95, when Robinson assisted head
coach Jacques Lemaire, the Devils missed the playoffs the next
season and have won but one postseason round since. Last spring,
after going an impressive 47-24-11 under Ftorek in the regular
season, they got rubbed out by Pittsburgh in Round 1 of the
playoffs, able to score just 18 goals in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek was not available to the media following Lamoriello's
announcement, which was made via conference call from his office in
East Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   Similar to the Bruins of 20 years ago, the Devils had lost 10 of
their last 16 games, a fall that prompted Lamoriello last week to
deal for Alexander Mogilny at the trade deadline. Earlier they
picked up highly-regarded Russian defenseman Vladimir Malakhov from
the Canadiens in exchange for Souray.
</P>
<P>
   With little improvement following those deals, Lamoriello pulled
the trigger, opting to finish the season with Robinson, who was
dismissed as the Kings' head coach last spring after getting Los
Angeles into only one playoff round in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of people phoned me and asked, `How are you
feeling?'' Robinson said recently, reflecting on his four years as
the Kings head coach. ``And I'd say, `Fine, why are you asking?'
And they'd say, `Because you look like hell on TV.' Being a head
coach does age a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who will turn 49 in June, now gets to find out if he
has a team for the ages, or one that simply ages him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1827EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
