<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-TIGERS-580&AMP;AD     03-23 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TIGERS-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT A TOURIST IN INDIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CLINTON-INDIA) 
(rk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAIPUR, India _ President Clinton rode into the tall grass and
wild countryside of northern India Thursday afternoon, clouds of
dust trailing his open-air safari vehicle as he went in search of
the elusive Bengal tiger.
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it _ or astute advance work by Indian
trackers _ the president came across not one, but two of his
quarry.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, like any wondrous tourist who had just seen one of
the sensations of the animal kingdom, Clinton was effusive about
the experience.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, there was a ``huge male'' yellow and black
striped tiger, known as Boomerang, lying imperiously under a tree.
``He's the biggest tiger out there, the biggest of the 16 on the
preserve,'' Clinton said, with some satisfaction, to a group of
reporters during an after-dinner conversation at his luxury hotel
here.
</P>
<P>
   To top the first sighting, Clinton's guide, Fateh Singh Rathore,
then steered the vehicle toward a female tiger stalking deer: ``She
missed getting the deer by a second,'' said Clinton, who then went
on to describe egrets, peacocks and storks.
</P>
<P>
   Before the president's departure for India, the White House was
upfront in saying that part of his purpose was to show off India,
in all its aspects, to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Clinton visited a village in the morning, and then
went about enjoying the high-end tourist market and publicizing the
conservation movement that is trying to save the dwindling numbers
of Bengal tigers.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential entourage chose the Ranthambhore Tiger Reserve,
one of 27 such havens in India that try to protect the tigers
threatened by the destruction of their habitat, and most of all by
poaching. An illegal market for tiger parts used for traditional
medicines flourishes in India and Clinton said he had been told
during his drive that 20 tigers had been slaughtered in the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,500 Bengal tigers remain in India, a dramatic reduction
from the estimated 40,000 that roamed the jungles as late as 1925,
according to local conservation groups.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton described his guide, Rathore, as a veteran
conservationist who had survived the wrath of his village neighbors
some years ago when he decided to try to set up the preserve here.
Some of the villagers' homes had to be moved when the preserve was
created more than 20 years ago, Clinton said, adding that Rathore
had done heroic work against the odds to save the endangered
animals.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with Clinton's safari, the White House said
Thursday the United States would give nine small grants totaling
$250,000 to wildlife groups working in tiger and elephant
conservation in India.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking off on his three-hour safari, Clinton toured a
16th-century palace-citadel known as Amber Fort, considered a
classic example of Mogul architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The president admired the walled compound, strolled through its
interior with his daughter, Chelsea, and had more encounters with
India's animal world.
</P>
<P>
   The fort serves as a habitat for monkeys, some of which seemed
fascinated with the presidential visitor, a fascination that
Clinton said he wasn't sure how to cope with.
</P>
<P>
   But, then he said, he realized that the monkeys were taken not
so much with him, but with the leis of flowers that were strung
around his neck when he arrived at the fort. Clinton threw a lei of
red blooms at the most curious monkey, a maneuver that solved the
situation. ``Once I was deflowered, they weren't interested in
me,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the advice of aides who accompanied him Thursday, the
president said, he forsook one of the traditions of the fort: an
elephant ride through the stone gate entrance. Other celebrity
visitors have made such rides, including Jacqueline Kennedy during
her 1962 tour of India as first lady, and Hillary Rodham Clinton
and Chelsea in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's large physique and presidential dignity were not
two concepts that went well together on the back of an elephant,
two of his top aides counseled, who then went off for a ride
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   After his foray into the outdoors, Clinton spent the night at
the Rajvilas, a luxury resort hotel of ersatz Mogul architecture
and handsome rooms decked out with sunken marble baths and canopied
four poster beds. White House staffers said the hotel was among the
fanciest the president and his advisers had stayed at during his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's two-bedroom suite, billed as the Royal Villa, usually
goes for $1,200 a night. His aides said that the hotel had offered
discounts for the White House party, a deal that is often arranged
with hotels abroad which garner publicity from a presidential
visit.
</P>
<P>
   But the prices at the gift shop, where fashionable pashmina
shawls _ made from the hair of goats grown in Kashmir _ were not
cut rate. One antique example of an outsized shawl, described by
the shop's sales woman as 120 years old, was tagged at $9,877.
</P>
<P>
   This probably far exceeded the cost of two carpets Clinton
bought at the Sheraton Hotel where he stayed in New Delhi. The
salesman later told the Indian papers that the price was a ``trade
secret.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
