<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-OSCARS-PREDICT24-COX     03-23 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-PREDICT24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweeping `Beauty' likely to give Spacey second award
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It makes simple sense that 1999's onslaught of
the most bracing films since the '70s, Hollywood's last golden age,
has beget an Oscar race whose unwieldly mix of the offbeat and
squarely conservative is flummoxing the industry and bedeviling
odds-makers. Shoo-ins seemed to evaporate with the release of each
new and unusual film last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since its fall arrival, ``American Beauty'' has rightly been
polishing the champagne glasses for a victor's party. Until
December rolled around and ``The Cider House Rules'' and the
attendant Miramax hype-cyclone came crashing in, tearing down
streamers and flipping off the music. With a smirk to last year's
Oscar upset _ underdog ``Shakespeare in Love'' blindsiding
Dreamworks' ``Saving Private Ryan'' _ Miramax is rabidly
campaigning to steamroll Dreamworks again, by crushing ``Beauty''
with a big ``House.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Shakespeare'' shocker may have elated this critic, but I
don't want to see a repeat. ``Cider House'' is excellent;
``American Beauty'' is better. It should win. It will win. Watch it
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my take on who/what will _ and who/what should _ win in
an extraordinary year when ``Being John Malkovich'' is challenging
a dowdy costume drama (``Topsy-Turvy'') and a bilious dark-comedy
about a pot-puffing suburban Everyman (``American Beauty'') will
conquer a Tom Hanks weeper (``The Green Mile'').
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN BEAUTY'' (DREAMWORKS)
</P>
<P>
   The story: Suburban ennui _ the white man's burden _ blossoms
with acidic comic immediacy, as one guy's midlife crisis explodes
into corrosive self-emancipation that takes a wrecking ball to his
adrift family unit. Watching the walls crumble is perverse release.
A bittersweet bouquet that rarely wilts.
</P>
<P>
   Awards: Golden Globe (drama), National Board of Review.
</P>
<P>
   Nominations: 8
</P>
<P>
   Box office: $103 million
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 3-2
</P>
<P>
   ``THE CIDER HOUSE RULES'' (MIRAMAX)
</P>
<P>
   The story: John Irving's masterful adaptation of his novel
preserves the wondrous Irvingian sweep in a coming-of-age fable
that enfolds birth, life, love, death, loss and redemption with
affecting power. Epic elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Awards: None.
</P>
<P>
   Nominations: 7
</P>
<P>
   Box office: $45.8 million
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 4-1
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GREEN MILE'' (WARNER BROS.)
</P>
<P>
   The story: A monumental chunk of cloying Hollywood melodrama,
based on Stephen King's serial novel, shows how some sweet Death
Row guards are ennobled by a giant black inmate's supernatural CPR
on the sick and dying. It makes them better men, and makes chumps
of us all.
</P>
<P>
   Awards: None.
</P>
<P>
   Nominations: 4
</P>
<P>
   Box office: $134.4 million
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 10-1
</P>
<P>
   ``THE INSIDER'' (BUENA VISTA)
</P>
<P>
   The story: A fired Big Tobacco employee blows the whistle on his
ex-bosses. ``60 Minutes'' smells a cover-up, and its crusade
unleashes a maelstrom of moral crises, both personal and
journalistic. The resounding message: Big Tobacco is an evil
empire, but sometimes journalists can be ninnies, too.
</P>
<P>
   Awards: L.A. Film Critics.
</P>
<P>
   Nominations: 7
</P>
<P>
   Box office: $28.3 million
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 15-1
</P>
<P>
   ``THE SIXTH SENSE'' (BUENA VISTA)
</P>
<P>
   The story: A precocious boy is tormented by grisly visions of
the dead. While Bruce Willis' psychiatrist helps relieve the boy of
phantoms, he finds he has a shocking issue of his own that needs
tending.
</P>
<P>
   Awards: None.
</P>
<P>
   Nominations: 6
</P>
<P>
   Box office: $288.5 million
</P>
<P>
   Odds: 8-1
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA'S RATING:
</P>
<P>
   What will win: ``American Beauty.'' Its shelf is already
drooping with trophies, everyone's seen it, it has the most
nominations and it carries the fewest equivocations about its
standing. But don't write-off ``Cider House Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   What should win: ``American Beauty.'' Crafted with hypnotic
precision and devilish elegance, it's the most roundly entertaining
and emotionally piercing film of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   BEST DIRECTOR
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Lasse Hallstrom, ``The Cider House Rules''; Spike
Jonze, ``Being John Malkovich''; Michael Mann, ``The Insider''; Sam
Mendes, ``American Beauty''; M. Night Shyamalan, ``The Sixth
Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Sam Mendes.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Sam Mendes. Not tethered to Hollywood
conventions, the Broadway hit-maker (``Cabaret,'' ``The Blue
Room'') imbues his film debut with a silky, dreamy sheen that
poetically articulates Kevin Spacey's drifting between reality and
the id, life and death. He wrests a spectacular ensemble
performance from his cast.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Russell Crowe, ``The Insider''; Richard Farnsworth,
``The Straight Story''; Sean Penn, ``Sweet and Lowdown''; Kevin
Spacey, ``American Beauty''; Denzel Washington, ``The Hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Kevin Spacey.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Kevin Spacey. I wouldn't mind Farnsworth swiping
this one from the whippersnapper; his organic understatement in
``The Straight Story'' revealed a confident master wringing wizened
wonder from thin air. But more people saw the high-profile Spacey,
who, let's face it, was nothing less than exhilarating _ biting,
empathic, cathartic _ as a deadpan dead man.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Annette Bening, ``American Beauty''; Janet McTeer,
``Tumbleweeds''; Julianne Moore, ``The End of the Affair''; Meryl
Streep, ``Music of the Heart''; Hilary Swank ``Boys Don't Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Annette Bening. A Hollywood insider in a film no
one has missed. She could get it to assure that ``Beauty's'' sweep
is pure.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Hilary Swank. And it could happen if the Academy
swallows hard. Swank's Golden Globe-winning turn as a transgender
gal posing as a boy was the most daring, challenging and revelatory
performance of the year. It rattled.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Michael Caine, ``The Cider House Rules''; Tom Cruise,
``Magnolia''; Michael Clarke Duncan, ``The Green Mile''; Jude Law,
``The Talented Mr. Ripley''; Haley Joel Osment, ``The Sixth
Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Haley Joel Osment. Oscar loves that rare commodity
_ a truly talented child actor _ and rewards them eagerly. This
kid's got it. It doesn't hurt he's in the highest-grossing movie of
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Jude Law. He lent sparkling dynamics to the
flaccid ``Talented Mr. Ripley'' in a performance rippling with
nuance that both charmed and curdled our regard.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Toni Collette, ``The Sixth Sense''; Angelina Jolie,
``Girl, Interrupted''; Catherine Keener, ``Being John Malkovich'';
Samantha Morton, ``Sweet and Lowdown''; Chloe Sevigny, ``Boys Don't
Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Angelina Jolie. She got the Golden Globe for her
showy turn as a mental patient. She's a hot young actress riding a
meteor, which Oscar adores. (See recently: Marisa Tomei and Mira
Sorvino.)
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Samantha Morton. As a mute naif, Morton's
glowing sun-face became a flickering screen of emotional
telegraphy. She was a miraculous font of comic poignancy _ Buster
Keaton by way of Harpo Marx, with a dash of Lil-- ian Gish.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ORIGINAL SCREENPLAY
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Alan Ball, ``American Beauty''; Charlie Kaufman,
``Being John Malkovich''; Paul Thomas Anderson, ``Magnolia''; M.
Night Shyamalan, ``The Sixth Sense''; Mike Leigh, ``Topsy-Turvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Alan Ball. Fresh, sharp, funny and coiled with
jack-in-the-box jolts, Ball's ``American Beauty'' script is
nevertheless a lazy choice considering the labyrinthine literary
pyrotechnics of ``Magnolia'' and ``Topsy-Turvy'' and the unfiltered
delirium of ``Being John Malkovich,'' which will take the trophy if
``Beauty'' doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Mike Leigh. A plush jungle of language, Leigh's
extravagantly detailed, gorgeously eloquent biographical aria to
Gilbert and Sullivan isn't just fine filmmaking. It traces the epic
contours of great literature, popping to life with time, place and
people, and waltzing to the lilting music of well-bred words.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ADAPTED SCREENPLAY
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: John Irving, ``The Cider House Rules''; Alexander
Payne and Jim Taylor, ``Election''; Frank Darabont, ``The Green
Mile''; Eric Roth and Michael Mann, ``The Insider''; Anthony
Minghella, ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: John Irving. The dark horse ``Cider House Rules''
will take this Oscar as a consolation prize after losing Best
Picture by a whisker.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Alexander Payne and Jim Taylor. The blueprint
for the year's zingiest comedy, the ``Election'' script is probably
too bitterly iconoclastic for the Academy's sugar-subsisting
palate. That makes us like it more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
