<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6154 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CAMPAIGN-GERALDINE-FE     03-23 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GERALDINE-FERRARO-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGETTING THE LADIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Campaign
Countdown commentary column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Campaign
Countdown, a rotating campaign-commentary column written by former
Democratic vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro and by
MSNBC host Laura Ingraham.) By GERALDINE FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    What is it with these guys?
 &HT;    No, not Al Gore or George W. Bush. Now that Super Tuesday is but
a memory, and with it has vanished any interest in the primary
race, we have a little time off from them, the calm before the
storm that the conventions will kick off in August.
 &HT;    In short, it's silly season, when third-party candidates get
their 15 minutes of fame and, while the candidates lie low, rebuild
their campaign treasuries and plan their fall strategies, some of
each party's less appealing elements get let out of the attic for a
breath of air.
 &HT;    We Democrats have our share of those, but I'm thinking
specifically about a couple of Republican mainstays, Hollywood
star/National Rifle Association icon Charlton Heston and Republican
National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson.
 &HT;    What, to repeat myself, is it with these guys?
 &HT;    If I were George W. Bush, huddling with my top advisers in
Austin, Texas, two words would be at the top of my list of
problems: gender gap.
 &HT;    Since this race began, every national poll has shown women
favoring Gore by large numbers, just as men favor Bush. That's the
gender gap, and you can bet that Gore is devoting some serious
thought to how to improve his standing among men.
 &HT;    As far as I can tell, Bush is doing exactly the opposite _
either he has completely lost control of his own soldiers, or he's
actively trying to alienate what female supporters he does have.
 &HT;    Now, we all know that Heston favors gun rights, and while we may
disagree on the Second Amendment, I'd be the first to say that he
has a First Amendment right to speak his mind.
 &HT;    Still, while in his day Heston may have been a better actor than
Ronald Reagan, he has none of Reagan's ear for political timing.
He's backing Bush, and you'd think that right now he'd be playing
it cool, getting the N.R.A. off the front pages and letting Bush
work on broadening his appeal.
 &HT;    At the very least, you wouldn't expect him to be picking macho
fights on gun-safety locks _ the devices intended specifically to
protect children _ and 72-hour background checks, which are meant
to protect all of us. You wouldn't expect him to be trumpeting his
opposition to training and licensing of gun owners.
 &HT;    It doesn't make sense. At least not to women, who are the ones
who rush to the schools when we hear about the latest horrible
incident. We're the ones who wait nervously for our kids to get
home each day, the ones who, if we live in the inner cities, are
terrified every time our children go out to play that just one
bullet, one little bullet could do something unthinkable.
 &HT;    And, oh yes, we're 53 percent of the population, and we vote.
 &HT;    If Bush wants to convince us that he deserves our votes, having
Heston out ranting that trigger locks and background checks
infringe on a sportsman's right to hunt isn't a smart way to go
about it.
 &HT;    And then there's Jim Nicholson, who chose last week to attack
three members of the advisory board for a bipartisan, nonpolitical
organization known as Women on Line. He lashed out at Rep. Carolyn
Maloney (D.-N.Y.), Rep. Nita Lowey (D.-N.Y.) and yours truly,
denouncing our pro-choice position on abortion and accusing us of
being anti-Catholic.
 &HT;    Actually, to a retired politician like me, it's kind of
flattering to find that Nicholson still considers me a worthwhile
target. Personally, I'd have expected him to aim elsewhere _ for
example, at the several Republican women who also serve on that
board.
 &HT;    Or, more likely, I'd have expected him to keep his mouth shut,
if only in the interest of helping his boy George get elected.
 &HT;    A politician as supposedly canny as Nicholson surely knows that,
according to nearly every poll, a majority of Catholics are
pro-choice _ even Catholic Republicans. He ought to know that
calling women names isn't likely to win other women's support. And,
most of all, he ought to remember that it was a large turnout of
female voters that elected President Bill Clinton in 1992 and again
in 1996.
 &HT;    Which brings me back to George W. Despite what went on in the
1984 campaign, I like the Bush family. I don't like their politics,
but they are very decent people.
 &HT;    So, in that spirit, let me give young George a little political
advice.
 &HT;    First of all, governor, get Charlton Heston down off the
mountain. The men who think of AK47s as camping gear are going to
vote for you anyway, but Heston's level of rhetoric is not only
turning off women, it's also repelling the real sportsmen who make
up the majority of the N.R.A. Remember, the object of a campaign is
to increase your support, not erode it.
 &HT;    Second, muzzle Mr. Nicholson. If you look at the polls, which
I'm sure you do, you've noticed that you're trailing Gore on every
issue that is important to women. It's not only choice and gun
control, it's the environment, it's education, it's health care.
 &HT;    In other words, it's the future of our children. And resorting
to the kind of ideological posturing that makes women wonder
whether you've even really thought about that future is hardly the
way to convince female voters to look for your name on the ballot.
 &HT;    Abigail Adams wasn't a Republican, but she had some good advice
for her husband, the future President John Adams, when she warned
him, ``Remember the ladies.''
 &HT;    If you won't listen to me, governor, listen to her.
 c.2000 Geraldine A. Ferraro  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Geraldine Ferraro was the Democratic vice-presidential
candidate in 1984. A former member of Congress, she is a political
analyst for Fox News and president of G&AMP;L Strategies in New York
and Arlington, Va., a corporate consultancy on workplace and
diversity issues.)
