<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0324-COX     03-23 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-POPE-0324-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POPE SAYS CHURCH 'DEEPLY SADDENED' BY CATHOLIC ACTIONS TOWARD
JEWS
 &HT;    (650&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a flame-lit memorial amid teary Holocaust
survivors from his homeland, Pope John Paul II Thursday declared
that his church was ``deeply saddened'' by historic persecution of
Jews by Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope's speech came midway through the first official papal
trip to Israel. The pilgrimage is meant to highlight the year 2000,
declared a ``Holy Year'' for reconciliation between faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assure the Jewish people that the Catholic Church, motivated
by the Gospel law of truth and love and by no political
considerations, is deeply saddened by the hatred, acts of
persecution and displays of anti-Semitism directed against the Jews
by Christians at any time and in any place,'' the Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   For some Jewish leaders, the Pope's comments still fell short of
what they had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Tension between Jews and Catholics ripples through the
centuries, back to accusations that Jews killed Jesus Christ, the
violence of the Catholic Church's Medieval crusades and the forced
conversions of the Spanish Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jewish leaders believe the church should outright apologize
for not speaking out strongly enough during the Nazi Holocaust. The
Pope, who has perhaps done more than any modern predecessor to heal
rifts between Jews and Catholics, did not offer such an apology
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But, the intensely emotional ceremony at the Yad Vashem
Holocaust memorial produced images many said were stronger than any
words.
</P>
<P>
   In the dim Hall of Remembrance, the Pope stood in his white
cassock and crucifix medallion. Around him on the sunken black
floor were the names of 20 Nazi death and labor camps. Several of
the camps were in his native Poland, where half the Holocaust's six
million Jewish victims met their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Near him were several Holocaust survivors from Poland, some of
whom knew the Pope in childhood.
</P>
<P>
   At the pontiff's side was Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
whose Polish maternal grandparents were killed by the Nazis.
Barak's voice cracked as he spoke, saying, ``This very moment holds
within it 2,000 years of history and their weight is almost too
much to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old Pope, speaking in a hoarse voice almost
inaudible at times, said he felt a ``need for silence, silence in
which to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he came in ``homage to the millions of Jewish people
who, stripped of everything, especially of their human dignity,
were murdered in the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   A man whose life has tracked the upheavals of the last century _
from Nazism to Communism _ Pope John Paul seemed moved and somber.
He mentioned ``personal friends and neighbors'' killed in the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Then he made his declaration and added, ``I fervently pray that
our sorrow for the tragedy which the Jewish people suffered in the
20th Century will lead to a new relationship between Christians and
Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pope, walking slowly and trembling with symptoms typical of
Parkinson's disease, greeted several Polish Holocaust survivors now
living in Israel _ of the more than 150,000 survivors here. He
spoke to them quietly in Polish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shook his hand and I told him who I am and he said he
remembered my father and his bakery,'' said survivor Bella
Ginzburg. ``Physically, he is a very old man, mentally he is
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Roman Kryscher(cq), 80, who lost five siblings and his father in
the Holocaust, knew the Pope in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that I will have to the end of my life. I
was so excited,'' Kryscher said. ``He was so different. He was once
so young and an athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he thought of the Pope's speech, Kryscher said
it was ``sufficient. He's already done so much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pope has repeatedly condemned anti-Semitism, and earlier
this month asked God to forgive Catholics for sins against Jews and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the survivors wept upon meeting him. Vatican
Spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls said the Pope was ``moved'' but did
not cry during the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony came after the pontiff had met with the rabbinical
hierarchy in Israel and blessed the state of Israel in a meeting
with Israeli President Ezer Weizman.
</P>
<P>
   He also met with a Jewish leader and a Muslim leader to discuss
religious reconciliation. But the discussion degenerated into
provocative political statements from both sides. The Muslim leader
left the stage after condemning Israel's occupation of Arab areas
of Jerusalem. It was the latest in a series of examples of how the
Pope's pilgrimage cannot be divorced from local politics.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Jewish state has laid out its largest security
operation ever for the Roman Catholic leader. But there is scant
knowledge here about Christianity. Those factors combined to create
the bizarre spectacle of the Pope riding in his glassed popemobile
on mostly empty streets, with security ropes holding back no one.
</P>
<P>
   In some spots, he was greeted by local Arab Christians or
foreign pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   It was his visit to Yad Vashem, shown live on Israeli
television, that caught the nation's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Those who approved of the Pope's speech, which was just 10 short
paragraphs, said it was important for its staunch declaration of
the Holocaust's immensity.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope spoke of ``millions'' of Jewish victims and said of the
Holocaust, ``No one can diminish its scale.'' That was hailed as a
stern rebuke for any so-called ``Holocaust deniers.''
</P>
<P>
   But, others said the Pope should have apologized for the
Catholic Church's actions during the war, especially the apparent
silence of wartime Pope Pius XII.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's statement offered no stronger acknowledgement of
Catholic wrong-doing than the Pope has made in the past _
considering that he has made many.
</P>
<P>
   Popes however, almost never criticize predecessors or the
Church. The Church is considered a perfect ``bride of Christ,'' and
Popes have the ability to rule with ``infallibility'' on certain
matters.
</P>
<P>
   But expectations were high with the first official trip of a
Pope to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was true that he raised himself, and sent an important
educational and morale message,'' said Israeli parliament member
Danny Naveh of the speech. ``But, there was here an additional
opportunity and that was missed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can argue if he should have said or shouldn't have said
that they are sorry for their actions. I'm sorry he didn't say
that,'' said parliament member Tommy Lapid, also a Holocaust
survivor. ``But, these are small details. I would say this was an
important declaration with enormous historical context.''
</P>
<P>
   (Palm Beach Post correspondent Douglas Belkin and Cox Newspapers
Middle East researcher Ellen Krosney Ben-Ze'ev contributed to this
story.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
