<HEADER>
A6158 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-TURNER-COX     03-23 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner U.N. grants focus on fighting AIDS in Africa
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ted Turner is taking on the problem that may pose the most
significant threat to economic and social development in Africa _
the terrifying spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Foundation, the organization set up to
distribute the Atlanta businessman's $1 billion gift to United
Nations projects, announced its sixth round of grants Thursday. The
$17 million in new grants will go to projects ranging from
biodiversity to the empowerment of adolescent girls, but better
than a third of the money _ more than $6 million _ will go to fight
AIDS in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The new awards, made after a meeting last week in New York of
the foundation's board, bring the total distributed since the
foundation was formed in 1998 to more than $237 million. Turner has
set a goal of distributing $1 billion over 10 years, which means
awarding at least $100 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on fighting AIDS in southern Africa comes after the
board met in November in South Africa and Mozambique. The board
went at the invitation of one of its members, Graca Machel, who has
been first lady of both countries.
</P>
<P>
   During a presentation on AIDS in the Mozambican capital, Maputo,
Turner, who is chairman of the board, was alarmed to hear
projections that, by the year 2030, AIDS will kill half of all
Mozambicans who are now 15 years old. And he was appalled to learn
that condoms are not universally available.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, during a visit to a ward for premature
infants at Maputo Central Hospital, Turner's wife, Jane Fonda,
called him over to see a baby with AIDS. The baby weighed perhaps 2
pounds and lived in an incubator.
</P>
<P>
   Turner glanced at the baby, looked stricken and quickly left the
room. The horror remained on his face for some time afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Also present on that trip was Tim Wirth, the former Colorado
senator who is the president of the U.N. Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased to support the secretary-general and the U.N.'s
efforts to alleviate poverty and strengthen global cooperation in
the 21st century,'' Wirth said in announcing the latest round of
grants. ``We are particularly proud of the strong package of
projects aimed at reducing the incidence and impact of HIV/AIDS in
southern Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   The specific grants announced Thursday were:
</P>
<P>
   $2.3 million over three years to the U.N. Children's Fund to
``improve the social and economic situation'' of adolescent girls
in Bangladesh, in part by giving them job training and access to
credit and savings programs.
</P>
<P>
   $1.1 million over three years to the U.N. Population Fund, or
UNFPA, to improve the reproductive health of adolescent girls in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   $2.5 million over 3 1/2 years to UNFPA to develop in Honduras
``a new model for nongovernmental delivery of quality reproductive
health services,'' and to offer a ``social license'' to
knowledgeable people who can run clinics offering family planning
services, treatment of sexually transmitted diseases and cervical
cancer, and other services to people regardless of age, income,
gender or marital status.
</P>
<P>
   $2.7 million over three years to the Joint U.N. Program on AIDS,
or UNAIDS, to fight the disease in Zambezia province in
north-central Mozambique. The program will offer, among other
services, sexual education, counseling, testing for HIV, help to
build youth leadership to address AIDS, and distribution of
condoms.
</P>
<P>
   $3.5 million over three years and 10 months to UNAIDS to fight
AIDS in Zimbabwe, where about 25 percent of the adult population is
infected. The program will offer peer education programs, try to
increase the commitment of political, religious and private
organizations to fighting AIDS, provide safe alternatives to
prostitution for women supporting themselves and their families,
and develop ways to meet the needs of the growing number of
children orphaned by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   $73,000 over three months to UNAIDS to develop a coordinated
plan of action for reducing the social and economic impact of AIDS
on ``families, communities and productive sectors in southern
Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   $600,000 over two years to the U.N. Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization to help the organization identify the most
important places to be nominated for international environmental
protection as World Heritage sites.
</P>
<P>
   $1.5 million over three years to the U.N. Industrial Development
Organization to improve the efficiency of electric motor systems in
China, ``leading to economic and environmental benefits with a
focus on Shanghai and Shandong provinces.''
</P>
<P>
   $500,000 over one year to the U.N. Staff College to enable the
college to provide conflict resolution training for U.N. staff
members in eight field locations.
</P>
<P>
   $1.5 million to the Office of the High Commissioner for Human
Rights to support organization of the World Conference Against
Racism, to be held next year in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   $1 million to the Office for Coordination of Humanitarian
Affairs for emergency relief for flood victims in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
