<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6159 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-HOUSE-CHAPLAIN-COX     03-23 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CHAPLAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hastert named House chaplain
 &HT;    Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.) appointed a Catholic
priest as the House chaplain Thursday in an effort to quell charges
of anti-Catholic bias within the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert unexpectedly interrupted floor debate on the nation's
budget to swear-in the Rev. Daniel Coughlin, vicar for priests in
the Chicago Archdiocese, as the next chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastert did so only after delivering a somber speech from
the House floor in defense of his original choice for the chaplain
post--the Rev. Charles Wright, former senior pastor of the North
Avenue Presbyterian Church in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said Wright withdrew his appointment Wednesday after
enduring four months of bitter political feuding over his
nomination. He accused Democrats of playing an ``unseemly political
game'' with religion by opposing Wright's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Charges of bigotry were ``carelessly tossed'' at the GOP,
Hastert said. ``Where I come from such slander is an ugly
business,'' he said. Those making the charges, ``don't know me or
are maliciously seeking political advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats and a group of Catholic Republicans have a
different side of the story.
</P>
<P>
   They were upset because Hastert selected Wright over the Rev.
Timothy O'Brien, a Catholic priest and professor at Marquette
University, who had more votes on a bipartisan selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Wright said that his withdrawal was a
positive move. ``I am very positive about it and hopeful,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a March 22 letter to Hastert, Wright elaborated on his
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these weeks following my appointment, anti-religious
charges of the selection process caused dissension among the
members and wounds between Catholic and other people of faith
across our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the political fight, Wright wrote, ``Let us be
thankful that God is not an independent, not a Democrat and not a
Republican. He is for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The chaplain issue upset the ranks of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tony Hall (D-Ohio), a long-time friend of Wright's, said he
was disappointed in members of his own party for turning the issue
into a political weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very ugly situation,'' Hall said. ``He got caught
between some Democrats who were trying to take advantage of this
and the Speaker who delayed the nomination for as long as he
could.''
</P>
<P>
   But most Democrats argue that the dispute arose because Hastert
ignored the wishes of a bipartisan selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed after all the work that we put into it to
see our choice ignored,'' said Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), a member of
the selection committee. ``I think we need to put this chapter
behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
