<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-WOMAN-CANDIDAT     03-23 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-WOMAN-CANDIDATE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE IS UNIQUE, BUT STILL LOST IN THE
CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Marina Shurina, a 25-year-old underemployed lawyer, sat
in a small spare room with white walls and empty shelves, waiting
for voters to call the campaign of Ella Pamfilova, one of the 11
people, and the only woman, running in Russia's presidential
election on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Shurina's phone was not exactly ringing off the hook. And with
no signs, posters or bumper stickers anywhere in sight _ not on the
street, not on the grubby stairwell, not on the door, not even
inside Shurina's second-floor office _ the chances of voters just
dropping by, looking for information, offering to lend a hand, were
virtually nil.
</P>
<P>
   But from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. each day this week, Shurina will
remain at her post at the Pamfilova campaign's only public office
in all of Moscow. On a bad day, she fields questions from about
four voters, usually referred by Russia's Central Election
Commission. On a good day, she will see maybe 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see that kind of flow, I try to spread it out so that
I can spend a good long time with each voter, and not just a few
minutes,'' she said cheerfully as a heavy wet snow splattered the
dusty window behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Pamfilova, a former government minister, longtime member of
parliament and a rare voice for social justice in Russia, is the
no-frills candidate in a campaign that, in the minds of many
voters, never really was a campaign at all.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment former President Boris Yeltsin handed over power
to his chosen successor, Vladimir V. Putin, on New Year's Eve, most
everybody has assumed that victory will belong to Putin. The only
question is by what margin and when _ on the first vote next
Sunday, or in a second round on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And yet the other candidates have never stopped running, with
the single exception of Yevgeni Savostyanov, a former Kremlin aide
and liberal democrat who this week threw his support to Grigory
Yavlinksy, leader of the Yabloko party, on a late-night political
talk show, minutes before a midnight withdrawal deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Savostyanov's gesture was one of the few moments of drama in an
otherwise monotonous campaign. Just about everything else _ from
the long Russian winter to the early election date that threw all
contenders but Putin off guard _ has conspired to cool popular
participation in Russia's third presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Pamfilova's goal from the start was not to get elected. As
she keeps saying at every stop, she wanted to make the point that a
politician in Russia can be independent and that a woman can run
for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish that in politics there were more women, smart, good
women,'' she said Thursday during a campaign stop at a
flower-arranging show at Moscow's cavernous Theater of the Russian
Army. ``Now, there are few, but tomorrow there should be more,
which is why I stepped forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamfilova, 46, an engineer by training, was one of the most
visible members of Yeltsin's first reform government, serving as
minister of social affairs. But in 1994 she resigned, disgusted
with the government's neglect of Russia's growing number of poor
people and with the corruption that she said discredited Russia's
young liberal reformers.
</P>
<P>
   After her movement, Civic Dignity, failed to seat any candidates
in parliamentary elections in December, she decided to run for
president and to set an example by refusing to accept any private
contributions. Her entire campaign is financed by the 400,000
rubles _ about $14,000 _ allotted each qualifying candidate by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can safely say that her campaign headquarters are wherever
she happens to be,'' said her press aide, Maxim Leskov. According
to early spending reports, hers is the poorest of the campaigns:
Putin's is one of the richest, with reported spending of 9 million
rubles, about $300,000 _ a figure that does not include the
publicity he gets for performing his official duties as acting
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are to get rid of corruption in Russia, then we have to
have more independent politicians,'' she said. ``I am not refusing
to spend money because no one has offered me any. People have
offered, but I have refused because I don't want to be indebted to
criminals or oligarchs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show that you can start from nothing,'' Pamfilova
said Thursday. ``I am fulfilling a minimum goal.''
</P>
<P>
   With a small budget and the little time allotted to the
truncated election campaign, Pamfilova has pitched most of her
campaign to television, taking advantage of all the free air time
offered by the competing channels. In the last week, she has filled
her days with talk shows, debates, interviews on foreign television
stations, even an appearance on the Russian version of ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire,'' where she astutely asked help from the
audience _ a move that one TV critic said showed both her wise use
of available resources and her ability to win the sympathy of
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, however, seems to have increased her popularity
ratings, which still hover between 1 and 2 percent. ``These are of
course relative, subject to the usual fluctuations,'' Leskov said.
</P>
<P>
   Being the sole woman has probably helped Pamfilova stand out in
the pack of candidates hovering at the bottom of the polls. She was
the only politician to show up at the flower-arranging exhibition,
where several women came up to her, practically with tears in their
eyes, promising support. The exhibition's director read her a poem
written in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch her, you can feel her lightness as a person,''
said Yelena Allakhverdova, an artist who had toyed with voting for
Putin until she met Pamfilova. ``I can feel things, and I can feel
that what she says is not a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamfilova is determined to hang on to the end. As she posed for
television cameras Thursday, clutching a bunch of daffodils, her
blond hair tied back in a girlish ponytail, she scoffed at the
thought of abandoning her cause and deserting her supporters by
bowing out before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But she also hinted that if the race was to go another round,
she might join the long line of politicians who have jumped on the
Putin bandwagon. ``As someone who has long been in opposition to
the Kremlin, I was skeptical at first,'' she said, ``but now I have
hopes that he will be independent. I am hoping that a process of
consolidation is taking place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
