<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6170 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-1STLD-W     03-23 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLYLAND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONS RUN HIGH AS POPE VISITS HOLOCAUST MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs for complete writethru of early version. Note byline and
dateline changes.) 
 (See also POPE-SURVIVOR) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT1, NYT2 are being sent to NYT photo clients. A
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Standing alone before a granite slab symbolizing the
graves of unidentified victims of the Holocaust, Pope John Paul II
bowed his head Thursday in a long silence that filled the cold,
dark Hall of Remembrance of Yad Vashem, Israel's Holocaust
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this place of memories, the mind and heart and soul feel an
extreme need for silence,'' the pope said later in a speech.
``Silence in which to remember. Silence in which to make some sense
of the memories which come flooding back. Silence because there are
no words strong enough to deplore the terrible tragedy of the
Shoah.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope is on a religious pilgrimage to the Holy Land, but his
visit to Yad Vashem, where he met with Holocaust survivors _
including several Jews from his Polish hometown of Wadowice _ was,
for Israel, the emotional highpoint of his trip. Blending regret
for the moral failures of many Catholics with a reminder of the
Jewish friends and neighbors he lost in the Holocaust, the pope
sought to heal the divisions between Catholics and Jews by
expressing his feelings inside the saddest, starkest memorial in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assure the Jewish people that the Catholic church, motivated
by the Gospel law of truth and love and by no political
considerations, is deeply saddened by the hatred, acts of
persecution and displays of anti-Semitism directed against the Jews
by Christians at any time, and in any place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to Yad Vashem was broadcast live on Israeli
television. The response of Israelis and Jewish leaders around the
world was mostly positive, though a few expressed disappointment
that the pope had not gone further in acknowledging the failure of
Catholic church leaders to condemn Nazi persecution of Jews during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But the sight of the frail pope speaking with such strong
feeling in the dark hall, where the names of concentration camps
are etched into the black floor, had its own resonance. So did the
symbolism of the moment when the pope, who usually sits in an
armchair while people file before him, shuffled humbly across the
darkened room alone, leaning on his cane, between the words
``Buchenwald'' and ``Auschwitz'' to shake the hands of six
Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your coming here today, to the Tent of Remembrance at Yad
Vashem, is a climax of this historic journey of healing,'' Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, said, his voice rough with emotion. ``Here,
right now, time itself has come to a standstill.This very moment
holds within it 2,000 years of history. And their weight is almost
too much to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who during the ceremony listened to the reading of a
letter from a Polish Jew imploring her gentile friend to protect
her son, has made reconciliation between Catholics and Jews one of
the priorities of his papacy. It has been a long odyssey that began
during his 1979 visit to Auschwitz in his native Poland, and which
he hopes to conclude in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   At a special Mass earlier this month, he delivered a sweeping
and unprecedented apology for the historic sins of the church,
including injustices toward the Jews. But in all of his many
statements of regret, the pope has never faulted the behavior of
Pope Pius XII, a figure whose silence during the Nazi era remains a
source of deep division between many Jewish groups and the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Holocaust survivors who attended the Yad Vashem
ceremony said that they too wanted the pope to acknowledge the
failings of his wartime predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very glad he is coming here, but I want him to recognize
the silence of that other pope,'' said Michael Goldmann-Gilead, 75,
who was a teenager in Katowice, Poland, when the war broke out in
1939, spent three years in Auschwitz and escaped in 1945 while
being transferred to another camp. ``I wanted that pope to say that
killing Jews is not allowed. That would have had an impact on
Hitler and his army.''
</P>
<P>
   But after John Paul spoke, Goldmann-Gilead said he was
``content'' with the pope's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope's very gesture of coming here,'' said Eli Zborowski,
one of seven survivors who shook hands with the pope, ``marks a
turning point for Jews and Christians. He will be well written in
the history of the human race, and of the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope is seen by many Israelis as not only the leader of 1
billion Roman Catholics but also as the spokesman for the entire
Christian world.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with President Ezer Weizman, the pope blessed
Israel _ an act seen by many Israelis as final church recognition
of their state. For centuries, until Pope John XXIII, the Catholic
Church taught that the Jews' exile was punishment for the death of
Jesus. Pope Paul VI, the last pope to visit the Holy Land, in 1964,
did not mention Israel by name and refused to address the Israeli
president by his title.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul also met Israel's two chief rabbis, Eliyahu Bakshi
Doron and Israel Meir Lau, at their office in west Jerusalem. The
pope's spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said that the pope and the
rabbis had a ``cordial and frank'' conversation. He said that the
pope had told his hosts that the time had come for Christians to
put an end to any lingering anti-Jewish sentiment, and also for
Jews to put an end to anti-Christian feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism, which had been vivid before the pope's arrival, was
muted after the pope's visit to Yad Vashem. Lau the Ashkenazic
chief rabbi, issued a statement about what he wished the pope had
mentioned. But his decidedly neutral comment made no explicit
expression of disappointment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited for statements that would speak about people from the
church who had committed crimes against the Jewish people,'' he
said. ``I also waited for statements that, for the sake of
generations to come, made it clear that the church itself on many
occasions had fed the flames of hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, a former grand rabbi of Ireland who is active
in interfaith relations, had a different view. ``People whose
expectations were too high, and who don't understand the workings
of the Vatican, may be disappointed, but this was a turning
point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's day was marked by other highs and also lows. He began
his morning by holding a private Mass in the Cenacle, the site
where tradition has it that Jesus presided over the Last Supper.
Navarro-Valls said the pope was the first priest to celebrate Mass
in that chapel since 1583, when it fell into the hands of the
Turks. He said the pope was so moved at being there that, after the
Mass ended, he dismissed his aides and entourage and knelt at the
alter and prayed alone there for 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But his hopes for a breakthrough encounter between Christians,
Muslims and Jews were dashed when the evening meeting intended to
promote interfaith discussion turned into an ugly dispute over the
fate of Jerusalem between Lau and Sheik Taysir Tamimi, who is the
newly appointed deputy chief justice of the Palestinian Islamic
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Tamimi participated in the meeting after the mufti of Jerusalem,
Ekrima Sabri, decided to boycott it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all aware of past misunderstandings and conflicts, and
these still weigh heavily upon relationships between Jews,
Christians and Muslims,'' the pope said after the two other
religious leaders delivered sharply antagonistic remarks. ``We must
do all we can to turn awareness of past offenses and sins into a
firm resolve to build a new future in which there will be nothing
but respectful and fruitful cooperation between us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
