<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     03-23 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUSTICE TO INVESTIGATE MISSING WHITE HOUSE E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department has launched a criminal
inquiry into why thousands of subpoenaed White House e-mail
messages were never turned over to a federal grand jury and three
congressional committees, according to court papers filed Thursday
by Justice officials.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry will focus on White House efforts to retrieve
correspondence that should have been stored and allegations that
White House officials threatened contract employees with
retaliation if they revealed the problem. The probe will be handled
by the Justice Department's campaign finance task force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task force has begun an investigation into whether
subpoenas issued to (the White House) were fully complied with and
whether persons were threatened with retaliation in order to
prevent the existence of the affected e-mails from becoming known
to the task force,'' said a federal court affidavit by Robert J.
Conrad Jr., chief of the task force.
</P>
<P>
   The missing e-mails, which were sent between 1996 and 1999, were
sought in connection with a number of investigations of President
Clinton, including the scandal involving Monica Lewinsky, the
former White House intern with whom Clinton admitted having a
sexual relationship, and the White House's receipt of secret FBI
files.
</P>
<P>
   The president and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton were cleared
of any criminal wrongdoing in the FBI files case, in which White
House officials obtained hundreds of personnel files from the FBI
early in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic messages also are wanted in connection with the
investigation of whether Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
illegally solicited campaign contributions from government
property, as well as other issues related to their efforts to fund
their 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Sheryl L. Hall, chief of White House computer
operations, said White House e-mails from August 1996 to November
1998 had not been turned over.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was first discovered in May 1998 when a computer
consulting company traced a programming error on one of four White
House computer servers back to August 1996. The company found that
one of the four White House Lotus Notes e-mail servers handling
mail for computer users was mislabeled and a search of e-mail under
subpoena was incomplete. The error involved e-mail to and from 464
White House computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who now works at the Treasury Department, said e-mail from
that server was not properly managed over a two-year period _
meaning it was not collected by the mainframe computer during the
subpoena-record search.
</P>
<P>
   Five employees of the consulting company have told lawyers for
the House Government Reform Committee that they were ordered not to
tell anyone _ including their bosses _ about the missing e-mail.
The House committee is investigating possible violations of
campaign finance laws by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at hearing Thursday, Betty Lambuth, a contractor who
was working on the White House e-mail system, told the committee
that after she advised her superiors of the problem, she was told
if she or any of her team mentioned the error to anyone, ``We would
lose our jobs, be arrested and put in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail had been sought under subpoena by a federal grand
jury, the Senate Judiciary Committee, the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee and the House Government Reform Committee in
several investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the White House Counsel Beth Nolan blamed ``entirely
unintentional'' computer breakdowns for the problem. In a letter to
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of House Government Reform
Committee, she also said that reconstructing the e-mail from 1996
to 1999 would cost $3 million and take two years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said two separate computer failures made it impossible for
document searches to find the e-mail messages. One problem affected
incoming mail to 526 White House users. Incoming mail for 200 other
accounts was affected by the second error, lasting from November
1998 to May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   She said that while researching the issue, a new problem was
discovered that could result in missing e-mails in Gore's office.
The scope of that problem was unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The White House automated-records management system was designed
to scan e-mail ``in boxes'' of every user every several minutes and
transfer copies of incoming e-mail messages to a mainframe
computer, where they were stored for production in response to
subpoenas, Freedom of Information requests and other requests.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
