<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-TRAVE     03-23 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-TRAVEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONGRESS CHALLENGES FIRST LADY'S TRAVEL BUT PLANS NO CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers said Thursday they have no plans to
overhaul laws governing White House reimbursement for campaign
travel despite election-year criticism of Hillary Rodham Clinton's
modest payments for using Air Force planes in connection with her
campaign for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers' comments came amid a special congressional
inquiry ordered by Republicans to examine the first lady's
reimbursement for travel to New York state in her Senate race
against New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents and vice presidents are required to reimburse the
Treasury for a share of the costs of political travel aboard
government planes. But the issue has drawn particular attention
this year because Clinton is breaking new ground by seeking
elective office while still the nation's first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee's panel on White House operations, conceded that Congress
has little inclination to overturn the reimbursement scheme that
effectively subsidizes political travel by Republicans and
Democrats when they serve in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are grumbling about the reimbursement formula
affecting White House officials this year just as Democrats
complained about the arrangement when the tables were turned and
Republicans held the White House in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the parties nor congressional leaders want to tamper
with an arrangement that benefits presidents and vice presidents of
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the campaigns of Hillary Clinton and Vice President
Al Gore are required by law and Federal Election Commission
regulations to reimburse the U.S. Treasury the equivalent of a
commercial first-class air fare for anyone who handles campaign
chores on political trips taken aboard government aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The required reimbursement falls far short of the actual costs
of operating the Air Force planes that the Secret Service
recommends for the first lady and the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made 26 trips to New York state aboard Air Force
aircraft in the last seven months of 1999 at an estimated cost of
$182,471, Kolbe said.
</P>
<P>
   But her campaign is only required to reimburse the U.S.
government $40,493 for that travel under a reimbursement formula
that has governed White House travel expenses dating back to Jimmy
Carter's presidency in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's obviously a pretty good deal considering the costs,''
Kolbe said. ``But that's the formula. That's the procedure and that
what's been used and I have no problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., the ranking Democrat on the panel,
echoed Kolbe's assessment. ``Everybody knows what the costs are and
everybody knows the reimbursement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John E. Sweeney, R-N.Y., won House approval last year on an
amendment to campaign finance reform legislation that would require
candidates to pay the full costs of flights aboard government
aircraft. But the House-passed measure remains tied up on the
Senate with little prospect for action this year, conceded Carey
Dearnley, Sweeney's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite little chance that the reimbursement formula will be
overhauled this year by the GOP-led Congress, Clinton's travel
aboard Air Force planes proved to be too rich a target for
Republicans to pass by on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney urged Clinton to abide by the spirit of his legislation
and pay the full costs of travel aboard Air Force planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to New Yorkers now, Mrs. Clinton, and pay your share,''
Sweeney said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe said his committee inquiry was warranted because the first
lady-lady-turned candidate is ``wearing a hat that we have never
seen before.'' He questioned tardy White House delivery of
requested documents on Clinton's travel and the slow pace of
charging her campaign for trips aboard Air Force planes.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe challenged the White House contention that Clinton needs
to travel aboard Air Force planes to guarantee her security. The
Secret Service ``prefers and recommends'' that the first lady use
Air Force planes, but ``it is by no means a requirement'' as
underscored by the first lady's travel aboard commercial aircraft
during her nationwide tour to promote her 1996 best selling book,
``It Takes A Village,'' Kolbe said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's campaign spokesman, accused Giuliani's
Republican allies in Washington of ``playing politics with the
first lady's security'' by urging her to fly aboard commercial
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to compromise Mrs. Clinton's safety for
political purposes,'' Wolfson said, adding that the Clinton
campaign ``pays the same travel rate that the Bushes and Reagans
paid when they flew.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe relied solely upon documents provided by the White House
to compile his committee's list of the 26 flights to New York
aboard Air Force planes that Clinton took between June 9 and Dec.
14, 1999, at a bottom line cost to taxpayers of $141,978, after the
Clinton campaign's reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson continued to press the
Republican National Committee's contention that Clinton had taken
72 trips aboard Air Force planes over the 13 month period ending
Jan. 31 at an estimated cost of $905,406. Nicholson aides attended
the hearing _ over the objections of Kolbe's staff _ to pass out a
flight-by-flight profile of Clinton's travel.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe denied that his committee was in cahoots with either the
RNC or the Giuliani campaign, saying that neither he nor his staff
had talked with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's travel may be fodder for the Republicans and
Democrats to issue rival press releases, Kolbe said, ``the fact of
the matter is that this is a subject of legitimate investigation or
information gathering _ this is not an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
