<HEADER>
A6175 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS &LR;      03-23 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     '94 KILLING CASTS SHADOW OVER MEXICAN ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Six years after the murder of presidential
candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio, many Mexicans believe the
government has not done enough to resolve the crime that is likened
here to the assassination of John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Colosio's death is still shrouded in mystery and suspicion
despite a costly investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Thursday by the Mexico City newspaper Reforma
showed that 68 percent of those interviewed think the
administration of President Ernesto Zedillo, who vowed to get to
the bottom of the killing, has done little or nothing to solve the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Another survey in the newspaper El Universal said 90 percent of
the respondents believe the murder was a plot, rather than the work
of the lone gunman charged with killing him. And 80 percent say
there is no government interest in clarifying it.
</P>
<P>
   Colosio, a popular candidate of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known by its Spanish acronym as the PRI, was
killed in the poor, dusty Tijuana neighborhood of Lomas Taurinas in
Baja California during a crowded campaign rally on March 23, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Aburto, a day laborer, was charged with the killing.
Aburto has only admitted to shooting Colosio in the head, but
denied firing a second shot to the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   He has never said why he shot Colosio, who was a virtual shoo-in
for president, or given interviews. Many Mexicans do not believe
Aburto was the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   In a report a year ago, special prosecutor Luis Raul Gonzalez
said there was no evidence anyone other than Aburto was involved in
the crime. He said his office had investigated 20 different
theories and could not substantiate any.
</P>
<P>
   His report created a furor from opposition lawmakers, who said
the conclusions and various investigations were confusing and
erratic.
</P>
<P>
   The Colosio investigation remains open.
</P>
<P>
   As with President Kennedy, conspiracy theories and accusations
abound with little or no proof, much less official backing.
</P>
<P>
   For Mexicans, no person is more cloaked in suspicion than former
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the free-market reformer who
left Mexico during an economic crisis for self-imposed exile after
his term ended in 1994. Colosio was the PRI nominee to succeed
Salinas, but Zedillo became the nominee after Colosio was killed.
</P>
<P>
   In El Universal's poll, nearly 93 percent of respondents said
they believe Salinas, who has never been charged with any
wrongdoing and has denied any part in the case, played a role in
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   A special Senate commission overseeing the probe has demanded
that Salinas be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   As Zedillo nears the end of six-year term and the nation embarks
on a new presidential election on July 2, many candidates shroud
themselves in Colosio's name, promising to live up to his ideals of
a better and more just Mexico. They also promise to resolve the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida, the new PRI presidential candidate,
traveled Thursday to Magdalena de Kino, Colosio's birthplace in
Sonora, to visit Colosio's mausoleum and attend a Mass. Labastida,
57, has said he represents the ideals set forth by Colosio.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the anniversary of his death, residents of
Magdalena de Kino shut off their lights for two hours and lighted
candles in their windows to protest the lack of government clarity
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The specter of Colosio's death also casts pallor on Mexican
politics and follows the candidates in 2000. Most of them now
travel with scores of bodyguards and in bulletproof cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years after the homicide, the case is reduced to a
campaign act in search of votes,'' Reforma said Thursday in an
editorial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
