<HEADER>
A6177 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-THEATER-AIDA-REVIEW-S     03-23 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-AIDA-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AIDA' GETS DISNEYFIED ON BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN WINN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Every story is a love story,'' the opening number
of ``Aida'' declares. Unfortunately, in the glossy, cold Disney
musical that opened Thursday night at Broadway's Palace Theatre,
very little makes this amorous tale special or gripping.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney nameplate per se isn't stamped on ``Aida,'' a pop
retelling of the 1871 Verdi love-triangle opera set in ancient
Egypt, as it is on the stage versions of ``The Lion King'' and
``Beauty and the Beast.'' This show is the first venture of
Hyperion Theatricals, the company's new adult theater division. But
a Disney ethos permeates the show, from the intensely saturated
colors of Bob Crowley's sets and costumes and Natasha Katz's
lighting to the blunt simplicities of the collaboratively written
book and Tim Rice's banal lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Bathed in Elton John's loud but often listless pop songs,
``Aida'' is a cartoon love tragedy with heaving breasts, silvery
moonlight and interfering parents. The characters in ``Beauty and
the Beast,'' with the possible exception of the dancing spoons and
plates, are drawn with more dimension, wit and emotional depth than
those in ``Aida.'' Eye-catching as it is at times, Robert Falls'
staging supplies almost none of ``The Lion King's'' theatrical
charge.
</P>
<P>
   That the whole enterprise doesn't sink like a Nile barge is
largely due to Heather Headley, who gives an arresting performance
in the title role. From the moment the Nubian princess is captured
as a slave by the Egyptian warrior Radames (``Rent'' alumnus Adam
Pascal), Headley commands the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing a sword and threatening to kill one of her Egyptian
captors unless her fellow Nubians are released, this Aida has a
fiery temperament balanced by a regal calling. Headley deploys a
penetrating gaze, grandly sinuous physical presence and a voice
that climbs to fearless, exposed heights.
</P>
<P>
   She also gets the sharpest lines in a leaden book (by Linda
Woolverton, director Falls and ``Golden Child'' playwright David
Henry Hwang). It's no wonder Radames falls for Aida. She's the only
character in sight, himself included, with any substance.
</P>
<P>
   The show opens in a modern-day gallery of Egyptian artifacts.
Stepping from a glass case, Amneris (Sherie Rene Scott) sings of
love and human failing in the grave opening number. The mobile
geometries of Crowley's stylized design transport the action back
to Egypt. Colored panels rotate and shuttle. Giant amulets,
abstract checkerboards and palm trees twinned by watery reflections
supply picture-book backing.
</P>
<P>
   The story unfolds in a plodding, deliberate way. Aida gets
captured, charming Radames with her feisty spirit, and turned over
to Amneris as a gift. Bored by Amneris, who's portrayed as a
shallow clotheshorse in the unfunny haute couture parody ``My
Strongest Suit,'' Radames is soon sneaking off to meet Aida and
hatch some wild travel plans with her.
</P>
<P>
   But duty calls. Radames' ambitious father Zoser (John Hickok) is
determined to have his son marry royalty. Aida, meanwhile, has
become the leader of the Nubian liberation movement, climaxed in an
exciting if baldly calculated gospel number that closes the first
act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida's'' operatic pedigree seems to have imposed a deadly high
seriousness on the librettists. The characters declaim their
feelings and motivations in wooden dialogue. Rice, the author of
supple lyrics dating back to ``Evita,'' is powerless to lift the
tide here.
</P>
<P>
   The music has a somewhat more varied texture. Between its
fervent pop-rock ballads and choruses, John achieves a certain
eloquent lyricism in the seductive love duet ``Enchantment Passing
Through'' and surging ensemble ``Not Me.'' But the score lacks
heart and personality. A song like the reprised ``Elaborate Lives''
rallies the listener while it's happening without lodging in the
memory.
</P>
<P>
   The voltage does switch on from time to time. Choreographer
Wayne Cilento (``The Who's Tommy'') gives Zoser's black-robed
ministers a pair of muscular dance numbers in a lean, techno-Fosse
style. The image of Radames and Aida entombed together at the end
is drawn with simple intensity.
</P>
<P>
   But Falls, who directed a brilliant ``Death of a Salesman'' on
Broadway last season, seems locked in the same front-and-center
delivery that mummifies the characters, book and songs. The single
pyramid in the production is a neon triangle, mounted like a road
sign over the principals' trio that opens the second act. OK, we
get it. ``Aida'' is a love triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Musicals, like pyramids, need a third dimension to stand up.
This one hasn't got it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
