<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GASOLINE-EUROPE-ART-8     03-23 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-EUROPE-ART-800(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEISKIRCHEN JOURNAL: AT $4 A GALLON, THE ROAD NOT TAKEN MAKES A
DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEISKIRCHEN, Germany _ When Uwe Olzem finished filling up the
tank of his Nissan coupe, he could only envy Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with paying about $3.65 a gallon for regular unleaded _
about double the price in the United States _ Olzem said he is
paying about $50 a week just to commute to his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame Americans for being upset at the higher
prices,'' said Olzem, a soldier in the German army. ``But they have
a very good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries prepares to
consider raising oil production quotas next Monday in at a meeting
in Vienna, Americans are fretting over the prospect of $2 a gallon
gasoline and fill ups at the pump costing $50 or more for some big
sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Europe, where prices have approached $4 a gallon for
years, most drivers only wish they had it has bad as the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wonderful,'' sighed Carica De Hoere, a teacher
from Harelbeke, Belgium, as she stopped here with a small group of
friends en route from a ski holiday in Austria. ``But of course, it
couldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices have jumped at least 20 percent in many European
countries compared to more than 50 percent over the past year in
the United States. But there have been few if any diatribes against
OPEC, nor grousing about the lack of gratitude for rescuing Kuwait
from Iraq in the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are European officials emulating the U. S. secretary of
energy, Bill Richardson, who has been on a whirlwind tour of oil
producing countries pleading for a sizable increase in production.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Germany, a country of carmakers and car lovers and the
legally-enshrined right to drive the autobahn at speeds of 100 mph
_ few seem worried that their way of life is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC is the least of our problems,'' said Hermann Otto Solms,
who oversees economic policy issues for Germany's Free Democratic
Party, which has pushed for cutting taxes. ``Our problem is that
our own gasoline taxes are too high and are still going up. If OPEC
reduces production, that is merely an additional problem.''
</P>
<P>
   If Americans view the prospect of $2-a-gallon gasoline as a
nightmare, most Europeans would be thrilled to see it so cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all think it would terrible to pay $2 a gallon, but I
just filled up my tank this morning for about $5 a gallon,''
remarked Paul Horsnell, assistant director at the Oxford Institute
for Energy Studies in Oxford, England.
</P>
<P>
   British gasoline prices are even higher than those in
neighboring countries because the value of the British pound has
climbed sharply against most other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline taxes are at the heart of the difference between
American and European gasoline prices and attitudes. If American
drivers are addicted to cheap gasoline, European governments are
addicted to gasoline taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes total about three-quarters of the price of a gallon of gas
in most European countries. Beyond paying for road construction
maintenance and public transportation, gas taxes have become a
major source of government funds and are increasingly used to
offset cuts in social security taxes and other levies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the cash cows of the nation,'' complained Olzen, the
German soldier. ``I'm not bothered by what OPEC does. What bothers
me is that the government is taking 75 percent of the money I pay
for gasoline and putting it into its own pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   That has had a number of effects. Because the cost of oil
comprises a smaller portion of the price of a gallon of gasoline,
prices here have climbed far more modestly.
</P>
<P>
   Energy experts and economists argue that Europe's high gasoline
taxes have also reduced its exposure to oil shocks. Though European
oil imports have risen in recent years, both individuals and
companies have invested heavily in ways to reduce energy
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Europeans have consistently been able to get by
with less gasoline than Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On average, Europeans drive less than half as many miles each
year than Americans, according to studies by the International
Energy Agency, a publicly-funded research institute in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The standard explanation is that distances between cities and
even within cities are so much greater in America than in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But that is only part of the story. In a study last year, the
Paris agency reported that the length of the average car trip in
the United States and Europe is virtually the same _ 8.7 miles
versus 8.1 miles _ but the big difference is that Americans made
nearly twice as many such trips.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Americans believe it is their God-given right to have as much
cheap gasoline as they want,'' said Gary N. Ross, chief executive
of PIRA Energy Group, an oil industry consulting firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of this addiction, and addiction is a good word,
Americans drive almost 50 percent more than Europe and its cars are
less efficient. It has cost the United States dearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Europeans who want to reduce gasoline taxes, like Sohms of
the German Free Democratic Party, admits to being amazed when they
visit the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most cities, except perhaps New York, people can't
understand why you would want to walk a short distance rather than
drive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans have long driven cars so small and fuel thrifty that
they would be laughed off the American road by any self-respecting
owner of a sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though Europeans have developed a taste for heavier and
more powerful models, but European models overall get better
mileage than American cars _ averaging about 27 miles per gallon
compared to about 24 _ according to estimates by the IEA.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the gap is widening. According to the German
government, the average fuel efficiency of cars on German roads has
improved to about 27. miles per gallon from about 25.8 since 1992.
By contrast, the fuel efficiency of American cars has not budged.
Since the sport utility craze in the United States began, new car
and light-truck mileage has declined from 25.4 miles per gallon to
23.8 miles in the period from 1992 through last year.The upshot is
that European drivers have become inured to high gasoline prices
and have learned to economize.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get used to high prices,'' said Freek Vlieger, a mechanic
from Woerden, the Netherlands, as he filled up his tank on the way
home from a ski holiday in Austria. ``For us, it's not so much of a
problem, because we don't use the car that much at home.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say people are happy about their lot. In Holland
and several other countries, people angry about gasoline prices are
trying to organize a ``strike'' on April 1, in which drivers will
refuse to drive or buy gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   But if people are angry, they are more angry about gasoline
taxes than the machinations of oil-producing countries. When
Germany's Free Democrats campaigned against the ruling Social
Democratic Party's plan to raise gasoline taxes in January, it
arranged to sell gasoline tax-free for one hour at a station in
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The result led to mayhem, with thousands of drivers clogging up
the streets around the station in a bid to buy gas at 25 percent of
the normal price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
