<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6183 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-OSCARS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-23 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OSCARS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCARS SHOW IS GETTING A FACE-LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: All times PST. Check local listings for time and 
 channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Streamlined, star-studded and ratings-enriched _ those are the
goals for the Academy Awards program Sunday night on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   First-time Oscars producers Richard D. Zanuck and his wife and
partner, Lili Fini Zanuck, have been brought in to spruce up the
show and stanch last year's ratings decline, when the TV numbers
ebbed to their lowest point since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   This year's program begins at 5:30 p.m., following the network's
half-hour pre-Oscars show.
</P>
<P>
   The Zanucks, themselves past Oscar winners for producing
``Driving Miss Daisy,'' wasted no time paring one piece of blubber
from the show. To the dismay of the dwindling contingent of
Hollywood choreographers, the 72nd Annual Academy Awards are
supposed to be free of any big, time-consuming dance numbers. Exit
Debbie Allen.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame, in a way. They've been choice targets for
post-Oscar cattiness. But the Zanucks are aiming for a 3 1/2-hour
show, more digestible than last year's record four hours and five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographer Kenny Ortega (``Dirty Dancing'') is part of the
Zanucks' staff, though, and dance is expected to survive not on its
own but as an element of the performances of the best-song
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The uncontested good news is the return of Billy Crystal, set to
host his seventh Oscarcast. Last year Whoopi Goldberg amused
herself with some of the bluest jokes in Oscar history.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Crystal has ready-made material in the recent theft
of 55 Oscar statuettes. The guess here is that Crystal will swing
his driver back and knock that off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   The acting categories this year aren't heavily stocked with
big-name nominees _ Russell Crowe? Janet McTeer? Hilary Swank? _
but there will be no shortage of star power in the presenter ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Older and newer Hollywood, and in between, are in the mix. The
presenters include Clint Eastwood, Cameron Diaz, Brad Pitt, Gwyneth
Paltrow, Ashley Judd, James Coburn, Cate Blanchett, Mel Gibson,
Heather Graham, Edward Norton, Samuel L. Jackson, Arnold
Schwarzenegger, Charlize Theron, Uma Thurman, Drew Barrymore and
Angela Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   Also Roberto Benigni, carrying with him hopes that he'll be as
delightful as a presenter as he was when he won for ``Life Is
Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other scheduled presenters are bound to attract notice. Jane
Fonda, recently separated from Ted Turner, rejoins the fold in
presenting an honorary Oscar to Polish director Andrzej Wajda.
Annette Bening, a best-actress nominee for ``American Beauty,'' is
due as a presenter. And due in another sense, too; she's poppingly
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Movies tend to lack hummable themes these days, but the live
performances of best-song nominees remain an Oscarcast staple.
Randy Newman, Phil Collins and Gloria Estefan somehow seem to be on
hand every year, and Sunday will be no exception.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, though, is to manage the nominee ``Blame Canada,''
from the randy ``South Park'' movie. There hasn't been an official
announcement, but watch for Robin Williams to give it a humorous
shot.
</P>
<P>
   While the Zanucks try to enliven events in the main tent,
producer and director Joel Gallen has been imported from the ``MTV
Movie Awards'' and ``VH1 Fashion Awards'' to salvage the half-hour
pre-Oscar show at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, ABC and the Motion Picture Academy launched the
pre-Oscar show to grab extra ratings and revenue. The maiden
effort, hosted by Geena Davis, was a dud.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they'll attempt a triple-host arrangement with ABC's
Meredith Vieira (``The View''), actress and model Tyra Banks and
MTV personality Chris Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be so hard. The idea is to prime the home audience for
the big show and to catch celebrities as they arrive at the Shrine
Auditorium in Los Angeles. Train the lens on the dresses and hope
that when someone says something stupid, it's a star and not one of
your hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Gallen promises, ``The audience will feel so close to the action
and frenzy of the red carpet (that) they may actually experience
rug burns.''
</P>
<P>
   So, wear knee pads and visors. This is no night for amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   But from a distance of 400 miles and two days, we can still
venture a few amateur predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cider House Rules'' will edge ``American Beauty'' for best
picture. And in a bigger upset, Michael Caine squeaks past Haley
Joel Osment, Jude Law and Tom Cruise for best supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   I also predict that Warren Beatty will win the Irving G.
Thalberg Award. After all, no one likes to be wrong all the time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
