<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARGIN-TRADING-RISKS-     03-23 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARGIN-TRADING-RISKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS CONCERNED AS INVESTORS BORROW MORE TO BUY STOCKS ON
MARGIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Borrowing money to buy stocks has become immensely popular among
individual investors today. And who can blame them? When stock
prices are rising, the biggest gains go to those who buy shares on
borrowed money.
</P>
<P>
   When stock prices are falling, however, borrowing to buy stocks
is an expensive and highly risky business. While recent tremors in
some formerly hot market sectors may have awakened some investors
to this unhappy reality, market regulators are growing concerned
that the recent surge in investor indebtedness, which has been
greatest at online brokerage firms, reflects the participation of
many people who do not understand how dangerous stock market debt
can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am troubled by the apparent ease with which real neophytes
are going online these days all by themselves and trading on
margin,'' said Bradley Skolnick, the Indiana securities
commissioner and president of the North American Securities
Administrators Association. ``A lot of people are purchasing rather
speculative, high-risk stocks with borrowed money and that's a
source of concern for me. In a volatile market, trading on margin
can find you in a whole lot of hurt very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lael Desmond, a medical school student in Indiana, learned the
hard way how risky borrowing on margin can be. In late 1997,
Desmond, who was then 26, opened an account at Ameritrade; by June
1998, he had roughly $30,000 in his account. An investing novice,
he began borrowing money to buy shares of Amazon.com, Dell
Computer, Excite, America Online and Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond, who was to begin medical school the following fall, did
not fully understand what investing on margin meant. Yes, when
stocks go up, an investor can double his gains by borrowing from
his broker, paying a relatively modest interest rate for the
opportunity. But if the stock _ which serves as the asset backing
the loan _ declines in value, the customer will be asked to put up
more money to make up for the shortfall. This is known as a margin
call. When an investor chooses not to put up more money, his shares
are sold but he usually still owes money to the broker.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond, according to his lawyer, Jeffrey Gery at Maddox,
Koeller, Hargett &AMP; Caruso in Indianapolis, thought his margin
borrowing was like a mortgage or bank loan. He had no idea that he
could lose money on it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the late summer of 1998, stocks took a dive due to to
the Russian debt crisis. On Friday, August 28, stocks began to fall
and continued their descent the following Monday, generating margin
calls of roughly $12,000 to Desmond. By Tuesday, the call had grown
to $21,000, which Desmond did not have. So he took out cash
advances on credit cards in the amount of $13,000 and borrowed
$8,000 from his brother. Nevertheless, by the time the funds were
wired to Ameritrade on the afternoon of September 1, the firm had
already sold Desmond's holdings.
</P>
<P>
   In Desmond's arbitration case, decided last January, he won
$40,453 from Ameritrade. Although the arbitrators did not give the
reason for their award, it is clear they believed Ameritrade sold
Desmond's holdings too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Gery, one of two lawyers who represented Desmond, said of the
case: ``It's been our impression that a lot of online firms think
they are Web sites first and brokerage firms second. But they are
brokerage firms first and they have a duty to maintain very high
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   It is investors like Desmond, trading through online brokers,
who are most responsible for the big jump in margin debt.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Steven Galbraith, an analyst at the investment firm Sanford C.
Bernstein &AMP; Co., estimates that margin debt as a percent of market
value has soared 459 percent at online brokers since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Growth in margin debt for all stocks on the New York Stock
Exchange, by comparison, has gone up 190 percent during the same
period. Meanwhile, the value of the market, as measured by the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 has risen 139 percent during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Some online brokerage firms have recently increased their margin
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hubbard, a spokesman at Charles Schwab, said the firm
required a greater down payment than the 50 percent minimum set by
the Federal Reserve on 270 securities its executives feel are too
volatile or illiquid. Michael Dunn, Datek Online's spokesman, said
his firm had a large number of stocks where it refused to extend
margin, while 227 others required higher down payments.
</P>
<P>
   T.D. Waterhouse requires higher than normal deposits on around
300 stocks and Ameritrade, while not supplying details, said it
required higher initial deposits on some stocks. Officials at
E-Trade did not return a phone call seeking information about their
current margin requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But brokerage firms make big money lending to investors, so it
is perhaps not surprising that many still lend freely. Galbraith
estimates that margin interest paid by investors accounts for 20
percent of a typical Internet brokerage firm's revenues. In a
recent study, he found that even the most volatile high-fliers _
including such stocks as Red Hat, Doubleclick, Broadcom, Inktomi
and Internet Capital Group _ were marginable at one online
brokerage firm or another.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the market's whipsaws become more pronounced,
borrowing to buy stocks becomes positively treacherous. A stock
that falls only 10 percent, for example _ not a big move in today's
wild market _ could trigger a request for more money from an
investor who has borrowed the maximum amount.
</P>
<P>
   If the investor does not have the funds to add to his portfolio,
the shares are sold, possibly weakening an already sickly stock.
This is why excessive investor indebtedness can exacerbate downward
moves in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because falling stocks always seem to bounce back these
days, investors remain unworried.
</P>
<P>
   Margin debt on the New York Stock Exchange has surged 75 percent
in the past 12 months and now exceeds $265 billion, an all-time
high. Debt ballooned almost 9 percent in February alone and now
accounts for more than 1.5 percent of the Big Board's total market
value, also a peak.
</P>
<P>
   Even more troubling is how fast margin debt is growing as a
share of overall consumer credit. According to Galbraith's
research, margin loans now account for 16 percent of total consumer
borrowings, up from 7 percent in 1995. Numbers like these prove
that the explosion in margin borrowings is coming from individual
investors, not institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've supplanted buying a washer-drier with debt with buying
Qualcomm on margin,'' Galbraith said. ``If you think of the
volatility of the asset being financed, it is probably more
dramatic than I suspect many of the people deploying leverage think
about.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   More investors seem to be discovering that margin trading has
pitfalls. The Securities and Exchange Commission reports that
investor complaints in that area have increased significantly in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board, which has set the margin requirement
at 50 percent since 1974, recently expressed concern over the
outsized growth in margin debt. Yet in January, when the explosive
growth in margin debt became evident, chairman Alan Greenspan
rejected calls to increase the amount required of investors when
they buy stocks on margin. He argued that an increase in the margin
requirement would be unfair to small investors because they would
be unable to secure credit, while institutional investors could tap
other sources of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the damage that heavily margined investors can sustain in
a downward move in stocks is great enough that some observers
question Greenspan's inaction. Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y.,
said, ``It's the little guys who are going to get unduly hurt when
the market goes down so I think there's nothing wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator has been urging Greenspan to reconsider his
reluctance to raise the margin requirement. ``He has not closed the
door on it,'' Schumer said. ``And right now the Fed is undergoing a
study of margin debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sylla, a professor of financial history at New York
University's Stern School of Business, called Greenspan's
small-investor argument inconsistent. ``He's worried about the
market being too high, but his argument that a margin requirement
increase would make it harder for small investors to participate is
in some sense saying, `I don't want to spoil the party for them
differentially,''' Sylla said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some regulators fear that investors are also borrowing from
sources other than their brokers to buy stocks, including credit
cards or second mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried not just about the margin but about people
borrowing on other assets like homes and the double dip effect that
would have in the event of a market decline,'' said Arthur Levitt,
chairman of the SEC. ``If we have a market decline, then that would
play out not just in terms of lower security values but also in
lower real estate values.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
