<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6191 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-CFN-COX     03-23 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CFN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CFN gets $130 million boost
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumer Financial Network said it received a $130.5 million
private equity investment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Financial Network is a comparison shopping and
information tool for all manner of personal financial services,
including home mortgages, insurance, credit cards and investments.
The service is offered to corporations, who in turn provide it to
employees through Intranets, private Internets.
</P>
<P>
   The information is available on a CFN-owned Web site,
www.youdecide.com. It also could be used by large Web sites, such
as Yahoo or Excite, hoping to create an integrated financial
services section.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based CFN is majority-owned by IXL Enterprises, the
parent company of IXL, the Atlanta-based Web design firm. IXL
Enterprises hopes to spin off the unit into a separate company.
</P>
<P>
   Including the investment, CFN is valued at $650 million. Last
year, the 220-employee company lost $38 million on $1.9 million in
revenue, not including its October acquisition of iExpert,
according to the IXL Enterprises annual report.
</P>
<P>
   Investors include Kelso &AMP; Co., a New York-based investment firm,
which is iXL's largest shareholder. Also, Chase Capital Partners,
Capital Research, First Union, Hearst-Argyle Television, J.W.
Seligman, Royal Bank of Canada, Equifax, Westway Capital, Nevo
Investments and several individual investors. iXL remains CFN's
largest single shareholder, with more than a 50 percent stake. GE
Capital remains the second largest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity of the investment _ from a media company, banks
and New York venture capital _ was an effort to tap into a network
of contacts that could potentially steer business CFN's way, said
Caroline Vanderlip, CFN's executive vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a technology with applications in a broad array of
fields, `` Vanderlip said. ``We use it to support financial
services, so a bank made sense. But we also knew that on the
private label side, that very well-connected sort of venture
capital money would help open doors for us.''
</P>
<P>
   CFN has offices in Buckhead, Duluth, Manhattan and Stamford,
Conn. Cathleen Raffaeli, CFN's president and chief operating
officer, works out of the Manhattan office with a staff of about
20.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
