<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-FUND-RAISING-HNS &LR;      03-23 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUND-RAISING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, GORE STEP UP CHASE FOR CAMPAIGN CASH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although he has pledged to eliminate unrestricted
donations to political parties, Democratic presidential contender
Al Gore will be in Houston on Friday to scoop up more than $500,000
for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican George W. Bush, whose record-shattering
fund-raising was almost matched by his record-setting spending,
also has hit the money circuit with events Thursday in Palm Beach,
Fla., and Friday in Little Rock, Ark. His appearances are expected
to net $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite heightened voter interest in fund-raising reform, both
candidates have stepped up their chase for campaign cash to prepare
for what could be a high-priced and nasty general election battle.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has moved to turn off the contribution spigot despite
vows to reach out to voters drawn to the campaign-finance reform
themes voiced by John McCain and Bill Bradley during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been the most vocal in his embrace of the reforms
championed by McCain and Bradley, including the elimination of
unrestricted soft money to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has never made campaign-finance reform a priority,
he endorsed modest changes, including abolition of soft money
contributions by corporations and unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both these guys are using the word reform, and I don't think
anyone is taking them at their word. They might talk about the
evils of soft money but that hasn't keep them from raising it,''
said Larry Makinson, director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, which monitors and analyzes fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is the name for unregulated contributions to
political parties that are intended for party building and not for
federal elections . However, in recent election cycles both parties
have used legal loopholes to funnel this money into issue ads on
the candidates' behalf.
</P>
<P>
   This year is shaping up to be no exception in the soft money
sweepstakes, with the Democratic Party predicting it will raise
$100 million and Republicans $177 million, much of it in
unregulated dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will fly to Houston on Friday night with the sole intent of
raising cash for his party. His first stop will be at the residence
of trial lawyer Denman Heard and his wife, Laura, who are hosting a
reception for 125 people expected to donate $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   He will then drop by the Museum District home of trial lawyer
Lee Godfrey, who is hosting a dinner for 40 people expected to
shell out $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising excursions have been politically awkward for
Gore who finds himself cheerleading for the kinds of contributions
he says he opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans contend that Gore's interest in campaign-finance
reform is hypocritical and is intended to blunt criticism of his
involvement in questionable fund-raising practices in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president says that he is so committed to reform
that he has instructed the Democratic Party not to spend any of the
soft money on issue ads aimed at Bush unless the Republican Party
starts airing attack spots first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to take whatever criticism comes with being an
advocate for campaign-finance reform because it is good policy,''
Gore said recently. Gore said that while he hopes Bush will accept
his challenge to eliminate soft money, he added, ``we're not going
to unilaterally disarm, and we're going to be ready if they try to
use special interest money to determine the outcome of the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans say they do not trust Gore's pledges based on
the 1996 presidential election when the Democrats blitzed the
airwaves with ads slamming GOP candidate Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let Al Gore do to us in 2000 what he did to us in
1996 with Bill Clinton, '' said Mike Collins, a spokesman for
Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said it is still unclear what role Bush will play in
helping the GOP raise soft money. He said party officials met this
week with Bush's chief of staff Joe Albaugh to discuss such
matters.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the Texas governor has been forced to
concentrate on replenishing his campaign coffers, which were
depleted by a tougher-than-expected primary against McCain.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of February, Bush had $7.5 million in cash compared
to $10.5 million for Gore, according to the latest monthly
campaign-finance reports filed with the Federal Election
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The figures represent a stunning reversal of fortune for the
candidates. Most political observers had assumed that having raised
an unprecedented $73.9 million, Bush would be flush with cash
during the pre-convention primary period while Gore would be out of
money.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bush's campaign, spending at a rate of $3 million a
week, went through more than $63 million, with about a third of the
money going for television and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan defended the spending rate
saying, ''We had a plan in place for the primary, and it was
successful.``
</P>
<P>
   The governor has scheduled 14 fund-raisers with a goal of
raising between $5 million and $10 million. He raised $750,000 at a
Palm Beach event Thursday and is expected to bring in another
quarter of a million in President Clinton's hometown of Little
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is prevented from raising more than $2 to $3 million more
for his own campaign because, unlike Bush, he is taking matching
federal funds. His campaign had raised about $37 million and spent
$27.4 million through the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore and Bush allege that the other is captive of special
interests, both of their parties take in their share of soft money
from groups and individuals with interest in federal legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats benefit from generous giving from trial lawyers and
labor unions, a recent analysis by Common Cause showed.
Republicans, meanwhile, were showered with support from tobacco
companies, the National Rifle Association and phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause President Scott Harshbarger said that if neither
Gore nor Bush makes credible moves toward campaign-finance reform
they will ``increase people's cynicism about the whole system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
