<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6195 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-GAPAC-WEB-COX     03-23 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPAC-WEB-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firms form virtual trading post
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. has teamed up with its two largest rivals
to form a virtual trading post for pulp, paper and wood products.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific, International Paper and Weyerhauser Co., the
three-largest U.S. forest products companies, said Thursday they
intend to develop a separate Internet-based venture to cut costs
and make ordering easier for their business customers and
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a mechanism for conducting business in every form _
direct business with large customers, spot business with
intermittent customers or regular business with suppliers,'' said
John Balboni, vice president of e-business for International Paper.
</P>
<P>
   Although the initiative will be restricted to
business-to-business transactions, it's possible that the companies
may expand beyond that at some point, Balboni said.
</P>
<P>
   Each company will own equal stakes in the venture, which is
expected to attract more partners. The companies may consider
selling shares in the venture to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to join forces was easy, given the increasing
number of Internet-based companies in the pulp and paper supply
business, said Ken Haldin, spokesman for Atlanta-based
Georgia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three parties had a mutual interest. We looked at it in
terms of knowing what our customer needs are and knowing that
electronic marketplace is where they're moving,'' Haldin said. ``By
doing this together, it's much more cost-effective than by each of
us taking a separate path.''
</P>
<P>
   About $200 billion in products are shipped annually in the U.S.
paper and forest products industry. Internet-based sales in the
paper industry are forecast to top $90 billion by 2004, according
to Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the European paper industry got its first
Internet supply company. PaperX.com, led by Harvard Business School
graduates and former chief executives from European paper
companies, said its site will handle 10 percent of all the paper
traded there by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific and its partners plan to create a single supply
ordering standard with a common technology platform for the forest
products industry. That should benefit small and large customers
alike, Haldin said. The venture will generate revenue primarily
through transaction fees and advertising, Haldin said.
</P>
<P>
   A search for a chief executive is on, and the venture is looking
at potential technology partners.
</P>
<P>
   The company's headquarters location hasn't been identified.
Executives are looking at ``neutral'' cities other than the home
bases of the three founding companies. International Paper is based
in Purchase, N.Y. Weyerhauser's headquarters office is in Federal
Way, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific is based on Peachtree Street in Downtown Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Two executives from each company have formed a steering
committee for the venture. Georgia-Pacific members include David J.
Paterson, vice president of electronic commerce, and Robert A.
Renner, director of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have hired Morgan Stanley Dean Witter as their
financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The first transactions for the new company, which still must
meet regulatory approval, could come in the third quarter, Haldin
said. Until then, the companies said they will continue normal
sales and procurement activities.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper's alliance with PaperExchange.com will
remain part of its electronic commerce strategy. PaperExchange, a
Boston-based online business-to-business marketplace for the paper
and pulp industry, filed for a $115 million initial stock sale last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
