<HEADER>
A6196 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-USAIRWAYS-IMPACT-COX     03-23 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAIRWAYS-IMPACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strike would impact Delta
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A possible shutdown at US Airways this weekend could flood other
airlines with stranded passengers, and Atlanta's two primary
carriers would get plenty of them.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines and AirTran Airways are among US Airways' top
competitors along the eastern seaboard and would be prime
alternatives for fliers left in the lurch.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean even bigger crowds than normal at Hartsfield
International Airport amid the busy spring break travel season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect our already heavy loads to turn into full
aircraft on many routes,'' Delta spokesman John Kennedy said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already tight, especially for Florida routes,'' agreed
Tad Hutcheson, marketing director at AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown threat stems from a contract stalemate between US
Airways and its flight attendant union. Unless there is a
breakthrough by 12:01 a.m. Saturday, the airline says it will cease
operations rather than let the Association of Flight Attendants
begin random walkouts under a plan called CHAOS, for Create Havoc
Around Our System.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways' bookings would be honored by other carriers under
certain conditions and where space is available. Such agreements
are worked out among carriers in case of a strike.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways itself has a relatively small presence at Hartsfield,
with 31 daily departures to seven destinations, compared with about
130 departures for AirTran and 660 for Delta. Flights to New York
by US Airways Express, an affiliate, wouldn't be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direct impact here wouldn't be too big,'' said Duluth
Travel owner Arthur Salus, who's been steering clients away from US
Airways for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But US Airways has a major Southeast hub in Charlotte. Many
passengers booked on connecting flights through Charlotte would
seek to re-book through Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said Delta doesn't have spare aircraft to add to routes
where the spillover might be greatest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot we can do other than accept tickets where we
have availability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran will add one extra daily Atlanta-Orlando flight starting
Saturday evening, Hutcheson said.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv.com, a fledgling Atlanta-based company that books
individual seats on small chartered private jets, will offer its
service in Charlotte starting Monday if a shutdown occurs, a
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
