<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-SURVIVOR-1STLD-W     03-23 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-SURVIVOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLOCAUST SURVIVOR THANKS POPE FOR SAVING HER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to CORRECT typo, WOJYTLA to WOJTYLA)  
(See also POPE-HOLYLAND) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT35 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Pope John Paul II made Edith Tzirer cry Thursday at
the Yad Vashem Holocaust memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Tzirer, a Holocaust survivor, had been waiting 54 years to thank
him in person for saving her life, she said. Staring into his eyes,
her emotions got the better of her. The Roman Catholic leader
reached up with his white-robed arm and patted her gently, standing
on the cold stone floor that bore the etched names of Nazi
concentration camps in Germany and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope doesn't remember her,'' Joaquin Navarro-Valls, the
Vatican spokesman, said later. ``But her story is probably true
because the pope was there at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   It took place in a small town near Krakow, Poland, in 1945.
Liberation Day. Tzirer was 14 then, painfully thin, tubercular and
alone. She had just been released from the Skarzysko-Kamienna labor
camp. Wearing her camp uniform, she was riding a train to Krakow,
where she had lost contact with her family at the beginning of the
war in 1939. The train ran out of fuel and stopped in a small town.
</P>
<P>
   While the other passengers ate and drank, Tzirer said, she sat
off in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know to this day how he saw me,'' she said. ``He moved
the people aside and came to me and asked me why I was sitting
there like that.
</P>
<P>
   ```Did you eat? Did you drink?' he asked. I said that I hadn't
in a number of days already. He went and brought me my first cup of
tea, the first cup in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a seminary student, she said, young, tall and handsome
with blue eyes. ``To tell you the truth,'' she said, ``I thought
that it was God himself who had shown up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tzirer said the man told her to come with him and board another
train, a cattle car bound for Krakow. She told him she was too weak
to walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked me up and I fell back down again like a sack of
flour,'' she said. ``He took me on his back and carried me. We
walked for three, four kilometers _ I'm not sure _ through the
snow.''
</P>
<P>
   The man told her that his name was Karol Wojtyla and that he was
from the town of Wadowice, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the cattle car was a Jewish family, whose members whispered
to her that she should watch out that the ``priest'' didn't mean to
``lock her up in a convent,'' she said. This frightened her, she
said, and in Krakow she ran away from him. Years later, she said,
in 1978, her life established in Israel, she read in a newspaper
that Karol Wojtyla had been named pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost fainted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's official biographer, Adam Bonieczi, said he was
skeptical about her story. ``I doubt she could remember him,'' he
said. ``He's told me a lot of similar stories, but I've never heard
him talk about her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tzirer's story was recounted on Israeli radio and television
throughout the day Thursday. Israelis believed it because it
reaffirmed the warm feelings they have toward the pope as a
Catholic leader who grew up with Jews, helped them after the war
and then led the church to recognize the enormity of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Also, her presence at Yad Vashem seemed to validate Tzirer's
story when she was presented to the pope Thursday, one of six
Holocaust survivors whom he met there. The program was pre-arranged
with the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The version of her story in the introduction to the Yad Vashem
ceremony, however, was slightly different than that told by Tzirer.
It said the young seminarian had found her lying by a fence and
took her to a train station, where she joined other survivors.
</P>
<P>
   When Tzirer came face to face with the pope Thursday, she
blurted out what she had wanted to tell him, an old Jewish saying:
``Whoever saves the life of a single Jew, it is as if he saved the
world in its entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she lost her composure.
</P>
</TEXT>
