<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quoting Scripture to capture message of 2000 Census
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes' office distributed several
Scripture verses and sermon ideas to promote participation in the
census. Here are two samples:
</P>
<P>
   Some interesting things happen when scripture is looked at
through Census eyes. We find that counting people is an integral
part of the Biblical story of our way with God and God's way with
us. If you have never preached a series on Nehemiah, try it.
Nehemiah is the tale of a public servant who rebuilt a great city,
Jerusalem, and in the process, helped a dispirited people find
their way. The importance of Nehemiah to the Jewish people cannot
be underestimated. One of the very first things that Nehemiah did
when he began the task of rebuilding was to enlist people to join
him in the effort. He took a census. As the city is rebuilt, he
lists the names of those who participated in the effort. Integrity,
trustworthiness, and confidence marked the activity of Nehemiah.
Those are the characteristics that the community of faith can
contribute to the process of getting a complete count for Census
2000. For our communities to be rebuilt everyone needs to be
accounted for and everyone has a part to play in the rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Census'' Text: Luke
2:1-7
</P>
<P>
   This is the famous Christmas story in which the political
authorities required all citizens to travel to the regional office
to be counted. Think of how fortunate and easy we have it. Just
fill out the form and mail it in.
</P>
<P>
   The census count is the background for one of the greatest
stories ever told. Joseph and Mary leave Nazareth en route to
Bethlehem. (By the way, the word ``Bethlehem'' means ``house of
bread.'' When people are not counted, they can forfeit money, jobs
and the means for purchasing bread.)
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the census journey, Verse 7 reads, ``She gave
birth to her first born.'' What a time to have a baby! What a
census journey to remember!
</P>
<P>
   They were registered for the census, but more importantly,
salvation was registered for those who chose to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
