<SLUG> BC-POPE-REFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBI HITS JEWISH CRITICS' CLOUDED VIEW OF POPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speaking hours after Pope John Paul II appeared at a Holocaust
memorial in Israel, the head of the Reform Jewish movement in
America has criticized Jewish organizations for failing to
acknowledge the tremendous progress made in Catholic-Jewish
relations during this pope's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Eric H. Yoffie, president of the Union of American Hebrew
Congregations, said in a speech at Assumption College in Worcester,
Mass. that Jewish groups have been too quick to criticize the pope,
too focused on the Holocaust to the exclusion of other issues, and
remiss at informing their own children about the modern state of
Jewish-Catholic relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, we teach nothing at all about other religious
traditions to our children, and what we do teach on Catholicism is
likely to focus on the Inquisition and the Crusades,'' Yoffie said
in remarks prepared for delivery. ``This is a moral failure of the
first order, and we have a profound responsibility to provide an
immediate remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoffie said Catholics do a better job teaching their children
about Jews than Jews do about Catholics, and he said he will order
an immediate revision of Jewish school textbooks to reflect recent
changes in Catholic attitudes toward Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Yoffie gave John Paull II credit for visiting a synagogue,
condemning anti-Semitism, and establishing diplomatic relations
between the Vatican and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a church where anti-Judaism was a prejudice so routine that
rare was the member who did not experience it, only by
demonstrating an intense depth of concern expressed in powerful and
suggestive language could the pope hope to change the church's
direction and overcome the hostility of centuries past,'' Yoffie
said. ``And this is exactly what John Paul has repeatedly done. . .
. I doubt if we could find any other example in history of a church
initiating a process of such profound repentance, acknowledging the
sins of its members over a 2000-year period against the
practitioners of the religious tradition from which it sprang.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoffie said Jewish groups have been too focused on criticizing
what the pope hasn't said about the role of the church during the
Holocaust, instead of acknowledging the importance of what he has
said.
</P>
<P>
   He called for Jewish and Catholic theologians to discuss what it
means to be a saint at a time of evil as a way to understand the
debate over Pope Pius XII, who the church appears likely to beatify
despite Jewish concerns that he did not speak out against the
Holocaust. And Yoffie called for more Catholic-Jewish discussion of
issues surrounding ethics, the family, and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holocaust cannot be the sole item on the Catholic-Jewish
agenda,'' he said. ``It cannot become an obsession that crowds out
all those other subjects that so urgently require our collective
attention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
