r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-CATALANOT     03-23 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-CATALANOTTO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS UPGRADE RESULTS OF TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Luis Alicea has what manager Johnny Oates
calls a ``track record.'' Oates has seen him play before and knows
what he can do.
</P>
<P>
   That might be all that keeps Alicea from losing his job as the
Rangers' every-day second baseman to the hard-charging Frank
Catalanotto. Oates has become enamored with the utility infielder
picked up from the Detroit Tigers, and his chances for more playing
time have increased daily this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a look that he has,'' Oates said. ``But when you've
been around this game a long time, you just get a feeling about a
guy that he can help you win ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto is one of several reasons why the Rangers, unlike
Jack of fairy tale fame, got more than a handful of beans when they
sent Juan Gonzalez to Detroit in the November nine-player trade.
The Rangers are feeling good about that swap.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Gabe Kapler is hitting with authority and making
diving catches. Catalanotto could end up being a front-line second
baseman rather than a utility infielder. Francisco Cordero, with
seven consecutive scoreless innings, is using his overpowering
stuff to throw more strikes down in the zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin Thompson (coming off shoulder surgery) still has to
pitch for us,'' general manager Doug Melvin said. ``You've got to
believe in a trade when you make it, and there's no reason to not
feel good about it ... seeing the progress of some of these guys,
overall our scouts and their evaluation of these guys were
accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers knew about Kapler, Cordero and Thompson. They also
knew that Bill Haselman would be a valuable backup catcher. But
Catalanotto might be an extra dividend the Rangers weren't quite
expecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we made the trade, a number of people said, `don't forget
this guy,' '' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler is among those admirers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cat's a great player,'' Kapler said. ``He's going to have
success because he's a hard worker, he cares about his teammates
and he plays to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates is finding that out quickly. Catalanotto went 0-for-3 in
Thursday's 4-2 loss to the Minnesota Twins, but is batting .371
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he doesn't know how many at-bats Catalanotto will get
this season. But asked how many he'd like for him to get, Oates
quickly said, ``The way he's swinging the bat _ 600.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Oates, ``If he keeps swinging the bat like this, he may
get 600.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Catalanotto can play regularly at second base, Oates
said, ``I'm going to try and find out. He hasn't done anything to
hurt his chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspect defense is supposed to be what keeps Catalanotto from
playing regularly, but he has made only one error this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've shown them I can play and I warrant some playing
time,'' Catalanotto said. ``I don't think I've been bad in the
field. I've made some plays and held my own. I feel more confident
I can do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was given a fair chance to win the job. They
gave the job to Luis going in and I understand that. But
eventually, if I keep hitting, I'll get a shot at a starting job
down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto, a left-handed hitter, could also see time at third
base if Tom Evans, a right-handed hitter, beats out Mike Lamb.
Oates has been using Catalanotto at second and third this spring.
Anything to get him more at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the right team, Catalanotto can really help,'' Oates said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
