<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-FLAWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON, ARMY SEEK CAUSE OF WEAR IN PATRIOT MISSILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Army has taken hundreds of Patriot missiles out of service
after finding flaws in the ground-defense weapon, built by Raytheon
Co. in Massachusetts plants.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials said Thursday they have replaced Patriots from
batteries in the Middle East and in South Korea because of worn
electronic parts in the missiles' radar guidance-systems.
</P>
<P>
   The wear seemed to occur after the missiles had been kept on
combat alert for at least six months. The Army said it has plenty
of replacement Patriots, which are meant to shoot down attacking
aircraft and missiles and said it isn't clear the flaws would have
caused the missiles with damaged components to misfire during a
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But the Army and Raytheon are still looking for the root cause
of the problem, said Major Scott Hays in Washington. Officials are
also reviewing how long missiles can be kept ready to fire at a
moment's notice. ``Those missiles got a workout, much more so than
those in Germany or in other locations'' where the weapons aren't
kept at a high state of alert, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army briefed congressional staffers on the problem earlier
this month but only disclosed it publicly Thursday after it was
reported by The Wall Street Journal. The issue is the latest to
emerge for the Patriot, which the military initially touted for its
accuracy during the Gulf War but later acknowledged had a
lower-than-claimed success rate.
</P>
<P>
   Missile-maker Raytheon suffered another setback in January when
a prototype failed to strike and destroy a target during a test of
a proposed National Missile Defense program.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 Raytheon lost out to the company now known as Lockheed
Martin Corp. in a competition to build a more precise version of
the Patriot called PAC-3. Last September Lockheed Martin received a
contract worth around $150 million to build 92 missiles and put
them into service by next year. Raytheon still builds ground-based
guidance radars for the PAC-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Raytheon was contracted to upgrade hundreds of
existing Patriots with more advanced electronics, a deal worth $47
million this fiscal year. Some of the missiles now in service up
are up to 10 years old, and several months ago the Army began
reviews of its missile stocks to discover which should be improved
first.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its past problems the Patriot remains a staple of US
defensive forces. Depending on outside temperature, it can take up
to 10 minutes to ready the missile to fire from its basic status.
But in units deployed near Iraq and North Korea, the missiles are
often kept on a ``hot'' alert status, eliminating the warmup time.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off seems to be a certain amount of wear on sensitive
electronic-components, which the Army has suspected based on
previous tests, Hays said. Sure enough, problems were discovered
when a batch of Patriots were taken apart at the Red River Army
Depot in Texas several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, wear was found in internal-guidance systems used
to link the missile with ground-based radar tracking the incoming
target missiles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing security issues, Hays and other Pentagon officials
declined to say exactly how many Patriots were taken out of service
and how many the Army has in all. Other countries that have
purchased the weapon or where Patriot batteries are manned by US
forces include Israel, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Germany, the
Netherlands, Japan, and South Korea. The Pentagon said those
countries were told of the issue within the last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon engineers are now reviewing the problem, and some of
the missiles might be test-fired at the White Sands, N.M., range to
see what impact the worn components might have on firing
operations, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Army must also estimate how much it would cost to fix
the problems and decide whether it would be worth saving the money
to spend on upgraded PAC-3 missiles instead. Until that decision is
made, the Army can't estimate the exact cost of the problem, said
Lieutenant General Paul Kern at a Washington press conference
Thursday. He added that the problematic components cost between
$80,000 to $100,000 in each missile.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Shea, spokesman for Raytheon in Lexington, Mass., said the
company didn't expect the problem to have a financial impact or to
affect foreign sales. Raytheon is currently producing a version of
the Patriot for the Greek armed forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
