<HEADER>
A6209 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GLOCK-MARK24-COX     03-23 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOCK-MARK24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glock will mark pistols to aid tracing in crimes
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Glock Inc. may have declined to join the settlement in
a federal lawsuit over handguns, but the company is already part of
a program that's a crucial part of the deal cut by Smith &AMP; Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   Glock and the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
are engaged in a voluntary pilot program that would ``fingerprint''
every handgun the company assembles at its Cobb County
manufacturing plant. It would enable police to trace the owners of
guns used in crimes when only the bullets or casings are recovered.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its agreement with the U.S. Department of Housing and
Urban Development, one of the parties to the suit, Smith &AMP; Wesson,
has agreed to participate in the program _ if it can be shown to
work.
</P>
<P>
   When a gun is fired, it creates a unique mark on the bullet and
the shell casing. Under the Glock program, each gun will be fired
before it is sold, and the laser images of these markings will be
cataloged. These images will be compiled in an existing national
database known as Integrated Ballistic Identification System
(IBIS). The goal is to have a fingerprint of every gun that hits
the street.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the gun industry has been reluctant to assume
responsibility for connecting guns to the criminals who use them.
But more than half of all U.S. law enforcement departments use
Glock's sidearms. ``It's the right thing to do,'' said Jim Pledger,
Glock's national sales manager and a former FBI agent. ``We want to
meet in the middle. We want to be supportive of law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the concept has been greeted with skepticism by some
gun enthusiasts, who say it won't work because any criminal can
change the markings a gun makes within seconds. The government
should focus on keeping guns out of criminal hands and not waste
time cataloging gun marks, said Bill Powers, spokesman for the
National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a whole lot of people who have expressed concerns
about whether it has any real value,'' Powers said. ``It doesn't
take a whole lot of brain power or effort to change the markings.
There's not a criminal out there (who's) worried about this.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ATF says the program has the potential to help police
get a head start on investigations _ even without a suspect or a
gun.
</P>
<P>
   If police can match a shell that's been cataloged, by Glock or
another manufacturer, they could trace the gun back to its original
sale, said Tracy Hite, an ATF spokeswoman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the value of this to law enforcement,'' Hite said.
``It will give us the ability to pursue a criminal case without a
firearm in hand. Currently, in most cases (without an eyewitness),
the recovery of the firearm is critical to identifying the person
or persons involved in a violent crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The IBIS system started taking root in the early 1990s. Hite
said IBIS other related systems currently have 500,000 images
collected from shells or bullets collected at crime scenes. About
8,000 matches have been made from cold cases and about 16,000
criminal cases have been developed from the information.
</P>
<P>
   Hite said Glock initially only will catalog the markings on its
9 mm guns. The pilot program's main goal will be to test if it's
feasible to integrate with a production line. The system is to be
up and running in a few months. After nine months, the program will
be evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   And the gun industry that sells about 2 million handguns
annually in the United States will be eyeing the Glock program,
said Robert Delfay, president of National Shooting Sports
Foundation, the world's largest trade association for gun
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to skepticism over whether markings are a reliable
way of tracing guns, Delfay said, there is also a concern about
cost _ Who would pay for the system? The government is subsidizing
Glock's pilot program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry position has been that we are supportive with
working with ATF to see if the system works and would be a viable
tool for law enforcement,'' Delfay said. ``If it is a viable tool
for law enforcement, we will do what we can to further
implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This industry is extremely responsible,'' Delfay said. ``They
realize while the ATF is a government agent it is somewhat removed
from the political motivations of the current administration. While
we're aware of the connection between the ATF and the Clinton
administration, we're not going to let that connection keep us from
cooperating with law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
