<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS CUT MOSS FOR BRUSCHI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Facing a $1.6 million cap hit on veteran
offensive lineman Zefross Moss's contract, the Patriots elected to
cut Moss to make room for linebacker Tedy Bruschi, whose two-year,
$3 million-plus deal became official once the Patriots made cap
space.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, 33, was arguably the Patriots' most consistent offensive
lineman the past three years, starting 42 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been speaking off and on with the Patriots for a few
weeks, so it's not shocking,'' said Moss's agent Don Cronson.
``These things happen, so we'll turn the chapter and move on to the
next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronson said the Patriots did not discuss a renegotiation of
Moss's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Moss was scheduled to earn $1 million this season, the final
year of his contract, and the team had already paid him a $100,000
roster bonus March 1. By cutting him now, the Patriots are
responsible for one-quarter of the $1.8 million signing bonus Moss
received when he signed his four-year, $5.2 million deal in 1997,
and the $100,000 roster bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots saved $1.05 million with the move, which they
applied toward Bruschi's cap hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have essentially replaced Moss at 50 percent of the
cost because they signed Grant Williams, whose cap hit is $850,000.
Moss has protected Drew Bledsoe very well on the right side. Now,
the Patriots will enter the season with three players _ Max Lane,
Williams, and Ed Ellis contending for the tackle jobs. If Bruce
Armstrong eventually returns, that means Williams, Ellis, and Lane
would vie for the right tackle job.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who went undrafted out of Alabama State, has been in the
league since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zefross can still play and play at a high level,'' said
Cronson. ``I'm sure there are teams out there that would need a
veteran presence like Zefross, who is a model citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Israel can add the New Orleans Saints to the list of
teams, including the Giants and Seahawks, that are interested in
him. Agent Gary Uberstine said that despite the Patriots saying
they were moving ``closer'' to signing Israel last week, ``They
haven't made us an offer. I keep reading comments from them, but I
think they're trying to get Steve at a reduced rate.'' That
apparently won't happen any time soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
