<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSCH-SUIT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF ROGER MARIS BATTLES WITH BUSCH
</HEADLINE>
  (mh) 
 By SANDRA L. NORTUNEN and LISE FISHER   
 The Gainseville (Fla.) Sun   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ For three years, the family of baseball
legend Roger Maris has been in a legal fight with one of the
largest beer distributors in the country _ Anheuser-Busch Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a judge's ruling in a federal lawsuit is being played as a
win for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The Maris family, which owns Maris Distributing Co. in
Gainesville, sued Anheuser-Busch in March 1997, claiming it
executed monopolistic practices and wrongfully terminated the Maris
company's wholesaler agreement, forcing the company to shut down.
Lawyers for the family have said the action was part of a pattern
of takeovers by Anheuser-Busch.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch, which is based in St. Louis, said it ended its
agreement with Maris Distributing because the company was selling
outdated beer and was not meeting the requirements of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   On March 15, a judge from the U.S. District Middle Court of
Florida eliminated some points of the case and allowed others to
continue to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris was given the distributorship by August Busch Jr.,
who owned the beer company and the St. Louis Cardinals baseball
team, where Maris played in 1967 and 1968. The beer distributorship
is said to have been a reward to Maris for helping the Cardinals
win the 1967 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   An Orlando lawyer representing the Marises, Bernie Dempsey, said
the judge's decision allows the family to take Anheuser-Busch to
trial on at least one claim _ that contracts that conspire to
restrain trade or commerce are illegal. The ruling opens the door
to other similar lawsuits against Anheuser-Busch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it a decision that is really favorable to Maris
Distributing, it is a decision that exposes Anheuser-Busch to the
possibility of lawsuits from any distributor who feels that
restrictions on public ownership has affected their ability to sell
their operations,'' Dempsey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is going to become a class-action suit,
but I can tell you that we have had a number of distributing
centers contact us about this since the case began,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Anheuser-Busch offered another spin on the judge's rulings.
The company said it was pleased with the judge's decision to
eliminate a separate claim of monopolistic practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court found that Anheuser-Busch Inc. had not attempted to
monopolize the market for beer distributorships,'' said a press
release from Royce J. Estes, vice president and deputy counsel for
the company. ``As to the remaining claim involving public ownership
of beer distributorships, the court found that this matter should
be resolved in trial. We are confident that the provisions in our
agreement with our beer wholesalers will be upheld.''
</P>
<P>
   The disputes between the Marises and Anheuser-Busch date to
1996, when the family declined Anheuser-Busch's offer of $20
million for the family's facilities in Gainesville and Ocala. The
family said the offer was less than fair market value.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said the Maris family was instructed to sell their
operations, for which there was no other viable buyer. ``In August
1996, they were basically told to either get out of the business
immediately or they were going to be terminated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the family filed state and federal lawsuits,
Anheuser-Busch filed a countersuit, stopped delivering beer to
Maris Distributing and terminated its wholesaler agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The family operated facilities in Gainesville and Ocala for 30
years, employing more than 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris died in 1985. His four sons _ Roger, Kevin, Randy
and Richard _ live in Gainesville, and his brother, Rudy, manages
the company, Dempsey said.
</P>
<P>
   After the plant was shut down, Berkhardt Distributors in St.
Augustine was awarded the new distributing contract for the
Gainesville market, and Bernie Little Distributorship of Eaton Park
took over the Ocala area.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville, Fla., Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
