<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-FINAL-FOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S HOCKEY FINAL FOUR TEAMS SEEING FAMILIAR FACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You? Again?
</P>
<P>
   When Brown and Dartmouth face off this afternoon, it will be
their fourth meeting of the season. When Minnesota takes on
Minnesota-Duluth, it will be their sixth. A national title might be
at stake, but the semifinal pairings make it seem more like a
neighborhood game of pond hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to Boston to play the team that's 2 1/2 hours
away?'' chuckled University of Minnesota coach Laura Halldorson.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she or any of the other three coaches is complaining.
After all, they get to vie for the crown in the four-team American
Women's College Hockey Alliance 2000 Division 1 National Ice Hockey
tournament, so the chance to meet someone new is not a high
priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another Ivy League game,'' said Brown coach Digit
Murphy of her appointment with Dartmouth, ``and the Ivy rivalry is
something you can't put away.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown takes on Dartmouth at 5 p.m. in the first semifinal at
Northeastern's Matthews Arena, followed by Minnesota vs.
Minnesota-Duluth at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ECAC champion Brown (24-3-3) enters as the favorite, with
tournament MVP goaltender Ali Brewer coming off a 35-save
performance and everyone chipping in to shore up the scoring lost
when Tara Mounsey went down last month with a torn ACL. The Bears
are 3-0 this season against Dartmouth, beating them by scores of
1-0 and 6-1 in the regular season before their 6-3 victory in the
ECAC final last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Murphy sees in the Big Green quickness and
intensity, with good passing defensemen who can shoot from the
point, and a team without superstars that plays as a unit. ``That
team's playing for the front of the jersey,'' she said, ``not the
back.''
</P>
<P>
   That Dartmouth (20-11) is in the tourney at all is a surprise to
some, but three of its wins came when they counted the most:
against Harvard, including last Saturday's 3-2 overtime victory in
the league semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to be critical of it, fine,'' said Dartmouth
coach Judy Oberting of her team's selection, which was made by a
six-member committee after Sunday night's ECAC final. ``I don't
think we have a history of getting a lot of respect, period.'' This
season, her young team featured only one senior, who played
sparingly because of injury. ``People talk about us being the
no-names, the low-profiles. All along the talk was of Harvard and
Brown meeting for the national championship. We used that to our
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   If Dartmouth consists of the no-names, then Minnesota-Duluth has
the big names, certainly on the international scene. Led by US
Olympic forward Jenny Schmidgall, the nation's leading scorer (88
points on 39 goals and 49 assists) who transferred this season from
Minnesota, ex-Canadian Olympic coach Shannon Miller's team boasts
three other Olympians as well: Sweden's Erika Holst and Maria Rooth
and Finland's bronze-medal goaltender, Tuula Puputti. Its offense
is the most potent in the tournament, with three scorers among the
top six in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was a bit of a long shot,'' said Miller, asked if
she thought from the beginning that her team could make the
``frozen four'' in its debut season. ``But if I didn't know it was
possible, I wouldn't have set it as a goal.'' Did her opponents
think it was possible? ``I'm positive they didn't,'' replied
Miller. ``That's what makes it so fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that, despite the plethora of Olympians, her secret
is depth, especially her third line. ``They were huge in that final
game for us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That final game'' was a 2-0 win over the University of
Minnesota to win the newly-formed Western Collegiate Hockey
Association tournament and earn an automatic bid to Boston. The
victory gave Duluth a 3-1-1 edge this season over the Gophers, who
before this season were pretty much the only game in the Midwest
when it came to Division 1 women's hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have another team in our league that strong is the best
thing that could happen,'' said Halldorson. ``Their program has
gotten a lot of national attention, which I think has benefitted
all of us in the Midwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota has some offense of its own, led by the nation's
leading goal-scorer (46) in Nadine Muzerall, and a defense that
includes senior Courtney Kennedy of Woburn and her sister, Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame Harvard couldn't be in it,'' said Murphy, ``but
you've got four teams who should put on a good show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, there will also be a Division 3 national
championship, in which Middlebury will face Augsburg (Minn.) in a
two-game series with a 15-minute ``mini-game'' as a tiebreaker if
necessary. Middlebury (22-2-0, including 18 shutouts) advances
after capturing its fifth-straight ECAC Division 3 title, while
Augsburg (21-5-1) won the Minnesota Intercollegiate Athletic
Conference tournament. The first game, which kicks off the
tournament, is Friday at 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
