<HEADLINE>
STOCKS AND BONDS ADVANCE VIGOROUSLY AMID OPTIMISM ON RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks soared again Thursday as investors poured into
technology and financial shares in a bet that the Federal Reserve
is almost finished raising short-term interest rates. Similar
optimism fueled the Treasury bond market, as the price on the
30-year bond rose to its highest level since August.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained 253.16 points, or 2.3
percent, while the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 1.6
percent. It was the tenth time since the beginning of February that
the Dow has gained or lost more than 200 points, a level that once
was eye-popping but has become almost routine.
</P>
<P>
   With very few companies having issued earnings warnings for the
first quarter, and interest rates dropping, investors are hungry
again for equities. Notably, the biggest, most liquid stocks were
the biggest gainers. Shares of companies like Microsoft, General
Electric and Cisco Systems, which all have billions of shares
outstanding, each gained more than 6 percent Thursday as investors
jumped into the mega-cap stocks that have performed so well for the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds also gained, with the interest rate on the 30-year
Treasury bond falling to 5.91 percent. The rally in bonds came as a
fight brewed Thursday between the Treasury Department and two
government-sponsored companies that help finance home mortgages.
Some analysts said safety-conscious institutional investors had
bought Treasury bonds and sold bonds of the two companies, Fannie
Mae and Freddie Mac, helping the Treasury market.
</P>
<P>
   Investor nervousness about Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac was not
confined to the companies' bonds. Shares in both companies stumbled
in morning trading Thursday, with Fannie Mae falling as low as $58
and Freddie Mac as low as $42.75.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac have significant tax and regulatory
advantages over commercial and investment banks, and Treasury
Undersecretary Gary Gensler on Wednesday urged a congressional
committee to consider stripping the companies of many of those
benefits. A bill pending in the House of Representatives would
repeal a conditional line of credit that Fannie and Freddie have
with the U.S. Treasury. While the amount of money available is
relatively small compared to the size of the companies, Gensler
said that its repeal would make clear to investors that the
government does not stand behind the debt of the companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the two stocks ended the day higher after investors decided
that the odds are against Congress' significantly changing the way
the companies do business. Fannie Mae ended the day at $62.50, up
$0.640625, and Freddie Mac finished at $47, up 56.25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Posner, who covers Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac for Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, said Congress is unlikely to pass legislation
that would raise borrowing costs for Fannie and Freddie, since
those increased costs would probably be passed on to consumers in
the form of higher mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, it's hard for me to see politically what
support this bill might have,'' Posner said. ``If legislative
momentum develops to make homeownership more difficult in the
United States, maybe Fannie and Freddie are at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bert Ely, who co-authored a paper released two weeks ago by
the American Enterprise Institute that argued against continuing
the subsidies for Fannie and Freddie, said investors would be wise
not to dismiss the prospect of Congressional action. As Fannie and
Freddie grow, with Fannie alone now issuing about $900 billion in
debt, the controversy will increase, Ely said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem that Fannie and Freddie have is the bigger they
get, the bigger a target they become,'' Ely said. The hubbub from
Gensler's comments ``will probably die down in the short term, but
there will be long-term repercussions from it,'' he predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
