<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CHAPLAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST ROMAN CATHOLIC HOUSE CHAPLAIN SWORN IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ending a bitter fight that melded the contentious
arenas of politics and religion, the House swore in the first Roman
Catholic priest ever to serve as House chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the Rev. Daniel Coughlin of Chicago follows
an acrimonious, four-month controversy that had Catholic,
Democratic House members accusing Republicans of anti-Catholic
bias.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan nominating committee last fall had voted a
Catholic, the Rev. Timothy O'Brien, as the top choice for House
chaplain, but House leaders instead selected a Presbyterian
minister, the Rev. Charles Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Wright Thursday withdrew from consideration, and House Speaker
J. Dennis Hastert, clearly angry at the partisan and personal
upheaval caused by the controversy, announced on the House floor
that he would name Coughlin in Wright's place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a more ugly and destructive political
campaign,'' Hastert, an Illinois Republican, told the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of this chaplain issue over the last four months
does not appear to be constrained by common decency,'' Hastert
said. ``It looks a lot like war, and it has an ugly face.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats noted the historical significance of swearing in
the first Catholic to the post of House chaplain. But they were
muted in their pleasure over their political victory, saying the
House needed to change the way it selected a chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process that got us here was so flawed, I don't think
there's anyone who's cackling with satisfaction,'' said
Representative Richard Neal, Democrat of Massachusetts and a Roman
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very sorry it has come to this point,'' a solemn House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt told his colleagues on the House
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The post of chaplain is a mainly ceremonial job, which pays
about $131,000 a year, and has not traditionally been politicized.
But the selection of a chaplain to replace a Lutheran pastor, the
Rev. James Ford, who had held the job for 21 years, became mired in
politics in a Congress still smarting from the partisan impeachment
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of partisanship and a lot of distrust here in
the House,'' said Representative James P. McGovern, Democrat of
Massachusetts. ``One of the things I had hoped would happen when
Speaker Hastert took over was that he would work toward ending the
politics of personal destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party also has been put on the defensive over the
issue of Bob Jones University, a private school whose leaders have
made anti-Catholic comments. Republican presidential contender
George W. Bush drew Democratic ire when he spoke at the South
Carolina school in February.
</P>
<P>
   Republican sources said Hastert held a meeting with Coughlin in
Chicago on Monday, the Associated Press reported. The following
day, he met privately with Wright, who signaled his intention to
withdraw. Coughlin was offered the job, only hours before his
appointment, and he flew to Washington almost immediately, the AP
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright withdrew, Hastert said because he ``did not want to serve
as the chaplain in a divided House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not allow this House to be torn apart and the office of
chaplain to be destroyed,'' Hastert told his colleagues as he put
Coughlin's name up for a vote. Coughlin, the vicar for priests in
the Chicago archdiocese, was given a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan, 18-member panel had winnowed a field of 38
candidates last year to three, including O'Brien and Wright. During
the vetting process, Democrats had been told that O'Brien was asked
what they considered offensive questions, such as whether O'Brien,
unmarried, could show that he was ``moral.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the selection committee, Democrats reported,
indicated they were ``uncomfortable'' with having a chaplain who
would walk the halls of the Capitol in a priest's collar and
vestment.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives J. Joseph Moakley, Democrat of Massachusetts,
and McGovern, both Catholics, sent a letter to Hastert in December,
asking him to explain why O'Brien was passed over. While the letter
did not explicitly accuse the Republicans of bias, it did note that
``it has been nearly 40 years since John F. Kennedy fought bigotry
and prejudice on his way to the White House. We are saddened that
the progress America has made toward religious tolerance and
inclusion does not seem to have reached the halls of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley said, ``I think Hastert probably did the only thing he
could do'' in naming a Catholic. ``This was a good way for him to
get out of it. I'm just glad it's resolved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 1959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
