<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6223 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RAVES-MAIN24-COX     03-23 2364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVES-MAIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The rave: At unconventional parties, devotees express themselves
through a rousing mix of dance, technology and spirituality
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pulpit, altar and pews are gone from ``the
Church.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone too from this stately building near Turner Field in
southwest Atlanta, is the choir calling the faithful to worship. In
its place, turntable wizards keep late-night crowds dancing until
daylight in a fog-filled sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Votive candles that once burned softly have given way to glow
sticks floating in the darkness like Technicolor popsicles.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sacramental wine. But it's easy to find $25 tabs of
the designer drug Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   The Church is the site of weekly rave, high-energy parties that
for thousands of metro Atlanta young people have become unbridled
expressions of music, dance, technology and touchy-feely
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   Seven nights a week, ravers attend parties at the Church,
formally known as Celebration Hall, or other venues such as the
Atrium, Studio Central, MJQ, the Masquerade and the International
Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Raves are unlike bars or alcohol-based parties; no one goes to a
rave to get drunk or picked up. Instead, ravers say they are
seeking PLUR _ an acronym for ``peace, love, unity and respect.''
For ravers, PLUR is gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my Sabbath, this is where my family is,'' says Stephen
Thomas, a lanky 20-year-old from Marietta, Ga., who goes by the
rave name DogFrequency. ``We're all just smiling strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about freedom of expression,'' says Dia ``D-Girl''
Ganblin, 20, of Atlanta. ``It's about being free and being
spiritual. For us, it's almost religious.''
</P>
<P>
   Dustin Shahan, 19, of Kennesaw, Ga., used to attend church
services with his family but has never been religious. A raver
since he was 14, he says PLUR has given him all the spiritual
guidance he needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reflect the unity in a society that is all messed up,''
said Shahan, who goes by the DJ name X-tastyle. ``There's no hate.
It's all love. The party reflects what the world should be more
like.''
</P>
<P>
   Raves in some form have been around for years, but they've grown
from semiprivate, underground affairs into gatherings that are
openly promoted.
</P>
<P>
   They surfaced in England in the mid-'80s, then were exported to
the pop-culture capitals of America: New York, Chicago, Los Angeles
and Miami. Finally they caught on in other cities and college
towns.
</P>
<P>
   As the parties got bigger and more visible, they sometimes
attracted unwanted attention. Concerns about drug use have led to
crackdowns and curfews recently in Savannah, Orlando, Tampa and
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, promoters have been throwing parties for about 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   These days digitally designed fliers advertising parties are
handed out at popular record stores, and rave promoters sometimes
hire off-duty cops to help with security.
</P>
<P>
   Raves can be as small as 100 people or larger than 2,000. Ticket
prices usually range from $15 to $25.
</P>
<P>
   Though professionally promoted, raves still have a back-alley
mystique.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these individuals tend to come from suburban areas
where they don't have a lot of nightlife,'' says Lt. Stan Savage of
the Atlanta Police Department, who keeps tabs on the rave scene.
``They come to the city to have a good time, and it gives them a
sense of living on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, raves are a chance to break out of a lifetime of
scheduled playgroups, parent-controlled little leagues and rigidly
structured extracurricular activities. A rave purposely defies
structure. The dress code, for instance, can be distilled into a
single word: ``whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Some partygoers are shirtless, others wear tank tops and chinos.
Super-sized surfboard jeans, Airwalk sneakers and ball caps twisted
to the back are de rigueur, but don't be surprised to see someone
sporting a three-piece suit either.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-gallon cowboy hats are cool. Giant monarch butterfly wings
hooked on your back? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   At one recent rave, a man standing about 6-foot-4 wore a
sparkling, all-white jumpsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The rave scene _ in principle, at least _ knows no color, ethnic
or sexual barriers. Though predominantly white, most parties have a
smattering of blacks, Asians and Latinos in attendance. At the
Church recently, the sight of two young women smooching didn't
cause a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Scott ``Cyborg'' Buchmann, 17, of Alpharetta, Ga., says he's
half-Puerto Rican ``and half crazy.'' When he goes raving, he
spends the night break dancing, spinning like a madman on his
hands, knees and back. ``You know how I learned to do this?'' he
asks proudly after a sweat-drenched performance. ``I went on the
Internet and taught myself.''
</P>
<P>
   High-tech hippies?
</P>
<P>
   Ravers' four-letter creed, PLUR, evokes the ``make love, not
war'' chants of '60s flower children. Their use of drugs and
disdain for some social conventions likewise follow a
countercultural path trod by the beatniks and hippies.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Walsh, 18, of Cullowhee, N.C., sounds like a refugee from
the Summer of Love when explaining why he's driven three hours to
attend a rave at the International Ballroom in DeKalb County. ``You
know these people are your brothers and your sisters,'' he says.
``You could just feel the good vibes coming off the flier.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet ravers diverge from earlier countercultures when it comes to
their attitude toward the world at large. Most ravers are not
trying to change the world, just trying to find a place in it for
their parties.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike hippies, who rejected technology, ravers embrace it.
Their music and slick party fliers are computer-enhanced
masterpieces. Ravers often use their e-mail addresses as party
nicknames.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder to be special today. It's hard to feel like you
can make a dent in society,'' says Joe Figura, 26, a longtime raver
who works for an Atlanta investment firm as a computer
troubleshooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that a lot of things people told us about things
like college are a complete scam,'' Figura says. ``I don't want to
wake up when I'm 50 and be locked into a life or a job I can't
stand.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to get a fix on the rave scene is to consider it the
anti-Buckhead (Atlanta's yuppie entertainment district).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to Buckhead, you have to worry about how you look
and who's looking at you,'' says James Chase, 24, a journalism
student at Georgia Perimeter College. ``I have never seen a fight
at a rave. You go to Buckhead, and there are 30 or 40 fights every
night.''
</P>
<P>
   While police have occasionally shut down raves and made drug
arrests, the parties haven't become a major public safety issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are parties out there, and we act on them when
we get information about drug use,'' says APD's Savage. ``But it's
not an epidemic. We don't need a rave party task force. As we get
information and evaluate it, we'll see if there is a need to
increase our enforcement efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ministers of music
</P>
<P>
   There is no pecking order among partygoers, but DJs rule the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties are about a natural energy that flows through the
music,'' Figura says. ``That's why the DJ is such a god, because he
sets the tone. He gets everybody on the same level.''
</P>
<P>
   To ravers, DJs such as Sasha, Danny Tha Wildchild and Rabbit in
Tha Moon are more than just platter pickers. They are highly
sought-after artists who travel around the world creating sonic
landscapes from spinning vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   DJs can earn as little as a few hundred dollars to as much as
$30,000 for a three-hour set, plus expenses. Most raves feature
three or more DJs in separate rooms playing a particular specialty,
such as trance, breakbeat, house, drum and bass, or jungle.
</P>
<P>
   T.C. Izlam, aka The Funky Alien, is ``hip-hop junglist'' _
representing a cross-bred style influenced by hip-hop, soul and
reggae. A typical set by Izlam includes samples from Mary J. Blige,
Queen, Frank Sinatra, Alvin and the Chipmunks and an organ riff
from the ``Batman'' theme song.
</P>
<P>
   After spinning and rapping at a packed party at the Atrium in
DeKalb County, Izlam describes his role: ``When you're standing
there in front of the crowd, you're like a minister. I have to
abduct everyone in the party. It's like the apocalypse is happening
right there, and you feel like a god on that stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Night at the rave
</P>
<P>
   Despite being mostly alcohol-free, some parties are advertised
as ``18 and older.'' That doesn't stop underage ravers who use fake
IDs.
</P>
<P>
   Before entering, all partygoers are frisked from head-to-toe and
asked to empty their pockets, purses and backpacks for weapons and
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, it helps to have plenty of cash. Small bottles of
water sell for $3, and a pack of chewing gum costs about a buck.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more expensive items for sale are $6 glow sticks _
plastic tubes of luminescent liquid. Ravers attach them to string
and swing them furiously around their bodies, creating arcs of
ghostly neon light. Others put glow sticks between their fingers
and perform hypnotic hand dances for fellow ravers.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual to see ravers wearing surgical masks or paper
dust filters, which keep out airborne dust kicked up by dancers and
smoke emitted by fog machines. Ravers sometimes slip tiny glow
sticks underneath the masks, adding to the already eerie effect.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother asking somebody to dance _ it's considered
declasse.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, everyone on the dance floor is bound together by a
convulsive, chest-rattling bass beat and clangorous synthesizer
riffs that can reach ear-shattering levels.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to hold a conversation near the dance floor is futile.
``People talk, but it doesn't usually go beyond a greeting or
acknowledgment of someone you saw at another party,'' says Eddie
Ku, 30, of Atlanta. ``People come to dance, not to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Limber bodies twist and contort to the electrified rhythms as
their movements blur in hyperkinetic frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a zone you go into where everything disappears,'' says
Adriana Chiknas, 18, of Decatur, Ga. ``It's just you and the music.
There's nothing like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Raving and rolling
</P>
<P>
   It's common to see ravers chewing on baby pacifiers, sucking on
sour gumballs, or downing bottled water. Not all of them are simply
satisfying their thirst or a sweet tooth.
</P>
<P>
   Some are using Ecstasy, or X, a synthetic drug that produces a
mildly hallucinogenic high similar to amphetamines. It's usually
sold in tablets imprinted with corporate logos or cartoon
characters.
</P>
<P>
   Pacifiers, candy and gum are sometimes used to keep those
``rolling'' on X from grinding their teeth when the drug kicks in _
a common side effect. Users may have a glassy, heavy-lidded stare
and slur their words. The drug also tends to dehydrate users,
leaving them with a strong craving for water.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstasy gives off a garlicky scent. If a critical mass of ravers
is rolling on X, the smell wafts upward on waves of pungent
perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The candy helps freshen a user's breath, and some ravers sniff
Vicks nasal inhalers, a practice that is said to help increase the
drug's potency.
</P>
<P>
   Ravers sometimes sit in ``cuddle puddles,'' small clusters on
the floor, massaging one another's shoulders and backs in a gesture
of solidarity that also enhances the drug's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Users say X makes them feel sensual, but not sexual. The feeling
has been compared to a warm, almost electric buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's PLUR to the utmost,'' says Judd ``Lizard'' Martin, 20, of
Roswell, Ga. ``You want to talk to everybody and touch everybody.
It's an all-over good feeling, but it's nothing like alcohol or
pot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ravers say the use of X is widespread, and many acknowledge
trying it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer admit to using GHB _ a cheaper illegal drug nicknamed
``Georgia Home Boy.'' A colorless liquid, GHB is sometimes called
the ``date-rape drug,'' because it can be slipped into a drink to
incapacitate a sexual-attack target.
</P>
<P>
   Both X and GHB can be lethal, and overdose cases are common in
Atlanta emergency rooms. ``On Friday and Saturday nights, emergency
rooms in urban areas can easily see 20 a night,'' says Dr. Robert
Geller, director of the Georgia Poison Center. The most common
sources, Geller says, are raves and gay bars.
</P>
<P>
   At a rave in November at the Nike Pavilion, nine people were
taken to Grady Memorial Hospital after overdosing on GHB. One of
the victims, a young man, collapsed in a heap. A young woman rushed
to him, lifted her shirt and rubbed his face in her bare breasts in
an effort to keep him conscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done this before, and that usually wakes them up,'' said
the woman, who would only identify herself as Carla. ``I'm sure
he'll live through this.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, a group of Atlanta promoters formed the Atlanta
Alliance to promote PLUR and to combat drugs. The Alliance began
handing out leaflets to ravers alerting them to the dangers of
Ecstasy, GHB and other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to get like other cities that have anti-rave
laws,'' said Christian Long, one of the founders of the Alliance.
``We have a flourishing scene, and it's well-respected, and we want
to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray of `Sunshine'
</P>
<P>
   At the Church, Jessica Bowie, 19, of Marietta, Ga., is dressed
up as a Catholic schoolgirl, complete with pigtails, a plaid skirt,
knee socks and black patent leather shoes. Bowie, who goes by the
nickname ``Sunshine,'' is a candy raver, a type of partygoer known
for outrageous costumes and goody bags filled with sweets,
whistles, bubbles, Slinkies and other knickknacks that they give
away.
</P>
<P>
   She offers to give a stranger a back rub with an electric
massager. Her gesture, in many ways, sums up her feelings about the
rave scene that she has made her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want everybody to feel good,'' Sunshine says. ``I've
never seen somebody leave a party mad. That's why we're here, isn't
it? To love each other and feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: The worldwide scene of rave parties: ajc.com/links
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
