<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6224 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WORLD-TB-DAY-COX     03-23 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-TB-DAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TB Day set to raise awareness
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One jumbo jet full of people, crashing every hour on the hour,
every day, for a year.
</P>
<P>
   That's the human toll of tuberculosis on the world. Every year,
8 million people acquire the lung-destroying illness, and more than
2 million die. Overall, up to one-third of the world's population
may be infected by the bacterium, though they do not all have
active disease _ the time when it damages the body and can be
easily spread.
</P>
<P>
   Today is World TB Day, a United Nations-sponsored initiative
that hopes to focus international attention on the persistence of
TB. But if you think that requires imagining Indian cities and
African villages, Georgia health workers suggest you think again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are areas we could go into in Atlanta that have rates of
tuberculosis similar to developing countries,'' said Dr. Henry
Blumberg, an infectious disease specialist at Emory University
School of Medicine. ``In the city of Atlanta, the TB rate is five
times the national average.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, TB cases have been declining since the early 1990s.
But last year in Georgia, cases began to rise again, from 631 cases
to 666, according to the state Division of Public Health. Georgia
is among the nation's 10 worst states for rates of TB.
</P>
<P>
   TB is a disease of poverty; Southern states have a
disproportionate share of U.S. cases. It is also a disease
associated with immigration; roughly two of every five cases
nationally (one of five in Georgia) occur in someone who was born
outside the United States. In Atlanta, that has meant TB infection
among immigrants who do landscaping and construction work, as well
as in graduate students who go home for vacations to countries with
high rates of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we are an international city, we need to have a
heightened awareness and diligence about finding people who are
infected and getting them the treatment they need,'' said Dr. Eric
Benning of the Fulton County Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   TB develops slowly and takes a long time, six months at least,
to treat _ two factors that make it difficult to tackle and to
lobby for. This week, Reps. Sherrod Brown (D-Ohio) and Connie
Morella (R-Md.) introduced a bill in Congress that calls for a $100
million contribution to international TB control programs.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, Georgia advocates have called for the state to
expand Medicaid coverage to TB patients, a move that could bring an
additional $2 million in matching funds to the state each year.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
