<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6225 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-RONNIESANDERS24-C     03-23 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-RONNIESANDERS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanders out front in Southern All Stars circuit
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ronnie Sanders enters Saturday's race at Peach State
Speedway in Jefferson hoping to pad his points lead in the Southern
All Stars stock-car circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, from Fayetteville, won the opener at Birmingham
International Raceway and has recorded two top-five finishes in
non-SAS races. He credits his car-builder, Frankie Grill, and his
engine-builder, Gary Dingler.
</P>
<P>
   Other local drivers in the 200-lap race include Dawsonville's
Ricky Turner, Johnny Henderson from Conyers and Scott Griffin from
Tyrone. Qualifying is at 5:30 p.m., the main event at 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unexpected win: Jody Coltrane went to Seven Flags Speedway
last Saturday to work on his brother's pit crew and wound up
winning the feature race. Coltrane ran into car owner Sonny
Blackwell, who asked if he wanted to drive a spare car. After
borrowing a firesuit and a helmet, Coltrane qualified second and
won the race.
</P>
<P>
   _ ASA changes: The American Speed Association opens this weekend
in Lakeland, Fla., with radical rules changes. The $30,000 racing
engines have been replaced with power plants built on the assembly
line. And B.F. Goodrich will make its return to the stock-car tire
business.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
