<SLUG> BC-REFORM-JEWS-GAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORM RABBIS EXPECTED TO SUPPORT SAME-SEX WEDDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a historic move that will place them at the center of a
debate now roiling the nation's religious organizations, America's
Reform rabbis are expected to give their official support next week
to ceremonies, including weddings, that bless the relationships of
gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, scheduled to take place Wednesday in Greensboro, N.C.,
would make the rabbis the first group of mainstream American clergy
to endorse same-sex ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Although individual clergy from a variety of liberal religious
groups, including Reform Judaism, already are performing such
ceremonies without sanction by their national organizations,
advocates for gay rights are hailing the expected vote by the
Central Conference of American Rabbis as a milestone in the
struggle by gays and lesbians for acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over how to treat gay and lesbian couples is one of
the hottest social issues currently vexing not only Judaism, but
also a number of Christian denominations. Later this year the
Episcopal, Presbyterian and United Methodist churches each are
expected to debate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gays and lesbians . . . have been subjected to implicit and
explicit signals from society, including religious groups, that
they were in some way sinful, not healthy, abnormal,'' said Rabbi
Paul Menitoff, executive vice president of the Central Conference
of American Rabbis, which represents 1,800 Reform clergy. ``This
kind of resolution being passed by a major religious group will
send a signal that will be important to Jewish gays and lesbians
and beyond, a signal that they're not viewed as sinful, but as
normal, healthy people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reform movement, the largest in American Judaism, has taken
the lead on liberalizing both ritual and political practices.
</P>
<P>
   Most states have now banned gay marriages, but Vermont lawmakers
are poised to define a new legal status called civil unions for
gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the primary reasons people do not support same-sex
marriage as a public policy matter is because of deeply held
religious views,'' said David M. Smith, communications director for
the Human Rights Campaign, a Washington-based gay rights group.
``As religious institutions support civil unions, it helps dispel
some of the mythology and take away some of the fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The rabbis' resolution is vaguely worded, and is still being
modified to acknowledge the concerns of some critics. But in the
resolution, which Menitoff said he expects to pass, the rabbis
resolve that same gender relationships are ``worthy of affirmation
through appropriate Jewish ritual'' and it calls on the rabbis'
organization to develop educational and liturgical resources for
same-gender ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution does not require rabbis to perform ceremonies,
nor does it specify what kind of ceremony might be performed, but
rabbis say the ceremonies already being performed range from the
simple blessing of a new home, to a makeshift commitment ceremony,
to a full-fledged wedding with the traditional recitation of seven
blessings, exchange of vows under a canopy, and the smashing of a
glass.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution allows each rabbi to decide whether to officiate
at a ceremony and calls on other rabbis to support such decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Reform rabbis have been engaged in heated debate via several
Internet discussion groups; some have threatened to walk out of
next week's meeting during the vote, while others are discussing
the formation of a traditionalist caucus within the Reform rabbis'
organization to advocate for conservative standards on conversion,
dietary practices and same-sex relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Already, an estimated 500 Reform Jewish rabbis and numerous
United Church of Christ ministers are performing same-gender
ceremonies without fear of reprisal from their national
organizations, and in eastern Massachusetts Episcopal Bishop M.
Thomas Shaw is authorizing same-sex ceremonies on a case-by-case
basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Unitarian Universalist Association, a religious organization
that does not profess a particular set of theological beliefs,
voted to endorse same-sex marriages in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In some other denominations, individual clergy have performed
same-sex ceremonies but some have been fired or otherwise
disciplined as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church is actively involved in the fight
against gay marriage, and last year the Vatican ordered an end to a
ministry to gays by an American priest and nun. The United
Methodists last year found two ministers guilty of violating church
law for blessing a gay marriage but then this year dismissed a
complaint against 68 ministers who officiated at a ceremony for a
lesbian couple.
</P>
<P>
   Within each church the issue of how to treat gays and lesbians
is hotly disputed. The three Protestant denominations, Episcopal,
Presbyterian and United Methodist, that take up the issue this
year, will be debating a variety of resolutions on policies
affecting gays.
</P>
<P>
   Next week's vote by the Central Conference of American Rabbis, a
111-year-old association, comes 10 years after the same group
endorsed ordination of gays and lesbians. In 1972, the Reform
movement became the first Jewish denomination to ordain women.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time the Reform movement came around to ordaining
women, lots of Protestant denominations had been ordaining women
for a long time, and American society had become so egalitarian
there was a sense one was catching up with the larger culture,''
said Jonathan D. Sarna, a professor of American Jewish history at
Brandeis University. ``But the larger culture is still divided on
the issue of gay marriages, and as a result this issue is more
divisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay Jews are welcoming the expected vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Jew, I really wanted to bring in the rituals that have
been important to me my whole life _ as I was bat mitzvahed and
confirmed, I wanted to have a wedding,'' said Tamara Indianer, 32,
of Arlington, Mass., who had a Jewish wedding with another woman.
``Although my partner and I have since split up, it was very
important to me to have my friends and family support our union as
I supported their heterosexual unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Margie Chebotariov, 39, of Miami Beach, agreed. The daughter of
a conservative cantor, she said she wanted Jewish ritual to be part
of her relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every bit of support we can get on any level, especially on a
religious level, is important,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that the resolution violates the teachings of
the Torah, is out of step with American public opinion, will harm
nascent Reform Jewish movements in Israel and Russia, and will
undermine rabbis who do not want to perform interfaith heterosexual
marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Other Jewish movements are unhappy with the Reform rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sanctification of a marriage between two people of the
same sex would not be appropriate,'' said Rabbi Jerome M. Epstein,
executive vice president of The United Synagogue of Conservative
Judaism. ``The Torah clearly prohibits that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Steven M. Dworken, executive vice president of the
Rabbinical Council of America, which represents Orthodox rabbis,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible mistake because they're separating
themselves from that which has been normative Jewish practice since
the beginning with Adam and Eve,'' Dworken said. ``This
sanctification of same-sex unions unfortunately establishes a
tremendous rift between the traditional segments of Judaism and the
Reform movement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
