A6235 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FLY-DECIPHERED-BOS &LR;      03-23 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLY-DECIPHERED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS DECIPHER GENES OF CRUCIAL FRUIT FLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the aid of powerful supercomputers, scientists have rapidly
deciphered the entire genetic blueprint for the common fruit fly,
the most complex organism yet decoded and a major milestone along
the road to understanding all human genes.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough underscores how quickly genetic research has
advanced in just a few years, as researchers moved up the
evolutionary ladder from identifying all the genes in lowly
bacteria to the more complex fruit fly. Now, the same researchers
who decoded the fly predict they'll decipher the human genome by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Purely as a technical feat, the deciphering of some 180 million
individual units in the genetic message of Drosophila melanogaster
is a major achievement, taking less than a year from start to
finish.
</P>
<P>
   But understanding the fruit fly, a work horse of genetic
research, has great value in itself. Because so many of the fly's
genetic functions closely parallel those of humans, the trove of
information will be of enormous value in studying human health and
disease, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a phenomenal milestone,'' said Dr. Francis Collins,
director of the National Human Genome Research Institute. The fly
genome _ its complete set of genes that is carried in every cell _
is the largest yet deciphered, and only the second animal, the
first being a worm.
</P>
<P>
   A creature's genome, or complete genetic blueprint, contains all
the genes and the chromosomes on which the genes are located. The
fruit fly, researchers said Thursday, has 13,601 genes compared to
an estimated 50,000 to 100,000 genes in the human genome. Taken
together, these genes comprises all the information for making
proteins which build and operate the body.
</P>
<P>
   One scientist who studies fruit fly development said the
achievement ``marks the end of a century of gene hunting and
heralds a new era of exploration and analysis.'' The researcher,
Thomas B. Kornberg, a biochemist at the University of California in
San Francisco, said that in the past several years, the
unanticipated genetic similarities between fruit fly and man ``have
really shocked people.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, it's been shown that alcohol will make
prevously sober fruit flies drunk and they will pass out. But with
repeated exposure, the flies learn to tolerate alcohol and even
exhibit withdrawal symptoms, suggesting very close metabolic
similarities to humans.
</P>
<P>
   The publication of the fly sequence in the current journal
Science also amounts to a vindication of the bold gene-reading
approach of J. Craig Venter, whose company Celera Genomics was a
key collaborator in the project. Called ``whole-genome shotgun,''
the method is faster than standard methods and the speedy
production of the fly sequence showed that it works.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome depended on Celera's hundreds of supercomputers that
were used to assemble millions of bits of DNA he created by
breaking up the fly's genome into fragments small enough to
decipher. Some biologists had questioned whether, even with the
supercomputers, the genome data could be pieced back together with
sufficient accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, the government genome chief, who previously was
skeptical of Venter's approach, said that the results ``show that
the `whole shotgun' approach can be successfully applied'' to a
creature as complex as the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Venter and Celera, based in Rockville, Md., are also using the
whole-genome shotgun method as they race with the government's
Human Genome Project in deciphering the human DNA message, which is
about 30 times bigger than that of Drosophila.
</P>
<P>
   However, the government agency and the private company have
publicly feuded over how Celera's genome data would be made public.
As a result, the two sides so far are going their separate ways
instead of collaborating.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Genome Project led by Collins says it will have a
``rough draft'' of the human genome deciphered by June. Celera,
which claims to have about 95 percent of the human sequence, says
it will finish it by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration between Celera and scientists led by Gerald
Rubin at the University of California in Berkeley, a noted fruit
fly researcher, involved dozens of investigators in several
countries. The paper in Science reporting on the sequencing project
listed nearly 200 authors. The main authors are Mark D. Adams and
J. Craig Venter of Celera, and Rubin, who heads the Berkeley
Drosophila Genome Project.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said in a statement that the ``unique collaboration''
between Celera in the private sector and the University of
California at Berkeley and Baylor University in the academic world,
was hugely successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a complete Drosopohila genome 18 months sooner and
millions of dollars cheaper than anyone expected,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with publication of the sequence, the data itself has been
put into a public database that can be accessed at no charge,
Celera gave companies who paid a subscription fee an early look at
the data last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2012EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
