<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-USAIR-UNION-570&AMP;ADD-N     03-23 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAIR-UNION-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN TO THE WIRE, US AIRWAYS AND UNION TRY TO RESOLVE CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass., Pa., N.C.)   (rk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a strike deadline set for 12:01 a.m. Saturday, US Airways
and its flight attendants were locked in talks Thursday in
Washington that are aimed at reconciling the airline's goal of
reducing its high operating costs with the union's push for a pay
increase.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the union, the Association of Flight Attendants,
said progress was slow, with many big issues still unresolved. The
two sides have agreed not to discuss details of the talks, but
industry analysts said the remaining sticking points included wages
and the airline's push to tighten work rules.
</P>
<P>
   The labor dispute has already hurt US Airways as the threat of a
strike has cut into its airline ticket sales. A strike would
undermine customer loyalty and hurt the airline's bottom line,
jeopardizing the ambitious strategy of Stephen Wolf, the company's
chairman, to steadily expand US Airways into a top-notch player
while reining in its costs, which are the highest per seat mile
among the major carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are very high,'' said Philip Baggaley, an airline
analyst with Standard &AMP; Poor's. ``This is the last major labor
group they need to settle with.''
</P>
<P>
   The union representing the airline's 10,000 attendants has
threatened a partial strike that would disrupt 49 of the carrier's
most heavily traveled routes. Fearing that the union's tactics
would wreak havoc and strand thousands of passengers, US Airways
has said that it will shut down operations if no tentative
agreement is reached by midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts say a shutdown could reduce revenue by $25
million to $30 million a day. Then the company would face
significant costs in carrying out its promise to continue paying,
as long as feasible, the salaries of more than 30,000 employees who
are not flight attendants. To help weather a confrontation, the
company recently drew down a $500 million credit line.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest disruption would occur in the East, where US
Airways, the sixth-largest carrier in the nation, controls more
than one-third of the region's market share. It runs a New
York-Boston-Washington shuttle, and its three major hubs are
Pittsburgh, Philadelphia and Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Several industry analysts said there was a good chance of a
strike because the company was demanding cost restraints at the
same time that flight attendants were angry about not having
received a raise in four years. Their last contract expired in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the flight attendants might hesitate to walk out
because many workers in the airline's other unions were upset that
the attendants might turn down a contract similar to those that
they have already accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Not embracing the flight attendants' cause, Roy Freundlich,
spokesman for the airline's branch of the pilots union, the Air
Line Pilots Association, said the pilots were neutral in the
dispute. He added, however, that the union would hold management
responsible for any ill effects caused by the company's threat to
shut down.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways said Thursday that it had arranged for other airlines
and Amtrak to honor its tickets if its operations are shut down on
Saturday. The airline advised customers holding electronic tickets
to call US Airways or a travel agent, or to go to a US Airways
counter to get their tickets reprocessed, either electronically or
on paper, so they will be accepted at other airlines. Customers
holding a Dividend Miles award ticket should call US Airways.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In previous rounds of bargaining, Wolf vowed to shrink the
airline if the unions insisted on high-cost contracts. His threats
helped persuade the three other major unions _ the pilots, the
mechanics and the ticket agents _ to sign a contract without
significant disruption.
</P>
<P>
   These agreements have enabled Wolf to move steadily to expand
the airline since he took its helm in 1996. He has agreed to buy
400 new planes, has expanded routes to Europe and has set up a
system of low-cost regional carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle to long-term growth, company officials say,
is its high cost structure. Merrill Lynch estimates that US
Airways' cost per available seat mile is 12.96 cents, compared with
9.72 cents at United, 9.44 cents at American, 8.88 cents at Delta
and 7.56 cents at Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Murphy, an analyst with Morgan Stanley, said the airline's
high costs were a carry-over from the smaller airlines that were
combined to form US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legacy of inefficiency from prior management, from
Allegheny, Piedmont, a management mentality before Steve Wolf of
running the airline for employees and not the shareholders,''
Murphy said. ``You cannot compete with companies like Southwest
when that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the company's record profits, in 1997 and 1998, the
flight attendants have demanded a substantial raise but have not
publicly disclosed the amount. In response, officials say the
company's financial picture has soured, noting that in the second
half of 1999 the airline lost nearly $160 million because of
soaring fuel costs, hurricanes and a maintenance slowdown. The
attendants' pay ranges from $17,145 to $36,918 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The airline is pressing the flight attendants to accept the same
formula its other unions accepted. That would link the attendants'
pay to the average of their counterparts at the nation's four
largest airlines plus 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The union's negotiators have balked at accepting this formula,
saying it would reduce their wages and benefits by 5 percent. In a
letter on the union's Web site, Lynn Lenosky, president of the
flight attendants' branch at the airline, said, ``While we don't
necessarily object to the term parity, we object to management's
attempts to force an unfair parity formula upon the flight
attendants.''
</P>
<P>
   She said management wanted the attendants to use the same
formula as the pilots, but she insisted that the formula should be
adjusted for the attendants because they do very different work.
Because US Airways has so many short routes, she said, attendants
typically serve 36 percent more passengers an hour than the
attendants at the four largest airlines: United, American, Delta
and Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling a narrowing of differences, the airline sent its
employees an electronic bulletin Thursday night saying that it was
offering the flight attendants alternative ways to calculate the
parity formula, while still achieving the company's goal of
remaining cost-competitive with the major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But company officials say they fear that other unions will
object if the attendants receive a better formula. In a letter to
employees last month, Wolf said, ``If the flight attendants were
paid above parity plus 1 percent, other employee groups could
rightfully ask for the same treatment, and the company would again
return to significantly uncompetitive labor costs across the
board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
