<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RUDY'S SECRET STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rudy Giuliani's plan for winning the Senate race is
now becoming very clear. He's going to drive New Yorkers so crazy
they'll vote for him just to get him out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the city thrilled to reports that the mayor had ended
his boycott on meeting Harold Levy, the interim schools chancellor.
Having already driven two chancellors out of town shrieking,
Giuliani wanted the school board to hire a businessman who
understood management principles. Levy is a Wall Street executive
who understands management principles. However, he was not the
mayor's idea. Therefore Giuliani refused to speak to him when he
was appointed in January. When Levy reached out, the mayor declined
to come to the phone.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers have come to regard stuff like this as normal, like
a wife so inured to a dysfunctional marriage that she no longer
thinks it is unusual when her husband requires her to stand at
attention while he eats dinner, and serve his peas in even-numbered
portions.
</P>
<P>
   We respond to any concessions _ like talking to the schools
chancellor _ with incredible gratitude. (Thirty-seven peas? Oh
dear, so kind of you to eat them anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   During the crisis over a police shooting of an unarmed black man
last year, the city was loud in its applause when the mayor reached
out to African-American officials by inviting them to breakfast at
Gracie Mansion. We had so lost track of reality, we barely bothered
to ask why the mayor hadn't been talking to these people all the
time. (That crisis, by the way, is not to be confused with the
current police shooting of an unarmed black man, nor the one before
that.)
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has turned City Hall into a fortress, with so much
security it is easier to get in to watch the U.S. Congress than a
hearing of a city council subcommittee. When we are not thanking
him for a modicum of polite behavior, we are waiting nervously for
the next outburst. The blow-ups usually come as a surprise because
Giuliani avoids face-to-face confrontations. You don't necessarily
know he's angry until he calls a press conference and denounces you
to the entire world as a terrible person.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gov. George Pataki say Giuliani has never explained
why, back in 1994, he suddenly endorsed Mario Cuomo's re-election
and sailed into an attack on Pataki, a fellow Republican whom he
had barely met. After Cuomo lost, Giuliani stopped fighting with
Pataki in public, except for a few extremely critical issues like
the renaming of a highway in honor of Joe DiMaggio. However, many
Republicans found it hard to understand why the governor cleared
the way for his Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Obvious explanation: The governor wants him out of here. No
sacrifice is too great to put him on that Washington shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Our current civic crisis involves Patrick Dorismond, who was
killed by a police officer as he walked out of a bar unarmed. We
still do not know a lot of crucial details. But we do know the
appropriate response for a mayor: This is terrible. No one should
leap to judgment over the officer's conduct. But my heart goes out
to the young man's family.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Giuliani has gotten into a long-running dispute over why
the police made Dorismond's juvenile record public. Only an
absolutely impossible person would pursue such an argument,
supporting the cops by sliming the dead person, explaining that the
records were unsealed because ``when you die, your privacy
interests end.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton is going to have a hard time overcoming this
exhaust-the-voters tactic. It might be worth it to promote the man
just to keep him from spending any more of our money on baseball
stadiums. He's committed $112 million to two minor-league parks
already, and we'll never get it back. The only bargain the city
ever got on athletics was the stadium the U.S. Tennis Association
built in Queens, leaving us with a great public facility and no
bill. The mayor, however, boycotts the place because that was his
predecessor's deal.
</P>
<P>
   And now it all makes sense. Giuliani is running not on what
he'll do in Washington, but what he'll stop doing in New York. And
there are so many impossible men in the Senate already, nobody
would even notice he's there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
