<SLUG> BC-INDIA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RURAL WOMEN TELL CLINTON OF THEIR RISE TO EMPOWERMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAYLA, India _ Ringing a flower garland around President
Clinton's neck and tossing rose petals on his head, dozens of farm
women clad in everyday dresses of rainbow-colored cotton welcomed
him to a dusty village in northeastern India Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Showing him a face of the nation a world apart from the halls of
Parliament in New Delhi or the high-tech office parks of India's
Silicon Valley, the women clapped hands to the beat of turbaned
drummers, danced and sang of doing daily chores that begin with
grinding wheat at 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grind and I grind until my knees ache, yet there is no
dignity for my work,'' the women sang. ``Awaken, women of my land!
It's time we empower ourselves!''
</P>
<P>
   Their stories contrasted with the common image of rural Indian
women as uniformly downtrodden and oppressed, denied education and
political rights, and passively accepting their woeful state as
their karma, or destiny.
</P>
<P>
   While still true of some, that monochromatic vision is outdated.
As Clinton learned, growing contact between cities and villages,
concerted efforts of Indian development agencies, and the election
of numbers of women to local councils have resulted in even many
unschooled females are empowering themselves economically,
politically, and most of all, psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   They have formed agricultural cooperatives and raised funds to
give small loans to women starting modest businesses. They have
battled for equal pay for equal work. They have demanded education
for children who previously labored in factories. They have run for
village posts and won, crusading for clean water and schools. They
have even persuaded some families not to marry off their children
before age 18.
</P>
<P>
   A typical story Thursday was that of Batto Devi, whose husband
died a few years ago, leaving the illiterate woman with no means to
support herself and her two children. Her in-laws tried to force
her to marry her husband's younger brother, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1984, Batto Devi was chosen for a women's development
program sponsored by the government of the state of Rajasthan, long
considered one of the most backward in India. Perhaps because of
its reputation for extremely low female literacy rates and
occasional incidents of ``sati,'' the illegal practice of burning
widows on their husbands' funeral pyres, Rajasthan has worked to
train Batto Devi and other women about their rights and how to
fight for them.
</P>
<P>
   She began working on a road building site, but soon learned that
the 25 cents a day that she and other women were being paid was
just half the minimum wage for men doing the same work. Batto Devi
fought until salaries were equalized and, for 13 years, she has
been a roadwork supervisor, a position once held only by men. In
her spare time, she has organized night schools and child care for
her employees.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 200 women in her cooperative, and they share
$1,500 in shared assets, which they loan to any member for small
business projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are small amounts, but they suit our needs, and we are
very happy,'' said Batto Devi, 35, of Dangarwada village. ``We
believe men and women are equal . . . and I will strive for greater
awareness among women of Rajasthan.''
</P>
<P>
   One group of women who formed a dairy cooperative in nearby
Dhoblai village demonstrated a computerized milk measuring machine
they bought to automatically calculate the fat content, volume, and
payment owed to each farmer. They also described an attempt by a
group of men to take over their franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that no matter what, we wouldn't let the men (do
that), because by rights, it was ours,'' said Santosh Chaudhary,
49, of Gokulpura. She said the women underpriced their competitors
till the men ``had to flee the village. I tell many women in
similar situations that they don't have to suffer in silence. They
can fight for their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The women gave the president his own membership card in their
cooperative. Moved, he replied, ``I grew up in a place with many
dairy cows, and I know what hard work is, and I will always
treasure this. I will put this up in the White House so everyone
will know I came here and what you are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   A male villager asked Clinton if he agreed with ``the
stereotypical image of Indians all over the world as backward
people,'' now that he had been in India for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said no, adding that ``if in India you can prove that
people can lift themselves from poverty. . .end discrimination
against women. . .and learn to work together across tribal and
caste lines because of democracy, you will give the world the
greatest gift it could have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
