<SLUG> BC-CAR-CARNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCREASED BACKING GIVES CAIN FULL RIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIMOTHY HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  Caution was the catchword in Saturday's NASCAR Winston West
Series season opener at Phoenix International Raceway. By the end
of the NAPA Auto Parts 100, nine caution flags slowed 39 laps of
the race.
</P>
<P>
   For Bill Sedgwick of Acton, the last caution was a blessing. For
Jerry Cain of Canyon Country, it was a black cat.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick, a lap down with about 10 to go, had just pitted to get
four new tires. When he got back on the track, he caught and passed
race leader and eventual winner Kevin Richards to get back on the
lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   Then disaster struck and Cain was caught in the middle of it. A
crash on lap 92 took out the third- through seventh-place cars,
including Cain's, and allowed Sedgwick to catch the lead pack. As a
result, Sedwick finished sixth, and Cain dropped to 23rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if everything's perfect, you still need Lady Luck to push
you over the top,'' Cain said. ``We had a top-three car until the
melee broke out.''
</P>
<P>
   But the weekend wasn't a total loss. With the strong race,
Cain's main sponsors, Puget Sound and Consumer Savings, and others
increased their funding of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Cain was able to add three more cars to his team and make a
commitment to race the entire 12-race Winston West season. Before
Phoenix, Cain was uncertain if he would be able to race the whole
season.
</P>
<P>
   With five Chevy Monte Carlos in his stable, Cain is looking
forward to this weekend's Coors 200 at Mesa Marin Raceway in
Bakersfield. As a NASCAR Super Late Model driver there, Cain was
consistently in the top 10 at weekly races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict that we will be in the top five in qualifying,''
Cain said. ``and if we don't crash, we will finish in the top
five.''
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series and the Featherlite Southwest
Series will join the Winston West Series at Mesa Marin this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tune in: NASCAR and Speedvision, a 24-hour cable network that
covers motor sports, announced plans to televise eight Winston West
Series races this season.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the broadcasts will be three events at Irwindale
Speedway. The others are two events at Mesa Marin Raceway in
Bakersfield and one each at Evergreen Speedway in Monroe, Wash.,
Portland Speedway in Oregon and Rocky Mountains Raceways near Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The Irwindale Speedway events will be the Home Depot 250 on June
24, the Home Depot 250 on Aug. 19 and the Home Depot 300 on Nov.
11, which will also be the Winston West season finale.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Winston West Series race at California Speedway on
April 29 is scheduled to be broadcast on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to growth in recent seasons, the series has
experienced an increased level of competition,'' said Tom Deery,
NASCAR vice president. ``This television coverage will allow fans
across the country an opportunity to view the intense competition
in the series. And it will allow these drivers to showcase their
talent to a national audience, while providing tremendous added
exposure to the teams and their sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Leader of the pack: NASCAR Busch Grand National Series driver
Ron Hornaday Jr. continued his streak as the top-finishing rookie
with his performance in Saturday's SunCom 200 event at Darlington
Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday, from Palmdale, has been the top-finishing rookie in
four consecutive Busch series events. He holds a 20-point lead in
the rookie standings. Kevin Harvick of Bakersfield and Jay Sauter
each have 44 and are tied for second in the rookie race.
</P>
<P>
   His eighth-place finish was histhird top-10 showing of the year
and placed him sixth in the season standings. Matt Kenseth leads
the series with 823 points. Mark Martin, who won the SunCom 200 and
his third race in five Busch events, is second with 725. Hornaday
has 641.
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Busch Grand National Series schedule is on
Saturday for the Cheez-It 250 at Bristol Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ventura action: Ventura Raceway held its second set of races
Saturday with VRA Sprints, IMCA Modifieds, VRA Pony Stocks and I-4
Modifieds.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Moody of Ventura won the VRA Sprints main. Rich Wolfe of
Studio City won the IMCA Modifieds main. Todd Keeter of Ventura won
the Pony Stocks main. Bryan Weaver of Ventura won the I-4 Modifieds
main.
</P>
<P>
   Racing continues April 1 with VRA Sprints, IMCA Modifieds,
Street Stocks and Pony Stocks. Gates open at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Irwindale revs up: Irwindale Speedway opens its 2000 season
on Saturday with a set of division races that will include the Home
Depot 100 for the NASCAR Super Late Models. Grand American
Modifieds, NASCAR Late Models and Super Stocks will also race.
</P>
<P>
   Gates open at 5 p.m. and racing starts at 7 p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
