<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE 3-MINUTE CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; In Geneva on Sunday President Clinton will be meeting with
Syria's president, Hafez Assad. Here's how I imagine the dialogue
will go:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton: ``Hafez, it's good to see you again. When you were
younger you were renowned for giving presidents and diplomats
12-hour lectures on the history of Syria. Neither of us has the
energy for that anymore, so I'm going to be very brief. This summit
should take just three minutes, because I have only three
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``First: Are you still in charge? Now don't be insulted by that.
Those idiots in the White House press corps ask me that all the
time. I know you're still president, but there are a lot of rumors
about your diabetes and memory loss _ so would you mind doing 20
push-ups for me and naming the last six U.S. presidents you dealt
with? (Assad starts doing push-ups on the floor and naming U.S.
presidents.) Good. Good ... No, no, Nixon came before Reagan, but
that's close enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, Hafez, health isn't your only weakness. We both
know that your authority has been challenged by the fact that you
haven't been able to win acceptance _ from your army, Baath Party
or Alawite community _ for your son Bashar to become your
successor. Why do I care? Because the Israelis are used to thinking
about Syria as a one-man regime, in which you could decide
everything. If that's not the case anymore, then you're just like
Ehud Barak _ more so than either of you would admit. And if you're
both in the same position, you're going to have to protect each
other from the political risks involved in any Syrian-Israeli peace
treaty. I need to make sure you both understand that before I go
any further.
</P>
<P>
   ``My second question is: Are you ready to offer the Israelis
something more than just a legalistic peace? Hafez, you can't
persuade the Israeli public _ and it's the public there that
ultimately will decide _ to give up as important a strategic asset
as the Golan Heights while you treat them like lepers. You have to
signal Israelis that there is something new in the Syrian attitude
toward them as a people. Because if you're just offering the
Israelis the same old Syrian hostility _ but without the Golan _
well, they may just prefer to keep the Golan, with your hostility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hafez, it doesn't take much. If you do the right thing, and
come up with the security arrangements Barak needs, the Israeli
public will endorse this deal for one big reason: because you've
agreed to let Israelis drive across Syria to Europe. For Israelis,
peace with Egypt was the gateway to the Sahara. But peace with
Syria, wow, that's the gateway to Europe. Psychologically, for
Israelis to know that they could drive to Istanbul and Athens
anytime they wanted ... well, you just can't imagine how important
that is to a people bottled up for so long. You'll make more money
from speeding tickets than you ever made from oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``But before we get too warm and fuzzy here, Hafez, let me ask
question three: Do you understand what will happen if you don't
make this deal? Syria has been able to survive as a rogue state,
even after the collapse of your Soviet backers, because you had
some oil, which is now running out, and because you were one of the
all-time great rogues. But Hafez, your son Bashar, the eye doctor,
he's no rogue. And a rogue state without a rogue leader or oil
won't last. You'll be Albania. Now, we're trying to restore ties
with Iran. It will take time. But if we break through with Iran,
before Syria makes peace, who needs you? Moreover, the Israelis
will unilaterally withdraw from Lebanon, and leave your army there
_ exposed as the sole occupier of Lebanon. So your choices are
clear: peacemaker with Israel or occupier of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you opt for peacemaker, well, I'm no eye doctor like your
son, but I can sure fix how the world would look at your country. I
don't have the clout to get you any aid money from Congress, but I
know a little bit about raising money from Asians, and we'll get
Japan and Europe to help you pay for peace. So there you have it,
Hafez. Three questions, three minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad: ``Bill, I will be even more brief. I am strong and I am
ready. But remember: I need all our land back in exchange for
peace. I'm not going to be the first Arab leader who gives the
Israelis an inch _ not one inch. Do you and Barak understand that?
Are you and he strong enough for such a deal? Are you ready?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
