<HEADLINE>
YOUR NUTRITION I.Q.
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With television quiz shows so popular, we thought we'd try a
quiz of our own. Regis won't be reading the questions, but you can
have as many lifelines as you like. There's no $1 million prize at
stake, simply your health, which should be worth at least that much
- or more.
</P>
<P>
   Designed with a little help from the American Dietetic
Association and its book, ``Complete Food &AMP; Nutrition Guide'' by
registered dietitian Roberta Larson Duyff (Chronimed Publishing),
plan to gather a few friends or relatives and put them to the test.
See how far they get. For fun, keep score so participants can
assess their nutrition savvy.
</P>
<P>
   And when you're in the mood to challenge yourself even more (or
have additional questions), turn to ADA's Hotline at (800)
366-1655, or go to its Web site, www.eatright.org (which is linked
to other nutrition and health Web sites).
</P>
<P>
   Now are your ready for the first question? The final answers are
on Page 4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. According to the Food Guide Pyramid, a serving of meat is
approximately the size of:
</P>
<P>
   a) a deck of cards
</P>
<P>
   b) a softball
</P>
<P>
   c) a paperback book
</P>
<P>
   d) a matchbox &QL; 
2. The calcium content of fat-free milk is the same as whole milk.
TRUE OR FALSE.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
3. Brown bread has more fiber than white bread. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
4. Irradiation zaps the nutrients from food. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
5. A food that is labeled 98 percent fat-free contains only 2
percent of its total calories from fat? TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
6. Fresh fruits and vegetables contain more nutrients than canned
or frozen. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
7. Which has the most vitamin C?
</P>
<P>
   a) 1 cup strawberries
</P>
<P>
   b) 1 medium kiwi
</P>
<P>
   c) 1 medium nectarine
</P>
<P>
   d) 1 medium apple
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
8. Which has the least fat?
</P>
<P>
   a) 1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   b) 1 tablespoon margarine
</P>
<P>
   c) 1 tablespoon peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   d) 1 tablespoon apple butter &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
9. How long can food be safely left out of the refrigerator?
</P>
<P>
   a) 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   b) 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   c) 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   d) 6 hours
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
10. Peanuts have no cholesterol. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
11. What is the recommended daily quota of fiber?
</P>
<P>
   a) 10 to 20 grams
</P>
<P>
   b) 20 to 30 grams
</P>
<P>
   c) 30 to 40 grams
</P>
<P>
   d) 40 to 50 grams &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
12. Both fat and cholesterol are found in:
</P>
<P>
   a) foods of animal origin, such as pork, chicken, fish, beef,
milk, butter and eggs
</P>
<P>
   b) foods of both plant and animal foods like those listed above,
and oils, like olive or canola oil, and avocado.
</P>
<P>
   c) large quantities in seafood
</P>
<P>
   d) none of the above &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
13. The key to healthy eating is:
</P>
<P>
   a) variety
</P>
<P>
   b) balance
</P>
<P>
   c) moderation
</P>
<P>
   d) all of the above
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
14. Cottage cheese is a great source of calcium. TRUE OR FALSE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
15. Fat supplies more than twice the calories per gram (9 calories)
of carbohydrates and protein (4 calories). TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
16. One teaspoon of salt contains about 3,500 milligrams sodium.
TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
17. To keep the body running normally, the minimum amount of sodium
considered safe and adequate for healthy adults is 500 milligrams
daily, or the amount in 1/4 teaspoon salt. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
18. According to the Food Guide Pyramid, the following would be
considered one serving in the Fruit Group:
</P>
<P>
   a) 3/4 cup fruit juice
</P>
<P>
   b) 1 medium orange, apple, peach or banana
</P>
<P>
   c) 1/4 cup dried fruit
</P>
<P>
   d) 1/2 cup cut-up, cooked, canned or frozen fruit
</P>
<P>
   e) all of the above
</P>
<P>
   f) none of the above &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
19. Snacking makes you fat. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
20. Brown eggs are more nutritious than white eggs. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
21. The Food Guide Pyramid gives a range of servings; the number
you eat depends on the amount of energy you need daily, age,
gender, health status and level of physical activity. TRUE OR
FALSE. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
22. Nutritionists generally recommend a maximum of what percentage
of dietary calories from fat?
</P>
<P>
   a) 10 percent
</P>
<P>
   b) 30 percent
</P>
<P>
   c) 45 percent &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
23. Fifty-five percent to 60 percent of your energy should come
from carbohydrates, mostly from complex carbohydrates and the rest
from sugar. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
24. Carrots are an excellent source of vitamin A, but you don't
care for them. Good substitutes would be (select as many as would
apply):
</P>
<P>
   a) sweet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   b) mangoes
</P>
<P>
   c) orange juice
</P>
<P>
   d) spinach &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
25. Low-fat on a food label means at least 25 percent less fat (as
compared to a standard serving size of the traditional food) per
serving. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
26. Salmon is higher in fat than chicken with the skin on. TRUE OR
FALSE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
27. Olive oil and canola oil are both high in monounsaturated fatty
acids and low in saturated fatty acids. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
28. Enriched means adding nutrients to foods that weren't present
in them originally. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
29. Butter is more fattening than margarine. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. Vitamins are a good source of energy. TRUE OR FALSE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
QUIZ ANSWERS &QL; 
Check to see how you did on the quiz. If you score 24 to 30,
consider yourself a nutrition whiz; 18 to 24, you are nutrition
savvy but could brush up on some of the finer points; 10 to 15,
keep trying and learning about nutrition and food for good health.
</P>
<P>
   1. a) A deck of cards. Two to 3 ounces of cooked lean beef,
poultry with the skin removed, or fish constitutes one serving.
</P>
<P>
   2. True. The better daily choice for including calcium without
the fat is two to three servings of low-fat or fat-free dairy
products, rather than whole or full-fat dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   3. False. According to the American Dietetic Association, being
brown in color does not mean a bread is high in fiber. If the bread
ingredient list notes that it contains whole wheat or other whole
grains, then it probably has fiber. The brown color may be from
caramel coloring. Check the Nutrition Facts label for the number of
grams of fiber per serving.
</P>
<P>
   4. False. Irradiation results in minimal nutrient loss, just
like other forms of food processing, such as drying, freezing and
pasteurization. Irradiation eliminates harmful bacteria and retards
spoilage and has been approved by the FDA for use in red meats,
poultry, fresh fruits and vegetables, and flour and grain products.
</P>
<P>
   5. False. The 98 percent fat-free claim refers to the weight of
the food, not its calories. If a food is labeled fat-free, it
contains .5 grams of fat or less per serving. Read the Nutrition
Facts label for grams of fat per serving.
</P>
<P>
   6. False. There is little difference, depending on the handling
of the produce. Canned and frozen produce is generally processed at
its peak and may contain more nutrients than fresh produce.
However, canned or frozen produce may have added sugar or salt,
which should be considered when purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   7. a) 1 cup strawberries. A cup of strawberries has a whopping
85 milligrams of vitamin C - more than an orange's 80 milligrams. A
kiwi runs a close second with 75 milligrams. An apple has only 8
milligrams while a nectarine has only 7. People age 15 and over
need 60 milligrams of vitamin C a day.
</P>
<P>
   8. d) 1 tablespoon apple butter. Apple butter has no fat at all,
because it's made from naturally fat-free apples and has no added
fat. A tablespoon of butter or margarine has 11 to 12 grams fat.
White, tub and light versions have less fat - and because they are
easier to spread, you usually use less. Peanut butter has 4 grams
fat, but it's a cholesterol-free source of protein and contains 1
gram of fiber.
</P>
<P>
   9. a) Two hours. Refrigerate or freeze perishables, prepared
foods and leftovers within two hours or sooner to keep harmful
bacteria from growing and multiplying. If you're not sure about a
food's safety, toss it. When in doubt, throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   10. True. Cholesterol is only found in animal foods. Peanuts are
a plant food.
</P>
<P>
   11. b) 20 to 30 grams. Many of us eat only half the recommended
daily quota of 25 to 30 grams of fiber. You can increase the fiber
in your diet with whole grains (breads, cereals, pasta and rice),
fruits, vegetables and legumes (dried beans and peas).
</P>
<P>
   12. a) Foods of animal origin, such as pork, chicken, fish,
beef, milk, butter and eggs. The key here is cholesterol.
Cholesterol is found only in foods of animal origin. Plants do not
contain cholesterol; however, some contain significant amounts of
fat, such as vegetable oils. Many seafoods are low in fat and
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   13. d) All of the above. An eating style that promotes overall
health is based on enjoying a variety of foods from all the food
groups, eating in moderation (using fats, oils and sugar sparingly)
and balancing the kinds of foods consumed (not too much of any one
food).
</P>
<P>
   14. False. Cottage cheese supplies only 65 milligrams of calcium
in a half a cup. If you are eating it for its calcium content, try
more calcium-dense foods such as milk or yogurt, which contain 300
milligrams of calcium per 8 ounces, or 1 ounce of Cheddar cheese,
which contains 200 milligrams of calcium.
</P>
<P>
   15. True. The calorie content of any food depends on its
nutrient content - how much carbohydrate, fat and protein it
contains. A calorie is defined as a unit of energy. One gram of fat
provides 9 calories, while 1 gram of either carbohydrates or
protein supplies 4 calories.
</P>
<P>
   16. False. One teaspoon of salt contains about 2,300 milligrams
of sodium.
</P>
<P>
   17. True. Sodium is a mineral that occurs naturally in food.
Sodium helps maintain proper fluid balance, regulates your blood
pressure, transmits nerve impulses and helps your muscles relax,
including your heart muscle.
</P>
<P>
   18. e) All of the above. Eat a variety of in-season fresh fruits
- and opt for frozen, dried and canned to avoid boredom and when
the fresh counterparts are out of season.
</P>
<P>
   19. False. There is no direct link between snacking and body
weight. The issue is total calories, not how often you eat. Your
calorie or energy balance at the end of the day - based on the
number of calories you ate and the number of calories you burned -
determines whether you gain, lose or maintain weight.
</P>
<P>
   20. False. Shell color doesn't affect nutrition quality. The
color of the eggshell varies with the breed of hen.
</P>
<P>
   21. True. The Pyramid is a guideline, not a rigid prescription,
and it contains the building blocks of a healthful diet. It's
designed for all healthy males and females, young and old, age 2 or
older. The minimum serving from the five food groups supplies about
1,600 calories, which is sufficient for inactive and some older
adults. The midpoint in the number of servings suggested provides
about 2,200 calories, a good target for many children, teen-age
girls, active women and inactive men. Teen-age boys, active men and
many athletes may eat from the top of the serving ranges, or about
2,800 calories.
</P>
<P>
   22. b) 30 percent. Nutritionists recommend no more than 30
percent, which includes less than 10 percent of total calories from
saturated fats, about 10 percent from monounsaturated fats and
about 10 percent from polyunsaturated fats.
</P>
<P>
   23. True. Most of your energy should come from carbohydrates,
complex as well as simple. Complex carbohydrates or starches are
found in grains, legumes and vegetables. Sugars, the most simple
form of carbohydrate, are either naturally present in foods, such
as fruit and milk, or added. Either way, your body uses them in the
same way - to fuel body processes and physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   24. a) Sweet potatoes b) mangoes and d) spinach. For vitamin A,
eat plenty of deep yellow, orange and some dark green leafy
vegetables - and some deep yellow fruits. Try to eat at least one
serving daily. Note that although orange juice has some vitamin A,
its better nutrient assets are vitamin C and potassium.
</P>
<P>
   25. False. Low-fat means 3 grams or less of fat per serving.
Reduced or less fat means at least 25 percent less fat per serving.
</P>
<P>
   26. False. Salmon has about 185 calories and 9 fat grams per
3-ounce cooked portion compared with 190 calories and 9 fat grams
in the same portion of roasted, light-meat chicken with the skin
on. Skinless, this same portion of chicken contains about 150
calories and 3 fat grams.
</P>
<P>
   27. True. However, these oils are still 100 percent fat with 120
calories per tablespoon, so they should be used sparingly. The goal
for health is to use oils high in monounsaturated fatty acids
instead of other fats and oils.
</P>
<P>
   28. False. Enriched means adding back nutrients that were lost
during food processing. For example, B vitamins, which are lost
when wheat is refined, are added back to white flour. Fortified
means adding nutrients that weren't present originally. Milk, for
instance, is fortified with vitamin D, a nutrient that helps your
body absorb the calcium and phosphorous in milk.
</P>
<P>
   29. False. Butter and margarine both have 100 calories per
tablespoon.
</P>
<P>
   30. False. Vitamins are not a source of energy, but help convert
food to energy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
