<HEADER>
A6251 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-TPC-HNS &LR;      03-23 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Three thoughts raced through the heads of
the world's best players on opening day at golf's chamber of
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   Risk. Reward. Ker-plunk.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, there was a lot more ker-plunk than reward at the
Tournament Players Course at Sawgrass.
</P>
<P>
   Made even more cranky by a cool, gusting wind, one of the
meanest tracks in the game put player after player over its knee
and delivered a relentless spanking in the first round of The
Players Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The leader board might say Hal Sutton is at the top of golf's
best field. In truth, the real leader is the TPC.
</P>
<P>
   The dreaded island green on the par-3 17th was the primary curse
for everybody from Sergio Garcia to Tiger Woods to Tom Kite. From
young blood to blue blood to orange blood, the 17th
indiscriminately doled out double bogeys or worse.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just the famous 17th. There was a twice-hit chip
by Craig Stadler immediately after he had whiffed in the deep rough
moments before at the 12th hole. Nick Price shanked a pitch on the
same hole. Fred Couples double-bogeyed two holes on the front nine.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th hole claimed seven double bogeys. The par-4 18th had a
scoring average almost identical to that of the par-5 16th. The
average score was 76.276, more than four shots over par.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't the water, it was the thick rough that extracted
foul shots and foul language at the tournament known informally as
the fifth major.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes this golf course great,'' said Sutton after
he managed a 3-under-par 69 to lead by a shot over seven players.
``There is always that urge to test it, to see if you can do (this
or) that. The risk is there at all times, with a reward out there,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes this a major. Major championships are about
being patient when conditions get difficult on a great golf course
where there is a lot of risk/reward. It takes a lot of patience,
especially on a difficult day.''
</P>
<P>
   And they don't come much more difficult than Thursday at the
TPC.
</P>
<P>
   The wind was strong, and the greens were hard and fast. Missing
fairways meant chipping out. Missing greens meant playing for bogey
or taking a drop after taking a bath. It was a day when play was so
slow that 21 players were stopped by darkness.
</P>
<P>
   And it was that rare time when the conditions were more
intimidating than even Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of an ominous feeling going out there, because you
knew you were going to have to hit some really good shots to shoot
well,'' said Jim Furyk, who shot par-72 and was one of only a
handful of afternoon players who stayed within shouting distance of
the lead. ``You could strike some really good shots and still shoot
75 or 76.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 22 players at 80 or above.
</P>
<P>
   No. 17 was an adventure for every group. There were 41 balls hit
into the water surrounding the 17th. Some players, like John Daly
and Duffy Waldorf, found it twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew some things were going to happen, some bad things,''
said David Duval, who shot 75. ``And some of those were going to be
off of good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Duval, Furyk lives a short drive from the TPC. And he was
in awe of the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I've played it a hundred times, I've never played
it like it is this week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, who managed a routine par on the 17th, fared better than
everybody else over the course of the day. But he admitted it was a
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to get that 69, because the golf course showed
its teeth,'' he said. ``You couldn't get through without some
bogeys. You just want to stay away from the big numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton's fourth hole was a prime example of doing so. He drove
one foot into the rough and had only 120 yards to the front of the
green. But with a creek in front of the green, he wasn't going to
take any chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rough is like wire,'' he said. ``It's really gnarly
stuff. I'm looking at my lie there, and, best-case scenario, I
probably could carry the water. But if I don't, I have to get up
and down for a 5 and I've brought 6 into play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just chipped into the fairway, knocked the next one on the
green and almost made my par. I made my bogey and walked off.''
</P>
<P>
   With a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   As for the greens: When the golfers are done this weekend, they
could bring the tennis pros in for a little Wimbledon warm-up. The
balls bounce like they're yellow, fuzzy and filled with air rather
than dimpled, balata and filled with whatever technological
breakthrough is hot this week.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton went on to birdie the par-5 11th hole when he reached the
green in two with a 4-iron and two-putted, then wedged his approach
to 10 feet on the par-4 12th for another birdie. He got to 3-under
when he two-putted the par-5 16th after reaching the green in two.
</P>
<P>
   But Sutton's success was the exception. Check out the list of
players in the 80s: Garcia, Shigeki Maruyama, Bob Estes, Stadler,
Tim Herron and Phil Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Stadler had two triple bogeys on the back nine. His double-hit
chip led to one. Then, after a flop shot flopped, he hit a second
chip at No. 16 into the water behind the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to make sure I hit the second one hard enough,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods, winner of 10 of the last 16 tournaments worldwide in
which he has played, wasn't immune to the struggles. He was
cruising along at 3 under par and tied for the lead until he hit a
9-iron that got caught in the wind and came up short on the 17th,
splashing a few yards shy of the bulkhead pylons. His double bogey
left him at 1-under 71.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a little 9-iron, and I tried to hit the ball right at
the bunker and let the wind drift it over,'' Woods said. ``But it
didn't do it and it went in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even after I went in the water, I wasn't upset. Anything
in the red (under par) is good. Under these conditions, if you'd
have told me I could shoot something in the red, I'd have been
happy. I figured I'd make my double (at 17), play 18 and still
shoot a number in the red.''
</P>
<P>
   Which he did. The main thing for Woods is that he remains
solidly in the hunt to continue his dominance. The last player to
have 10 victories in a shorter period of time than Woods' recent
success was Byron Nelson, who won 11 in a row in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was survival more than anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can get your name on the leader board or close to
it in the first round, you've done your job,'' said Lee Janzen, who
shot 2-under 70 and was tied for second with six others.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, there were some cries that the course was becoming
unplayable by midafternoon, when scores ballooned the worst amid
capricious zephyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely want to keep the golf course fair, which, if
the wind keeps blowing, is going to be hard to do,'' said Billy
Mayfair.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
