</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FTOREK-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON REPLACES FTOREK AS DEVILS COACH  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Concerned by a recent slump and determined to avoid the early
playoff exit that has become a disturbing habit for them in recent
seasons, the New Jersey Devils Thursday dismissed their coach,
Robbie Ftorek, and replaced him with Larry Robinson, one of his
assistants.
</P>
<P>
   It was a drastic move by a team that has the third-best record
in the NHL and is in first place in the Eastern Conference. But it
was one that Lou Lamoriello, the team's president and general
manager, believed was necessary after watching the team lose 12 of
its previous 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was over a period of time that I thought about this because
I didn't see light at the end of the tunnel,'' Lamoriello said in a
conference call announcing the change. ``The decision was reached
because I felt we should change direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about taking such drastic action with only eight games
left, Lamoriello said he felt comfortable with the decision because
Robinson represented continuity at the coaching level. He said that
Robinson was familiar with the team and the players and added, ``It
would be too late if I waited any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's first task will be to restore to the team some
chemistry that clearly has been missing for the last month. Several
of the team's veterans were disgruntled with Ftorek, but they kept
it under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   The move reflects the franchise's misgivings about Ftorek's
ability to lead a talented team deep into the playoffs. The last
three seasons the Devils have exited the postseason earlier than
expected, losing in the second round in 1997 and in the first round
the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were acquired by the YankeeNets on March 17 for $175
million, but Lamoriello said Thursday that the new owners had
nothing to do with his decision. ``The new ownership respected the
judgments I've made,'' Lamoriello said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that the move may be the beginning of a
more hands-on approach by the YankeeNets organization.
</P>
<P>
   At a Yankee loss last week, George Steinbrenner, the New York
Yankees' principal owner, was fending of questions about the team's
poor spring training record when he said that changes would be
coming, but not with the Yankees. The inference was clearly to
other teams under the Yankee umbrella. Also, according to a Yankee
official, people in the organization have been watching tapes of
Devils games since early in the season _ just as they had studied
New Jersey Nets games before the YankeeNets merger was completed
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Playing without any consistency the last month, the Devils
(41-25-8) have shown no signs of improvement. They played with
little inspiration in losing three of their last four games. Just
as importantly, the Devils are in serious danger of losing the
Eastern Conference title to the Philadelphia Flyers, who trailed
the Devils by three points entering Thursday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello admitted Thursday that he had deliberated the
decision for several days because of the way his team had been
playing. The 5-0 loss to the Carolina Hurricanes on Tuesday must
have reinforced his conviction that a change was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson was appointed assistant coach last May, he said he
had no intention of becoming the head coach and did not want to
lurk over Ftorek's shoulder. Lamoriello said that Robinson reminded
him of that when he approached him to take over the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry reminded me that when he was hired he had no intention
to be the head coach, but I told him he was the best person to lead
the team,'' Lamoriello said. After a practice Thursday at the
Nassau Coliseum, where the Devils play the New York Islanders
Friday night, Robinson said: ``Lou said he wanted to meet with me.
I stood there with my wife and thought `Oh no. Uh-oh. Oh no.' I
thought that's what it was about.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way did I want to come here lurking to be the next head
coach,'' said Robinson, who won six Stanley Cups with Montreal and
was inducted into the Hockey Hall of Fame in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was considered a key to the Devils' winning the Stanley
Cup in 1995 when he was the assistant to Jacques Lemaire. Robinson
left the Devils to be the head coach of the Los Angeles Kings and
returned to the Devils after coaching the Kings for three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lamoriello said he had a high regard for Ftorek, who has been
with the organization for nine years, the last two as head coach,
when he amassed a record of 88-49-19. Lamoriello said Ftorek would
stay on in the organization in some capacity. ``He has the option
of staying as long as he sees fit,'' Lamoriello said.
</P>
<P>
   At practice Thursday, Devils players said that no matter who is
coaching, the burden was on them to pull out of the slump. ``It's
still up to us, the guys in this room, to get it done,'' said
defenseman Scott Stevens. ``Obviously we're going to get a little
different direction in different areas with Larry. Not a big
difference, little things, like positioning. Get things cut and dry
a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bold move with eight games left in the season,'' said
the right wing Randy McKay. ``The easy way is to point the finger
at one person. It's a drastic change and it's up to us to turn it
around.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the players accepted responsibility, there was thought
that a strain had developed between Ftorek and many of the players,
especially the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   In the first month of the season, the defenseman Ken Daneyko was
benched in St. Louis. It would have been Daneyko's 999th career
game, meaning his next one, No. 1000, would have been played at
home. But by sitting Daneyko in St. Louis, Ftorek assured that
Daneyko's milestone game would be played on the road, infuriating
Daneyko and annoying many of the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek also benched the defenseman Lyle Odelein on more than one
occasion for no apparent reason. Players said they often did not
understand Ftorek's logic, and would regularly wonder ``what
riddle,'' as they put it, Ftorek would come up with each day
</P>
<P>
   One of Ftorek's problems in recent games was that he was unable
to blend into the lineup the team's newest acquisitions, Vladimir
Malkahov and Alexander Mogilny. The two Russians simply have not
played up to expectations, especially Mogilny, who has just two
assists in his four games with the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello insisted Thursday that he had no input from players
about his decision. He said it was his ``responsibility to
recognize what was going on'' with his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
