<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LAMORIELLO IN RANGERS' FUTURE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sudden sacking of Robbie Ftorek as coach could be the
beginning of the end for the Devils' organization as their
loyalists have come to know and love it, if not the beginning of
what could be Lou Lamoriello's eventual takeover of the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   And if Lamoriello does become a Lincoln Tunnel commuter, Devils
loyalists should feel free to blame George Steinbrenner and the
YankeeNets combine.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Devils third over all in the National Hockey
League with 95 points and only eight regular-season games
remaining, Lamoriello decided that the Atlantic Division leaders
had lost what he described as their ``ice discipline'' under Ftorek
during a 5-10-2 slump that hit bottom in Tuesday night's 5-0 loss
to the Carolina Hurricanes at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we were playing,'' Lamoriello said Thursday, ``I
didn't see the light.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Devils' president and general manager did see was a
hockey team stumbling through the darkness toward the Stanley Cup
playoffs, ripe for a first-round embarrassment for the third
straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to be more specific about what he meant by the loss of ice
discipline, Lamoriello stick-handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not playing up to our capabilities,'' he said. ``Whatever that
means.''
</P>
<P>
   To lead the Devils out of that darkness, Lamoriello promoted
Larry Robinson as Ftorek's successor. As a Canadiens defenseman two
decades ago, Robinson was considered hockey's heavyweight champion.
But as a head coach with the Los Angeles Kings for four seasons
between terms as a respected Devils assistant to Jacques Lemaire
and Ftorek, he inspired only one playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   When the Devils rehired Robinson last summer, hockey people
nodded knowingly.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Devils' seven-game swan dive against the Penguins
in last year's playoffs, Lamoriello now had Robinson if the Devils
sputtered. And they have.
</P>
<P>
   Moves like this have established Lamoriello's reputation as the
NHL's chess master, its most respected general manager. But this
surprising change of coaches this late in the season also involves
what looms as Lamoriello's last stand: trying to win a second
Stanley Cup for John McMullen, who has sold the Devils for $175
million to the new YankeeNets combine controlled by Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Lamoriello insisted that the YankeeNets ownership, which will
not officially take over until July, had no input in Ftorek's
firing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They,'' Lamoriello said of the new ownership, ``respect the
judgments I have made and will make until they take over.''
</P>
<P>
   But when YankeeNets does take over, Lamoriello will be a
front-office free agent _ free to retire and enjoy his reported
share of at least $25 million in the Devils' sale, free to stay
with the Devils if the new ownership is smart and offers to retain
him, free to join another team as its general manager if he is
smart.
</P>
<P>
   And why couldn't that team be the Rangers?
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers miss the playoffs for the third straight year as
they seem destined to do, the Madison Square Garden honchos might
decide that Neil Smith is expendable, especially if Lamoriello were
to show any willingness to defect to the Devils' fiercest rival.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that McMullen is a buddy of Charles F. Dolan, the
Garden impresario.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, like every other NHL club owner, knows that under
Lamoriello, the Devils not only have been a more consistent winner
_ at least during the regular season _ than the Rangers lately but
have done it with a relatively inexpensive payroll, currently a
bargain $37.6 million compared with the Rangers' wasteful $61.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Also keep in mind that Lamoriello's coaching change could
backfire. Ranger historians remember 1989, when Phil Esposito, then
the general manager, fired Michel Bergeron and took command behind
the bench for the final two games. The Rangers lost both games,
then were swept by the Penguins in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that, Esposito was gone and Neil Smith was hired.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly only 3 points ahead of Philadelphia before the Flyers'
game with the Kings' last night, the Devils play five of their
eight remaining games on the road, beginning Friday night with
back-to-back visits to the Islanders and to Toronto before going to
Pittsburgh on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But for better or for worse, Larry Robinson is now behind the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
