<SLUG> BC-U.N.-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TELLS U.N. THAT DUES PROBLEM MAY THREATEN PEACEKEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ With other countries resisting the U.S. effort
to lower its dues to the United Nations, the U.S. representative on
Thursday warned that failure to revamp the payment system could put
international peacekeeping in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1996 act of Congress, the United States stopped paying
its 31 percent assessment for peacekeeping operations, unilaterally
lowering it to 25 percent and thus falling steadily deeper into
debt. The Clinton administration also made a deal with Congress to
cut regular budget payments, from 25 percent to 22.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. envoy, Richard C. Holbrooke, now has to win agreement
from 187 other, very reluctant, nations. His chances of succeeding,
most diplomats say, are not good.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeeping, however, is supported by many nations, and the
prospect of its collapse if assessments are not restructured _ and
not just for the United States _ attracts attention.
</P>
<P>
   As he shifted the focus from regular budget dues to
peacekeeping, Holbrooke picked up some support from Russia. Before
a crucial session of the General Assembly finance committee
Thursday, the Russian representative, Sergey Lavrov, and Holbrooke
issued a joint statement saying that they had agreed ``to intensify
Russian-American cooperation in the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   But an hour later in open debate _ a session that amounted to
the full General Assembly's sitting as a finance committee _ Lavrov
joined other nations in rejecting a deal with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is open to reforming the assessment scale based on
capacity to pay, Lavrov said, adding, ``At the same time, there
should not be any doubt that the principle of real capacity to pay
is inseparable from member states' responsibility to fulfill their
financial obligations without conditions and demands.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Russia, despite its economic difficulties, paid in
full its current contribution to the regular budget and has for six
years made payments to peacekeeping budgets that exceed its annual
assessments.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese representative was more blunt, saying that although
China did not object to a review, it did question how in today's
economy the United States could ask for a reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that reform means only the lowering of the ceiling,''
said China's new representative, Wang Yingfan. He noted that the
``major contributor'' _ he did not name the United States _ is now
assessed at 25 percent of the regular budget, even though its share
of the world economy, the rough guide to assessments, is 27
percent.
</P>
<P>
   China does not pay dues equal to its share of the world economy
because it is given a discount based on the low per capita income
of its 1.2 billion people, a situation that many other governments
criticize.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's representative, Robert Fowler, speaking also for
Australia and New Zealand, suggested that members should look for
more effective ways to punish debtors. The Canadian message was pay
up first and then we can talk about changing things.
</P>
<P>
   By the United Nations' accounts, the United States owes more
than half the total $3 billion in unpaid dues.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, under huge pressure from Congress to curb
peacekeeping costs, is arguing here and around the world that
United Nations efforts in that field need to be strengthened, not
weakened, but that there will have to be a more equitable sharing
of costs. Many nations are given discounts on peacekeeping bills
based on quarter-century-old calculations. And there is no system
to update peacekeeping assessments, as there is for the general
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, some of the defects of the U.N. system are at
such a scale that they seriously threaten our core goals,
especially peacekeeping,'' Holbrooke said in his speech Thursday.
``If not corrected, they could threaten the future of the
institution itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
