A6257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-LANDERS24-COX     03-23 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LANDERS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road warriors: Lady Bulldogs welcome travel
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ With nearly 20,000 miles logged on their season
already, what's another 4,200-mile round trip for the Georgia Lady
Bulldogs?
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's ambition for a second consecutive Final Four takes a
roundabout route this weekend in the West Regional. There, the Lady
Dogs play North Carolina on Saturday night in the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   It is the longest journey of the season for the Lady Dogs, who
have been to New England, Virginia, Texas and California and to
Illinois twice in their nonconference schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, we've been taking charter flights or buses for some of
our SEC games, usually coming back the night of the game,'' Georgia
coach Andy Landers said. ``We're a little bit excited about going
back out on the road like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Dogs won the Preseason NIT in Champaign, Ill., as well
as tournaments at Maine, Houston and Long Beach State. They made a
second trip to the Midwest, losing a regular-season game at
Illinois on Jan. 2, and finished up their SEC road swing at
Kentucky and Arkansas in the same week.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, through flight delays, time in hotels, countless
communal meals and trips to malls and movie theaters, they resolved
what coaches and players conceded had been problems in team unity
the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Landers purposely wanted to take his troops on the
road to get them ready for the long haul of NCAA play in March. The
Lady Dogs have had only 11 games at home, including their first two
wins in the NCAA Tournament last weekend. The time spent away from
home has been beneficial off the court as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing out of the ordinary,'' senior forward Angie Ball
said. ``It's just being together a lot, talking and laughing and
coming up with inside jokes. We've all learned to appreciate each
other a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The correct word for it is maturity,'' Landers said. ``We had
people coming in from a lot of places and a lot of different
backgrounds, and they all needed time to get to know each other and
get comfortable with each other. They've been very professional in
how they've handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball, from Toronto, watched La'Keshia Frett, Tracy Henderson and
Kedra Holland-Corn from the bench as a freshman. The next year, the
arrival of Kelly and Coco Miller and others brought substantial
roster changes, and it took time to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably gotten to know the twins better than anybody,''
Ball said. ``When they first got here, they were so quiet, and they
really kept to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve guard Camille Murphy has taken freshman guard and
roommate Tameiko Washington of Tennille under her wings, guiding
her through the same familiarity process she went through a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling has really pulled us together more as a family
unit,'' said Murphy, who is from Syracuse, N.Y. ``If you can get
people to cooperate and like each other off the court, then
whatever you do on the court is magnified even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
