<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6258 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-IMPRESARIOS-ART-2T     03-23 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-IMPRESARIOS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRESARIOS WORKING ON THE FRINGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 Eric V. Copage, a reporter for the City Weekly section of The New
York Times, writes about culture.  
 By ERIC V. COPAGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Limor Tomer, a Juilliard-trained pianist and former
music history teacher at New York University, descended into the
dim light of the basement of Two Boots, an East Village pizzeria.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, the owners of the pizzeria had used the
basement, called the Den, sporadically for video nights and private
parties. But now Tomer, walking around the 500-square-foot space,
was evaluating it for her own use.
</P>
<P>
   She looked at the size of the sound board, the size and quality
of the speakers and the postage stamp-size stage in the corner,
then smiled. ``The room holds 50 people, but it has a comfortable
vibe,'' Tomer said recently. ``It is completely open. It doesn't
say drum-and-bass or jazz or classical. So anything could be played
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, in the brave world of new music in New York,
versatility is the key word. Tomer is one of a small but avid group
of advocates who are presenting music that falls between the cracks
of genres. It is music that won't fill 600-seat auditoriums but may
be the wellspring for mainstream music to come. Call Tomer and her
ilk downtown Diaghilevs, mini-impresarios, or settle for a less
grandiose term, music curator.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, while they usually work on a small scale, what they
do is hugely important to the artistic soul of New York. In an
environment in which culture is straitjacketed and niche-marketed
at warp speed, they are keeping in circulation its most precious
artistic currencies: experimentation, risk taking and innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these edgy impresarios have a steady venue; some are
peripatetic and, like sonic Johnny Appleseeds, move from church to
cafe to bar to basement, as well as smaller traditional venues
throughout the city, to find places for unfamiliar, often
challenging, music. They differ from nightclub bookers in that they
are not primarily trying to fill up a space. They differ from the
typical concert producer in that they are not merely signing up an
artist.
</P>
<P>
   They are on a personal mission: exposing others to the music
about which they are enthusiastic. Even when the music is not hard
to classify _ like German lieder or chamber music _ they are
putting that familiar music in unfamiliar places, and thereby
cross-pollinating audiences.
</P>
<P>
   George Steel, who is the executive director of the 685-seat
Miller Theater at Columbia University, also uses smaller venues
downtown. ``It's a wonderful period of transition in terms of
instrumentation, in terms of the amount of improvisation,'' he
said. Steel recently presented a concert by the chamber group the
Absolute Ensemble at the Flea, a 75-seat theater in TriBeCa. It
featured a chamber transcription of the Mahler Fourth Symphony with
a part for a Yamaha DX7 electronic keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   He presented the concert at the Flea because, he said, ``you can
grab a beer and go into the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The social pressure is off the audience to behave in the usual
prom-night fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel's next downtown adventure will be in July, when he
presents contemporary classical music at the Cornelia St. Cafe in
Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   David Linton, a composer specializing in electronic music, has a
somewhat different approach to curating. His idea is that
presentations should be a cross between a party and a concert, a
kind of switched-on Lilith Fair, without the feminist slant.
</P>
<P>
   The artists in his shows specialize in electronically generated
sounds, ranging from techno to Morton Subotnick-like sheets of
sound. Linton has put on shows in places like Context Studios, a
performance space, and the basement lounge at CBGB's, both in the
East Village, as well 168 Bar in Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   His SoHo loft was the original home of Sound Lab, an underground
club for electronic music. His latest curatorial project, Unity
Gain, a series of freewheeling works by composers, will be
presented the first Wednesday of every month at Galapagos, a bar
and gallery in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. Some of the composers will
show up at virtually every presentation, and others will
participate less frequently, resulting in a mix of new and old
music so that audiences will never know exactly what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   This mixing and blending of musics and audiences stems from
several factors. An increasing number of musicians feel at home in
more than one musical genre. Even a musician devoted to classical
music, for instance, cannot escape the dissonant harmonies that are
frequently found in movie soundtracks or the African music played
in the background music at an upscale coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yet audiences seem increasingly segmented, as record companies
and concert promoters stream performers into a given niche.
``People into one thing tend not to cross over into another
thing,'' said Tomer, who also curates three nights a week for the
BAM cafe at the Brooklyn Academy of Music and organizes a monthly
series of classical music at Joe's Pub at the Public Theater in the
East Village.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the growing segmentation is the price of
tickets. When $20 to $25 tickets are the cheapest seats, everybody,
musician, curator and institution alike, can feel the creeping
conservatism higher ticket prices might inspire. Conversely, when
the entrance fee is about the same as a movie ticket, musicians and
curators feel freer to experiment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, artists dedicated to their art will eventually find
places to perform, especially in today's New York City, where a
booming economy has put a new performance nook on nearly every
block. But through their passion, these music curators facilitate
exposure. Many are performers or former performers who see their
role as advocating and nurturing colleagues rather than merely
pushing acts.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of music curating in New York can be traced back,
if not to the prewar Copland-Sessions concerts, then at least to
1960, when the composer La Monte Young ran a series of concerts in
Yoko Ono's Chambers Street loft. In 1971, Rhys Chatham became the
first curator at the Kitchen, an alternative performance space then
in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   And while curators like Phill Niblock, who runs the Experimental
Intermedia concerts, Thomas Buckner of the Interpretations Series
and Jim Staley of Roulette have been active for decades, today's
curators face vastly different challenges. For years, there was
little interest from the uptown crowd. But today happenings
downtown travel uptown at warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   NBC recently opened a theater space called P.S. NBC at the Here
Arts Center in SoHo, one of the city's leading alternative
theatrical spaces. The purpose? To scout talent for the network.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, over the last several years mainstream music
institutions have noted the increased openness of their audiences
and taken steps to exploit it. Lincoln Center has used its summer
festival to explore fringier territory like ``The Electronic Ordo
Virtutum,'' a new interpretation of Hildegard von Bingen's
12th-century proto opera.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, it has turned to smaller venues _ the 600-seat John
Jay College Theater and the 500-seat New Victory Theater _ to
present more experimental productions during its regular season.
Carnegie Hall is also building a more flexible setting for music,
the Judy and Arthur Zankel Hall, to expand the kinds of programming
it presents.
</P>
<P>
   Will today's music curators and their close relationships with
artists be ennobled by alliances with larger institutions, given
greater budgets and more freedom? Or will they be made virtually
obsolete, gobbled up by mainstream venues?
</P>
<P>
   The betting is that there will always be lofts, bars and living
rooms where people working in what will always be the no man's land
of experimental music will gather. There will always be those who
take joy in seeking out relationships with fringe artists, and
midwifing a musician from obscurity to an appreciative audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's late after a performance at Tomer's Saturday Balkan Cabaret
at the Den at Two Boots. The musicians are packing, but the
audience is still lingering _ talking, basking in the
reverberations of the music. Asked what she would do if the music
she is so passionate about suddenly went mainstream, Tomer knitted
her brow and offered an idealistic response: ``If what I am
interested in becomes popular enough to support itself, if it
creates enough momentum to garner bigger institutions, then I am
gone. I will go on to the next uncharted area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
