<HEADER>
A6260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-NYT &LR;      03-23 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATORS PLAN RESPONSE TO JUSTICES' RULING ON FDA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Texas, Miss., Ariz., Mass.)   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Against long odds, antismoking advocates expect to
push next week for legislation to overturn Tuesday's Supreme Court
decision that bars regulation of the tobacco industry by the Food
and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, a Tennessee Republican who is also a heart
surgeon, said in an interview Thursday he was ``likely'' to
introduce legislation next week drawn from the 1998 bill that died
in a Senate filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Frist had drafted the part of that year's tobacco bill giving
the FDA the specific regulatory authority that the Supreme Court
ruled the agency had improperly assumed for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Reed, the White House aide who handles tobacco issues,
said that President Clinton would get involved in the issue after
his return from Asia and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed said that even though the FDA provisions of the 1998
bill had bipartisan support, it would be hard to get them through
``the current Congress,'' which he said had a ``lousy record'' on
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Republican majority leaders in both houses of
Congress Thursday reiterated their opposition to any FDA tobacco
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Michele A. Davis, an aide to Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, said
Armey believed ``the FDA already has too much power.'' John
Czwartacki, press secretary for Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi,
said Lott stood by his reaction to the Supreme Court ruling on
Tuesday, when he said the agency already took too long to get drugs
and medical procedures approved and did not need more duties.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who led the fight for
the 1998 bill, has shown little inclination to take up the cause
again. Having encountered the influence of the special interests,
especially the tobacco companies and their clout before in a $50
million campaign,'' he said on Tuesday, ``I can tell you that I'm
not optimistic that we will be able to get that done until we have
campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry advertised heavily against the 1998 bill, saying
its tax increases would not curb smoking but just make it more
expensive for the poor. Except for two Democrats from
tobacco-growing states, though, the only senators who voted to kill
the bill were Republicans, who for years have received the bulk of
contributions from the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis released Thursday by the Center for Responsive
Politics showed that pattern was continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Examining contributions reported to the Federal Election
Commission from Jan. 1, 1999, through March 1, 2000, it found that
82 percent of the industry's $2,587,106 in contributions by
political action committees and individuals and in soft money,
which can come directly from corporations, had gone to Republicans.
The GOP received $2,125,920, and Democrats received $454,936.
</P>
<P>
   A leading antismoking lobbyist, Matthew Myers, president of the
Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids, called the opposition of Republican
leaders to any legislation ``a real testament to the campaign
finance system.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Supreme Court's 5-4 decision, some industry
spokesmen have suggested that they would accept some regulation in
exchange for some kind of protection from lawsuit verdicts or
federal encouragement for their efforts to produce cigarettes less
threatening to the health of smokers.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed scoffed at that idea. ``I don't think the court's
position put the industry in any stronger bargaining position than
it was before,'' he said. ``It's still unpopular. It's still on the
ropes in court. It's still outside the political mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning the planned legislation, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts, the senior Democrat on Frist's subcommittee on
public health and a major foe of the tobacco industry, said, ``I
think it's got life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Lott's expected opposition was the main obstacle.
Otherwise, Kennedy said, ``The Senate could act quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted legislation was necessary: ``Youth smoking is a
genuine crisis. The tobacco companies are shameless in trying to
hook kids on smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Frist spoke in more measured terms. He called youth smoking
``the number one public health challenge in this country today.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that, ``If we are going to truly reduce youth smoking,
then government regulation is going to be required.''
</P>
<P>
   Frist said he wanted to talk to more colleagues and review the
court's opinions and the 1998 legislation to decide whether the FDA
was indeed the best regulatory agency for that job. But he said he
thought he was likely to reach the same conclusion he had
previously and put forward an FDA bill.
</P>
<P>
   Myers, the antismoking lobbyist, said that ``it's too early to
declare'' the legislation dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Senator Frist introduces it and moderate Republicans
support it, then there could be a real push,'' he said. ``Then it
will depend on how hard the Republican leadership opposes it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
