<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOST CONNECTED ACTOR OF ALL TIME
</HEADLINE>
  
 
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The classic six degrees of  &UR; Kevin Bacon &LR;  game presents the
challenge of connecting any actor to Bacon, the links being movies
in which both parties have appeared. For instance, writes
 &UR; Malcolm Gladwell  &LR; in ``The Turning Point'' (Little, Brown;
$24.95), &UR; O.J. Simpson &LR;  was in ``Naked Gun'' with  &UR; Priscilla &LR; 
 &UR; Presley &LR; , who was in ``Ford Fairlane'' with  &UR; Gilbert &LR;   &UR; Gottfried &LR; ,
who was in ``Beverly Hills Cop II'' with  &UR; Paul Reiser &LR; , who was in
``Diner'' with Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   On average, writes Gladwell, citing computer studies by a
scientist at the University of Virginia, actors are 2.8312 steps
from  &UR; Kevin Bacon &LR; . That makes Bacon 669th in a ranking of the
``connectedness'' of Hollywood actors.
</P>
<P>
   Among the top 15 people, with the lowest numbers of steps, are
 &UR; Robert Mitchum &LR; ,  &UR; Gene Hackman &LR; ,  &UR; Donald Sutherland &LR; ,  &UR; Shelley &LR; 
 &UR; Winters  &LR; and  &UR; Burgess Meredith &LR; , perhaps because they've each made
many movies. The No. 1 well-connected actor:  &UR; Rod Steiger &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The reason, writes Gladwell, is Steiger's range. ``He's been in
38 dramas, 12 crime pictures and comedies, 11 thrillers, eight
action films, seven Westerns, six war movies, four documentaries,
three horror flicks, two sci-fi films, a musical and more.'' He has
managed to act with everyone ``because he has managed to move up
and down and back and forth among all the different worlds and
subcultures and niches and levels that the acting profession has to
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FAVORITE FLICKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles magazine says that  &UR; Yasser Arafat &LR; 's favorite movie
is ``Pretty Woman,'' which aides say he's seen 20 times.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The Earth Island Journal has bestowed its 1999 Brown Screen
Award for the ``Least Environmentally Sensitive Film'' to ``You've
Got Mail.'' EIJ calls the movie a ``sappy celebration of franchise
fascism'' with a terrible message, that ``the death of small-town
values is inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. The  &UR; Ayn Rand &LR;  Institute says that this year's Oscar
nominees reflect a ``culture of decay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Art is the barometer of a culture,'' says senior writer
 &UR; Robert Tracinski &LR; . ``That which we view as good or great art is a
window to our most fundamental moral values and convictions. The
nominees for best picture fall, broadly, into two categories: the
`realistic' film such as `American Beauty' that depicts the essence
of human nature as depraved and amoral, and the `uplifting' film
such as `The Sixth Sense' that depicts morality as possible only in
a mystical realm.'' The Randians didn't mention ``The Cider House
Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Firat Yener  &LR; was at one of those late-night San Francisco
clubs last week when  &UR; Liza Minnelli &LR; , looking particularly
unglamorous, came in with her entourage. When no one recognized
her, the club sent minions out into the crowd to inform them that
she was there, in an effort to create the customary and expected
fuss over the diva.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; QUICK TURN-AROUND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In November, the heirs of San Francisco museum benefactor
 &UR; Madeleine Haas Russell  &LR; put up for auction some of the art she had
bequeathed to them, including  &UR; Giovanni Segantini &LR; 's ``Springtime
in the Alps,'' which had hung at the Palace of the Legion of Honor
from 1924 until recently.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, auctioned by Christie's, fetched $9.5 million, far
above its estimate of $4 million to $6 million. It was bought by
 &UR; Martin Zimet &LR; , owner of the French &AMP; Co. Gallery in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's heirs are probably gnashing their teeth at the news,
reported in the New York Times this week, that Zimet has put the
painting on sale for $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: ``Describe a movie scene that provides the best insight &LR; 
 &UR; into the relationship between the sexes.'' A: ``The scene in &LR; 
 &UR; `Bob &AMP; Carol and Ted &AMP; Alice' in which they're all ready to have &LR; 
 &UR; their supposed tryst and they all just lose it. ... I think that &LR; 
 &UR; probably sums up the relationship between men and women: the &LR; 
 &UR; bravado, the come- &LR; 
 &UR; ons, the possibilities, the fantasies and then, when it comes &LR; 
 &UR; down to it, for a lot of people, this empty experience.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sandra Bernhard &LR; , decidedly unromantic, in the Nation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
