<SLUG> BC-BKC-OKLAHOMA </SLUG>
 STATE-ADKINS-TEX 
COWBOYS' ADKINS DOES IT ALL _ QUIETLY (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desmond Mason scores and dunks. Doug Gottlieb passes. Brian
Montonati rebounds and plays defense. Glendon Alexander shoots and
makes 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State is still playing in the NCAA Tournament because
those players have blended their various skills. Joe Adkins does
all of that. The 6-1 senior guard from Oklahoma City is Oklahoma
State's silent and unnoticed most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins is a major reason why the third-seeded Cowboys (26-6)
have reached the Sweet 16, where they'll face No. 10 seed Seton
Hall (22-9) on Friday night. Top-seed Duke (29-4) plays
fifth-seeded Florida (26-7) in the other East Regional semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he gets the credit he deserves,'' Oklahoma State
assistant coach Sean Sutton said. ``He's just about our best
on-the-ball defender, night-in and night-out. He can score points,
handle the ball, make free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Adkins statistics are modest _ 11 points per game, 3.4 rebounds
per game, 4.1 assists per game. But twice he has scored 21 points
this season; three times he has had eight or more rebounds; twice
he has had nine assists. Adkins, who was named an honorable mention
All-American by The Associated Press, is the Cowboys' Mr. Fix It.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Joe comes out there, he gets something done
regardless of what it is,'' said Mason, the senior guard/forward
from Waxahachie who averages a team-best 18.3 points per game.
``There are days when he comes out and scores and there are other
days when he dishes the ball. And he's always been a good defensive
player.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first-round victory over Hofstra, Alexander held Craig
``Speedy'' Claxton to 20 points on 7-of-18 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, it's about pride,'' said Adkins, who usually
fills the role as the Cowboys' designated defender on perimeter
scorers. ``Watching film of Hofstra, I saw that Claxton had scored
40 a couple of times. I was like, `Nah, I can't let him get 40 on
me in front of all those people.' Plus, everybody is watching back
home on TV, so if I get lit up, they're going to let me know about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State is likely to need some perimeter defense against
the upstart Pirates. In two NCAA Tournament victories, Seton Hall
is shooting 52.2 percent from 3-point range. In a second-round
upset of second-seeded Temple, Seton Hall was 15-of-30 from 3-point
range.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins is not shy about shooting. He weathered a January slump
that saw him make just 28 percent of his field-goal attempts. But
in the 12 games since the calendar flipped to February, Adkins has
raised his shooting percentage to 40 percent while averaging 14.3
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   The past two seasons, Adkins has won the Mr. Clutch award
presented by the Oklahoma State coaching staff. Whether it's
game-clinching free throws or an attempt to beat the shot clock,
Adkins is the Cowboys' best option.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he brings to the table is his confidence,'' Sutton said.
``He's not afraid to take the big shot when the game is on the
line. The game is hanging in the balance and he just jumps up and
takes and makes a big shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a streaky shooter. But he never lets things effect him.
That's a great quality to have.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma State's second-round victory over Pepperdine, Adkins
hit two 3-pointers during his team's game-clinching spurt. After
the first, he did an Austin Powers-like ``Yeah, baby'' and after
the other _ set up by a sweet pump fake _ Adkins performed a
body-shake boogie.
</P>
<P>
   And after the game, the microphones and notepads crowded around
Mason, Gottlieb and high-scorer Fredrik Jonzen. Adkins was wide
open.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really worry about that,'' Adkins said of his low
profile. ``Those guys deserve all the hype because they're our best
players. I just kind of go along with the flow. We need guys who
just go out and make plays when we need them. That's why I try to
do.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
