s f BC-BIZ-HOME-GYM-ART-$ADV     03-23 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-HOME-GYM-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AT-HOME SPA, SPARING NO EXPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn., Kan., Colo.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)  
 (af)  
 By JENNIFER FREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could call Avis Gold's exercise area a home gym. But then
you could call the palace at Versailles a building.
</P>
<P>
   The glass-enclosed workout center at Gold's home in Purchase,
N.Y., has nine pieces of equipment worthy of a health club,
including the giant Trotter MG2300 multigym _ a $12,000 weight
machine with a dozen stations. The adjoining spa, done with Italian
marble mosaics, includes an eight-person hot tub (with a tiered
cedar ceiling and a screen that can be lowered for privacy), a
steam shower and counter tops of brushed nickel and granite.
</P>
<P>
   Filling 2,000 square feet, about the size of the average new
home, the gym cost about $40,000 for equipment alone, according to
Richard Miller, president of the Gym Source in Manhattan, who
supplied the machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The equipment is the cheapest part,'' Miller explained. The
spa and workout space, he added, could easily cost many times as
much.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the stationary bike stuck in a dusty corner of the
basement. Especially in wealthy suburbs, home gyms, if not all as
elaborate as Gold's, are becoming de rigueur in new construction
and common in renovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of our generation rewarding itself,'' said Valerie
San Antonio, who is in her early 40s. She built a gym on the third
floor of her Greenwich, Conn., home that is big enough for an
aerobics class. ``It's our generation trying to extend what used to
be middle age.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 18.1 million Americans exercised at least 100 days a year
in their homes in 1998, up 61 percent from 1987, according to
American Sports Data of Hartsdale, N.Y. More women, in particular,
are involved, Miller said. ``Women have always dictated what goes
into a home,'' he said. ``If a man wanted a gym a few years ago, he
usually got stuck with some small gym out of the way. Now it's
important to her. It gets a better space.''
</P>
<P>
   The availability of reasonably compact equipment built to health
club standards has furthered the trends. The Sporting Goods
Manufacturers Association reports that sales of home gym equipment
rose to $2.8 billion wholesale (roughly half the cost of retail) in
1998, from $771 million in 1988. Many home gyms are now equipped
with a television or two (his and hers), telephones, refrigerators,
stereo systems and gym equipment that can run to $50,000, though
the average is $10,000 to $15,000, plus construction or remodeling
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some are customized with punching bags for kick-boxing
enthusiasts or stock-quotation machines for Wall Streeters. The
exercise area often adjoins a sauna or steam room that can be more
elaborate than the gym itself.
</P>
<P>
   Gold's workout center, installed about four years ago and since
expanded, includes a Precor elliptical trainer _ a hot new aerobics
machine that lets users climb, step and glide without bashing their
knees. There are also jump ropes, boxing gloves, a mini-trampoline
and other gadgets. ``We're very athletic,'' said Gold, who is 41.
``We knew right off that we wanted to put a gym in our home.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Westchester County and Connecticut suburbs of New York
City, builders of custom homes that generally cost several million
dollars say 80 percent include separate, often elaborate home gyms.
``Years ago, we'd carve a room out of the basement,'' said Arnold
Karp, a builder in New Canaan, Conn. ``Now it's really become a
feature room, not one you want to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles S. Cohen, who owns a commercial real estate firm in
Manhattan, built a gym in 1995 in his 16-room mansion (with an
elevator) in Greenwich. He adds about $10,000 of equipment a year,
Miller said, most recently the Quantum Thera-Crunch device for
working those abs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no wait for machines,'' said Cohen, 48, who has at
least 25 of them. ``And there's none of the getting dressed and
undressed. Here it's a one-costume change.'' He is building another
gym in his Manhattan apartment, with an additional $30,000 of
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Silicon Valley in California, some 90 percent of new
multimillion-dollar homes include elaborate exercise areas, often
adjoining outdoor pools and hot tubs, said Jude Kirik, president of
Pacific Peninsula Architecture in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   The trend isn't confined to the coasts, though homeowners in the
heartland may not have to spend as much to have space for a gym.
When Fred Mahler, 37, a financial planner, moved into a new home in
Overland Park, Kan., four months ago, the first thing he did was to
complete a 750-square-foot gym, spending $14,000 on equipment.
``It's probably the only room that's finished,'' Mahler said.
</P>
<P>
   In their home near Telluride, Colo., with breathtaking views of
the San Juan Mountains, Harvey and Jill Roisman, 54 and 45, have
installed $50,000 worth of machines, including a virtual reality
recumbent bicycle _ with the pedals comfortably in front of the
seat, rather than below _ that simulates an 18-speed mountain bike
traveling through all kinds of terrain. When sand appears on its
screen, the bike becomes sluggish. If it hits a tree, it stops.
</P>
<P>
   Roisman's favorite machine is the WaterRower, which uses a tank
of water for resistance. ``The advantage is that you hear the swish
of water,'' said Roisman, a retired clothing manufacturer. ``It's a
little more realistic. More fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the weight scale, which does just about everything
but hide the cookie jar. It calculates users' ideal weights and
tells them whether they have gained or lost and when they have hit
highs and lows.
</P>
<P>
   But is exercising at home the best way to go? Dr. Richard Stein,
a spokesman for the American Heart Association and chief of
cardiology at the Brooklyn Hospital Center, isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   People who spend their days in tense jobs, like dealing with
irate customers at a complaint desk, might prefer the peace and
quiet of a home gym, Stein said. And many who have home gyms, like
Gold and Cohen, also have personal trainers to motivate them.
</P>
<P>
   But most exercisers seek a social environment, Stein said, where
they ``can talk to people on the exercise floor and locker room.''
He thinks much of the new equipment ends up collecting dust, the
way stationary bikes or treadmills did before them. ``Having a
commitment to meet a friend at a gym gets you over the motivational
hurdle,'' he said. ``Not a home gym.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
