<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6266 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-MAYS-$ADV     03-23 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-MAYS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCHOLARLY SHAREHOLDER ACTIVIST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Ga., Del., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Charles M. Elson tells it, he had his epiphany in 1991, while
he was teaching a class about proxy rules at Stetson University's
College of Law in St. Petersburg, Fla. He owned some stock in a
beleaguered bank _ he won't say which one _ and he used its proxy
to illustrate some points.
</P>
<P>
   When he got to the section on directors' stock holdings, ``I
stopped cold,'' Elson recalled. ``I owned more shares than they
did. I began to wonder if there was a connection between their not
owning stock and the bank's doing so badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Elson, 40, has served on blue-ribbon commissions,
written myriad papers, taught classes and served on boards, all
with an eye toward getting companies not only to pay their
directors in stock, but also to strong-arm them into investing in
the company with their own money.
</P>
<P>
   If he had his way, it would be a legal mandate. And come August,
he will have a formidable soapbox from which to argue his case. He
will be heading a new center at the University of Delaware _ in the
state that is host to the most legal incorporations in the country
_ that will provide a forum for debate on exactly what the laws on
corporate governance should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a place where the Court of Chancery can meet with
finance types, CEOs, corporate lawyers, everyone,'' Elson said.
``And maybe we'll see better laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Elson does more than talk the talk. As a director at Sunbeam in
1996, he spearheaded a move to pay its directors in shares, and to
make them buy stock. He was catapulted to fame when he led the move
to oust Albert J. Dunlap, the chief executive who had brought him
onto the board.
</P>
<P>
   Elson's Sunbeam shares, including the $100,000 worth he bought
with his own money, lost much of their value. ``I guess I'm a
guinea pig for my own theories,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Elson joined the board of Nuevo Energy, an oil
company. He has bought $100,000 worth of Nuevo shares, too.
</P>
<P>
   The other Nuevo directors are probably in for some serious
philosophical debates. ``Charles is polite and warm, but he's not
at all bashful about taking people on,'' said J. Harvie Wilkinson
III, a former professor of Elson's and a judge for whom Elson once
was a clerk.
</P>
<P>
   John Nash, president emeritus of the National Association of
Corporate Directors, said, ``Charles is truly interested in
maximizing shareholder value, and when he takes something on he
goes at it with a vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   That is almost an understatement. Ask Elson about corporate
governance _ or about litigation, wines, any of the myriad things
that inspire his passion _ and chances are that you will be treated
to an erudite, immensely entertaining dissertation on what went
before, what's happening now and what the outcome should be.
</P>
<P>
   Elson can tell you why companies stopped issuing shares to
directors in the 1920s, and how chief executives started putting
their friends on their boards soon afterward. And he can deliver a
diatribe on how this has resulted in lackadaisical board oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM, GM, American Express: Their boards all let them blow
tremendous market shares and reputational capital,'' Elson said.
</P>
<P>
   Putting opinions in historical context comes naturally to Elson.
The oldest of three sons of a wealthy Atlanta businessman, he was a
history major at Harvard University and studied law at the
University of Virginia. He had planned to be a legal historian but
was quickly seduced by what he calls ``the drama of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   A summer stint at Dewey, Ballantine in New York, combined with
volunteer work defending students against charges of misbehavior,
soured him on that idea. ``I couldn't maintain my professional
detachment defending the students, and at Dewey I was bored to
tears,'' Elson recalled.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1986, after a year as clerk for Wilkinson, Elson became a
corporate lawyer for Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell in New York. It was the
height of the takeover era, but Elson never quite bought into the
decade's money culture. In 1990, when he was nearly 30, two job
offers landed on his desk. One was to manage a hedge fund, for
$130,000 a year; the other was to teach at Stetson, for $52,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured, `I like teaching, I'm not married, Florida isn't
expensive, the worst that could happen is I'd hate it and come
back,''' he said. He piled his belongings into his brother's car
and drove south. He soon looked up some friends of his parents,
whose daughter fixed him up with Amy Kemker. They married in 1993
and had their first child, Caroline, in November.
</P>
<P>
   Elson soon began writing about director compensation. Al Dunlap
read one of his articles and invited Elson to visit him. The two
hit it off, and they remained friends until Elson engineered
Dunlap's ouster from Sunbeam. ``He hasn't spoken to me since,''
Elson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap has said he viewed Elson's actions as betrayal, but
others saw them as a demonstration of principle. ``Charles was, and
still is, a voice of reason on our board,'' said Jerry W. Levin,
Dunlap's successor at Sunbeam.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he ousted Chainsaw Al, he became my hero,'' said Nell
Minow, the shareholder activist, using the name Dunlap acquired
because of job and other cost cuts he made. ``If every director was
like Charles, I could go into another line of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Elson's friends say his ethical stances have always been
tempered by a sense of fun. ``There's a joie de vivre about him,
and a sense of caring,'' Wilkinson said. He pointed to an
autographed picture of William Howard Taft that Elson once sent
him. ``It was signed on my birthday, and it was just like Charles
to notice that and send it along,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elson, who serves on several museum and college boards in
Florida, is bringing his put-your-money-where-your-mouth-is views
to the public sector, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's no stock to buy, but trustees should donate
sizable amounts,'' he said. ``The important thing is having
something personal at stake in the decisions you oversee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
