<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6272 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CLINTON-INDIA-ART-623     03-23 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-ART-623&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN INDIAN VILLAGE, CLINTON LISTENS TO WOMEN TELL OF MODEST
PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAYLA, India _ The day before President Clinton arrived in this
village for his only visit to rural India during his five-day tour
of the nation, the laminated cards emblazoned with the word
``invitee'' were cherished by those who had them.
</P>
<P>
   A widow, Mohini Devi Gupta, was already wearing her badge. She
is one of the 125 village women who belong to a self-made savings
and loan association. She used her $120 loan to pay for her son's
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one woman who will be garlanding President
Clinton and that's me,'' she said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Gupta did not hang the flower garland around
the president's neck Thursday, but she did tie a rakhi, a woven
bracelet, around his wrist, signifying in the Hindu tradition that
he was her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to her surprise, she actually got a chance to speak with
him. Here he was, the most powerful man on earth, with some of the
flower petals they had showered on him still in his hair, and he
was actually listening to her and other poor women, nodding
sympathetically as though he understood everything they said.
</P>
<P>
   Gupta and a young mother, Pushpa Devi Yogi, told him how they
and other women had banded together, each contributing about $2 a
month to a fund and making modest loans within the group to start
small businesses, among other things. They make rope doormats and
sparkly, colorful bangle bracelets. They also fashion disposable
dishes out of leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The members of a women's milk cooperative described how they cut
out middlemen by selling their milk directly to the Jaipur Dairy.
Women serving on the village council for the first time under a
quota system that has brought a million women into local offices
across the nation spoke of the satisfactions of having a voice.
</P>
<P>
   And one of those council members had a good question for the big
shot from America. People all over the world stereotype Indians as
a backward people, she said. ``Do you think we are backward?''
</P>
<P>
   The president replied with an emphatic ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You are proving that democracy can be used to lift the poor;
can be used to end discrimination against women and keep children _
girls and boys _ in school; can be used to bring people of
different tribes and castes together,'' he said. ``That is very
important to me and my family, my wife who has been in Indian
villages, and to our whole administration.''
</P>
<P>
   They were silent and stoic, their reactions to his comments one
measure of the distance these women still have to travel, the
obstacles they face _ and the glimmerings of hope.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton called for a computer in every village and waxed
eloquent on the importance of educating girls here in the
northwestern state of Rajasthan, village men dressed in loincloths
and soft cotton turbans of pink, yellow and white crowded into a
small storefront to watch him on a television perched high on a
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, Ram Kishore Sharma, a farmer from the dominant
landowning upper caste of Brahmins, said he disapproved of women
who cannot read serving on the village council. Nor did he like
women emerging from the seclusion of their interior courtyards,
faces unveiled, to walk boldly in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming out of their homes,'' he said, ``and because of
that, we're losing our honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharma stood companionably with a few other men, their arms
draped over one another's shoulders. They shook their heads in
agreement, but one, Prabhu Dayal, gently suggested that change was
coming and could not be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big change is in primary education,'' he explained.
``Everyone is sending their girls and boys to primary school.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The village of Naila, population 8,000, is large and prosperous
by Rajasthani standards _ with the attraction of being only about a
half-hour's drive from the opulent Raj Vilas, where the president
and his entourage are staying in Jaipur.
</P>
<P>
   Kalu Ram Meena, the village chief, said he found out that the
president was coming two or three weeks ago. Ever since, he
explained, the villagers have been busy _ repairing the road,
clearing debris and painting the beautiful old mansion where the
president would meet with women and council members.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways the village is typical. The main street is paved,
but the rest are mostly dirt pathways. Bristly haired pigs and
curly tailed dogs roam freely. Carts pulled by camels and petite
donkeys ply the roads. The fragrant, earthy smell of dung hovers in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   Women wear brilliantly colored scarves of orange, purple and
green over their heads and some cover their faces, walking
elegantly through town with huge sacks balanced on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Female literacy is low, though it has improved in recent years.
Almost three out of four rural women cannot read or write _ and
only about 5 percent of the women from untouchable castes are
literate.
</P>
<P>
   Govindi Raiger, an unlettered woman, was one of those invited to
the village encounter with Clinton. Because her father had told her
to seek it, she had won a council seat set aside for a woman from
an untouchable caste.
</P>
<P>
   Asked her age, Raiger looked flummoxed. Family members called
out their guesses. ``Thirty,'' said one. ``No, 40,'' said another.
No one seemed to know the ages of her five daughters and son,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Two of her daughters finished five years of school, two had none
and the youngest, about 7, was doing poorly in the second grade and
not attending regularly. Gopal Lal Meena, principal of the girl's
school, which serves mainly low-caste children, said 8 out of 10
girls drop out by the fifth grade, while most of the boys finish.
</P>
<P>
   Raiger said she knew a president was coming to the village, but
not his name or where he was from. ``I will tell him we need a road
in my neighborhood,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the village was cordoned off to outsiders as a
security measure, though a gaggle of children showed a backdoor way
in via a dirt path. At the point where the path ended in the
village, the men were clustered at the storefront to watch
television. They could tell the meeting was nearing an end when
Clinton offered a closing thought. ``I hope you will not lose your
enthusiasm and your spirit when things don't change as fast as you
would like,'' he said. ``I know it's easy to get discouraged. I
know there is still injustice and unfairness. But what you are
doing here is astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   With the show winding up, dozens of villagers began hurrying
down the dirt path away from the village. As a group of women
dashed by, Kamla Devi Sharma paused long enough to explain, ``I'm
going to see the flying machine,'' then rushed on, her long orange
scarf fluttering behind her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
