<HEADER>
A6279 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV26-     03-23 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE SAVINGS, MADE EASIER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 26)
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Vt.)  (af) 
By JAMES SCHEMBARI  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Starting to save for our children's education seems like
entering an abyss. For parents with several children (I have four),
the required totals are so incomprehensibly huge that many of us
just throw money into different investments and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Many friends in the same situation have asked me about the
college savings plans that the IRS allowed states to set up four
years ago. The plans are popular: 23 states, including New York,
New Jersey and Connecticut, have them, with more expected this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The plans aren't perfect, but they provide substantial tax
benefits. The initial investment choices, different in every state,
are similar to mutual stock, bond or money market funds; the money
is handled by investment companies. But federal taxes on all
earnings are deferred until withdrawal, when they are taxed at the
child's rate.
</P>
<P>
   Some states also defer their own taxes on earnings, but most
waive them entirely. And some states, like New York, even allow
investors to deduct some contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Page, 39, a lawyer for the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission in Washington, set up savings plans for her niece and
nephew in Vermont. ``The tax savings are incomparable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The savings programs are different from so-called prepaid plans,
under which parents pay a predetermined amount, which the state
guarantees will eventually pay for most of their children's college
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The tax benefits are the same as for the savings plans, but some
experts say the prepaid plans are managed so conservatively that
investors could easily accumulate the guaranteed tuition, and then
some, by investing themselves. Most prepaid plans cover only state
schools, while the savings plans can be used anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But the newer savings plans don't give you much control over
your money. If your fund's strategy sours, you cannot easily move
your money to another fund. Maine, for example, lets you put all
your money into an equity fund, but who has the guts to remain
fully invested in stocks just before your child begins college?
</P>
<P>
   Try to withdraw the money early, and you'll lose the state and
federal tax savings and pay a penalty. Parents must bite their
nails until they start writing the tuition checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really want to create your own asset allocation, and
you're really into searching out mutual funds yourselves, you may
not be happy with these plans,'' said Joseph F. Hurley, author of
``The Best Way to Save for College'' (BonaCom Publications, 2000).
``But if you trust that these companies have done their homework,
you should feel very comfortable with these.''
</P>
<P>
   Some states offer plans meant to reduce risks by moving assets
around as your child ages. TIAA-CREF, which runs funds for several
states, invests 75 percent of the money for a newborn into a growth
stock fund and 25 percent into a bond fund. Allocations are
adjusted every two years until, just before the child enters
college, the mix is 10 percent growth, 40 percent bonds and 50
percent in a money market fund. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William Schubart, 54, an executive in South Burlington, Vt., has
invested in his state's plan for his two children. He likes the tax
savings, but realizes that he might be able to get better returns
elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in the market who will invest themselves,
take the risk and make more money,'' he said. ``If somebody had
done that in the last five years, they could send their kids to
school and their neighbor's kids to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors may be able to do better themselves, but college
savings plans didn't do so badly last year. The most aggressive
investment options in the Iowa, New York, and Rhode Island plans
rose 17.3 percent, 17.2 percent and 14.8 percent, respectively,
compared with 19.5 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index. You can shop around among the plans, because most states
don't have a residency requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley recommends the plans, but as part of a broader strategy.
``Look at overall allocation,'' he said. ``Keep your most
aggressive investments in a taxable account and your conservative
investments in the college account,'' to make sure that enough
money will be available for education.
</P>
<P>
   I wish these accounts had been around 12 years ago, when my
oldest child, Marian, was born. But I'm more than willing to
sacrifice some potential returns for the tax savings. I will still
be entering that abyss, but with a lighter burden. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (James Schembari is an editor at The Times. His column on the
prime earning, spending and striving years appears the fourth
Sunday of each month. E-mail may be sent to
jimschem(AT)nytimes.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
