<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6280 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCARS-ZANUCKS-LADN &LR;      03-23 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-ZANUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR TAKES A CHANCE ON ZANUCKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each year on Academy Awards night, everyone who's watching
 &UR; _ &LR;  an estimated 800 million people worldwide  &UR; _ &LR;  is a movie fan,
drinking in the pageantry of the event and cheering or bemoaning
the winners and losers.
</P>
<P>
   And each year, on the morning after the Oscars, everyone becomes
a TV critic.
</P>
<P>
   They gather around their workplace watercoolers or call in to
talk-radio shows to rail about the length of the broadcast, the
unimaginative music, the silly production numbers, the bad writing
the presenters are forced to recite  &UR; _ &LR;  and that's even before they
get around to grousing about the ballot outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000, the dawn of a new millennium, seemed as good a
time as any to revamp the Academy Awards, which is the
second-most-popular live broadcast in America each year behind the
Super Bowl. It wasn't a thorough housecleaning (widely acclaimed
host Billy Crystal is back) but the Academy of Motion Picture Arts
and Sciences took a big risk in turning over the producing reins to
Richard and Lili Fini Zanuck, film veterans who between them had
absolutely no prior experience mounting a live television show.
</P>
<P>
   Under that kind of pressure, the Zanucks should be ready to
crack about now. But less than two weeks before the big night, they
were as cool as the ice sculptures at the Governors Ball,
hobnobbing with the celebrants at the annual nominees' luncheon in
Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't entirely off duty that afternoon. Lili had dragged
along a briefcase crammed with vital papers, and the
husband-and-wife team spent time before lunch conferring with ABC
executives about various details of the show.
</P>
<P>
   The self-confidence they displayed last September when they were
announced as Oscar producers still is evident. They are mindful of
the fact that, with this show, there are no retakes or chances to
fix a gaffe in an editing room, yet they are unruffled  &UR; _ &LR;  at least
in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no perspective since it's our first time,'' Richard
said. ``But everybody tells us we're right on schedule or a little
bit ahead, so that's reassuring to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zanucks know a lot about Oscars, at least from the other
side. Richard, son of Hollywood legend Darryl F. Zanuck, as a youth
attended the gala affairs with his dad. The Zanucks also have gone
to several Oscar ceremonies in their own careers, taking home a
pair of the statuettes for the 1989 best picture winner, ``Driving
Miss Daisy,'' as well as Richard Zanuck's Irving G. Thalberg Award
in 1991 for a producing career that includes ``Jaws'' and ``The
Sting.''
</P>
<P>
   Now here they are, creating their own Oscars event and handling
the public's curiosity about it as they would a much-talked-about
film with a surprise ending. They are giving away very little about
the three-hour show itself
 &UR; _ &LR;  as if the set design, how the nominated costumes are shown and
what Crystal has up his tuxedo sleeve are the primary sources of
all the suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is their way of building interest in the show. Or
maybe they don't want the critics to start carping too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what is going to be new and different about this year's
telecast, Lili evaded discussion of the staging, instead going into
the apparent horse race for all the top categories.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Burt Bacharach and Don Was' music portion of the
program, Richard said, ``There's a lot of music in the show, the
nominated songs, and we're doing a little piece on some of the
great songs from the movies of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   He forgot to mention that little surprise about Robin Williams
being brought in to perform (and probably to ad lib) ``Blame
Canada,'' the best song nominee from ``South Park: Bigger, Longer
and Uncut.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the costume presentations? Last year, host Whoopi
Goldberg opened the show in a Queen Elizabeth I gown, her face
painted a chalky white, and she returned throughout the program in
other nominated costumes. In previous years, they have been shown
off in dance numbers that tried too hard and even some tableaux
that were like watching grass grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way I can answer that is to just kind of touch on
what we're trying to do thematically, which is represent every
category as is presented to the (movie) audience, not interpreting
anything,'' Lili said. ``So we're not having a fashion show with
costume nominations this year, but obviously there will be a
presentation of them as they appeared in the specific films.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Billy won't be wearing them.''
</P>
<P>
   So what will Crystal be doing if he's not changing from, say,
Jodie Foster's ``Anna and the King'' hoop skirts into Gwyneth
Paltrow's debutante resortwear from ``The Talented Mr. Ripley''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lips are sealed about Billy,'' Richard said. ``That's one
of the promises he asked us to make to him when he took the job. He
wants to be as spontaneous and surprise the audience as much as he
can. But Billy's in great form and it'll be funny and very
enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I kind of think the fact that he took last year off gave
him a whole year to think up some really good things,'' Lili added.
</P>
<P>
   The academy and ABC have had a whole year to live down last
year's ceremonies, which dragged on for four hours, five minutes.
At that length, they could have set up telephone banks and raised
money for a charity.
</P>
<P>
   When academy president Robert Rehme announced the Zanucks were
taking over from Oscar veteran Gilbert Cates, his statement read,
``The skill, professionalism and creativity of Richard and Lili
Zanuck will guarantee an exciting, interesting fabric into which we
can weave the presentation of our 20-some Oscar awards.'' That
probably translates to ``bring it in well under last year's time or
you, too, can be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC's official running time on Sunday's TV logs is 5:30-8:30
p.m. local time, but it would be a minor miracle if the
presentations actually finished in three hours. Advertisers love
Oscar's huge, rapt audience, but they aren't happy about paying
premium rates to air their spots after midnight back East, when
most viewers with day jobs have given up and gone to bed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways the Zanucks are paring down the show is by
limiting the best song nominees to 90-second digests rather than
the full three to five minutes each usually requires. There won't
be a big dance sequence built around the best picture nominees  &UR; _ &LR; 
no pompon girls showered with rose petals for ``American Beauty''
or dreamy Agnes DeMille-styled interpretation of apple picking for
``The Cider House Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   And they promise to use the hook without hesitation. Director
Louis J. Horvitz will signal the musicians to ``play off'' any
winner talking longer than 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme is make it short,'' Richard said. ``No matter what,
it has to be entertaining, and that's the same whether we're making
a movie or doing a live television show. And the fact that there is
a deadline is actually a great relief to us because we know exactly
what to head for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies always can be pushed a little bit, the start dates, and
they can slide around, but this is a definite date that we're
aiming for, and that's kind of a good feeling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it certainly is a little bit like when you prep a movie,''
Lili said. ``We know that on March 26 certain departments will wish
they had two more days, but it's just the way it goes. We know that
at 5:30 we're going live around the world, but we're still pretty
calm about it. We're having a good time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
