<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURIST PRESIDENT PREACHES GOSPEL OF DEMOCRACY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAIPUR, India _ President Clinton played tourist Thursday but
could not resist a touch of missionary work as he preached the
gospel of democracy, equality and high technology to a group of
poor villagers near this hectic, vibrant Rajasthan city.
</P>
<P>
   Answering a resident of Nayla village, who asked if the world
thought of Indians as backward, Clinton said, ``No.'' And he said
he hoped his weeklong trip to South Asia would help the world see
India ``in a more complete light.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the president said, ``there are many people here who are
poor, but you are proving that democracy can be used to lift the
poor, can be used to end discrimination against women and keep
children, girls and boys, in school and can be used to bring people
of different tribes and castes together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the computer ``will make this happen more quickly
if it is used wisely and put in every village in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's stop in the village came as he continued his journey
through north-central India with a tour of Amber, the fortified
mountaintop town that was the ancient capital of Jaipur state until
water ran short and the maharajah and his entourage moved to the
valley below.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was greeted by colorfully painted elephants, and the
president, apparently recalling that the animals are the Republican
symbols, remarked: ``It's nice to be around some friendly
elephants.'' Clinton shopped the local craft stands and was shown a
clay sculpture of his head with a turban.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, Clinton moved on to Ranthambore National
Park in hopes of seeing some of the famous Indian tigers. Reports
abounded locally that personnel in the park, once a shooting
preserve of local royalty, had been trying for weeks to lure as
many of the ferocious beasts as possible into the area Clinton was
to visit.
</P>
<P>
   By luck or not, Clinton and daughter Chelsea spotted two tigers
_ a male and female.
</P>
<P>
   As he often does on foreign trips, Clinton in Nayla cited the
United States as a nation with an imperfect past that can serve as
an example to aspiring people and nations.
</P>
<P>
   After U.S. independence from Britain, Clinton said, it was
almost 150 years before women could vote, 100 years before slaves
were freed and another 100 years before blacks acquired equal
rights under law.
</P>
<P>
   India can give the world the greatest gift it could have now if
``you can prove that people can lift themselves from poverty and at
the same time end discrimination against women and their girl
children and learn to work together across tribal and caste lines
because of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   India, Clinton said, could be an example to nations fighting
tribal, ethnic and religious wars, such as in Africa and Bosnia and
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In India, the caste system, illegal but flourishing, assigns
people to social strata as a result of their birth. In a twist, the
current Indian president, K.R. Narayanan, is from the lowest caste,
the untouchables, the first member of that group to rise to head of
state.
</P>
<P>
   En route to Nayla and as the president hit the sightseeing
trail, Clinton's motorcade whisked through streets that had been
momentarily cleared of their usual parade of honking cars, buses
and bicycles as well as camel-drawn carts that serve as a reminder
that much of the province is desert.
</P>
<P>
   Holy cows wander the broad sun-drenched boulevards of the old
Pink City, which was laid out by a French architect for a maharajah
before U.S. colonists had dreamed up the Declaration of
Independence, much less thought of having Pierre L'Enfant design
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   In Nayla, Clinton was welcomed by more than a dozen women
dressed in the bright colors of Rajasthan, a northwestern state.
Reds, purples, oranges and maroons swirled as women danced and sang
about women's work, including the trendy phrase: ``It's time we
empowered ourselves.'' However, the question that provoked
Clinton's sermonette was posed by a man.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was draped with a garland of flowers and showered with
rose petals before hearing the women discuss their lives, including
the fight for equal pay with men and attempts to marry later.
Clinton commiserated especially with dairy women, telling them he
knew how hard that work was.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
