<HEADLINE>
BOEING LEADS AIRBUS IN JET ORDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. has jumped to an early lead over Airbus
in new airplane orders this year with the announcement Thursday
that an unidentified customer has reached a firm agreement to buy
50 next-generation 737s.
</P>
<P>
   At list prices, the order would be worth about $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Randy Harrison said the identity of the
customer, at its request, was not being made public at this time.
</P>
<P>
   But other people familiar with the order said the customer is
International Lease Finance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The latest order pushed Boeing's tally for the year to 95. By
the end of February, Airbus had 34 firm orders for new planes,
according to its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The latest orders were quickly posted on Boeing's Web site. In
the past, the company has waited until the end of the month to add
new orders. Harrison said the Web site order tally will now be
updated weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The change is the second in recent months that Boeing has made
in the way new orders are made public, and reflects the intensity
of the order battle between Boeing and its archrival.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Boeing decided to include orders from undisclosed
customers for the first time, something Airbus had been doing.
</P>
<P>
   The change helped Boeing narrow the gap with Airbus in firm 1999
orders, but the European plane maker still ended the year with
significantly more orders than Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time ever that Airbus had beaten the Boeing,
although they tied one year.
</P>
<P>
   The latest 50-plane order from International Lease includes a
mix of 737 models, the -600, -700, -800 and -900.
</P>
<P>
   International Lease had announced at the Paris Air Show last
year that it planned to buy up to 100 next generation 737s. But it
took months for details of the agreement to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the deal said the additional 50 planes are
not the typical options that a customer converts to firm orders.
Rather, the agreement with International Lease for the first 50
planes gave it the option to cancel the order for the 50 additional
planes, which it chose not to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
