<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE OPENS INQUIRY OF WHITE HOUSE E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: 2nd Take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department has begun a criminal
investigation into whether White House officials illegally
suppressed large numbers of executive office e-mails subpoenaed in
investigations of the White House campaign fund-raising and other
activities, documents filed in federal court disclosed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are also looking into charges that White House
officials threatened employees of a non-government contractor if
they disclosed any of the missing messages, according to the court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry by the Justice Department's campaign finance unit
started after Republicans accused the White House of concealing
private electronic communications being sought by investigators in
Congress, the Justice Department and the Independent Counsel's
Office. The investigators had sought White House e-mail messages
dealing with campaign fund-raising, Monica S. Lewinsky and other
matters. The attempts to obtain the electronic messages date as far
back as 1998 in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's court filing, which declared its
intentions to carry out the investigation, provide no evidence as
to the contents of the e-mail messages. But in the papers, the
department contends a criminal investigation is justified because
of the possibility that some of the e-mail messages may have been
relevant to the investigations and may have been deliberately
concealed.
</P>
<P>
   The papers also refer to earlier documents filed in a civil suit
in which employees of Northrup Grumman, the company hired to
maintain the system, say they had been been pressured to remain
silent about the missing messages.
</P>
<P>
   Two computer specialists working for Northrup Grumman have
testified before Congress and said in depositions that they were
threatened with jail by White House officials if they disclosed a
glitch in the system that would make it difficult, if not
impossible, to ever retrieve any messages. The two workers said the
threats were made in June 1998 amid the furor over the Lewinsky
case.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have denied there was any attempt to avoid
compliance with subpoenas and said that the problem was an
inadvertent computer glitch caused by malfunctioning systems that
failed to properly store all electronic messages written to
presidential aides from outside the White House. ``No one attempted
to hide responsive information from this committee or any other
investigative body,'' Beth Nolan, the White House counsel, said in
a prepared statement she had been scheduled to deliver on Thursday
at a hearing on the e-mail controversy before the House Government
Reform and Oversight Committee. Her appearance was postponed until
next week.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also denied threatening anyone in connection
with the e-mail messages but acknowledged an effort to keep the
problem of the missing messages from becoming public.
</P>
<P>
   Although it had been known for weeks that the e-mail messages
were missing, Thursday's opening of a criminal inquiry ratcheted up
the seriousness of the issue. It quickly spread into the
presidential campaign, where Vice President Al Gore has already
come under attack by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for his campaign
fund-raising tactics. Whether the content of the missing e-mails
related to Gore is unknown, but officials said the the computer
server in Gore's office has a separate problem that may have caused
e-mail messages there not to be recorded properly.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida for a fund-raising reception, Bush commented on the
e-mail controversy. ``This is a White House that needs to let the
sun shine in when it comes to campaign funding allegations,'' he
said, adding, ``I look forward to seeing where these e-mails are,
what was in those e-mails.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
