<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARTBURN-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY TO WITHDRAW HEARTBURN DRUG
</HEADLINE>
  (mh) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The manufacturer of Propulsid, a medication for
severe heartburn that has been linked to 80 deaths, said Thursday
that it would withdraw the drug from pharmacies this summer and
instead distribute it free to a limited number of patients for whom
all other medicines have failed.
</P>
<P>
   The action by Janssen Pharmaceutica of Titusville, N.J., a
holding of Johnson &AMP; Johnson, taken with the approval of the Food
and Drug Administration, comes on the heels of the withdrawal of
another prescription drug, Rezulin. Rezulin, a diabetes medication,
was linked to 63 deaths from liver failure; on Tuesday the FDA
ordered it off the market.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has known since 1994 that Propulsid could cause fatal
heart rhythm disturbances in people with cardiovascular disease or
those taking certain other medications, but left the drug on the
market because it believed the benefits outweighed the risks. But
that assessment was changing, officials said. The FDA had scheduled
for April 12 a meeting of a panel of experts who were to discuss
Propulsid, including proposals to ban or severely restrict its use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about very restrictive actions,'' said Dr.
Florence Houn, the FDA official in charge of gastrointestinal
medications, ``and the company decided to take this voluntary
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement between the agency and the company,
Propulsid, which had $950 million in sales last year, will be
marketed until mid-July, to give patients and doctors time to
switch to alternative therapies. After that, doctors who want to
prescribe the drug will be required to document that other
therapies have failed and that their patients do not have
conditions or take other medications that would make the Propulsid
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Propulsid, whose chemical name is cisapride, was approved in
1993 for patients with heartburn, but is now typically prescribed
``off-label'' to patients with other, more serious conditions.
Within a year of its approval, the FDA began receiving reports of
injuries and deaths. As of Dec. 31, the agency said, Propulsid had
been associated with 341 reports of heart rhythm abnormalities,
including the 80 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The agency had issued new warnings for the drug and changed the
label five times, most recently in January, and Greg Panico, a
spokesman for Janssen, said the company sponsored educational
seminars for doctors and pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   But it became clear over time, he said, that the agency's
warnings were not being heeded, perhaps because the directions for
how to safely prescribe Propulsid had become too complicated.
``With each new labeling change, the label became more complex,''
Panico said.
</P>
<P>
   Houn said the agency allowed Propulsid to remain on the market,
despite the injuries and deaths, because it had an unusual
mechanism of action and the only other drug that worked the same
way caused serious, and sometimes permanent, neurological damage.
Instead of withdrawing it, she said, ``we have been working to try
to manage the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of Public Citizen's Health
Research Group and a frequent critic of the food and drug agency,
said Propulsid should have been taken off the market long ago. He
described the drug as ``a serious public health hazard,'' and said
the agency had wrongly concluded that it could ``fix the safety
problem'' by changing the label.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 30 million patients have taken Propulsid since it came
on the market, although only about 300,000 patients take the drug
today. They include people with gastrointestinal complications of
diabetes and infants and children, who are prescribed the drug when
they suffer severe constipation.
</P>
<P>
   Some stroke patients and people with Parkinson's disease also
take the drug, Houn said, adding that these patients, as opposed to
those with heartburn, are the ones who will probably continue to
receive it under the new limited-use program.
</P>
</TEXT>
