A6294 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-2NDTAKE     03-23 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: those e-mails.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It remains unclear what, if any, sensitive information is
contained in the thousands of e-mails in question. One of Northrup
employees working on the computer system, Betty Lambuth, has
testified that a colleague told her they were full of evidence
dealing with the Monica Lewinsky controversy and a variety of other
investigations, including Vice President Gore's fund raising. But
the colleague, Robert Haas, denied on Thursday at a congressional
hearing that he had any idea what was in the e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Haas did search the e-mail accounts of several White House aides
to determine whether any messages from Miss Lewinsky had not been
stored properly. He said he found numerous such e-mails, which he
turned over to superiors, but White House officials said all of
them had been discovered by other means and sent along to the
office of then Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department review was disclosed on Thursday in legal
documents filed by the Justice Department's Civil Division, which
is defending the White House in the lawsuit over the e-mails filed
by a frequent White House antagonist, Judicial Watch. The Civil
Division has asked Federal District Judge Royce C. Lambeth to
postpone consideration of the civil case pending the outcome of the
criminal inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ray, who replaced Starr as independent counsel, agreed
with the Justice Department's request.
</P>
<P>
   In the government's legal papers, Robert J. Conrad, Jr., the
head of the Justice Department's campaign finance unit, known
internally as the Task Force, said that prosecutors had recently
learned of the charges related to the malfunctioning automated
records system.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of these allegations,'' Conrad said, ``the Task
Force has begun an investigation into whether subpoenas issued to
the EOP (Executive Office of the President) by the Task Force were
fully complied with and whether persons were threatened with
retaliation in order to prevent the existence of the affected
emails from becoming known to the Task Force.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad did not indicate whether prosecutors had reached any
conclusions about the e-mail issue. Other law enforcement officials
said on Thursday that investigators had not determined the content
of the missing e-mails or established whether anyone tried to
intentionally suppress them.
</P>
</TEXT>
