(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
No. 7 TULSA (31-4) VS. No. 6 MIAMI (23-10)
When: 6:55 p.m. TV: KTVT/Ch. 11
TULSA GOLDEN HURRICANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   COACH: Bill Self, 7th season, 129-79. Self has established
himself as one of the brightest young coaches in the country. In
only his third season at Tulsa, he has built the Golden Hurricane
into the WAC's top team and a legitimate Final Four contender.
</P>
<P>
   KEY STATS: Tulsa's aggressive defense has averaged 11.8 steals
per game. Opponents are averaging 20.5 turnovers per game.
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTING REPORT: The Golden Hurricane plays with a post player
and four quick guards. Tulsa's pressure defense is perhaps the best
in the country. The Golden Hurricane is balanced on offense and
gets a lot of easy baskets because of turnovers, a major reason for
its high shooting percentage, 47.5. Tulsa is also deep. Sixth-man
David Shelton (14 points per game) is the team's leading scorer but
not the only key contributor off the bench. This team can win with
full-court and half-court styles.
</P>
<P>
   WILL WIN IF: The Golden Hurricane's pressure defense can disrupt
Miami's offense and create easy scoring chances.
TULSA STARTERS
G TONY HEARD 6-0 175 Sr. Key stats: 9.7 ppg, 40 pct. 3-pointers G
GREG HARRINGTON 6-2 185 So. Key stats: 10.9 ppg, 43 pct. 3-pointers
C BRANDON KURTZ 6-10 245 Sr. Key stats: 11.0 ppg, 6.8 ppg F ERIC
COLEY 6-5 210 Sr. Key stats: 11.3 ppg, 3.3 steals F MARCUS HILL 6-5
195 Jr. Key stats: 11.1 ppg, 4.3 rpg
MIAMI HURRICANES
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Leonard Hamilton, 14th season, 200-209. His teams are
known for tough defense and a grind-it-out offense. Formerly the
head coach at Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   KEY STATS: The Hurricanes shoot 42.8 percent from the field,
27.2 percent from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTING REPORT: The Hurricanes rely on rugged defense, with an
emphasis on pressuring the ball. This is a big, strong team that
prefers to battle in a half-court game. Miami doesn't have a pure
point guard, so it sometimes struggles offensively, especially with
turnovers. Johnny Hemsley is a streaky but dangerous shooter.
</P>
<P>
   WILL WIN IF: The Hurricanes can reduce the game to a slowdown
pace and if they do a good job preventing turnovers against Tulsa's
pressure.
MIAMI STARTERS G VERNON JENNINGS 6-4 203 Sr. Key stats: 7.8 ppg,
