<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-FOYT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLOW START TO NASCAR SEASON FOR FOYT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A.J. Foyt, who had knee surgery in February,
still is hobbling around. Sort of like his NASCAR Winston Cup race
team.
</P>
<P>
   The 65-year-old Foyt, who is on crutches after having 23 pins
removed from his leg, was at Texas Motor Speedway on Thursday to
help promote the DirecTV 500, which takes the green flag April 2.
Foyt is the owner of a fledgling Winston Cup race team that has
made only two of five races and is without a full-time driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be a tough road,'' Foyt said. ``You've
got 90 percent of the top drivers all under contract. It's sealed
and signed, and you're not going to break them. I knew going in
there like this that it was going to be hard to break in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when I was going before and owned my own cars, I didn't
care, because I was driving the car and knew what I could do. But I
don't know what some of these other people can do. I knew that it
was going to be the bumpy road. I just wish I was younger.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt, who recently was named driver of the century by ESPN's
``RPM 2Night'', began the season with rookie Mike Bliss as his
driver. But Bliss qualified for only one race, and finished 35th
among 43 cars in the season-opening Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   After Bliss was 47th in qualifying for the 43-car field on March
12 in Atlanta, Foyt switched drivers. He signed veteran Dick
Trickle, 58, to a two-race contract.
</P>
<P>
   Trickle, who has 293 career starts, qualified Foyt's Conseco
Pontiac 12th for the TranSouth Financial 400 at Darlington, S.C.,
last week. He finished 31st.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Dick Trickle,'' Foyt said. ``I knew he had a lot of
experience. I knew he was up in age. I didn't expect him to run all
day like a 20-year-old boy, but I felt like he would be competitive
and help me understand what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt said he has not decided who will be in the car next week or
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm evaluating it,'' Foyt said. ``I haven't gone that far down
the line yet. ... This is my home state. Maybe I'll have to get in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Foyt, who also owns two Indy Racing League teams, said he is
committed to the Winston Cup series. Patience is what won him seven
Winston Cup races and a record 67 Indianapolis-style championship
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you see A.J. Foyt's name on something, I'm 100
percent there,'' Foyt said. ``... I've got a good reputation.
People know that when I go into something I'm not going in there
just to say I've got a team. That's not my way. I go in there
because I love challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, I knew it was going to be rough. I told my
partner that it wasn't going to be a bed of roses. I look at next
year as being a lot easier, and then we'll have some points where
we've got provisionals, so if you make a mistake at least you can
start the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he will start worrying about where he finishes. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
