<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUTTON POSTS ONLY SCORE IN 60S TO LEAD GUSTY TPC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Hal Sutton spent the final day of
practice rounds at The Players Championship warning fellow
competitors about adopting a ``defeatist attitude'' from their
effusive praise of Tiger Woods, the world's hottest and top-ranked
golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton spent Thursday laying a blueprint for others to follow in
trying to cut into Woods' .700 winning percentage over the past
seven months at PGA Tour events. Amid swirling, 30 mph wind gusts
that pushed the average score to 76.2 for competitors at the TPC at
Sawgrass, Sutton offset four bogeys with five birdies and an eagle
to shoot a 69 and take the opening-round lead.
</P>
<P>
   Woods looms two strokes behind, at 71, and said he was
``ecstatic'' to break par on a day when 19 golfers failed to break
80 and two players (Phil Mickelson and Franklin Langham) carded 46s
on the watery back nine.
</P>
<P>
   Before play was suspended because of darkness with 21 golfers on
the course, 41 players, including Woods, splashed tee shots at the
signature 17th hole, which features an island green. If the highest
scores recorded on each hole by opening-round competitors were
added, Thursday's total would have reached 120 at the par-72
layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything under par is good,'' said Woods, winner of seven of
his past 10 starts at tour events. ``It was hard to pull the right
club because the wind was all over the place. It just depended on
which gust you caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Stadler, who soared to an 83, said: ``Actually, it could
have been in the 90s. I was lucky I made some putts early.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, the most outspoken critic of Colin Montgomerie's
assertion that players resigned themselves to being Woods'
runner-up after the first round of last week's Bay Hill
Invitational, used a conservative approach to carve out the lead.
Sutton said he focused on avoiding ``really big numbers,'' like the
matching sevens that Austin resident Bob Estes took at Nos. 10 (a
par-4) and 13 (a par-3). Or the eight that Stadler carded at the
par-4 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton also did not fall prey to the wide-eyed Woods wonder that
seems to grip peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be bad business to take a defeatist attitude
like that,'' Sutton said. ``By praising Tiger all the time, I don't
know what it's doing for Tiger. But it's certainly putting a
defeatist attitude in the guy that is doing all the praising. Tiger
is just as capable of making a mistake as anyone else. And on this
golf course, there are a lot of mistakes to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring gaffes resulted in drowned golf balls. John
Daly and Duffy Waldorf each dunked two at No. 17, the same hole
where Sergio Garcia three-putted for a triple-bogey during a round
of 82. Even the guys who persevered, like Lee Janzen (70), said
conditions were ``brutal.''
</P>
<P>
   The key, Janzen said, was adopting the right mental attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear the wind whipping outside, I get excited for the
challenge,'' Janzen said.
</P>
<P>
   More than anyone else, Sutton proved equal to that challenge
Thursday. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks balanced three birdies with
three bogeys in a round of even-par 72, tying Jim Furyk for low
round by an afternoon starter. Asked about the wind, Furyk said:
``We're all hoping it lays down (Friday). That was enough
punishment for one day. For one week, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Elkington, the 1997 TPC champ, withdrew Thursday because
of a stomach virus.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lee Janzen, a two-time U.S. Open champ, said Thursday he plans
to compete in the GTE Byron Nelson Classic (May 11-14) and
MasterCard Colonial (May 18-21). Janzen, a Colonial regular, will
be competing at the Nelson for only the second time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   _ With 10 victories in his past 16 starts at PGA Tour events,
Tiger Woods has reached a double-digit win total in fewer events
than any player since Byron Nelson in 1945. Nelson won 10-of-10
during his 11-event winning streak. Ben Hogan won 10 of 19 from
1949-53. Johnny Miller won 10-of-23 in 1974-75. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
