<HEADLINE>
YOU NEED TO `HEAR' HOW TO BET DUBAI RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Casner won't be wearing traditional Arab garb when he races
one of the horses he owns at the Dubai World Cup on Saturday.
Casner, the Southlake resident who's a part owner in Bet Me Best,
didn't a year ago when he went to the races there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very western country,'' Casner said, explaining why he
packed his businessman's wardrobe of a coat and tie.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, racing in Dubai shares some similarities with racing in
the United States. Although the Muslim religion won't allow you to
place a bet in Dubai, you can hide workouts as if you were trying
to score big on a bet.
</P>
<P>
   It happened last year. And let's hope those of us who can bet on
the race at North American simulcast outlets such as Lone Star Park
at Grand Prairie can learn from last year's experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Maktoum family, which rules Dubai and operates horse racing
there, always has a contingent of horses entered in the Dubai World
Cup. Most of the attention last year was centered on High Rise, a
horse who had competed snazzily in Europe's classic races the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   A lesser-known horse named Almutawakel also was part of the
Maktoum stable, but he was offered as a separate betting entry.
There were murmurs that Almutawakel had raced well in Dubai in one
of those infamous ``trial'' races conducted at the Maktoum family's
private Al Quoz training facility.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all they were _ murmurs _ because the Maktoums allow
only invited guests to view the trial races. The closest visiting
press can come to viewing the horses is the day after they work out
at Al Quoz, and that viewing session was abruptly canceled this
year. Instead, the press was shown still photos of some of the
horses.
</P>
<P>
   We would love to hear some good murmurs this year, because
Almutawakel won last year at odds of more than 20-1.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum led Almutawakel into the winner's
circle. But if he was a Common Joe, and not the crown prince,
Sheikh Mo would be asked to appear in the stewards' office after
his picture was taken in the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, people in this country have to sit down because of
suspicion of falsified workout times. It happened to
Louisiana-based trainer Don Cormier and a racetrack clocker after
they were accused of recording inaccurate workout times during the
off-season at Evangeline Downs.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance is this: They're trying to hide a horse's true
ability in order to cash a big bet at race time.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheikh Mo doesn't need to cash a bet. That $12 million
everyone is running for in Saturday's races comes from his family's
stack of oil money.
</P>
<P>
   No, Sheikh Mo's M-O comes from the chip on his shoulder. That
chip may have been placed there by those who question his operating
methods in the horse business.
</P>
<P>
   It's his bat, his ball, his game, however. And we either don't
bet his races or we learn his tendencies, as we learn any other
stable's tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Almutawakel isn't running in the World Cup on Saturday, but
another one like him is. That's Gracioso, who has won a Group III
race in Europe like Almutawakel. Maktoum family racing manager
Simon Crisford says Gracioso is training smartly and may be capable
of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Crisford has seen the horse race in Dubai. But all that the rest
of us can go by are the pictures.
LATE SCRATCHES ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Nelson Bunker Hunt of Dallas topped one of the sessions of the
Ocala Breeders' Sale Company 2-Year-Olds In-Training auction this
week in Florida when he spent $390,000 on a Montbrook filly named
Tuff Tuc. She'll go to trainer Bob Baffert. Hunt also spent $75,000
on a Lord Carson colt and $35,000 on a Belong To Me colt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Snuck In, who won the Gallery Furniture Texan Juvenile the
last time he raced, makes his return after a 15-week layoff in
Saturday's $125,000 Rebel Stakes at Oaklawn Park. Snuck In, trained
by Steve Asmussen, hasn't started since he suffered a foot abscess
and was scratched out of the Risen Star Stakes last month.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arrested Dreams was showing signs of wear and tear when she
bore out in the stretch of her most recent race at Fair Grounds.
And after she was scratched out of the Victoria Lass Stakes last
week in New Orleans, owner Louie Roussel announced he was retiring
the filly. Arrested Dreams was champion 2-year-old filly in 1998 at
Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   _ Although Heritage of Gold (Horse of the Meet at Lone Star Park
at Grand Prairie last year) won her seasonal debut in the Oaklawn
Breeders' Cup Handicap last week, it's unclear if she'll face
Silverbulletday in her next race. That's the $500,000 Apple Blossom
at Oaklawn on April 9, which is expected to include Breeders' Cup
Distaff winner Beautiful Pleasure. Mike Pegram, owner of
Silverbulletday, said he'd rather get a race at Santa Anita before
the filly goes to Churchill Downs for the Louisville Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 500 horses will be auctioned Monday and Tuesday
during the Fasig-Tipton Texas 2-Year-Olds In-Training Sale at Lone
Star Park at Grand Prairie. This is the same sale that produced
graded stakes winner Dreams Gallore, and this year's event is
offering a horse by 1992 Horse of the Year A.P. Indy and out of an
Argentine graded stakes winner named Indianita. Sales horses will
be working out over the track Saturday and Sunday.
SPOTLIGHT ON ... WORLD CUP FIELD FACES HORSE WITH NAME TO WIN
</P>
<P>
   ``Breakfast at Lone Star'' is back. It's that annual eye-opener
known as Dubai World Cup day, when the parking lot gates at Lone
Star Park at Grand Prairie open at 7:45 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The first race from Dubai _ the $2 million United Arab Emirates
Derby _ is scheduled for 8:35 a.m. Three other races are scheduled
before the feature _ the $6 million Dubai World Cup _ goes off at
11:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daily Racing Form'' is expected to have past performances for
the races available for sale Friday. Two horses in the races are
owned by Texans. Bet Me Best, who races in the Golden Shaheen, is
owned in part by Bill Casner of Southlake. Behrens, who races in
the $6 million Dubai World Cup, is owned by Bill Clifton of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a huge betting race, especially if Dubai Millennium
gets beat. Despite the expected field of 14 horses or more, Dubai
Millennium is listed as an odds-on favorite in the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Does he deserve it, or is it a kiss-up by bookmakers to Sheikh
Mohammed al Maktoum, the crown prince of Dubai who also owns Dubai
Millennium?
</P>
<P>
   If it's the latter, it couldn't be more bold than the horse's
name. (The sheikh named him in hopes that the Seeking The Gold
horse would win the Dubai World Cup in 2000).
</P>
<P>
   Dubai Millennium may not be worth odds-on, but he is a deserving
favorite. He has won seven of eight career races and shaded two
minutes for the 1 1/4 miles in his last race at Dubai's Nad al
Sheba Racecourse.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Behrens, five other horses are from North
America: Ecton Park, Malek, Puerto Madero, Public Purse and Saint's
Honor. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
