<HEADLINE>
SHELTON GIVES TULSA PUNCH OFF THE BENCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ David Shelton has learned to do the most with
the least. And Tulsa has been a major benefactor of his charity
work.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-seeded Golden Hurricane (31-4) will face
sixth-seeded Miami (23-10) in Friday's South Regional semifinals
largely because of Shelton's efforts in becoming his team's top
scorer. In the second game, No. 4 seed Tennessee (26-6) will face
No. 8 seed North Carolina (20-13).
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Tulsa's season ended with a 41-point loss to Duke in
the East Regional. Golden Hurricane coach Bill Self decided that
his team needed a new blueprint. More quickness and speed was
needed. One of the new pieces to the makeover was Shelton, a
6-foot-6 forward from Independence Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recruited David because we knew he loved to play and we
knew he was a warrior,'' Self said. ``And we had him projected as a
starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Shelton found himself starting the season on the bench
as Tulsa's sixth man. Self decided on a lineup of 6-10 Brandon
Kurtz at center surrounded by guard/wing players Eric Coley, Tony
Heard, Marcus Hill and Greg Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about rotating the guy who would sit out every
game,'' Self said. ``But the season started and we were playing so
well, I decided that, `Man, I like this.' The next thing you know,
David had the attitude that he could care less about starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thinking changed. He trusted the coaches. We convinced
David that he can be the best sixth man in America or just be
another good player who starts. I honestly believe he's as
effective or more effective than any other sixth man in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton is the leading man in an ensemble. Six Tulsa players
average 9.7 points or more per game. Shelton leads the way at 14
points. Of those six players, Shelton's 22 minutes per game ranks
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing as much as I'd like, but we're winning so I'm
happy,'' said Shelton, a Cincinnati native and the son of former
NBA player Lonnie Shelton. ``This team has a lot of guys who have
accepted their roles and that's what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton has a versatile game. He makes 36 percent of his 3-point
shots. He leads the Golden Hurricane in free throws made (162) and
attempted (210). He averages 4.6 rebounds per game and half of his
rebounds come on the offensive end.
</P>
<P>
   What those numbers translate to is this: Shelton is hard to
guard. He's capable of scoring from the perimeter, driving to the
basket to score or get fouled and he can scrap around the basket
for rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they need me to be physical, I will,'' Shelton said. ``If
they need me to play a finesse game, I will. I had been a starter
since my freshman year of high school. This is my first year not
being a starter. I'm not going to say I like it, but I've adjusted
to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to get more shots. In high school and junior
college, I shot the ball 25 times a game. Here I'm not the first
option or the second option. I don't have to put up 25 shots for us
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than the 6-10 Kurtz, Shelton is the tallest Tulsa player
who receives significant minutes. His ability to play either
forward position plus provide solid rebounding has allowed Self to
play the kind of quick, pressing lineup he envisioned at the
beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Shelton is the reason why we've had such a chance to be
this good,'' Self said. ``He's a terrific player, he's ego-less,
he's a physical presence who can score.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
