<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAR HEELS CLUELESS ABOUT THEIR UNEXPECTED SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Those who love a good mystery have the perfect
team for which to root in the NCAA Tournament South Regional. Even
its coach has no idea why North Carolina has finally started
playing up to its reputation and pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels entered their 26th consecutive NCAA Tournament
with an 18-13 record. After ending the regular season with a 90-76
loss at Duke and a 58-52 loss to Wake Forest in the first round of
the Atlantic Coast Conference tournament, North Carolina had no
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't expect to be in this position,'' senior point guard
Ed Cota said. ``But we put ourselves in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   There were questions as to whether the Tar Heels were either
over-seeded at No. 8 or even deserved an at-large NCAA bid. Then
came two victories, including a stunning second-round upset of No.
1 seed Stanford. Now, the Tar Heels are in the Sweet 16, where
they'll play No. 4 seed Tennessee on Friday night in a semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina coach Bill Guthridge said ``the switch came on''
for his team. Why now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know,'' said Guthridge, 78-27 in his third
season after taking over for the legendary Dean Smith. ``I've liked
this team all year and I felt like if we could just get over the
hump, everything might be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, North Carolina was stunned in the first round by
Weber State. Now, the Tar Heels find themselves an unlikely
underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regular season means nothing if you come into the tourney
and lose in the first round. We found that out last year'' said
junior center Brendan Haywood. ``The tournament is a new season. We
felt like we could make a statement and make amends for what's
happened this season.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Guthridge, the mother of North Carolina coach Bill
Guthridge, died Wednesday at the age of 96. Guthridge said he will
travel from Austin to Parsons, Kan., for the funeral Monday. ``It's
really a blessing,'' he said Thursday. ``She really hasn't been
with us for the last five or six years.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tennessee senior center C.J. Black made a quasi prediction on
Friday's game with North Carolina: ``If (Brendan Haywood) doesn't
respect my jumper, I'm going to have a career night.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Miami's Vernon Jennings on Tulsa: ``I've seen their
highlights. They haven't been on national television too much. I
saw how bad they were beating teams and I was like, `What's going
on with these guys?' They were beating people by 25 points and I
was wondering if their conference was that bad or are they that
good. They've been going through the NCAA Tournament better than I
imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tulsa senior forward Eric Coley said that his team's travel
schedule should be enough to provide respect: ``When we go to
Hawaii we play on the road the next day. East Coast teams don't
have to do that. We have to go to into those altitudes, fly to
Hawaii and then take a six-hour flight to play back in the states.
People think that's no big deal. We do it and people say we're
supposed to do it. People in the East and Midwest don't give us the
respect we deserve.` nn
</P>
</TEXT>
