<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTIS SEEMS CONTENT TO BE A RANGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Texas Rangers outfielder Chad Curtis said he
doesn't foresee demanding a trade at the end of the year though he
has that right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not big on demanding a trade or anything like that,''
Curtis said. ``A lot of people asked me in New York if I wanted to
be traded because I wasn't playing as much as I wanted. I said I
signed a contract to play for the Yankees and my obligation is to
fulfill that as long as I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis signed a three-year contract with the Yankees before the
1999 season. By being traded during the middle of a multiyear deal,
Curtis has the right to demand a trade at the end of the season. If
he did so and the Rangers failed to comply, he could become a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll cross that bridge when we come to it, but I don't
foresee that happening,'' Curtis said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis maintains that stance though his chances of playing time
were reduced when the Rangers acquired switch-hitting designated
hitter David Segui. Curtis is a right-handed hitter and was
expected to get playing time at DH while platooning with Lee
Stevens. But Segui is expected to play against left-handers and
right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think about it,'' Curtis said. ``Obviously I've
got a better chance of getting (at-bats) with a left-hander at DH
than a switch hitter. I recognized that could be detrimental to my
number of ABs. But I've learned in this game if you prepare
yourself and just see what happens, pretty good things usually
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel I can help this team in different ways; it's a
matter of getting ready to do that.'' ROUGH DAY FOR LAMB
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Mike Lamb continues to struggle in his efforts to be the
Rangers' Opening Day third baseman. Lamb bobbled one grounder for
an error and made what manager Johnny Oates said was a bad throw on
another play in the Rangers' 4-2 loss to the Minnesota Twins on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb has committed five errors this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he can play better than he's played this spring,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb was 1-for-4 and is hitting .286. Tom Evans was 1-for-2 as a
designated hitter and is batting .368.
</P>
<P>
   In the possibility that Evans, a right-handed hitter, could win
the job, Oates has had Frank Catalanotto, a left-handed hitter,
increase the work he's getting at third base. BY PRESIDENTIAL
DECREE
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush will throw out the ceremonial first
pitch at the Texas Rangers' home opener Monday, April 3, the team
announced Thursday. The Rangers will play the Chicago White Sox in
the opener, scheduled to start at 2:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the second time President Bush has thrown out the
first pitch at a Rangers' game. He also performed the duty at the
Rangers' home opener in 1991 at Arlington Stadium. The only other
president to throw out a first pitch at a Rangers' home game was
Gerald Ford at the home opener in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand single tickets remain for the opener. LAS VEGAS
MEETING
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are one of six teams expected to be represented at a
meeting in Las Vegas on Monday. Officials from Las Vegas are trying
to convince four to six teams to move their spring-training bases
from Florida in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' lease in Port Charlotte expires after next season,
and the club is considering a move to Las Vegas, Arizona or another
part of Florida. Remaining in Port Charlotte is also an option. A
decision is expected this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers, Houston Astros, Kansas City Royals,
Toronto Blue Jays and Baltimore Orioles are also looking into Las
Vegas. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Left-handed reliever Mike Venafro, sidelined this spring with
a strained ligament in his left middle finger, made his first
appearance in a spring game Thursday. Pitching against the Twins'
Triple-A team in Port Charlotte, Venafro went one inning, allowing
one run on three hits and a walk. Venafro struck out one and
reported no problems with the finger.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Wetteland threw on the side in camp Thursday and is
expected to pitch Friday against the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bucky Dent's father, Russie Stanford, died Friday. Dent left
the team Thursday and is in Georgia for the funeral. He is expected
back Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gabe Kapler went 0-for-3 Thursday, snapping his nine-game
hitting streak. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
