<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6308 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-TENNESSEE24-COX     03-23 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TENNESSEE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slay is driving force for Volunteers
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ron Slay listens during games. He can't help it
_ most everybody wants to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents, put off by his evocative personality and refusal
to be intimidated, give it to the freshman. Opposing crowds, goaded
by the way he'll move his hands as if dishing out cards after an
assist, will rain trash talk down on him. At Vanderbilt, where Slay
came off the bench to score 13 points in only 14 minutes in the
Vols' 13-point loss, Slay heard ``everything in the dictionary,
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Slay gives as good as he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron is the most unusual player I've ever coached in the fact
he's so outgoing and gregarious,'' said Tennessee Coach Jerry
Green.
</P>
<P>
   Though senior C.J. Black is the Volunteers' main inside threat,
and Tony Harris, their play-making point guard, and Vincent
Yarbrough can put up big scoring and rebounding numbers, Slay is
their heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   From the early preseason practices, when the 6-foot-8-inch
forward from Oak Hill (Va.) Academy came in with game and mouth to
match, he's been the player to galvanize his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to lead,'' he said simply.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player, you have to give him his due,'' Black
said. ``I knew as long as he listened, he'd be a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Listen? Or talk?
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a little bit of both,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Slay came to Tennessee with strong credentials. During his
senior season he led Oak Hill to a 31-0 record and final USA Today
No. 1 high school ranking, averaging 17 points, nine rebounds and
2.5 blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Easy to pick out because of his white headband _ ``As soon as I
find another trend, I'll put the headband away'' _ Slay is even
more noticeable for the way he can take over games down the
stretch. In the first-round win over Louisiana-Lafayette, the
Volunteers trailed 40-32 with just more than three minutes gone in
the second half when Slay scored. In the next three minutes he had
an offensive putback and blocked a shot. With eight minutes left
and the Vols still down by four, he took over the game, scoring 11
of UT's next 15 points, including the shot that put UT up 56-54
with 4:07 left, its first lead since early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Slay finished with 15 points and four rebounds as the
fourth-seeded Vols avoided the upset, winning 63-58.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron has always been very explosive off the bench,'' Black
said. ``He keeps us going. He always plays with consistency. When
we need offense, he gives us a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that when things aren't going right, he's always
there to help put us ahead,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Slay is hard to intimidate. Before playing defending national
champion Connecticut in the second-round game, he dismissed any
advantage in experience the Huskies might hold. ``I don't think
anything counts from last year, defending champs or not,'' he said.
``Everyone has the same ammunition. We'll just see who uses it
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay's best may be yet to come. Late in the regular season, as
it became apparent the Vols would enjoy a high NCAA seed, Slay gave
notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to build up to the NCAA tournament and then it's
going to explode,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
