u s BC-GLF-TPC-ROUND124-COX     03-23 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC-ROUND124-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sutton leads a parade of big numbers
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ The tournament that wants to be a
major had all the frustrating feel of one Thursday. Twenty-two
scores in the 80s. World-class players making quadruple-bogeys.
Mis-hit balls rolling into the water as though scooting across a
billiard table.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the TPC at Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton has the first-round lead at The Players Championship
by one stroke at 3-under-par 69, and almost everyone else has
reason for a stiff martini.
</P>
<P>
   If it gets any uglier at the TPC at Sawgrass, where the wind is
gusting with such gusto that a Britsh Open might break out, the
world's finest might be climbing to the first tee today with paper
bags over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The average score Thursday was 76.28. Only 13 players are under
par. Tiger Woods, the world's No. 1 player, rinsed one at the
famous island 17th for double-bogey and was happy with a 71. John
Daly (77) and Duffy Waldorf (80) plunked two balls apiece into the
pond, where 19 double-bogies and 10 uglier numbers were recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price (73), who has won three majors, shanked a chip at the
12th hole, then chunked the next one. Five holes later, his ball
became the 36th (of 41) to find the water at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Horror stories were as plentiful as windshirts. Sergio Garcia
started with a 43 en route to an 82 in his first Players
Championship. Phil Mickelson, ranked 12th, made the turn in 46 and
eventually shot 83, continuing the nightmare from his final-round
82 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a course you can play when you're not striking it
well,'' said Mickelson, who triple-bogeyed the 13th. ``The misses
just get magnified in such a strong wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Morning tee times, when the wind was slightly down and the
greens less dried out, were as valuable as good parking. All the
70s behind Sutton _ from Kenny Perry, Len Mattiace, Joe Ozaki,
Billy Mayfair, Lee Janzen, Bernhard Langer and Brad Fabel _ were
morning rounds. Tom Lehman and Justin Leonard also were at 71. With
British Isles conditions in the afternoon, how fitting that Nick
Faldo managed a decent 73.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the toughest weather we've had on the whole Florida
swing and then you come to the toughest golf course,'' Faldo said.
``You can't make a mistake out there or you tie yourself in
knots.''
</P>
<P>
   As players left the 18th green with glazed eyes and stunned
expressions, defending champion David Duval sounded almost content
with a 75. Colin Montgomerie managed the same, rallying after an
opening 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``75 is not a great score and I'm certainly not pleased with
it,'' said Duval, ``but it's not terrible on a day like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
