<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LANGENBRUNNER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' LANGENBRUNNER IS FIT AND ON FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When Dallas Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner
left practice on Jan. 27, he figured if his season wasn't over it
was pretty darn close.
</P>
<P>
   The pinched nerve in his neck wasn't healing.
</P>
<P>
   The pain was constant.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment of cortisone shots wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor said surgery looked to be the only remaining option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, actually, I decided it was going to happen,''
Langenbrunner said of what probably would've been season-ending
surgery. ``It still wasn't gone. What else could we do?''
</P>
<P>
   They decided to try one more cortisone shot. A just-to-be-sure,
what-can-it-hurt measure.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, his neck began feeling better. Better soon
developed into good enough for him to return on Feb. 9 after an
11-game hiatus. He played in four games, getting two goals and two
assists, before pain flared again. He missed another trio of games
before returning on Feb. 23 against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   He has been one of Dallas' hottest players ever since.
</P>
<P>
   How hot? Texas-in-July hot.
</P>
<P>
   He has eight goals and seven assists in 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no different than this time last year,'' said Joe
Nieuwendyk, a good friend and former linemate of Langenbrunner's.
``He's the kind of guy you know is going to be there in the end. He
plays hard, he's got a good heart and good work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he had this all season. What he didn't have were the
numbers. In fact, he had fewer goals (7) in the 40 games before the
injury than he has had in the 17 games since (10).
</P>
<P>
   So what sparked the turnaround?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes when you are pressing too hard offensively
you stop working and you lose your foundations, and that's what he
did, lost his foundation,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``He
started to become a worker first and a scorer second.''
</P>
<P>
   Hello, he's killing penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Langenbrunner doesn't kill penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Langenbrunner qualified. ``It's not like I ever have.
I just didn't here. We have so many good players who can do it
better than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries to the Guy Carbonneaus, Blake Sloans and Jere Lehtinens
tossed Langenbrunner into that role. Short-handed goals like the
one he scored on Sunday against San Jose may make it hard for the
Stars to take him out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner laughs.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the year, it seemed as if he could've thrown
a beach ball at an open net and it wouldn't have gone in. Now, he's
leading a one-on-three while short-handed and his shot sails goes
five hole.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, his playoff scoring touch has returned after all.
</P>
<P>
   He should be so lucky. He had 10 goals and seven assists in 23
playoff games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing the same way he did in the playoffs last year,''
Stars winger Brad Lukowich said. ``Someone asked me who's one of
the guys you look to be a player like? Personally, I think he's one
of the guys a lot of the younger guys look up to. Even Hitch says
himself: `Watch this guy, try to emulate what he does on the
ice.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which elicits another chuckle from Langenbrunner.
</P>
<P>
   He figures one of the best things he has done on the ice since
returning is playing on a line with Mike Modano, who has posted the
best numbers in the NHL since Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easier when you are playing with a guy who's going
that good,'' Langenbrunner demurred as he sharpened his stick
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Stars forward Kirk Muller, who had been listening as
Langenbrunner talked, said, ``You are making him right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Muller, of course, was joking.
</P>
<P>
   But still, not bad for a guy whose season was supposedly over.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
