<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Equity Lender Files for Bankruptcy Protection
</P>
<P>
   First Alliance, a nationwide home equity lender facing a host of
lawsuits accusing it of deceptive sales practices, announced that
it had stopped making new loans to homeowners and that it had filed
for bankruptcy protection. The mortgage company, which had offices
in more than a dozen states, including New York, New Jersey and
California, said that it has closed its loan offices and laid off
85 percent of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Profit Up 49 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Riding a surge in trading of stocks and bonds, Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter reported that its first-quarter net income rose 49
percent, making it the fourth big investment bank to post
stronger-than-expected earnings. Morgan Stanley benefited from
investors' seemingly insatiable appetite for the securities of
companies in technology and telecommunications industries. Shares
of Morgan Stanley rose $4.50, to $94.75.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler Becomes Head of IMF
</P>
<P>
   Horst Koehler of Germany, the president of the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development, became the International Monetary
Fund's managing director just as the Clinton administration and
members of Congress were discussing how the agency might be
improved. The election put an end to an awkward episode in which
Koehler became Germany's second choice for the job after its first
failed to garner broad support.
</P>
<P>
   No Phone Accord Reached in Japan
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the United States and Japan over deregulation of
the telecommunications market ended without an agreement on the
magnitude and speed of reductions in the fees that Nippon Telegraph
and Telephone charges for access to its local network.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine Transactions Scrutinized
</P>
<P>
   An executive of Credit Suisse, the European banking giant,
testified before the House Banking Committee that his institution
engaged in unusual transactions on behalf of Ukraine's central
bank, but he maintained that all of them were legal. Credit
Suisse's activities in Ukraine have come under scrutiny after the
International Monetary Fund revealed last week that Ukraine's
central bank secured IMF loans by misleading the fund about the
country's financial health. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers,
who also testified, said the Treasury department would review
audits of the transactions in question before he supports further
IMF lending to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Chase in Talks for Robert Fleming
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan is negotiating to acquire the asset management
and investment banking firm Robert Fleming Holdings. A deal would
end the independence of Fleming, one of Britain's last privately
held banks.
</P>
<P>
   Stake Sold in Mobilcom of Germany
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom scored a rare strategic victory in the jockeying
for advantage in the European telecommunications industry with a
$3.6 billion deal to acquire nearly a third of Mobilcom, the
aggressive provider of low-cost phone service in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   February Rate Rise Was Unanimous
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's policy-making committee was unanimous in
its decision to raise the federal funds rate by a quarter-point in
February, according to minutes of the meeting. However, some
members had urged that the rate be pushed even higher.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx Posts 37 Percent Gain in Earnings
</P>
<P>
   FedEx, the parent of Federal Express, the big overnight delivery
company, said that its third-quarter earnings rose 37 percent,
exceeding Wall Street expectations, on growth in international
shipments.
</P>
</TEXT>
