<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TRIMBLE CHALLENGED
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble will face a bid to oust him as leader of the
Ulster Unionists at a meeting of the party council in Belfast
Saturday from a fierce opponent of the peace accord. Trimble will
be challenged by the Rev. Martin Smyth, a former grand master of
the militantly Protestant Orange Order. The move threatens further
damage to the pact, now stalemated over paramilitary arms.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: 2 FINED IN KOHL SCANDAL
</P>
<P>
   Two key figures in the campaign finance scandal involving former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl were each fined $500 for refusing to testify
to a parliamentary committee investigating illegal donations to
Kohl. They were Hans Terlinden, a former Christian Democratic party
chief of staff, and Horst Weyrauch, the party's former financial
consultant. Terlinden faces a possible jail term if he does not
testify by April 6.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO: EXPLOSIVES REMOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATO peacekeepers found explosives laid on a bridge in north
Kosovo, not far from the divided town of Mitrovica. The discovery
was made a day after a nearby railway bridge was blown up, and as
peacekeepers moved to close all roads linking Kosovo and the rest
of Serbia, ahead of the anniversary Friday of the start of the NATO
bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   HUNGARY: MEDIA CONTROL GROWS
</P>
<P>
   The government tightened its grip on the state news media by
electing another oversight body containing no opposition members,
in violation of the media law, the opposition said. The government
of Prime Minister Viktor Orban has already appointed
government-only boards to oversee state radio and television; it
expanded the practice to the TV network that broadcasts to
Hungarians living in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: DEFINING MARRIAGE
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Anne McLellan plans to enshrine a heterosexual
definition of marriage in a bill that would also widen rights to
homosexual couples. Seeking to avoid a split in the ruling Liberal
Party, McLellan said the bill would define marriage as ``the lawful
union of one man and one woman to the exclusion of all others.''
The bill would amend 68 federal statutes to erase legal differences
between heterosexual and homosexual couples in many areas,
including spousal income tax credits and pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: ATTACK BY ALBRIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright urged the United Nations
to confront China over Beijing's ``widespread denials'' of basic
freedoms. The bulk of the Chinese delegation to the 53-nation Human
Rights Commission in Geneva walked out on Albright's speech, the
first by a secretary of state to the group since it was created in
1946. Albright flew from South Asia for her 15-minute address.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SUHARTO TO BE QUIZZED
</P>
<P>
   Former President Suharto is healthy enough to be questioned on
corruption charges, although his speech is slurred by illness,
according to an examining doctor quoted by a newspaper. Attorney
General Marzuki Darusman said he hoped to summon Suharto for
questioning by next week.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: MAHATHIR RULING STALLED
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the sodomy trial of former Deputy Prime Minister
Anwar Ibrahim said he would not call Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad to testify unless defense lawyers could show that the prime
minister had played a role in fabricating charges against Anwar.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS: FIGHTING AIDS
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Foundation, created with a billion-dollar fund set up
by Ted Turner, will give $6 million to fight AIDS in southern
Africa, the foundation said in announcing $17 million in new
grants. Other grants will go to U.N. agencies working in
Mozambique, Bangladesh and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: REFORMERS LASH OUT
</P>
<P>
   The main democratic reform group accused the authorities of a
``lack of serious resolve'' in the investigation into the shooting
that wounded Saeed Hajjarian, 47, one of the group's main
strategists in its election victory. The Islamic Iran Participation
Front said six suspects, including a 20-year-old student accused of
being the hitman, Saeed Asgar, were being held by an unidentified
military institution that had refused to hand them over to civilian
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: U.N. ENVOY ABOLISHED
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan has abolished the position of
special U.N. envoy in Iraq. The incumbent, Prakash Shah, an Indian
diplomat, left Baghdad last year and has been doing the job part
time from India. Annan told Shah there was no longer a need for a
high-level representative for Iraq, where the United Nations has no
arms inspectors and is largely limited to aiding the ``oil for
food'' program.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: LAWYERS ASSAIL MUGABE
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to President Robert Mugabe's rule grew when
Zimbabwe's biggest independent law association accused him of
heading a dictatorship and said he should resign. The challenge
from the Zimbabwe Lawyers for Human Rights group came three days
after Zimbabwe's biggest opposition alliance, the National
Constitutional Assembly, called on Mugabe to step down over the
occupation of white-owned farms by squatters led by ex-guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   COMOROS: LEADER RUSHES HOME
</P>
<P>
   The islands' military leader, Col. Azaly Assoumani, cut short
his pilgrimage to Mecca and returned home early after a failed coup
on Tuesday against his one-year-old government. Azaly, who had been
scheduled to return on Saturday, convened an emergency Cabinet
meeting, officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
