<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6326 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-POPE-HOLOCAUST-HNS &LR;      03-23 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-HOLOCAUST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE PAYS HOMAGE TO MILLIONS OF JEWS `MURDERED IN THE HOLOCAUST' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CECILE S. HOLMES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a moving visit to Israel's Holocaust memorial,
Pope John Paul II on Thursday recalled the horrors of Nazism but
stopped short of apologizing for the silence of the Vatican's
leadership during World War II while millions of Jews were sent to
their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul said the Roman Catholic Church was ``deeply saddened''
by Christians' persecution of Jews through the centuries, and he
urged the two faiths to build a new relationship born of their
common roots.
</P>
<P>
   But the pope did not go as far as some Jews had hoped. He did
not assign blame to the church hierarchy or to Pope Pius XII, the
wartime pope who many Jews say failed to raise his voice when so
many were being killed.
</P>
<P>
   During a solemn remembrance service for the victims of the
Holocaust that was broadcast live on Israeli television, John Paul
said, ``I have come to Yad Vashem to pay homage to millions of
Jewish people who, stripped of everything, especially of their
human dignity, were murdered in the Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope added, ``As bishop of Rome and successor of the Apostle
Peter, I assure the Jewish people that the Catholic Church,
motivated by the Gospel law of truth and love, and by no political
considerations, is deeply saddened by the hatred, acts of
persecution and displays of anti-Semitism directed against the Jews
by Christians at any time and in any place.''
</P>
<P>
   More than any monument in Israel, Yad Vashem literally means ``a
place and a name'' for the Jews who died in anonymity under Adolf
Hitler's Third Reich. The memorial represents one people's
determination to never forget those who perished in the Holocaust
and to avoid such suffering in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Between the German invasion of the Soviet Union in the summer of
1941 and the end of the war in Europe in May 1945, Nazi Germany and
its allies tried to kill every Jew under their domination. Many
historians, though, consider the beginning of the Holocaust era to
be in January 1933 with Hitler's accession to power. About 6
million Jews died during the Holocaust. While 5.5 million Gypsies,
Poles and other prisoners were killed in Nazi death camps during
the war, the Jews were the only group the Nazis tried to destroy
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, given in English while the eternal flame of Yad
Vashem flickered in the foreground, John Paul recalled the horror
of that era.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this place of memories, the mind and heart and soul feel an
extreme need for silence,'' he said. ``Silence in which to
remember. Silence in which to try to make sense of some of the
memories, which come flooding back. Silence because there are no
words strong enough to deplore the terrible tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's speech Thursday reflected the themes of unity and
interreligious harmony that he has developed during his 21-year
pontificate, years he has worked tirelessly to reconcile Jews and
Christians. He was the first pope to visit the Nazi death camp of
Auschwitz and attend services at a synagogue in Rome. Two weeks
ago, he apologized for the sins of Christians throughout history,
including those against Jews, though he did not mention the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the fourth day of his pilgrimage to the Holy Land,
the pope met with Israel's two chief rabbis in west Jerusalem and
held an interfaith meeting late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   He also blessed Israel in a meeting with President Ezer Weizman.
The meeting with Weizman is viewed by many Israelis as the Catholic
church's recognition of their state since, in previous centuries,
the church taught that Jews were exiled and condemned to be
dispersed from their homeland because of the death of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's official presence in Israel was equally significant
because the last pontiff to visit was Pope Paul VI. He came to the
Holy Land in 1964 for a brief tour and never once mentioned Israel
by name.
</P>
<P>
   In his address Thursday, John Paul emphasized the common roots
of the two faiths and his personal experiences of the Holocaust.
``Let us build a new future,'' he said, ``in which there will be no
more anti-Jewish feeling among Christians or anti-Christian feeling
among Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel, accompanied John Paul to
Yad Vashem. When it was Barak's turn to speak, he said the pope's
visit will be recorded ``as a moment of truth, as a victory of
justice and hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, whose grandparents perished in the Treblinka death camp
in Nazi-occupied Poland, spoke of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the darkness of Nazism descended,'' he said, ``and my
people were led from all over Christian Europe to the crematoria
and the gas chambers, it seemed that no longer could one place any
hope in God or man. That in the words of the prophet Joel, `The sun
and the moon darkened, and the stars withdrew their luster.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And the silence was not only from the heavens. During that
time, here in the land of Israel, the poet Natan Alterman wrote
these searing, tormented verses: `As our children cried under the
gallows, the wrath of the world we did not hear.'''
</P>
<P>
   A letter was read during the service. It was written by a
Polish-Jewish mother to her gentile friend, asking her to look
after her 7-year-old son: ``I am sure that you can find it in your
heart to love him. Every day I pray to God that, on account of my
suffering, he will be happy in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother, Genia Kleptish-Yudska, and her son, Michael, both
died at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The service at Yad Vashem lasted more than an hour, and during
the ceremony, the pontiff often stood, slightly trembling, his eyes
downcast toward the floor where the names of death camps are
inscribed.
</P>
<P>
   For the 79-year-old John Paul, who was born in Wadowice, Poland,
the Holocaust remains a personal tragedy, and he spoke Thursday of
his ``Jewish friends and neighbors, some of whom perished, while
others survived.'' He was 19 when the Nazis invaded.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 Holocaust survivors from in or near Wadowice were on
hand for the pope's address, and he spoke to several, gently
patting the arm of one woman who began crying as he greeted her.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Tzirer, now in her 60s, lives in Israel today, but she
grew up in Krakow. At the beginning at the war, her family fled
their home, but they were eventually captured by the Nazis. By the
time she was 11, she was alone and interned in a Nazi labor camp.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1945, when the camp was liberated, the 14-year-old
girl was lying next to the camp fence, exhausted and suffering from
tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   A young priest came to her aid, she said Thursday, giving her a
piece of bread and a cup of hot tea. The priest then carried her
two miles on his back to a place where she joined other Holocaust
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   That priest, she said, was Karol Wojtyla, later archbishop of
Krakow and today pope of the world's 1 billion Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
