<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' PAGE ARRESTED AFTER EARLY MORNING FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys offensive lineman Solomon Page
was arrested Thursday in Morgantown, W.Va., and charged with
disorderly conduct and obstructing police.
</P>
<P>
   Page, who was released after posting a $200 bond, will contest
the charges, his agent Angelo Wright, said. A hearing was set for
April 12 in Morgantown Municipal Court.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys spokesman Rich Dalrymple said the team was aware of the
situation and is in the process of gathering information. ``There
is nothing more to say at this time,'' Dalrymple said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the arrest report, Morgantown police officers were
responding to a fight complaint about 3 a.m. when they saw Page
throwing punches. Police said he refused to stop and then jerked
away when an officer grabbed his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said has hasn't talked to Page, the Cowboys' second-round
pick in 1999. But Wright talked to Page's mother, who told him his
client was breaking up a fight when police came.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the biggest guy and they sprayed him (with Mace),''
Wright said. ``And then he put up his arms because he couldn't see.
He'll probably fight this.''
</P>
<P>
   Page, who played at West Virginia in Morgantown, started six
games for the Cowboys last season as a rookie. He is expected to
compete with Tony Hutson for the team's starting right-guard
position in 2000. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
