<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al-Amin protests treatment in Alabama jail
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis and Dana Tofig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY COUNTY, Ala. _ Three decades after he and others
fought to bring Alabama civil rights into the 20th century, the
former H. Rap Brown stood before a Montgomery County, Ala., judge
Thursday, his lawyers vowing to fight for his freedom in a new
century.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black-and-white striped jailhouse uniform, Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin _ former voting rights advocate turned
revolutionary turned Muslim cleric _ listened as his lawyers said
they would fight plans to bring him back to Georgia to face charges
he killed a Fulton County sheriff's deputy March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, his legs and arms in shackles, said nothing as he stood
in orange jailhouse sandals before Montgomery County District Judge
Lynn Bright. He was apprised of his rights and given the
opportunity to waive extradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in the business of waiving anything,'' said one of his
lawyers, J.L. Chestnut. ``I'm in the business of making waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut and Al-Amin's other lawyers, Rose Sanders and Musa
Ban-Fodio, a Muslim attorney from Stone Mountain, said their client
is being persecuted and mistreated because of his religious faith
and his reputation as a 1960s black radical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider him a political prisoner and he has been treated
like a political prisoner,'' Sanders told the judge during the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said Al-Amin was being denied religious freedom in
jail and was being treated poorly because he had been a civil
rights activist.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery officials say his treatment in jail has nothing to do
with his past and everything to do with the criminal charges
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, 56, is being held in solitary confinement 23 hours a
day. He is confined to a 10-by-10-foot cell with a cot, toilet and
sink. His food is standard jail fare: cold cereal for breakfast,
turkey bologna sandwich for lunch and his only hot meal for dinner.
During the one hour he is allowed outside his cell, he can exercise
and bathe.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Alabama became the first of several states
to re-adopt striped prison uniforms and chain gangs, practices that
had largely disappeared with the advent of civil rights and prison
reform movements. The state has since abolished chain gangs again.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery Sheriff D.T. Marshall said, ``I don't care what
(Al-Amin's lawyers) say. They don't run the jail. I run the jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County (Ga.) District Attorney Paul Howard has said he
will seek an indictment against Al-Amin today for the killing of
Deputy Ricky Kinchen and the wounding of Deputy Aldranon English.
The officers were shot as they were trying to serve an arrest
warrant on Al-Amin on March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said a challenge to the validity of the murder charge
will be filed when extradition papers arrive from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said she also will file a petition to complain about how
Al-Amin is being treated in the Montgomery County jail. She
complained to Bright that Al-Aminwants to attend a Friday prayer
service with other Muslims in the county jail, but the sheriff will
not allow him to leave solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is treated differently and you have to ask why,'' Sanders
said. ``Do you think any Christian person would be denied this
request?''
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Marshall said prisoners in maximum security
are not allowed to leave that section of the jail. He said Al-Amin
was placed in high security because he is considered a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a dangerous person, I don't care how meek his
lawyers say he is,'' Marshall said. ``The deputy who is dead would
probably like to go to church Sunday, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Andrea Jones
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
