<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police doubt bloodstains linked to Al-Amin case
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Blood splatters found near where two Fulton County
deputies were gunned down last week probablyweren't from the former
Black Panther accused in the shooting and may not be related at
all, police said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators initially believed Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, who
they say shot Deputies Ricky Kinchen and Aldranon English on March
16, was injured when the two officers returned fire.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen was killed in the gunfight. English, who was seriously
wounded, told authorities he thought he had shot his assailant in
the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, captured Monday night in White Hall, Ala., has no
injuries, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting investigation is fraught with unanswered questions
and conflicting accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police say they believe Al-Amin was alone when the
deputies, who were trying to arrest him on relatively minor
charges, were shot. English has said no one else was standing
outside Al-Amin's grocery store and no one was inside the black
Mercedes-Benz the suspect was said to be driving the night of the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The black Mercedes-Benz registered to Al-Amin is still missing.
The car hasn't turned up in Alabama and investigators are trying to
determine how Al-Amin got from Atlanta to White Hall, where he was
arrested by federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   As for the blood found outside the house in the West End
neighborhood of Atlanta, police spokesman John Quigley said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The abandoned house is about a block or more from the actual
scene of the shooting. There is no trail of blood that leads from
the shooting scene to the house. The blood starts at the house. It
was checked because it was not dry. Since a shooting had just
occurred a short distance away, it is the investigators' job to
check the blood. It's currently being tested at the GBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Although English said he thought he had shot Al-Amin in the
stomach, the suspect had no bullet wounds or injuries when FBI
agents and U.S. marshals captured him Monday night in a wooded area
of White Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have speculated that English either missed his
target or the suspect was wearing body armor. Al-Amin was outfitted
with body armor the night of his capture, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities never shot at him the night he was seized, said Bill
Imfeld, FBI special agent in charge of the Alabama investigation of
Al-Amin. Earlier reports that Al-Amin had been fired upon by
marshals or FBI agents were incorrect, Imfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama authorities have said Al-Amin was first spotted peering
out from a shed near the home of a friend in White Hall. Yet FBI
officials said Thursday that they searched the shed the day Al-Amin
was arrested and found no trace he had ever stayed there or even
hidden there briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
