<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6332 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-FRUITFLY-GENOME-A     03-23 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FRUITFLY-GENOME-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PITTSBURGH: common ancestor.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Besides the 1,299 small gaps remaining, there is one major
omission from the fly genome: the large DNA regions that form the
central part of the fly's four chromosomes, the giant DNA molecules
in which the genome is packaged. This DNA is thought to contain
almost no genes and to play a largely structural role.
</P>
<P>
   Both the public consortium and Celera seem to agree that the
structural DNA does not have to be decoded to call a genome
complete. When biologists from the public consortium announced in
December the completion of the first human chromosome, No. 22, they
did so without having tried to decode its structural DNA.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the fly, 60 million of the 180 million DNA units
in the genome are structural DNA, and 120 million units are in
regions that code for genes. The structural DNA consists of the
same string of DNA letters repeated thousands of times over, and
cannot be decoded by present techniques. Most of the remaining gaps
in the fly genome occur in the zones where the gene-coding arms of
the chromosomes merge into the central regions of structural DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The sequencing of the fly genome depended largely on DNA data
and computer programming developed at Celera by Dr. Mark Adams, Dr.
Hamilton Smith and Dr. Eugene W. Myers. Myers, a mathematician,
devised an ingenious strategy for assembling genomes, which he
first offered to the public consortium but was told would not work.
He then joined Celera and gave the strategy its first test with the
fly genome, which he successfully assembled from three million tiny
pieces of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   A team of fruit-fly experts and software engineers then met at
Celera's headquarters in Rockville, Md., for a two-week
``annotation jamboree.'' Annotation is the process of analyzing a
genome with the help of computer programs to figure out where the
genes lie and to assign likely biological roles to each gene based
on its similarity to genes of known function.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 or so participants at the jamboree were the first to see
the fly genome and try to define the little creature's complex
genetic programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very exciting event,'' Rubin said. ``We had all these
people together, some experts in biology, others in bioinformatics.
Each needed the other's help to answer their questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The biologists would describe a pattern that should be looked
for, and the bioinformaticists _ a new class of expert who use
computers to analyze genomes _ would stay up all night writing the
appropriate software. ``There was a feeling it was a
once-in-a-lifetime experience that we were going through
together,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Successful completion of the fly genome, Release 1.0, takes
Celera a leap forward in its race to complete the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still optimistic that when people see the Drosophila
results, there will be renewed efforts at collaboration,'' Venter
said, alluding to recently broken-off negotiations with the public
consortium to join forces on the human genome. But the public
consortium, treading piece by piece along the genome, is also
making substantial progress in a race now in its final laps.
</P>
</TEXT>
