<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISK-FREE? MORE LIKE A FREE LUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star The latest proposed fix for Social
Security is so misguided its critics say it risks repeating a
financial fiasco akin to the savings and loan crisis.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reform offered by House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer,
a Texas Republican, and Rep. Clay Shaw, chairman of the
subcommittee on Social Security and a Florida Republican, would
have government cover market risk if workers are allowed to invest
their Social Security taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   This approach is a compromise. The administration wants to let
government invest payroll tax revenue in private financial markets.
The GOP-controlled Congress is pushing to allow individuals to put
at least part of their Social Security taxes into personally
managed investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The problem created by protecting individual investors from
market risk, however, is what economists call ``moral hazard.'' It
results from knowing you won't have to pay for your mistakes, that
somebody else will. Someone with a gambling problem, for instance,
might be more prone to gamble if they know a friend or relative
will bail them out if they get into financial trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Economists generally contend that insurance protection
encourages moral hazard. It's not as if people intentionally have
auto wrecks or burn down their homes because they carry auto and
homeowner's insurance. It's just that human nature being what it
is, people aren't as careful when they're covered against risk.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;L analogy offered by critics of Archer-Shaw plays off how
government encouraged the savings and loan industry to take risks
that devastated many thrifts. The resolution of the resulting mess
cost taxpayers upward of $150 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The debacle occurred because the interest rates S&AMP;Ls were paying
to lure deposit money rose far above the rates on old mortgages,
which were the S&AMP;L's primary income source. Regulators responded by
allowing S&AMP;Ls to move beyond making home loans. This prompted
riskier initiatives to enhance profits. Meantime, deposit insurance
coverage was raised from $40,000 to $100,000 to encourage
individuals and institutions to chase high-yield CDs. Moral hazard
resulted because eager depositors knew they'd be covered even if
their S&AMP;L went broke making bad moves.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer-Shaw proposal would create the same type of moral
hazard. If individuals were to pursue risky investments because of
Uncle Sam's promises to cover their losses, government's liability
might eventually become unmanageable. Meanwhile, as individuals saw
the value of their private Social Security accounts decline, they
would probably chase riskier investments in hopes of a big score to
make up losses. They would do so knowing that if their risky bets
went sour, Uncle Sam would bail them out.
</P>
<P>
   They would discover, however, that government will only do so
much. Those involved in the S&AMP;L collapse certainly did.
</P>
<P>
   A recent analysis by the Cato Institute summed up the challenge
by noting the need for the sharing of both profit and risk. Only if
workers have a stake in both gains and losses can a partly
privatized Social Security system work.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer-Shaw bid makes the concept an easier sell
politically, but it would lead to financial disaster for government
and workers alike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
