<SLUG> BC-HMO-KAN </SLUG>
  
 AGGREGATE PROFIT DECLINES FOR KANSAS CITY HMOs  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Health maintenance
organizations in the Kansas City area suffered an aggregate decline
in profit last year, though results among individual plans varied
widely.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A representative group of 11 area HMOs showed aggregate earnings
of $11.3 million in 1999, according to reports filed with the
Missouri Department of Insurance. That represents a 49 percent
decline from 1998, when the group posted earnings of $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   The overall drop occurred despite rising insurance premiums that
have bedeviled employers and individual consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Heese, acting chief financial examiner for the Missouri
Department of Insurance, said much of the financial decline
occurred because health care costs are rising faster than premiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely concerned with the trend of HMO earnings
being significantly less than the prior year,'' Heese said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the effect on consumers will be even higher
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The premiums were inadequate in the past and are now coming in
line with what they need to be,'' said Michael B. Wood, executive
director of the National Center for Managed Health Care
Administration at the University of Missouri-Kansas City. ``I think
they'll continue to go up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Many managed care companies and industry experts say rising
prescription drug costs are cutting into HMO bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a national basis, probably two out of three HMOs lost money
last year,'' said Mark B. Whiting, a principal with the Kansas City
office of the William M. Mercer Inc. benefits consulting firm.
``Pharmacy costs were tough on everybody last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But HMOs are apt to get little sympathy from consumers, who
sometimes lock horns with their health plans, said Richard Hellman,
a physician and president of the Metropolitan Medical Society of
Greater Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Hellman said he understood that it was ``incredibly difficult''
for an HMO ``to predict the true cost of health care for a
community for the next year. But I wouldn't want patients to suffer
because the HMOs set their premiums at the wrong level or didn't
spend enough of premium money on patient care.''
</P>
<P>
   HealthNet's HMO business posted a loss of $9.8 million last
year, even as HealthNet's HMO revenue rose from $127.1 million in
1998 to $183.1 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   HealthNet spokeswoman Cheryl Dillard blamed the 1999 net loss on
rising drug costs and one-time expenses related to upgrading
HealthNet's computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster its finances, Dillard said HealthNet had raised
premiums and implemented a pharmacy co-pay plan that encourages
members to use less-expensive generic drugs and drugs from a
preferred list.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Department of Insurance said membership in
HealthNet's state-regulated HMO plans rose from 76,000 in 1998 to
91,000 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect improved performance this year,'' Dillard said.
</P>
<P>
   Humana Kansas City Inc. posted a strong bottom-line result of
$13.1 million last year. But Dennis A. Matheis, president of
Humana's Kansas City area operations, said that Humana operated
several plans in the Kansas City area and that together they about
broke even last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting a double-digit increase in drug costs, like
every other plan,'' Matheis said. ``Part of the increase in
premiums in 2000 reflects that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
