<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CENTURY INVESTMENTS CREATES FUND TO INVEST IN NEW
BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
 CENTURY-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mutual fund giant
American Century Investments on Thursday announced the formation of
a $100 million fund to invest in new businesses in Kansas City and
around the nation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the same time, American Century Ventures Inc., the new
venture capital fund, announced a $2.5 million investment in Kansas
City-based RecordsCenter.com. RecordsCenter is an Internet-based
business that provides a secure way to exchange large legal
documents online.
</P>
<P>
   The new venture capital fund arrives amid a venture capital boom
in the Kansas City area. At least six new venture capital funds are
operating or about to begin operations in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Older venture capital groups such as Kansas City Equity Partners
and Commerce Bank-affiliated Capital for Business also are adding
to their portfolios of business investments.
</P>
<P>
   With $100 million in its pocket, American Century Ventures will
be among the largest such firms based in the area.
</P>
<P>
   American Century Ventures isn't a mutual fund in which
individuals can invest. All of the money is coming from American
Century's own resources, rather than any of its mutual funds or
from outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists traditionally invest in young or start-up
companies with an eye on blockbuster rewards. They know many of the
deals won't pan out, but expect to reap enough rewards from the
winners to more than make up for the losers.
</P>
<P>
   Such financial rewards won't be the driving force behind
American Century Ventures, said Harold Bradley, president of
American Century Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in it for the financial pop,'' Bradley said. ``It's
not that financials aren't important, they're just not primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's principal mission is to help build businesses that
will develop products and services that American Century can use to
do a better job investing and running its mutual funds, he said.
American Century not only will invest in these emerging companies
but also use their products, helping to develop or enhance them and
generate ideas for new products.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the emerging company can roll out the new or improved
products to a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   Such products might take many forms, Bradley said. He said they
could include broadband and wireless communications, data-mining
technologies and others that many kinds of businesses and
industries would use.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we were looking for in investors, a strategic
investor who has more than just a checkbook,'' said Brad Davis,
president of RecordsCenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   RecordsCenter.com has a similar relationship with C3 Holdings of
Kansas City, Davis said. C3 Holdings had provided ``seed'' money
for RecordsCenter.com, which began in 1997, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   RecordsCenter's products include DoxNet, Virtual BoardRoom,
Virtual Minutes and Virtual DataRoom.
</P>
<P>
   Such strategic thinking already had led American Century to
invest $38 million in seven venture deals. Among them are W.R.
Hambrecht &AMP; Co., an online investment banking firm in San
Francisco; TradePoint Financial Networks, an electronic stock
exchange in London; Archipelago in Chicago, an electronic stock
trading system; and Optimark Technologies in New Jersey, an online
trading system for large block trades among institutional
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Those investments have been added to American Century Ventures,
but aren't included in the $100 million yet to be invested, Bradley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley heads the venture after having managed the American
Century Heritage Fund for two years and having been head of
equities trading at American Century before that. He was
instrumental in arranging the seven early strategic investments,
and serves as a director in some of those ventures.
</P>
<P>
   American Century Ventures also has hired Diane Mulcahy as vice
president. She had been with a Boston-based venture capital firm
called Bessemer Venture Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kansas City is gaining more venture capital funds, the
investments aren't limited to Kansas City area companies. That will
be true of American Century Ventures, though its first announced
deal is with RecordsCenter.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley said American Century's connections to W.R.
Hambrecht in San Francisco and J.P. Morgan in New York, which owns
a large piece of American Century, could bring more venture capital
to Kansas City businesses. Bradley said he would pass along to
these partners any deals he saw potential in, but which he didn't
consider as strategic investments for American Century Ventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
