<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Friday, March 24, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055
or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running
in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BOFA _  &LR;  Bank of America fired far more employees than it
originally projected in the 16 months after North Carolina's
NationsBank took over the San Francisco bank, according to a
just-filed regulatory document.
</P>
<P>
   From October 1998, when NationsBank bought the old BofA and took
its name, through December 1999, 12,600 bank employees qualified
for severance packages, meaning their jobs were eliminated and no
comparable positions were offered, the bank said earlier this week
in its annual 10-K report filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; MANEX  &LR; _ On Sunday afternoon, a senior visual effects supervisor
from Manex Entertainment of Alameda will be shoulder to shoulder
with Hollywood's brightest stars, promenading the red carpet into
the Shrine Auditorium. There, he will wait anxiously to find out if
the startling illusions he helped craft for ``The Matrix'' will win
the Academy Award for best visual effects.
</P>
<P>
   For a small special effects company removed from Hollywood's
power orbit, Manex seems to be soaring high.
</P>
<P>
   Its creative director took home an Oscar last year for ``What
Dreams May Come,'' and the firm designed effects in this week's Jet
Li release ``Romeo Must Die'' and the upcoming ``Mission Impossible
2.'' In February, it hired a respected Industrial Light &AMP; Magic
veteran as its president and announced a new eight-figure infusion
of capital.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the company will bask in a different kind of
attention. An Alameda County Superior Court judge will hear
allegations that the man who's been running Manex for the 21/2,
managing director Robert Bobo, 29,  &LR; defrauded investors and is now
trying to hastily sell the firm for his own profit. By Carolyn Said
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
