<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-NAPSTER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Napster Hopes Update Ends College Bans  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Napster Inc. of San Mateo and Indiana University will test a new
system tomorrow that allows students to use the popular music
retrieval software without clogging the college's Internet
connections.
<P>
   If the two-week test is successful, it may help lift
restrictions against the program made by Indiana University and
about 100 colleges around North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have made a significant step working with them to
reduce the problem,'' said Eddie Kessler, Napster's vice president
of engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Napster has created a furor on both college campuses and in
recording company boardrooms with its software that gives users an
easy way to search and download hundreds of thousands of popular
songs over the Internet for free.
</P>
<P>
   So many college students were using Napster to download their
favorite MP3-compressed songs from other Napster users that it
caused digital traffic jams on their school's high-speed Internet
connections. Napster fans at Indiana University's Bloomington
campus, for example, were taking up to 60 percent of the school's
bandwidth before administrators blocked the program in February.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the test, Indiana University's Internet equipment
will now automatically give academic programs a higher priority
than recreational programs like Napster, said Mark Bruhn, the
college's information technology policy officer. So, for example, a
student using a Web browser to research a history project will get
that information before a student using Napster to download the
latest Dr. Dre song.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Napster's server software has been upgraded to first
search for songs located on the hard drives of computers tied to
Internet2, a new high-speed Internet network that connects Indiana
University and about 200 colleges and educational institutions.
This step keeps traffic off the busier World Wide Web. But if the
requested song is not on Internet2, Napster will search the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Bruhn said he wanted a solution not only to the Napster problem,
but to other similar bandwidth-hogging music and video sharing
programs that figure to crop up in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Napster has spawned similar programs like Macster,
Wrapster, iCrave and Gnutella.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to look ahead,'' Bruhn said. ``If it wasn't Napster,
maybe in four months time we'd have had another application we
would have trouble with.''
</P>
<P>
   Chad Paulson, a sophomore at Indiana University who started an
organization called Students Against University Censorship to fight
the Napster bans, was pleased with the test but suspicious that
university officials would use the results to banish Napster for
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to quit until all the schools have resolved
this issue,'' said Paulson, who has gathered 14,000 signatures on
an online petition at www.savenapster.com.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at Berkeley, which capped access to
off-campus Web sites like Napster, is monitoring the test, said
Cliff Frost, the school's director of communication and network
services.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at bennye(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
