<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
HULL HAS TOUCH, STAGE TO PUSH PAST HIS DAD (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD AND JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The questions have started again. Two months
later than expected, but in earnest nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody wants to know how Stars winger Brett Hull feels about
being two goals away from tying his father's career mark of 610.
</P>
<P>
   Well, considering he was nine goals away on Dec. 31, he says he
feels relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like there is light at the end of the tunnel,'' Hull
said. ``It's been frustrating at times.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he now has two goals in the past two games. Always a
streaky shooter, Hull has a tendency to score goals in bunches. He
also has demonstrated from time to time in his career a flair for
the dramatic. For example, his 600th and 601st goals came on New
Year's Eve, the last goal in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   So wouldn't it be just like Hull to score 610 against his
father's old team, the Chicago Blackhawks, tonight, or Sunday
against the Colorado Avalanche, when ABC has a lot of the country
watching?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on that streak. He's scoring during practice. Everything
is going in now,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``If he keeps
going like this, he's going to be a scary guy to play against
because he's unloading from anywhere and everywhere.'' NHL CLAMPS
DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thornton's three-game suspension for hitting San Jose's
Marco Sturm in the face with his forearm proved the NHL is taking a
no-tolerance stance on blows of any kind to the face or head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is everything. It probably couldn't come at a worse
time with everything that's been going on in this league for the
last month,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Hitting someone in the
face with anything is not a good idea right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's suspension came a day after the NHL suspended New
Jersey defenseman Scott Niedermayer for 10 games for his clubbing
of Florida winger Peter Worrell on top of the helmet with his
stick, and one month after Boston's Marty McSorley was suspended
for the final 23 games of the regular season for hitting
Vancouver's Donald Brashear near the temple with his stick.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's penalty was not as severe. He looked to have hit
Sturm with his forearm, but the referee called him for high
sticking and ruled it a match penalty, which automatically takes it
to the league for review. It was Thornton's first match penalty of
his 10-year career, and consequently, his first suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed and surprised,'' Thornton said. ``Even Marco
Sturm's agent, who spoke on his behalf (during Thursday's review),
admitted that I didn't hit him with my stick. I'm a first-time
offender after 10 years, and they did not even take that into
account.'' TOUGH DECISIONS
</P>
<P>
   It could get difficult for Ken Hitchcock to select his 20-player
roster come playoff time. The Stars will soon have an overload of
front-line talent, and someone will have to sit. Winger Blake Sloan
(ankle fracture) could return next week, and winger Jere Lehtinen
(ankle injury) still appears to be on track for an early April
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the younger guys are now vying for that starting
position in regard to the playoffs,'' Hitchcock said. ``I think
some guys, in particular people like Aaron Gavey, have earned the
right to stay in the lineup even if we do get healthy.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Grant Marshall's right groin seems healthy and Hitchcock
cleared him to play tonight against Chicago. Also cleared to play
is center Guy Carbonneau, who makes his return from a fractured
wrist.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ken Hitchcock said goalie Ed Belfour will likely play in seven
of the final nine regular-season games. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
