<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, MARCH 24
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(ss) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-EUROPE-GENES-FOOD-NYT (moved Monday, March 13)
</P>
<P>
   A front-page article sent on Monday, March 13 about opposition
in Europe to genetically modified food attributed an assertion
erroneously to Benedikt Haerlin, who leads a campaign against such
food for the environmental group Greenpeace. While he attacked the
conclusions reached by many scientists in the debate, he did not
refer to scientists as liars.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CUBAN-BOY-NYT (moved Tuesday, March 21.)
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, a front-page article sent on
Tuesday, March 21 about the dismissal of a lawsuit seeking a
political asylum hearing for Elian Gonzalez referred incorrectly in
some editions to the number of people who survived when Elian's
boat capsized while escaping from Cuba. Two adults survived; the
boy was not the sole survivor.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT (moved Sunday, March 12)
</P>
<P>
   A report in the Computer Briefs column sent on Sunday, March 12
about myCustoms.com, a new company, misstated a previous title held
by a founder, Manoj Karamchandani. He was a systems manager for
eBay, in charge of international Web site operations and
technology, not a vice president.
</P>
</TEXT>
