<HEADER>
A6349 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BOFA-BOFA_SFCHRON &LR;      03-23 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-BOFA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Layoffs at BofA Way Over Estimate  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Bank of America fired far more employees than it originally
projected in the 16 months after North Carolina's NationsBank took
over the San Francisco bank, according to a just-filed regulatory
document.
</P>
<P>
   From October 1998, when NationsBank bought the old BofA and took
its name, through December 1999, 12,600 bank employees qualified
for severance packages, meaning their jobs were eliminated and no
comparable positions were offered, the bank said earlier this week
in its annual 10-K report filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   BofA had estimated that 5,000 to 8,000 people would be dismissed
after the takeover as overlapping positions were cut.
</P>
<P>
   The 12,600 layoffs are part of the 19,000 to 20,000 jobs the
bank has said were cut after the takeover, more than 10 percent of
the bank's total head count. The remainder disappeared through
attrition as employees quit or retired and were not replaced. More
than 1,800 of the slashed jobs were in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The job figures, as well as other sensitive matters such as
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Hugh McColl's recently
disclosed $76 million pay package for 1999, were the subject of an
internal bank memorandum, described as a ``Senior Manager Blast
Fax,'' circulated this week.
</P>
<P>
   The document, a copy of which was obtained by The Chronicle,
gives managers guidance on what to tell inquisitive employees and
journalists about job and pay issues.
</P>
<P>
   If asked why the actual number of fired employees is so much
higher than the earlier estimate, the memo instructs managers to
explain that advanced technology allowed the bank to eliminate more
positions, that more opportunities were found to combine functions
and attrition was less than originally expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still some consolidation to go,'' the memo notes.
``However, we are busily engaged in business as usual, including
hiring people to fill openings.``
</P>
<P>
   BofA spokesman Robert Stickler said the documents were authentic
but declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, BofA disclosed McColl's compensation, as well
as similar but smaller packages given to President Kenneth Lewis
and Chief Financial Officer James Hance, in a filing with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   If asked why McColl's pay package was so large, the memo tells
managers to point out that BofA's chief hadn't received a raise
since 1997 and that the bank's profits rose nearly 27 percent in
1999. To explain a $72 million stock and options award for McColl,
the document notes he had built the bank into the nation's largest
and provided shareholders a compounded annual return of 23 percent
before the grant was made.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also points out that the executives got their awards
when the bank's stock price was more than $70. It has since fallen
to near $50, sharply reducing the grants' value.
</P>
<P>
   The bank ``must be expecting some negative fallout,'' said
Michael Stead, chief investment officer of Sife Trust Fund, a
Walnut Creek mutual fund that owns 20,000 BofA shares. ``Employees
are being laid off while McColl gets an incredibly rich
compensation package.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA's memo also addresses the recent departures of three former
directors from the old BofA from the combined bank's board,
including Richard Rosenberg, CEO of the San Francisco bank from
1990 through 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg left because he had reached the board's mandatory
retirement age of 70; retired Nestle executive Timm cq &LR;  Crull cq &LR; 
declined to stand for re-election; and General Motors executive
Shirley Young resigned because her principal occupation had
changed, the memo claims.  &LR; stated.
</P>
<P>
   A recently published report suggested the departures were
engineered to increase McColl's hold on the board, a contention the
memo denied.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
