<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STAKING OUT EDUCATION AS A MAJOR CAMPAIGN ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Fla., Ohio)   (rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ In a gesture meant to frame his education
proposals as expressions of concern for underprivileged and
minority children, Gov. George W. Bush plans a special visit on
Friday to the high school here where federal troops had to be
deployed in 1957 to enforce racial integration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush intends to make the case that more than 40 years after
Central High School became an early battleground in the fight for
civil rights, educational opportunities for American school
children of different races and classes are still unequal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we have a great challenge of our own,'' reads an advance
copy of Bush's remarks, which was provided by a senior campaign
official. ``Access is universal, but excellence is not. All can
enter our schools, but not all are learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous gap of achievement between rich and
poor, white and minority,'' the speech continues.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in Bush's brief but carefully honed address adds to the
education proposals that he laid out last year. They call, in part,
for a system of financial rewards and punishments to improve the
performances of public schools in poor areas and of the students
they serve.
</P>
<P>
   But the staging and evocative setting of the event, along with
the tenor of the planned remarks, offer the best proof yet of how
heavily Bush is betting on education as an issue that can expand
his appeal beyond the traditional Republican base and, more
importantly, convince moderate and swing voters that he is a
Republican they can feel good about supporting.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Bush's visit demonstrates anew his eagerness to wrap
himself in the kind of symbolism and place himself in the kinds of
tableaus that Republicans have often ceded to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Vice President Al Gore say that such gestures by Bush
are largely hollow, and that the substance of many of his proposals
belie his claims that they are intended to help needy Americans.
These critics say that what Bush is really accomplishing is an
oratorical and political sleight of hand.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's aides say that he is not only laying out initiatives
that would make measurable differences in children's lives but also
showing Americans the kind of tone he wants to set for the country,
and the kinds of words and actions that would be a part of his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public education _ the opportunity it creates _ are still
worth fighting for,'' according to Bush's prepared remarks, which
add that the issue is ``still worth the full attention of a
president.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Bush essentially secured the Republican
presidential nomination in primaries on March 14, he has faced
perhaps no challenge greater than wooing Americans in the center of
the political spectrum and assuring them that there is as much
emphasis on the first word as the second in his slogan of
compassionate conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   And from that moment, Bush has talked about education almost
incessantly. It was the issue receiving the most attention in his
victory speech in Austin, Texas, that night, and it was the subject
of his first general-election television commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in turn, has also focused on education during the last
week and a half, creating a surprising and somewhat unexpected
dynamic: The issue that has attracted perhaps the most debate by
Bush and Gore so far is one in which the federal government's
involvement is limited. Only about 7 percent of the financing for
public elementary and high schools comes from the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has consistently said that the president has a power,
through the bully pulpit, that transcends that figure, and he plans
to reiterate that point in Friday's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``A president does not bear responsibility for every policy in
every school in every district,'' the speech says. ``But a
president must be the keeper of our common ideals.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush has proposed that when public schools fail to improve,
federal money should be funneled instead to the parents of
students, so they could pursue other education options, or used to
encourage the growth of charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Though there is vigorous dispute among education experts about
the wisdom of the remedies, the Bush campaign feels that
emphasizing education works to his advantage. That was clear in his
advisers' willingness to divert attention to what Bush planned to
do in Little Rock even as Bush, in several appearances in Florida
Thursday, hammered Gore on other fronts.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday afternoon in Orlando, where he was
visiting a high school, Bush called Gore ``an obstacle to reform''
of the Social Security system and the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   The governor portrayed Gore as a politician hampered not only by
an investment in the status quo but by questions of ethics and
honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man who said he invented the Internet, and didn't,''
Bush said. ``He's a man who said during a debate he was responsible
for the earned income tax credit, yet it was passed two years
before his arrival in the United States Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at an elementary school in Cincinnati, Gore said Bush
was using ``personal negative attacks against me just as he did
against John McCain in the Republican primaries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
