<HEADER>
A6351 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MANEX-MANEX_SFCHRON &LR;      03-23 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANEX-MANEX </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 No Illusion _ Manex Boss Faces Real Lawsuit  &HT;     By Carolyn Said 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
On Sunday afternoon, a senior visual effects supervisor from Manex
Entertainment of Alameda will be shoulder to shoulder with
Hollywood's brightest stars, promenading the red carpet into the
Shrine Auditorium. There, he will wait anxiously to find out if the
startling illusions he helped craft for ``The Matrix'' will win the
Academy Award for best visual effects.
<P>
   For a small special effects company removed from Hollywood's
power orbit, Manex seems to be soaring high.
</P>
<P>
   Its creative director took home an Oscar last year for ``What
Dreams May Come,'' and the firm designed effects in this week's Jet
Li release ``Romeo Must Die'' and the upcoming ``Mission Impossible
2.'' In February, it hired a respected Industrial Light &AMP; Magic
veteran as its president and announced a new eight-figure infusion
of capital.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the company will bask in a different kind of
attention. An Alameda County Superior Court judge will hear
allegations that the man who's been running Manex for the 21/2,
managing director Robert Bobo, 29,  &LR; defrauded investors and is now
trying to hastily sell the firm for his own profit.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers filed in the lawsuit describe a labyrinth of
promises, financial entanglements and alleged deceptions as
intricately byzantine as the world within a world of ``The
Matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobo, 29, referred calls on the matter to his attorneys, who
said they were ``vigorously defending Mr. Bobo and the companies''
but considered it inappropriate to comment further on the eve of a
hearing. Their court filings in the case said there is insufficient
evidence to support the accusations and claims of ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But those claiming part ownership of Manex _ Michael Van
Himbergen of Santa Rosa, Roger Davis of Novato and Dr. Steven
Gillam of England _ say they have plenty of proof to back up their
assertions.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents reviewed by The Chronicle show letters and
agreements that appear to show Van Himbergen, Davis and Gillam have
stakes in Manex, although the amount and other details are murky.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts in the early 1990s, when a group of special
effects pros in Massachusetts created an f/x  &LR; a special-effects
house called Mass.Illusion, owned by Cinergy, a small independent
movie studio (``Judge Dredd'').
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Cinergy was foundering financially and needed to sell
Mass.Illusion. It asked Van Himbergen and Davis to find investors
to take over the company.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mass.Illusion had almost $1 million in debt, it had
some valuable assets: a ``brain trust'' of highly talented effects
wizards, and a $7.5 million contract to produce the special effects
for ``What Dreams May Come.'' And Mass.Illusion had already
submitted test shots for ``The Matrix'' that had impressed the
movie's co-writers/directors, brothers Andy and Larry Wachowski.
</P>
<P>
   Van Himbergen, who had worked as an executive producer at
Mass.Illusion, said in an interview and in court documents that he
arranged to turn the firm over to Bobo and George Q. Vaile of the
Manex Group of Ohio in exchange for Manex assuming the debt.
</P>
<P>
   For his part of the deal and for helping turn the company
around, court documents state, Van Himbergen was promised part
ownership of up to 30 percent of Manex, while Davis was promised 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But, the lawsuit states, another 50 percent of Manex was
promised to Gillam.
</P>
<P>
   Bobo took over running the company from Vaile in November 1997,
but Van Himbergen said in an interview that he still played a vital
role in Manex. ``Bobo had zero contacts in our industry. I gave him
all of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Himbergen said he had ``invested nine months of my life'' in
Manex, creating a business plan, teaching the new managers from
Manex how to run a studio, and creating other opportunities, first
as an executive producer, then as vice president of strategic
relationships. He said he masterminded its move to the sprawling
Alameda Naval Air Station in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And while two other sources who said they were involved in the
transaction confirmed Van Himbergen's view of events, one noted,
``Everyone's going to tell you something a little inflated. There
were a lot of people who helped'' engineer the deal and ``educate''
the new Manex management.
</P>
<P>
   But as time wore on, Van Himbergen said, he became wary of
Bobo's business practices. ``I watched Bobo time and again lie to
employees, to service providers, to goods providers, to the film
companies we had contracts with,'' he said in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   A disillusioned Davis quit Manex in October 1997. Van Himbergen
hung on until May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to cajole, remind and force (Bobo and Vaile) to make
good on their promises'' about an ownership stake in the firm, Van
Himbergen said in an interview, but were met with ``a whole
cascade'' of obfuscations and excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, according to court documents, Gillam was pressuring
Bobo to repay a $150,000 loan. Bobo offered Gillam something that
might prove more lucrative: majority ownership of intellectual
property created at Manex, the documents said. In exchange, Gillam
agreed to reduce his ownership stake to 15 percent and forgive the
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Like most special-effects houses, Manex uses high-end software
to create its effects but also writes its own custom code or
``special sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Matrix,'' Manex had created breakthrough technologies,
called FloMo and Bullet Time, that enabled the stylish effects
where actors Keanu Reeves and Carrie-Anne Moss hover in midair
before delivering ferocious karate kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Gillam asked to get copies of the software so he could turn it
into a commercial package, but was rebuffed, according to the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit estimates that Manex racked up as much as $50
million in sales for its work on a string of big-budget Hollywood
features and several smaller projects, but says that Bobo ``has
failed to account for the millions received.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the glamour of creating dazzling effects that awe
millions of moviegoers, most effects firms struggle to survive on
profit margins of about 6 percent, according to Daily Variety.
Firms might underbid to land a high-profile project. Several
special-effects houses, including Manex, are trying to expand their
revenues with plans to produce their own films.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Manex said it planned to launch its own small studio,
along the lines of Miramax or New Line Cinema, and would soon start
producing films at the Alameda base. Those plans have not yet come
to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing their custom technologies _ like Manex's FloMo and
Bullet Times _ is another way special-effects houses can make
money, industry experts said. ``Unless you know how to harvest the
IP (intellectual property), what you have is a service business
that can barely pay its bills even though the cash flow is really
high,'' said a special effects producer describing the
special-effects industry.
</P>
<P>
   Today's hearing asks for a restraining order to prevent a sale
of Manex. The lawsuit claims that Bobo is attempting to sell Manex
for about $20 million in an attempt to defraud Davis, Van Himbergen
and Gillam of their ownership rights.
</P>
<P>
   According to Davis' court declaration, the sale is being handled
by Jed Dumas of Bear Sterns in San Francisco. Dumas, managing
director in the private client service group, said yesterday that
neither Bear Sterns nor he have been engaged to seek a buyer for
Manex.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of the allegations in the lawsuit are true or not, a
wide range of effects professionals agree that Manex has a hugely
talented staff.
</P>
<P>
   Why would they stay at a firm that's under a cloud?
</P>
<P>
   It might be because the lawsuit allegations are unfounded. Or it
might be because of the nature of the people drawn to the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effects is very passionate work,'' said one producer. ``People
are much more wedded to projects that are interesting and cool than
to things like ownership of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Another producer said, ``This isn't Silicon Valley. These are
all free-lancers basically; maybe $10,000-a-week free-lancers. As
long as they're getting a paycheck and working on a movie'' they're
happy. ``The gold is the Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; E-mail Carolyn Said at csaid(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
