<SLUG> BC-SRS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY KANSAS FAMILIES STRUGGLE AFTER LEAVING WELFARE, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONNA McGUIRE  
c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Many former welfare
families in Kansas struggle after leaving cash-assistance rolls, a
yearlong state study has found.
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a third of the 809 families studied returned to
welfare, most within six months of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Less than half the parents remaining off welfare had jobs _ a
lower work rate than many other states have reported _ and most of
those parents earned wages below poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   A third of the families reported trouble paying bills. And
despite financial problems, many eligible families were not
receiving food stamps, Medicaid or state-assisted child care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study findings suggest that families...are subject to
multiple social, emotional, intellectual and other barriers to
successful, long-term employment,'' said Janet Schalansky,
secretary of the Kansas Department of Social and Rehabilitation
Services.
</P>
<P>
   State welfare policies must evolve to address those problems,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas welfare rolls have fallen by nearly half, to 12,152
families in January, since the state implemented work requirements
and changed other welfare rules in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the study's findings, such as low wages, mirrored those
being reported across the country. However, at least six states
have announced much higher work rates, ranging from 61 to 71
percent. And in 1999, The Kansas City Star found that 69 percent of
former Jackson County, Mo., recipients surveyed had jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, slightly more than 40 percent of adults who left
welfare were employed.
</P>
<P>
   SRS hopes to improve work rates by putting additional emphasis
on job retention skills and training to promote job advancement.
SRS also plans to provide on-the-job coaching and mentoring and to
help more former recipients gain access to food stamps or other
services that could help ease their financial burdens. For those
programs, the state for the first time will maintain contact with
families after they leave welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Many states embraced job training and education for welfare
clients prior to welfare reforms of the mid-1990s. Those reforms
set time limits on benefits and instituted a ``work first''
philosophy, which pushed clients to seek work immediately.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the former Kansas recipients surveyed were
earning $7 or less per hour one year after leaving welfare. That
wage amounts to $14,560 a year for full-time work, an income below
poverty for a family of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to sustain them,'' said Stacey Herman, an SRS
spokeswoman. ``We need to think about how we can get these people
promoted in their jobs and how we can train them so they can get
better jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings raise many questions, some of which state officials
hope to answer through a follow-up study, Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   State employees conducted the study between December 1997 and
November 1998 from a random sample of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Other results:
</P>
<P>
   About half the families thought they were better off financially
than they had been on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Those unemployed most frequently cited health, transportation
and child care problems as barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after leaving assistance, nearly one in five
parents said they lacked enough money for food. By a year after
leaving, only about one in 12 reported that problem.
</P>
<P>
   One in five families had been evicted from their homes within a
year of leaving welfare, and nearly a third had lost utility
service. About a fourth had sought help from family or friends.
Only about 2 percent had turned to food pantries or other community
agencies for help.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one in five families were thrown off welfare for not
meeting work rules, and 7 percent were discharged for not
cooperating with child support enforcement rules. Though parents
said they understood why they lost benefits, some did not realize
they could have qualified for exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
