<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- March 23, 2000 -- ART-NOTES-2 -- With the
important spring and summer auctions approaching, Sotheby's and
Christie's have begun crowing about the big-ticket works they have
to offer. Great old masters have traditionally been sold in London,
and while sales of such paintings and drawings by Christie's and
Sotheby's in New York have been growing stronger, often eclipsing
auctions in London, Christie's is still saving a few jewels for its
major old master drawings sale in London on July 4. The star will
be this Michelangelo drawing, ``Study for the Risen Christ,'' in
pen, and red and black chalk, a study for a marble statue
commissioned for the Church of Santa Maria sopra Minerva in Rome.
(Christie's/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- March 23, 2000 -- ART-NOTES-1 -- With the
important spring and summer auctions approaching, Sotheby's and
Christie's have begun crowing about the big-ticket works they have
to offer. And with all the negative publicity from the continuing
federal antitrust investigation into their practices, both
companies are more determined than ever to put out the word that
business is going on as usual. Christie's says it will have the
season's most important work: ``Still Life With Tulips,'' a 1932
portrait by Pablo Picasso of his mistress Marie-Therese Walter. The
painting, seen here, estimated to go for $25 million to $30
million, is to be auctioned in New York on May 9. (Christie's/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 23, 2000 -- WHITNEY-BIENNIAL-4 --
``Sanitation,'' an installation by Hans Haacke, a well-known
German-born New York artist, puts Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani in the
company of the Nazis, with quotations by him written in the Fraktur
script favored by the Third Reich and the sound of jackboots
marching eminating from open garbage cans. The artwork, which is on
view at the Whitney Museum during its 2000 biennial, recalls the
fury over the First Amendment issues raised by the ``Sensation''
exhibition at the city-subsidized Brooklyn Museum of Art last fall
when Giuliani attacked some of the art work as ``sick'' and
``disgusting.'' (Richard Perry/The New Times)
</P>
