<P>
   (NYT35) JERUSALEM -- March 23, 2000 -- POPE-SURVIVOR -- Pope
John Paul II made Edith Tzirer cry Thursday at the Yad Vashem
Holocaust memorial. Tzirer, a Holocaust survivor, had been waiting
54 years to thank him in person for saving her life, she said.
Tzirer said that she was 14 in 1945 and had just been released from
the Skarzysko-Kamienna labor camp, in a small town near Krakow,
Poland. She was too weak to walk to the trains exiting town, she
told the concerned, young seminary student whose name was Karol
Wojytla. So he picked her up and carried her several kilometers in
the snow. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) UNDATED -- March 23, 2000 -- NY-ASIAN-ART-2 -- In these
first days of spring, Asia Week has blown into town like a lion and
like a lamb. It brings the roar of big-deal auctions and a big-guns
art fair. It also offers a chance to linger quietly over a
fantastic array of Asian art. A Mughal portrait is on display at
Terence McInerney's Asian Art Fair booth. (Terence McInerney
Ltd./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- March 23, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 26 --
HOMEBREW-COMPUTER-CLUB-3 -- Twenty five years ago a weapons
designer and a peace activist called the first meeting of he
Homebrew Computer Club in Menlo Park, Calif., that turned out to be
the birth of the personal computer revolution. Frederick Moore Jr.
was the activist who called the first meeting of the club in a
garage in Palo Alto, Calif., in 1975. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 23, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH
26 -- HOMEBREW-COMPUTER-CLUB-2 -- The emergence of the PC as the
ubiquitous tool of the information age had its roots in the
Homebrew Club. A central value of its founders - the free sharing
of information - has until recently been submerged in the Silicon
Valley gold rush. Dan Sokol, who copied the punched tape of
Microsoft's first commercial program in 1975, still believes he did
the right thing. Bill Gates feels otherwise. (Thor Swift/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
