<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-VOA-USIA-WOMEN-ART-NY     03-23 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOA-USIA-WOMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID CELEBRATION OF SETTLEMENT, WOMEN RECALL PAIN OF BIAS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.M., Kan.)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 41, 42 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mh) 
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shirley Hill Witt has a doctorate in anthropology.
She taught at Colorado College and the University of North
Carolina. She went on to become the mountain states regional
director for the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights and then the state
of New Mexico's secretary for natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   But for several years, Witt, now retired at age 65 and living in
the hills outside Albuquerque, N.M., felt like a failure because
she could not get the job she coveted most: foreign service officer
with the U.S. Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
   She took the arduous battery of tests in 1981, sat for oral
exams and ``was led to believe that I did very well,'' she recalled
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She came up short, however, in one area where no amount of
competence or preparation would help: She was not a man. It took
four years to get hired, after which she was assigned to Venezuela,
Somalia, Zambia and Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the government paid the price for Witt's four
years in limbo. She was among the 1,100 women who won $508 million,
about $460,000 each, in the nation's costliest sex-discrimination
case ever. After 23 years of litigation against the U.S.
Information Agency and the broadcasting organization it once
oversaw, the Voice of America, the government gave up _ but without
acknowledging that it had routinely discriminated against women in
hiring and promotion. A judge must still approve the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The suit asserted that the agencies had manipulated the hiring
process to exclude women, in some cases resorting to fraud,
altering test scores and destroying personnel and test files.
</P>
<P>
   The Voice of America has consistently denied the accusations,
and no disciplinary action was ever taken against the agencies'
managers as a result of the claims. The information agency no
longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Thursday, several of the women who were part of
the suit recounted the jolts of inexplicable rejection. Many of
them had been achievers in school and in their early careers, and
they said that in applying for the jobs in question in the 1970s
through the mid-1980s, they had taken all the right steps. But
while often assured they would be hired, they said they waited and
waited while transparently less qualified men were hired.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were ecstatic about the size of the settlement,
large enough to compensate for the wages they might have earned.
But they also spoke of the pain of feeling they had failed to
measure up to the needs of a government they trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could be compensated for the desperation and sense of
worthlessness I had then,'' said Teri Schaefer, 45, an education
reporter for Fox 4 News in Kansas City. She passed the tests to
join the Voice of America in 1983 but could never land a job, while
men were hired routinely. ``The money doesn't make up for that,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer said she was newly married in 1983 and bent on finding
a job when she took a written test for a news writing or news
announcing job. ``I was told I passed, but was told there were no
openings,'' she recalled. ``There were never any openings.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of months, Schaefer said, she found a full-time
job for a small broadcasting company. ``But I continued to call
VOA,'' she said, because jobs there were more stable and had good
benefits. Oddly, she noticed, the agency was hiring, but mostly
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never said, `We have too many girls here,''' Schaefer
said, ``although the person who interviewed me did say, `We don't
have many girls here.'''
</P>
<P>
   A decade earlier, in 1972, Dilara Hashem rapped on the same
doors. Then a refugee from Karachi, Pakistan, and living in London,
she applied for a visa. In Karachi, Hashem, now 64, had been a
radio news reader. She had also written two novels, and she spoke
nearly flawless English.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to join the Voice of America, whose broadcasts she had
admired back in Pakistan, she applied for a job and passed the
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Hashem recalled that once she was settled in Washington with a
visa, ``They said, `OK, we can take you part time.' No benefits, no
leave.'' Then she saw three men, one from Calcutta and two from
Bangladesh, sail into full-time jobs. All, she said, were far less
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1976, she lost the the part-time job. She said the
agency told her it was because of budget pressures, but at the same
time, VOA hired a man from Bangladesh to do just what she had been
doing. ``He had no broadcasting experience,'' she said. ``I felt so
humiliated when they let me go.''
</P>
<P>
   Hashem now has a full-time job broadcasting at the agency, and
her programs on American music and American life are heard
throughout Bangladesh. She has written 17 more books, mostly
novels.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Woolf said she was smitten by her father's career as a
foreign service officer. She lived abroad with her family until she
was 14, and she speaks French and Arabic. ``I liked the lifestyle,
the career, and felt I was fully grounded for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Woolf, now 54 and editing news for an Internet communications
company, sought her niche in the information agency in radio and
television. In time, the agency gave her a three-year assignment to
NATO in Brussels, Belgium, as director of the organization's
broadcasting operation.
</P>
<P>
   There, she said, ``I was encouraged by senior colleagues to
apply for lateral entry into the foreign service,'' which she said
would have opened more opportunities to use her expertise in the
media. She took all the tests, she said. ``I thought I had
passed,'' she recalled. ``Lo and behold, I was told I had failed. I
was told I was too much of a specialist.''
</P>
<P>
   She stayed for six more years, but after repeatedly failing to
get the work she felt she was qualified for, Woolf gave up on the
information agency in 1991 to become media services director for
the Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went right to the core of my self-esteem,'' she said. For
the women who spent 23 years fighting back, Woolf said, ``it was
the shaking down of your self-confidence that kept us all together,
all fighting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
