impersonator named Julian Eltinge, has been uncovered from layers
of paint in the theater that once bore the actor's name. The
theater, located on 42nd Street, is set to reopen as a new
25-screen AMC Empire multiplex later this month. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT45) UNDATED -- March 23, 2000 -- OBIT-FINE-B&AMP;W -- Vivian
Fine, a composer who wrote ballet scores for Martha Graham and Jose
Limon, as well as copious amounts of orchestral, chamber and vocal
music, died Monday at the Southern Vermont Medical Center in
Bennington after an automobile accident. She was 86 and lived in
Hoosick Falls, N.Y. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT44) MOSCOW -- March 23, 2000 -- RUSSIA-WOMAN-CANDIDATE --
Ella Pamfilova, right, is the sole woman in a field of 11 in
Russia's presidential election on Sunday. Despite her low ratings,
she met some ardent supporters at a flower-arranging exhibition in
Moscow. (James Hill/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT43) ANNAPOLIS, Md. -- March 23, 2000 -- MARYLAND-GUNS -- In
response to growing public and political pressure for stronger gun
control laws, the Maryland Senate put aside legislative tradition
Thursday to bypass a critical committee and bring to floor debate
Gov. Parris N. Glendening's proposal for mandatory locks on all new
handguns. The bill would enact one of the toughest laws in the
country, mandating attachable trigger locks this year and built-in
locks in three years, with an eye toward monitoring technology.
(Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) BALLSTON, Va. -- March 23, 2000 -- VOA-USIA-WOMEN-2 --
Donna Woolf was among the 1,100 women awarded $508 million - about
$460,000 each - in their sex discrimination case against the United
States Information Agency. Woolf, who speaks French and Arabic,
tried to make inroads at the USIA in the area of radio and
television, but was told she ``was too much of a specialist.'' She
left in 1991 to become media services director for the Agency for
International Development. ``It went right to the core of my
self-esteem,'' she said of her inability to get ahead at the USIA.
(Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) WASHINGTON -- March 23, 2000 -- VOA-USIA-WOMEN-1 --
Dilara Hashem was one of 1,100 women awarded $508 million - about
$460,000 each - in the nation's costliest sex discrimination case
ever, against the United States Information Agency. In 1972, Hashem
was eager to join the Voice of America, whose broadcasts she had
admired back in Pakistan. Once settled in Washington, she recalled
that ``They said, 'OK, we can take you part time.' No benefits, no
leave.'' Then she saw three men sail into full-time jobs, all of
whom, she said, were far less experienced. (Susana Raab/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) UNDATED -- March 23, 2000 -- MARGIN-TRADING-RISKS --
Borrowing money to buy stocks has become immensely popular among
individual investors. And who can blame them? But market regulators
are growing concerned that the recent surge in investor
indebtedness, which has been greatest at online brokerage firms,
reflects the participation of many people who do not understand how
dangerous stock market debt can be. (Naum Kazhdan/The New York
Times)
</P>
