the Homebrew Computer Club in Menlo Park, Calif., that turned out
to be the birth of the personal computer revolution. John T.
Draper, an early member of the club, was known as ``Cap'n Crunch''
for using a cereal-box whistle to unlock telephone technology.
(Thor Swift/The New York Times)
