<P>
   (NYT19) PUNTA ABREOJOS, Mexico -- March 23, 2000 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., MAR. 2 -- MEXICO-WHALES-COX-1 -- The village of Punta
Abreojos with its 1,000 inhabitants has run a fishing cooperative
since the 1930s that exports abalone, lobster and other seafood to
Asia and the United States. As the last gray whale breeding habitat
on Baja's coast that is untouched by commercial development, many
fishermen are developing campsites and whale watching for tourists
here. But that activity only lasts for several months out of the
year. Most have to seek work elsewhere or return to fishing
full-time to make a living. Women from Punta Abreojos shuck abalone
at the prosperous fishing cooperative. (Susan Ferriss/Cox News
Service)
</P>
