``Sanitation,'' an installation by Hans Haacke, a well-known
German-born New York artist, puts Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani in the
company of the Nazis, with quotations by him written in the Fraktur
script favored by the Third Reich and the sound of jackboots
marching eminating from open garbage cans. The artwork, which is on
view at the Whitney Museum during its 2000 biennial, recalls the
fury over the First Amendment issues raised by the ``Sensation''
exhibition at the city-subsidized Brooklyn Museum of Art last fall
when Giuliani attacked some of the art work as ``sick'' and
``disgusting.'' (Richard Perry/The New Times)
