<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FLA24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush stomps for cash and votes
 &HT;    in Florida
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Should U.S. Sen. Bob Graham become Vice
President Al Gore's running mate, winning Florida will become more
difficult, Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Graham on the vice president's ticket, Bush said he
is not taking Florida for granted and the Sunshine State is vital
to his plans for winning the presidency. ``That's why I'm back
here,'' said Bush, who campaigned in Orlando and West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Describing Graham as a ``respected senator,'' Bush said while
Graham would ``increase the degree of difficulty ... I could still
carry this state.'' Recent polls suggest that Florida is up for
grabs and Gore believes he has a reasonable chance of winning the
state despite the fact that Bush's younger brother, Jeb, is
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked about his prospects here during a 20-minute
interview with four Florida reporters. He also said that while he
believes the United States needs to increase its domestic oil
exploration to decrease the nation's dependency on foreign imports,
he would oppose exploration off Florida's coast.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating his charge that Gore ``will say anything to get
elected,'' Bush said that Democrats are trying to portray him as a
failed governor who has led his state to the brink of
environmental, educational and social disaster. He said Texans
would not have overwhelmingly reelected him if he was doing a poor
job.
</P>
<P>
   While he often criticizes Gore for a ``Washington mentality,''
Bush said that Washington experience will not disqualify someone
from becoming his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke favorably about U.S. Sen. Connie Mack but said he has
not given any thought to potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   At the Hilton, Bush met privately with many of his major
contributors before giving a brief speech in a banquet room
occupied by elected officials and people who gave at least $1,000
to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's staff said the campaign raised about $750,000 during this
trip.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bush's first trip to Florida since locking up the
Republican nomination. He was greeted at the Hilton by his brother,
House Speaker John Thrasher of Jacksonville and local GOP
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to bring a new attitude to Washington, D.C.,'' Bush
told the crowd. ``Let's get rid of the ugliness and the name
calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County Commissioner Warren Newell came with a note
for Bush from his three children.
</P>
<P>
   Newell said he gave a similar note to former President George
Bush and Newell's kids got a nice letter from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to get a response the same way they got one from
his dad,'' said Newell.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bush spent a couple of hours at Colonial
High School in Orlando where he talked to about 400 students in the
school gym for about 30 minutes before answering about a dozen
questions on topics ranging from relations between China and Taiwan
to whether Social Security will be available when they grow older.
</P>
<P>
   The question that got the loudest applause and cheers was about
increasing gas prices, which hurt the pockets of high school
drivers who usually earn only minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like we have a lot of drivers here,'' said Bush as the
applause died down. He told the students that if he were president,
he would force OPEC ``to open the spigots.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush left West Palm Beach around 7 p.m. for a campaign trip to
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post staff writer Trebor Banstetter contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
