<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MARYLAND-GUNS-ART-855     03-23 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARYLAND-GUNS-ART-855&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND SENATE BRINGS GUN LOCKS TO FLOOR DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 43 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. _ Amid growing public and political pressure for
stronger gun control laws, the Maryland Senate put aside
legislative tradition on Thursday to bypass a critical committee
and bring to floor debate Gov. Parris N. Glendening's proposal for
mandatory locks on all new handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which had been stalled in committee until some unusual
parliamentary maneuvering on Thursday morning, would enact one of
the toughest laws in the country, mandating attachable trigger
locks this year and built-in locks in three years, with an eye
toward monitoring technology and eventually requiring ``smart
guns'' operable solely by lawful owners once the technology is
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has reached a point of real frustration that is on
the verge of turning to anger,'' Glendening said in an interview.
``What the public is saying is: no more,'' he added, citing strong
public polling support for the proposal, which includes a mandate
that manufacturers provide ballistic signatures for each new gun to
aid in tracking gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recorded this forever,'' Glendening, a Democrat, said in his
Statehouse office after monitoring and downloading the debate with
his laptop computer and hearing gun-control opponents, caught
short, rising to demand points of order and vowing to fight further
through filibusters.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the governor predicted passage of the bill by both
houses now that the measure had been forced by a Senate majority
from the powerful Judicial Proceedings Committee, a panel where the
proposal had earlier been pronounced dead by most members, many
from rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was brought to the floor in the
Democratic-controlled Senate on a 26-19 vote, with five Democrats
joining the Senate's 14 Republicans in opposition. Glendening
predicted that the 32 votes needed to end filibusters in the
47-member Senate would be found within a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago, no one gave us a chance on this,'' Glendening
said of the proposal, emphasizing that in his view, the opposition
lawmakers saw the ground cut from under them in the last week by
Smith &AMP; Wesson's agreement with President Clinton to begin
marketing ``smart guns'' within three years. Statehouse opponents
here had sought to put off the subject of gun control by arguing
that ``smart gun'' technology, one of the features in the
governor's proposal, was totally impractical.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a key psychological breakthrough,'' Glendening said
as he also cited growing public disgust with repeated instances of
sensational gun violence, including the harrowing disruption of a
Baltimore suburb this week when a suspect in four gun deaths held
hostages and was finally shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the excesses of the National Rifle Association in
personally attacking the president are producing a very negative
reaction in the public,'' the governor added. ``In a moderate to
progressive state like ours, all the NRA is doing is solidifying
people and making them stronger in their resolve to control gun
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor cited in particular the ``courage'' of the Senate
president, Thomas V. Mike Miller Jr., a Prince George's County
Democrat, in finally deciding to bypass the traditional committee
process in a floor maneuver that had not been used in decades.
Miller, whose district includes the Beretta U.S.A. gun factory,
described Thursday as ``D Day'' on the deadlocked gun control
issue. He agreed that trigger lock legislation favored by many
could reach the floor for debate once the smart gun question had
been deferred by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than an immediate endorsement of smart guns that
Glendening originally proposed, technological progress toward the
gun would be monitored annually by the Legislature instead. This
was a concession the governor quickly made once Smith &AMP; Wesson made
its commitment to market smart guns nationally on the same
three-year timetable he sought in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening had campaigned strongly on gun control promises in
both his winning campaigns for governor. He made the state the
first in the nation to adopt legislation that prevents individuals
from buying more than one gun a month. The measure, adopted four
years ago, has since been passed in other states. He also took the
lead in the smart gun proposal, deferring that when legislative
leaders agreed to bypass the committee and to a compromise package
that protects the rest of the governor's proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond gun locks, the measure would bar anyone with a record as
a juvenile offender from buying firearms until the age of 30 and
would require training lessons for new handgun buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest state opinion polls showed 67 percent support for
approving smart guns, the governor noted, and _ for the first time
_ a 54 percent majority favoring an outright ban on handguns, if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more willing to do something about this,''
Glendening said. ``People are saying if you can't do something
about it, such as smart guns, then let's get rid of it all
together.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The governor has been citing the problem of gun violence in
virtually every speech lately, emphasizing that more than 7,000
state residents have been killed by guns in the last decade. A
natural disaster costing 7,000 lives in Baltimore would summon
furious demands from the public to take action, he tells audiences.
``Yet because we kill one another one at a time, there's not the
same sense of outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Constantly updating a list of vivid national incidents of fatal
shooting sprees, Glendening regularly tells constituents, ``Think
about what you have seen in the news for the last two months and
ask whether we're going to live the rest of our lives this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from shying from the controversial gun issue, Glendening has
built his career around it, beginning with 12 years service as the
elected chief executive of Prince George's County, a Washington
suburb with a history of substantial gun violence. ``I buried eight
police officers in my 12 years there,'' he grimly noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be the first state in the country to mandate that every
new gun must have an integrated lock system,'' he said, predicting
that other states would follow suit in the face of what he
described as a growing public resolve to press the gun-control
issue upon reluctat politicians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
