<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORGAN STANLEY NET UP 49 PERCENT IN QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riding a surge in trading of stocks and bonds, Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter &AMP; Co. reported Thursday that its first-quarter net
income rose 49 percent, making it the fourth big investment bank to
post stronger than expected earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley, the biggest firm on Wall Street measured by
market value, benefited in various ways from investors' seemingly
insatiable appetite for the securities of companies in technology
and telecommunications industries. As an investment bank, the firm
is a leader in underwriting stock offerings for high-technology
companies; as a brokerage firm and mutual fund manager, it feeds
demand for those stocks from individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   All of those businesses have been running at record levels so
far this year, fattening profits for all of the established
securities firms.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley earned $1.54 billion, or $1.34 a diluted share,
in the quarter ended Feb. 29. That was 5 percent less than the
record $1.62 billion Morgan Stanley earned in the previous quarter
but much more than the $1.04 billion, or 88 cents a share, it
earned in the 1999 period.
</P>
<P>
   The results easily surpassed analysts' forecasts of $1.06 a
share. Shares of Morgan Stanley rose $4.50, to $94.75, on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing that Morgan Stanley's executives predicted no
slowdown in stock and bond issuance or merger activity over the
next few months, analysts started raising their estimates of the
firm's earnings for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was another blockbuster result in the brokerage
industry,'' said Richard Strauss, an analyst at Goldman Sachs
Group. ``Trading, like at the other firms, was huge last quarter,
and our sense is that nothing has changed in that regard in this
early part of the second quarter. Meanwhile, investment banking is
going to really kick in big in the second quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The firm's revenue from investment banking held steady from the
previous quarter at about $1.34 billion. Included in that amount
are the fees the firm received for advising companies on takeovers,
like the German telecommunications company Mannesmann's $33 billion
acquisition of Orange PLC. But the firm is still awaiting receipt
of fees for several other huge mergers and acquisitions that have
been announced but have not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The backlog of deals is higher than it was a year ago and the
flow of IPOs looks like it will continue to be robust,'' said
Robert Scott, the firm's chief financial officer. Scott said
commissions at the Dean Witter brokerage unit hit new highs,
despite the firm's efforts to switch more of its individual
customers to paying annual fees instead of commissions on their
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Trading revenue doubled from the previous quarter, to $2.28
billion, and commissions rose 32 percent, to $1.04 billion.
Overall, the firm's net revenue _ revenue after interest expense _
was $7.41 billion, up 39 percent from $5.34 billion in the first
quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Scott also said the firm had postponed for several months its
plan to raise prices for customers of its original online-trading
system, which was called Discover Brokerage. The firm is rolling
that operation, which charged a basic commission of $14.95 a trade,
into its new service, which charges $29.95 a trade. Morgan Stanley
has not disclosed how many online accounts its customers have
opened or how much trading they do. To attract online traders, the
firm has opened two branches exclusively for them, one on Park
Avenue in Manhattan and one in San Francisco, Scott said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
