</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMUGGLING OF IRAQI OIL IS RISING, U.N. IS TOLD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Steeply rising oil prices have brought a huge
increase in the smuggling of Iraqi oil, the U.S. coordinator of the
international fleet that patrols the waters off Iraq told a
Security Council committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The coordinator, Vice Adm. Charles Moore, told the committee on
sanctions against Iraq that much of the oil passes through Iranian
waters, diplomats said after the closed briefing. The admiral
coordinates a small fleet from more than a dozen nations that
polices the Persian Gulf, looking for ships that violate an
international embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Moore and his team from the Pentagon told the committee that a
political or diplomatic overture to Iran was necessary if the
smuggling was to be curtailed, according to the representative of
the Netherlands, Peter van Walsum, who is chairman of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not discussed anything of that sort yet,'' van Walsum
said after the meeting. He said the subject could be raised at the
panel's next meeting, for which no date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said that Moore, briefing the committee the
day before a debate on the sanctions, reported that at current
rates of oil shipments, Iraq could earn up to a billion dollars
this year in illegal sales. Diplomats said the profits go directly
to Saddam Hussein or those he chooses to reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate of smuggling is at record levels,'' a Western
diplomat said. The oil, often bought and sold by private brokers
using ships with fraudulent papers, goes to many destinations,
including Iran, Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
   Iranians skim part of the profit, diplomats said. It is not
known whether the Iranians enriching themselves by allowing tankers
to use their territorial waters are backed by the government in any
way. But twice in the past _ in March and September of 1998 _ the
Iranians were able to shut down the trade, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   According to Western diplomats who heard Moore's briefing, Iraq
was able to illegally export 1,868,466 barrels of oil in 1996,
10,497,000 barrels the following year, 13,296,000 barrels in 1998
and 7,557,838 barrels in 1999. If current prices stay high, it is
estimated that Iraq will sell about 4.8 tons of illegal gas oil _
akin to diesel fuel _ this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the trend continues,'' a diplomat said, ``more oil will be
smuggled out of Iraq this year than the total smuggled out in the
last four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that the oil comes from fields at Basra and is
exported on vessels from the Iraqi port of Abu Flus. This port is
not authorized for exports by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   All smuggled Iraqi oil is by its nature outside the control and
surveillance of the ``oil for food'' program, in which the United
Nations allows Iraq to sell a limited amount of oil so it can buy
food and other necessities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2239EST &QL; 
