<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PLAN TO KEEP PIRATES FROM SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Doug Gottlieb of Oklahoma State was asked
whether age and experience would help his veteran Cowboys against
the young and injury-depleted Seton Hall Pirates here on Friday
night in the semifinal of the East Regional of the National
Collegiate Athletic Association basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope age plays well, because I'm the oldest guy, I think, in
college,'' said Gottlieb, a senior guard who is 24 years old and
began his college career five years ago at Notre Dame. Turning
serious, Gottlieb said that after the first 5 or 10 minutes of the
game, ``Once you get playing, it's just hoop.''
</P>
<P>
   He said experience counts more in the final minutes of a tense,
close game ``when every decision counts and every play is
magnified.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (26-6) and the Pirates (22-9) play in the second
game of Friday's doubleheader, starting at about 10 p.m. in the
Carrier Dome. In the first game, starting at 7:38 p.m., Duke plays
Florida. The winners will meet Sunday afternoon for a berth in the
tournament's Final Four the next weekend in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State starts four seniors. Seton Hall, because of the
ankle injury to Shaheen Holloway, will probably start only one
senior, Rimas Kaukenas, who is recovering from an illness that
might be strep throat. Seton Hall has played close games so far in
the tournament, beating Oregon and then Temple in overtime last
weekend in Buffalo. Holloway's replacement, Ty Shine, a sophomore,
made 7 of 11 3-point attempts and Seton Hall hit 15 of 30 over all
to beat the Owls. So the Cowboys said they hope to nullify that
aspect of Seton Hall's attack.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Mason, the Oklahoma State senior forward, said he and
his teammates would ``make them put it on the floor and dribble,
not let them spot up and shoot the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Glendon Alexander, a senior guard, said: ``In our program,
defense comes first. We've taken teams out of what they want to do,
make guys be dribblers instead of shooters.''
</P>
<P>
   While Holloway and Seton Hall Coach Tommy Amaker said it was
doubtful that Holloway would play, Oklahoma State was not so sure.
Holloway sat out practice Thursday, watching from the bench and
shouting encouragement while his bandaged left ankle rested high on
a chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling Holloway will play,'' Gottlieb said. ``I'm
sure he'll give it a go.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Sutton, the coach of Oklahoma State, agreed. ``I'd be
surprised if Holloway doesn't play some,'' he said. ``If he doesn't
play, it certainly does hurt their ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway and Kaukenas are Seton Hall's co-captains. Holloway,
the point guard, severely sprained his left ankle, with a partial
tear of a ligament, during the first half against Temple when he
stepped on the shoe of an Owl while driving in for a layup. He said
that Thursday was the first day he had been able to walk without
crutches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's a nice, little progress,'' Holloway said.
``It's up in the air. I've got confidence in Ty and Darius Lane, if
I don't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane, discussing what he has learned of Oklahoma State, said:
``Gottlieb likes to push the ball up and catch you while you're
sleeping. We've got to get back on defense as soon as we shoot the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane said he liked the advantage of playing here on a Big East
court, where the Pirates have won before this season, although
against another team, the Syracuse Orangemen. Seton Hall is seeded
No. 10 in the East Regional; Oklahoma State is No. 3. The game site
is about a five-hour drive from Seton Hall and the Pirates, serious
underdogs, might have fan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' Lane said. ``We're Big East family. It would be
nice. We need all the support we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oklahoma State might also feel like a home team. Sutton said
he had kept most of his players in upstate New York after Sunday's
game ``because the NCAA was not able to get our charter out of
Buffalo until an ungodly hour.'' He said it was probably
advantageous that his team did not have to go back home and then
return. ``Most coaches I'm sure would tell you they would much
prefer to keep them under wraps, away from the co-eds and fellow
students back on campus,'' Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
