<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FRESHMEN: YOUNG, GIFTED AND (YES!) UNUSUAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   North Carolina and Tennessee meet Friday night in the South
Regional in Austin, Texas, as two odd teams in: underachievers
turned gladiators, once selfish teams that transformed into united
and spirited clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams also feature a freshman as the odd player in.
</P>
<P>
   For Carolina, forward Julius Peppers is the football player
turned hoop monster. For Tennessee, forward Ron Slay is the
on-court comic, a flamboyant, active player.
</P>
<P>
   Both players are reserves, yet both are pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina (20-13) and Tennessee (26-6) beat higher-seeded
teams to advance to the Round of 16, with the Tar Heels defeating
No. 1 Stanford and the Volunteers beating No. 5 Connecticut. In the
other South Regional game tonight, Miami (23-10) will play Tulsa
(31-4). On Sunday the winners will meet to decide the region's
Final Four entrant.
</P>
<P>
   Peppers played 24 minutes, scored 6 points and grabbed three
rebounds against Stanford. Slay played 29 minutes, scored 8 points
and earned 4 rebounds against Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Peppers, at 6 feet 7 inches and 270 pounds, is not even in the
Carolina basketball media guide. He joined the team four games into
the season after leading the Tar Heels' football team in tackles
and sacks as a defensive end. Now he throws that punch into
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually shoot in one of the gyms on campus and a couple of
the basketball guys saw me there and told me I should come out for
the team,'' Peppers said. ``Ed Cota used to see me there all of the
time, and he is the one who went to tell the coaches about me. The
coaches called me in; they liked me and the rest is history. I'm
not just a football guy who's trying to play basketball. Right now,
I'm a basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   A basketball brute.
</P>
<P>
   Cota, a point guard, said: ``Everybody respects Julius because
he's earned a role on our team and we are stronger with him. He
works hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Peppers places his 270 pounds under the basket, next to
Carolina's 7-foot center Brendan Haywood, and serves as a space
eater. He creates extra room for Haywood to operate, and he
rebounds effectively. His shooting touch is soft, especially for a
big man. His season-high in points is 14 and in rebounds it is 13.
</P>
<P>
   Slay is, well, unconventional.
</P>
<P>
   You might see him after a score run upcourt with his arms moving
like a pinwheel, cajoling the crowd; or take a charge and simply
lay flat on the floor until a teammate pulls him up; or blow smoke
from his index finger after shooting an imaginary pistol; or make
funny faces and gestures to reporters and cameras at sidecourt
after a Tennessee dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been called everything and I've called people
everything,'' Slay said. ``I'm in your face and they're in my face.
I call it passion. I'm out there having fun and working hard. Just
call me the emotional leader. I have an outgoing personality and I
get it from my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Slay, 18, is the oldest of seven children. He played three years
of high school basketball in Nashville and used to enjoy playground
games against local basketball stars such as Carlos Rogers and
Anthony Mason, now National Basketball Association players. Slay
played his senior season at Oak Hill (Va.) Academy. He has a
football background, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played safety and wide receiver in high school in
Nashville,'' Slay said. ``I broke my arm as a junior, and it was
right before I was supposed to try out for Oak Hill. I went there
and shot with my left hand because my right one was in a cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches took a gamble; they said if I could shoot that
good with my left, the right must be OK. We went 31-0 last year and
won the national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after he arrived at Tennessee, Slay injured his knee and
underwent knee surgery. Nearly four weeks later, he played in
Tennessee's season opener against Elon and scored 17 points in his
debut.
</P>
<P>
   Slay is a quick 6-8, 225 pounds, a player who averaged 9.6
points and 4.3 rebounds a game this season. In Tennessee's last 10
games, he has played at least 20 minutes a game. He is athletic,
can drive past defenders, has a quick, soft shot, is a good leaper
and a solid defender.
</P>
<P>
   Slay's style earned him trouble late in the season in a game at
home against Georgia. Slay taunted the Georgia bench during
Tennessee's 110-83 victory. Later he had to apologize. His coach,
Jerry Green, told him to have fun but to calm down.
</P>
<P>
   Slay rolled on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team has been criticized for inconsistent play and not
having a killer instinct,'' Slay said. ``They say we're soft and
then they say we're hard-headed and out of control. People say a
lot. And we started listening and losing, like in our game in the
Southeastern Conference tournament against South Carolina. We
learned from that to be ourselves and that's why we're playing
relaxed, fun team ball now. I expect that to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   All the way to Final Four?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta go there,'' Slay said.
</P>
<P>
   And, one day, even the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta go there, too,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
