u s BC-BBO-RAINES-NYT &LR;      03-23 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RAINES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EMOTIONS INTACT, RAINES ENDS a 21-YEAR CAREER  
(jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ One dollar represented the stakes in the bet
between Tim and Virginia Raines, and the wife was sure she would
win the cash and a lifetime of bragging rights on this question:
</P>
<P>
   Would Tim Raines cry on the last day of a major league career
that began 21 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   A friend with a Camcorder followed Raines around the Yankees'
clubhouse to capture his final moments as a player in baseball and
to document conclusively, for the Raines family archives, whether
he shed tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't so far,'' he said after a morning news conference,
laughing his high-pitched cackle, but knowing he still would have
to say goodbye to teammates who revere him.
</P>
<P>
   After 2,561 career hits, 1,548 runs and 807 stolen bases, Raines
hoped to make the Yankees' opening-day roster, at age 40, about
eight months after being told by doctors that he had lupus _ an
incurable immune system disorder.
</P>
<P>
   He had performed better than anybody expected here in camp,
batting .292, but Raines did not feel right. Raines found he had to
force himself to prepare mentally, and he knew that after an
off-season of medical treatment, he was not in optimal condition.
</P>
<P>
   Raines came to camp wanting to prove to himself that he could
play the game even after the onset of lupus; he wanted to leave on
his own terms. Raines walked into the office of Yankees Manager Joe
Torre on Monday to ask about his standing.
</P>
<P>
   When Torre offered no assurances he was going to make the team,
Raines told his manager he was going to retire in three days, after
the Yankees had a day off Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Raines left Torre's office, called his wife and told her he had
retired, a possibility the couple discussed the night before.
``Baby, I went in and did it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you OK?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he said. ``Did you cry?'' she asked, and with a chuckle, he
assured her there were no tears.
</P>
<P>
   Raines, commonly known as Rock by his teammates, was in the
lineup for the game Monday night, facing Pittsburgh's Kris Benson.
With the count of 2 balls and 1 strike, Benson threw a belt-high
fastball _ the type of pitch Raines once feasted on, as in 1986,
when he led the National League in hitting with a .334 average.
Raines fouled the ball straight back and accepted this as a sign
that it probably was a good time to retire. He struck out on the
next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   He told a few teammates, Derek Jeter and Paul O'Neill and Tino
Martinez, of his plan to retire, but most of the others were
oblivious to his intentions. Raines was not in the lineup for
Tuesday night's game, and he sat in the dugout, looked around and
absorbed the experience. It was a perfect setting for his last
game, he thought, a beautiful evening for baseball. He loved
playing on nights like this.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning that night, the Yankees were losing to
Toronto, 8-3, and Torre turned and asked Raines if he wanted to
pinch-hit. Raines declined, the first time he could remember
turning down an opportunity to hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to turn down the at-bat, something had to be wrong,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Raines returned to his locker after the game, sat and savored
the moments. He broke into the majors with the Expos in 1979, when
Willie McCovey and Gaylord Perry were still in the National League,
when Jeter was 4 years old.
</P>
<P>
   While a rising star in 1982, Raines entered drug rehabilitation.
His first child, Tim Raines Jr., was 2 years old and Raines felt
his choices were clear-cut. He was an example, he said Thursday ,
of someone from a small town who made a bad decision to begin using
drugs in a big city. ``It never should've happened in the first
place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many addicts, Raines recovered his life, playing another
17 seasons, with a career that nearly overlapped with that of his
son. Tim Raines Jr. has played two years in Baltimore's minor
league system and may reach the majors in another two years, and
father and son had dreamed of playing together in the big leagues.
But the father had called the son earlier this week to tell him he
was retiring, and the son said he was proud.
</P>
<P>
   Raines joined the Yankees in 1996, his joyous personality making
him a favorite among teammates. Even in the worst of days, in the
most miserable of slumps, Raines seemed to find humor. He was
perhaps the only person, teammates said, who could tease the
intense O'Neill during a bad game and make O'Neill smile just a
little.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to have a lot of fun,'' O'Neill said.
``Certain guys represent the personality of a team, and he was one
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines intended to tell the rest of his teammates about his
decision this morning, but was delayed by traffic on Interstate 4
and arrived late. (``If you're not retiring, then you're fined,''
Torre said, joking).
</P>
<P>
   But he told them in a meeting and he was attacked with hugs. He
and O'Neill had always done paper-rock-scissors to see who would
retrieve a ball to play catch before batting practice, and for
old-time's sake, they did it again, Raines prevailing, O'Neill
whipping his head around in mock fury.
</P>
<P>
   Raines threw out the first ball before Thursday's exhibition,
surrounded by the other eight position players, and each hugged him
again, Jeter the last. Raines had been his favorite teammate, ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the best,'' Jeter said into his friend's ear.
</P>
<P>
   Raines walked off, without falling tears, his eyes glistening.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
