<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-STUDENTFE     03-23 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SCOTUS-STUDENTFEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A WISE RULING ON STUDENT ACTIVITIES FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 24:
</P>
<P>
   By a surprisingly lopsided margin, the Supreme Court this week
rejected an effort by conservative Christian law students to
prevent the use of their student activities fees to support groups
whose views they find objectionable. The 9-0 decision against the
students was a ringing and heartening affirmation of the right of
universities to establish forums for the free exchange of
contending ideas as part of the educational process. It also dealt
at least a temporary setback to groups intent on ``defunding the
left'' and on pushing universities in a more conservative
direction.
</P>
<P>
   The suit had been brought against the University of Wisconsin by
three students who objected that mandatory student fees collected
by the university were being used in part to support groups that
espoused gay rights, women's rights, environmental action and other
liberal causes with which they disagreed. The students argued that
using their money for such purposes violated their own First
Amendment rights of free speech and free association. A federal
district court and a federal appeals court found in favor of the
students, relying on Supreme Court precedents in other areas that
that court has now judged to be irrelevant to this case.
</P>
<P>
   In overturning the appellate ruling, Justice Anthony Kennedy
made a compelling case for the importance of a free and open
exchange of ideas among students in higher education. He noted that
the hundreds of student organizations at the University of
Wisconsin include a wide range of views, and that it is thus
inevitable that part of the student fee money goes to support
speech and activities that some students will find objectionable or
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But the overriding point is that a university has the right to
determine that its mission is well served by having students engage
in vigorous philosophic, religious, scientific, social and
political discussion in their extracurricular activities. If a
university reaches that conclusion, Kennedy said, ``it is entitled
to impose a mandatory fee to sustain an open dialogue to these
ends,'' provided the money is given out under neutral criteria that
do not favor some viewpoints over others.
</P>
<P>
   The court did take issue with a minor element of the Wisconsin
system, a method of determining whether to finance or withhold
funds from student organizations through a referendum of the
student body. The court rightly worried that such referendums might
allow majority views to suppress minority views, and it asked the
appeals court to examine that issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's ruling on student fees covers only public
colleges and universities, but it ought to serve as a guideline for
similar struggles at private institutions as well. Unfettered
debate is the hallmark of any great university, whether it is
public or private in nature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
