<HEADLINE>
CAN YOU SAY NUMBER ONE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The Kentucky Derby campaign looks a little
different after Sunday's San Felipe Stakes at Santa Anita. It
sounds a little different, too.
</P>
<P>
   If San Felipe winner Fusaichi Pegasus goes on to win the May 6
Kentucky Derby, he'll be the first champion with a foreign-language
name since 1982 (Gato del Sol) and perhaps the most mispronounced
since the first in 1875 (Aristides, properly said as
air-is-TIE-dees).
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi is pronounced foo-saw-EE-chee. It's a combination of
his Tokyo-based owner's name, Fusao Sekiguchi, and ichi-ban, which
is Japanese for ``No. 1.'' Sekiguchi, a retired high-tech
executive, names many of his horses in that fashion, including 1996
Japan Derby winner Fusaichi Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Get used to the name. Fusaichi Pegasus is indeed No. 1 in most
3-year-old rankings and deservedly so after his deceptively narrow
three-quarter-length victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Derby picture came into focus as Fusaichi Pegasus came to
the wire with Kent Desormeaux on the cruise control, The Deputy
under Chris McCarron's whip to keep up, and Anees a respectable
third.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, two of the season's major players hadn't been
tested: Anees, the 2-year-old champion, who was making his first
start since winning the Breeders' Cup Juvenile in November; and
Fusaichi Pegasus, the $4 million yearling who hadn't faced
stakes-quality competition while winning two of his first three
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus looked like a million bucks, at least, in the
paddock, and was in command on the track in the deepest 3-year-old
race of 2000. The performance placed the son of Mr. Prospector and
a Danzig mare at the top of the list of those who have displayed
the ability to win the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Charismatic, the one-time claimer, didn't emerge as a
classic-caliber colt until April, following a lackluster fourth-
place finish in the Santa Anita Derby with a victory in the
Lexington Stakes two weeks before the Kentucky Derby. But that kind
of career arc is rare for a Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   Almost always, the eventual Derby winner has proved his quality
before the final round of major preps, which this year include the
April 8 Santa Anita Derby and the April 15 Blue Grass at Keeneland
and Wood Memorial at Aqueduct.
</P>
<P>
   Based on who's beaten whom, by how much and how quickly, this is
the Kentucky Derby ``A'' list (in no particular order): Fusaichi
Pegasus; WarChant, trainer Neil Drysdale's !ital!other colt; Anees;
Mighty, the stretch-running Louisiana Derby winner; Captain Steve,
the Bob Baffert-trained Hollywood Futurity winner, and The Deputy,
the Irish-bred Santa Catalina winner.
</P>
<P>
   The ``B'' list: Hal's Hope, trained by octogenerian Hal Rose,
and HighYield, from the D. Wayne Lukas barn, 1-2 finishers in a
low-rated Florida Derby; Surfside, Lukas' dominant filly; Red
Bullet, the Gotham winner at Aqueduct; Aptitude, Bobby Frankel's
lightly raced Gotham runnerup; Acres, a freak at Laurel but a
troubled sixth in the Gotham; Archer City Slew, the San Vicente
sprint winner; Chief Seattle, the Breeders' Cup Juvenile runnerup
now based in Dubai; Frankel-trained Cocky, who hung around for
third in the San Rafael; Commendable, the Lukas-Bob Lewis colt
who'll have to pull a Charismatic; Lukas-trained Exchange Rate, who
beat Mighty in their Louisiana Derby prep, and More Than Ready, who
couldn't hold on at 1 1/16 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Anita Derby field shapes up as Anees, Captain Steve,
Cocky, Surfside, The Deputy and War Chant. Fusaichi Pegasus is
going to the Wood or Blue Grass.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hello, Dubai: Saturday's $6 million Dubai World Cup _ the
planet's richest horse race _ has drawn nine U.S. jockeys and
nearly as many American horses to Nad Al Sheba racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 14 horses entered for the 1 1/4-mile race are Behrens
(Jorge Chavez), Malek (Alex Solis), Puerto Madero (Laffit Pincay),
Ecton Park (Chris McCarron), Public Purse (Corey Nakatani), Saint's
Honor (Kent Desormeaux), Running Stag (Shane Sellers), Strudel Fitz
(John Velasquez) and Dubai-based 1999 Kentucky Derby runner Worldly
Manner (Jerry Bailey).
</P>
<P>
   Dubai Millennium (Frankie Dettori), a 4-year-old son of Seeking
the Gold who has won seven of eight starts in Dubai, England and
France, is the local favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita will take bets this afternoon and Saturday morning
on the World Cup. It's scheduled for about 9:30 a.m. Pacific time.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: Only Pincay is expected back from the United
Arab Emirates in time to ride Sunday at Santa Anita in the $150,000
Santa Ana Handicap for fillies and mares. Pincay rides Virginie,
with whom he teamed to win the Beverly Hills last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Happyanunoit, the Matriarch winner, assigned a race-high 121 for
the Santa Ana at 1 miles on turf, will be ridden as usual by Brice
Blanc. But most of the field will have new riders.
</P>
<P>
   __ Antley off: Jockey Chris Antley told Santa Anita stewards he
won't compete again until April while he clears away off-the-track
distractions.
</P>
<P>
   It's more evidence that Antley, who has done well in the stock
market and can live without his racetrack income, has trouble
staying focused on his job.
</P>
<P>
   Steward Tom Ward said the rider of 1999 Kentucky Derby and
Preakness winner Charismatic reported no personal problems in a
Thursday morning meeting. Antley wasn't tested for drugs after
taking off his mounts on short notice Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Ward said Antley acknowledged trouble making weight since
returning from a break, during which he had knee surgery, following
the Breeders' Cup in November. He has ridden three winners in 30
starts at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old said he plans to continue exercising horses at
Santa Anita. He'll be replaced by Garrett Gomez aboard San Vicente
winner Archer City Slew in the $600,000 Spiral Stakes (formerly the
Jim Beam) at Turfway Park in Kentucky on Saturday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SANTA ANITA LEADERS &QL; 
Jockeys (through Wednesday): Corey Nakatani, 59 wins; Kent
Desormeaux, 53; Laffit Pincay, 48; Alex Solis, 41; Victor Espinoza,
41. Trainers: Bob Baffert, 27; Bill Spawr, 21; Bobby Frankel and
Ron McAnally, 18; Vladimir Cerin, 16. &QL; 
PINCAY WATCH &QL; 
All-time wins leader Laffit Pincay increased his total to 8,894
with a pair of victories Wednesday at Santa Anita. Pincay is in
Dubai to ride Puerto Madero in the $6 million Dubai World Cup on
Saturday but is scheduled to return in time to ride Virginie in the
Santa Ana Handicap on Sunday. &QL; 
ON THE STAKES SCHEDULE &QL; 
At Santa Anita: Saturday, $75,000 San Pedro Stakes, 3-year-olds, 6
1/2 furlongs; Sunday, $150,000 Santa Ana Handicap, fillies and
mares 4 and up, 1 1/8 miles on turf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Golden Gate Fields: Wednesday, $125,000 Berkeley Handicap,
3-year-olds and up, 1 mile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Turfway Park, Florence, Ky.: Saturday, $600,000 Spiral
Stakes, 3-year-olds, 1 miles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Fair Grounds, New Orleans: Sunday, $600,000 Explosive
Bid, 4-year-olds and up, 1 miles on turf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
Santa Anita is promoting ``50 Cent Fridays'' for the rest of the
season. Parking, general admission, soft drinks and hot dogs will
cost 50 cents. . . . With Pat Day committed to Surfside in the
April 8 Santa Anita Derby, Victor Espinoza has been named to ride
Cat Thief in the Oaklawn Park Handicap in Arkansas the same day. .
. . Bob Baffert said 2-year-old fillies champion Chilukki will get
a rest after her weak performance in the Fair Grounds Oaks. . . .
After Sonny Hine died of cancer at age 69 last week in Florida,
Carolyn Hine said she will sell the couple's horses. Sonny was best
known for training 1998 Horse of the Year Skip Away, owned by
Carolyn. He also trained 1981 champion sprinterGuilty Conscience. .
. . Jorge Chavez led the jockeys for the second straight year and
Bill Mott topped the trainers for the seventh time in eight years
at the Gulfstream Park meet that ended last week. Attendance
declined 4 percent. . . . Santa Anita Handicapwinner General
Challenge remained No. 1 in the NTRA media poll. He breezed 5
furlongs in 59 seconds on Wednesday to stay on target for the April
9 San Bernardino Handicap. . . . Bay Meadows' season ends Sunday
and San Francisco Bay Area racing moves to Golden Gate Fields
starting Wednesday. . . . Del Mar released a $6.1 million stakes
schedule for its July 26 to Sept. 13 meet, including the $1 million
Pacific Classic on Aug. 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
