<HEADLINE>
DUCKS LIKE PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; VANCOUVER _ Another night, another crucial game for the Mighty
Ducks, who should know the drill well by now. After all, they've
been fighting for their playoff lives for weeks now.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, ninth-place Anaheim (31-32-12-2) takes on 10th-place
Vancouver (26-34-14-8). The Ducks hope to end a Canadian losing
streak at seven games and possibly move back into a tie for the
eighth spot in a Western Conference playoff race that seemingly
becomes more muddled every day. Heading into Thursday's play only
seven points separated seven teams battling for the final five
postseason berths.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tired flock: It was an exhausted group of Ducks who arrived
in British Columbia early Thursday morning after beating the Kings
Tuesday night in Los Angeles and losing in Edmonton on Wednesday
after overnight plane flight. But Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said
nobody should be complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be exciting for everybody to be playing in these big
games,'' he said. ``You want to be involved and play in these types
of situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a day to rest our minds and bodies. These are like
playoff games, so this should be easy if you want to win and be the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks are in the midst of playing eight games in 13 days and
four in six nights before getting five days off next week to rest
up for the final five games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously a lot of games in a short period of time, but
we have to find the energy,'' said Anaheim defenseman Oleg
Tverdovsky. ``There is no time to feel sorry for ourselves. If we
keep focused, we will be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Limited success: The Ducks are a combined 1-5-2 versus their
next two opponents _ 0-1-2 against Vancouver and 1-4 versus the
Phoenix Coyotes, who they play on Sunday at The Pond.
</P>
<P>
   However, Anaheim is a combined 7-0-3 against Nashville, Chicago
and the Kings, the teams they play in the final five games of the
season. Ducks are 2-0 against the Predators, 2-0-2 versus the Kings
and 3-0-1 versus Chicago. Anaheim plays Nashville and Los Angeles
twice and Chicago once.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
