<HEADLINE>
2 BROKERAGES SETTLE WITH NEW YORK STATE ON BIAS COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ending a three-year inquiry into accusations of
racism and sexual harassment at Wall Street firms, the New York
state attorney general announced a settlement with two affiliated
brokerages Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage firms, Garban LLC and Garvin Guy Butler, agreed to
pay a $200,000 fine and agreed to allow employees _ even some whose
legal claims had expired under the statute of limitations _ to
recover lost pay and damages in state-monitored arbitration,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's investigation began in 1997 shortly after
three female employees filed separate complaints accusing the
companies of sexual and racial discrimination that dated back to
1984.
</P>
<P>
   The original plaintiffs, Donna Weber, Suzanne Taylor-Bernstein
and Toni Oliveri, all worked at the company's offices at 120
Broadway in Lower Manhattan. They maintained that supervisors
condoned or were involved in making racist, anti-gay and harassing
comments and made unwanted sexual advances.
</P>
<P>
   The workers also charged that their supervisors retaliated
against them for making complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints contended that pornographic material was
regularly displayed on computer screens and walls on the company's
trading floor. It also said that pornographic magazines were often
in open view on desks.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints said that company meetings were often held in
strip clubs like Scores, and one complaint said that at a Christmas
party, the company hired two female strippers who performed sexual
acts on each other in front of the employees.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement could lead to significant punitive damages,
because it would allow the complaints of discrimination to be taken
to independent mediation instead of going to industry arbitration,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry arbitration panels are generally dominated by older
white men and have been criticized as being too sympathetic to
brokerage managers, particularly in matters relating to sex and
race discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case should send a strong message to all of Wall Street
that we will not tolerate an old boys' club or frat house
atmosphere in the workplace,'' said the state attorney general,
Eliot L. Spitzer. ``It is wrong, it is discriminatory and it is
illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which ends a three-year investigation by the
attorney general's civil rights bureau, must be approved by a judge
in state Supreme Court in Manhattan, law enforcement officials
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Telephone calls to officials from Garban and Garvin Guy Butler
in New York and England were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer called the settlement ``an important step toward
ensuring that women and minorities are treated equally on Wall
Street'' and said that at least 31 current and former employees
could recover lost pay and benefits, as well as lawyers' fees and
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The two firms have about 600 employees combined. If the current
and former employees choose to take their cases to arbitration,
they are precluded from filing state or federal lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints by the three women were settled individually
shortly after the attorney general filed suit, law enforcement
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Schulman, the lawyer for Oliveri, said that like most
brokers at the firms, she signed an agreement when she was hired
that precluded her from filing a lawsuit and forced her to accept
the decision of a panel from the National Association of Securities
Dealers. Schulman said Oliveri was the first to file her
complaints. The other two women testified at her hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Schulman said that Oliveri won an undisclosed judgment from the
NASD panel, but that the other two women settled, also for
undisclosed amounts, because ``they saw the tough time my client
was given.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
