<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LEGIS-BUDGET-580&AMP;A     03-23 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-BUDGET-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ALBANY BUDGET DEADLINE NEARS, NO BUDGET IS WITHIN SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With eight days before the deadline for a new
state budget, Gov. George Pataki and leaders of the Legislature
remain divided over how much money is available to spend for the
coming year, making it all but certain that the budget will be late
for the 16th year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the Republican-led state Senate and
Democratic-controlled Assembly are seeking significantly more money
than the $76.8 billion that the governor proposed in his budget
earlier this year. But the governor has said that he wants to keep
a tight lid on spending and has not signed on to the proposals of
either house.
</P>
<P>
   The three sides are so divided at this point that it is unclear
what will happen next. The two houses were scheduled to convene
conference committees a few weeks ago to work out their
differences. But that has not happened yet, spurring legislative
leaders from both houses to blame one another for the delay.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the negotiations could be held up by issues that
have little to do with the budget. For example, the Democratic
speaker of the Assembly, Sheldon Silver, wants money to build a
Second Avenue subway running the full length of Manhattan, and he
has said that there will be no budget unless he gets his way.
</P>
<P>
   More than that, though, Silver is seeking assurances from
Pataki, a Republican, that he will not try the kind of wholesale
vetoes he made in 1998, when the governor cut more than $1 billion
in programs, mostly Democratic, from the budget that the two houses
sent to him.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has refused to give such assurances, making Silver very
reluctant to pass a budget with Senate Republicans this year, lest
he leave Democrats vulnerable to another round of painful vetoes.
So far, Silver has refused to convene conference committees to work
out a detailed budget, a move that Joseph L. Bruno, the Senate
majority leader, has been demanding for some time.
</P>
<P>
   The main sticking point in the budget negotiations is coming up
with a spending figure that all three sides can agree on. The
Senate Republicans have proposed a spending plan that is $900
million larger than the governor's, not including $400 million in
tax cuts that they are seeking. The Assembly Democrats have
proposed a plan that is $1.8 billion above Pataki's.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has not said how much of an increase he is willing to
support. But people involved in the negotiations say he is willing
to consider up to $1 billion, something that may still be
unacceptable to Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Once an overall budget figure is reached, the two houses can
convene a conference committee to decide how the available money
should be spent. But that will create a new set of problems this
year, because the two houses have different spending priorities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Assembly Democrats are calling for a $1.3 billion
increase in state aid to schools, compared with the $900 million
that the Senate Republicans requested in their budget proposal. At
the same time, the $400 million in tax cuts that the Republicans
are proposing would severely restrict what can be spent on benefit
programs supported by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is due on April 1, the start of the new fiscal year.
As it did last year, the deadline brings a new wrinkle because of a
1988 law that calls for withholding state legislators' pay when a
state budget is late. But whether that will lead to a relatively
timely budget is unclear.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last year, the law fell far short of the result its supporters
desired: adoption of a budget on time. Instead, lawmakers adopted a
budget on Aug. 4, 126 days into the fiscal year, tying the record
for lateness.
</P>
<P>
   Before last year, the latest state budget was in 1997, also 126
days overdue, when the Assembly Democrats refused to negotiate
until Pataki and Bruno agreed to preserve the state's rent
stabilization laws.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was 104 days late in 1996, when Pataki refused to
enact a budget until the Legislature agreed to changes in the
state's workers' compensation law to save employers money.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats justify the spending increases they propose this
year by saying that the governor's budget underestimated the
state's revenue between now and the end of the next fiscal year by
$1.4 billion. It also overestimates expenses by $400 million, they
said, for a total difference of $1.8 billion. The Senate
Republicans argue that the governor underestimated the state's
revenue by $1 billion and overestimated expenses by $400 million,
for a total difference of $1.4 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
