<SLUG> BC-NY-DAILY-NEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S DAILY NEWS REPLACES ITS TOP EDITOR AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edward Kosner, the former Newsweek editor drafted 16
months ago to revamp the slumping Sunday edition of The Daily News,
has been named the newspaper's editor in chief, the publisher,
Mortimer B. Zuckerman, announced in a news release Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Kosner, 62, becomes the newspaper's fourth top editor in four
years. He replaces Debby Krenek, who was promoted to the top job in
October 1997, after the seven-month editorship of Pete Hamill. In
an interview Thursday, Zuckerman called Krenek ``an absolute
princess of a person'' who ``made a terrific contribution to the
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Krenek ``told me that she wanted to consider
other alternatives for various reasons, and she was kind enough to
give me the time to put together the team that we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Goodwin, who as editorial page editor presided over
commentary that won the newspaper major national awards two years
in a row _ a Pulitzer Prize in 1999 and a Polk award earlier this
year _ was named the newspaper's senior executive editor,
effectively Kosner's No. 2 newsroom executive.
</P>
<P>
   Krenek's 6 p.m. farewell speech to the newsroom Thursday gave
form and substance to the rumors that had consumed the nation's
sixth-largest newspaper since Monday, when a gossip item in The New
York Post predicted the ascension of Kosner and Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Zuckerman nor Kosner were on hand for Krenek's remarks.
Likewise, according to journalists who were present, Krenek made no
reference either to the publisher or to her successor as she stood
in the center of the newsroom and told colleagues, ``I love The
Daily News.'' As she left two hours later, Krenek's colleagues rose
in a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Thursday whether the reshuffling at the top would
mean changes in the current lineup of senior editors, including the
senior managing editor, Arthur Browne; the executive editor, Robert
Sapio; and the two managing editors, Bill Boyle and Richard Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the role those editors would play in the new lineup,
Zuckerman said: ``I think they hopefully will remain with the paper
in positions of serious responsibility. There will be some time in
which Ed and Michael will review, not the staff so much as the
paper, and they'll all work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached Thursday evening, Kosner said: ``It's a wonderful paper
and I think we're going to try to make the paper even smarter. With
all due respect to The New York Times, we're going to try to make
it the smartest paper in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooperation has not always been in evidence between the staff of
the daily newspaper, under Krenek's command, and the Sunday
department controlled by Kosner.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, a cover article in The News about Bruce Teitelbaum,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's campaign manager, was written by a
journalist who is not on The News staff. The reporters who
regularly cover the mayor and Teitelbaum were not involved.
</P>
<P>
   A senior staff member, Joe Calderone, who heads the
investigative reporters, said of Krenek, ``She gave us the time and
the space and the encouragement to do really good work.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the frequent turnover at the top ranks of his
newspaper, Zuckerman said: ``My objective is always to try and
improve the paper. We won three Pulitzers under Debby and many
other awards. We are going to go for more. Debby had other plans to
fulfill. And _ I know this is going to be a shock to the system _ I
made mistakes in some of my choices. I was also learning this
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy with what Debby did with the paper and I'll
be happy with what these people do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
