<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE JOINS INVESTMENT BANK; GORE RAKES IN CONTRIBUTIONS; BUSH
VOTERS ARE LOYAL; FREE AIR TIME FROM A TELEVISION STATION OWNER;
SOUTH CAROLINA CONGRESSMAN'S PLAN TO QUIT CREATES STAMPEDETO
REPLACE HIM; OUSTED CHAIRMAN TAKES REFORM PARTY TO COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: COLO., ARIZ., Ohio, S.C., TEXAS, R.I., WASH., VA., MINN.) 
(DW) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS: NEW JOB FOR QUAYLE
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months after dropping out of the race for the
presidency, former Vice President Dan Quayle is back in business.
But this is real business, with Quayle having announced that he has
joined an investing banking firm, JD Ford and Co. which arranges
small mergers and acquisitions. The firm has 12 employees and is
based in Denver, but Quayle, who is a lawyer, will be opening an
office in Phoenix. ``He's certainly not going to be window
dressing,'' said Joseph M. Durnford, who founded the company four
years ago and is its chief executive. ``He's already working on a
specific transaction and said he didn't want to be window
dressing.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE DEMOCRATS: A BUMPY ROAD TO REFORM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a bit of unfortunate timing for the Gore campaign, Vice
President Al Gore was raising hundreds of thousands of dollars
Thursday at three events just as his Republican rival, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, was calling him ``an obstacle to reform.'' Bush
told The Washington Post that Gore has ``a major credibility
problem'' on his desire to overhaul the campaign finance system and
was too partisan to find a consensus on shoring up Social Security.
Gore attended a fundraising luncheon in Cincinatti and two
fundraising receptions in Detroit, all for the Democratic National
Committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE VOTERS: ENTHUSIASM FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's supporters are more likely to feel
strongly about their support than are voters who favor Vice
President Al Gore, according to the latest poll for Hotline, the
online political tip sheet. The poll of 1,000 voters taken on March
16 through March 19 by a Democratic pollster, Jef Pollock, and a
Republican, Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, found that 59 percent of Bush
supporters held that position strongly, as against 49 percent of
Gore backers. The poll also found that voters who said Sen. John
McCain was their first choice for president were evenly split when
asked to choose between Bush and Gore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE MEDIA: FREE AIR
</P>
<P>
   Candidates in Congressional and gubernatorial contests will be
provided with five minutes of free air time this year on the 18
television stations across the country owned by the Belo Corp., the
company's chairman, Robert W. Decherd, said Thursday. Expanding an
initiative it began in 1996, Belo, which also publishes the Dallas
Morning News and the Providence Journal, will turn over a
five-minute block of news programming to each qualified candidate
during the final 45 days of the campaign. In the pilot project four
years ago, six of Belo's stations provided 73 candidates with more
than six hours of free air time. The company has stations in, among
other places, Dallas, Houston, Seattle and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   THE HOUSE: CROWDED FIELD
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Sanford, a Republican from the coastal district of
South Carolina, became a well-known figure around the state earlier
this year because of his maverick support for Sen. John McCain. But
rather than exploit his popularity, he is, at least for the moment,
leaving politics in keeping with a promise to serve no more than
three terms. The prospect of filling a rare open seat has attracted
seven Republicans to the June 13 primary. The leading contenders
are H.B. Limehouse, the former transportation commissioner who has
the backing of the state's Republican establishment, and state Rep.
Henry Brown. The winner will likely face Andy Brack, chairman of
the Charleston County Democratic party.
THE REFORM PARTY: OUSTER CONDEMNED
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gargan, the ousted chairman of the Reform Party, told a
federal judge Thursday that he had been improperly removed from the
job in a ``raw power takeover'' at a raucous meeting last month.
The testimony came on the second day of a hearing before Judge
Norman K. Moon of U.S. District Court in Lynchburg, Va., to decide
who controls the party and millions of dollars in federal campaign
money. Gargan is an ally of Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota. The
current chairman Pat Choate is an ally of the party's founder, Ross
Perot. Gargan testified that the meeting was invalid because proper
notice of it had not been given to party members and those who
attended were not properly credentialed as outlined in the party's
constitution. He also said he had not called the gathering to
order. Dale Cooter, Choate's lawyer, tried to paint Gargan as a
tyrant who wanted to rule the party by himself, going against the
executive committee's wishes and overturning its decisions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
