<HEADLINE>
HOPING TO END FUROR, SPEAKER SELECTS HOUSE'S FIRST ROMAN CATHOLIC
CHAPLAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill.)  (CHANGES ``Father'' to ``the Rev. in 8th graf; ADDS 9th graf with
context of controversy; CORRECTS reference to beliefs of Bob Jones
University in 10th graf; ADDS 13th graf with Couglin accepting the
job.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT28 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to quell a political and religious furor
over the selection of the House chaplain, Speaker Dennis Hastert
took to the House floor Thursday and appointed, by fiat, a Catholic
priest who had not been in contention for the job.
</P>
<P>
   In a sober speech laced with bitterness, Hastert stood before
his hushed colleagues and defended his initial decision to select a
Protestant minister over a Roman Catholic priest.
</P>
<P>
   And he accused Democrats of conducting unseemly political
warfare by portraying him and other Republicans as anti-Catholic.
The House has never had a Catholic chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a more cynical and more destructive
political campaign,'' Hastert said on the House floor, insisting
that his earlier choice of the Protestant minister had been based
on merit, not denomination. ``That such a campaign should be waged
in connection with the selection of the House chaplain brings shame
on this House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks a lot like war,'' Hastert added. ``And it has an ugly
face.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leader, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, who
did not know about Hastert's decision until the speech on the House
floor, struck a conciliatory note in his response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never said, and never believed, that there was bias of
any kind in the making of this selection,'' Gephardt told his
colleagues on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's decision to name the Rev. Daniel Coughlin, a vicar of
the Archdiocese of Chicago, appeared to be an effort to close an
episode that has dogged Republicans since late last year, exposing
the party to charges of anti-Catholic bias and leaving some members
politically vulnerable in their home districts.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the chaplain's selection _ a seemingly
innocuous procedure _ also helped dredge up just the sort of
partisan animosity that Republicans hoped to leave behind after
President Clinton's impeachment. It was in this spirit of
conciliation that they elected Hastert as speaker in 1999 to
replace Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fade away with time, as Republicans had hoped, the
conflict escalated last month when Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, kicked off his
South Carolina campaign by visiting Bob Jones University, an
evangelical college whose leaders have made anti-Catholic
statements. Bush's visit roiled his campaign and provided House
Democrats with added ammunition in the fight over the House
chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   For Hastert, the decision to appoint Coughlin follows four
months of hand-wringing over how to handle the chaplain
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   An exit strategy finally emerged this week, when the Rev.
Charles Wright, the Protestant chaplain who had been awaiting final
approval, withdrew from consideration on Wednesday, saying he could
not serve in a ``divided House,'' Hastert said. His withdrawal
cleared the way for Hastert to appoint Coughlin, who had been
recommended by the archbishop of Chicago, Cardinal Francis George.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin (whose name is pronounced COG-lin) was offered the job
only Thursday. After accepting, he flew to Washington, where he was
sworn in just after Hastert's speech.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker can, if he chooses, use his unilateral authority to
select the chaplain, whose job it is to deliver the morning prayer
and counsel members.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hastert faced considerable pressure from Roman Catholic
Republicans, and Republicans from predominantly Catholic districts,
to resolve the lingering conflict. Some members, fed up with the
partisan brawl, suggested doing away with the position of chaplain
altogether, an alternative that Hastert called a ``grave mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that Hastert had decided to appoint a Roman
Catholic drew praise from Republicans and Democrats alike. ``It was
his only recourse under the circumstances,'' said Rep. Marge
Roukema, R-N.J. ``He made the best of an impossible situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, though, expressed deep dissatisfaction with
Hastert's attack, saying that he mishandled the process and had
nobody to blame but himself for the controversy. `` I don't care
who is chaplain,'' said Rep. John D. Dingell, a senior Michigan
Democrat who is Catholic. ``If you're going to have a process, you
want it to be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, a bipartisan committee, set up by Hastert to
pick the House chaplain, winnowed a long list of candidates to
three, with a Roman Catholic priest, Father Timothy O'Brien,
receiving the most votes.
</P>
<P>
   As agreed, the list of three was forwarded to Hastert, Rep. Dick
Armey of Texas, the majority leader, and Gephardt, without a vote
tally and in alphabetical order.
</P>
<P>
   After a round of final interviews late last year, Hastert
selected Wright, with the support of Armey and, eventually,
Gephardt. Republicans said that other House leaders had played no
role in the choice of Wright.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats on the committee complained, saying they did not
understand why the committee's first choice was not selected. They
also pointed out that during interviews with the panel, O'Brien had
been asked what they described as inappropriate questions about his
clerical collar and his ability to counsel married couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that anti-Catholic bias played into it,'' said Rep.
Anna Eshoo, D-Calif., who was on the selection panel. ``Do I
celebrate the fact that history has been made and the House has its
first Catholic chaplain? Yes. Has it been hurtful? Absolutely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
