<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MAN, 35, STALKED TEEN BEFORE CHURCH SHOOTING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH RENDON 
and CARLOS ANTONIO RIOS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Oscar Castillo's obsession with a teen-ager almost
half his age was no secret at the small Pentecostal church both
attended in nearby Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned parishioners had stayed after regular services
Wednesday night to discuss the situation with both Castillo, 35,
and the 18-year-old high school student, Esly Alicia Contreras.
</P>
<P>
   The parishioners heard Castillo profess his love, and they heard
Contreras comparing her feelings for him to that of a brother.
Castillo left, but only briefly. The next thing parishioners heard
was gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, a native of Nicaragua who had become an active member
of the Iglesia Cristiana Esposa del Cordero after kicking a drug
habit, had returned with a gun _ a type so unusual that police were
still trying to determine the make late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He shot not only Contreras, but her mother, their minister, and
another parishioner before going outside and killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Contreras' condition was upgraded to good and she
was expected to be released from the hospital. However, her mother,
38-year-old Angela Contreras, and pastor Carlos Matamoros, 49, were
in critical condition at Memorial Hermann Hospital in Houston. The
fourth person wounded, Jose Luis Dones, 32, of Pasadena, was grazed
by a bullet and treated at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo died in the parking lot outside the single-story,
aluminum-sided church, which is a few blocks from Pasadena's City
Hall and police department.
</P>
<P>
   Pasadena, a petrochemical city of nearly 134,00 people, is about
10 miles west of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Esly Contreras' 15-year-old brother, Robert, said his mother had
asked for the meeting after Wednesday night's services, seeking
guidance from church elders. About 20 other parishioners stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed his love for her, and she told him in front of
the witnesses and elders that she liked him like a brother, but she
did not have a romantic interest in him,'' Pasadena Police Lt. M.P.
Jackson said. ``Apparently that led up to his emotional instability
and caused the shooting. That's the best information at this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   One witness, Concepcion Montana, told her husband, Jose Montana,
that Castillo entered the church, grabbed Esly Contreras by the
hair and shot her. He then shot the mother and pastor before
running out of the church, the husband said. One of the bullets
fired at the others apparently grazed the other wounded man.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo at first had romantically pursued Angela Contreras,
according to her son.
</P>
<P>
   When the single mother of five, who works as the church
secretary, did not return his affection, Castillo turned his
attention to Esly Contreras.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Castillo stalked Esly Contreras, a student at Sam
Rayburn High School, her brother said. Castillo would park near the
school bus stop in the mornings and afternoons and watch her get on
and off the bus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo also would often drive by the family's apartment
complex and had threatened the young woman, her brother said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no information late Thursday to indicate that the
family had reported the stalking to police.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Martinez, 28, manager of the apartments where the
Contreras family lives in a two-bedroom unit, said the family was
close-knit and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Contreras usually took her children to church with her
for evening service. On Wednesday, however, she had left Robert in
charge of his three younger siblings while she and her oldest child
went to the church.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors described Esly Contreras as quiet, noting that though
she does not participate in any extracurricular activities at
school, she is active at her church.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Lewis, a spokesman for the Pasadena school district, said
counselors were working with students on an individual basis
Thursday to talk about the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, church members, many who had witnessed the shooting
and were kept inside the building until police completed their
investigation, were holding a vigil at Memorial Hermann Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, a native of Managua, Nicaragua, had been in the United
States for about seven years and was a supervisor for Flori-Tex
Landscaping in Pasadena, said an acquaintance, Alvaro Espino.
</P>
<P>
   Espino said Castillo had been a drug user but had cleaned up
about three years ago and become religious.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was getting his life in order,'' Espino said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Castillo's mother died several months ago and that
Castillo had been saddened that he was unable to attend the funeral
in Nicaragua. On Thursday, authorities were trying to find a sister
to tell her about his death.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication that he had been married or had
relatives in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County court records show Castillo was sentenced to 20
days in jail in June 1997 for a conviction of assault bodily
injury. Details were not available.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Pasadena police were trying to identify the weapon
used in the shooting rampage. The department called in agents with
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to help try to
determine the type of semiautomatic pistol Castillo used.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun used is a particularly unusual caliber and a
particularly unusual brand that we don't recognize. The serial
numbers appear to have been ground off,'' police Lt. M.P. Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what kind it is. It's one we've never seen
before. It's not a caliber we use here in the United States. It
could have been imported from South America or Europe.''
</P>
<P>
