<SLUG> BC-CHASE-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE SEEKS TO BUY ONE OF BRITAIN'S LAST PRIVATELY HELD BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Chase Manhattan Corp. is negotiating to acquire the
British asset management and investment banking firm Robert Fleming
Holdings, the companies said Thursday. A deal would end the
independence of Fleming, one of Britain's last privately held
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the talks said that an announcement of a
purchase could come within a week, though the companies might still
decide to abandon the effort. While a price for the British bank
has yet to be fixed, the executives said, it is expected to exceed
3 billion pounds, or about $4.75 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A purchase of Fleming would follow Chase's $1.35 billion
acquisition of the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Group last year, which helped
strengthen Chase's high-technology investment banking business.
</P>
<P>
   It would also give Chase, of New York, the third-largest
American banking company, a powerful presence in Asia, where
Fleming has a successful asset management practice, but not much
more in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Fleming said, ``Discussions are at an early
stage and no further announcement will be made unless and until
appropriate.'' Unusually, Chase also confirmed the talks, but said
it did so ``at the request of Robert Fleming Holdings.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a successful deal would still not give Chase the
size to join the upper echelon of investment banks like Goldman
Sachs Group or Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are definitely getting a strong presence in Asia,'' said
Tom Rayner, an analyst at SG Securities. ``But it's not going to
help them compete much in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said a more logical purchase for Chase would be
Dresdner Bank's Kleinwort Benson unit, which would give Chase an
immediate investment banking presence in Europe at a time when
mergers and acquisitions are occurring at a rapid pace. ``There are
better propositions around,'' Rayner said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Chase rose $6.9375 Thursday, to $98.50. News of the
talks was first reported in The Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, which is not a publicly traded company, is 29.4
percent-owned by the Fleming family, which included Ian Fleming,
the late writer who created James Bond. The company operates a
joint venture with T. Rowe Price Associates, which has about $35
billion of managed assets. The bank also owns Jardine Fleming,
which was once Hong Kong's biggest broker. In all, the bank manages
$137.4 billion for its clients. Robert Fleming has about 7,800
employees with offices in more than 40 countries.
</P>
<P>
   If Chase acquired Robert Fleming, the deal would bring a
near-end to Britain's privately held banks. It would leave only
Cazenove &AMP; Co. as the last major British-based investment banking
business.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Citigroup bought the Schroders investment
banking business for $2.21 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Others sold to foreign companies in the last several years
include Warburg Dillon Read and Barings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
