u f BC-CREDIT-SUISSE-UKRAINE     03-23 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-SUISSE-UKRAINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT SUISSE DEFENDS WORK FOR UKRAINE AS AUTHORIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The head of the emerging markets business of Credit Suisse, the
European banking giant, said Thursday that his institution engaged
in unusual transactions on behalf of Ukraine's central bank, but he
maintained that all of them were legal and were undertaken only at
the central bank's request.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before the House Banking Committee, the Credit Suisse
executive, James P. Healy, said that, among other things, his bank
received $705 million from the Ukrainian central bank from 1996 to
1998, which Credit Suisse then lent to banks in Ukraine. The
central bank guaranteed any losses Credit Suisse might incur on the
loans and paid Credit Suisse commissions for distributing the money
_ essentially paying it to conduct risk-free activities.
</P>
<P>
   In most countries, central banks do not rely on intermediaries
to distribute loans to domestic banks. Healy said the maneuver was
necessary in Ukraine, however, because the central bank there
wished to ``avoid the domestic political pressures it would face if
it engaged in direct lending of U.S. dollars to Ukrainian banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse's activities in Ukraine have come under scrutiny
after the International Monetary Fund disclosed last week that
Ukraine's central bank secured loans by misleading the fund about
the country's financial health. The IMF said the central bank used
nearly $1 billion to conduct banking transactions that allowed it
to double-count its foreign currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Government investigators in the United States said last week
that some of the transactions that artificially inflated the
Ukrainian central bank's reserves were conducted with the help of
Credit Suisse's investment banking arm, Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Healy said Thursday that while there had been accusations that
some part of the $705 million the central bank deposited with
Credit Suisse ``may have been used to mislead the IMF,'' his bank
``does not know of any such conduct, nor has it ever been in a
position to know.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Credit Suisse was unaware of exact
``performance criteria'' outlined by the IMF to Ukraine's
government as a condition for receiving IMF funds.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who heads the House Banking Committee,
said it was his understanding that most investment and commercial
banks make it a point to familiarize themselves with such criteria
in emerging markets _ a view that some Western bankers confirmed in
interviews Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the transactions Credit Suisse engaged in for the
Ukrainian central bank were conducted through Cyprus, an offshore
financial haven favored by many Eastern European countries and
Western financial institutions. Healy said Thursday that it was
Cyprus' favorable tax climate, not its bank secrecy laws, that
makes the Mediterranean island so attractive to financiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss Banking Commission, the country's leading bank
regulator, said earlier this week that it was investigating Credit
Suisse's activities in Ukraine because of the IMF's disclosures
about how its loans were handled by the country. Credit Suisse
declined to comment on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers, who also testified
Thursday, said he was ``deeply concerned'' about the accusations of
improprieties involving IMF loans to Ukraine. Summers said that the
Treasury Department would review audits of the transactions in
question before he supported further IMF lending to the country. He
said he considered the possibility of misuse of the funds to be ``a
matter of especially serious concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-23-00 2347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
