<DOCNO> NYT20000323.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-23 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6526 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FT.COM-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-23 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FT.COM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NEW MARKETING EFFORT TRIES TO RAISE FT.COM'S U.S.
PROFILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By COURTNEY KANE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FT.Com, the Internet venture of The Financial Times, the
London-based financial newspaper, is embarking on its first
consumer marketing campaign to raise its profile in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements, with the theme ``The world doesn't turn on a
dime,'' emphasize the importance of a global perspective in today's
business environment. The $35 million campaign features Dan Aykroyd
in a series of humorous television commercials, in addition to
print, outdoor and online ads.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which begins Sunday, is the first from BBDO New
York, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group, since
the agency was awarded the account in November. The commercials are
the first that Aykroyd, the actor known for his work in the early
years of ``Saturday Night Live'' and in many films, has done, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The humor in the commercials, said Paul Waddington, marketing
communications director for FT.com in London, ``helps us to get
away from any perhaps connotations of stuffiness that the parent
brand has.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first commercial, Aykroyd portrays Kopeky, the chief
executive of a leading American foam rubber company, who is
negotiating with three Italian businessmen over the sale of his
company. After intense price negotiations being passed back and
forth on paper, Kopeky thinks he has pulled a fast one on the
Italians by agreeing to sell his company for what he believes to be
the astronomical price of 11 million lire, which a subtitle notes
is just $5,741. After shaking hands to seal the deal, the three
Italians raise their glasses to Kopeky and offer felicitations in
Italian that are translated in a subtitle as `idiot, moron and
chowderhead.`
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent commercials with Aykroyd portray him in similar
predicaments where his ignorance of global business also hurts him.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Sann, co-chief executive and chief creative officer at BBDO
New York, noted that this sort of inept businessman has always been
part of Aykroyd's repertory, ``so, it seemed like a natural fit and
you get more spin and noticeability of having a celebrity of his
stature.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of a celebrity, in addition to the campaign's quirky
humor, is indicative of many Web publishers' attempts to attract
attention in a media category that has quickly grown cluttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're late to the party,'' said Sue Haxager, senior vice
president and senior account director on the FT.com account at BBDO
New York. ``There are already a variety of business news services
and the dot-com noise in general.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective,'' she added, ``we are trying to say that
we are a dot-com and that FT, which has a very conservative image,
is doing something radically different, and we felt if we
approached it to somberly the `Internetness' of it wouldn't come
across.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, which was introduced in 1995, was revamped last
month and is now being offered as an international business portal
with news, views and archives. The target is a broader business
audience in middle management ages 25 to 54.
</P>
<P>
   FT.com says it has 1.2 million users every month. About 12
percent of those users come from the United States; 56 percent come
from Britain; about 20 percent from Europe, with the remainder from
the rest of the world. It competes with several financial Web news
sites, including MarketWatch.com, TheStreet.com and WSJ.com, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build upon the growing reputation of the newspaper
in the U.S. and broaden it to increase the audience for the
Financial Times brand over all,'' said Stephen Hill, group chief
executive at FT.com's parent the Financial Times Group unit of
Pearson PLC in London. ``What we want to is get people's minds to
integrate the two services of the Financial Times Group.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, the 11 print ads for FT.com use the distinctive
salmon-pink color of The Financial Times as the backdrop. One
headline proclaims: ``Greeks, Chinese, Germans, Russians, Italians,
Uzbeks, Namibians, Turks, Japanese and Americans all speak the same
language. Money.'' Another ad directs readers to FT.com's Markets
and Portfolio channel by promising, ``Learn so much about Charles
Schwab, you can call him Chuck.'' A third headline states, ``Phrase
often heard by FT.com users: Cha-ching!'' And, ``When your company
does business in countries you can't spell.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper and magazine ads will begin appearing next week in
publications including The Economist, Forbes, The New York Times,
The Wall Street Journal and USA Today. The online advertising
portion of the campaign, created by (AT)tmosphere in New York, a
digital branding agency started by BBDO New York last year, will be
on various media properties including MSNBC.com, MSN.com and
Hotmail.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
