u a BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT     03-23 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK BEGINS ATTACK ON VIRUS-CARRYING MOSQUITOES
</HEADLINE>
 (mh) 
By By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until last summer, the presence of mosquitoes in and
around New York City was about as consequential as the presence of
pigeons _ and far less obvious. Then came West Nile, a
mosquito-borne virus that killed seven people in the metropolitan
region, caused brain infections in 62 others and prompted
widespread spraying of insecticides in the city and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the chances of a sequel to last year's outbreak,
health officials from the state, the city and counties around the
region began Thursday the first part of a three-step attack on
mosquitoes, specifically a city-loving species, Culex pipiens, that
breeds in puddles and old tires, seeks meals in back yards and
bedrooms and is the link known to carry the West Nile virus from
birds to people.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Queens, close to the epicenter of last
year's outbreak, Dr. Antonia C. Novello, the state health
commissioner, said people should not panic and, for the most part,
should embrace the coming warm months, not fear them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not destroy your summer,'' she said. ``Trust our system.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan consists of three strategies: disrupting the
mosquitoes' reproduction, monitoring mosquitoes and birds for signs
of the virus and, finally, instituting new procedures at hospitals
to catch the earliest hint of human cases.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials from the region joined Novello to describe
similar efforts in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The health officials said pesticide spraying would occur only as
a last resort, if clear signs emerge that the virus threatens
people.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, their plan earned the endorsement of some private
environmental groups. William Cooke, a spokesman for the National
Audubon Society, said the program was a reasonable approach that
could prevent an outbreak and minimize the use of pesticides. He
said it was particularly important for the public to become
involved, eliminating stagnant water where the mosquitoes breed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people do in their back yards may help prevent
spraying,'' he said. ``We need to work aggressively now so we don't
see the planes, the helicopters, the trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   But other environmental groups criticized the control plan,
saying that any spraying at all would be ill-advised and largely
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquito-control project gained some urgency last week after
scientists reported that the virus had survived the winter in a
sample of dormant adult mosquitoes and in a red-tailed hawk that
died in February.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Novello described the first part of the control
program, which will use television advertisements, pamphlets and
volunteers like the Boy Scouts to encourage residents of the
metropolitan region to make mosquito control part of their spring
cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Once those control efforts are well under way, the next phase
will begin: weekly testing of trapped mosquitoes, dead birds and
captive flocks of chickens to pick up any early signs that the
virus is spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the watch will begin at hospitals for human cases.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the first phase, health officials said, is to reduce
the mosquito population by interrupting the breeding cycle at its
weakest link, when larvae emerge from eggs and wriggle in pools and
puddles for several days before the new mosquitoes emerge and take
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Novello urged people to discard used tires, remove pails or
other containers that hold water, invert children's swimming pools
and frequently change the water in bird baths. People with pools
are being advised to be sure that the water is chlorinated and that
any water trapped in pool covers is removed. ``Most important of
all,'' she said, ``clean clogged gutters.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Novello said the effort to prevent the
recurrence of West Nile had produced a system that should help
promptly signal future outbreaks of this and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, officials around southern New York state scrambled to
find laboratories capable of identifying the virus, shipping some
samples as far as California and Wisconsin. This year the state
Health Department has set up its own testing centers.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all of the preparations, Novello said, some mosquitoes
may still end up carrying the virus and pose a threat to people.
The chances of being bitten by a Culex mosquito are greatest at
dusk and dawn, she said, and if residents of the affected areas
need to be outside at those times, they should wear long sleeves or
use insect repellent.
</P>
<P>
   In the vast majority of people infected with West Nile, there
are almost no symptoms, or at most a flulike reaction or aches,
virus experts say. In a few cases, particularly in the elderly, the
virus can cause potentially fatal brain swelling, called
encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   At the federal Environmental Protection Agency, which is
responsible for managing the use of pesticides, officials said they
were investigating some complaints by environmental groups that
pesticides were improperly used last fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen L. Johnson, the agency's deputy assistant
administrator for pesticide programs, said his staff had analyzed
the plans for fighting the mosquitoes this year and found they were
likely to minimize the use of pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appear to utilize spraying of a chemical as the last
resort, and that's the approach we think is appropriate,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
