<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS KEEP THEIR GUARD UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ As the Los Angeles Lakers ponder a possible
extended rest for veteran guard Ron Harper, coach Phil Jackson will
rest easy knowing his offense can survive the absence.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Harper, playing on bad knees and old legs, is
probably heading for the injured list to recharge for the playoffs.
Jackson said a decision will be made soon. Harper would have to
miss five games.
</P>
<P>
   Harper's experience directing the triangle offense was
indispensable in November, but the Lakers are now equipped to play
without him, thanks to the development of both Kobe Bryant and
Brian Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant has matured as the initiator of the offense and no longer
needs Harper to calm him down. Shaw, 34, has adapted to the
offense, has the size (6-foot-6) Jackson likes and has become a
consistent producer off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw has averaged 21 minutes over the last seven games, the most
consistent playing time he's received this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way he's playing. He's doing a good job,'' said
Jackson. ``We're just trying to use our guard corps in a way that
gives us a mixture of things _ speed, defense, ability to set up
the offense, the ability to make it run a little bit quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw has already supplanted Derek Fisher as the third guard most
nights and looks forward to doing more if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kind of take it as it comes,'' he said. ``Whatever
happens, just try to keep what we have going, going. And whoever
gets the minutes, be productive and try to do as well as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The additional minutes help, Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can relax a little bit more. You don't have to press as
much, because you know that you're going to get the minutes.
Sometimes you feel like if you come in for a short period of time,
you have to make something happen within that period of time, real
quick . . . or you're going to come out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw figures that Fisher, who started while Bryant was out in
November, will take Harper's starting position, but he's
comfortable with any role.
</P>
<P>
   ``(If) we can take care of our business and lock up the top spot
(in the West) and rest Harp at the same time, then that's great,''
Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sympathy: The Phoenix Suns come to Staples Center tonight
without All-Star guard Jason Kidd, who will miss the rest of the
regular season after breaking his left ankle on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel bad for anybody who suffers an injury, but especially
Jason, me growing up with him and knowing how much he loves to be
on the floor and play basketball,'' said Shaw, a fellow Oakland
native.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw and others were surprised to hear that popular ex-Sun Kevin
Johnson is coming out of a two-year retirement to take Kidd's
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be interesting,'' Shaw said. ``I think it would be
hard. There have been some rules changes that have occurred since
the last time he played.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' injury woes _ all five starters have missed
significant playing time _ stands in stark contrast to the Lakers,
who haven't had a player go down since Bryant returned from a
broken hand in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the name of the game, basically, is how do you prevent
that. You don't,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   But he lauded the work of conditioning coach Jim Cotta and
trainers Chip Schaefer and Gary Vitti and said the players have
been dedicated to their weight training and conditioning work. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
