<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHIGAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARTANS CONQUER FEAR, ORANGEMEN
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-SYRACUSE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ When the Syracuse Orangemen had finally
been vanquished, 75-58, Michigan State guard Mateen Cleaves was
asked how the Spartans felt, staring at double-digit deficits in
the second half, with time ticking away on their season.
</P>
<P>
   Was it fear?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' Cleaves said after Thursday night's victory. ``I
don't say it was fear ... a sense of urgency, probably. I mean, you
do think about it maybe being your last game. Well, in a way, I
guess you could say it was fear, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves and his teammates overcame any fear by outscoring
Syracuse 17-0 in the last 5:55 of the game, turning a 58-58 tie
into a rout.
</P>
<P>
   When Cleaves is afraid, he seeks comforting companionship and
calm, reasoned verbal discourse. So, when he walked into the locker
room at halftime with the Spartans trailing by 10 points, he cut
loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``I can't repeat what was said. Let's just
say I got in some people's faces. I didn't think we were playing
hard, and it was about time we started.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he saved coach Tom Izzo the trouble of
delivering the sermon himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I got to the locker room, Mateen was just
finishing up,'' Izzo said. ``There was nothing left for me to do
but pick up the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know that in the second half, we reached deep down,
after being really badly beaten up to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a complete turnaround that Cleaves _ held scoreless to
that point _ launched with a 3-point shot with 17:43 remaining.
That basket brought the anguished, green-clad crowd at The Palace
to its feet with a roar. The Spartans (29-7) _ the top-seeded team
in the Midwest Regional _ were on their way to victory over the
Orangemen (26-6), who had held leads up to 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves' shot merely closed the gap to 42-32, but it was quickly
followed by a 3-pointer from Morris Peterson, who wound up 5-of-9
from beyond the arc and scored 16 of his 21 points in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that one,'' Peterson said, ``I told Mateen to keep
feeding me the ball because I felt hot. And he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves hit another 3-pointer, Peterson two more, and the
Syracuse zone, that had befuddled the Spartans in the first half,
began to unravel. The Orangemen recovered briefly and still held a
49-38 lead with 15:13 remaining. But they scored nine points the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   After MSU surged into the lead, the last Syracuse basket came
with 5:46 remaining, tying the game at 58-58. From there to the
finish, the Spartans went on their run to finish off the game. They
shot 68 percent in the second half, including 9 of 15 from
three-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't really a 17-point game,'' Izzo said. ``In the first
half, they had 14 points off the break and they were killing us.
They outshot us, outran us, and beat us in every way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they still fought hard in the second half, but it
seemed like we hit a few key baskets and the roof caved in.''
</P>
<P>
   That was pretty much the way Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim saw it,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were active in our zone and played well for 30 minutes,''
he said. ``Then they came out hit nine of their first 13 from
3-point range in the second half. That's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a bit wearing on Cleaves, who finished with 10
points and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we finally started playing aggressively,'' he said.
``But I'm getting tired of these halftime speeches.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
