<HEADLINE>
`BAND' FEEDS FRENZY FOR BOY GROUPS, REALITY TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 
(UNDATED) - The ABC network apparently be lieves our thirst for
reality TV is undying.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC apparently is right. Its Making the Band, which pre mieres
tonight, could be the guilt iest pleasure since that other ABC show
. . . what's it called? Stars Regis somebody.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it's car-wreck tele vision _ the gawk factor is what
attracts you even if you don't want it to do so. Making the Band
chronicles the creation of a boy band called O-Town, put together
by Lou Pearlman, the guy behind the Backstreet Boys and 'N Sync (so
blame him).
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 guys audi tioned for the five positions. We see
them singing their guts out, in that vocal-gymnastics way boy bands
favor. The first episode shows Pearlman whittle the group down to
25, who are whisked away to Orlando for a more thorough
auditioning.
</P>
<P>
   We get to know guys like Kiaika Kahoano of Hawaii, who cries
when he's selected. Actu ally, several cry _ they're the sensitive
type.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't call, I'm going to be crushed,'' one hopeful
says. Hard to say which one _ most have the angular features,
fresh-scrubbed faces and moussed hair of boy-band chart-toppers;
they tend to run together.
</P>
<P>
   MTV recently aired 2Gether, a spoof of the boy-band phenome non.
What a waste. The network should have secured the rights to this _
it's far funnier than fiction could ever be.
</P>
<P>
   It's oddly suspenseful when Pearlman, standing onstage, reads
the names of the eight fi nalists. Three more will be cut
eventually, but not before we watch them live together in a fab
Orlando house over the coming weeks, learning to be stars. And
since Making the Band is made by the same folks who brought us Real
World and Road Rules, we see almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   At a tearful airport goodbye, the girlfriend of one finalist
says, ``I've always had a real strong trust with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cut to her true love.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the situation is I'm going to be surrounded by
beautiful women and maybe I can be strong enough to not take
advantage of that. But I'm 21 . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Sick as it sounds, this should be fun. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz &LR;  &QL; 
ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8974. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
